<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGUIRE-HOME-RUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE THAT! MCGUIRE (55) ANSWERS SOSA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ In what seems a game of home run cat-and-mouse, Mark
McGwire is playing Tom to Sammy Sosa's Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa, of the Chicago Cubs, homered on Sunday afternoon to
tie Mark McGwire for the home run lead, at 54 all, only to have
McGwire _ almost exactly seven hours later _ blast one out of Busch
Stadium on Sunday night. The seventh-inning hit off the Braves
right-handed relief pitcher Dennis Martinez traveled an estimated
501 feet to dead center field.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did McGwire take sole possession of the home run lead,
but he also gave the Cardinals an 8-7 lead in the game, since there
were two runners on base when he struck the blow. The lead stood up
as the Cardinals took the final game of their series with the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire also drew closer to catching Roger Maris' single-season
record of 61 homers, set in 1961. McGwire has 26 games left in the
season, Sosa has 25. Sosa has moved to within a home run or two of
McGwire several times in the last few weeks _ after McGwire had
held the lead for virtually the entire season _ and even went ahead
once when the two teams played about two weeks ago. But each time
Sosa makes McGwire uncomfortable, McGwire unloads.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, on Aug. 19, Sosa went one ahead of McGwire, only to
have McGwire hit two in the same game to regain the lead. This is
as good a race as anything seen at Churchill Downs or Belmont Park.
McGwire was asked after the game how he felt about ``it''?
</P>
<P>
   ``What, the win?'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   He understands that the greatest interest is not in the
Cardinals' victories at this point _ they are eight games under
.500 and out of contention. ``It feels good to come back and win a
game, feels even better doing it against one of the best teams in
the National League,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sosa, McGwire said, ``I can only take care of myself.''
He added: ``I don't see the homer thing as a challenge between me
and Sammy. You don't get an Oscar at the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   But he knows the stakes, of course. It is for the most heralded
record in American sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great year, what a historical year,'' he said.
``Wouldn't that be something if both Sammy and me hit _ what is it?
_ 62 or 63 homers each? Well, we just have to see what happens.
Sept. 27 is the finished product'' _ that is, the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited for Sammy,'' McGwire added. ``He's having a
magical season. Way better than I'm having. He's got a higher
batting average, he's driven in more runs and his team is in the
race for the wild card in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire handicapped himself on Saturday when he argued so
belligerently on a called third strike in the first inning that he
virtually forced Umpire Sam Holbrook to throw him out of the game.
So he was not around to fully respond at the plate to Sosa's 53d
homer on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire made up for it on Sunday night, after walking and
hitting a single and a double in three trips to the plate. The home
run was also his first in the four-game series against the Braves.
He had not hit a home run since Wednesday, against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire became only the second player in National League history
to hit 55 home runs in a season. Hack Wilson set the record of 56
with the Cubs in 1930. McGwire hit 58 home runs last season, but
only 24 of those were with St. Louis. He hit 34 with Oakland in the
American League, before being traded to the Cardinals on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals play Monday night in Florida against the Marlins,
while the Cubs return home to play Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire also drove in his 119th run, giving him a career high.
The record for runs batted in appears fairly safe for Wilson, who
holds that one, too. He knocked in 190 runs in his remarkable 1930
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
