A0040 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-SIDEBAR-LADN     08-31 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUGGISH DEFENSE AWAKENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The USC defense spent the summer preparing for the
four-receiver, one-running-back formation that Purdue threw at the
Trojans on Sunday in the Pigskin Classic at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   They knew quarterback Drew Brees would keep the Trojans'
defensive backs busy all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did know,'' USC defensive coordinator Bill Young said.
``They just do an awful good job of (executing).''
</P>
<P>
   Make that a good job for one half. And, as USC defensive back
Daylon McCutcheon said after the Trojans' 27-17 victory: ``Great
teams do great things when the game is on the line. And the game is
on the line in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The great things in the second half included an interception by
middle linebacker Chris Claiborne, which set up the go-ahead field
goal, an interception and forced fumble by cornerback Antuan
Simmons and overall spirited play from the Trojans secondary.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first half, it was all Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Brees, the undefeated prep quarterback from Texas, looked very
comfortable in his first game as a starter. The 6-foot-1, 204-pound
sophomore completed 18 passes in 27 attempts for 148 yards and had
touchdown passes of 3 yards to Gabe Cox and 9 yards to Cliff
Jackson as Purdue led 17-10. It would have been worse if Simmons
hadn't blocked a field-goal attempt with 1:17 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Eight receivers caught passes for the Boilermakers before
intermission and many times Brees would patiently roll out while
waiting for receivers to get open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made an average quarterback look like an All-American,''
Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we were like a new team,'' USC safety
Rashard Cook said. ``Our defense was flying around and flying to
the ball. We played like we expected ourselves to play.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's defensive backs were outstanding in the second half.
Simmons had nine tackles and set up the clinching touchdown with
his forced fumble. Ife Ohalete, who played nearly every defensive
play in the final three quarters after Grant Pearsall left with a
twisted knee, had seven tackles and two pass breakups. Cook had
seven tackles, Ken Haslip had three pass breakups and McCutcheon
had three tackles and two pass breakups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure we'll play against a better secondary all year,''
Purdue coach Joe Tiller said.
</P>
<P>
   Brees was 12 for 25 for 100 yards in the second half and was
intercepted by Claiborne and Simmons. The Boilermakers rushed for
39 yards after intermission and never got closer than the Trojans'
47-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest defensive play of the second half came late
in the fourth quarter when Brees' pass bounced off the shoulder
pads of the Boilermakers' Randall Lane and into the hands of a
diving Clairborne at Purdue's 27-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play was all about heart,'' said McCutcheon, who had
tight coverage on the play.
</P>
<P>
   But, McCutcheon, being a three-year letterman, is well aware
that one scorching Sunday afternoon doesn't make a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only one game,'' said McCutcheon, who nearly entered
his name in the past NFL draft. ``It's important to win the opening
game, because it sets the tone for the season. But we have a long
way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
