<HEADLINE>
MET'S MINAYA INTERVIEWS WITH DODGERS FOR GM JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Omar Minaya, the New York Mets' assistant general
manager, spoke to the Dodgers on Sunday, ending the first round of
interviews for their vacant GM position.
</P>
<P>
   Interim GM Tom Lasorda, who compiled a list of seven candidates
for the job, said he isn't sure if Gary Hughes, Florida's director
of player personnel, will be in this week. Hughes had been
scheduled for an interview before the end of the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Minaya, 40, who made his reputation with Texas as a top scout in
Latin America, was the sixth candidate to interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have said they want a new GM in place by the end of
the regular season. The other candidates: Florida GM Dave
Dombrowski, Cincinnati GM Jim Bowden, former Yankees GM Bob Watson,
Atlanta assistant Dean Taylor, Baltimore assistant Kevin Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing is that all but one of these guys aren't going
to get the job,'' said Lasorda, including Hughes in the mix. ``Any
one of these guys could do what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Minaya considers himself a long shot because he never has been
the top man in running a major-league operation. But he impressed
Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked his knowledge of so many areas of the game,''
Lasorda said. ``Farm director, assistant GM, head of scouting
overseas. All of those are the kinds of areas we were looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot bat: Mark Grudzielanek entered Sunday's game batting .250
(27 for 108) with no walks and just four runs since arriving in a
July 31 trade with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Although Grudzielanek was starting to warm up, hitting in seven
of his past eight games, Sunday was his best effort with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek went 3 for 3 with two runs. His seventh-inning
double was his first extra-base hit since Aug. 9 against
Pittsburgh, a stretch of 74 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an offensive player,'' hitting instructor Mickey
Hatcher said. ``He has gotten 200 hits in a season and made
All-Star teams. He's been pressing, but tonight he just relaxed and
did what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Catcher Tom Prince learned he was playing just
minutes before game time. Charles Johnson could not get his arm
loose and was scratched. ``It was either sit from the beginning or
risk getting hurt during the game,'' said Johnson, rested for
Saturday's game after playing Friday night. ``It isn't anything
serious.'' ... Not only did he have a key two-run double in the
seventh, Prince threw out Edgardo Alfonzo attempting to steal in
the fifth. Prince has thrown out 10 of 22 baserunners this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
