<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY'S TWO HOMERS FUEL M'S ROUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ken Griffey Jr. returned to the home run record chase
Sunday and Bill Swift departed the Mariner starting rotation with
one of his best performances of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But their postgame moods were remarkably different following the
Mariners' 13-3 victory over the New York Yankees at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Swift was happy with what he did _ holding the Yankees to two
runs and five hits over 62/3 innings. Griffey uttered his usual
``no comment'' when asked if his 46th and 47th homers proved that
his powerful swing is back and Roger Maris' single-season record
(61) is reachable.
</P>
<P>
   Only his bat sounded off in the series finale.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a total reversal of the first two in the series,
when the Yankees scored early and often and won both to clinch a
postseason berth. Griffey's three-run blast to right field in the
second inning off Yankee starter Hideki Irabu put Seattle in front
by seven runs, erasing most of the drama from the two teams' last
meeting of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team went quietly. Just when it appeared their rivalry
had cooled off:
</P>
<P>
   -- Two batters were hit by pitches, prompting a bench- and
bullpen-clearing (but incident-free) gathering near the mound;
</P>
<P>
   -- Mariner shortstop Alex Rodriguez and Yankee left fielder Chad
Curtis exchanged words after a play at second base;
</P>
<P>
   -- And one of the 55,341 fans jumped out of the left-field seats
carrying a football, running into center field to get Griffey's
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   The fan got a signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an NFL ball and I signed it,'' Griffey said. ``He
already was in trouble, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Two security guards wrestled the fan to the ground, roughed him
up and carted him away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him running toward Junior and I thought about going
after him,'' said left fielder Shane Monahan, describing the
fifth-inning incident. ``But he had a `Griffey' jersey on so I
didn't think anything bad would happen. I figured I'd let the cops
take care of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a tad hard on the guy. They gave him a `chicken
wing', bending his arm behind his back and kicked him a few times
in the ribs.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and Monahan were a tad hard on Yankee pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Each had two hits. Griffey drove in five runs. Monahan drove in
three.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his third-inning verbal battle with Curtis, Rodriguez
had three hits and scored twice. Joey Cora, Russ Davis and David
Segui chipped in two hits apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team showed some character, and Bill Swift did a great job
of pitching,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``I'm proud of this
group; the way they got kicked around for two days and came back
shows character.''
</P>
<P>
   But the focus of the day fell on Griffey's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting four homers in August coming into this series,
Griffey hit three in three games. He hit 12 homers in September
last season to finish with a career-high 56.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he stayed back on the ball better the past three days
and kept his back (left) shoulder in,'' Mariner hitting coach Jesse
Barfield said. ``Can he break the record? If they pitch to him. Of
the three guys, (Sammy) Sosa is the best bad-ball hitter. Junior
and (Mark) McGwire hit strikes for home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella, ``Junior hits them in bunches. Let's hope he
stays hot. He's got 47 and we've got a month to go. Let's see what
happens. I'd like to see it happen for a few people. Records are
made to be broken. This is getting exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift bored the Yankee fans for most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off horrendous back-to-back starts, the right-hander went
to work with a four-run lead after Rodriguez, Segui, Davis and Rob
Ducey drove in first-inning runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they were tired, or I made good pitches,''
said Swift, who is being moved to the bullpen for the remainder of
this season to open a spot in the rotation for Mac Suzuki. ``I'm
happy with the way I pitched and it's a good way to go out (of the
rotation).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think long relief is going to be better for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Paniagua, Swift's replacement in the seventh inning,
started the late-game fireworks when he unintentionally drilled
Scott Brosius in the back with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius left the game but wasn't seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee reliever Mike Buddie retaliated in the top of the eighth,
hitting Ducey in the leg immediately after throwing an identical
pitch that sailed between the batter's legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out there to play baseball, not fight,'' Ducey said when
asked if he thought about charging the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get two guys hit, it's serious,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Curtis touched off a brief scuffle when he failed
to slide as the Mariners turned an inning-ending double play.
Curtis veered off as he approached second base and Rodriguez took
exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in the heat of battle and I thought he should have slid
or gotten out of the way sooner,'' Rodriguez said. ``No big deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
