<HEADLINE>
LONG HAUL PAYS OFF FOR JOSEPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Two years ago, Kerry Joseph was the No. 3
quarterback with the Cincinnati Bengals. Last summer, he was a
running back with the Washington Redskins until being released on
the final roster cut.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Joseph was one of five safeties retained by the Seahawks
when they cut their roster to 53 players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road for me. I've been through a whole lot,''
Joseph said. ``After I got cut at running back, I kind of went into
the tank. I wondered if my football career was coming to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph's improbable journey included a side trip to the World
League this spring, where the former McNeese State quarterback
played safety for the league champion Rhein Fire and did it well
enough that the Seahawks decided to sign him the week before
training camp opened.
</P>
<P>
   Another mild upset was Robert Wilson beating out sixth-round
draft choice Bobby Shaw for the sixth wide receiver spot. Wilson
did it with his special-teams performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three games, Robert Wilson has probably been our best
special teams player,'' coach Dennis Erickson said. ``We kind of
discovered him by playing a lot of people there during the
preseason and all of a sudden he stood out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson never played special teams until he signed with the
Seahawks as a rookie free agent last year, when he spent most of
the season on the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the guys who are here were big-time players at their
schools, so they didn't play special teams,'' said Wilson, who has
been sharing a room at an Eastside motel with Shaw since the team
returned from its Eastern Washington University training camp.
``It's something you have to learn to do. It's desire. It's
toughness, because you're going to get knocked down and knocked
out, but you've just got to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph and Wilson overcoming long odds and stiff competition to
earn roster spots were the upside to a day when eight players had
to be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson dislikes making any cuts, but Sunday's were the hardest
since he became Seahawks coach in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to release some pretty good football players,''
Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Included in Sunday's cuts were linebacker Michael Barber, who
started games the past two seasons; defensive lineman Carl Hansen
and Shaw, this year's sixth-round draft choices who could be
re-signed to the practice squad Monday; and running back Michael
Black and cornerback Joey Eloms, promising rookie free agents who
also could end up on the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Also released: guard Chris Brymer, defensive end Reggie Lowe and
center Greg Bloedorn. The Seahawks made eight cuts because they had
a World League exemption on last week's cut to 60 for Bloedorn, who
agreed to an injury settlement before being released.
</P>
<P>
   The moves, and any the club might make this week, are tied to
the Seahawks having less than $200,000 left under their salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Barber's $400,000 salary and special-teams performances that
were only adequate made him a casualty. There also is less than a
50-percent chance the Seahawks will claim a player who was released
by another team, and if they do, it will probably be a younger
player who could be signed for the NFL minimum.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Joseph and Wilson playing their way onto the
roster, another slight surprise was keeping four tight ends. The
Seahawks used their 53rd spot at that position because Deems May
also can be used as a third fullback and Itula Mili, a sixth-round
draft choice last year, has too much potential to pass on or try to
sneak through waivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the road Itula could be really, really good,'' Erickson
said. ``We obviously didn't want to put him out there because we
would have never gotten him back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
