<HEADLINE>
KARL TAKES ON ANOTHER UNDERDOG ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What, you ask, was George Karl's greatest fantasy,
before signing a juicy $20 million deal with the Milwaukee Bucks
over the weekend?
</P>
<P>
   To coach Michael Jordan and the Bulls to the 1999 NBA title _
assuming there is a 1999 season in this locked-out, tuned-out NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Getting that gig in Chicago would have been one heck of a way
for Karl to prove his ability to handle the pressure, to win the
big one.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, with a chance to let His Airness do his thing, what
a way for Karl to sling a little humble pie into the faces of
Sonics owner Barry Ackerley and club president Wally Walker _ the
two fellas who labeled Karl ``The Incredible Leaking Man'' at his
dismissal proceedings in June, then sent Karl off to find work
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Which Karl did this weekend, to the tune of a whopping $5
million a year. It is the kind of career-affirming salary that puts
Karl in the same economic league as Rick Pitino and John Calipari
and the other heavy hitters of NBA coaching.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing is, despite the juicy deal with the Bucks, not
much has changed for Karl. His wife will probably still have to bug
him to go deposit his paychecks or find some worthwhile tax
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   And even Karl would have to admit that, more than rebuilding a
perennial loser, he would rather be coaching Jordan and the
Jordanaires to their seventh title in nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, his 6{ seasons in Seattle seemed to point Karl
in the direction of a better job in a bigger market, or at least
with a team already on the move up.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Terrell Brandon and Ray Allen are two great young
players, but Karl _ whose taste for winning is best fed by
competitive, committed veteran players _ would rather have a
wunderkind like Tim Duncan and David Robinson with whom to attempt
a title in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Or Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Or Patrick Ewing and Allan Houston at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Karl craves many things, not the least of which is to be
considered the most creative, forceful leader of NBA players in an
era where egos and salaries and expectations have gone mad.
</P>
<P>
   But now Karl will have to settle for something else. He will
have to prove he has the patience, tenacity and stomach to do what
Pitino is trying to do in Boston; what Calipari is doing in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He will have to do what he has already done in Albany, N.Y.,
where he coached a CBA team named the Patroons to a championship
and incredible win record.
</P>
<P>
   He will have to do what he already tried in Cleveland and Golden
State, two other perennial losers.
</P>
<P>
   He will have to do what he has already done in Spain, with a
club team called Real Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   He will have to do what he was brought in to do by former Sonic
general manager and wheeler-dealer, Bob Whitsitt.
</P>
<P>
   So while Karl dreamed of the Bulls and titles and NBA glory, he
will settle for another challenge.
</P>
<P>
   And this makes perfect sense, even for a man who dreamed of
coaching the world's greatest player on one of the NBA's greatest
dynasties to yet another title.
</P>
<P>
   Because if nothing else, George Karl is an underdog. He is the
second-chance coach whose insecurities are matched only by his
healthy ego _ a combination that gives him color and an edge and
energy that are both taxing and fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   His players will love him and loathe him, just like other places
where his certain sort of anxious magic have worked.
</P>
<P>
   Now even Karl understands he has a tough task at hand. Judging
from how things are going for the Celtics and Nets _ two other
franchises trying to overcome years of futility _ Karl's job should
be at best frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Bucks owner Herb Kohl and general manager Bob Weinhauer
truly give Karl carte blanche _ the way Pat Riley was handed the
Heat franchise in Miami and told to do whatever he wants (including
tamper and infuriate the NBA commissioner) _ Karl has a few long
and winding seasons ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing Karl likes the bratwursts and beers in his new town.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing Karl thinks he better identifies with the
working-class, hard-working atmosphere of Milwaukee than the
tepidly unemotional climate in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He will need some of those intangibles to make things feel good.
Otherwise, best pal and University of Utah coach Rick Majerus will
have to make a few extra pit stops through Wisconsin this winter,
just to keep his friend in good spirits.
</P>
<P>
   There is no amount of money that will assuage Karl's great big
love of pure and committed basketball _ which makes it somewhat
intriguing that Karl decided to leap at the brass ring of a
big-time, guaranteed contract instead of waiting for the
opportunity of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   But if we have learned anything about George Karl, it is that he
is cat-like. He has more than one life. And all of those lives _
judging by the former ones, including his incarnation in Seattle _
are crazy and entertaining and action-packed. Karl's new ventures
are always full of thrills, verbal spills and surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Bucks make the playoffs next season?
</P>
<P>
   What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
