r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAPD-HERO-DEBATE-2tak     08-31 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-HERO-DEBATE-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEROES OR KILLERS?' _ LAPD MEDALS, SUITS OFFER CONTRASTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PATRICK McGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ LAPD detectives Larry Winston and Phillip Wixon
are hero cops to many people.
</P>
<P>
   To others, they are trigger-happy killers.
</P>
<P>
   The clashing descriptions stem from the detectives' actions in
the same deadly gunbattle with robbery suspects outside a Ventura
County liquor store in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives, members of the LAPD's controversial Special
Investigation Section, were seriously wounded in the close-quarters
firefight that left robbery suspect Robert Cunningham wounded and
accomplice Daniel Soly dead, with 27 gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Federal lawsuits allege the two LAPD veterans ``murdered'' Soly.
But Chief Bernard C. Parks believes the actions of Winston, 24-year
veteran, and Wixon, a 31-year veteran, qualify them to receive the
Los Angeles Police Department's coveted Medal of Valor at a
ceremony next week.
</P>
<P>
   An LAPD commendation board found that the pair displayed
``outstanding judgment and tremendous courage in the heat of a
deadly gunbattle with two vicious criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the robbers' parents charge the detectives shot
without warning and without identifying themselves as police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time when it is okay to call these brutal
misanthropes what they are, and that is murderers,'' reads one of
the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   That Winston and Wixon evoke such strong and contrasting
reactions is not surprising given the controversial history of the
Special Investigation Section.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives _ the first members of the 23-year-old unit to
receive the LAPD's highest honor _ dismiss the lawsuits'
allegations as untrue and irrelevant, and say they are proud of
their actions and the affirmation of the Medal of Valor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to death. It's obviously the highlight of my
career,'' said Wixon, 53.
</P>
<P>
   Wixon took a bullet in the abdomen and returned to the job after
a nine-week recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   Winston, 43, who took six months to recover from a gunshot wound
to his groin, said he is flattered to share the Medal of Valor
ceremony this year with 17 officers who participated in the 1997
North Hollywood bank shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honored, but there isn't a person in the (SIS) unit that
isn't worthy of it as far as I'm concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the SIS put Soly, 27, a fugitive parolee, and Cunningham
under surveillance, they were suspected of 24 armed robberies at
small businesses in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley and portions of
neighboring Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   They financed a heroin habit by bursting into liquor stores and
fast-food restaurants with guns and their faces covered with ski
masks or bandannas. The heists grew increasingly violent as they
hit victims to force their compliance, police allege.
</P>
<P>
   Police caught a break when Soly's girlfriend tipped them off
that he had robbed a Pizza Hut in Simi Valley in Ventura County
while she sat in the car. But the investigation stalled without
enough evidence to arrest the pair so the SIS was brought in to
track them.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of July 26, 1995, eight undercover detectives
followed Soly and Cunningham to Southwest Liquor and Deli in the
quiet community of Newbury Park.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives said they saw the suspects get out of a white
Toyota Supra and pull bandannas over their faces before entering
the store, according to an LAPD report on the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Winston and Wixon decided to arrest the suspects when they
emerged from the store and were clear of bystanders, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said the robbers got about $600 before they were seen
putting handguns in their waistbands as they ran to their car.
</P>
<P>
   Wixon, Winston and Detective Brian Davis moved in with their
cars to pin the robbers' car, but Cunningham stood up through a
sunroof and began shooting at Wixon and Winston, according to the
commendation report.
</P>
<P>
   Wixon was shot in the abdomen as he tried to jump out of his
car.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to breathe, Wixon regained his composure and fired
several shotgun rounds at Cunningham, said the LAPD report, which
added that the suspect ducked back into the vehicle and continued
firing at officers.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Winston was hit in the groin by a shot from
another detective, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he lay wounded on the ground, Winston saw the suspects
continuing to fire,'' the commendation report said. ``Though
seriously wounded, Winston fired several more rounds at the
suspects'' in an effort to draw their attention away from his
wounded partner.
</P>
<P>
   Wixon said Soly began revving the engine of his car and pushing
against a police car, which Wixon feared would be pushed back onto
his wounded partner, the report said. The detective stood up,
exposing his position, to confront the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to save his and his partner's lives, Wixon fired at
the driver and then held his weapon on the passenger while other
SIS detectives took the suspects into custody,'' the commendation
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite claiming in a criminal trial that the officers fired
first, without warning, Cunningham was held responsible for Soly's
death and was convicted of murder, robbery and the attempted murder
of three police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham is serving several life sentences in prison.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this case, 24 other robberies _ blamed on
Cunningham, Soly or both _ were solved, cases closed.
</P>
<P>
   In awarding Wixon and Winston the Medal of Valor, and also
awarding SIS detective James Harris a distinguished service medal,
the commendation board concluded: ``The utter disregard for their
own personal safety displayed by these three detectives in order to
assist and protect their fellow officers is a tribute to all
members of the Police Department and to the entire law enforcement
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County prosecutor Donald Glynn wrote to the LAPD that
the public owes the SIS detectives ``a debt of gratitude for their
continuing efforts to control the worst of the worst criminals in
our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Yagman, the attorney pressing the lawsuits, declined to
comment on the detectives' actions being honored with the Medal of
Valor.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit filed on behalf of Armand and Betty Soly, the
parents of Daniel Soly, Yagman alleges that the plainclothed
Winston and Wixon fired first into the suspects' car, without
identifying themselves as police officers, and that the suspects
returned fire in self-defense, not knowing that their attackers
were police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without announcing themselves as police (they) opened fire
with approximately 15 shotgun blasts and shots from handguns; all
with the intent of taking the law into their own hands, and
murdering the occupants of the vehicle,'' the lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also names the police chief, mayor, police
commissioners and City Council members, alleging they all tolerated
``a custom of excessive force.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Attorney Cory Brente, who is defending the officers
in the suit, said the detectives did not get a chance to identify
themselves before Cunningham shot Wixon.
</P>
<P>
   He said the criminal jury that convicted Cunningham of murder in
Ventura County did not buy Cunningham's claim that he was unaware
it was the police approaching them in several cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else drives on the wrong side of the road and comes up
fast in front of you after you've committed a robbery?'' Brente
said. ``It's the police.''
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for acquittal in the criminal trial, Cunningham's
defense attorney urged a jury to send the message that SIS should
be disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``By their finding, the jury stated unequivocally that these
officers operated properly,'' Glynn wrote to the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Barkat, who owns Southwest Liquor and Deli, said Wixon
and Winston deserve the medals for showing bravery in confronting
suspects who they knew were armed and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really appreciate what they did,'' Barkat said. ``They had
followed them. They knew something would happen. They did a very
good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston said he is not losing sleep over the lawsuits, knowing
the unit's actions will be defended by the city.
</P>
<P>
   Both detectives acknowledge that their work is dangerous, but
neither said it was hard to decide to return to the SIS when they
left the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be downright scary,'' Winston said. ``I had second
thoughts about whether I was going to come back to police work. But
when I made up my mind I was coming back there was no other place I
wanted to go (but SIS).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best job in the Police Department. There's a lot of
satisfaction. It's the kind of people we get off the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Wixon also said the shootout in Newbury Park in Ventura County
did not discourage him from staying with the SIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the scaredest I've ever been, but it was scary,''
Wixon said. ``It's not much fun getting shot.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``Police work is dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to stay with SIS, Wixon said he balanced the
experience of the Newbury Park shootout against what he says is the
esprit de corps of the SIS and the times he has put violent
criminals in jail or rescued innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the self-satisfaction of doing a good job, of getting a
kid back from kidnappers. The entire unit deserves an award for the
kind of work they do every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
