<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT METS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Gary Sheffield was being helped into the
trainer's room Sunday night, Jose Vizcaino remembered that game
nine weeks ago when his right ankle looked so bad he cried.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield was headed to the hospital after turning his left
ankle in an eighth-inning rundown during the Dodgers' 4-2 victory
over the New York Mets. But Vizcaino, who hasn't played since his
injury, forced a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``No swelling, that is a great sign,'' said Vizcaino, who
sprained his ankle June 21 and might not play again this season.
``Mine got so big I couldn't believe it. That doesn't mean Gary
won't be out, but I think we'll get him back.''
</P>
<P>
   With 25 games to play and trailing the Mets and Chicago Cubs by
seven games in the wild-card race, the Dodgers still are hoping.
</P>
<P>
   They played perhaps their most inspired game in weeks and gave
the crowd of 44,746 something more to think about than a postgame
concert with the Village People.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when relievers Jeff Shaw and Antonio Osuna were
exhausted and unavailable, former Met Dave Mlicki (8-6) pitched the
Dodgers' first complete game in more than two months.
</P>
<P>
   It also came in a game Eric Young said the team looked very down
until his two-run single tied the game 2-2 with two outs in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was flat,'' Young said. ``We needed a lift and we got
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got another when reserve catcher Tom Prince, a
last-minute substitute for Charles Johnson, doubled home two more
runs in the seventh that gave the Dodgers their first victory in
the series.
</P>
<P>
   Prince was the first batter to face Turk Wendell, who took over
for Mets starter Masato Yoshii (5-8).
</P>
<P>
   But with a season of disappointments, the focus was on
Sheffield, who wasn't expected to play Sunday after spraining his
left thumb on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sheffield) is a gamer in every sense of the word,'' manager
Glenn Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield wasn't the only big-name player injured.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodger Mike Piazza, who was 10 for 16 in his past five
games, left in the third inning after Young fouled a ball off his
right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's not all right, he couldn't play,'' said Mets manager
Bobby Valentine. ``I think it's muscular. The trainers will let us
know tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Piazza, the Mets generated little offense against
Mlicki.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Baerga homered with one out in the second and Edgardo
Alfonzo added another to open the third.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo, who won Saturday's game with a home run off Shaw, also
beat the Dodgers Aug. 2 with a ninth-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   But Mlicki settled down and did not allow a runner to second the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really didn't mean any more playing my old team,'' said
Mlicki, 7-2 since joining the Dodgers on June 4. ``I knew we had a
tired bullpen so I just got on a roll and kept on going.''
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki got the runs he needed in the seventh when Bobby Bonilla
opened with a single to right. Mark Grudzielanek, who had his first
three-hit game as a Dodger, doubled to left. Bonilla came racing
around third, but third-base coach Joey Amalfitano put on the
brakes.
</P>
<P>
   That got rid of Yoshii, who now has just one victory in his past
16 decisions, but Prince was waiting. He hit a ground-rule double
that bounced into the lower stands near the left-field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood changed in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   With Sheffield at third and Raul Mondesi at first, Mondesi was
picked off first. He got caught in a rundown but was tagged out by
Baerga, who then threw to the plate. Mets catcher Jorge Fabregas
got Sheffield hung up. Sheffield stayed alive for several moments
as Fabregas threw to Alfonzo to make the tag.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sheffield's last attempt to stop he caught his left foot
in the turf and went down. He writhed on the ground in pain and had
to be helped off the field by trainer Charlie Strasser and hitting
instructor Mickey Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprains are better when they are on the outside of the
ankle,'' Vizcaino said. ``That seemed to be where his was. He is
too good to lose. We sure all hope we don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
