r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-MCCUTCHEON-LA     08-31 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-MCCUTCHEON-LADN </SLUG>
 
McCUTCHEON TURNING INTO LOUD LEADER 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB MIECH  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC cornerback Daylon McCutcheon has seen enough
mediocre play by the Trojans in his career. But he hasn't heard
enough, which he plans to change as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most versatile USC football player, McCutcheon
showed off his agility Sunday afternoon against Purdue with a bevy
of big plays in the Trojans' 27-17 victory before 56,623 at the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would mess up in the past, and I'd sit there and sit
there, and wait and wait, and nobody would say anything,''
McCutcheon said. ``And then there's two or three games left in the
season, and it's too late to say anything because it doesn't
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't wait for that. I'll get it done, and I won't stand for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon admitted that he had a big mouth against the
Boilermakers, which he will use as he sees fit throughout the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, we're a family,'' McCutcheon said. ``When you're a
family, you'll get yelled at by your mom or your dad, and you'll
get mad at your brothers or sisters. But deep down, you know I'll
be the first to be there in bad times. I'll be on you, I'll jump on
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I make a mistake, I want guys to jump on me. And when
you do well, I'll be the first to congratulate you.''
</P>
<P>
   None other than Chris Claiborne, a junior linebacker considered
to be the most talented USC front-line player, took heat from
McCutcheon on a day when the on-field temperature hit 118 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's showing more leadership this year,'' Claiborne said of
McCutcheon. ``And it is rubbing off on a lot of guys, and me. He'll
get on us, and I was listening to him a lot (on Sunday). I was
messin' up, and I take it as nothing but constructive criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon, 21, shut down every Purdue receiver who went up
against him at his left corner slot, he rushed every Boilermakers
punt from the left end and he returned a kickoff 25 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's special,'' said defensive end Sultan Abdul-Malik. ``He
can play offense and he can play special teams. You want your best
players out on special teams, and he's definitely one of our
best.''
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon, who wears No. 1 on his uniform, said he just wants
to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything they want me to,'' he said. ``I just stand on
the sideline and wait for my number to be called. I wouldn't mind
running a few routes and catching a few passes, whatever they want
me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He nearly caught one against Purdue deep in Boilermakers
territory at the end of the third quarter. But he did get an assist
when he popped the ball from wide receiver Randall Lane's hands,
and Claiborne snatched it just before it hit the ground.
</P>
<P>
   USC took over at the 31-yard line, and four plays later senior
kicker Adam Abrams booted a 45-yard field goal that gave the
Trojans the lead for good at 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Chris had just talked on the sideline, about how one of
us had to come up with a play,'' McCutcheon said. ``(Secondary)
coach (Dennis) Thurman talks all the time about how, when it gets
heated, how the good players make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the crowd yelling, but I thought it was just because I
had stripped the ball from the receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon hopped from a television interview to a room for a
radio show, talked with one reporter in an equipment hall and then
met a dozen or so writers at his locker stall.
</P>
<P>
   That's where his younger brother Marcus, 14, had been waiting
for 40 minutes or so. Marcus McCutcheon will begin playing football
on the frosh-soph team at Huntington Beach Edison High this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had a pretty good game,'' Marcus said of his older
brother. ``He could have picked one pass on the sideline, and
another had to be thrown just perfectly in the end zone. It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he wants to play some offense, but mostly he wants to
win. After the intrasquad scrimmage, he talked about being more of
a leader. And he's showing it. He's a great role model.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
