<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANGELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS PLAY SPOILER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The call came through to Helen Robinson, the legendary
Red Sox switchboard operator who has known them all, from Don Aase
to Al Zarilla, so no one had to tell her the identity of the voice
on the other end during Sunday afternoon's 8-6 loss to the Anaheim
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   After being serenaded by the crowd of 31,476 on his 80th
birthday, Ted Williams was calling to say thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told Helen he was deeply touched,'' said Sox broadcaster
Sean McDonough, who had informed the Fenway fans that Williams was
watching at home before leading them in the singing of ``Happy
Birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's fondest wish before he dies, he said, is to see the
Sox win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only got one wish, too,'' said Mo Vaughn, whose three-run
home run in the fifth inning drew the Red Sox within a run, 7-6,
but wasn't enough to prevent the Angels from taking the rubber
match of this three-game set and the season series, six games to
five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of all the great players in the past. You've got a lot
of great players who have been in this clubhouse and stepped out on
this field. When we do win it, we will be doing it for the present
team and all the guys who put their time in making the Red Sox what
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Vaughn reminded his listeners, the Sox are not yet
a playoff team. Their lead in the wild-card race, after the Texas
Rangers also lost Sunday, remains eight games with 28 to play. But
even though the Angels, who lead the AL West by three games over
Texas, could be a first-round opponent in a rematch of their
memorable '86 showdown, Vaughn wanted no part of that discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Especially after the Red Sox lost their first series since
dropping two of three to the Indians in Cleveland July 21-22. This
was their 12th series since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't gotten there yet,'' Vaughn said. ``They haven't
gotten there yet. The playoffs are a whole different thing. It's
not for us to look at. We still have to take a game-by-game
approach. If you relax or slack off, an eight-, nine-, 10-game lead
can drop that fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Red Sox took a 2-0 lead two batters into the bottom
of the first, as Darren Lewis tripled into the left-field corner
and John Valentin followed with his 18th home run and second in two
games, off Angels starter Jeff Juden of the Salem Judens.
</P>
<P>
   Party time? Not so fast. The Angels tied the score in the second
against Sox starter Tim Wakefield on Garret Anderson's 305-foot
home run just inside the Pesky Pole, Anaheim's first extra-base hit
of the series after 21 straight singles.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, the Angels parlayed two walks, two passed balls, a
bunt single by Darin Erstad, a 55-foot roller by Tim Salmon down
the third-base line that stayed fair, newcomer Gregg Jefferies's
two-run double to the gap in left-center, and an infield out for
four runs and a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole inning started with a leadoff walk, then two passed
balls, then another walk,'' said Wakefield (15-6), losing for the
first time in seven decisions since the Indians beat him July 21.
``I've always prided myself on damage control. But they got that
dribbler off the plate for a run, I made a good pitch to Jefferies,
and he doubled in two runs. I couldn't stop the bleeding today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added a seventh run off Wakefield in the fourth when
Gary DiSarcina was hit by a pitch, took second on a wild pitch, and
scored on Erstad's bloop single to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of a crazy game,'' Vaughn said. ``They got a lot of crazy
hits off Wake. A lot of guys on base, and the one big hit by
Jefferies.''
</P>
<P>
   Play was held up in the middle of the fourth for the serenading
of Teddy Ballgame. Nomar Garciaparra, the first batter after play
resumed, launched his 28th home run just to the right of the
420-foot sign, and an inning later Vaughn followed with a mammoth
442-foot drive well up into the center-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   But Angels reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa (7-3) shut out the Red
Sox on one hit for the next 3 1/3 innings, striking out Valentin
with a runner on third to end the seventh, and DiSarcina's infield
hit that glanced off Garciaparra's glove and rolled into short
center field accounted for the Angels' final run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the key to the whole game was Hasegawa,'' Jimy
Williams said. ``He shut us off, he shut us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Sox slouch toward September with 79 wins, one more
than they had all of last season, with one game left in August. One
month left in the regular season, and wishing season begins.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone in New England knows what else happened the year
Teddy Ballgame was born. Who knew the wait would be 80 years and
counting?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
