u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     08-31 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MADE IT THROUGH SAFE AND SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Thankfully for the Patriots, the most
dangerous time is over.
</P>
<P>
   With Saturday night's meaningless 24-7 victory over the
meaningless Philadelphia Eagles came the end of the meaningless
season. As most people understand, the only thing that can give the
exhibition season meaning is if your players start being carted off
on stretchers, an event that has bad meaning for both the people
involved and the team that employs them.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Pete Carroll's Patriots, that did not happen
this summer, and that is the best thing any team can get out of
meaningless season. Thus, when New England travels to Denver to
open its season next Monday night, Drew Bledsoe will be healthy and
Terry Glenn will be healthy and Bruce Armstrong will be as healthy
as a guy can be after he's played pro football for nearly a dozen
years and Ben Coates will be healthy and everyone else on offense
who matters will be healthy, and that is a healthy situation.
</P>
<P>
   Across the line of scrimmage, Willie McGinest will be healthy
and Ty Law will be healthy and Ferric Collins will be healthy and
Lawyer Milloy will be healthy and Ted Johnson will be very healthy
after signing his new contract and everyone else who matters on
defense will be healthy, and that is an even healthier situation.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is, rookie running back Robert Edwards and
cornerback Tebucky Jones might even be healthy. Steve Israel won't
be healthy, of course, but that is no longer a news bulletin now,
is it?
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, one thing seemed evident about these New
England Patriots after they made their final cuts Sunday, and that
was this: They may not have a running game but they have something
more important. They have the most talent in the AFC East, and that
talent is healthy. And that means the rest of the division is
looking at a serious problem when the Patriots come into their
towns, because in the end, it is talent that wins in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches are important and schemes are important and coaches with
schemes are especially important, but coaches with schemes but no
talent end up with teams that are unimportant. Those coaches end up
with teams that resemble the exhibition season. They become
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   So, all things being equal and all hands (and knees) being
healthy, what might you look forward to this season from the
Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   You might expect another 10-6 season, at worst, and 11-5 at
best.
</P>
<P>
   You might expect another AFC East title, at least one home game
in the playoffs, and 4 1/2 months to brag that your team is better
than their team as long as their team isn't in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Might you expect a Monday night win to open the season? Probably
not, at least not if you go by what you see, as the football
philosopher Bill Parcells likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   If you do that, you must go by the historical evidence until
something happens to alter that reality, and the evidence indicates
New England hasn't beaten the Broncos in Denver since the Roosevelt
Administration ... Teddy Roosevelt's administration.
</P>
<P>
   If the question is, are the Patriots talented enough to beat the
Broncos in Denver next Monday night, the answer is yes. That is
especially true now that these Broncos have an offensive line that
is replacing 60 percent of its starters, a rookie starting at
strong safety, and a quarterback who should have quit while he was
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But if the question is, will they do it, history says no. That
said, the normal response from these Patriots would be to argue
that that was then and this is now and it's all history and this is
a different team and so forth and so on. But the fact of the matter
is that these Broncos have beaten these Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The last three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   By an aggregate 105-24.
</P>
<P>
   And they're healthy, too.
</P>
<P>
   But don't lose heart over this, because anything can happen in
football if you have talent. And the Patriots have at least as much
of that as the Broncos, with the exception of one position. And you
know what position we're talking about, so let's not beat a dead
horse (or a dead running game) any longer.
</P>
<P>
   The key thing to remember about next Monday, though, is that it
is Week 1, not Week 18, which means it is one game, not one and
done. The Patriots' season opener is not as meangingless as an
exhibition game, but it is the next best thing, because if they win
it means nothing if they don't keep winning and if they lose it
means nothing as long as they don't keep losing.
</P>
<P>
   What means more is that when you look at the Colts and the Bills
and the Jets and the Dolphins, you do not see a team that is better
than the Patriots, so who cares what happens in Denver in the long
run? New England's AFC East rivals are not better on offense and
not better on defense and not better on special teams, so what's
left to debate about, local cuisine?
</P>
<P>
   Any of those teams might beat the Patriots in a game because
anything can happen when a ball is shaped the way a football is.
But none of the teams in the AFC East can honestly argue this
morning that they wouldn't trade their 53 guys for Carroll's 53
guys. So while any one of them might beat the Patriots in an
afternoon, none should beat them in a season.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here in New England with a new season dawning is a
playoff team. Nothing that happens in Denver short of injuries will
change that, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Now all they have to do is go give those facts some meaning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 0147EDT &QL; 
