<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BANKBOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN'S MONEY IN THE BANK 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Maybe they should rename the PGA Senior Tour
the Hale Irwin Retirement Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who didn't play his best golf and complained about his
shot-making, gutted out a 4-under-par 68 Sunday for a 15-under 201
and a two-stroke victory in the BankBoston Senior Classic at
Nashawtuc CC. It was his sixth victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The victory pushed Irwin over the $7 million plateau in Senior
Tour earnings, making him the fifth player to reach it. Irwin, who
counted BankBoston among his nine 1997 titles, also joins Don
January (1983-84), Chi Chi Rodriguez ('86-88), and Bob Charles
('89-90) as the only champions to successfully defend a title at
Nashawtuc.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't come easy.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sigel, who won one of his two US Amateur titles at The
Country Club in Brookline in 1982, blitzed the front nine, shooting
a 6-under 30. Hot nines are Sigel's specialty. He fashioned the
Senior Tour's best nine-hole score this year when he ran in seven
consecutive birdie putts at the Bell Atlantic Classic for a
sparkling 27.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's front nine wasn't a record setter, but it was music to
his ears _ his six birdies gave him the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front nine was pretty neat,'' said Sigel. ``I guess my
putter has some feelings. It doesn't want to go in the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Sigel opened the door for Irwin by making two bogeys
down the stretch. He failed to get up and down from a green-side
bunker on No. 16, missing a 4-footer for par. After making a heroic
birdie on No. 17, Sigel hooked his tee shot into the junk along the
left on the par-5 18th and never recovered. ``I wasn't prepared for
the driver at 18,'' said Sigel, who shot a 66 to finish with a 203
total, good for second place. ``I had hit 3-iron off that tee all
week, so it was a weird feeling, even though I feel it was the
right shot. I thought I had a chance to win. I had to have some
help from the leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-round co-leader Joe Inman (71) and David Graham (68) tied
for third at 204, while Norwood's Allen Doyle (69) and Al Geiberger
(71) tied for fith at 205.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin opened the door early, and if anyone on the leaderboard
had put together a great round, the tournament was for the taking.
Sigel's 66 and John Jacobs's 66 (tied for 36th at 214) were the
best rounds of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin started off with a bogey 5 on the opening hole _ his only
bogey of the week _ and luckily saved par on No. 3. ``I was more
bothered by my par on the third hole than I was by my bogey because
I hit it so poorly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the start I hoped to have. Thankfully, my
putting pulled me through and I hit some opportune iron shots,''
added Irwin, who hit a 6-iron to 20 feet and knocked it in on the
365-yard sixth hole. He drilled a 25-footer for a birdie 2 on the
200-yard eighth to get back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   But it was on the back nine where Irwin won the tournament and
Sigel lost it. While Sigel was KO'd by a pair of bogeys, Irwin
drilled three birdies to put away the title. Irwin needed only a
tap-in on the 538-yard 10th hole for a birdie 4 to go to 13-under.
</P>
<P>
   He fired up a 6-iron to 6 feet on the par-4 12th and knocked it
in to go to 14-under and take the lead from Sigel.
</P>
<P>
   On the 15th, he nearly holed his 9-iron and drained the 3-footer
to go to 15-under and essentially put the champagne on ice.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he cautiously two-putted his way home in even par.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time this season that the reigning PGA Senior
Tour Player of the Year has successfully defended his title. He
also did it at the PGA Seniors' Championship and the Las Vegas
Seniors Classic. This was the 19th official Senior Tour victory in
his career, tying him for seventh place with Gary Player on the
all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the wins are wonderful,'' said Irwin. ``What is
particularly pleasing is to come back to a place where you've won.
Nashawtuc is a great little course. This is one of the best events
on the Senior Tour.'' He should say so. He has finished first twice
and second once in his three appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin collects $150,000 for his victory, increasing his 1998
earnings to $2,251,750. If he continues his current success, he
could become golf's first $3 million winner. ``I was wondering when
somebody was going to mention that,'' said Irwin. ``It will be a
pretty hard chore to get to $3 million. I'll have to keep up this
level of play if I'm going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   His level of play has been spectacular. He has not been out of
the top five in 16 starts this year. His average tournament check
has been a whopping $140,734. ``I'll probably play in six, maybe
seven more tournaments,'' said Irwin, who doesn't want goals like
passing the $3 million dollar mark affecting his game.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, all he has to do is play his normal game and his
retirement fund will get even bigger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 0152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
