A0129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MFSPROCHAMPIONSHI     08-31 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MFS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANG LEAVES HAARHUIS BROKEN MAN 
</HEADLINE>
 PRO CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Just eight points of the 130 played were the
difference in the match. Michael Chang won 69, Paul Haarhuis 61
Sunday in their title battle at the MFS Pro Championships at the
Longwood Cricket Club, a 6-3, 6-4 Chang triumph.
</P>
<P>
   It was that even. Chang, the fourth seed and 22d-ranked, won his
first tournament in 13 months, since he claimed the Legg Mason
Classic in Washington. This was his third final since then and the
seventh time in eight matchups that Chang, who has overcome
tendinitis in his left wrist as well as a knee injury, has defeated
the 85th-ranked Haarhuis, who got into the tournament through a
wild card.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding factor in the match, played before 6,800, was that
Chang held his serve six times in break situations, while Chang
broke Haarhuis twice in five sets. Chang became the first American
to take the title since 1984, when Aaron Krickstein won it.
</P>
<P>
   Chang now has won 32 career titles; this was his 20th on the
hardcourt. He also grabbed a check for $45,000. Haarhuis, who was
appearing in his first final in 2 1/2 years and is known mainly for
his doubles play, earned $26,000. At the same time the players'
rankings changed _ Chang is now 20th for Monday's US Open and
Haarhuis will be in the low 60s.
</P>
<P>
   There were two break chances for Haarhuis in the fifth game of
the first set and one more in the seventh game. Then, in the second
set, there were three more, two in the second game and another in
the eighth. Chang, who has 341 wins on hardcourt, leading all
active players, held off each break point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was trying to be a little bit tougher on those
points,'' said Chang. ``Obviously, you don't want to get to that
situation, but if I'm able to go out and hit a service winner, then
all the better. It makes it easier.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh game of the first set, with the score 30-all,
Haarhuis belted a forehand up the line that landed wide, and he
followed that with a backhand into the net. That made it 4-2,
Chang. Then Chang served for the set in the ninth game, giving up
just one point while winning on an ace to the forehand side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to change that much in the second set because I
felt the first set I was just as good,'' Haarhuis said. ``I had my
chances, I created chances. I just didn't come up with the right
shots at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, Chang got past Haarhuis in the ninth game,
Haarhuis double-faulting, the shot floating quite wide. ``I just
mistimed it, I guess,'' Haarhuis said. ``I went for a deep second
serve. I guess I hit the frame with the ball.'' That made it 5-4,
Chang. In the 10th game, at 30-all, Chang socked a forehand passing
shot cross-court, and then he punched in an overhead winner for the
match.
</P>
<P>
   The two had had some practice sessions together during the week,
and Chang figured it would be a difficult matchup. One of their
previous matches was a five-setter in the 1993 Wimbledon opener, a
Chang victory.
</P>
<P>
   All the pressure was on Chang; he was the seeded player. And
there was the huge gap in rankings. But Chang didn't look at it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been in this situation before, I don't think about
rankings,'' Chang said. ``He got a wild card into this tournament,
but he normally would have been able to get straight into it. But
his wrist was hurting and he was out two or three months off that,
and that's why his ranking has dropped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt comfortable through the whole match, until I was
match-point down,'' said Haarhuis. ``He just played the big points
better. I had more break points but I didn't convert on a single
one and he converted twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we flipped a coin and it falls the other way, I would have
won. My other matches I felt he was the better player and today I
didn't feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Haarhuis and partner Jacco Eltingh defeated Chris Haggard and
Jack Waite in doubles, 6-3, 6-2, to share the winners' check of
$21,830.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 0156EDT &QL; 
