<HEADER>
A0130 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-31 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES QUESTION GORDON'S TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ The winning crew chief and the second-place owner
did not exchange any punches. And, as far as we know, there were no
reporters ``snooping around'' Jeff Gordon's Chevy Monte Carlo,
looking for a bottle of androstenedione. So at least this is not a
story of the New Hampshire International Speedway becoming the site
of a midafternoon talk show. But that's not to say the necessary
elements weren't in place Sunday. They were. You don't have to be
Oprah, Montel, Jerry, or Sally to recognize jealousy and
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   You already know that no one frisked Gordon after he won his
ninth Winston Cup race of the season, an improbable victory at the
CMT 300. Nope. NASCAR officials didn't touch the man when it was
over. But they were very interested in his tires. That's right.
Gordon has 17 top five finishes (more than anyone) and 10 straight
top five finishes (more than anyone), but it's not because of the
silver-tinted Nikes he wore as he drove his car at 127 miles per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the shoes; it was the tires.
</P>
<P>
   Tires. That's what Gordon's crew chief, Ray Evernham, and Jack
Roush _ the owner of second-place finisher Mark Martin's car _ were
talking about near the track's garages after the race. But it
wasn't the kind of talking that friends do, unless they are friends
who want to end their relationship. Evernham didn't like that Roush
went on the radio after the race and suggested that there was
something foul about his crew's tire changing. He also didn't like
it when NASCAR officials impounded his tires and would not allow
him to break down his pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to get off my race team's back,'' Evernham said
before leaving the track. ``It disgusts me that a grown man
(Roush), supposed to be that intelligent, is not paying attention.
Why do they keep trying to take wins away from my guys?''
</P>
<P>
   Roush and others couldn't understand how Gordon won this race.
We're talking about a man who immediately lost his pole and quickly
fell to 17th place. To make things worse, he noticed that his car
was ``tight.'' So his crew adjusted the air pressure in his tires
and, during a pivotal pit stop, decided to loosen it by changing
two right-side tires instead of all four. That means, late in the
race, Gordon was speeding on two good tires rather than four. He
was going just over 127 on lap 278, 22 laps from the finish. A
skeptic would say he should have been finished. If you tried
traveling at 65 m.p.h. on the Mass. Pike with two good tires, you
would find yourself in the breakdown lane, waiting for the Triple A
tow trucks. That didn't happen with Gordon. It was just the
opposite. He had the nerve to roll into victory lane with a smile _
and a flat tire.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after, the howls started to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they don't find anything, is (Roush) going to stand up
and say, `Those guys just beat us?''' Evernham said. ``Is that
what's going to happen? I don't like people screwing with the race
team. They do whatever they can to take away the feeling my guys
have in victory. When it's all said and done and they don't find
anything _ and they won't _ is he going to apologize for saying the
things he said on the radio?''
</P>
<P>
   We can tell you that there were 90,000 people here and that a
poll of the crowd may have revealed that 89,000 couldn't stand
Gordon. It would not be surprising if many people rose at 5 a.m.
and crept through hours of traffic on a two-lane road just for the
chance to boo Gordon. Two hours before the race, two men walked
outside the stadium with a huge flag that read, ``Jeff Gordon's
Crying Towel.'' Gordon says lots of fans write him letters and give
him encouragement. A few of them were here, courtesy of the Make A
Wish Foundation. The majority, we presume, watched the race on TV.
</P>
<P>
   This always happens with champions, no? The officials always
treat them better. They are always allowed to create their own
standards. They must be pumping their bodies with illegal
substances and ... pumping/deflating their tires with illegal air.
Or maybe Gordon is corking his tires. Perhaps his voice sounded
kind of funny Sunday because there was helium in his tires,
simultaneously making his car go faster and tweaking his vocal
cords.
</P>
<P>
   Really, if Roush truly wants to scale his frustration, he could
start a Dealing With Jeff Gordon Peer Group. This is a driver, only
27, who has broken many hearts on Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe that kid won another race?'' Dale Earnhardt
said. ``Two tires and away he goes. I don't know how he does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hamilton said he saw country singer Jerry Reed before the
race. ``What was his big song? `When You're Hot, You're Hot'?''
Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is hot. He is so hot that people are targeting his tires,
expecting to find something more than hot air. Gordon will tell you
that he probably shouldn't have won. Midway through it, he just
wanted to sneak in the top 10. Then he thought of the top five.
Later, he sat up in his seat and said, ``Shoot, we can win this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. It was his fifth win in his last six races. He left here
Sunday on his way talking about his next race in Darlington, S.C.
Maybe someone there will accuse him of having a gamecock in his
tires. Another theory, much more unpopular, is that Gordon is the
best at what he does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
