<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANG A POPULAR CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It runs in the family: running.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chang's 96-year-old great-grandmother in Guangzhou,
China, trots up the stairs to her fifth-floor walk-up apartment
several times a day, and might be on the tennis tour herself if she
had a better serve.
</P>
<P>
   If his grandparents hadn't run out of the People's Republic in
1949 a few steps ahead of the Mao Zedong takeover mob, Chang
wouldn't have been born in the USA and might be living in Shanghai
instead of serving tennis balls at such game rooms as Longwood
Cricket Club.
</P>
<P>
   It was Longwood Sunday where Chang reclaimed the oldest
professional tennis tournament (the MFS Pro, born the US Pro in
1927) for the natives. Most people thought MFS stood for Meddling
Foreigners' Sunroom, and couldn't remember the last time an
American won a tourney that was launched on a vacant lot in
Manhattan 71 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it was Aaron Krickstein out of Detroit, outpointing the
Argentine Jose Luis Clerc way back when a president lied about
inappropriate behavior with Iran and Nicaragua and was considered a
hero _ 1984. In fact, since the tourney went bust in New York and
relocated in The Bean in 1964, only three other US citizens have
made it all the way: Bob Lutz and Jimmy Connors, 1972 and 1973,
Eddie Dibbs in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that Bostonians don't have a broader view.
They've loved such foreign victors as Rod Laver, Bjorn Borg, and
Guillermo Vilas. But somehow the crowds all week at Longwood seemed
to be pulling for Chang, who makes road-runners seem dodo birds.
</P>
<P>
   They took him to their hearts for a couple of reasons. He is a
tiny guy with a large ticker who's had to stick up for himself
against bullies like Ivan Lendl, Stefan Edberg, and Pete Sampras,
and has done it very well, a David with racket instead of sling.
Sometimes he beat up on them by making them look like statues,
running them right out of the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   And the folks recognized him for what he's been, a genuine
champion _ French Open ruler in 1989 _ with 32 titles in his kick,
a candidate one day for the Hall of Fame, a guy who wouldn't
understand ``quit'' if he could find it in a dictionary. Chang was
a name everybody knew as Longwood and MFS struggled to run a good
tournament, worthy of Boston, after seven years of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   But aficionados also saw Chang as a sneakered replay of another
diminutive French boss, Napoleon, and wondered if he's swerving and
groping toward his own latter-day Waterloo. Napoleon burst from
exile for an 1815 comeback that didn't work. Chang, exiled from the
winner's circle for 13 months, ended his driest spell in a decade
(fading from No. 2 to 22) with his 6-3, 6-4 victory over Paul
Haarhuis Sunday, and senses comeback. But was it really?
</P>
<P>
   Too soon to tell. Only 26, Chang, like Jim Courier and others
for whom every point is a baseline war, may be battled-out. He
might be a tennis version of a game, milling prizefighter who
doesn't own a knockout punch to make shorter work of his foes, and
finds his body more susceptible to injury.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a joyful afternoon for those many who admire
Chang's first-class spunk, sportsmanship, and spirited pursuit of
the best he can be _ as well as elusive tennis balls he hunts down
like a bird dog on speed.
</P>
<P>
   He was good-natured even when he accepted one of his prizes, a
wristwatch. Isn't that the traditional retirement gift?
</P>
<P>
   However, Chang's legs, which have carried him farther, faster,
than Betty Grable's took the actress, aren't retired. That was
obvious as he made the Dutchman, the best little Haarhuis in the
Netherlands, hit too many balls.
</P>
<P>
   The customers applauded warmly as Chang talked about his
astounding French Open triumph of 1989. ``I believe God wanted me
to win that, to give the Chinese people, half a world away,
something to feel good about at the time of Tienanmen Square.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang, speaking openly about his faith, makes some
uncomfortable. Not me. He's so clearly sincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think God wanted him to win Boston?'' a woman said. ``What
about his lousy 13 months without a win?''
</P>
<P>
   Her companion answered, ``You've heard of Job, haven't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions aren't exactly Jobian for Chang. He left town with
$245,000 stuffed in his pockets, and ``new confidence for the US
Open.'' Moreover, two young women in the south stand hoisted a
sign: ``Michael _ will you marry me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some other things to do at the moment,'' he smiled
politely.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't know God's plans for the US Open, but is thankful to
have this edge on Job: Bank checks have come into use since that
time. If Chang had to carry all that money in cash, he might run
himself into a hernia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
