<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T LET RECENT WOES THROW YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The questions must have seemed strange to Nomar
Garciaparra after the day he had at the plate at Fenway Park
Sunday. Only a few people wanted to talk about his 28th home run
and the double he hit against the Anaheim Angels. Most wanted to
ask him about his 23d error of the season. Was it a sign of fatigue
or, worse, a slump?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is absolutely not, if you ask any opponent who has
seen Garciaparra perform this season. He is considered a prime
candidate for the American League's Most Valuable Player award. But
what about those who have seen his high level of play day after day
and find it painful to see him go through a blip in the field?
Garciaparra isn't too crazy about it, either.
</P>
<P>
   While his offense is going strong, Garciaparra has made six
errors in the last nine games, 10 in the last 27. How can this be?
A year ago, in winning the Rookie of the Year award, he made only
21 errors the entire season. Here are a few thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   First, let it be said he doesn't have a sore shoulder. He might
have earlier in the summer, but with his work ethic how could one
tell? He missed nearly three weeks in May because of the injury but
has played in 116 of 134 games. No one would blame him if he asked
for a day off, but you know he won't.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there's nothing wrong with his throwing mechanics. His way
of throwing over the top is difficult to execute. But until lately
he'd been right on target.
</P>
<P>
   And last, if he takes time off, who will carry the offensive
load? Since July 23, when Garciaparra and Mo Vaughn swapped spots
in the order, Garciaparra moving to cleanup, he has been on fire,
batting .478 with 11 home runs. Vaughn has hit .352 in that time,
and their success has rubbed off on John Valentin, who is making a
strong late-season surge as the No. 2 hitter. The Red Sox need
their shortstop's bat and his leadership. The rash of errors won't
help his MVP bid, but he probably doesn't care about that, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a special player,'' said Jimy Williams. The errors
are ``the way he plays,'' added the manager. ``I'm not worried
about the throws he makes. I had Tony Fernandez back in Toronto,
who used to throw balls on the run like that. He's the only other
guy that could run to that foul line or third base and then throw
back and get guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``A slump? It can happen. Balls can take a little hop at the
end. Sometimes you're thinking one way and all of a sudden the ball
moves you into an off-balance position. You don't worry about
Nomar. You know his fire. You know his work ethic. He goes out and
plays hard every day.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that Garciaparra is falling apart at the
seams. He is a student of baseball. A great hitter with power who
can run like a deer. His arm is strong. And he probably knows his
body better than the trainers or the doctors. But he is also human,
and thus susceptible to a down period entering the final month.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the errors come from trying too hard. He sets very high
standards, the kind that are almost impossible to live up to every
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you've made so many spectacular plays so early
in your career,'' said Vaughn. ``Things can get into your head.
He's just got to play the game the way he's always played the game.
I don't really think there is a problem. Still, you can't take
things for granted. As fast as you go up, you can go down just as
fast. If you don't come out on the field intent on being focused
and playing your game, it can beat you up. You have to stick with
what you know and what got you here.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra is not lacking for theories on the subject, but he
prefers to let his bat and glove do the talking. In the fourth
inning, he came to the plate as the leadoff man. The scoreboard
flashed a sign that said, ``Happy 80th Birthday Best Hitter That
Ever Lived,'' referring to Ted Williams. Garciaparra promptly hit a
home run. Maybe he thought the sign was referring to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that it felt pretty good,'' said Garciaparra of
the home run, which put him within two of his rookie season total.
``The first thing I said when I approached the dugout was, `Happy
Birthday, Ted!' It was nice to do that. He means a lot to all of
us. He's a guy who loves to hit. He loves to talk about it. You can
tell by the way he talks about it, his heart and soul are into this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   You can tell by the way Garciaparra talks, his heart and soul
are into the game, too. And throwing errors are the least of his
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern is going out there and trying to win,'' he
said. ``I'm happy with a victory, upset with a loss. There will be
ups and downs, and you have to deal with everything. Fielding
slumps? You got to battle through things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is all everybody wants. It's all we've been focused
on. If we don't believe that, we should pack up and go home right
now. You can tell by the way we play our hearts out on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra in a slump? Don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know he's a great player,'' said Angels manager Terry
Collins. ``I know he's made some errors, but he's a gamer. Those
kinds of guys grind it out. Even if they're hurt, they never admit
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I like about him is that after an error, he will
never lay back on the next ball. He will never goose a ball to
first base. He plays the game all out, every play, every day. I
like this guy as well as any of the others around, and I've got a
great one.''
</P>
<P>
   And so do the Red Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
