<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS TRADE JONES AND JELLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ When a player signs a three-year, $3 million
contract with a $500,000 signing bonus, it ensures him a
significant role with the team.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran wide receiver Brian Stablein became an exception to that
rule Sunday. He had his contract terminated in a surprising move,
after the Patriots discovered that he was an insurance policy they
didn't need.
</P>
<P>
   Stablein, one of five cuts and part of an eight-man reduction by
the Patriots to get to the NFL roster limit of 53, saw limited duty
during the exhibition games after an impressive training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Also looking for work Monday are Phil Dawson, who made three
straight field goals in place of the injured Adam Vinatieri; the
team's fourth-round draft pick, defensive tackle Leonta Rheams;
cornerback Kato Serwanga, and veteran fullback Marrio Grier.
</P>
<P>
   The team also made two trades. It dealt popular veteran
defensive tackle Mike Jones, who had been with the Patriots for
five years but wasn't expected to make the roster, to the St. Louis
Rams for a fifth-round pick in 2000, and sent receiver Dietrich
Jells, who caught two touchdown passes Saturday night against the
Eagles, to Philadelphia, also for future considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Devin Wyman (knee) joined rookie linebacker Ron
Merkerson on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But the surprise was Stablein.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the Patriots signed Stablein, they were unsure
whether Terry Glenn would return to full strength from a broken
collarbone and an injury-filled '97 season. They also thought they
might deal Vincent Brisby, who had demanded a trade because of his
falling down the depth chart, but that deal never materialized
because the Patriots were asking for at least a second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has come back strong, as evidenced by his three receptions
for 71 yards in the 24-7 exhibition win over Philadelphia. And
Brisby has been competing for a starting job with Shawn Jefferson,
though it appears he's on the short end at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The player who seemed most upset by the signing of Stablein was
Troy Brown, who felt his 47 receptions and fill-in work for the
oft-injured Glenn should be rewarded in some way. Brown, who in
another rather surprising move started Saturday night over
Jefferson and Brisby, wound up having a brilliant exhibition
season, also replacing Dave Meggett on punt returns.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also drafted Wisconsin receiver Tony Simmons in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, New England elected to go with only five receivers
and four tight ends (Ben Coates, Lovett Purnell, Rod Rutledge, and
long-snapper Mike Bartrum).
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have to pay all of Stablein's $500,000 signing
bonus but none of the remainder of the contract. They also are rid
of Jones's contract, which was for approximately $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   With Jones and Rheams gone and Wyman on IR, the Patriots will go
with eight defensive linemen: Chad Eaton, Willie McGinest, Mark
Wheeler, Henry Thomas, Chris Sullivan, Brandon Mitchell, Ferric
Collons, and rookie Greg Spires.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also kept seven linebackers: Chris Slade, Todd
Collins, Ted Johnson, Tedy Bruschi, Vernon Crawford, Bernard Russ,
and Marty Moore. The team went with six last year, but Moore
fractured a rib cage Saturday night and will miss 4-6 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are also going light at cornerback. Serwanga's
departure leaves the team with Tebucky Jones and veteran Steve
Lofton as backups to Chris Canty and Ty Law. The Patriots are also
carrying Steve Israel, who still is unable to play.
</P>
<P>
   Grier had been a special teams fixture for the past two seasons,
but he was expendable with the additions of fullbacks Tony Carter
and Chris Floyd, both of whom have performed well on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   The team also kept rookie center Jason Andersen, a seventh-round
pick from Brigham Young, giving them 10 offensive linemen. Player
personnel director Bobby Grier belives in keeping as many big guys
as possible, and in Andersen's case he's keeping a third center
behind Dave Wohlabaugh and Heath Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 19 draft picks in the last two years, 17 have been kept.
Only receiver Tony Gaiter and Rheams have been cut. Rheams should
be re-signed to the practice squad, as should Serwanga, if they
clear waivers. The five-man squad should be named by 4 this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The cutting of Dawson indicates the team is reasonably assured
that Adam Vinatieri will be able to return from a groin pull that
has sidelined him for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Management could not be reached for comment concerning the cuts,
but there may be a tweak or two of the final roster as other
players around the league clear waivers.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the Patriots will have nine new faces this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
