<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDAST-WEINKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEINKE BACK FOR OLD COLLEGE TRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When he came back for the second time,
he did what they told him. ``Sing a song,'' they said. He sang.
``Pick up the equipment,'' they said. He picked it up. ``Get
this,'' they said. He got it. With a smile on his face, laughter in
his heart, knowing that the time was coming when the upperclassmen
and veterans would listen to him. Seek his advice. Look for and
accept his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Accept it? Now they're embracing it. His career stat line says
Chris Weinke is only a sophomore, with only 13 passes thrown, seven
completed. Hardly the kind of resume a team with aspirations for
the national title would want from its starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But then you move on down the resume. First, check the birthdate
_ July 31, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   1972? That would make Chris Weinke 26 as he lines up under
center for the first time in 1998 when Florida State begins its
season against Texas A&AMP;M in Monday night's Kickoff Classic at
Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Now it makes sense, this air of confidence Seminoles coach Bobby
Bowden has when talking about his quarterback. ``Chris Weinke
doesn't scare me,'' says Bowden, who had to go to Plan B this
spring when projected starter Dan Kendra tore up his knee and was
lost for the season. ``In fact, I never felt so good about a
sophomore quarterback in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Weinke, listen to his story about why he is back at
Florida State, where he first started as a college player eight
years ago, and you would feel confident too.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to him talk about his plans, how he wants to be the next
in a series of good-to-great QBs who have come through the Florida
State system. Hear what he has to say about his decision to give up
a career in baseball and chase another in football and it all makes
sense, sounds so plausible that when Seminoles quarterback coach
Mark Richt says, ``Chris Weinke is an NFL prospect,'' it rings
true.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the 6-foot-5 inch, 225-pounder about it and he doesn't
disagree. ``It took me six years to figure out what I want to do,''
said Weinke, who spent six seasons in the Toronto Blue Jays
organization.
</P>
<P>
   One day Weinke looked in the mirror and told himself a trip to
The Show was not coming any time soon. Sure, he was 25, but instead
of being a young prospect, he was getting closer to the aging
veteran that Kevin Costner played in ``Bull Durham.''
</P>
<P>
   Each season that passed, the outcome became more obvious.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to move on to something else. Money was not a
problem. He had taken the $300,000 the Blue Jays had given him when
he signed and invested it wisely, mainly in real estate. At 25, he
was, on paper at least, a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   What did he want to do? Sure, he could move into the business
world, but he was still a kid, still wanted to play games.
Football? He had come out of high school in Minnesota as a hot-shot
quarterback everyone in the country was chasing, including Florida
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me,'' said Richt, with a smile, ``and asked about
coming back. I told him sure, but there were no guarantees he would
be a starter. He came back anyway. That showed me something, told
me something about him as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke said he had no doubts about his decision. He was coming
back to Florida State on a work-study program. He wanted to learn
how to be an NFL quarterback. Going to classes and getting a degree
were part of the overall master plan, but he came back for the
football.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden was amazed. ``Guys have left before,'' he said. ``They
say, `I want to go play baseball.' I say fine, and in two years,
they come back after meeting Mr. Curveball or something like that.
But Chris was gone six years. I didn't expect to see him back.''
</P>
<P>
   What Bowden saw was not some wide-eyed freshman. ``None of that
hoo-rah stuff works on him,'' said the coach. ``You tell him this
is the job that's got to be done and he goes out and does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke said his only concern was the physical aspect of the
game. ``Could I still do it?'' he said. ``Mentally, I knew I could
handle it. But I had questions about how I could handle the other
part. The first spring I was rusty, no question about it. But I
felt I was getting better every day. It was a whole new learning
process. I felt I could do anything they asked me to do, if I
worked hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
   At Florida State the path to success has been fairly consistent
for quarterbacks. Come in and sit for a year or two, maybe redshirt
a season, play a year of backup, and you'll get your chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kendra, a wild and crazy QB from Pennsylvania, was the next
in succession and he had two more seasons awaiting him. Weinke sat
and watched last season and was prepared to do the same this year.
</P>
<P>
   All of that changed in the spring game when Kendra went down
with a knee injury that was going to sideline him at least for the
summer and probably the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before that, I was telling myself to get ready to play,''
said Weinke.
</P>
<P>
   Kendra started on rehab and then decided he wouldn't make it
back in time for the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the job was Weinke's. So much so that Kendra is
talking about playing fullback when he comes back.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke has gone about things like a businessman. He has bonded
with his teammates, particularly his offensive linemen. He has
taken on a leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a unique situation,'' he said. ``I've been through more
than 90 percent of the sophomores. Maturity plays a major role in
my mind. I think it's important for me to be leader. I look forward
to that opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden says he is totally confident in one of the most
inexperienced quarterbacks ever to play for him. ``Let me tell you
something,'' he said. ``When you stand in that batter's box against
guys who throw 90-mile-an-hour fastballs, there's no reason to
think he can't stand in the pocket. And that's the way he has
responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M, with a better than average defense and a hunger that
comes with having fallen out of the Top 10 in recent years, will be
an indicator of what to expect from the Seminoles, and from Chris
Weinke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
