<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RESOLVE, SAME RESULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ The Revolution showed some signs of
rejuvenation in Walter Zenga's first game as coach Sunday. But they
did not have enough defensive substance to hold off the Miami
Fusion, and a 3-2 loss buried them deeper in Major League Soccer's
Eastern Conference cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Diego Serna scored the Fusion goals, including the winner in the
80th minute after the Revolution had rallied from a two-goal
deficit. Serna scored twice in the first half, and the Fusion
nearly had several more goals before the Revolution tightened their
defense in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't change anything for the second half,'' said Zenga,
who wore shorts, a short-sleeved shirt, and a baseball cap with his
trademark Spiderman logo. ``They changed on the field. They kept
possession of the ball and tried to make something better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when a new coach arrives, things can get better. But
I don't have a magic wand. Last year, I was a coach on the field.
But if I make a player play well, the credit should go to the
player, not to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, who trail Miami by 9 points for the final
Eastern playoff spot, reverted to their goal-giving ways early.
They had been outscored, 12-3, in the last three games before
Thomas Rongen was replaced by Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   Serna and Paulinho McLaren, veterans of the Colombian and
Brazilian leagues, had no trouble solving the Revolution's offside
trap in the first half. They broke through several times, thanks to
the passing of Kris Kelderman and Carlos Valderrama, easily
slipping past their markers. Central defenders Brian Dunseth and
Richard Goulooze were either too slow to react or were out of
position, and defensive midfielder Ivan McKinley struggled to keep
up.
</P>
<P>
   The Fusion mostly attacked to the Revolution's left side, with
Serna going directly at Janusz Michallik. Serna scored in the 17th
and 28th minutes, causing the Revolution defense to become more
cautious. When the Revolution offense needed another attacker,
players were wary about advancing.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution set the tone in the second half, tying the
score on Edwin Gorter's deflected drive in the 56th minute and Raul
Diaz Arce's left-footed volley in the 74th. Imad Baba had three
near-misses and Joe-Max Moore sparked the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga's substitutions 10 minutes into the second half also had a
positive effect, as the Revolution scored a minute later. But Dahir
Mohammed had just as much trouble staying with Serna as Michallik.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were without personality in the first half and I tried to
change the face of the team,'' Zenga said. ``Everyone played at 110
percent. At halftime, I said everything and nothing. They had lost,
5-1 and 6-1, and when that happens the players lose concentration
and think it doesn't matter if they lose again. I wanted to
transfer my mentality to them, because I don't like to lose, and in
the second half we changed mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, the Revolution's goalkeeper last year, alternately sat on
the bench and stood, consulting assistant coaches Sid Mazzola and
Pete Simonini. His final substitute, Jair, had a chance to tie the
score but shot high in the 81st minute.
</P>
<P>
   But though Moore had one of his best performances of the season,
the Revolution could not match the athleticism and enterprise of
Serna. On the winning goal, Serna overpowered Mohammed just inside
the penalty area, dodged a sliding tackle attempt by McKinley, then
played a one-two with Valderrama. That forced goalkeeper Ian Feuer
to commit, and Serna then kept possession in the goal area and
scored into an open net.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a difficult player to cover,'' Michallik said. ``I gave
him too much room on the first goal, and he is the kind of player
who can take advantage of it. But it was good the way we fought
back, in these conditions, on their turf.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UFdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Zenga is adjusting to life as a coach. He retired in December
after a nearly 20-year career as a goalkeeper, though he plans to
return to play for the Revolution next year. Asked during Sunday's
postgame news conference how he felt in his first game as a coach,
Zenga said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is my life. Every time I do something new in my career,
I don't win. So this is normal. I am only looking to improve the
team in the next five games.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga conducted the press conference in English but afterward
was interviewed in Italian and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Had he lost in his first game as a player, also?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a manner of speaking,'' Zenga said. ``In Italy, that
is a way of getting a point across.''
</P>
<P>
   While playing for the Italian national team, Zenga lost only
seven games in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moore had an inspired second half in one of his best
performances of the season for the Revolution, who visit the New
York/-New Jersey MetroStars Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though it was hot and it was hard to run, we worked hard,''
Moore said. ``We started stringing something together in the second
half and continued to work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little more space in the second half, I felt sharp. I
hadn't been playing as well as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the team found extra motivation in the second half,
Moore said:
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have enough motivation from the beginning,
soemthing is very wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
