<HEADER>
A0148 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BANKBOSTON-GRAHAM     08-31 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BANKBOSTON-GRAHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR FINISH MAY HAVE GRAHAM PACKING HIS BAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ It was a struggle and Lou Graham knew it.
</P>
<P>
   He had just signed his scorecard _ another 80 _ to swell his
54-hole total to 242, a gruesome 26 over par and 41 strokes behind
BankBoston Classic winner Hale Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's nightmare was a continuation of last weekend's
nightmare, which was a continuation of the previous weekend's
nightmare, which was, well, you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   These are tough times for Graham, who over an illustrious PGA
and Senior PGA Tour career has won six times, including the 1975 US
Open, and has earned more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   So Graham, who Sunday at Nashawtuc Country Club turned in his
second dead last finish in as many weeks, has gone home to
Nashville to think about his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be it,'' said Graham, who in '75 overcame an
11-stroke deficit after 36 holes and then beat John Mahaffey in a
memorable US Open playoff. ``I don't know if I'll be coming back or
not. Right now, I have no reason to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no excuses why I'm playing so poorly. Besides, people
don't want to hear excuses. I've just been terrible all year and
I'm not seeing any improvement from one week to the next. If
anything, things are just getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   So, just how bad has Graham been?
</P>
<P>
   Consider this. At Nashawtuc, he had rounds of 82, 80, and 80 and
over the 54 holes had 26 pars, 21 bogeys, four double bogeys and
only three birdies _ two of them on Sunday's back side. There were
only three rounds of 80 or better at this year's Bank Boston;
Graham had all three. And this came on the heels of last week's
Northville Long Island Classic, in which he went 27-over 243.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 Senior Tour appearances, his best round is a 74 and he has
13 rounds of 80 or better. He missed the cut in the PGA Seniors
Championship and withdrew from the Pittsburgh Classic. He hasn't
had a finish higher than 71st and his earnings are a paltry $9,279,
including the $500 he won here.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 60, was on top of his game and raking in the dough in
the late 1980s and 1990-91, before a wrist injury, which eventually
required surgery, slowed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can't use that as an excuse,'' he said, sitting in his
automobile dejectedly discussing his recent woes. ``The wrist is
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What isn't fine, though, is my game. My driving is bad, my
iron game is bad, my wedge game is bad. The only part of my game
that has been decent is my putting. Not great, but decent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the longer I play this way, the harder things become. It's
difficult enough to play this game without having to think about
your swing and what you might be doing wrong while you're in the
middle of your swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start doing that and every shot becomes work, every shot
becomes 100 percent pure effort. You can't play golf that way.''
</P>
<P>
   And no one knows that more than Graham, who Sunday bolted the
course less than 20 minutes after dropping in a 5-foot putt for a
par on his 54th hole of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to be fun, not work, and that's what it's
become,'' he said. ``When that happens, it's time to think about
other things.''
</P>
<P>
   And what, if anything, has Graham learned from this year-long
stretch of misery? ``Let me tell you, this is a very humbling
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
