<SLUG> BC-CAR-CMT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON QUIETS LOUDON CROWD WITH VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 300-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Judging from the hostile reception he got during
the driver's introduction before Sunday's Farm Aid on CMT 300 at
New Hampshire International Speedway, you would have been correct
to assume that Jeff Gordon, the two-time and defending NASCAR
Winston Cup champion, was the most scorned man at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Vilified by those critics who have struggled with the incredible
success of his meteoric Winston Cup career as driver of the No. 24
Dupont Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Gordon gained a measure of
satisfaction Sunday by turning the jeers to cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost.
</P>
<P>
   When he was introduced over the track's public address system as
the repeat winner of the Sunday's race, marking his ninth Winston
Cup triumph of the season and third overall at NHIS, Gordon was
loudly booed by those among the crowd of 90,000 who would have
preferred to have seen anyone else but Gordon soak up the glory in
Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Runner-up Mark Martin, whose car owner, Jack Roush, accused
Gordon's team of cheating and demanded that NASCAR impound the 24's
last two sets of tires, would have been the people's choice. Maybe,
even, third-place finisher John Andretti would have been treated to
a warmer reception.
</P>
<P>
   But the people were muted when Gordon scored a stunning comeback
victory to maintain his 67-point lead over Martin in the Winston
Cup championship, 3,597 to 3,530.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I wasn't winning it might be a different
reaction,'' Gordon said, when asked if winning helped insulate him
from all the booing. ``I think when you are winning, it's much
easier to let that stuff roll off your back. I've said it before,
but I'd love more than anything to have those boos, or whatever
their remarks are, to be cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have a lot of fans out there who are cheering,'' he
added. ``They tell me every week, they write me and all types of
things, and that makes you feel good about what you are doing. But
when you are winning, you don't pay as much attention to those
types of things (booing). Actually, I think it's inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inspiring to the team and myself and everybody to
go out there and win and do it more. It almost fires us up.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Gordon submitted an inspired effort Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who become the first Winston Cup driver to win from the
pole position at NHIS, richly deserved every penny of his $205,400
payday after he got hung out to dry by the single-file draft on a
restart and stumbled from second all the way to 17th on Lap 84.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a pinball,'' Gordon said. ``Those guys were just
using me up. There was no way you could get back to the inside.
Everybody was looking for that, especially on those restarts. I
would go down in the corner and drive in easy, but I would lose the
front end or slide the back in. Once you got wide, you were in big
trouble. On fresh tires, we just had trouble trying to keep the
thing on the bottom of the racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, nevertheless, fought his way back into the Top 10 on Lap
136, got into Top 5 with 100 laps to go and, after pitting under
caution on Lap 233, got some quick pit work from his Rainbow
Warriors on a two-tire stop that enabled him to emerge from the
pits with a lead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a furious challenge from Martin and Andretti, Gordon
never surrendered the point in leading the final 67 laps. The fact
Gordon managed to stretch his lead over cars with four fresh tires
_ in a car that had just two fresh right-side tires _ prompted
Roush's suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping short of calling upon NASCAR to have Kenneth Starr
mount an investigation, Roush charged that Gordon's crew chief, Ray
Evernham, illegally had tampered with the tire when he adjusted the
air pressure on the winning pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we did put something in the tire,'' said Evernham, who
expressed his digust at Roush's allegations. ``We put in air.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was all it took to deflate any hopes any driver had of
beating Gordon to Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a pattern this year,'' said Gordon, who will be
eligible for another $1 million Winston No Bull 5 bonus in the next
race at Darlington, S.C. ``We've been getting stomped the first
two-thirds of the race and the last third, Ray and my pit crew pull
me out. I don't know what the deal is. Other than a few races, we
really haven't been the dominant car. Of course, you look at today,
with the circumstances where I got knocked back, we pretty much
fought our way back all day long. You look at a guy like Jeff
Burton (the repeat winner of the July 11 Jiffy Lube 300 who
finished fifth) and it took him 25 laps to get to the front. It
took us a lot longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just amazing the way the races are coming down and the
way we're winning races today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 0222EDT &QL; 
