<SLUG> BC-CAR-CMT300-PITSTOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIT STOP PIVOTAL FOR GORDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Eight-point-two. Another Jeff Gordon Winston Cup
win took nearly three hours but turned on 8.2 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Evernham once again made the call and Gordon and the Rainbow
Warrior team once again ran with the call and made the crew chief
look like the Red Auerbach of the racing world.
</P>
<P>
   There were 67 laps left in the Farm Aid on CMT 300 at New
Hampshire International Speedway Sunday and coach Evernham called
for his team to put two tires on Gordon's car for the sprint to the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his rivals put on four tires, which would give their
cars more grip for the stretch run, and others took on two.
Evernham wanted to gain position on the track. He figured the car
might handle even better with only two new tires.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon went into the pits in fifth place. His team put on the
two tires and filled his car up with gas in 8.2 seconds. He came
out of the pits in first.
</P>
<P>
   And when the race was over Gordon had held off Mark Martin and
all other contenders and was soon in Victory Lane celebrating his
sixth win in his last eight races.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors joined him there. They put on their Winston Cup
baseball hats for one team photo. Changed into their CMT hats for
another. Then their DuPont Automotive Finish hats and their Pepsi
hats.
</P>
<P>
   And when Gordon and Evernham moved on to a press conference,
several of the Warriors took the long walk back to the end of pit
row to clean up. Their uniform shirts tied around their waists,
giving way to Refuse to Lose tees, they loaded up carts and folded
chairs and broke down computers.
</P>
<P>
   A pickup-load of their tires were gone by now _ NASCAR officials
had commandeered them to check them out _ and most of their
competitors long since had cleared out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can check out anything they want,'' said Andy
Papathanassiou, a onetime Stanford football player and now in
charge of the guys who go over the wall each Sunday for Gordon's
team. ``Until they do a psychological examination of Jeff Gordon,
they're not going to find the secret of our success.''
</P>
<P>
   In the press conference Evernham and Gordon took turns touting
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the track, Papathanassiou, too, talked team. He talked of
year-round workouts and lifting and practices for the pit guys.
Talked of drowning out crowds and cars and going about business in
the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff is a tremendous talent,'' Papathanassiou said. ``The way
things work for us, all sides reinforce the others. We know we have
a good car and Jeff knows he can drive it hard. If the car and
driver are good, we don't want to be backing it up in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be a good pit crew and be the worst part of this team
and I don't want to be the worst part of anything,'' he said. ``I
don't want just the driver or the car taking this team to victory,
I want to contribute to this team and the other guys do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   They are guys like jackman Barry Muse and front tire carrier
Jeff Knight. Rear tire carrier Darren Jolly and front tire changer
Shane Parsnow. Like rear tire changer Mike Trower and gas man Mike
Belden and catch can man Chris Anderson. Like Patrick Donahue of
South Portland, Maine, who works behind the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we're taking fifth-place cars to wins,'' Gordon
said. ``It's just unbelievable. That's just chemistry. You keep
hearing everybody talk about team chemistry, and that's what that
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver. Car. Coach. The players in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about a two-tire stop is you have half as much time
to beat someone out and you still need the same distance to
leapfrog someone on the track,'' Papathanassious said.
</P>
<P>
   The 8.2 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good,'' he said. ``Real good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
