<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST WILL CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Saturday's running of the $750,000
Travers Stakes at Saratoga raised more questions than it answered
about the 3-year-old division. When Coronado's Quest held on grimly
to repulse Victory Gallop by a nose, what had been a two-horse race
between Real Quiet and Victory Gallop for the sophomore
championship became a three-horse affair.
</P>
<P>
   Which should be the front-runner? How about Real Quiet, who won
the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness and came within a nose of
winning the Triple Crown in the Belmont Stakes? His negatives are
that he is on the shelf with sore stifles and is not expected to
race again until the Malibu Stakes at Santa Anita Dec. 26. Should
it be Victory Gallop, second in the Derby and Preakness and the one
who denied Real Quiet the Famed Triad? Working against him is the
fact that he has lost the Haskell and the Travers to Coronado's
Quest. And what of Coronado's Quest, who has won five straight
stakes since April 11? He did not compete in the Triple Crown, when
horses build strong reputations.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, trainer Bob Baffert was successful in doing with
Silver Charm, who also won the Derby and Preakness but lost the
Belmont by a short margin to Touch Gold, what he is trying to do
with Real Quiet this season. He held Silver Charm out until the
Malibu and his strategy worked. His horse won the coveted Eclipse
Award as Touch Gold ran against older horses in the Breeders' Cup
Classic and fared poorly, running ninth and last. The fact that
Silver Charm ran second in the Malibu, and never faced an older
horse all year, did not keep him from winning the hardware.
</P>
<P>
   However, Real Quiet is not as charismatic as Silver Charm and is
not nearly as popular. For him to get the votes that Silver Charm
did, Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop would have to fail against
older horses. So, they probably will continue to run against each
other until they have to play their cards against their elders at
the Breeders' Cup at Churchill Downs Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest, off at 7-5 ($4.90 to win) under Mike Smith,
became deeply entrenched in the championship fray when he hit the
wire in 2:03 2/5 for the 1 1/4-mile Travers. Victory Gallop, the
6-5 choice, and Alex Solis were an inch away, and Raffie's Majesty,
an 11-1 shot ridden by Jorge Chavez, was just a nose behind Victory
Gallop in as a thrilling a finish as imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great race, but it was probably better for TV than it
was for me,'' said Shug McGaughey, trainer of Coronado's Quest, who
was emotionally drained after the race. ``We have three options
now. We could go in the Super Derby ($500,000, 10 furlongs, Sept.
27 at Louisiana Downs). We could go in the Woodward ($500,000, 9
furlongs, Sept. 19 at Belmont, but against older horses). Or, we
could go in the Pegasus ($500,000, 9 furlongs, Sept. 25 at
Meadowlands, restricted to 3-year-olds). We just want to do what's
best to get our horse to the Breeders' Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   A former bad boy, Coronado's Quest was an absolute gentleman
Saturday. Had he wasted any energy on antisocial behavior, he would
not have been able to prevail, considering his scant margin of
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coronado's Quest is doing fine,'' said McGaughey. ``He'll get
a couple of days off, then we'll probably get the tack back on him
( &UR; tomorrow &LR; ). He'll let me know in the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop deserves points for consistency. He had been
first or second in his last 11 races (six wins, five seconds) and
the most likely scenario is that he and Coronado's Quest will stage
another battle in the Super Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thankful that he ran so well,'' said Elliot Walden,
who trains Victory Gallop. ``He ran a great race once again. It
would have been nice to have seen him come out on top. We are
looking toward the Super Derby, but nothing is etched in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Awesome Again, one of the top older horses in the country,
captured the $300,000 Saratoga Breeders' Cup Handicap Sunday.
Patiently ridden by Pat Day, Awesome Again took over when ready
passing the eighth-pole and drew off under a hand ride to a
3-length tally. The 1-5 shot ($2.50 to win), toured the 1 1/4 miles
in 2:03.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
