 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2477 - August 31, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To publish any of the special ``separate buy'' articles listed
below, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81. e-mail: nyt &LR; calva.net
NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2477 -- August 31, 1998 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. THERE IS A WAY OUT OF THE RUSSIAN CRISIS ``Today they
(President Yeltsin and his entourage) seem to be waking up to
what's happening,'' writes Mikhail Gorbachev, former leader of the
Soviet Union and Nobel Peace Prize winner. ``Continuing to cling to
power while closing their eyes and plugging their ears could be
self-defeating. The appointment of Chernomyrdin as acting prime
minister is therefore likely to signal the beginning of the process
of transferring power to an heir apparent. We are witnessing
Yeltsin's political sunset.'' 1,000 words. 
____________________________________________________________________
__ 2. IMAGINING RUSSIA WITHOUT YELTSIN Five years ago, the
so-called reformers running Russia concluded that three things were
essential for economic growth : a stable exchange rate, low
inflation and the re-election of Boris Yeltsin. The challenge was
to achieve each as quickly as possible, after which the economic
transformation would be largely secured. But it was a trap. By
Grigory Yavlinsky. 800 words. (Economist Grigory Yavlinsky is
leader of the Yabloko Party, a democratic reform party in Russia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
``YELTSIN IS AT THE END OF HIS ROPE'' - ALEXANDER
</P>
<P>
   LEBED INTERVIEW The bitterly besieged Boris Yeltsin had no
choice but to bring Viktor Chernomyrdin back as prime minister,
according to retired General Alexander Lebed, even though
Chernomyrdin bears partial blame for Russia's current crisis.
Lebed, the former hero of the Afghan war and now governor of the
Krasnoyarsk district, says that Chernomyrdin will be hard-pressed
to avoid an explosion of popular wrath as matters go from bad to
worse. Still, he adds, ``Our only hope lies in the very man who got
us into this mess.'' From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. Q&AMP;A format.
(English translation available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
HUN SEN STAGES AN ELECTION Cambodia's new leader, Hun Sen, got the
world's endorsement for an election that was neither free nor fair.
The voting would not have happened at all if not for the cajoling
of foreign diplomats and how the world will treat Cambodia now is
not yet settled. The international community pushed Hun Sen to
adopt the trappings of democracy, but even those may evaporate
completely, once the world turns away. By Tina Rosenberg. From The
New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   5. SPIELBERG BASHES INTELLECTUALS Steven Spielberg's film
``Saving Private Ryan'' has one false and creepy note, writes
Nicholas Lemann. From SLATE. 500 words. 6. TWO MEN IN A TUB Being
an astronaut is glamorous, exciting and dangerous. It can also be
tedious and undignified, particularly if you're preparing to build
the International Space Station. By Mary Roach. From Discover.
1,500 words + photos. (Also available in Spanish.) 7. RING-A-ROSES
Sisters, the closest of friends, share a bond that transcends time,
notes Kirsten Chapman, the youngest of three sisters. When her
sister Sonja died suddenly at 36, her world shrank. But, Chapman
discovered with wonder, the magic circle does survive. From New
America News Service. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
SEARCHING FOR ROOTS WE NEVER HAD The search for family roots is a
common phenomenon. People want to see where they came from in order
to understand and appreciate themselves better. But sometimes the
world has changed so rapidly that the real roots and old family
connections no longer exist. By Herbert Stein. From SLATE. 1,000
words.
_____________________________________________________________ 9.
MARTHA STEWART 'ASKMARTHA' COLUMNS :
</P>
<P>
   A. HOW DO TERRARIUMS WORK? How to make a self-contained
ecosystem or 'terrarium' (a miniature indoor garden in a sealed,
transparent container.) 1,000 words + photo . B. GROWING AND
COOKING PEPPERS : Since Columbus took both hot and sweet peppers
back to Spain from America 500 years ago, they have found their way
into cooking all over the world. Tips + recipes. 1,500 words +
photo. C. WATER GARDENS : If you have ever spent time gazing into a
lake, exploring tidepools along the coast or watching a stream
tumble over pebbles and stones, you know how calming and relaxing
water can be. To enjoy that experience every day, add a water
garden to your home. (It's easier than you might think, explains
Martha Stewart.) 1,000 words + photo.
</P>
<P>
   _____________________________________________________________
10. HURRICANES AND GLOBAL WARMING Global warming as a result of
increasing levels of carbon dioxide (CO2) in the atmosphere is one
of the major environmental challenges today. If, as some experts
predict, hurricanes become more frequent as a result of global
warming, they will themselves contribute to transferring more CO2
into the atmosphere from the oceans. By Eleanor Lawrence. Nature
News Service. 600 words. (N/A France and Spain.) Embargo 1800 GMT
Wednesday, Sept. 2.
_____________________________________________________________
