A0525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     08-31 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Sept. 6.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ROUND ROCK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Michelle Huneven. Vintage Contemporaries, $13.
</P>
<P>
   This lively tale focuses on two men, both recovering alcoholics,
living at a halfway house in rural California, and the woman
violinist with whom they both become involved. Their struggle
implies that spiritual healing requires facing past truths and then
getting on with life, one day at a time. Last year in the Book
Review, Valerie Sayers called this an ``immensely likable first
novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW WE LIVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Sherwin B. Nuland. Vintage, $14.
</P>
<P>
   Using the voice of both teacher and storyteller, a surgeon
attempts the daunting task of explaining how the human body works
and what happens when something goes wrong. His account, originally
published in hardcover as  &UR; THE WISDOM OF THE BODY &LR; , is full of
``fascinating tales of surgical pitched battle'' told ''in forceful
and terse prose,'' F. Gonzalez-Crussi wrote here in 1997. In the
dreamlike  &UR; JUDITH'S PAVILION: THE HAUNTING MEMORIES OF A
NEUROSURGEON &LR; , by Marc Flitter (Warner, $12), a physician recalls
his many successes and failures, and the struggles of the patients
whose lives have transformed him. The writing ``is as elegant and
delicate as his surgery,'' Abraham Verghese said here last year.
```Judith's Pavilion' lingers with the reader long after the book
is over.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONCE A DANCER ... &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Allegra Kent. St. Martin's, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   The renowned ballerina, who flourished under the wing of George
Balanchine, surveys her eccentric life and career and tells how she
managed to cap off each success with a compensating failure. Last
year our reviewer, Joan Acocella, found much of this memoir to be
``witty, fast-paced, full of deft omissions, wonderful
catchings-up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIVING AFTER MIDNIGHT: A NOVELLA AND STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Lee K. Abbott. Ohio State University, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   The characters who populate this collection of short fiction
tend to be ordinary Americans who share a hot-wired pop-culture
awareness and a fascination with the magic and mysteries of
language. ``The quality of these stories is uniformly high,''
George Garrett wrote here in 1991. ``The level of excellence is
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A COUNTRY OF STRANGERS: BLACKS AND WHITES IN AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David K. Shipler. Vintage, $15.
</P>
<P>
   The author, a Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist and former
correspondent for The New York Times, talks to a lot of black and
white Americans and discovers an uneasy racial divide in which each
side knows precious little about the other. The result is an
``engaged and engaging'' book that ``provides something that
statistics alone will not: the rich fabric of the everyday workings
of race in this nation,'' K. Anthony Appiah said here in 1997. A
former federal judge examines the interaction between racial
injustice and the law dating to Colonial times in  &UR; SHADES OF
FREEDOM: RACIAL POLITICS AND PRESUMPTIONS OF THE AMERICAN LEGAL
PROCESS &LR; , by A. Leon Higginbotham Jr. (Oxford University, $15.95),
finding that the legal system perpetuates the notion of inferiority
even today. This ``is a carefully researched and impressively
documented book,'' Yale Kamisar wrote in these pages in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABOUT YVONNE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Donna Masini. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   A professor at New York University who suspects her husband is
having an affair is gradually driven to the edge of insanity by her
jealous fantasies. Last year in the Book Review, Maggie Garb called
this a ``haunting novel of sexual obsession'' and a fresh critique
of contemporary Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEGGAR AND THE PROFESSOR: A SIXTEENTH-CENTURY FAMILY SAGA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Emmanuel Le Roy Ladurie. University of Chicago, $15.
</P>
<P>
   By drawing on the correspondence and memoirs of three
generations of an upwardly mobile Swiss family in the 16th century,
this kaleidoscopic history adds color and texture to our
understanding of the Renaissance and Reformation. The author is
``an erudite and elegant chronicler of early modern times,'' Eugen
Weber said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OFF MINOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By John Harvey. Owl/Holt, $11.
</P>
<P>
   In this moody British police procedural, Inspector Charlie
Resnick tracks down a child rapist and killer in the grubby
industrial city of Nottingham. Harvey reveals ``the devastating
impact of murder on everyone it touches,'' Marilyn Stasio wrote
here in 1992. ``No one escapes the glare of the author's insights
or the warmth of his compassion for the pathetic frailties of human
nature.'' An earlier mystery featuring the jazz-loving Inspector
Resnick,  &UR; CUTTING EDGE &LR;  ($11), revolves around a baffling series of
surgical mutilations of staff members at a teaching hospital in the
Midlands. ``Harvey creates characters of astonishing psychological
diversity,'' Stasio said in these pages in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOD OF IMPERTINENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Sten Nadolny. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   The hero of this comic fable is Hermes, the Greek god of
thieves, who is freed after 2,000 years chained to a volcano and
sent on a mission to the brave new world of french fries, golf and
channel surfing. His adventures make for whimsical ``post-modernist
beach reading,'' Bill Christophersen wrote here in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
