<SLUG> BC-MATT-DAMON-IN-ROUNDERS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MATT DAMON, FAME MEANS PUTTING A LID ON PRIVATE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Matt Damon and Gretchen Mol in a scene
from ``Rounders.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Matt Damon is confronting the first road-block on his fast track
to fame.
 &HT;    He's one of the hottest young stars in Hollywood _ currently
basking in the box-office success of ``Saving Private Ryan'' _ not
to mention one of the youngest Academy Award winners ever. But he's
paying a price for success as he struggles to keep the media out of
his private life.
 &HT;    Last year, Damon, 27, was unabashedly and publicly affectionate
with co-star and gal pal Minnie Driver as ``Good Will Hunting''
soared to success and earned him an Oscar for Best Screenplay along
with his co-writing buddy Ben Affleck. Then, he told Oprah and a
few million viewers about the sudden end of their relationship. The
backlash taught him a lesson about the public eye.
 &HT;    In a hotel room in Beverly Hills, Damon pushes aside the plate
of raw vegetables which would have been his lunch. He's ready to
talk about his latest film, ``Rounders,'' in which he co-stars with
Edward Norton as a brilliant young card shark. But, first, he tries
to explain why he isn't talking about his love life anymore.
 &HT;    Has his frequent companion Winona Ryder stolen his heart? Could
marriage be on the horizon in his future? The strikingly boyish
actor shrugs, ``I've made the decision not to discuss personal
stuff except with my family and friends.
 &HT;    ``That's a big shift for me because I was raised to be very open
with everyone,'' he says. ``If you were close-mouthed, it usually
meant you had some problem that was getting in the way of your
personal growth. I'd read interviews with celebrities who would
suddenly clam up, and I kind of frowned on it. But, I've begun to
realize that everything I say can come back to haunt me so I can't
do it anymore.''
 &HT;    Damon visibly relaxes as the conversation turns to
``Rounders,''directed by John Dahl (1993's ``Red Rock West'' and
1994's ``The Last Seduction''), in which he and Norton are a couple
of hustlers who've made their living fleecing unsuspecting
opponents in the high-stakes underground poker clubs of New York
City.
 &HT;    Norton ends up behind bars. Damon uses his winnings to put
himself through law school _ but loses his future tuition in one
fateful game with a Russian poker-club owner played by John
Malkovich and gives up cards, determined to reform his life.
 &HT;    His resolve weakens when Norton is released from prison and
lures him back to the high-stakes world where an unpaid gambling
debt can be a dangerous liability.
 &HT;    Damon and Norton both spent a fair amount of time cruising poker
clubs in New York to develop their skills. ``I found out it's a lot
different than playing with friends where you might lose 40 bucks
on a bad night,'' Damon says. ``We saw some high stakes games, and
I realized that poker is never contingent on luck, it's always
about skill. I went to clubs and watched games that were too rich
for me.''
 &HT;    But Damon can only shrug when he reflects on how he's won big in
a tough business after turning in respectable but hardly
scene-stealing performances in his early screen years in ``School
Ties'' (1992) and ``Geronimo: An American Legend'' (1993). Even in
``Courage Under Fire'' (1996), Damon's bravura cameo on screen with
Meg Ryan was largely ignored by critics.
 &HT;    Then came ``Good Will Hunting,'' the lead in Francis Ford
Coppola's ``The Rainmaker'' (1997) and his Oscar.
 &HT;    His rise to the top was fueled by a drive reminiscent of the guy
he plays in ``Rounders.'' ``My character has a passion for poker,
and I felt a pretty clear parallel with my own passion for
acting,'' Damon smiles.
 &HT;    ``I dropped out of college and went to L.A. with my backpack to
try to make it in Hollywood,'' he says. ``I felt compelled to do it
even though it sounds like I was totally naive. This guy was happy
playing poker. I was happy acting.
 &HT;    ``Believe me, I lost count of the people who told me I was
making a big mistake. But I would have done it even if I hadn't
scored with `Goodwill Hunting.'''
 &HT;    In fact, Damon's passion for acting is reflected in his
commitment to the strict and, ultimately, debilitating diet regimen
he adopted while filming ``Courage Under Fire.'' ``I lost 41
pounds, and I didn't have any supervision at all. I did it on my
own,'' he recalls.
 &HT;    ``I thought my character needed to look almost gaunt. I really
thought it would help my performance,'' Damon says.
``Unfortunately, I nearly ruined my health. I was running 12 miles
a day, drinking pots of coffee, and simply not eating. I just
didn't waver.
 &HT;    ``When I tried to put the weight back on at the end of the
film,'' he continues, ``my stomach was a mess because I started
eating everything I could get my hands on _ things you'd never put
on the same plate like yogurt and clams. It was a nightmare. I had
to take a lot of medication and, eventually, I went back home to
Boston to recover.''
 &HT;    That was a low-point for Damon who didn't realize that, in a few
months, he'd be riding the crest of success of ``Goodwill
Hunting.'' ``Ben Affleck and I were worried that we might not be
able to act in the film,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``There was a lot of talk about other actors and we absolutely
refused. Then, I was at home on medication trying to gain weight
and I looked at the reviews for `Courage Under Fire,''' Damon says,
``and I barely got a mention. That was pretty heart-breaking. I was
really feeling down.''
 &HT;    Now, Damon has again lost weight for ``The Talented Mr. Ripley''
directed by Anthony Minghella. He's playing the title role in the
film based on Patricia Highsmith's mystery novel.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to lose about 15 pounds, because I just want to look
perfect and refined in those tailored suits that Mr. Ripley
wears,'' he says. ``Then, I'm going to lose another 15 pounds or so
when I do `All The Pretty Horses,' with Billy Bob Thornton because
I'll play a guy who's just gotten out of a Mexican prison.
 &HT;    ``But my life has changed since `Courage Under Fire,''' he adds.
``I have a nutritionist with me on the set everyday, and my hotel
room is a lot bigger.''
 &HT;    In an interview while on location in Italy, filming ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley,'' Damon reveals he'll be joined by Affleck to
work on their next script.
 &HT;    ``People keep asking if Ben and I are feeling the pressure to
duplicate `Goodwill Hunting,''' Damon says. ``I honestly don't
think we do, otherwise we'd never write another script. We'll just
give it our best shot and not worry.''
 &HT;    They will also return to the screen again together later this
year in Kevin Smith's much anticipated ``Dogma.'' ``Ben and I play
angels,'' he reveals. ``I'm the Angel of Death. Basically, we're
both trying to get back into heaven.''
 &HT;    Damon pauses to consider whether there's a downside to fame,
besides the sacrifice of his privacy. ``It's hard to grumble about
anything,'' he says finally. ``But I've been on the road almost
constantly for almost a year-and-a-half making films. I don't even
have an apartment.
 &HT;    ``I carry my clothes and stuff in a couple of duffle bags. I
have some furniture and odds and ends in storage in New Jersey, but
I'm not sure I ever want to see it again,'' Damon says. ``Who needs
an old ratty couch that I bought five years ago?
 &HT;    ``I don't even have my CD collection anymore. I gave up the car
I was leasing, because I never had time to drive it and that had
the CD player. So I gave my CDs to a friend, and he's playing them
while I'm working.''
 &HT;    Then he adds with that now famous grin, ``And you thought being
a star meant you had everything.''
 c.1998 Jeanne Wolf  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
