<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINDY-CRAWFORD-IN-TV-SPECIAL-ON-SEX-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINDY CRAWFORD AND ABC GRAB ATTENTION WITH SPECIAL ON SEX 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Cindy Crawford 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Sex with Cindy Crawford.''
 &HT;    Sounds enticing doesn't it. ABC sure thinks so, for that's what
they've titled an hour-long special hosted by the supermodel and
slated to air Sept. 22 at 10:00 p.m. (EST).
 &HT;    ``That title must have come from some marketing genius at ABC,''
Crawford jokes. ``At the start it was kind of a joke, or just the
working title, and it stuck.
 &HT;    ``Normally, I don't like things that are titillating for the
sake of being titillating, but in this instance the title perfectly
describes what the show is about,'' she says. ``It worked, and we
couldn't think of anything else.''
 &HT;    The special marks the first result of a three-year development
deal Crawford recently signed with ABC. Chatting from her rented
vacation home in the Hamptons on Long Island, N.Y., the supermodel
explains that she didn't want to kick off her relationship with the
network by starring in a sitcom, TV movie or talk show.
 &HT;    She felt that a special would serve as a more appropriate
``get-to-know-you'' endeavor. Once she and ABC executives agreed to
team for a special, they next pondered a worthwhile subject.
 &HT;    ``I told them what I was interested in and what didn't interest
me. Like always happens in conversation, it kept coming back to
sex,'' Crawford says, knowing a thing or two about the topic.
 &HT;    Ironically, she explores a different facet of sex in the current
issue of Playboy in a 14-page spread shot by celebrity photographer
Herb Ritts.
 &HT;    ``I'm not a journalist or a sex expert, but I'm curious about
sex,'' Crawford says.
 &HT;    Brainstorming sessions generated a number of the topics explored
in ``Sex'' _ among them monogamy, AIDS, physical attraction, teens
and sex and sex in the media _ as well as the venues for discussion
of the selected topics. Crawford particularly welcomed the idea of
visiting a block party in Madison, Wis., and leading a conversation
with some of the town's residents.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to know what people were really doing, thinking and
talking about behind closed doors in Middle America,'' Crawford
says. ``The people in this cul de sac range from a young
interracial couple to a couple that's been married 55 years, from a
guy who just had an affair through the Internet, to a lesbian
couple.
 &HT;    ``The diversity of these people was amazing, and they were very
open and candid. So that's where we start.
 &HT;    ``The whole idea is that talking about sex is crucial to people
having healthier sex lives and relationships,'' Crawford says. ``It
opens up that box of `It's been 50 years since the Kinsey Report.
How far have we come?' ''
 &HT;    Crawford walked away with the impression that it's far easier to
have sex than to discuss it. Her ``Sex'' experience got her
thinking about her own sexual issues, as well.
 &HT;    ``My mother was always open about talking to me about sex, which
was interesting because her mother was not as open,'' she says.
``It let me talk with my then-boyfriend, now-husband (Rande
Gerber), too. I remember saying to him, `Are men really like that?'
or `Do guys really think this?'
 &HT;    ``I also got to explore issues that mattered to me, like sex
education. So many parents think that if you teach a child about
condoms they'll go have sex, and that's ridiculous,'' Crawford
says. ``Those kinds of things were my reasons for doing the
special.''
 &HT;    Crawford laughs. ``Now, why would ABC want me in there? Well,
look at our title,'' she says. ``It's a place, though, where I
don't mind being exploited, because I'm proud of the show.
 &HT;    ``A kid might not watch Barbara Walters if she hosted the show,
but that kid might watch me. That's fine. Not everyone reads The
Wall Street Journal or New York Times for their news, if you know
what I mean.
 &HT;    ``Maybe we're the show for those people who don't read the
Times, but we're giving you some good information and we do it
without being preachy,'' she says.
 &HT;    Crawford, as practically the whole planet knows, transformed
herself from a model with a mole into Cindy, Inc. She hosted MTV's
``House of Style'' fashion program for six years, starred in and
produced two best-selling exercise videos, wrote a makeup guide,
hosted several talk shows and award programs and starred in the
1995 action film ``Fair Game.''
 &HT;    After so many years in the spotlight, one can't help but wonder
what Crawford thinks she does for a living?
 &HT;    ``I'm a model,'' she says unequivocally. In fact, she remains an
in-demand cover girl and one of Revlon's most ubiquitous faces in
its print and TV ads. ``That's the engine that drives everything
else I do.
 &HT;    ``I still have so much momentum from the modeling. Maybe it
hasn't made the world a better place, but I think there's a place
for beauty in the world,'' Crawford says.
 &HT;    ``If it makes someone happy to look at a pretty picture of me,
that alone has value. Hopefully, people got something useful out of
the exercise videos I did, and, hopefully, they'll get something
out of the `Sex' special, too.''
 &HT;    Whether or not Crawford acts again remains to be seen. Though
she had a cameo on ``3rd Rock from the Sun'' not long ago, ``Fair
Game'' made her just that for critics who skewered her performance
as a lawyer on the run from bad guys.
 &HT;    ``I knew with that movie that I was opening myself up to
criticism,'' she says softly. ``It was fun to do once because,
honestly, who doesn't want to do a movie?
 &HT;    ``I understand the allure of acting, but I don't think it's
something that's as natural to me as modeling,'' Crawford says.
``If Martin Scorsese called and asked if I wanted to do a movie
with him, and if he said he'd mentor me and nurture me, then sure,
I'd do some more acting.
 &HT;    ``Otherwise, in order for me to make the acting work I'd have to
abandon everything else in my life right now, and I don't want it
that much.''
 &HT;    Newlywed Crawford would much rather spend time with Gerber, a
long time friend with whom Crawford became romantically involved
not long after the end of her tabloid-heaven marriage to actor
Richard Gere.
 &HT;    ``I was definitely open to remarrying and my desire for a
family, for children, has never left,'' she says. ``To me, being
married is the ideal way of doing it. I'm not saying it was easy to
get there, but I was never anti-marriage.
 &HT;    ``With Rande, he's just a nice guy. In my life there are so many
people who are fascinating and diverse, but it's nice to have
someone who's a solid person, who supports me and wants me to be
happy,'' Crawford says.
 &HT;    ``He also has his own life and is very confident. In the end,
he's a nice guy. I don't know how else to put it.''
 &HT;    Mother Nature, it's mentioned to Crawford, catches up to all her
creatures. Crawford recently turned 32, ancient in modeling circles
and approaching lateness in the game for would-be moms.
 &HT;    Growing older, Crawford admits, concerns her.
 &HT;    ``I'm curious about it,'' she says. ``The other day I was
obsessing that my knees were starting to droop. I'm a typical woman
in that I have to find faults in myself where no one else could
possibly notice anything.
 &HT;    ``In terms of a family, I thought I'd have one by now. If that's
in the cards, great, and if it's not, I guess it's not,'' she says.
 &HT;    ``So, I'm not afraid of aging. I hope I'll be strong about it. I
hope I'll be busy enough doing other things that I won't be
obsessing about it every minute.''
 &HT;    Crawford laughs nervously.
 &HT;    ``But I don't know,'' she says. ``I don't know.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
