<SLUG> BC-ASHLEY-JUDD-IN-SIMON-BIRCH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHLEY JUDD MAKING NAME FOR HERSELF, NO LONGER JUST A JUDD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Ashley Judd with Ian Michael Smith in a
scene from ``Simon Birch.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    This Judd's for you.
 &HT;    Ashley Judd is beautiful, smart and she has kept her sense of
humor. That hasn't always been easy.
 &HT;    She remembers growing up a Judd, not one of The Judds. ``I
remember when I was a teen-ager and my mother and sister were on
the road in concert. I would flip over to David Letterman where our
family was his nightly fodder,'' the actress says, sipping tea.
 &HT;    She winces and recalls, ``Dave would say, `You know my fantasy
is to date the Judds. Hey, I bet you didn't know that the Judds
have another daughter, but she can't sing. And she's really ugly
and they keep her in the basement. Every once in awhile they throw
her down a canned ham.'''
 &HT;    ``It was all this crazy stuff,'' Judd says, admitting her
feelings were hurt for another reason. ``As a teen-ager, I had a
crush on the guy, which just made it worse!''
 &HT;    Judd, 30, is having the last laugh. She's gorgeous. It's true
she can't sing, but she has gotten rave reviews for acting in ``A
Time to Kill'' (1996), ``Heat'' (1995), ``Kiss the Girls'' (1997),
``Smoke'' (1995) and ``Ruby in Paradise'' (1993).
 &HT;    She doesn't live in the basement and doesn't like canned ham.
``Water and mushroom soup. Those are two of the keys to a good
life,'' Judd says.
 &HT;    Like it or not, her star power shines through the minute she
waltzes into suite at the Four Seasons Hotel in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    Mark Steven Johnson, her director in the new ``Simon Birch''
marvels that she is ``vivacious, strong and sexy.'' Womens'
magazines praise her ``feisty spirit.'' Interview Magazine dubs her
``a young Elizabeth Taylor.'' The movie opens Sept. 11.
 &HT;    Judd plays a single mother in ``Simon Birch,'' Disney's twist on
John Irving's novel ``A Prayer for Owen Meany.'' Her role is
Rebecca Wenteworth, the mother of pre teen Joe played by Joseph
Mazzello. Her son's best friend is Simon Birch, the smallest boy
ever born in one town. He's played by Ian Michael Smith, a
12-year-old Chicago native with Morquio's Syndrome, a rare genetic
disorder that causes dwarfism.
 &HT;    Judd says, ``I couldn't put the script down. It really touched
me. It's so real and dear, because it doesn't shy away from the
tragedies in life. Yet, it finds a certain calm and peace with what
God has created.''
 &HT;    Working with Smith was ``a joy,'' Judd says. ``He is a magical
child. He's free, pure and alive.''
 &HT;    Judd appreciates the free part. During her Hollywood tenure, she
hasn't had much down time. She laughs and says, ``At times, I was
so busy it got to be about sheer survival, but I like a
challenge.''
 &HT;    Judd is pretty good in survival. Born in Los Angeles, she grew
up poor in Kentucky and Nashville, attending 12 schools in 13
years. Before her mother Naomi and sister Wynonna became the
singing superstars The Judds, the three struggled to live on a
nurse's paycheck.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes when we were growing up, we were so poor that our
heritage was the only thing we had,'' Judd says, mentioning the
family's mantra at the time. ``Mama would say, `Kids, pour more
water in the soup. Better days are coming.'''
 &HT;    Did she feel deprived? ``What hurt me was seeing my mother not
being able to provide for us and how that made her feel,'' Judd
says, adding the upshot was the sisters grew even closer.
 &HT;    She laughs at the memories.
 &HT;    ``Wynonna remembers picking on me a lot and says she feels bad
now,'' Judd says. ``There's no reason for her to feel bad. I picked
on her, too.'' She lapses into mock anguish and adds, ``She would
sit on me and it hurt.''
 &HT;    And the younger sister's revenge? ``The only thing I could do is
sock Wy in the boob. It was my only course of defense,'' Judd says,
quickly stating, ``Really, we were more of a team than we were
enemies.''
 &HT;    At 14, Wy allowed Ashley to drive. ``We had a '57 Chevy. I
remember one day, I was waving to a farmer in his field and ran off
the road into a fence. Wynonna was always cool about things like
that. She wouldn't tell on me for driving the car if I didn't tell
on her for returning our canned goods to get spending money,'' Judd
says.
 &HT;    When Judd was 15, her mother and sister hit it big as country
music superstars. Ashley insists she never felt left out.
 &HT;    ``It's funny because as kids, I was encouraged to read and Wy
was encouraged to sing. We were never competitive, because we had
individual interests. It was like one kid plays soccer and the
other is on the debate team. I don't know any more simple way to
explain it.''
 &HT;    ``As grown ups, people just assume we're competitive, but what
we hope to articulate is that your identity is not about what you
do. It's about who you are.''
 &HT;    When the Judds were on the road, Ashley lived with her father.
During summers, she logged time with her mother and sister on the
road. ``I was paid $10 an hour to sweep out the tour bus,'' she
says.
 &HT;    After graduating from the University of Kentucky, Naomi Judd
thought her book smart daughter would be an anthropologist.
Surprise, surprise. Judd broke the news one day that she wanted to
act. ``Now my mother says I was an actress since I was a girl, but
I say, `No, no, no, remember mother. Acting is telling the
truth!'''
 &HT;    Judd is nothing but truthful about her experience in Hollywood.
She has gotten a slew of press for breakups with actor Matthew
McConaughey (her co-star in ``A Time to Kill'') and, more recently,
singer Michael Bolton. ``I just try to stay completely ignorant of
what the press is saying about my love life,'' she says, shrugging.
``I live my life the way I want to live it.''
 &HT;    Judd reveals that her personal life includes traveling around
the country to watch her favorite basketball team, the Kentucky
Wildcats. Lately there hasn't been much time for hobbies since Judd
has become one of the hardest working women in show biz.
 &HT;    She just wrapped the drama ``Eye of the Beholder,'' due out next
year. She also shows up next year in the thriller ``Double
Jeopardy.''
 &HT;    These days Judd is on Hollywood's A list. Maybe one of the
reasons is that she is able to hold her own with the likes of
Morgan Freeman, Robert De Niro and Al Pacino, to name a few past
co-stars.
 &HT;    Is Judd ever nervous around these masters?
 &HT;    ``I laugh now. When I did `Heat,' I brought my wire-haired Jack
Russell Terrier named Goat to the set. The first time I met Al
Pacino, Goat ran into the guy's bathroom and Al came out holding
the dog and saying, `Is anyone missing something?'''
 &HT;    ``He put the dog down and she ran at his feet. This made poor Al
bump into a garbage can. What an introduction!'' Judd says.
 &HT;    After such heady moments, Judd will return to the family
homestead to regroup. She is very close with her mother and
sisters. ``My mother and I agree to disagree, and it's lovely. I
don't think parents and children can ever resolve all their
differences.''
 &HT;    As for her sister, well, no one is punching the other in the
boob anymore. Judd loves playing aunt to Wy's son and daughter. ``I
love getting on the floor and playing with the kids,'' she says.
``I do cannonball dives head first into Wy's pool to make them
laugh. I love it more than they do.''
 &HT;    But does she sing them to sleep? At least Letterman got one
right.
 &HT;    ``I probably sing fine,'' Judd says, laughing. ``But I don't
care enough to want to find out.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
