<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSEANNE-IN-HER-NEW-TV-TALK-SHOW-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSEANNE JOINS RANKS OF TV TALK-SHOW HOSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Roseanne posing for her new talk show 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1998 TV Guide (Canada)  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Watch out, Rosie, Oprah and Sally! Roseanne is coming to host
talk-show television.
 &HT;    Expectations are high for ``The Roseanne Show.'' If it's a hit,
the actress-turned-gabber can expect to rake in somewhere in the
vicinity of $50 million a year.
 &HT;    Come Sept. 14, Roseanne's syndicated daily show will be aired by
King World Productions. And it's anyone's guess exactly what will
air. Roseanne, you see, is sort of vague about that.
 &HT;    Earlier this year, she poked fun at her image while hawking the
show. ``I am the most qualified person ever to host a talk show,''
she declared. ``I've got five kids by three different men ... I
came from a trailer park where I was a Jew passing as a Mormon ...
My brother and sister are both homosexual ... I have multiple
personalities, several of whom don't even know they're famous!''
 &HT;    This from a woman who had had it with television. She abandoned
her acclaimed sitcom ``Roseanne'' with a few last potshots at ABC,
at people who worked with her and Hollywood in general.
 &HT;    She even manufactured a sour send-off for the May 1997 series
finale, exploding the wacky, much-maligned winning-the-lottery
plot. In a quick, desultory voice-over, Roseanne Conner reported
that the episodes of the last season were nothing more than the sad
fantasies of a wife who had lost her husband.
 &HT;    In post production, Roseanne killed off Dan (John Goodman), just
as the final episode sentimentally celebrated the bonds of family.
Yet, for all her criticism about the industry and those who work
therein, she tried to swing a deal for a new series, sending her
character off into the Las Vegas desert, and complained when ABC
balked.
 &HT;    She high-tailed it to New York, playing the Wicked Witch of the
West in ``The Wizard of Oz'' on stage, saying she based her
performance on serial killer Ted Bundy. Despite all evidence to the
contrary, the legendarily prickly comic had not burned every bridge
in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    This was made apparent when it was announced that she had signed
for the talk show _ before ``Roseanne'' even officially died and
went to reruns.
 &HT;    Trouble is, no one has any idea which of her personalities will
show up on the new set. Although the show has had the luxury of
more than a year of pre production, no one had seen a second of
test footage a month before the debut.
 &HT;    When the series was introduced to critics this summer, instead
of screening a sampling of the show, a video bio of Roseanne was
unveiled, recalling her past glories as if she were a head of
state.
 &HT;    Los Angeles Times critic Howard Rosenberg's praise of her old
show was loftily cited _ though it wasn't mentioned, for obvious
reasons, that when Rosenberg panned a series starring her
then-husband Tom Arnold, Roseanne retaliated with a blistering fax.
 &HT;    The press conference that followed didn't unveil a Roseanne much
interested in talking. A simple question about what qualities she
admired and disliked about other talk shows and how that would be
reflected in her show was met with sarcastic reticence.
 &HT;    ``What are you asking me, really?'' she demanded. ``What do you
want to know?''
 &HT;    As specific as Roseanne got was, ``It's kind of a little bit of
everybody, a little bit of everything, it's not just _ you know,
we'll have a little bit like `Oprah' and a little bit like `Rosie'
and little bit like blah blah blah.''
 &HT;    Entertainment Weekly shuddered at her performance, forecasting
another possible trainwreck like ``The Chevy Chase Show'' or ``The
Magic Hour.'' In a follow-up interview, Roseanne scarcely managed
to assuage any fears.
 &HT;    Asked how or if she planned to bring the uncondescending,
blue-collar sensibility of her sitcom to her talk show, she
replies, ``I don't know what you're talking about.''
 &HT;    Roseanne said she hoped to incorporate recurring comic
characters, and suggested that her show would be original in a
derivative sort of way.
 &HT;    ``I had the same concerns with the sitcom,'' she says. ``We'll
have a different format _ you can't reinvent the talk show, but you
don't have to do the same thing everyone else does.''
 &HT;    She still declined to elaborate how she would employ what she
has seen on other shows. ``On the `Roseanne' show, we used every
sitcom as an inspiration,'' she says. ``Everything can teach you
something.''
 &HT;    Yet she declined to cite even one specific example, except to
say her new series wouldn't emulate late-night talk shows. ``I
don't like those,'' she adds. ``I can't stay up that late.''
 &HT;    Roseanne saved her biggest chunk of enthusiasm for her show's
set. ``It's just incredible,'' she exults. ``There's nothing like
it. My show `Saturday Night Special,' a short-lived late-night show
on Fox, had a unique set. I'm really into sets.
 &HT;    ``This one's like a house, a Victorian house,'' she continues.
``It's on a turntable, with three sets, and each one is a room.
We'll rotate the set on each segment.
 &HT;    ``One is a garden, filled with roses, another is the kitchen,
and the other is the living room. It's very Victorian, it's very
feminine. A desk is something I didn't want to do. I wanted to do
something feminine in the kitchen, which is the female center of
the home.''
 &HT;    And how would the set come into play in the talk-show format?
``We'll have guys in G-strings help prune the garden,'' Roseanne
says. ``In the kitchen, we'll have supermodels eating pie. I'd like
to have a pie-eating contest. We'll talk about food, women and
food. We'll have household hints.
 &HT;    ``We'll go to all three places with every guest,'' she
continues, correcting herself. ``It's not going to be set by Show
One. We'll do whatever works, we'll keep working on it. We know it
won't be as great as the show will be in the second or third year.
We're trying to downplay all the hype.''
 &HT;    As for the kind of guests she hoped to book, Roseanne was vague.
``We are going to talk to people who have something to say,'' she
suggests, ``who will offer us something unique.
 &HT;    ``There are a lot of people in this world and this country who
have inspired hope and higher things in people. They've done it
themelves, they've gotten themselves from a low point to a high
point,'' Roseanne says. ``I just want people to entertain me _ I'm
really an average viewer, with the same sensibilty.''
 &HT;    Roseanne concedes that there will be inevitable bugs to work
out. ``People have to see it before anything can be decided,'' she
says. ``I don't make art for critics, I make it for people. Without
people, nothing can develop. It wasn't until the third year that I
really thought `Roseanne' hit its stride.''
 &HT;    The comic says she spent the past year traveling to Hawaii, the
Virgin Islands and New York with her family, away from the
tabloids, which routinely kept readers abreast of her antics while
her sitcom rode atop the ratings. She's bracing herself for a new
round of salacious reporting.
 &HT;    ``I know that it's coming,'' she says. ``I'm trying to ignore
it, to stay centered. It's tough when you're a target. But now I'm
more mature, and I can handle it far better.
 &HT;    ``Also,'' she adds, ``I'll have a daily voice to respond to
them.'' Roseanne says that her young son Buck _ whom she had with
her third husband, Ben Thomas, from whom she split last year _ has
been an inspiration.
 &HT;    ``He's actually a great help,'' she says. ``He saw me on TV on
`Roseanne,' then pointed to me and said, `You're Roseanne!' The
pilot was on again recently, and in it, John Goodman had short
hair. He said, `It's Mom and Dad!'
 &HT;    ``He thought John was Ben. He thinks everyone's parents (are) on
TV, and in his reality, they are.''
 c.1998 TV Guide (Canada)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is a senior writer for TV Guide Canada.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
