<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Lost in (air) space
 &HT;    (For immediate release)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   McGwire, Sosa, Clinton, Lewinsky, Yeltsin, Diana _ who cares?
</P>
<P>
   My current news interest is absorbed by a weather balloon. It
has defied the air forces and commercial airlines of at least four
nations, including at least one military assault.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, it had been afloat for one week, launched Aug. 24
near Saskatoon in western Canada to measure ozone levels. It wasn't
supposed to drift away but it did, on a northeast course.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it all so remarkable is that it is floating around up
there somewhere near 35,000 feet with 1,000 rounds of cannon fire
pumped into it near Newfoundland on Thursday by two Canadian CF-18
fighter planes, and still it continues to drift _ over Canada, over
the Atlantic, over Iceland, over Norway and, now, over Russian air
space.
</P>
<P>
   There was a report that British fighters downed it, but that was
denied by London, as well as proven wrong by radar, which tracked
it as far as Bear Island in the Barents Sea north of Norway. When
asked why the CF-18s had not fired missiles at it, a Canadian Air
Force spokesperson said he did not think Canadians would have
``appreciated having a missile blowing over their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   And so The Balloon That Wouldn't Die floats on.
</P>
<P>
   One tries to draw a comparison between adventurer Steve
Fossett's doomed-by-lightning balloon flight and this one, and you
really can't, because it's all unfathomable to the lay person.
</P>
<P>
   Question: How long will it take for enough helium to leak out
through 1,000 shell holes in a 25-story-high weather balloon before
it falls to earth? Or will it require a missile or two to put down
this monster of a windbag, said to be the length of five football
fields?
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Canadian, U.S., British and Norwegian air forces
have been following the balloon, and trans-Atlantic commercial
flights have either been diverted or delayed because the balloon
began to intrude on the normal flight lanes between Europe and
North America.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I've grown weary of all those other stories about
presidents and princesses and home run hitters. The runaway balloon
is different, and I think the entire world should be looking up as
this story unfolds, instead of looking down at those others.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear to be another in a string of bad-luck launches
by both U.S. and Canadian space agencies. Two launches from
Florida's Cape Canaveral last month exploded shortly after leaving
the launch pad, and the runaway balloon was a joint project of the
Canadian Space Agency and several environmental and space research
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economic loss of the balloon and any embarrassment
that results from it, something good can come of this. Whatever it
is that makes the balloon so resistant to weather, weapons _ and
leaks _ I want to have put into my auto tires, have my trousers
made of, my roof covered with and my atomic waste wrapped in.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, any similarities in this week's meeting in Russia
between Bill Clinton and Boris Yeltsin, and an out-of-control bag
of wind floating above them, are purely coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
