<HEADER>
A0591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX     08-31 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Mourning the passing of a conservative
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Supreme Court Justice Lewis Powell, who died last week,
was one of the notable conservatives on the bench in the 1970s and
'80s. He helped to sustain affirmative action, ruled anti-abortion
laws an unconstitutional invasion of privacy and carefully policed
the line of church-state separation.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, conservative.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of just how far to the right the political
boundaries have been dragged since Powell left the court in 1987 _
a pull that had begun in deadly earnest with Ronald Reagan's
election as president _ that few of the conservatives on today's
court would be caught dead within shouting distance of any of those
rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet President Richard Nixon correctly understood Powell as a
conservative when he persuaded the Virginia attorney to take a
Supreme Court position Powell had earlier twice ducked.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to imagine Chief Justice William Rehnquist or
Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia forswearing the
ideological absolutes that Powell shunned. Powell's conservatism,
in its prudence and respect for judicial stability, was far more
profound than the judicial bomb-throwing the current court's
reactionary activists try to pass off as legal conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, recognizing the Constitution as dynamic rather than
hidebound, searched for the fine legal lines that would equally
accommodate pressing social needs and prevent excesses in their
name. Thus his crucial ruling in the Bakke case that barred rigid
racial quotas but allowed race to be taken into account for
university admissions.
</P>
<P>
   A corporate lawyer for most of his career, Powell usually took
business's side in civil cases, and he was only infrequently among
the court's liberals on law-and-order issues. He found some
church-state separations extruded beyond constitutional support,
but he took the distinction seriously, again unlike most titular
conservatives these days.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was what has become a rarity in today's noisy crowd of
rightward dogmatists _ an open-minded conservative. The
intellectual habit continued into his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   A steady supporter of capital punishment on the bench, Powell
turned later against execution on the practical grounds that the
uncertainties in the process would in time bring the judicial
system into discredit. And he concluded that his make-or-break vote
had been wrongly cast in sustaining state laws against sodomy.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for liberals, we'd still be singing ``God Save the
Queen,'' but a long campaign of denigration has so defamed and
distorted the term that candidates now delegitimize opponents with
the dismissive ``Too liberal for...(fill in your state or town).''
And liberals demean themselves by ducking the label in favor of the
weaselly ``progressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans will no longer speak, as is proper, of the
Democratic Party but use instead the truncated, sneering ``Democrat
Party,'' and ideological pressure groups have made ``conservatism''
narrow and doctrinaire.
</P>
<P>
   When we let our political language be stunted, we let our
political options be stunted. That is exactly of the aim of the
forces that are doing the stunting.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
