<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, September 1, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Summer vacation is all gone
and as usual, the list of ``things to do this summer'' that I made
in a fit of spring optimism, has not been addressed. I'm thinking
it can't hurt to look it over now since it too late to do anything
about it. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ This is my week, folks. I'm going to catch myself
a home-run ball, and I'm going to keep it. For me. Until someone
offers me a billion dollars for it. And then I'll sell it. (Minor,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ Voters often elect the wrong people. Usually this
is only a matter of opinion. Occasionally it's irrefutable.
Democracy is not perfect. The election last week of a dead Oklahoma
woman to a spot in the Democratic runoff for U.S. Senate seems a
pretty clear case of the democratic system gone awry. (Lane,
Daytona Beach News-Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WIGGINS-COLUMN _ My birthday gift to you? I want to give you
back some of your memories, Dad. Here, my recollections of you and
me through the years: (memories follow). (Wiggins, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GUSHEE-COLUMN _ Monday, August 31, is the first anniversary of
Princess Diana's birthday in eternity. That is a pious phrase long
used by Christian faithful to describe the day a saint died. To be
sure, Diana struggled much, knew great pain and was, in many ways,
a good and gracious person. But she is not likely to be a saint.
The remarkable relationship between the troubled princess and her
adoring public is more complicated. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
