<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Body language is easily read by ex-inlaw
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. Sharon and I are not related; we just have
matching last names because we used to be married to brothers - but
now we're not. We haven't been married to anybody in a long time
which could explain the conversation we had the other night in
front of a particularly revolting television movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hating this show, right?'' Sharon asks as she fumbles
around on her end of the sofa for the remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not loving it,'' I mumble trying to be polite just in case
she's not yet totally grossed out watching an unshaven bully knock
his witless wife into the wall. ``How could you tell?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Body language,'' she says as she flips to the weather channel
and asks if that's okay. I tell her it's fine and we watch the
pregnant weather lady point beyond her belly to a storm in Alabama.
``Omigosh,'' I hear Sharon mutter, ``it's raining again in Texas.''
I grunt.
</P>
<P>
   We watch in silence for a few minutes as someone explains what
next Tuesday's jet stream is going to do to the weather in North
Carolina. We don't really care but there's nothing else on. It's
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``What body language?'' I ask. ``What'd I do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You folded your arms across your chest which means you're
blocking everything out. You're easy to read.'' I tell her I'm not
so sure I like folks to know what I'm thinking by the way I tilt my
head or bend my elbow, and the reason my arms were flopped over my
chest was because my hands were going to sleep hanging off the side
of the couch. She's not buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time you did this was when I asked you if you thought
you'd ever get married again. You wiggled your eyes, bit your lip,
and folded your arms. And then you lied and said, 'Maybe.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I lie about a thing like that?'' I ask and she says
it's because I don't want to have to explain why I've been single
for 20 years. I remind her she's been single longer than I have.
She doesn't respond and for the next few minutes we share a
comfortable silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to rain next Wednesday,'' she announces
matter-of-factly. Then she gets to what's really on her mind.
``Aren't you tired of living alone?'' I roll my head to one side to
get a better look at her. Is she serious or are we acting out a
psychological experiment?
</P>
<P>
   She looks sincere. ``Sometimes,'' I confess honestly, ``when the
plumbing breaks or the power goes off in a storm, I think maybe
it'd be nice not to be alone. But then I remind myself how tough it
would be for anyone to put up with my odd habits. Three o'clock
yesterday morning I was down in the basement ironing. A couple of
days ago I sat with my feet in the desk drawer for six hours -
thinking. Husbands aren't geared to this kind of behavior. Besides,
they're always hungry.'' She nods tacit agreement.
</P>
<P>
   We study the ceiling for a couple of minutes before I ask: ``How
about you? Do you think you'd ever get married again?''
</P>
<P>
   She changes the subject at warp speed to a new diet she's trying
and begins babbling about carbohydrates and grapefruit juice. I ask
her if that's a thinly disguised yes. No answer so we turn back to
the television. Sharon picks up the remote and begins flipping
channels. The weather hasn't changed and the bum is still beating
his wife. She hits the power button and the screen goes dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at it this way,'' she chuckles, ``no more arguments over
who controls the remote.'' I remind her we never had to deal with
that issue because remotes hadn't even been invented while we were
still married. ``Ummm,'' is all she has to say about that.
</P>
<P>
   Body language forgotten, we confess. Yeah. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only this time,'' she says, ``it's going to be somebody who
wants me big time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what you mean,'' I assure her. ``Anything good on at
ten?''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes for
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service. Her e-mail address is:
eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
