<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Throw back home-run ball? Not me, pal
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To heck with Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire and what's-his-name
from the Mariners. McGruff, I think his name is. No, that's the big
brown crime dog.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey. Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not going to get sidetracked with discussions about our
old friend Moises Alou, although, geez, wouldn't it be nice to see
him in a Marlins uniform right about now?
</P>
<P>
   And while I'm sitting here denouncing all that was once near and
dear to my heart, to heck with this job. They can take it and,
well, you've heard that song, even if it is really bad country
music.
</P>
<P>
   To heck with those little coupons I've been sending in to
Florida's Pre-Paid College Program. Going, going, gone.
</P>
<P>
   This is my week, folks.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to catch myself a home-run ball, and I'm going to keep
it.
</P>
<P>
   For me. Until someone offers me a billion dollars for it.
</P>
<P>
   And then I'll sell it.
</P>
<P>
   And the best part is, because I am a liberal newspaper person
and an outspoken Clinton supporter, I won't even have an ounce of
guilt about keeping the ball, then selling it to the highest
bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I don't know if you've been paying attention to all this,
so allow me to brief you. Just a tiny little lesson, I promise.
</P>
<P>
   There is this incredible home run race going on in professional
baseball right now. Two guys _ Sammy and Mark _ are primed to break
an old baseball record, the one established in 1961 when Roger
Maris hit 61 home runs in just one season, post-season play
excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this race has done a couple of things, not the least of
which is fill up ballparks around the country and make owners a lot
of money.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to my point.
</P>
<P>
   I've invested a lot of emotion and time and sweat equity in this
game. Just thinking about last October exhausts me.
</P>
<P>
   I deserve a little payback, don't ya think?
</P>
<P>
   Now, as luck would have it, I am scheduled to watch McGwire play
on Wednesday and Sosa on Friday, an enviable baseball-viewing week
made possible because I have no other real life.
</P>
<P>
   But, first, please understand something. As fans go, I really am
a nobody. I mean, I could sit through an entire no-hitter and never
know the difference. But all this home run hullaballoo does beg the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Just how greedy are we fans?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Pretty darn greedy.
</P>
<P>
   Why, just the other day I ran into a fellow baseball fan in the
hall at work. And we were standing there, procrastinating, when he
asked me that very question. ``I'd throw it back,'' I said, aghast.
</P>
<P>
   But then, I got to thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Those guys make a lot of money. Those guys get winters off.
Those guys have special people to massage their sore muscles. Those
guys probably don't even do their own laundry.
</P>
<P>
   So. Cooperstown, Schmooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   I'm keeping the Spalding.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if Sammy Sosa is sweet.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if Mark McGwire is the only human being on Earth
with biceps bigger than my thighs.
</P>
<P>
   Mine, mine, mine.
</P>
<P>
   And I don't care if I have to knock over some little kid to get
it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
