<HEADER>
A0610 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN01-COX     08-31 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories all point to this: I love you, Dad
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service-Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy 79th, Dad!
</P>
<P>
   My visits with you and mom have been precious to me these past
few years. I've especially enjoyed our talks about your childhood
recollections, even as your short-term memory fades.
</P>
<P>
   When I confessed recently that I wished we always could have
talked so easily, you told me how, as a child, kids teased you
about your curly red hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since then,'' you said softly, ``I've been shy.''
</P>
<P>
   That explains a lot. While I was shy of you, you were shy of me.
How nice to be beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   My birthday gift to you? I want to give you back some of your
memories, Dad. Here, my recollections of you and me through the
years:
</P>
<P>
   1944. I am 2. There is a war going on and you are wearing a
white sailor suit, bouncing me on your foot while holding my hands
and singing about a merry-go-round (boop-boop) that broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, perhaps a year later, you lift me, and I touch
your face, so unlike Mom's. ``Stickers,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   You are stationed in Brooklyn in 1945, and on a walk across a
street, you and mom hold my hands and swing me upsa-daisy onto the
sidewalk, a thrilling, weightless sensation at the moment of
alighting.
</P>
<P>
   A cloud goes by. We are in your friend's small yellow airplane,
flying over Vero Beach. When we land, Mom is on the ground right
where we left her, waving. Or is she shaking her fist?
</P>
<P>
   You keep finding pennies in my ear. This is hard to understand.
Your friends from the naval base also find pennies in my ear. Your
friends drink a beverage called Jax Beer. Much later, as a teen in
Gainesville, I learn that this is the worst beer ever brewed.
</P>
<P>
   Age 5. The string of the kite is paid out and you hand me the
stick and I stagger forward with the pull of the wind. You give a
dime to a kid who races to the store on his bicycle to buy more
twine. This is living.
</P>
<P>
   I have a little brother now and as we walk through the
impossibly technicolor carnival midway, the barkers call you by
name. ``Hey Red! Over here, Red! Whadda ya say Red, three throws
for a dime, Red.''
</P>
<P>
   To me, this is as amazing as an ear full of pennies. ``Daddy,
how do all those men know you?''
</P>
<P>
   These were the days of nicknames: Red, Whitey, Blackie, Shorty,
Fatso, Curly, Baldie and Slim.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1947, and we live on a sandy road in Jacksonville. I can
see you stopping at the driveway to let me ride the running board
the last 20 feet. What were you, crazy? (I got that expression, by
the way, from you. You never said mean things to anybody, Dad. At
moments of exasperation, you might explode with ``What are you,
crazy?'')
</P>
<P>
   I can see you walking on your hands across the floor, change and
keys raining from your pockets. I spend hours learning to walk on
my hands, wanting to be like you.
</P>
<P>
   During your engineering studies at the University of Florida, I
can recall watching you use a French curve to draw a big swoopy
design that looked something like crescent moon with a medallion at
the point. This was to be on the cover of the premier issue of The
Florida Engineer, a magazine that you founded and edited.
</P>
<P>
   I remember driving with you. You always drove into the deepest
puddles, Dad, so we could see the splash. And when we drove by
ponds or lakes, we would ask you how deep the water was and you
would say, ``How the heck do I know?''
</P>
<P>
   But Dad, you knew everything.
</P>
<P>
   You are Mr. Science. You informed me that ice skates don't skate
on ice but on a thin film of water melted by the friction of the
blade. When I studied Morse code for my Scouting badge, you helped
me practice.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Scouting. Dad, you had never been in the woods in your life,
and yet you signed on as Scoutmaster and won the Scoutmaster's fire
building contest right off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when you freed up that vine at Itchetucknee Springs so
the Scouts could take turns playing Tarzan over the ravine, our
bottoms grazing the tree tops below? Do you remember how when it
was your turn, you sailed higher than anybody else and just kept
going when the vine parted?
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember plunging 30 feet and breaking your pelvis, and
how a bunch of terrified 12-year-olds carried you to the truck?
Watching you disappear into those trees was the worst moment of my
life, Dad.
</P>
<P>
   What were you, crazy?
</P>
<P>
   But, oh, were you fun, Dad! I guess it was about 1954 when we
saw the teeter-totter acrobats on Ed Sullivan, and you built us a
teeter-totter and taught us to do forward flips and back flips
until Bernie Bostick missed the mattress and sprained his ankle.
Mom had some choice words.
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday when I was about 16, you came home from a neighbor's
house with beer on your breath and I ratted you out to Mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie,'' Mom says, ``your father will drink beer, he just
won't buy it.'' You never smoked and you never swore, Dad. Even
when the television antenna smashed your thumb, you said only,
``Ow.''
</P>
<P>
   I liked that.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be honest, Dad, you didn't talk to be talking. You were
blunt. But all I had to do was mention a problem with algebra or my
motorcycle, and you were there, sleeves rolled up, brain engaged,
teaching, fixing, advising.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the driving lesson in the white 1951 Hudson, when I
drove 3 miles until we smelled something burning. Turns out, if you
leave the parking brake engaged, the brake lining will burn. What
was I, crazy? you asked.
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember why, in my senior year, I couldn't bring myself
to look at you for three days? You said I could use the car and,
after I made plans, you said you needed the car. On the fourth day
of my sulk, the new Elvis album mysteriously appeared on my bed. I
burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the first time I felt grown up around you. I was 20
and in the Navy. It was the day after Marilyn Monroe's death, so
that would make it Aug. 6, 1962 and you flew to California on
business near my base. We had dinner, and talked like real people.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when we said our good-byes we shook hands, this being
before the manly hug was invented.
</P>
<P>
   But I've saved my fondest memory for last, Dad.
</P>
<P>
   I am about 9, sick with a high fever, and you come into my room
and feel my head, asking if there is anything you can do. I mention
comic books _ Donald Duck and Superman _ and you head for the
drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   That was just what dads do, and I gave it no thought. But here
is the part I will never forget: Mom is holding my hand, and she
cautions me, ``Be careful of what you ask for, Ronnie.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you asked your father for the moon, he would go out and get
the tallest ladder he could find.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny how something like that stays with you, huh, Dad?
</P>
<P>
   Your loving son,
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
