<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0616 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-WRESTLING-SCHOOL0     08-31 2448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WRESTLING-SCHOOL01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oof! Wham! Slam! Wrestling wannabes pin their hopes on learning
the ropes
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service-Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   After he finishes his 4 a.m. to 1 p.m. shift, Publix stock clerk
Jay Cintron goes to his home in Lantana, changes out of his
uniform, gets dressed in his workout clothes and continues pursuing
his dream. He wants more than anything to be a professional
wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   He's dead serious about this goal, to the point that he's chosen
his signature wrestling move (``I think I'll use the sleeper hold.
I like to put guys to sleep.'') and his future stage name: Puerto
Rican Prince Papa Jay. Seems that back in the rough neighborhood in
the Bronx where he grew up, he always greeted friends and teachers
with, ``Hey, what's up, Pops?,'' so everyone called him Papa Jay.
</P>
<P>
   He added the rest for flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be Puerto Rican Kid Papa Jay, but I got a little
bit older, so I changed it to Prince,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   To further his wrestling dreams, the 21-year-old has spent $100
a month since December to attend sessions once a week at a local
school run by a former professional wrestler. At his home every day
after work, he carefully follows a training regimen that starts
with 50 pushups and finishes with dumbbell curls.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to psyche himself up and toughen his resolve, he tops it
off by whacking himself in the head with a piece of sheet metal.
</P>
<P>
   The number of whacks depends on how he feels that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it until it hurts,'' he says matter-of-factly. ``Usually
about three or four times.''
</P>
<P>
   The move is pure testosterone. In the movies, Rocky Balboa
pounded sides of beef with his fists. On the football field,
linebackers get ready with thunderous head butts. Cintron simply
has his own method, involving a solid sheet of aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense. After all, he's only about 5-foot-8 and 207
pounds; a lot of the guys he grapples with at wrestling school run
about 250 to 300 pounds. The sheet metal regimen, he reasons, is
good practice for learning how to take a blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds crazy, I know,'' he admits. ``But I'd rather hit
myself first and know what the pain is like before I hit someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Cintron is part of a growing throng hoping for a future in the
pro wrestling arena.
</P>
<P>
   Every Sunday morning, he and about a dozen other guys in their
late teens and 20s make their way to World Gym in Delray Beach to
attend Flex Armstrong's Pro Wrestling World Do-Jo, a school for
wannabe wrestlers. Some are former college or high school athletes.
Most are blue-collar guys working regular jobs but angling for more
money and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, wrestling schools' popularity has soared
nationwide, mainly because the sport has come such a long way since
the days when guys like Gorgeous George would pull their oversized
briefs over their guts and 'rassle around.
</P>
<P>
   The two main wrestling groups _ World Championship Wrestling and
the World Wrestling Federation _ grapple for a pool of money
estimated at more than $1 billion a year from pay-per-view and
merchandising alone. More than 30 million tune in weekly to watch
WCW and WWF matches, shows that regularly draw the top cable and
pay-per-view ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Monday's show at the Miami Arena has been sold out for
weeks. So has the Nov. 2 show at the new arena in Fort Lauderdale,
says WCW marketing director Michael Weber.
</P>
<P>
   In every town _ whether it's a basketball town like Chicago or a
hockey haunt like Hartford _ there are screaming legions waiting to
see their favorites. Doesn't matter whether it's 7-footer Kevin
Nash or Bill Goldberg, who is wrestling's biggest sensation since
Terry ``Hollywood'' Hogan (formerly ``Hulk'' Hogan) or ``Macho
Man'' Randy Savage.
</P>
<P>
   With every month, the sport wades deeper into the mainstream. In
July, NBA stars Karl Malone and Dennis Rodman mixed it up with WCW
superstars. Two weeks ago it was, of all people, Jay Leno who
``defeated'' Hogan in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict that in the next five years, the money will be
equivalent to what's being earned in the NFL,'' says Weber. Former
NFL players already dominate the sport: Goldberg, Kim Bokamper and
``Chief Wahoo'' McDaniels all played before jumping in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Or there may come a time when NFL players will be clamoring to
make wrestling money.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong understands his students' thirst for the limelight and
the big paydays. He was one of them once. After wrestling in the
Army at Fort Benning in Georgia, Armstrong _ whose real name is
Flex Armstrong (he won't reveal his birth name ``for professional
reasons'') _ played a little semi-pro football and did some
powerlifting.
</P>
<P>
   A friend invited him to try out at a wrestling camp, and he did
well. After about six months of training, he wandered over to a
World Wrestling Federation show and was invited to star in one of
the undercard bouts after a wrestler didn't show. He did well
enough to later join the WWF circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the guys are big fans and come from all walks of
life,'' says Armstrong, 29. ``The guy who eventually became the
Ultimate Warrior in the WWF was a chiropractor in Scottsdale, Ariz.
Now he's a multimillionaire. It's all about money and the love of
the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   So, tucked in a corner of the cavernous 60,000-square-foot gym,
away from the yuppies running on treadmills and the body builders
pumping free weights, Armstrong's students spend the better part of
four hours bouncing against the homemade ring's ropes, slamming to
the barely cushioned plywood mat and wrapping each other in holds
that look downright painful.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong runs his class with the authority of a high school
football coach: He instructs them on fundamentals _ an assortment
of head slaps, pile drivers, head locks and the ``tombstone'' move,
which basically involves dropping someone on his head.
</P>
<P>
   They practice how to tumble without getting hurt. They take
turns throwing each other into the corner turnbuckles. They learn
how to bounce off the ropes and send the other guy slamming into
the mat after delivering a stiff-arm ``clothes line'' to the throat
of an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Before they can do the tricky maneuvers, though, they must first
absorb the basics, such as running the ropes (bouncing from one
side of the ring to another). Then there's the ``head scissors''
move, in which one wrestler wraps his thighs around his opponent's
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them we don't play games here,'' Armstrong says,
``because if they go try out somewhere and have a poor performance,
it's my name and reputation that suffers, because I'm the one who
trained them.''
</P>
<P>
   Spend a couple of hours watching a class in all its
body-slamming, neck-choking, arm-twisting glory, and it's hard to
remember this is all supposed to be a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestlers don't really wrestle, right? Everyone knows they don't
play hard, they play act. Aren't they just a bunch of thyroid
giants and fat, hairy dudes bouncing around the ring during a
``match,'' executing pre-arranged moves, winning when someone
decides they're supposed to win and falling when they're told? It's
a parade of contorted faces and pulled punches and fake blood.
</P>
<P>
   Right?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no. Pro wrestlers have to be athletes as well as actors,
says WCW's Weber.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling is real in the sense that wrestlers do feel pain after
getting picked up and slammed down. They have to be able to carry
out the moves, choreographed or not, and do them safely.
</P>
<P>
   During a match nine months ago, Armstrong broke his neck when he
did a flip over the top rope of the ring and landed square on his
head. Paralyzed for three minutes with what doctors later called a
``spinal stinger,'' he regained movement and nursed his neck back
to mobility between a few more matches. Five months later he
resumed his career and he now competes in Japan and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But wrestling is artificial in the sense that promoters who set
up shows can decide who wins, says Weber. Wrestlers don't plan out
every move before a match, but there are certain things that have
to happen in order to tell a story. Mess with the story line and
all hell could break loose.
</P>
<P>
   Need proof? Look at a lawsuit filed earlier this year in Atlanta
by the WCW.
</P>
<P>
   The organization accused legendary wrestler ``Nature Boy'' Ric
Flair of reneging on a three-year, $1.95million deal, forcing
last-minute rewrites of ``story lines'' that propel the game. The
WCW, which refers to wrestlers as ``characters,'' says Flair
started missing work leading up to a nationally televised program
in Tallahassee and put plans with other wrestlers at risk. WCW
wants at least $2 million in damages, plus legal costs. The suit is
still pending.
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday morning, eight students _ all men _ turn out for
class at Armstrong's ring. The crowd is a collage of body types and
personal styles. Among them, there are three with shaved heads, two
goatees, two visible tattoos and one ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   There are guys like Wayne Ingstrup, 27, of Palm Springs, who
wants to go by the stage name ``Insane Wayne Suicide.'' He's
athletic, but with his long hair, goatee and untanned skin, he
looks more like he just stepped out of a computer lab. His goal is
to be the guy the audience hates. Lacking girth and Adonis-like
muscle tone, he's already devised his bad-boy equalizer: a baseball
bat wrapped in barbed wire. Who needs a power move with a tool like
that?
</P>
<P>
   There's Joe Cabibbo, a stocky 24-year-old construction worker
from Lake Worth with a peach-fuzz haircut who enjoys wrestling as
an outlet for releasing his frustrations. ``I just love playing the
bad guy,'' he says. ``Being a wrestler is my first love.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants to learn the sport, but he's equally fascinated with
the behind-the-scenes dealings and business aspects. And his
girlfriend, a mental health worker, loves the fact that he's
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all on the bottom rung, but we're hungry,'' Cabibbo
says. ``I have no mind-set for if I fail.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's Maurice Hennebicq,who already has the uniform, if
not the skills. A burly man with curly black hair, a bird's nest of
a beard and a hairy chest, he showed up for his first class in
style. He wears a black stretch tank top, a leather forearm cuff,
black elbow pads, black leather boots and black leggings with the
words ``BIG MAURICE'' stitched in red letters across his keister.
To say he stands out among the rest of the group's wardrobe of
faded T-shirts and beat-up sneakers would be an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   During class, the men break into groups. Some practice holds and
power moves, while Armstrong works with two at a time in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   One man drapes his armpits over the top of the ring as his
opponent pulls the upper rope into his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you sell it!'' Armstrong yells. He wants more
screaming and groaning from the student absorbing the punishment.
He wants more arm flailing. He wants him to act like his head is
about to pop up like a Pez dispenser. (The word ``act'' isn't said,
but everyone knows what ``selling'' means.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Get your chin down into your chest!'' Armstrong yells.
``That's it. That's it!''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he takes over and shows them how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, he demonstrates on 25-year-old Shawn Ambrosino.
Ambrosino, a 6-foot-1, 310-pound former college defensive tackle,
climbs the shaky corner ropes until he can stand steady and tall on
a turnbuckle. In his baggy jeans with frayed hems, faded yellow
T-shirt, clunky boots and scraggly face, he looks like he just
emerged from a concert mosh pit _ and won.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrosino stands perched upright on the ropes, until Armstrong
grabs the student's ample waistline and barrel chest and flops him
in a somersault on his back. Ambrosino lands like an asteroid. The
ropes waggle violently. The yuppie gym rats in the next room crane
their necks around the corner to see just what the hell made that
sickening thud.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrosino grimaces, groans, arches his back. He is a master at
``selling it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the granddaddy of them all,'' Armstrong says of the
throw. He high-fives Ambrosino. ``Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   As if nothing happened, Ambrosino rolls to his feet and collects
the accolades of the others in the group.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, as the students take turns using the moves
they just learned, Armstrong takes stock of his ambitious herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have so much potential, it makes me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hulk'' Hogan turned Ambrosino on to becoming a wrestler. He
used to watch the Hulkster on TV and copy the tanned, muscular
wrestler's moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked larger than life to me,'' he says. ``He wasn't a
role model. It just seemed that for him to be doing that every
night would be tough. That was something I could look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   After playing football for the University of Central Florida,
Ambrosino returned to Royal Palm Beach and got a job working as a
customer service representative at a bank.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months ago, a friend at the gym told him about wrestling
school. He gave the school a try and quickly developed a love for
throwing another guy around a ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from football, I loved the contact,'' he says. He
thinks about it for a second, searching for the right term. ``Not
the contact ... the collision.'' He says ``collision' the way a
pyromaniac might say ``fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrosino is one of Armstrong's pet pupils. His jumps are
sharper, his throws are a little more physical. And with a body
like a steamer trunk filled with wet cement, he knows how to sell a
move.
</P>
<P>
   A guy his size has a better chance of making it to the
professional ranks, says the WCW's Michael Weber. At the
organization's monthly auditions in Atlanta, only about two or
three out of a group of 15 candidates has what it takes to be
accepted in its Power Plant wrestling school. And an even smaller
percentage graduate from the wrestling school to the professional
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is the look,'' Weber says. ``We won't even look at
you if you're under 200 pounds. And just because you were an
All-American football player doesn't mean you can do this type of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrosino already has a stage name picked out: Gemini. That way
his character can be both a good guy and a bad guy, he reasons. All
he needs to do is paint his face two different colors. The way he
figures it, no one will know which side of Gemini will show up in
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to think up a hook, a concept you can work with,'' he
says. ``You have to bring something new to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, it's sports entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
