</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Useless facts plentiful on Web
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Bill Husted
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever seen the results for one of those surveys about
what kind of television people watch, you know most of us favor
educational programs and care nothing at all for the shows that
flaunt sex, violence and lowbrow humor.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with the Internet's World Wide Web. If you ask
your co-workers and friends how they use the Web, you'll find that
almost all of them are engaged in serious research.
</P>
<P>
   But, let's suppose you don't fit into any of these
super-studious categories. And that _ unlike most of your friends _
you actually waste time browsing Web sites that contribute nothing
at all to the world's storehouse of knowledge. This column is for
you. It's a look at some of the best ways to waste time on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Given the seriousness of today's quest, let's meet at a site
called The Three Stooges _ a starting point at
http://www.byrum.org/3stooges/. Here you'll find trivia about the
Stooges as well as a chance to get involved in serious political
movements. For instance, you'll learn how to organize to protest
the removal of ``The Three Stooges'' from the Family Channel's
programming lineup. For those of you who want still more, check out
The Official Three Stooges site at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .threestooges.com/.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of you should follow me. We have only a limited
amount of time to waste, so we'll need to keep moving. What you
need now are some facts. That way, when your more studious friends
begin to brag about all that they've learned from their day
browsing the Web, you'll be prepared to answer in kind.
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop will provide all sorts of important information
such as the fact termites can live to be 50 years old and there are
just 14 blimps left flying in the world. The page is called _ maybe
you would have guessed _ The Bin of Useless Facts, and it's located
at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .campbell.k12.ky.us/programs
</P>
<P>
   /oasis/BRAIN/RAK002.HTM. It is unlikely that anything you learn
here will get you ahead at work, but where else would you learn
that ``months that begin with a Sunday will always have a Friday
the 13th''?
</P>
<P>
   If by now you are worried you are wasting too much time browsing
the Web, perhaps you need a good time-wasting hobby. While many
come to mind, it would be difficult to go wrong with something such
as matchbook cover collecting.
</P>
<P>
   You can learn more about this hobby at a Web site called Online
Matchcover Auction at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.matchcovers.com/. Besides being able to trade matchbook
covers there, you'll learn stuff you won't find anywhere else,
including at any of the useless facts sites. For instance, you'll
find out the first matchbook cover advertisement appeared in 1895
and was for an entertainment troupe that promised ``A cyclone of
fun _ powerful caste _ pretty girls _ handsome ward-robe _ get
seats early.''
</P>
<P>
   If this seems like a stupid way to spend your time, you may want
to check your intelligence over at a site called IQ Test at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.iqtest.com/welcometest
</P>
<P>
   .html. It's really an amazingly accurate gauge of IQ. The real
question is whether IQ is an accurate gauge of intelligence,
however. And it's sort of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if the IQ tests come back with some bad news for you,
you may as well try a page called Stupid News, Andy Savage Online,
at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .andysavage.com/news/news.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
