<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The dead candidates society
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Voters often elect the wrong people.
</P>
<P>
   Usually this is only a matter of opinion. Occasionally it's
irrefutable. Democracy is not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The election last week of a dead Oklahoma woman to a spot in the
Democratic runoff for U.S. Senate seems a pretty clear case of the
democratic system gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, dead people cast ballots to elect the living. In
Oklahoma, it must work the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe that won't even be a problem. In a Senate filled with
the likes of Strom Thurmond and Slade Gorton, a dead person might
look right at home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the primary puts Oklahoma Democrats in an awkward
position. The timing was a big problem. The candidate, Jacquelyn
Morrow Luis Ledgerwood, died of a heart attack only a month before
the election. This left no time to take her off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to garner 21 percent of the vote, finishing second
in a field of four. She now has a shot at winning the primary in
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If she wins, she would be the Democratic nominee against
incumbent Sen. Don Nickles in November, a man who is to the right
of anyone alive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even a dead candidate offers voters more choice than they
get in most states. In almost half the congressional races in the
country, the incumbent was re-elected without an opponent from the
other major party. At least Oklahoma Democrats have a chance to
vote for somebody, dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   And for somebody who would be guaranteed not to surprise or
disappoint anyone after the election. In an age of low expectations
in public life, who could ask for more?
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's doubtful the majority of Oklahoma Democrats intended
to nominate a person who is no longer a member of the caucus of the
living.
</P>
<P>
   People may argue about this candidate or that. People may vote
liberal or conservative. But there are five categories of
candidates everyone wants to avoid:
</P>
<P>
   -- Nonexistent and nonhuman candidates. Cartoon characters for
example. You'd be surprised at how often they turn up as write-ins.
And inanimate objects, too. Two years ago, a write-in line on the
Volusia County general election ballot read: ``Volusia County Soil
and Water Conservation District (Vote for one).'' Water got the
most write-ins, edging out soil. Sadly, only votes for humans were
tallied.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dead candidates. See above. It happens.
</P>
<P>
   -- Insane candidates. There are forms of mental illness that
drive people to plop down filing fees, talk to reporters and
prepare amazingly detailed platforms. (``We can tap the icecaps for
water, energy and economic development! Details in the 145-page
position paper that I will post on the Web! I will not allow the
government or the lackeys of the so-called New World Order to
suppress this!!!'') The unseen running mate in such races all too
often is the voice the candidate hears in his head. As a candidate
for the House of Representatives told me many years ago, ``After
that head injury, a lot of things just started making sense to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Jailed candidates. Ever since the legendary James Curley of
Boston was elected mayor from behind bars, this has not been seen
as an insurmountable obstacle. But this is America. We expect our
leaders to go to jail after we elect them and not a moment before.
Anything else is jumping the gun.
</P>
<P>
   -- Candidates who have lost more than three consecutive
elections. The people can be very wrong on occasion, but after
three or four times, the collective wisdom must be on to something.
Three-strikes-and-you're-out laws should be expanded from criminal
sentencing to politics.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, politics would lose a lot of color and a certain amount of
choice if these five kinds of candidates were kept off ballot. But
brighten up, we would still enjoy the services of angry
single-issue candidates, disgruntled former public employees,
grudge candidates, people who have discovered the One Big Truth
that explains everything, the delusionally ambitious and people who
like to be videotaped.
</P>
<P>
   They would be happy to take up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   They always are.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
