<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mariner Write has simple, stable word processing
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The developers of Mariner Write are nothing if not courageous.
They are releasing their simple but powerful word processor just at
the time when more and more people are playing it safe by choosing
Microsoft software.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Write's developers hope there's still a niche market for
those looking for an inexpensive alternative to Word 98,
Microsoft's latest version of its word processor.
</P>
<P>
   As such, Mariner Write is a good deal. It's fast, lean and
stable. The program includes most of Word's features but costs
$69.95. Word retails for $365.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing from Write are features that let you draw tables,
write outlines, auto-correct typos and automatically create indexes
and tables of contents. Word does all of these.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, the only two glaring weaknesses are the lack of
auto-correct and outlining. Both have become standard now in word
processing.
</P>
<P>
   But Writer does some things Word doesn't. For one, it lets you
highlight and edit noncontiguous text, a feature long part of Nisus
Writer.
</P>
<P>
   Writer even bests Nisus in one area. It handles styles far more
elegantly than this popular word processor. In Nisus, you set
rulers and fonts in two different places. Write combines both
rulers and fonts in a menu in the title bar of the document. It's
easy to switch among styles as you write.
</P>
<P>
   Word also lets you do this, but it's not as elegantly
implemented as in Write.
</P>
<P>
   Write also has Word beat in terms of stability and efficiency.
Even the latest version of Word, crammed as always with new
features, is unstable on anything but the fastest Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Worst yet, it's a hog. Word requires 13.3 megabytes of RAM and
occupies 5.2 megabytes on your hard drive. In contrast, Write takes
only 875 K of disk space and needs only 2 megabytes of RAM.
</P>
<P>
   It has a simple, uncluttered interface. There's just one
toolbar, which provides access to most of the things you'll need.
Move your cursor over a button to reveal its function.
</P>
<P>
   The toolbar can be moved to anywhere on your screen.
</P>
<P>
   Write lets you drag and drop copy, insert automatically updating
page numbers and look at your words as they'd appear in print. It
also undoes up to 10 of your last actions and saves documents in
most word-processing formats. Write supports headers, footers but
not endnotes.
</P>
<P>
   Write includes some nice extras in the form of macros such as
one that capitalizes every sentence on command. It does so quicker
and more accurately than either Nisus or Word, which have a similar
feature.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Write is not a bad little package if all you want to
do is write or design newsletters and the like.
</P>
<P>
   You can download a demo of the program from the company's Web
site at http://www.marinersoft.com. Or you can reach Mariner at its
headquarters in LaGrange, Ky. at 502-222-6695.
</P>
</TEXT>
