<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just a few dollars to spare? You can still acquire stocks
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even when the stock market goes kablooey, as it did last week,
there are people who still want to get into it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not talking about committed stock investors, already in and
eager to ``buy on the dips.'' I'm hearing from newcomers, people
with only a few dollars to spare and a yearning to get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``How,'' a tenderfoot bargain hunter asked the other day, ``does
a person buy stock if he doesn't have thousands to put into a
brokerage account?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good question. There are two good answers _ mutual funds
that will open very small accounts and direct purchase or no-load
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these alternatives is an automatic winner, or even an
easy choice. Mutual fund managers have all sorts of stock-picking
strategies, for example. The performance of individual stocks is
infamously hard to assess.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, alternatives exist for people with high hopes and
low bank balances. The accompanying chart gives some examples, and
there are many more to be found. Here's a more detailed look at the
choices:
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar Inc., a widely respected mutual fund research firm,
came up with 48 funds that will open an account for $500 or less.
(A few other funds say they will accept a minimum investment of
zero dollars, but that's too metaphysical for me to figure out.)
</P>
<P>
   The 48 include a variety of investment styles. MSB, for example,
invests in a blend of value and growth stocks. That means,
respectively, stocks that people think have attractively low prices
and stocks that have attractive growth records or prospects or
both. MSB likes to buy stock in very large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Muhlenkemp buys the shares of midsized, value companies. Pax
World is a ``domestic hybrid,'' meaning that it buys U.S.
securities, including stocks, bonds and convertibles. It describes
itself as a socially responsible fund, avoiding defense, tobacco,
liquor and gambling-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   Investment styles are not the only thing to consider. You must
think over how much risk you're willing to tolerate. You should
also check out the fees and operating expenses of any fund you
consider. Morningstar's list included the well-known Fidelity
Destiny I and Destiny II funds, for example. But the front-end
sales charge of each of those is 8.67 percent, which was enough to
put them off my list.
</P>
<P>
   As you begin an investment program, you're also beginning your
investment education. When you call up a fund company, you should
ask for the fund's prospectus and most recent quarterly or annual
report. It will tell you about sales charges and operating
expenses. You should also think over the things the company has to
say about how it picks stocks, and about why its recent performance
has been good, bad or just so-so.
</P>
<P>
   Those documents also will give you comparisons of how the fund
did in comparison with similar funds and with stock market
averages. Check out both long-term and recent performance. You
might also want to check how long the manager has been on board. Is
he a newcomer, or someone who has been around long enough to shape
the fund's performance?
</P>
<P>
   You can continue your education at the nearest public library.
Look for general-purpose books on financial planning. Kathy Kristof
has a good one, as do Marshall Loeb, Jane Bryant Quinn and Grace
Weinstein. Public libraries often carry the Morningstar ratings
books, which are packed with both statistics and plain-language
assessments of a fund's practices and philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, some good places to start are www
</P>
<P>
   .morningstar.net, http://www
</P>
<P>
   .accessatlanta.com/business
</P>
<P>
   /finance/dividendreinvestment
</P>
<P>
   .html or http://www
</P>
<P>
   .investorama.com/director.html.
</P>
<P>
   `No-load' stocks
</P>
<P>
   About 200 companies will sell stock directly to the public, so
you don't have to go through a broker. A major advantage of these
direct investment programs is that your first step into the market
can be a baby step _ committing as little as $50. Another advantage
is that you won't have to pay a big percentage of your money as a
stock broker's fee.
</P>
<P>
   Low costs are also important if you want to put your second
investment into an entirely different company, thus moving toward a
basic investing goal _ spreading or diversifying your investments
among different kinds of companies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another advantage is that direct-investment companies tend
to be larger, older and steadier companies. They may well go down
with the overall market, but they aren't likely to go under.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``no-load'' is a casual one and not always true. Some
companies charge a fee for selling you some of their shares. It
will likely be less than a broker would charge, but it's something
to check.
</P>
<P>
   These programs are not for short-term or nervous investors.
That's because each company sells or buys back shares on its own
schedule, perhaps once a week or even once a month. This is an
investment strategy for the long haul. It is not for people who
hope to snatch today's profit before the sun goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential drawback: tax paperwork, particularly if you
choose to reinvest dividends. The company will send along a form
called a 1099 that contains the information you need to report to
the Internal Revenue Service. But you'll have to keep up with and
manage that paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   To find companies beyond those listed in the table, try the
library. Look for books by Charles B. Carlson, an author and
specialist on direct investments. Ask also if your library has
newsletters on the subject, including Carlson's DRIP Investor and
The Moneypaper.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, check out www.netstockdirect.com,www
</P>
<P>
   .noloadstocks.com or www
</P>
<P>
   .dripinvestor.com. The latter has information on a larger group
of stocks that will sell directly to individuals but only after
they have acquired at least one share of the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Why now?
</P>
<P>
   Why should you pump money into a sinking stock market?
</P>
<P>
   The readers I hear from clearly are bargain hunters. If savvy
investors want to buy when prices are down, newcomers want to do
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   A more basic reason is that successful investing is a long-term
process. You put a little money in this month, and you learn a
little. You do the same thing next month and the month after that.
You have to start sometime, and today is better than tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, some people just like to swim against the tide. On Main
Street, such people are called ornery or even wrongheaded. But on
Wall Street, there is an honorable term for them: contrarians.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:hezell(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
