r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAX-TV01-COX     08-31 2380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAX-TV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pax TV becomes nation's seventh network
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   And then there were seven.
</P>
<P>
   Today (Monday, August 31), Pax TV becomes the nation's seventh
network with a slate of family-themed shows.
</P>
<P>
   The West Palm Beach-based network kicks off at noon with Great
Day America (WPXP-Channel 67), a one-hour entertainment/talk show
broadcast live from Universal Studios in Los Angeles. Yes, the show
is new, but don't expect to see too much original fare on Pax TV.
Only 20 percent of the network's shows are first-run.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pax TV will primarily boast infomercials, a meditative
show called Worship (it features scenes of nature, Burt Bacharach
music and words of wisdom) and repeats of old network fare.
</P>
<P>
   But it's those repeats Pax TV is counting on. Over time, the
network hopes to build an audience on such popular shows as Touched
By An Angel, Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman and Diagnosis Murder. For
old-time TV buffs, there's always Medical Center, Bonanza and The
Big Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our idea is that you can still actually (air) television shows
that really rely on just telling stories about relationships
between people, and that don't rely on sexual titillation and
people perpetrating violence on one another,'' says Jeff Sagansky,
Pax TV president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Steve Sohmer, Pax TV's head of marketing and promotion:
``This is no schizophrenic mosaic trying to be all things to all
people. Pax TV is a brand that's absolutely, positively,
unblinkingly crystal clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but the producers behind Pax TV's original shows
candidly admit the network is in for a Godzilla-sized battle. While
Pax TV bills itself as a network for all ages, such shows as
Diagnosis Murder and Dr. Quinn mostly attract viewers over 50.
</P>
<P>
   For example, according to TN Media, a New York-based media
buying firm, last fall Diagnosis Murder was TV's
second-oldest-skewing show, with a median age of 57. Touched By An
Angel's median viewer age was 52, while Dr. Quinn's was 51.
</P>
<P>
   Great Day America co-host and executive producer Michael Young
worked at CNBC during its 1989 launch and remembers how difficult
it was to get viewers and guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first year, we were trying to get all the newsmakers in
the financial community to come on and be guests,'' recalls the
former Flamingo Fortune host. ``But we didn't just have to call
them and find out if they were available, we had to call them and
explain the damn network. It was hard to get guests and get people
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Young acknowledges the same thing is happening with
Pax TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go out there to get guests, the first thing you have
to do is say, `This is our show and this is what it's about,' and
they go, `Oh, where is it on?' We tell them Pax TV and they say,
`What's Pax TV?''' says Young. ``Now, not only do we have to
explain the show, we have to explain the network. And that'll get
easier, but right now it's a difficult thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Booking guests has gone a bit smoother at Woman's Day TV, a
half-hour lifestyle/talk show based on the popular magazine and
hosted by Phyllis George and Sloan Lindemann. Some of the
celebrities scheduled to appear include Kris Kristofferson, Donny
and Marie Osmond and The View's Star Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman's Day is a cache, it's like an institution,'' says
executive producer Brad Nathanson. ``That brand is helping us a
lot. But we're not thinking about ratings at the production office.
We're just thinking about making a great show.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the producers of It's A Miracle, a reality-based show
about people who claim to have witnessed miracles. Like so many
other reality-based shows, It's A Miracle will recreate the actual
events _ but with a twist. Instead of using actors, producers will
use the real people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unsolved Mysteries do real drama re-creations,'' explains Jean
Wiegman, the show's executive producer. ``Ours are more reality
based. Theirs have more of a dramatic structure.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it tough getting non-actors to ... act?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really,'' says Wiegman, who produced such Fox specials
as Why Planes Go Down and Inside a Crash. ``We get them, like,
mourning towards the lake. We don't get them to do a lot of
dialogue. We've chosen stories that are multi-dimensional and
compelling. Hopefully people who like this kind of alternative
programming will find us and stay with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers note there are some advantages to working for an
upstart network. The biggest perk: Network suits don't meddle as
much, and Pax TV programmers are actually open to casting
suggestions and storylines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other networks have their rules and regulations and they
don't like to change them,'' grumbles John Ryan, producer of Little
Men, a drama about an woman running a boys boarding school alone in
1871. ``Pax TV is more willing to take a chance. For instance, they
left it up to the executive producers and myself to find the
(Toronto) location. They just went along with us. We showed them
some pictures and they bought into it. With the networks, they
would've flown up here, they would've hemmed and hawed and said,
`No, we want something a little different.'''
</P>
<P>
   Before getting involved with Pax TV, many producers admit they
knew little about the network's founder, Lowell ``Bud'' Paxson. All
they knew was the cash-rich entrepreneur started the Home Shopping
Network and is a staunch conservative with deeply held religious
views.
</P>
<P>
   Little Men's Ryan says he searched the Web to get more
information on Paxson. Ryan adds he was asked to produce Little Men
because of his extensive background of producing such period TV
movies as Lonesome Dove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm familiar with this time period and horses and buggies,''
says Ryan, who has produced about 15 TV movies for the major
networks. ``You do one period thing and then all of a sudden, I'm
called when they need a producer who knows his way around animals
during that period.''
</P>
<P>
   Great Day America's Young remembers being called by someone at
Paxson Communications who asked if he would be a roving reporter at
the company's West Palm Beach unveiling party last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me what kind of compensation I wanted,'' he
recalls, ``and I said, `I never met Bud Paxson, so after it's over,
I'd like to go to lunch with him and find out about his network.'''
</P>
<P>
   Young did meet with Paxson and pitched what eventually became
Great Day America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept waiting for Bud to ask me what my religious preference
was,'' says Young. ``He never did, and he still hasn't done it. He
couldn't have made a bolder statement in hiring Jeff Sagansky. Jeff
is a very committed Jew, and if Bud was one of those right-wing,
born-again Christians who don't think Jews are saved, he wouldn't
have hired someone like Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV hopes to attract families
</P>
<P>
   If you get tired of watching countless Touched By An Angel
repeats or sleep-inducing infomercials, the Pax TV folks hope
you'll check out their new programs. Here's the lowdown on all of
their original shows.
</P>
<P>
   GREAT DAY AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: Have you seen the last hour of the Today show?
Now you know what Great Day America will look like. This one-hour
show will broadcast live from Universal Studios in Los Angeles and
offer mostly lifestyle information, current events and celebrity
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Says co-host Michael Young: ``Today has beaten the hell out of
Good Morning America in the ratings, and we'd rather emulate the
leader. But I'm nowhere near as handsome as Matt Lauer.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect big name guests, though. The first week you'll see
Rod Steiger and Harrison Young. Harrison who? He played the older
Matt Damon character in Saving Private Ryan. Susan Crenshaw
co-hosts. Interestingly, Crenshaw replaced Maria Calleia, who was
introduced to TV writers as the show's co-host. Now Calleia's just
a regular contributor. Explains a show insider: ``Contract
negotiations never worked out. But there are no hard feelings.''
Sounds so Hollywood, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   When it debuts: noon, Monday
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 5 p.m., weekdays
</P>
<P>
   IT'S A MIRACLE
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: Think Unsolved Mysteries meets Oprah. Producers
re-create miracles, then interview the people involved. You'll hear
about dogs who saved little boys from drowning and lovers who fell
in love at an organ donors convention. Wait ... the producers swear
It's A Miracle won't turn into a sleazy, reality-based show. ``This
isn't When Animals Attack,'' says Jean Wiegman, the show's
executive producer. ``We're not going the sensational route; we're
going the inspirational route.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hosted by the odd-couple pair of Nia Peebles (Dance Party)
and country singer Billy Dean. If the stories are boring, at least
we know the hosts can sing and dance.
</P>
<P>
   When it debuts: Sept. 6
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 9 p.m., Sundays
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE MEN
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: It's the story of Jo Baher, one of the Little
Women characters who must run a boarding school for boys alone
after her schoolteacher husband dies. Of course, Jo struggles to
keep the school running but manages to offer a lot of life lessons
along the way. ``There's going to be plenty of opportunity for
adventures and Tom Sawyer-ish action,'' says executive producer
Carl Binder.
</P>
<P>
   And there'll be some romance. Jo might find love with bad boy
Nick, who's released in Jo's care after doing time in the joint.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, producers are scrambling to meet tight production
schedules on the Toronto set. ``It's been nip and tuck around
here,'' notes producer John Ryan (Lonesome Dove). ``We go to camera
in two weeks, and we just hired our leads last night!''
</P>
<P>
   When it debuts: Nov. 7
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 8 p.m., Sundays
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN'S DAY TV
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: Woman's Day the magazine comes to life. Hosted
by Phyllis George (yes, that Phyllis George) and Sloan Lindemann (a
former New York City assistant D.A.), the show is designed to
entertain and inspire women of all ages. ``The demographics are
pretty wide,'' says Brad Nathanson, executive producer and
director. ``It's 26 to 54. We're not going after the MTV
generation.'' Expect segments on cooking, fitness, beauty, time
management and gossip. ``We're not trying to emulate a talk show,''
sniffs Nathanson. ``None of us like that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   When it debuts: Monday
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 2 p.m., weekdays
</P>
<P>
   FLIPPER: THE NEW ADVENTURES
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: Just like the old Flipper, except he'll have
some new adventures. Whip Hubley (Top Gun) stars as Dr. Keith
Ricks, the Florida Keys marine biologist (the show is filmed in
Australia, though) whose best buddy is a dolphin. Let's hope it's
better than the awful Flipper movie starring Elijah Wood and Paul
Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   When it debuts: Saturday
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 8 p.m., Saturdays
</P>
<P>
   REEL TO REEL
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: A movie trivia game show hosted by former
Hollywood Squares host Peter Marshall. What??? Peter Marshall's
still alive? You think that's funny, check out the Who's Who of
C-list stars scheduled to appear on the show: Abe Vigoda, Police
Academy's Michael Winslow, Stella Stevens, Robert Hays, Linda
Blair, Jeff Conaway, Stephanie Powers and Shelley Duvall. First
question: What was the last movie each of these stars made?
</P>
<P>
   When it debuts: Monday
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 2:30 p.m., weekdays
</P>
<P>
   CLOUD NINE
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: A trio of do-good teen angels take over a TV
station and broadcast uplifting kid shows. Sounds like the story of
Pax TV. Actually Pax TV is trying to copy ABC's successful 1
Saturday Morning cartoon block. Forget that Power Rangers stuff,
these angels program shows about a shipwrecked family (Adventures
of Swiss Family Robinson); a merry group of animal friends (Get
Along Gang); a mismatched soccer team (Hurricanes); a show that
answers silly questions kids have (Inquiring Minds); a team of
peacekeeping heroes (Starcom); a magical forest where you shrink
and wishes come true (The Sylvanian Families); adventures of two
toothbrushes (The Toothbrush Family); and a cool mayor who helps
children solve problems (Zaktales).
</P>
<P>
   Says Andy Heyward, Cloud 9's executive producer: ``The stories
will center on personal and work problems and at the same time be
warmhearted and (deal with) kid-relatable issues.''
</P>
<P>
   When it debuts: Saturday
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 7-9 a.m., Saturdays; 6-9 a.m., Sundays
</P>
<P>
   Shows that lost viewers
</P>
<P>
   will be finding new life
</P>
<P>
   on network's lineup
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV will air several shows you've either heard of or seen
before. Here are five you may have never watched or even knew
existed.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTY
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: Based on Catherine Marshall's novel about a
spunky young woman (Kellie Martin) who leaves a cushy life in
Tennessee to teach at a missionary school in a remote Appalachian
community.
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 6 p.m., Sundays
</P>
<P>
   When it aired before: CBS, 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE GOES ON
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: A gentle drama about a working-class family
dealing with all sorts of problems including handicapped children
and AIDS. Gee, wonder if the ultra-conservative Pax TV will lose
those AIDS episodes? Stars Kellie Martin and Patti LuPone.
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 7 p.m., weekdays
</P>
<P>
   When it aired before: ABC, 1989-93
</P>
<P>
   I'LL FLY AWAY
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: A thoughtful drama about race relations in the
South in the 1950s. Sam Waterston stars as the gentlemanly
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 10 p.m., Sundays
</P>
<P>
   When it aired before: NBC, 1991-93
</P>
<P>
   THE HOGAN FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: A typical sitcom about a harried mom (Valerie
Harper) juggling family and career. Mostly remembered for when
Harper left the show after one year in a well-publicized spat with
NBC. The network replaced her with Sandy Duncan, who played her
husband's divorced sister.
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: 4 p.m., weekdays
</P>
<P>
   When it aired before: NBC/CBS, 1986-91
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL CENTER
</P>
<P>
   What it's about: Before ER and Chicago Hope, there was Medical
Center, starring the hunky Chad Everett as a dedicated doctor
dealing with personal medical dramas.
</P>
<P>
   When it airs: midnight Sundays
</P>
<P>
   When it aired before: CBS, 1969-76
</P>
