r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHTOOLS01-COX     08-31 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PC voice recognition: Last word still elusive
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it is something left over from the film ``2001,'' but I
have always felt rather self-conscious talking to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, since publishers are claiming great strides
recently in the advancement of voice recognition systems, I am
talking to mine on a regular basis these days. The results are
mixed, at best.
</P>
<P>
   I have several new systems to test; the one we'll examine today
is L&AMP;H Voice Xpress Plus, a program confined to dictating text and
formatting commands to Microsoft Word 97 or 98, or the considerably
less elaborate word processor contained within the program.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, if Voice Xpress is representative of the breed,
computer dictation programs have indeed made great strides over the
past few years. It will not only record your words, but you can
dictate formatting changes, manipulate menus and almost entirely
eliminate the use of the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The program comes with a head-mounted microphone, with one
earpiece, in case for some odd reason you want to hear your voice
played back to you. It's comfortable enough, although it interferes
annoyingly with the ingestion of food and drink.
</P>
<P>
   First come the mechanical issues of setting up the software,
which attaches itself like a leech to Microsoft Word, and getting
the microphone adjusted and calibrated. Then the user must
``enroll'' in the program. This is simply a curious way of saying
you have to teach the program to understand your voice.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a simple matter. It consists of uttering 416
statements, mostly witty aphorisms, until the program understands
all or at least most of it. It can take awhile.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with my review of any voice recognition program is
my voice. It has been likened to that of Burl Ives with a toad in
his throat. I tend to mumble, and whistle at ``ess'' sounds. Even
my wife often can't understand me.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, once I opened Word the old-fashioned way, I used
the voice recognition program to open the File menu. From there, I
used voice commands to open a story. Amazingly, it all worked.
</P>
<P>
   Voice Xpress runs significantly behind your dictation; it takes
awhile to figure things out. If, for instance, you dictate ``Mary
had a little lamb'' and the program decides you said, ``Mary had a
little ham,'' you simply tell it to ``delete last word'' and then
try again. If you can't get it to understand, then you can go into
spelling mode.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often it fails to recognize I am giving editing
commands and not dictation, but that may be my fault. Anyone who
enunciates so poorly that a program came up with ``Thelma'' when
the phrase was ``the movie'' shouldn't be too critical.
</P>
<P>
   Working carefully, I can generally create a sentence every five
minutes or so. At that rate, I fear I won't live long enough to
create the Great American Novel, or even an average American novel.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't believe programs like this are really intended for
people with two good hands for typing. Regardless of how much you
dislike typing, you'll find getting comfortable with Voice Xpress
more trouble than it's worth unless you're in Rex Harrison's vocal
league.
</P>
<P>
   But for those with physical problems that make it difficult or
impossible to type, a voice recognition program, and especially one
that allows the manipulation of a standard word processor in a
virtually no-hands mode, could be a godsend.
</P>
<P>
   Before drawing any final conclusions, we'll look at a couple of
more commonly available programs of this sort.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
