<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0630 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAXSON01-COX     08-31 2349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAXSON01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can Bud Paxson make money on the first-ever, feel good TV
network for families?
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At noon Monday, engineer Bill Meyer will click a computer mouse
at PAX TV's satellite uplink center and _ poof! _ the nation's
seventh commercial broadcast network will start running with the
big dogs _ ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   At PAX TV's West Palm Beach headquarters, there won't be a
champagne-popping party for the 160 employees _ not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a party when we start making money,'' says Lowell
``Bud'' Paxson, who built the network that could put him and West
Palm Beach on the broadcasting map.
</P>
<P>
   If PAX TV works, Paxson, 63, becomes a billionaire, a media
power broker running with the Michael Eisners and Rupert Murdochs
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   And he will have done what no one else has ever done: Create a
network dedicated to G-rated shows and built primarily with
stations he owns _ not affiliate stations, which is how other
networks work.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson owns or operates 71 TV stations _ more stations than
anyone in the United States. With those stations, plus 24
affiliates and some cable access, PAX TV will reach 76 million of
America's 99.4 million TV households.
</P>
<P>
   What they will see is a new kind of commercial network TV:
Wholesome shows. Spiritual shows. Uplifting shows. Shows such as a
new Flipper series and reruns of the CBS hit Touched by an Angel.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a Christian network, Paxson says. No preachers, no
pitches, no pontificating.
</P>
<P>
   But the network is the result of a powerful partnership: God and
Bud Paxson.
</P>
<P>
   To understand PAX TV, you must know the imposing, 6-foot-7-inch
man who pushed all of his chips to the middle of the table to
create it.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson, who grew up in Rochester, N.Y., as the son of a Kodak
machinist, likes to do business at what he calls ``stupid speed.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't climb through windows of opportunity, he dives.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a kid he was smart about business. He raised hamsters
that he sold for $1 each and became a disc jockey _ Buddy Bud _
when he was a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   After earning a degree at Syracuse University, Paxson bought
radio stations in Newark, then Jamestown, N.Y., and Waterbury,
Conn. He moved to Florida in 1968 when he bought an AM in Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   It was a small station with a small budget, where the title of
owner meant he also had to collect past-due ad bills. One unpaid
account meant he couldn't make the station's payroll. He went to
collect the $1,000. But instead of cash, the appliance store paid
him with 112 can openers. He sold them on the air.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his first home run when he and a partner created the
Clearwater-based Home Shopping Network in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   But as he built himself into a millionaire, Paxson's home life
was crumbling. On Christmas Day 1986, right after the family had
unwrapped the gifts in their Sarasota home, Paxson's second wife,
Barbara, dropped the bomb: She was leaving him for another man.
</P>
<P>
   Despondent, drained and dumped, Paxson spent New Year's Eve
alone in a suite at the Las Vegas Caesar's Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The miserable millionaire tore through the suite looking for a
Bible. He found it, opened it. He read how God saved Job. He read
on and on. And then, he says, God filled him with a pure and
perfect peace.
</P>
<P>
   He dedicated his life to God, and Paxson doesn't care who tries
to use this partnership to make him look foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not speak to me,'' explains Paxson. ``You do not hear
an audible voice. The old cartoon is pretty accurate. You've got
the devil on one shoulder and the little angel on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people can only hear the devil, Paxson says. He listens for
the angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you develop your faith, you become sensitized to an
internal knowing, and it's a knowing that grows.''
</P>
<P>
   That knowing led Paxson to take the biggest gamble in broadcast
history.
</P>
<P>
   He cashed out of the Home Shopping Network (and Silver King
Broadcasting) with $133 million in 1991. Next, he built a
47-station radio network that he sold for $633 million in spring
1997. Along with the radio stations, he had been buying TV
stations.
</P>
<P>
   He had an idea. In 1992, Congress had ruled that cable systems
had to provide a channel for all local stations. Paxson knew he
could build a network out of low-power stations that cable systems
had to carry.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``must-carry'' rule, universally hated by cable
operators and cable networks, was challenged and slowly worked its
way to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Paxson bought his third TV station, this one in
Atlanta, and suddenly had buyer's remorse. What if the Supreme
Court killed must-carry?
</P>
<P>
   He was worried. He couldn't sleep. He needed help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to the Lord, `Gee whiz, we're going to have a
must-carry decision. What have I done?' '' he recalls. ``The Lord
said, `Don't worry about must-carry.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Paxson worried no more. ``We went out and bought 50 more TV
stations.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, 1997, the Supreme Court upheld the must-carry rule.
When Paxson got the news, he broke down and cried.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lord on his side, Paxson says, ``it was not a gamble at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   PAX TV was announced in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Television on his own terms
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we believe in,'' Paxson says, ``simply good
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Michael Eisner may know what middle-class families want
in their theme parks, but Paxson thinks he knows what they want on
their TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the family is at the heart of
society,'' he contends. ``That is the common denominator, and if
ABC, CBS and NBC knew it, television wouldn't be at the sorry state
that it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry or not, monolithic ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox must lure huge
audiences to their shows. They can't make money on shows watched in
``only'' 10 million TV households.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson's lean network doesn't need those numbers to make money.
Because Paxson owns the stations and because his original
programming will be cheap by network standards, PAX TV just needs
to average 994,000 TV households to make money.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson's betting that at 9 p.m. Mondays, 994,000 TV households
would watch reruns of Touched by an Angel instead of Melrose Place,
NFL football or any other show.
</P>
<P>
   Or, at 8 p.m. Saturday, he's hoping 994,000 TV households would
rather watch Flipper than Cops or America's Funniest Home Videos.
</P>
<P>
   When reruns of Touched by an Angel were headed to CBS-owned The
Nashville Network's schedule, Paxson rushed up with an eye-popping
bid and bought the right to run the 88 episodes 10 times each for
$950,000 per episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a preemptive buy,'' he says. ``I needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxson reportedly paid $300,000 per episode for reruns of Dr.
Quinn, Medicine Woman.
</P>
<P>
   The last two commercial networks _ WB (Warner Bros.) and UPN
(Paramount) _ launched in January 1995, both with the huge cash
reserves of a movie/TV studio behind them. Each has reportedly lost
more than $150 million annually, and neither is producing the 20
hours of original programs that PAX TV offers on Day One.
</P>
<P>
   The six networks sell national ads. An owner of a group of
affiliated stations sells target markets and local ads. PAX TV can
sell all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why it can't miss,'' says Paxson.
</P>
<P>
   With a smile, Paxson recalls surfing channels recently and
seeing a stand-up comic on Comedy Central. ``He mentioned PAX TV
and said, `No sex, no violence, no ratings.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street and media analysts aren't laughing at the PAX TV
idea. None is predicting doom or success _ but there's agreement it
could fly.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran TV ad buyer Paul Schulman, with heavyweight clients such
as Energizer batteries, The Gap and Ralston Purina, says, ``When
you have a goal of a 1 rating (994,000 TV households), that's not a
ridiculously high measuring board. And it is possible that they
will not achieve it in year one.''
</P>
<P>
   That only means that Paxson has to stay in the game, says
Schulman, ``and certainly Bud Paxson has the dough to stay in this
for the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulman, with offices in Boca Raton and New York City,
concludes, ``The way I look at their schedule, it's pretty much a
poor man's CBS because most of the programs that they have acquired
are programs that will have an older audience skew. Most
advertisers are interested in the 18-49 audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxson describes his target viewers as women 25-50 who will use
the remote to take their families to a peaceful place, the home of
shows that affirm life.
</P>
<P>
   Original Paxson shows will aspire to inspire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus told about his father in story and parables,'' says
Paxson. ``And that's what we want to be known as, the story and
parable teller. I think (show creator) Martha Williamson got it
right with Touched by an Angel. God exists, and He loves you,
period.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paxson prefers God's subtle message.
</P>
<P>
   He's received ``at least 200 requests'' from TV preachers who
want to buy time on PAX TV. He has said ``no.'' When Fox recently
bought The Family Channel, part of the deal was that the Fox Family
Channel had to continue airing Pat Robertson's 700 Club. Fox,
desperate to dump the Christian talk show, offered Paxson ``a ton
of money'' to take the 700 Club. Paxson said ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   On a mission from God, there's no room for hitchhikers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sagansky: Obscurity with an ocean view?
</P>
<P>
   Now that Paxson's built the foundation, the game of PAX TV is in
the hands of Jeff Sagansky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sagansky is Paxson's biggest asset, no question,'' says ad
buyer Schulman.
</P>
<P>
   As the president and CEO of PAX TV, Sagansky is a 47-year-old
former CBS programming boss who took the network from No. 3 to No.
1. His job now is to find the writers and producers who will create
family-friendly PAX shows that viewers fall in love with.
</P>
<P>
   And do it at Paxson's ``stupid speed'' _ which means building
from the current 20 original hours to more than 100 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sagansky is moving quickly. Projects are blessed _ by Sagansky,
Paxson and William Scott (programming president) _ without
expensive pilots. A single script can earn an order for 13 episodes
of a show _ rare at other networks.
</P>
<P>
   And what is PAX TV paying people to create new shows? One
veteran TV producer says, ``They're in the ballpark, but barely.''
</P>
<P>
   At CBS, Sagansky green-lighted shows such as Dr. Quinn and
Touched by an Angel. But at PAX TV, the Ivy League-educated exec
doesn't have a CBS-sized budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not paying network money,'' he says. ``I've worked at a
studio, I've worked at a network, and these networks and studios
spend way more than they have to, way more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagansky wants network-quality shows for far less than network
money. A typical network one-hour drama costs $1 million per
episode to make. If it becomes a hit, the price goes up
dramatically. Della Reese recently had a salary snit at CBS and
will earn $100,000 per episode for Touched by an Angel. Her
co-star, Roma Downey, gets more per show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who are into the studio system, they only know how
to do things within that system,'' says Sagansky. ``They aren't
calling because our whole economics are different.''
</P>
<P>
   So, where does he find talent willing to work cheap for a
brand-new network? Other than waiting in the Betty Ford Clinic
parking lot for people who used to have careers, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Sagansky laughs.
</P>
<P>
   PAX TV's potential writers, producers and actors are ``people
who have a real passion for the show and really know producing and
know this material can be done for a little less money, and just as
well. Those are the calls I'm getting, those are the calls I want.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're out there. You have to look hard. Already I think I
have three or four people who want to work in the genres we're
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those could be Bruce Nash. The TV producer, a former Palm
Beach Gardens resident, is talking to Sagansky about doing a
series.
</P>
<P>
   And Nash isn't near the downside of a career. This fall he'll
produce a special, This Is Your Life for CBS, Magic's Biggest
Secrets for Fox, two reality shows for ABC and Secrets of Pro
Wrestling Exposed for NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do a lot of shows that are darker, edgy, controversial,
eerie, whatever they are,'' Nash says. ``Where do I sell great
stories where we can see people in a positive light? I need that
for myself creatively.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagansky is committed to PAX TV with a four-year contract. He's
living at a Palm Beach hotel. His wife, Christy Welker, who has
family in Fort Lauderdale, is on the way from Los Angeles with
their daughters, Summer, 4, and Gillian, 9.
</P>
<P>
   Sagansky shares Paxson's passion. ``The timing for this is
perfect,'' he begins. ``Just look across the board at 8, 9 o'clock,
there are so few family offerings. I'll tell you, frankly, I am
shocked at what goes on at 8 o'clock. It's all sexual titillation
and a huge amount of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever watch Cops on Fox or The World's Scariest Police
Chases?''
</P>
<P>
   Ready, set, go!
</P>
<P>
   If, starting at noon Monday, PAX TV stalls and eventually goes
bust, Bud Paxson will be down to his last few million, his faith
and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter Nicole, 15, goes to the Alexander W. Dreyfoos Jr.
School of the Arts. Another daughter, Julie, lives in Cleveland.
(Her dad guards her age. ``She'd kill me if I told.'') His son,
Devin, 33, owns seven TV stations and lives on Palm Beach. Devin's
sons, Austin, 3, and Dakota, 9 months, are Paxson's only
grandchildren. Paxson's son Todd, 36, raises dogs and horses in
Loxahatchee.
</P>
<P>
   If PAX TV sinks, Paxson's third wife, Marla, may not get to host
her show, Celebrities &AMP; Charities, scheduled for spring.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he has any aspirations to do his own show, Paxson
scoffs. ``No, never. You do what you do best. I do one thing best,
build companies. Do the impossible. I'm Don Quixote. Let's go.
Dream the impossible dream.''
</P>
<P>
   PAX TV go bust? Paxson delights in skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all the naysayers _ I've been in the kitchen preparing
crow. Get ready for a feast.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
