<HEADER>
A0631 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-LATINAS01-COX     08-31 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LATINAS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foundation seeks to aid Latinas in public service
 &HT;    By Suzanne Gamboa
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Whether their public office experiences ended amid
embarrassment, scandal or defeat, Lena Guerrero, Nora Linares and
Christine Hernandez gained one important thing from their
government careers: experience.
</P>
<P>
   And it's that experience that the three former Texas public
officials said they can pass on to other Latinas looking to enter
the world of public leadership in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other Texas Latinas, the three are forming the Latina
Foundation, an organization they hope will help teach young,
ambitious Hispanic women interested in public service what they
need to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience that Nora and I had, as difficult as it seemed
to be, we hope to teach others what we've learned,'' said Guerrero,
whose campaign for Railroad Commission and political career ended
amid revelations that she had lied about her educational
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero, who also was an Austin representative in the Texas
House, was a panelist at the Region 5 conference of the National
Association of Hispanic Journalists. The conference drew
journalists from across Texas under the theme of ``Countdown to the
Millennium: The Latino Legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the audience for the panel that included Guerrero was
Linares, former director of the Texas Lottery Commission, and state
Rep. Hernandez, a San Antonio Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Linares was fired in 1997 after confirming that her close friend
had worked as a consultant for lottery operator Gtech. She has
since reached a legal settlement with Gtech over her dismissal.
Hernandez lost an expensive campaign to replace U.S. Rep. Henry B.
Gonzalez in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we go out and speak to people, they say, `How did you get
involved? How did you get into politics?' '' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost a campaign for which she raised $300,000, Hernandez
said she can teach other Latinas not only how to wage a campaign,
but also how to raise money for a campaign. Lack of money, she
said, intimidates many Latina women and keeps them from running for
elective office.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Latina Foundation was informally organized in 1997,
Guerrero said the group of Latinas _ ``a handful of us'' _ is
trying to obtain nonprofit status. The lessons members can pass on
range from the practical _ ``don't wear orange; you don't look good
in it'' _ to the professional _ ``when you want public apologies,
call me, because I can write them,'' Guerrero said in a blend of
English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said many Latinas will begin their careers as a school
board member, a county commissioner or a local court judge. But as
a neophyte politician, a Latina may not have handled something like
a bond issue. Hernandez said the Latina Foundation hopes to provide
practical advice for such day-to-day issues.
</P>
<P>
   And being the center of controversy also has its lessons,
Linares said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned something, and we want to teach others what we
learned,'' she said of herself and Guerrero. ``There are issues
that happen around you that we don't have any control over.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
