<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0634 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-UT-STADIUM01-COX     08-31 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-UT-STADIUM01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT stadium gets all decked out
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When the Texas Longhorns meet the New Mexico
State Aggies on the field, the average Texas fan will encounter a
bigger, prettier stadium that athletics officials swear on their
playbooks will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   Three shifts of construction crews have been working around the
clock for the past three months to finish a massive renovation of
Royal-Memorial Stadium's east side, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It is down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday, power saws, scaffolding, lumber, paint, drop
cloths, insulation, forklifts and all manner of construction tools
were strewn from the ground level to all five upper levels, with
crews creating a cacophonous roar. It will all be gone by kickoff,
said George Abikhaled, senior project manager of the University of
Texas System Office of Facilities Planning and Construction.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, athletics officials are so sure the public areas of the
stadium will be ready, they are planning to show off the east side
at an open house from 5 to 7 p.m. Thursday. Those who want a peek
at the public areas _ no club areas or skyboxes _ should come to
the east-side entrances off East Campus Drive, which recently
reopened to traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having this open house because it's so different-looking
we're afraid people will be confused when they come here on game
day,'' said Chris Plonsky, associate athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   The formerly grungy east side will become the ``sexiest side of
the stadium,'' Plonsky predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The east side was decrepit. It was horrible,'' she said. ``I
wouldn't go to the women's restroom over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the dark, dank interior concourse has been transformed into
a bright, airy space that's been expanded outward toward the field.
It boasts three times as many women's restrooms; new concession
stands; 50 skyboxes, or luxury suites; two new clubs for the
well-heeled; and a new 5,535-seat upper deck, expanding the
stadium's capacity to 79,438 seats.
</P>
<P>
   A similarly overhauled west side, with 14 luxury suites, a
festival-style mezzanine and novelty stands, made its debut last
season.
</P>
<P>
   What the average fan won't notice next Saturday are two stadium
projects that won't quite be ready: a club open to 1,262 donors who
will sit in new chair-back seats on the east side and certain
improvements to the Moncrief-Neuhaus Athletic Complex, which abuts
the stadium on the south side. Both are scheduled to be completed
by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the club, which has been named the University of Texas
Club, will be open for the first game to the 700 donors who have
purchased seats so far. Because the kitchen isn't done, food will
be brought in by the operator, Club Corporation of America. CCA is
also catering the luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   A contract is being finalized for the club, which will remain
open year-round for faculty, staff and alumni to dine in and
entertain guests. The club, along with the massive spending on
renovations and other athletics projects in the past two years, now
totaling $94.9 million, has fueled faculty concerns that the
university overemphasizes sports.
</P>
<P>
   Plonsky stressed Friday on a tour of the stadium that no tax
dollars are being used for the projects.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the east-side upper deck, she pointed to the roof of
the Moncrief-Neuhaus Athletic Complex, in the south end zone, where
the End Zone Club is returning this year. Another party spot for
donors, the club will be visible to fans in the stadium. It will be
open next Saturday, but the second floor of the athletic complex
won't. That floor houses coaches' offices and the Champions' Room,
a sort of Longhorn hall of fame featuring trophies, memorabilia and
a replica of former Coach Darrell Royal's office. Officials expect
it to be open to the public by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic complex project got behind when Diamond
Construction went bankrupt and another contractor, Silverton
Construction Co. Inc., had to take over, Abikhaled said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the east side, fans will see a new banner scoreboard on
the upper deck, Big 12 Conference school flags across the top and
towers at either end.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the west side, where the outer facade is concrete gray,
the east side is pale orange and cream brick, similar to campus
academic buildings.
</P>
<P>
   All 14 skyboxes on the west side have been leased, but 20 of 50
remain on the east side, ranging in cost from $50,000 to $60,000 a
year. Athletics officials had predicted that all would be gone by
the season's start. Since they won't be, some suites will be leased
on a game-by-game basis at a cost of $8,000 for a regular game to
$12,000 for the Texas A&AMP;M game Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Two suites have been converted to the Touchdown Club, which has
36 seats being sold to season ticket holders by the pair at $7,000
for both. The buyers get free food and beverage service. So far, 12
seats have been sold, Plonsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still going to close on four or five more suites next
week, I think,'' Plonsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Some students, meanwhile, are unhappy to be losing 1,800 seats
near the field. They'll be moved to the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   There will be 2,800 seats for students in the new upper deck, a
net gain of 1,000 seats, said Mark Harrison, athletics ticket
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But Luke Mislinski, 21, a senior chemical engineering major,
said he hated to see the students moved. He liked being close to
the band and the players. The students make a lot of noise, which
is ``demoralizing to the visiting team,'' he said. ``I hate for us
to lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   Check out www.austin360.com to see a video of the completed
stadium, and while you're there, tell us what you think about the
renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-29-98 0023E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
