<HEADER>
A0635 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-CHARITY01-COX     08-31 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-CHARITY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What Diana did for charity
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diana's enormous impact on charity during her 16 years as
princess of Wales is undisputed. But, even a year after her death,
she continues to influence charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
   Her legacy reverberates in the $114 million raised by her
memorial fund. In her example of hands-on volunteerism still
broadcast around the world. And in the increased focus her efforts
continue to bring to such causes as land-mine victims, cancer and
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to say that someone's death was timely,'' says David
Walker, executive director of Hope House, Palm Beach County's
largest residential provider for AIDS patients. ``But it occurred
just as we were establishing a program for children who have AIDS
and those who'll be orphaned because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the heightened attention brought to Diana after her
death, there was also heightened attention brought to the things
she cared most about,'' he says. ``While we haven't experienced any
increase in funding, there has most certainly been an increase in
awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   Local agencies _ such as the American Cancer Society, American
Heart Association and American Red Cross chapters based in West
Palm Beach _ report no surge in donations directly linked to Diana,
but on the national level, charitable giving has risen
substantially, according to the American Association of
Fund-Raising Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Americans contributed $143 billion to charity last year _ up 7.5
percent from the $ 133 billion given in 1996. Even adjusted for
inflation, donations rose 5.1 percent in 1997, making it the
greatest increase since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Research director Ann Kaplan attributes that boost not only to
Diana's death _ which thrust her charitable works into the
spotlight _ but also to the death of Mother Teresa Sept. 5 and
attention given to huge individual donations, such as media mogul
Ted Turner's $1 billion pledge to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Langan, spokesman for the National Charities Information
Bureau, says generosity extended beyond Great Britain after the
Aug. 31 car crash that killed the princess.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the incredible amounts of money being sent to
her foundation, there were an awful lot of people giving to
American charities,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But regardless of where the money went, it's safe to say she
had a remarkable impact, and it's still very much going on.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the Diana, Princess of Wales Memorial Fund was
established just days after her death, donations poured in and
continue to do so at a rate of $113,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   But there also has been controversy.
</P>
<P>
   First, the fund's legal team was found to have charged $800,000
for a few weeks' work. (The bill was later cut by 20 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Then, the fund allowed a food company that was sponsoring the
London Marathon to emblazon Diana's signature _ in the royal color
purple _ on tubs of Flora margarine. British commentators and the
princess' brother, Earl Spencer, were horrified.
</P>
<P>
   Companies must make a hefty donation to the fund to be
sanctioned, and more than 200 a week apply, but fund trustees have
been conservative since the margarine fiasco. They've licensed only
seven items: a Beanie Baby bear, a crystal candle holder, scented
candles, a tribute CD, a set of postage stamps, a set of enamel
boxes and a photograph of flowers piled outside Kensington Palace
by mourners.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute CD has raised nearly $23 million, and the postage
stamps $14.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest money-raiser so far, however, has been Elton John's
recording of ``Candle in the Wind 1997,'' which has raked in more
than $30 million. John's CD isn't licensed, but all proceeds are
directed to the memorial fund.
</P>
<P>
   (The 500 British charities that raise the most in private
donations, meanwhile, earned $7.2 billion last year _ an 11 percent
increase over 1996, according to ``The Chronicle of Philanthropy.''
Many attribute that gain, at least in part, to the emphasis given
charities after Diana's death.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite its role in memorializing Diana, the fund isn't linked
to any events marking the one-year anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first place, this is out of respect for the family,''
spokeswoman Jo Greenstead told Reuters news service. ``And, as it
says in the mission statement, the fund doesn't want to stimulate
the emotions that surround the memory of the princess.''
</P>
<P>
   The memory of the princess is best sustained, perhaps, by things
like the international treaty banning land mines, recently ratified
by the British parliament. And by the $3.25 million _ raised by the
sale of her dresses two months before the crash _ now being used by
AIDS and cancer charities worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, Princess Diana is the gift that keeps on
giving,'' says Stephen Lee, director of Britain's Institute of
Charity Fund-Raising Managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her overall effect on charity is probably more significant
than any other person's in the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff researchers Lynne Palombo and Barbara Gellis Shapiro
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
