<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0636 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-CRUISE01-COX     08-31 1600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-CRUISE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A whole new world for first time cruisers
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas _ The white-jacketed Austrian waiter brought out
china trays, and with a grand flourish set them down on the table
amid stemmed crystal and English china.
</P>
<P>
   On each tray was a gourmet feast of five appetizers including
smoked salmon rosettes with capers, duck and vegetable spring
rolls, and wild mushroom bisque.
</P>
<P>
   The two women from Illinois took one look at it and screeched in
unison: ``Oooooh, gross!''
</P>
<P>
   Other adults, and their numerous children, at surrounding tables
also were not interested in this weird food.
</P>
<P>
   This scenario _ sophisticated amenities and passengers mystified
by them _ was repeated throughout my recent three-day cruise on
Disney Cruise Line's gorgeous new Disney Magic mega-cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   My traveling companion also was grossed out by the menu. She
skipped the escargot and went straight for the pizza. She was my
8-year-old niece, Ruby Hernandez, who I borrowed from my sister in
order to get a kid's viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian waiter, who had come to the ship from the Queen
Elizabeth 2, complimented one guest on her dress and bent down and
kissed her hand. The woman jerked her hand back and she and her
husband, who was wearing a tank top and shorts, exchanged looks
that said, ``Gross!''
</P>
<P>
   A guest on the QE2 probably would have been pleased by the
waiter's attentiveness _ indeed, would have expected it.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the Magic's passengers were first-time
cruisers who were taking the ship as part of a seven-day package.
They spend three or four days at Disney World and three or four
days on the Magic, which cruises out of Port Canaveral and goes to
Nassau and Disney's island, Castaway Cay, in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Most passengers had children in tow, except for 350 honeymoon
couples (a natural extension of Disney World's wedding pavilion).
And the crew was extremely kid-friendly. Waiters, room stewards and
even maintenance workers made a point of greeting children along
with adults and would bend down to their level to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian waiter automatically wiped pizza sauce off Ruby's
face as he chatted with her, and he asked each child at our table
what they did that day.
</P>
<P>
   But this ship does not have the ambience of a theme park and
Minnie and Mickey are not omnipresent. In fact, you have to check
the schedule for the times of their appearances around the ship.
</P>
<P>
   The $350 million Magic, which debuted July 30, is as elegant as
any ship afloat and has service equal to those that cost twice as
much.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the high-rise Marriott-sized atriums and flashy neon
lights of many new mega-ships, the Magic has a majestic three-story
atrium-lobby with two graceful curved staircases, and subdued
lighting that would befit an elegant inn. Artwork, particularly
drawings from Disney cartoons in the 1930s and '40s, lines
wood-paneled walls.
</P>
<P>
   Our room had beveled glass over a desk, sleek wood furniture,
and art including a sketch from Pirates of the Caribbean in 1965
and a black and white portrait of Mr. and Mrs. Walt Disney taken on
the deck of a ship in 1934. Our balcony had a cushioned bench, a
great nook for reading a book, a chair and weather instruments
including a compass and barometer.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the passengers on my cruise didn't appreciate the
magic of The Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers complained about the size of the cabins, calling them
closets. They didn't realize that the Magic's cabins, most with
sofas, queen-sized beds, desks _ and almost half with balconies _
are 25 percent larger than the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   And unprecedented on ships _ many rooms have two bathrooms, one
with a toilet and vanity, the other with a bathtub and vanity.
</P>
<P>
   They complained about the rubbery theme park hamburgers and
dried pizza offered at bars on the swimming pool deck. They might
not have been informed judges of the herb-crusted baked salmon with
Zinfandel glaze, but they knew a mediocre hamburger when they saw
it.
</P>
<P>
   But if the marble floors, chandeliers, sleek black terrazzo
floors and Art Deco columns in the French restaurant were lost on
them, they appreciated other things:
</P>
<P>
   The Disney camp, called the Oceaneer Club, covers almost an
entire deck and includes a computer and science room for older
children, and costume room and theater for small children. The camp
keeps children entertained from 8 a.m. to 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby loved the camp, and I had a hard time tearing her away from
it. On the second night, I picked her up at midnight and she
implored me to stay until it closed at 1 a.m. I relented _ how
could I resist with ``Never had a friend like me'' from Aladdin
playing in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most camps on other ships, the Disney club also takes
children to dinner. Parents could take their children on this
cruise and never see them except at bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   When parents or guardians register their kids, they are given
beepers to keep for the entire cruise so the club is in constant
contact with the parent. If the child is ready to leave, they
message the parent.
</P>
<P>
   Teens have a coffee house just for them, and children have a
pool with a slide and a lifeguard.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Theater, which presented three original plays. There
were stellar performances by actors from Broadway and the English
theater. And even small children were enthralled by the sound
effects and Disney songs and characters.
</P>
<P>
   Castaway Cay, Disney's 1,000-acre island in the Bahamas that has
a dock for the ship, white sand beaches including a mile-long beach
just for adults with massage cabanas, and trails for hiking and
biking.
</P>
<P>
   A day and most of a night in Nassau for gamblers who missed
having a casino on board.
</P>
<P>
   This ship differs from other ships in many ways. There is no
captain's party, no officers mingling with passengers, no tours of
the bridge. The only captain sighting was when he gave a toast at
the huge French restaurant, and left soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   One experienced cruiser and travel agent from Oregon observed
that the ship was run like a hotel, not a ship. She called the
Magic a ``trainer ship'' for those who have never taken a cruise.
</P>
<P>
   There is no casino, no Las Vegas-type shows with dancers in
thongs and elaborate headdresses, and no R-rated comic acts, even
at Disney's comedy theater and three bars just for passengers 18
and over. There were no four-letter words at the comedy
improvisation act I saw. The most risque joke: ``Marv Albert asked
me if I wanted to go out for a bite.''
</P>
<P>
   The Magic also didn't have a cruise director, the comedian/host
who serves as the laugh track for a ship, cracking jokes at
lectures and bingo and serving as master of ceremonies at shows.
</P>
<P>
   At the port lecture and at bingo, pleasant, and bland, young
women served as hosts.
</P>
<P>
   The general atmosphere of the ship was sedate, a far cry from
the rowdiness of Carnival ships.
</P>
<P>
   Another invention: Passengers play musical chairs at dinner,
changing restaurants each night, and taking their waiters with
them. On arrival, passengers receive tickets telling them the time
and which restaurant and which table they have each night.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange mix on the Disney Magic _ a ship so
sophisticated, it recalls the ocean liners from another era. But
experienced passengers would be appalled by the tank tops at
dinner, and all the children.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there is a restaurant, pool and three bars for
adults only, there is no getting away from Disney and kids. On what
other ship would announcements begin, ``Ladies and gentlemen, boys
and girls. ''
</P>
<P>
   If passengers weren't passionate about Disney, they would
quickly tire of listening to Disney tunes. They would soon be
humming ``It's a whole new world ... '' whether they liked it or
not.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if passengers are bringing children and/or
they are extremely pure of heart and love Disney, the Magic is the
ship for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic is, indeed, a whole new world.
</P>
<P>
   Island is all Disney, all fun _ all business
</P>
<P>
   CASTAWAY CAY, Bahamas _ Disney Cruise Line's Disney Magic docked
at this tiny Disney-owned island just after the sun came up.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 8:30 a.m., about 2,000 adults and children started
walking off the gangways loaded down with masks, fins and suntan
lotion, and boarded a Disney-style tram bound for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   A band played Jimmy Buffett songs and pretty soon the long white
stretch of sand was as busy as Disney World's Blizzard Beach on a
summer afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of kids went to the Oceaneer Club's camp for arts, crafts,
storytelling and games.
</P>
<P>
   Their parents, and the adults without kids, boarded the tram
again and went to the quiet mile-long adults-only beach. They
pulled lounge chairs into the shallow water, and drank beer, eyes
closed against the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby were open-air cabanas, where they could get massages, and
a beach-side cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Other Magic passengers rented bikes and rode the miles of paths
shaded by towering pines.
</P>
<P>
   And back at the main beach, there were kayaks, sailboats, paddle
boats and rafts.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue was available at a covered pavilion with picnic tables
that offered views of coconut palms and the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,000-acre island, formerly Gorda Cay, is in the Abacos. No
one lives on the island anymore except for 70 Disney employees, who
live here in six-month shifts.
</P>
<P>
   But when the ship is in, the island comes to life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
