<HEADER>
A0637 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-CLONE01-COX     08-31 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-CLONE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Canine cloning more byte than bark
 &HT;    Has sidebar: DOG-WEBSITE
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven years ago, Missy was a cast-off, a mixed-breed stray
taken home from the pound only after a long night of second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   She turned out to be one charming dog.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of life without her, even through it's probably a
few years down the road, prompted her owners to donate $2.3 million
to Texas A&AMP;M researchers to try cloning their precious pet.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are a mystery, described only as rich dog lovers. But
Missy's life is an open Web page (http://www.missyplicity.com), her
allure explained in part by pictures and anecdotes with titles
like, ``How Missy Found A Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Missy-laneous revelations:
</P>
<P>
   _ She wasn't her owners' first love. She was taken in as a
companion for Liebe, a shepherd-coyote mix who was 15 and ailing.
Missy, about 4 months old and frisky, recognized Liebe's frailty
and became her faithful protector.
</P>
<P>
   _ Missy earned her owners' ``permanent love'' on a stormy night
when she led a search to rescue Liebe, who was tangled in thick
brush and branches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Missy's beauty draws constant compliments from people who want
a dog like her, but her background is a mystery. The owners
describe her as ``the dog equivalent of a Rorschach test: People
see the breed or blend they want to see.'' The best guess is part
collie, part husky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Missy loves to howl with the coyotes and chase cats. But if a
cat stops and hisses, Missy stops and lies down.
</P>
<P>
   Although the first news reports of the cloning appeared this
week, Missy's Web site has been drawing attention for months.
Messages posted from around the world show strong feelings for and
against the attempt, which is considered far more complicated than
the Scottish sheep experiment that created Dolly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why clone a dog when you can just as well go out and buy
one?'' asked one message. The reply from the project's coordinator:
``True, our client could go buy another dog. But he's never met a
dog like Missy.''
</P>
<P>
   Conventional breeding is ruled out because Missy's been fixed.
Even if she hadn't been, cloning is the only way to duplicate her
mixed-breed genetic traits.
</P>
<P>
   That means any clone will look like Missy, but personality is
less certain: There's no guarantee any animal clone would be as
lovable as the original.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't discouraged inquiries from numerous pet owners,
including one who wrote: ``About a year ago, even before Dolly was
heard from, I dreamed the idea of cloning our cat, Walter.''
</P>
<P>
   While cat cloning is not in the research group's plans, success
with Missy could lead to commercially available dog cloning costing
thousands rather than millions, the researchers suggest. But the
first Missy pups, if there are any, are probably two years away.
</P>
<P>
   It's already too late for one Italian dog lover, who asked the
Missy team to advise colleagues in her country on how to begin
duplicating her pet. The initial reply was cautious but encouraged
further correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   Her second message included one detail that dashed all hope: The
dog was buried three months ago. Until tissue-preservation
techniques are perfected, only owners of live pets need apply.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
