<HEADER>
A0638 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-WEBSITES01-COX     08-31 0214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-WEBSITES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fetch some dog trivia off the web
 &HT;    Sidebar to DOG-CLONE
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missy may make history as the first dog cloned, but she's too
late to be first with a page on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever impels people to think everyone will be fascinated by
their musical taste or reading habits also leads to sites like
``TRAMP Our Barking Cocker!'' (http://4peaks.com/ftramp.htm).
</P>
<P>
   Many pets get prominent positions on owners' Web pages, which
have grown increasingly common as they've become easier to make and
dirt cheap or even free to post.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of sites dedicated to specific breeds,
such as Scottish terriers (http://w3.ag.uiuc.edu/VJR/Scottie.html)
and a profusion of commercial and advice sites like, ``The Dog
Owner's Guide'' (http://www.canismajor.com/dog/guide.html) and Dog
World Magazine (http://www.dogworld mag.com).
</P>
<P>
   Of all the dog-related sites on the Web, the most unusual may be
the Virtual Pet Cemetery (http://www.lavamind.com/pet.html). It's
an ``online burial ground'' where loving tributes allow Misty the
brown mutt and many others to byte long after their last bark.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
