<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Storms in 'the box' can delay home sales, insurance
 &HT;    By Paul Owers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coast is clear now, but would-be home buyers and sellers
should watch the Atlantic for storms that could abruptly stop
residential real estate deals.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bonnie postponed some closings in Palm Beach County
and the Treasure Coast earlier this week when it entered ``the
box.'' When a tropical storm or hurricane blows into the box _
stretching from the Gulf of Mexico to the Dominican Republic and
from North Carolina to Honduras _ the two state-created insurers of
last resort won't issue policies.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Residential Property &AMP; Casualty Joint Underwriting
Association, which provides basic homeowner insurance, and the
Florida Windstorm Underwriting Association, which insures against
wind damage only, stopped writing policies Monday, after Bonnie
crossed into the box over the weekend. The insurers resumed issuing
policies Thursday, after the storm moved out.
</P>
<P>
   But Hurricane Danielle or subsequent storms could enter the box
before hurricane season ends Nov. 30 _ meaning the insurance window
would slam shut again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's foolish to wait to get coverage,'' Jay Newman, executive
director of the JUA, said Friday. ``We estimate that if Danielle
follows the same track as Bonnie, it'll be in the box Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   As the six-month hurricane season enters its busiest period,
real estate agents have been scrambling to help their clients get
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Some home buyers planned ahead, buying coverage before their
closings, but others waited until Bonnie was breathing down on the
Southeast, said Mickey Bradley, president of the St. Lucie
Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had problems with some closings,'' he said. ``It can be a
huge inconvenience for a seller who has a moving truck in his
driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the windstorm pool is not writing policies, home
buyers still should have their agents fax insurance information to
the agency's headquarters in Jacksonville and send checks and
photos of houses, spokesman Alan Cook said. The pool will make the
coverage effective as soon as it resumes writing policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be careful and get your ducks in a row,'' said
John Pinson, managing broker at Prudential Florida Realty in Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Most private insurers, such as State Farm, don't use the box,
instead choosing to stop writing policies only when a particular
county is under a watch or warning for a tropical storm or
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the box is too restrictive,'' said Tom Hagerty,
spokesman for State Farm. ``Under that box, a Realtor in
Tallahassee wouldn't be able to issue a policy even though there's
no imminent threat of a hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   The windstorm pool and the JUA insure homeowners who are unable
to buy coverage on the private market.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, the windstorm pool, created in 1970,
covers ho
</P>
<P>
   Private insurers not affected by 'box'
</P>
<P>
   mes east of Interstate 95 from PGA Boulevard south to the
Broward County line and east of Alternate A1A from PGA north to the
Martin County line. In St. Lucie County, it covers homes within
1,000 feet of the coast. The windstorm pool does not insure homes
in Martin County.
</P>
<P>
   The JUA, established after Hurricane Andrew in August 1992, grew
to 937,000 polices in the fall of 1996. Officials have since
transferred 700,000 policies to private insurers. It now has more
than 42,000 policies in Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties.
</P>
<P>
   State law bars the JUA from offering wind coverage in windstorm
pool areas.
</P>
<P>
   If a home in the windstorm pool area can't get coverage anywhere
else, it must buy wind coverage from the pool and basic homeowner
coverage from the JUA.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
