<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rexall to close vitamin production plant in Idaho
 &HT;    By Phil Galewitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Rexall Sundown Inc. plans to close an Idaho
vitamin manufacturing plant and will shift production to its Boca
Raton and Deerfield Beach facilities.
</P>
<P>
   About 12 to 18 of the Idaho plant's 110 employees are interested
in transferring to South Florida and have been offered jobs, Rexall
President Damon DeSantis said recently. The rest decided not to
apply and will be laid off, DeSantis said.
</P>
<P>
   The 62,000-square-foot plant in Meridian, Idaho, was owned by
Richardson Labs, a vitamin and diet products maker that Rexall
bought in January for $98 million in stock. Richardson's main
product is the diet supplement Ultra Chroma Slim.
</P>
<P>
   Rexall said it expects to hire about six more employees, in
addition to those who transfer from Idaho, to handle the increased
local production. Boca Raton-based Rexall employs about 1,300
people at its Boca Raton and Deerfield facilities.
</P>
<P>
   DeSantis said it makes sense to consolidate operations to save
money. But when the deal was made, Rexall (Nasdaq: RXSD, $21) and
Richardson officials said the Idaho plant would remain open.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
