   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ One thing I don't recall saying in the
confessional was that I'd done something ``inappropriate.'' I just
said guilty again, Lord, and hoped for a break. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSE-TEACHERS _ Who should choose your child's teacher? These
days more and more parents are getting involved, trying to choose
the right teacher for their children. During this week of school
many parents will be trying to switch their children from one class
to another, to avoid ``bad'' teachers and get ``good'' ones.
Principals resist, because trying to accomodate parents can produce
a scheduling nightmare. Still some parents will insist, because
their children are at stake. ``I decided I had
</P>
<P>
   to fight,'' says Barbara Dale, mother of two. (Emerson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH ILLUSTRATION, PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSE-TEACHERS-TIPS _ Tips for parents.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-CHARITY _ Diana's enormous impact on charity during her 16
years as princess of Wales is undisputed. But, even a year after
her death, she continues to influence charitable giving. Her legacy
reverberates in the $114 million raised by her memorial fund. In
her example of hands-on volunteerism still broadcast around the
world. And in the increased focus her efforts continue to bring to
such causes as land-mine victims, cancer and AIDS. (Grantham, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DOG-CLONE _ Eleven years ago, Missy was a cast-off, a
mixed-breed stray taken home from the pound only after a long night
of second thoughts. She turned out to be one charming dog. The
thought of life without her, even through it's probably a few years
down the road, prompted her owners to donate $2.3 million to Texas
A&AMP;M researchers to try cloning their precious pet. (Kalajian, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DOG-WEBSITE _ Missy may make history as the first dog cloned,
but she's too late to be first with a page on the World Wide Web.
Whatever impels people to think everyone will be fascinated by
their musical taste or reading habits also leads to sites like
``TRAMP Our Barking Cocker!'' (http://4peaks.com/ftramp.htm).
(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-CRUISE _ NASSAU, Bahamas _ The white-jacketed Austrian
waiter brought out china trays, and with a grand flourish set them
down on the table amid stemmed crystal and English china. The two
women from Illinois took one look at it and screeched in unison:
``Oooooh, gross!'' The vast majority of the Magic's passengers were
first-time cruisers who were taking the ship as part of a seven-day
package. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KID-CRUISE _ The Disney Magic was docked at Cape Canaveral. I
was the first one to see it! We were driving on a bridge over the
Banana River in Cape Canaveral. I screamed, ``Tia, Tia (that's my
aunt)! I think I see the ship!'' Our room was a kid's heaven. It
had a big bed. On the wall, it said, ``A dream is a wish your heart
makes,'' a song from Cinderella, which goes dah dah dah-dah-dah ...
(Hernandez, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   SUGAR _ Sugar is under attack. No, it's not the
environmentalists this time. It's not the free-trade crowd. And
it's not the South Florida Water Management District or the U.S.
Army Corps of Engineers. The new foe is a best-selling diet book
called Sugar Busters! It's raising anew all those nagging questions
about the health effects of sugar _ one of Florida's most lucrative
agricultural products. (Utley, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
