<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TITANIC-VIDEO01-COX     08-31 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-VIDEO01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titanic, the video, hopes to make another big splash
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will our level of curiosity over the RMS Titanic ever sink?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Monday August 31, at midnight, videocassettes of Titanic _ the
most financially successful movie in history, which re-creates the
maiden voyage of the least successful ocean liner of all time _ go
on sale.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount Home Video has shipped between 20-26 million
videocassettes to stores, a record high for pre-sale copies,
according to industry estimates. It foresees Titanic becoming the
all-time video champ, topping Disney's 25-30 million sales of The
Lion King.
</P>
<P>
   The 6,000-store Blockbuster Video chain agrees, stocking its
outlets with so many copies of the two-cassette video that it
guarantees the movie will be available to rent. Video Avenue is
issuing a similar promise, noting that it expects to stock each
store with 200 rental copies.
</P>
<P>
   But can there be anyone left on the planet who hasn't already
viewed the $200 million epic?
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that everyone and his brother has already seen
Titanic, but our research suggests that's actually not the case,''
says Blockbuster Video corporate relations director Liz Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they just want to see it again. Blockbuster research
indicates that 43 percent of ``active video renters'' _ those
renting at least once in the past three months _ are likely to buy
a copy of the movie, even though 61 percent of those polled has
already seen it.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster, Video Avenue and Best Buy stores will be among
those feeding the Titanic frenzy by staying open after midnight to
sell and rent the 11-time Oscar winner.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the movie has already brought in more than $600 million in
theaters in the United States, and an estimated $1.8 billion
worldwide. Yes, it has played in Palm Beach County and the Treasure
Coast for 35 consecutive weeks since its release in December, and
is still on the big screen at the Value Cinemas in Lantana.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean there's an iceberg in sight for video
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Dorrit Ragosine, Paramount Home Video's executive director for
public relations, says a reasonable video sales estimate would be
around $400 million. The number comes from multiplying the copies
shipped by the minimum retail price of $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Many outlets, like Blockbuster, are selling the coveted tapes at
$24.99, with various pre-order rebates and future rental bonuses.
Going up against Paramount's pricing guidelines are such Internet
firms as Reel.com (www.reel
</P>
<P>
   .com), selling the Titanic tape for $9.99, plus $3.85 for
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   King of the world film director James Cameron personally
supervised the pan-and-scan reframing of the movie to make it fit
the squarer format of television screens. The video is also
available in a wide-screen, letterbox version, though fewer than 4
million copies of that format have been shipped.
</P>
<P>
   And no, the video version does not contain extra ``director's
cut'' footage not previously seen in theaters. ``James was asked
that at a press conference,'' notes Ragosine. ``While he was
flattered that anyone would want to see more after a three-hour
(and 14 minute) movie, there are no such plans at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   `TITANIC' BY
</P>
<P>
   THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Number of Titanic videos: 20-26 million
</P>
<P>
   Ratio of videos to U.S. citizens: 1-to-13.4
</P>
<P>
   Estimated box office and video sales: $2.2 billion
</P>
<P>
   Gross National Product of San Marino: $408 million
</P>
<P>
   Cost of two-cassette video: $24.99
</P>
<P>
   Cost of matinee at Value Cinemas in Lantana: $1.50
</P>
<P>
   Miles of videotape needed to make Titanic copies: 6.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Number of times that would stretch around the planet: 260
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
