<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0649 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORT-REFORM01-COX     08-31 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORT-REFORM01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyers get out ``big guns''
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service Palm Beach Post Capital Bureau
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The cardboard flier features an automatic
pistol, opens ominously to a warning that state Rep. Bill Andrews
refused to disarm wife beaters.
</P>
<P>
   A missive from an abused women's shelter? A gun-control group?
</P>
<P>
   For Andrews and four other suddenly-vulnerable lawmakers, its
something far more threatening: the unleashed vengeance of
Florida's trial lawyers, who through a front group have dumped
$371,000 worth of mailers, broadcast and ``push polls'' against the
legislators, all five of whom supported a measure limiting
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivation is clear: I voted straight party line on `tort
reform,' '' said Andrews, R-Delray Beach, who until the past two
weeks had been expecting a relatively easy primary campaign against
an unknown opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he and four other lawmakers have seen the past
legislative session's most divisive bill now become possibly the
most lethal issue of this election season. Andrews will attacked
with $21,373 worth of mailings and phone ``polls'' by Tuesday's
primary, according to records filed with the state Division of
Elections. Rep. Rick Minton, D-Fort Pierce, is being hit with
$18,713 in mailings and phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles William, D-Live Oak, is the biggest target, with
$200,969 in ads _ including radio and television spots _ urging his
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Carruthers, executive director of the Academy of Florida
Trial Lawyers, said his group promised during this spring's debate
they would involve themselves in the races of legislators who sided
with large corporations at the expense of injured consumers. ``We
intend to let voters know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The meddling has infuriated Republican leaders, some of whom
have said their push for the law was repayment for all the help
they received from business interests in taking control of the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker-designate Rep. John Thrasher, that chamber's chief
architect of the bill, has hinted he might try to hold a special
session this fall to override Gov. Lawton Chiles' veto that kept
the law from taking effect _ unless trial lawyers stop their ads
and work toward a compromise. ``Maybe there won't be a need,''
Thrasher said.
</P>
<P>
   And state GOP chairman Tom Slade complained that the group
actually sponsoring the ads _ the Coalition for Family Safety,
which lists numerous environmental and consumer groups among its
members but draws much of its money from the trial bar _ is
violating tax laws by running political ads despite its tax-exempt
status.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition president Charlie Roberts, though, called that a
``bogus argument'' intended to deflect attention from the five
legislators' voting records. He said IRS regulations prohibit his
group from donating to particular campaigns, not from exercising
their first-amendment rights. ``The IRS code is not intended to
muzzle citizens and it doesn't muzzle us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One beneficiary of the ads, meanwhile, said she was grateful for
the help although she doesn't know anything about her benefactors.
``It's nice of them of them to do it,'' said Michelle Nemo, a Lake
Worth resident and Minton's opponent Tuesday in the Democratic
primary for the District 78 House seat.
</P>
<P>
   Both Minton and Andrews were attacked for voting: against a bill
to prevent those with court injunctions against them in domestic
violence cases from owning a gun; for a bill giving billionaire
Wayne Huizenga a $60 million tax break; and for the tort reform
bill.
</P>
<P>
   In Andrews' race particularly, the last-minute wave of
advertising could prove pivotal. Because supporters assumed he
would coast to re-election, he was only able to raise $28,756 by
Aug. 7, all but $3,000 of which was already spent. The $21,400
spent by the Coalition quadruples the $5,445 that Andrews'
opponent, Rob Ross, had raised by Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Delray Beach resident and Andrews supporter JoAnne Peart, 48,
said she has received two fliers and two phone ``polls'' attacking
him in the past few days. ``I'm afraid it might affect people who
don't really know what's going on,'' she said. ``They'll keep
hammering away, negative, negative, negative, and it just might
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
