<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSILE-POLICY-COX     08-31 1755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-POLICY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Technology transfers have bipartisan history
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When a rocket carrying an American-made commercial
satellite burst into flames over a small village in southern China
one winter day in 1996, mangled metal and debris cascaded down from
the sky, leaving more than 200 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, debris is still crashing down from that fiery
crash, creating havoc in the form of congressional probes that are
examining technology transfers to China and why the licensing
control of commercial satellites was shifted from the State
Department to the more business-friendly Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have seized upon the issue, saying President
Clinton's decision to move jurisdiction to the Commerce Department
in March 1996 placed the nation's security at risk. Rep. Dana
Rohrabacher (R-Calif.) went so far as to warn that ``every man,
woman and child in the United States now is in jeopardy of nuclear
incineration.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thad Cochran (R-Miss.) unleashed criticism on the White
House's export policy, saying it had ``elevated our risk to
national security.'' And Sen. Richard Shelby (R-Ala.) said the
fallout from the satellite crash had resulted in ``the most serious
allegations that I've heard on any administration in the last
eight, 10, 12 years, maybe longer.''
</P>
<P>
   But documents obtained by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and
interviews with officials in the Reagan, Bush and Clinton
administrations show that Republicans were just as aggressive as
Democrats in removing commercial satellites and other high-tech
equipment from a list of exports controlled by the State Department
known as the Munitions List.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus to transfer the jurisdiction from the State
Department to the Commerce Department actually began under
President Reagan, took root under President Bush and became reality
with Clinton's 1996 executive order.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the decision to transfer the approval process to the
Commerce Department had the backing of key Republicans such as
House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) and former Rep. Toby Roth
(R-Wis.), who headed the House International Relations subcommittee
responsible for monitoring export controls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would have approved
</P>
<P>
   Even top Bush administration officials concede that had Bush
been re-elected president in 1992, he likely would have approved
moving the jurisdiction of commercial satellites and other
technology to the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense in the Bush administration that something
was broke in the satellite licensing process,'' said Arnold Kanter,
who worked then at both the National Security Council and State
Department and now is an international business consultant. ``If
Bush had been re-elected, I can easily envision the satellite
transfers going to the Commerce Department.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Transferring that authority from State to Commerce was
legal,'' said Gingrich in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not have been wise, but it was legal. There was a
bipartisan effort to do it,'' added Gingrich, who has kept his
distance from the fray, commenting little on the matter before this
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich also noted that there is a big difference in
transferring the jurisdiction for approving the licensing of
commercial satellites to the Commerce Department and transferring
highly sensitive technology to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what a special select committee appointed by
Gingrich looked at in a series of closed-door sessions last week.
The committee, headed by Rep. Christopher Cox (R-Calif.), is
looking at whether Loral Space and Communications, the maker of the
satellite that exploded, and Hughes Electronics, the company hired
to help figure out what went wrong, put the national security at
risk by helping the Chinese figure out the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats see it, few issues in Congress are as ludicrous as
the Republican allegation that the president put the nation's
security at risk by putting the control of commercial satellites in
the hands of the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt Gingrich signed several letters with me to make that
happen,'' said Rep. Sam Gejdenson (D-Conn.), who worked with Roth
both as chairman and then as ranking member of the export policy
panel. ``This is ridiculous. They are attacking the president
because they don't have an election-year agenda.``
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Roth said the decision to transfer jurisdiction to
Commerce Department was a ``good thing,'' and the congressional
push to return control to the State Department constitutes a
knee-jerk reaction that is not as deliberative as his
subcommittee's hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term ramifications of the debate over jurisdiction is
that the country will lose its stronghold as the top commercial
satellite maker in the world, Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. satellite manufacturers make more than 70 percent of the
world's commercial satellites, but the industry is facing
increasing competition from German and French companies that do not
have to wade through the layers of government that American
companies face, said Clayton Mowry, director of the Satellite
Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   How the decision was made
</P>
<P>
   The satellite industry began lobbying for the transfer to the
Commerce Department in the late 1980s as a result of frustration
over delays in the State Department's approval process.
</P>
<P>
   For years, makers of commercial satellites as well as other
products lobbied to be removed from the State Department's
Munitions List, which is a list of technologies intended for
everyday use but can be used for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The reason?
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of distinctions made that were fairly
arbitrary,'' said William Loughrey, director of governmental
affairs for Scientific-Atlanta, a Georgia-based company that
specializes in cable television, telecommunications and satellite
transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Bush and Clinton administrations,
Scientific-Atlanta sought to remove its ``ground station
equipment,'' which transmits and receives satellite signals, from
the State Department list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make the change from State to Commerce because it
was a faster and more transparent process,'' Loughrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, companies that make equipment on the State
Department list are precluded from selling equipment to certain
countries. Facing competition from abroad, that put
Scientific-Atlanta in a bind. Not only did the State Department
take longer to approve its licenses, it limited the countries where
its products could be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial satellite makers like Hughes faced even more of an
uphill battle. ``Commercial satellites are not weapons,'' said
Steven Dorfman, vice chairman of Hughes Electronics Corp. ``They
are no different than telephone cables and headsets, which might be
used for military communications.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether ``we want to shut down on the spread of
inexpensive global communications and all that means for the free
flow of information and the hope of democracy in China because the
military might also be making phone calls,'' Dorfman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hope for those `on the list'
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the spring of 1995, more than five years after
the first legislative attempt to wrest away jurisdiction from the
State Department, that the satellite makers saw hope in their quest
to transfer jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the Clinton administration appeared to be in
concert with Republican leaders on the Hill, to transfer oversight
authority.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 10, 1995, memo outlining the Republican effort to
make that happen, William Clements, the National Security Council's
director of non-proliferation and export controls, wrote to his
boss Sandy Berger, then the NSC's deputy director and now Clinton's
national security adviser, to say that the chances for legislation
looked promising. Roth, Clements wrote, is ready to do business.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, according to the memo, had told Clements that a number of
key Republicans, including Gingrich, would support an ``export
administration act'' that stripped control of commercial satellites
from the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roth is committed to passing an EAA in this session,'' the
memo states. ``He (Roth) has already talked to the Speaker,
Congressmen Spence and Hunter (of the National Security Committee)
and Senator Bond (chairman of the Senate subcommittee). They were
all supportive. Scientific-Atlanta and IBM are the two largest
employers in the Speaker's district. Both companies have been very
involved in the export control wars. Consequently we believe the
Speaker can be engaged if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The memo is important because it shows that the controversial
decision to transfer the jurisdiction from State to Commerce was a
bipartisan affair. Indeed, in a 1997 letter to Attorney General
Janet Reno outlining why the export policy was changed under the
Clinton administration, Roth sounds slightly like a Clinton
apologist:
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, the administration's export control policy changes
were in response to strong bi-partisan urging by those of us in
Congress who actually had the legislative and oversight
jurisdiction. To us, the administration's efforts were then, and
are today, entirely appropriate to adjust out-of-date Cold War
policies to the new realities of the post-Cold War era and to take
account of the rapid changes in the global availability of high
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for reforms began in the 101st Congress when Bush was
in the Oval Office. Roth and Gejdenson, then-chairman of the export
monitoring panel, heard extensive testimony about the issue for six
years, prior to Clinton's 1996 executive order.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1996, testimony was taken from the top industry
executives about the need for completely overhauling the policy on
export controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes made by the Clinton administration have been
consistent with the recommendations received during those hearings,
which began well before President Clinton was elected,'' Roth wrote
in his letter to Reno.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1995, Roth introduced a bill calling for revising the
export policies to allow commercial satellites, supercomputers, jet
engine technology and telecommunications equipment to be
transferred to the Commerce Department's control.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Clinton signed an executive order doing that, and
more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
