<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Aug. 31, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NUCLEAR (San Francisco) _ The crash and burn of Russia's
economy could inspire the deadliest sort of ``fire sale'' _ the
illegal sale of its nuclear weapons technology to terrorists and
renegade nations, western experts and arms-control advocates warn.
By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-ARREST (San Antonio) _ The brother of an unemployed
laborer shot to death in the house country singer Johnny Rodriguez
was living in said he doesn't believe a defense attorney's account
that his brother was mistaken for an intruder. Rodriguez was
charged with murder and is being held on a $250,000 bond. By KATE
HUNGER and WILEY ALEXANDER.
</P>
<P>
   GIS-SMOKING (San Francisco) _ During the Vietnam War, the U.S.
government gave cigarettes to GIs. About 30 years later, the
government has decided those soldiers ``smoked on government time''
and has prohibited them from receiving disability payments if they
developed lung cancer, emphysema or other diseases from smoking. By
KATHLEEN SULLIVAN;
</P>
<P>
   CAVE-RESCUERS (Schoharie, N.Y.) _ After helping Craig Douglas
get unstuck from a cave last month, the volunteers who put their
lives and jobs on hold in order to save him were stuck holding
bills of their own. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   MAIL-CYANIDE (Albany, N.Y.) _ A state judge, who in 1994
committed a woman to an Albany psychiatric hospital, said his name
appeared on the former patient's list of persons to whom she
allegedly planned to mail packets of sodium cyanide. By MELISSA
GRACE and CAROL DEMARE.
</P>
<P>
   BOTULISM (Albany, N.Y.) _ Grace Wheeler is meticulous about
preventing botulism when she cans home-grown vegetables. But every
three months, she voluntarily gets eight shots of the potentially
lethal toxin injected into the muscles of her neck. This toxin,
tamed and distilled, is being used to treat everything from muscle
disorders to wrinkled skin. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-RIVER (Redwood Valley, Calif.) _ The Russian River is
San Francisco's hot weather playground, a place for canoeing and
swimming and weekend barbecues in the shade of redwood trees. And
all year round, it's an endangered waterway. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHY-TREES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Just because a tree looks good
doesn't mean it's healthy. Tree experts say homeowners can do early
risk detection once they learn to recognize some telltale signs of
poor tree health. Some common problems are unknowingly created by
homeowners thinking they're doing the right thing _ including
overwatering. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   SILK (Albany, N.Y.) _ Fashion materials may come and go, but one
fiber that has remained a mainstay in well-rounded wardrobes is
silk, the oldest and strongest of all natural fibers. Silk fabric
has been valued over the centuries for its luxurious feeling of
softness and for its exceptional ability to be evenly dyed, giving
it a richer appearance than most other dyed fabrics. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GENEALOGIES (Undated) _ ``Genealogies of a Crime''
is a spooky French film by writer-director Raoul Ruiz. The subject
is the ridiculousness of a certain brand of French intellectuality
and Ruiz and co-writer Pascal Bonitzer skewer it with gusto.
Francophiles may find it all irresistible. Moi, non. By BARBARA
SHULGASSER.
</P>
<P>
   ART-EXHIBIT-PRICE (Moraga, Calif.) _ The story of the nascent
American avant-garde centered in New York City has been often told,
but artists outside New York still get little attention. ``C.S.
Price: Landscape, Image and Spirit,'' at the Hearst Art Gallery of
St. Mary's College, attempts to bring critical attention back to at
least one West Coast modernist. By DAVID BONETTI
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Seattle) _ A few things still puzzling you as the old
San Francisco 49ers gear up for a new season? Not sure that this is
your Super Bowl champion a'borning? Well, here's something to tide
you over until next Sunday, anyway. They have a kicker. Maybe.
We're not sure yet. With these guys, we never are. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPREWELL (Oakland, Calif.) _ The last time we saw the Golden
State Warriors' Latrell Sprewell, he had done the unthinkable _
construct a lawsuit so preposterous that a judge laughed him out of
court. Now, he's planning a new lawsuit. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ In October, a black college
student named Jermaine Henderson got into a flap in a bar with a
couple of white, off-duty cops. Henderson either did or did not
sucker-punch one of the cops. They busted him and either did or did
not beat the hell out of him later while he was in cuffs in a
police garage. Leaders of Albany's minority community want the
federal government to investigate the case as a potential civil
rights violation. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   FLORES-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ President Clinton and former
Boston Globe columnist Patricia Smith both suffer from the same
syndrome: It's-not-my-fault-itis. I've had it with both of them. By
VERONICA FLORES.
</P>
</TEXT>
