<HEADLINE>
29.) 
 YOU FILL UP MY CENSUS, EVEN IF I CAN'T FIND YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, August (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Obscured by the debate over whether the Census
Bureau should use statistical sampling to supplement the next
national head count is a little secret: the ``actual enumeration''
mandated by the Constitution never really takes place.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 census, the bureau wants to count everyone who lives
in 90 per cent of the households in each of the country's census
tracts _ neighborhoods containing about 1,700 dwellings each _ and
use the data gathered from them to estimate the remaining 10 per
cent who haven't been located. It would then conduct a nationwide
survey of 750,000 households and use the results to adjust the
official figure up or down.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of sampling say it offends the Constitution, which
mandates an ``actual enumeration'' of the population every 10
years. Their criticism grew even louder last week after a federal
court in Washington said the Census Bureau's plans for using
sampling violated statutes governing how the count is to be
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   When the opponents of sampling say actual enumeration, they mean
just that. ``You have to go nose-by-nose, head-by-head,
neighborhood-by-neighborhood to count people,'' said Pete Jeffries,
spokesman for Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Such comments evoke a dreamy past in which clipboard-toting
census-takers troop through communities counting people one at a
time. But since the first census in 1790, the traditional head
count has been conducted in ways that belie that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a kind of line-up-everybody operation
where the U.S. Marshals or the census enumerators had to actually
see the people,'' said Margo J. Anderson, author of The American
Census: A Social History'' (Yale University Press, 1988).
</P>
<P>
   Conducted in a country that has always loathed heavy-handed
intrusion by its federal government, the census has instead relied
on the word of whoever in the household chooses to provide the
information. If that person gives erroneous information, for
whatever reasons _ personal, political, economic _ no one tries to
verify it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, the Census Bureau moved even further away from the
original idea when it began to mail out census questionnaires, and
generally relied on the information that was sent back. With
mail-back forms, there are no government representatives noting
evidence _ bicycles stacked on the porch, raincoats hanging in the
hall _ that would look the information-giver in the eye and say,
``Are you sure you're the only one living here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, it was a bigger change in census-taking to go from
enumerators going to every house to mailed questionnaires than
anything we're talking about now,'' said Barbara Everitt Bryant,
Director of the Census Bureau during the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   The fall off in the number of households that mail the
questionnaires back _ it dropped to 65 per cent in 1990 from 78 per
cent in 1970 _ is a prime reason the Census Bureau wants to change
its methods. In the 1990 census, counters went back again and again
to households that did not send back the form and to households
where no one was home when a census taker came calling. In some
cases, households were finally contacted as late as August, a major
reason why the 1990 Census had an estimated 26 million errors,
including people missed, people counted twice and people counted in
the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   Since census tallies are used for allocating seats in the House
of Representative and drawing boundaries for legislative districts,
the Census Bureau has to find out not just how many people live in
a given neighborhood but how many people live there on the same
date, April 1 of the census year. Thus, information gathered in
August is barely relevant.
</P>
<P>
   And if a census-taker never is able to catch up to the occupants
of a household at all, he would ask landlords, neighbors,
shop-keepers, even people on the street _ measures that are closer
to guesses than actual enumeration.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau has even used a form of sampling to help fill
in data. In 1970 Census Bureau statisticians sent counters to a
sample of houses that were considered vacant and found that a
percentage of them were in fact occupied. This data were then used
to extrapolate how many people actually lived in the rest of the
nation's presumably vacant dwellings. As a result, a million people
were added.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of sampling say, though, that in the past, those were
measures of last resort. This is the first time the census
deliberately intends not to at least try to count everyone. What's
needed, they say, is for the Census Bureau to merely try harder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
