u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-ISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     08-31 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
29.)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, August The Week in Review  
 (editors: the last item in this package has also moved as a
separate file, DIANA-MARKETING-REVIEW)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reno Orders Inquiry Into Gore Fund Raising
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno ordered a 90-day investigation to
determine whether to seek an independent prosecutor to examine Vice
President Al Gore's fund-raising telephone calls from the White
House during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno first examined Gore's solicitations last year, but absolved
him of wrongdoing, saying she could find no evidence that he knew
the money he raised was ``hard money'' to be spent on behalf of
specific candidates _ a use that Reno said could be illegal.
Federal officials are generally prohibited from raising such money
on government property.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the White House belatedly turned over a November 1995
memorandum with handwritten notations by a senior Gore aide that
suggested Gore could have known some of the contributions were for
the use of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Limited Review Set For King Assassination
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years after Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was assassinated
on the balcony of a motel in Memphis, Attorney General Janet Reno
ordered a review of new evidence that raises questions about the
conviction of James Earl Ray as the sniper who alone killed the
civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   The review, which will be narrower than the full-scale reopening
of the case sought by King's family, will focus on claims like one
by Donald Wilson, a retired FBI agent, who said that after the
killing he found paper in Ray's car that bore the name Raoul. That
was the name of the shadowy figure who Ray, after recanting his
confession, claimed had manipulated him into the plot.
</P>
<P>
   But FBI officials said agents recently investigated Wilson's
claims and found them to be, as one agent put it, ``a total
fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Elusive Terrorist Reported Captured
</P>
<P>
   The elusive Abu Nidal, one of the world's most notorious
terrorists, who has eluded capture for nearly three decades,
appears to have fallen into the hands of Egyptian authorities as a
result of a spying scam.
</P>
<P>
   Despite official denials in Cairo, U.S. and Arab intelligence
officials said the 61-year-old Palestinian, whose real name is
Sabri Al Banna, was double-crossed in a murky spy-against-spy plot
after being used to identify Islamic fundamentalists plotting
terrorist acts in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   _ By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Leaders Vow To Mend Ecological Ways
</P>
<P>
   In his heyday in the late 1950s, Mao Tse-tung called a mass
campaign to kill sparrows, accused of eating too much grain. The
result was disastrous as insect populations soared.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, awareness of ecology in China has changed, to say
the least. But it took this summer's disastrous floods and an
unusual public outcry to jolt the government into admitting past
mistakes and vowing sweeping changes in policy.
</P>
<P>
   As less-than-record rains caused record damage, China said it
would halt logging in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River system
and restore lakes and wetlands downstream that used to soak up
excess water, but were drained to make farms.
</P>
<P>
   Execution will not be easy, since the new policy threatens the
livelihoods of hundreds of thousands of loggers and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIK ECKHOLM
</P>
<P>
   Intel in Antitrust Probe
</P>
<P>
   The government's antitrust investigation of Microsoft has
widened to include the company's dealings with Intel, its
chip-making alter ego.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Microsoft bullied Intel into backing away
from the development of new technology that conflicted with the
software giant's blueprint for the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state investigators, Microsoft replies, are
misreading routine talks between business partners.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Microsoft say the Intel inquiries seem to be a
last-minute effort by the Justice Department and 20 states to
strengthen their slender case, which is scheduled to go to trial
Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVE LOHR
</P>
<P>
   Mother Teresa Workers Killed by Serbs
</P>
<P>
   Three Albanians working for the Mother Teresa aid organization
were killed by cannon fire in Serbia in what appeared to be a
government effort to terrorize aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   The three were hit as they rode on tractors pulling wagons
loaded with supplies for refugees who had fled a government
military offensive in the province of Kosovo. The wagons carried
food and white boxes with large blue circles bearing the name of
the donor, Doctors of the World.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the police, riding in an armored personnel
carrier, could not see what was in the wagons and opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trial for Bomb Suspects
</P>
<P>
   Two suspects in the bombings of U.S. Embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania were brought to the United States to be tried on charges
stemming from the Aug. 7 blasts, in which more than 250 people died
and more than 5,000 were injured. Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-'Owhali
and Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, are to be tried in federal court in New
York City, where Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has ordered increased
security.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   American Quits Iraq Inspection Team
</P>
<P>
   After months of agonizing, William Ritter, the longest-serving
American weapons inspector in Iraq, resigned to protest what he
called the ``surrender to Iraqi leadership'' by the Clinton
administration and the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   He said the U.N. Special Commission for which he worked had been
on the ``doorstep'' of uncovering new information about Iraq's
hidden weapons programs when the administration helped stymie an
August inspection. The administration praised him, but defended its
approach toward containing Saddam Hussein. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ By JUDITH MILLER
</P>
<P>
   Libyans May Be Tried In Lockerbie Crash
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of grief for the families of the dead of Pan Am
103, blown up over Lockerbie, Scotland, there was some promise of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Libya signaled its cautious acceptance of an American and
British plan _ first suggested by Tripoli _ to try the two Libyan
suspects in a Scottish court, but with Scottish judges instead of a
jury, and in a neutral third country, the Netherlands. Libya wants
sanctions lifted, but is considered likely to delay handing over
the two men, both intelligence agents.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN ERLANGER
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carcinogen Found in Fetuses of Pregnant Smokers
</P>
<P>
   Researchers reported the first direct evidence that a
cancer-causing substance from tobacco is transmitted to fetuses by
pregnant smokers. Dr. Stephen Hecht of the University of Minnesota
Cancer Center said his findings established that the
nicotine-derived chemical NNK is not only received by the fetus but
processed by the body.
</P>
<P>
   The study, sponsored by the National Cancer Institute, did not
determine whether the infants with the traces of NNK byproducts in
their urine were at greater risk of developing cancer, but Hecht
called the finding an unacceptable risk.
</P>
<P>
   By Hemingway, One Last Time
</P>
<P>
   ``In your novels, are you writing about yourself?'' a student
once asked Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does a writer know anyone better?'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   But now in a final, posthumous novel to be published next year
for the centennial of his birth, the adventurer and prankster who
was Hemingway can keep readers guessing. The book, ``True at First
Light,'' an unfinished fictional memoir based on a 1953 safari to
Kenya with his fourth wife, Mary, weaves in the story of Debba, an
18-year-old girl of the Wakamba tribe whom the narrator woos, weds
and beds _ cheered on by his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Is it true? Patrick Hemingway, the author's 70-year-old son, who
carved the 100,000-word book out of a 200,000-word manuscript for
Scribner, said he joined the safari from his farm in Tanganyika and
saw no Debba. Nor apparently did the photographer for Look
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both Hemingway and Mary later tantalized biographers with
tales of a romance. A.E. Hotchner even quoted Hemingway's account
of three-way nuptials that included his bride's widowed 17-year-old
sister.
</P>
<P>
   But the book, portions of which were excerpted by Sports
Illustrated in the 1970s, ranges far beyond the love triangle.
There are autobiographical flashbacks, meditations on the soul and
suspenseful hunts. This much at least is true: Mary gets her lion.
Its skin adorns the floor of the Hemingway Room in the John F.
Kennedy Library in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RALPH BLUMENTHAL
</P>
<P>
   I'll Take the Diana Bath Mat
</P>
<P>
   What does Diana, Princess of Wales, have in common with the
likes of Marilyn Monroe, James Dean, Albert Einstein and Babe Ruth?
A thriving afterlife as a brand name.
</P>
<P>
   While it is no longer unusual for celebrities to be
commercialized after their deaths, the rapid development of Diana
into a powerful merchandising phenomenon has been exceptional.
Dianabilia ranges from inexpensive trinkets like postcards and
T-shirts to moderately priced coins and stamps to expensive dolls
and plates.
</P>
<P>
   Those who possess, or profess to possess, more refined tastes
may scratch their heads in bewilderment. But the instant blanket
coverage of breaking news events now offered by global media helped
turn millions who never met Diana into souvenir hunters eager to
get something to remember her by.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of that media attention is being demonstrated again as
TV networks, magazines and newspapers mark Monday's anniversary of
her death.
</P>
<P>
   Will the cottage industry that has grown up around Diana last?
Experts in building brands, licensing and merchandising believe it
could, particularly if her image is tended properly.
</P>
<P>
   It took some time after the death of Elvis Presley for big
demand to develop for products paying tribute to him. But the
shrewd management of his estate has meant that more than two
decades after his death, he may be a more regal king than he ever
was in life.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STUART ELLIOTT
</P>
</TEXT>
