<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-RIVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIANS FIGHT TO SAVE THE RUSSIAN RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD VALLEY, Calif. _ The Russian River begins here, just a
trickle from invisible cracks in mountains thick with fir trees.
</P>
<P>
   It ends 110 miles away on the Pacific Ocean, where waves crash
up to the river's mouth forming the estuary at Jenner, a haven for
harbor seals and cormorants.
</P>
<P>
   In the miles between, the river runs lazy and inviting in summer
months, swollen and menacing in wet winters _ a source of drinking
water for a half million people.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, it's San Francisco's hot weather playground, a
place for canoeing and swimming and weekend barbecues in the shade
of redwood trees. In the fall, the fields near its banks are ablaze
with the orange and red hues of grape vines that signal another
harvest in an increasingly important wine region. In winter, it's
one of the most flood-prone U.S. rivers, a nightmarish torrent 200
times its summertime size, ripping out banks and houses and
threatening lives.
</P>
<P>
   And all year round, it's an endangered waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of trapping, logging, gravel mining, damming,
straightening, sewage dumping, water pumping and farming right up
to its banks have put the Russian River on an environmental group's
list of America's Most Threatened Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   And now _ inspired by a new spurt of local activism, buoyed by
tougher federal laws to save wild salmon and steelhead _ the
river's future has come to the top of the agenda for public action
by an amalgam of water agencies, government offices, growers,
utilities and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the next month, 300 people who have been attending a
series of recent meetings will decide whether to launch a Russian
River Watershed Council, under which varied interests in Sonoma and
Mendocino counties would work together to restore the river. It
would be modeled after councils formed to protect such Pacific
Northwest rivers as the Umpqua and Coquille in Oregon and the
Skagit in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian River's story is in the next 25 years. It could be
the most dramatic restoration in the country,'' said Richard
Charter, 52, of Friends of the Russian River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take the cooperation of agriculture,'' said
Charter, who played on the Russian River as a toddler and fought
every river battle for the last 30 years. ``Developers have to get
less greedy. Gravel miners have to realize they don't run the
county. Water agencies are going to have to make a commitment to
conservation and wise management.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the warning lights on the dashboard are red,'' said
Charter. ``Everything is wrong. Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian River is born high on a summit, its tiny headwaters
hidden in craggy, forested mountains 15 miles north of Ukiah.
</P>
<P>
   The river, a third the length of the Sacramento River and half
as long as the Thames, drains an area of 1,485 square miles. Its
biggest tributaries are the East Fork of the Russian and Big
Sulphur, Mark West, Maacama and Dry creeks.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful East Fork is artificially supplemented by 159,000
acre-feet a year of Eel River water, enough to make up two-thirds
of the Russian as it flows through Guerneville in summertime.
</P>
<P>
   The Eel water bursts into the Russian through a two-mile tunnel
drilled into a mountainside in Potter Valley in 1908 when a company
later bought by PG&AMP;E built a hydropower plant.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as people of the Russian River watershed weigh decisions
about their economic and environmental future, they look north to
its beginning and down the separate reaches as it sweeps toward the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   On the upper reaches of the river as it flows from the Potter
and Redwood valleys, through Ukiah and Old Hopland to Cloverdale,
two important decisions loom.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E, following a state order to switch from power generation to
distribution, is deciding what to do with the Potter Valley
hydropower plant. Its proposal, which must be approved by the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, could shrink the size of the
river downstream if less water were diverted from the Eel for the
Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen miles downstream of the power plant, the Army Corps of
Engineers is trying to address problems created by the operation of
its 40-year-old Coyote Valley Dam. Critics say this dam, and the
corps' Warm Springs Dam on the Dry Creek tributary, speed up
erosion of riverfront property downstream. The dams can also harm
fish considered threatened species by the National Marine Fisheries
Service by releasing water warmer than is good for them.
</P>
<P>
   Long-time grape grower Malcolm King doesn't plant to the edge of
his riverfront property the way many growers tempted by valuable
acreage do. Nonetheless, in last winter's floods, he saw a half an
acre of his 40-acre vineyard liquefy and melt away after weeks of
dam releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks and vegetation can handle the natural peaks and
drops of a few hours duration,'' said King. But the huge volume
over time ``supersaturates the banks and the water is dissolving
the very fine topsoils laid down forever.''
</P>
<P>
   On the sweeping Alexander Valley reach from Cloverdale to
Healdsburg, the Sonoma County Board of Supervisors is preparing an
ordinance to address environmental effects of transforming land to
vineyards _ including erosion and loss of stream-side habitat for
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   In Sonoma County, vineyards jumped in the last decade from
30,000 acres producing $67 million worth of wine grapes to 48,000
acres producing $289 million.
</P>
<P>
   The river's ability to withstand floods and provide for wildlife
suffers from the disappearance of natural willows, alders and
cottonwoods, now bulldozed down to a narrow band to make room for
the vines that produce wine grapes, say scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem the river faces it sewage.
</P>
<P>
   For years, treated sewage overflow from Santa Rosa has entered
the river via Mark West Creek near Mirabel Park. Locals joked that
Santa Rosa's favorite saying was, ``Flush twice for Guerneville.''
</P>
<P>
   After decades of dumping the treated discharges through the
little river towns, the county has a new plan. Santa Rosa promises
it won't release more than 1 percent of its highly treated sewage
overflow into the river. Most will get piped to geothermal beds and
to water crops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
