<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-BOS &LR;      08-31 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENCE ON CLINTON PUTS WOMEN SENATORS AT RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The fallout from President Clinton's extramarital
affair with Monica S. Lewinsky could be radioactive this fall for
Democratic women candidates who, their opponents say, have a double
standard on sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Most vulnerable are Senators Barbara Boxer of California,
Patty Murray of Washington, and Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois,
all first-term members who rode a feminist wave in 1992 after the
Senate's clumsy handling of lawyer Anita Hill's allegations that
Supreme Court nominee Clarence Thomas had sexually harassed her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The three Democrats also vigorously pressed for an
investigation of their Senate colleague, Republican Robert Packwood
of Oregon, who was accused of sexual misconduct by more than a
dozen women. Packwood resigned under fire in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But when President Clinton was sued by Paula Jones for sexual
harassment, the same senators had little or nothing to say. And
when Clinton confessed Aug. 17 that he had a relationship with
Lewinsky, a former White House intern, that was ``not
appropriate,'' Boxer, Murray, and Moseley-Braun expressed sadness
and disappointment but not indignation or outrage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Now their opponents are starting to exploit what they call the
women's partisan hypocrisy and test it as a campaign weapon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Barbara, your silence on this issue is deafening,'' Matt
Fong, Boxer's challenger and California's Republican state
treasurer, said Wednesday in the campaign's first face-to-face
debate in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; US Representative Linda Smith, the leading Republican
candidate to oppose Murray on Nov. 3, has called on the president
to resign and has questioned Murray's muted response to the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Isn't it amazing how Patty Murray has been silent about the
problems of the president?'' Smith asked at a recent GOP picnic in
Washington state. ``She seems to have traded in her tennis shoes
for a pair of Hush Puppies,'' referring to Murray's slogan of being
a ``mom in tennis shoes'' during the 1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The senators have responded, but mostly by trying to change
the subject. Moseley-Braun said she was hurt by the president's
actions but proud of his agenda. Murray said that she was
disappointed Clinton misled the country but that ``there's no one
better when there's a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said that what the president did was wrong, but whether he
sexually harassed the intern was ``a matter for Monica Lewinsky to
state.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Political analysts call the Clinton-Lewinsky affair the ``X''
factor, the big unknown, in the midterm congressional elections.
Even if the impact is small, as Democrats hope, it still could be
the margin of defeat for Boxer, Murray, Moseley-Braun, and other
women who faced tough reelection races even before anybody had
heard of Lewinsky or Linda Tripp, a former friend of the intern who
secretly taped their telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Moseley-Braun, whose term has been dogged by financial and
political controversies, is trailing her opponent, GOP state
Senator Peter Fitzgerald, 46 percent to 39 percent, according to a
recent Chicago Tribune poll. A telling feature of the survey: a
1992 gender gap that helped Moseley-Braun make history by becoming
the first African-American woman in the Senate has disappeared; the
conservative Fitzgerald is more popular than Moseley-Braun with
women.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, whose daughter is married to Hillary Rodham Clinton's
brother, is even with Fong in a recent California Field Poll, with
each receiving 45 percent of the likely vote. Boxer's gender gap is
closing, too; her support from women is half what it was in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being close to Clinton could hurt Barbara Boxer, and having
her opponent hammer on it could have a bit of the effect of tarring
her in a race that is so close,'' said Elizabeth Sherman, director
of the Center for Women in Politics and Public Policy at the
University of Massachusetts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In Washington state polls, Murray is well ahead of the field,
but party officials there believe the expected Murray-Smith race
will be lively and close.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Democrats' concerns about their women candidates this year go
well beyond the fate of the three senators. First, polls show the
president's popularity is beginning to erode among married,
suburban women, the so-called soccer moms, who view the scandal
more harshly than men. These women contributed heavily to Clinton's
win over Republican Bob Dole in 1996, and they disproportionately
support Democratic women candidates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Second, the scandal may so disillusion and disgust some
Democrats that they sit out the November elections. A weak
Democratic turnout not only would boost Republican prospects, but
also narrow the gender gap that has helped women in the past three
elections.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Third, women candidates who normally benefit from the
publicity and fund-raising of a presidential visit are seriously
weighing the risks of bringing Clinton into their districts this
fall. Women running on a clean-government, family-friendly agenda
may not be eager to share a podium with a president being pummeled
by press questions about his sex life or details in independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr's expected report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I'm anticipating an inside-outside campaign this fall,''
said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst at the Claremont
Graduate University in Claremont, Calif. ``Inside, the president
will go below the radar, raising money for Democrats. Outside,
you'll see Mrs. Clinton, who's now viewed so much more favorably
than her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Gail Riecken, a Democratic US House candidate from Evansville,
Ind., told reporters this week that having the president come to
her district ``is just something I would not even entertain at this
point.'' Riecken, a city councilwoman running against GOP
Representative John Hostettler, already has had the first lady
campaign with her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Democratic Party line is that the Lewinsky affair won't
resonate beyond the Washington Beltway, and instead, local issues
will dominate campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Devlin, campaign manager for Tammy Baldwin, a Democrat
seeking the nomination for an open House seat in Madison, Wis.,
said questions about Clinton have not come up in candidate forums
or on the stump because voters there aren't obsessed with the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Alan Secrest, a Democratic consultant, said, ``We're telling
our candidates, `Don't race to the ramparts, do run your own
campaigns, and make it clear that the president did something
wrong, self-indulgent, and selfish.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Democrat Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky said women candidates
must not defend Clinton's behavior, but they also should not
forget, in the hail of Republican attacks, that this administration
has put women first.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the whole picture _ how this president has
empowered women and pushed their issues, like family leave and
child care _ it is very hard for us to turn on him,'' said
Margolies-Mezvinsky, a former congresswoman who is running for
lieutenant governor of Pennsylvania. ``Yes, he's flawed. Yes, he
did something very wrong. But think what the alternative to him
might have meant for women.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Strategically, Republicans can't allow women candidates who
were highly critical of alleged misbehavior by Packwood and Thomas
to ``straddle the fence'' and try to excuse sexual misconduct that
the president has admitted, said Mary Mead Crawford, a spokeswoman
for the National Republican Congressional Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Are these women fair game? You bet,'' Crawford said. ``If
they treat similar situations differently, then they are
hypocrites. At the least, it tells us whether they are speaking
from feminist conviction or a partisan perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Pat Deal, a vice president of the National Women's Political
Caucus, a group that backs liberal women candidates, said the
Republican attacks on women are a ``contorted'' and unfortunate way
to make Clinton an issue in upcoming races.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``To the extent that many women candidates represent family
values and high levels of integrity, this should really be a good
time to elect them,'' said Deal. ``I hate to see this scandal used
as an issue to defeat them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
