<HEADLINE>
KILLER II, OR MERELY A COPYCAT?
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Should the cat be cloned? I'm weighing the pros and cons. Now
that Killer is well into his golden years, I'm forced to imagine
life without him, a prospect I prefer not to dwell upon, but one
that's inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes news that a wealthy California couple plans to give
$2.3 million to livestock cloning experts at Texas A&AMP;M University
to clone their 11-year-old mixed-breed dog, Missy. According to a
story in Friday's Globe, the Missyplicity project, if successful,
would ``tap into the yearnings of less well-heeled pet owners,''
some of whom have written to an Internet site saying they plan to
freeze their aged or dying animals in hopes that cloning will
eventually be available ``at Wal-Mart prices.''
</P>
<P>
   I understand how they feel. In this uncertain world, the one
thing you can be sure of is the constant devotion of a pet.
Actually, in my case, it's more a case of the pet being sure of the
constant devotion of a human, but it really amounts to much the
same thing. It means the world to me, this bond that Killer and I
have forged during the 16 years in which I have been his devoted
servant.
</P>
<P>
   I think of all the little things Killer and I share. Reading him
his horoscope every day (he's an Aries). Cooking his favorite
shrimp and asparagus. Cleaning up after him. Killer has taught me
the rewards of service. He keeps me humble, not that I could be
otherwise with the legacy of ancestral guilt I've been handed. But
if ever there was a chance that something would go to my head,
Killer is always there to remind me not to get above myself.
</P>
<P>
   Every human-animal relationship is different. There were other
cats in my life, and there will be more. In fact, there already are
other cats. But my relationship with Killer is special. It's
tempting to think of having a replica of him after he's gone.
Certainly not before he's gone. He wouldn't stand for it.
</P>
<P>
   Cloning is still in the experimental stages. According to a
recent Chicago Tribune story, even if scientists eventually iron
out all the kinks, cloning won't produce exact copies of the
original. Each clone will have its own personality, shaped by its
own experience. I could get a Killer clone who wouldn't claw the
furniture to shreds, which would be no Killer at all.
</P>
<P>
   Cloning him would amount to an act of hubris. I'd be tempting
fate, asking for trouble. I'm reminded of the sort of expectant
parents who anticipate a child that will combine all their own best
features and instead produce a little stranger as imperfect as they
are, but in different and sometimes maddening ways. I'm not trying
to draw a parallel between creating a baby and cloning a cat, so
don't take offense. I'm just pointing out that reproduction is
always unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   A Killer clone would be a conversation piece. And he'd provide
column fodder. Cloning would eliminate the heart-rending process of
deciding which cat to adopt. There are so many pets waiting for
homes. What's the point of cloning more? The California couple
could better spend their millions on curbing animal overpopulation
and taking care of homeless animals. But I understand what drives
them to spend millions trying to clone Missy. Love sometimes leads
us to do strange things.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I have to ask myself if Killer would want to be
cloned. I don't think he would. He takes a dim view of other cats.
He'd be offended by the notion that a clone of himself would
replace the original in my affections. I'm sure he'd prefer that I
acquire another cat after he's gone, a very different cat who will
remind me, every day, of how lucky I was to live for so many years
with the best cat ever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
