</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-CONFERENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACADEMICS WORLDWIDE ANALYZE PRINCESS DIANA'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her fairy-tale-turned-sour spawned made-for-TV movies, tabloid
obsession and tears around the world. And in death, Diana, the
princess of Wales, has spawned something else: an academic frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   At the one-year anniversary of her death at age 36, Diana is
being awarded status the academy more commonly accords to figures
like Ernest Hemingway and Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   She has been the subject of at least 15 conferences worldwide,
including one at the London School of Economics, arrayed with
figures as giant as Henry James and Thomas Jefferson, and the topic
of monographs with such titles as ``Diana and the Fantasy of
Ordinary Suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   So fast have scholars around the world developed the field, in
fact, that they are already postulating the revisionist perspective
on Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say this is the ivory tower stooping to remain relevant,
in an age when American colleges offer courses on the Geography in
Jimmy Buffett Music and The Psychology of Weight Lifting. But
scholars say it is hardly surprising that someone hounded by the
paparazzi would now be deconstructed by academicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a history of studying the communicators who became
well-known since the classical period in Greece,'' insists Dr.
James Golden, a former professor at Ohio State University and a
member of the President's Commission on Thomas Jefferson. ``If you
can analyze the message, analyze the audience, then you've got
something worth an academic assignment, no question. I have no
problem looking upon it as an academic exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither, apparently, do many scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Using television ratings to estimate that one-third the world's
population ``connected'' with Diana's death, Boston's Emerson
College has sponsored a trilogy of conferences under the title,
``The Global Rhetorical Phenomenon of Diana, Princess of Wales.''
At the second, conducted in French in Paris at the six-month mark
in late January, scholars debated such propositions as ``Diana is
not dead because she never `existed.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the third conference, held at the ivy-covered University of
London last week, academics from Britain, Australia, and the United
States discussed her effect on the monarchy, Diana as a feminist
icon, and the ethics of using her as poster princess for seat-belt
safety campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   They dissected the significance of ``Dianaiana'' _ a term coined
to describe everything from the tea towels that commemorated her
wedding to her biographies, which one scholar numbered at 175.
</P>
<P>
   While they insisted that tabloids were not invited, the
organizers apparently could not resist a few tabloid aspects. There
were special presentations by the doctor who treated Diana, her
lover's former butler, and the first British reporter to confirm
her death, as well as a special ``artistic salute'' by singer Jose
Feliciano.
</P>
<P>
   But why all this scholarly attention to Diana, a woman, as one
scholar sniffed, ``whose highest aspiration was to dance with John
Travolta''?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a characteristic of our time, when everything is so
concentrated in time because of the media, that things are
immediately processed,'' said Rabbi Howard A. Berman, who traveled
from Worcester to attend the conference. ``The modern intellectual
approach is far more immediate than the past, where someone had to
be dead for 50 years before you took them seriously. I don't think
that's true anymore, and I think we're the better for it.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been said so many times in this anniversary week,
scholars say Diana inspires inquiry because she related to so many
people on so many different issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have popular figures who provide a meaning or a
case study of a theory you might be advocating, so that figure
becomes useful to discussions of those issues,'' said Gregory
Payne, a professor of communication at Emerson. ``So if you have,
say, a feminist perspective, you can take her strong stand against
Charles, her strong stand against the monarchy and make her a
feminist icon. She becomes relevant to discussions of feminist
theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Women to whom Diana is frequently compared _ Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis or Mother Teresa _ did not draw the same inquiry, Golden
says, because they did not champion as many issues _ or,
practically speaking, appear in so many photographs.
</P>
<P>
   They also did not draw so much controversy. And as the life of
Diana had its controversies _ from her days as nursery school
teacher to her frolics with Dodi Fayed in the Mediterranean _ so
does the scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially there was the rush to sainthood,'' Payne said. ``Now
we have voices of revision, questioning whether the outpouring of
grief was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   But the revisionists are in for a fight with the hard-core
Dianaianaists.
</P>
<P>
   Their latter-day skepticism ``smacks of elitist snobbery and
ivory tower arrogance,'' Berman said. ``She was a major cultural,
social phenomenon in late 20th century life, and it's very
appropriate that she is the subject of serious inquiry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
