<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-ASSASSINATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CASE FOR ASSASSINATION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ Here's an unusual way to make America a kinder
and gentler superpower: legalize assassination.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Make it OK to knock off outlaws beyond our
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Before dismissing the controversial idea, consider the cruel
irony of the rules that exist today. The Pentagon can rain cruise
missiles on known terrorist camps and factories _ as it did 10 days
ago _ killing and injuring any innocent people who happen to be in
the wrong place. And yet, because of an executive order signed by
President Reagan, the US government cannot hunt down and kill a
terrorist, mass murderer, or war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   That means Osama bin Laden, the mastermind of bombings that have
killed hundreds of people, is off-limits unless he has the bad luck
to be at a site that is bombed. And it means that Iraqi leader
Saddam Hussein cannot be targeted, even though he tried to
assassinate former president George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it possible to say that we can justify actions (in
which) innocent people inevitably get killed, instead of going
after someone who has openly declared war on us and is personally
responsible for killing Americans?'' asks L. Paul Bremer III, who
was Reagan's chief of counter-terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer first proposed ending the assassination ban a decade ago,
while testifying before Congress. Since the twin bombings of US
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, he has stepped up his rhetoric. We
live in a turbulent world where the old rules of conventional
warfare no longer hold, he reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In its pursuit of bad guys around the world, Washington relies
on the courts of other countries, or on extraditions, or, as a last
resort, on attacks of safe houses and terrorist camps. But all
those measures have flaws.
</P>
<P>
   American drug enforcement agents amassed overwhelming evidence
that Pablo Escobar and other drug barons had killed US citizens in
the 1980s and early '90s. Jail? Escobar and his associates made a
mockery of Colombia's justice system by murdering, threatening, and
paying off prosecutors and judges. Extradition? The drug lords
didn't like the prospect of trials in the United States, so they
bullied and bought off a constitutional convention to do away with
extradition. Attacks? Even though American officials often knew
Escobar's whereabouts, they could not bomb Colombia, a friendly
country. So they sat and stewed for years, until Escobar died in a
shootout with police.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the US response to the car bomb that blew up at a
Marine barracks in Beirut in 1983, killing 241 Americans. US forces
fired into the mountains of Lebanon, even though that was not a
hiding place of the Shiite Muslims of the Islamic Jihad, who had
claimed responsibility for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In such attacks, innocent civilians become ``collateral
damage.'' And that raises the question of whether a selective
assassination policy might be more effective, and even more humane,
in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   But even backers of allowing assassinations don't propose giving
US agents free rein. Bremmer, for one, wants checks and balances.
Just as the Pentagon has to have a sound reason to launch a strike,
a president should have a finding, or some other legal document,
before deciding on an assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just have the president blithely signing orders to
kill people,'' Bremer says.
</P>
<P>
   But backers of assassination haven't gotten a ringing
endorsement from the Congress, the Clinton administration, or
scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interesting,'' a White House official said when told of the
suggestion. As he thought aloud, though, his interest quickly
cooled. This country is the leading target for terrorists, he said,
so America's enemies would say, ``If they can assassinate our
leaders, we can assassinate theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Harvard Law School, professor Ann-Marie Slaughter, an
expert on international law, sees a deeper moral reason for banning
assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, you'd be saying it's all right to kill an
individual without judicial process,'' Slaughter says. ``But that's
a violation of a core tenet of the world's great legal systems and
religions, which all have a prohibition of extradicial killings.''
</P>
<P>
   A bedrock belief of the American system is that a suspect of a
crime is entitled to a trial to confront his accusers and see the
evidence. Intelligence data, which is used to track terrorists
across borders, is not subject to scrutiny or cross-examination,
Slaughter says.
</P>
<P>
   Jeswald Salacuse, a professor of international law at the
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy, cautions against any move to
get rid of the executive order. ``There's a hysteria building in
this country that says we are threatened from all over and anything
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, both Slaughter and Salacuse concede that it's easy to sit
on a campus and denounce assassinations as immoral. Real life
offers examples that beg for an exception. What if Hitler was alive
and committing genocide today? Under the assassination ban,
President Clinton would not be allowed to order US troops or
intelligence officers _ or even foreign mercenaries _ to poison or
shoot Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Larry Johnson, the State Department's former
counterterrorism director, says the assassination ban at least
ought to be modified. The US government should be allowed to kill a
malevolent foreign leader if war has been declared, Johnson says.
He calls that the ``Hitler option.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``janitors' option'': If someone has murdered
or consipired to murder US citizens and is beyond the reach of law
enforcement, he's fair game. ``Otherwise we end up launching a
nighttime strike on a weapons plant that guarantees we are going to
kill janitors and cleaning ladies, not the people who planned the
operation,'' Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, US presidents will continue to deal with the
executive order as they have in the past: by obeying it and yet
ignoring it. An aide to a Republican senator who is an expert in
military affairs explained that the Pentagon has not technically
tried to assassinate anyone, but it has targeted missiles at the
hiding places of bin Laden, Saddam Hussein, and other pariahs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they happen to be in the way,'' the aide said, ``then no
executive order is going to protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David L. Marcus is the Globe's diplomatic correspondent.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
