<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE HYPE REIGNS, THE ISSUES GET LOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagese of hysterical parents, baby-faced suspects and
schoolhouse carnage have dominated the news for much of this year.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed one horrifying incident followed another. The shooting
of students by a classmate at a high school in West Paducah, Ky.,
was followed by similar shootings at schools in Mississippi,
Arkansas, and Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they triggered a bout of national soul-searching: ``As
the U.S. witnesses the latest school shooting, can anything be
learned _ or done?,'' asked Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Congress called for tougher juvenile crime laws. President
Clinton went to Worcester Thursday to tout new ways to help
educators identify potentially violent pupils. He'll convene a
conference on the topic this fall.
</P>
<P>
   It would probably surprise most people to learn that the number
of children killed in schools actually declined during the last
three years, compared with the period three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, the hype has overshadowed the facts, or at
least the context, in this high-profile story. The problem is not
new _ it happened in the spring and summer of 1996 when black
churches were burning in the south _ and it's not confined to
institutions. For example, a recent flurry of concern about
increasing ``road rage'' has little basis in statistical fact.
</P>
<P>
   Although the school violence story is not the only one in which
a series of events were joined together to represent what was
represented to be a meaningful trend, it is an unusually good
illustration of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have come to think of schools as unsafe. But the 40
children killed by guns in schools during the 1997-1998 school year
are a small fraction of the 3,024 children who die from gunfire
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Further, children are 23 times more likely to be killed in a gun
accident than in a school shooting and 90 percent of all juvenile
murders occur at home, according to the Justice Policy Institute, a
Washington D.C., think tank that studies juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   For added perspective, the institute reports the number of
children killed by gun violence in schools is about half the number
of Americans killed by lightning every year.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the school shootings, a series of anecdotes
conspired to become the ``truth'' _ a truth that helped drive the
debate about how to respond to these violent attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media coverage of these dramatic killings has created a
misperception that schools are dangerous,'' said Vincent Schiraldi,
the director of the Justice Policy Institute. ``In fact, schools
are still the safest place in America for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the harm with a little media hype? Plenty, says Jason
Ziedenberg, one of the authors of the school report.
</P>
<P>
   Ziedebnberg doesn't criticize the media for covering the
shootings, only for covering the events without context.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put it in perspective because the consequences and policies
being thrown about were disconcerting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The saturation coverage and linking of the school shootings
created an overblown response that threatens to divert resources
and attention from issues that pose a greater threat to children,
warns Ziedenberg.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, the governor proposed reducing the number of
after-school athletic events after a nonfatal shooting in Richmond.
FBI data, however, show that one in five violent crimes committed
by children occur in the hours immediately after the end of the
school day. In many urban areas, schools remain a safer alternative
to the street in the hours following the end of classroom
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating after-school programs, argues Ziedenberg, would
actually increase the threat of violence against children.
</P>
<P>
   The well-publicized school shootings also prompted a national
crackdown on misbehaving students _ with sanctions that may have
once been perceived as unduly harsh.
</P>
<P>
   In Tyrone, Ga., two elementary school students were suspended
for composing a list of people they wanted to harm. Among the
targeted victims were the Spice Girls and Barney the dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of increasing the number of police in schools and
instituting harsher sanctions against children, the institute urges
the expansion of after-school programs and restricting the mass
sale of guns.
</P>
<P>
   Ziedenberg said both sides of the political spectrum attempted
to use the school shootings to push their own agenda _ from
conservative US Senator Orin Hatch, a Utah Republican, to the gun
control lobby. The saturation media coverage urged them on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that more media leads to these kinds of
pile-ons,'' he said. ``Crime is cheap to cover. There is a drama
unfolding with a cast of characters. There are plenty of people to
book and everyone is suddenly an expert on why this kid went crazy.
It goes on and on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, this year's new interest in ``road rage.'' Many of the
stories reported an upsurge, or even epidemic, in the numbers and
intensity of aggressive drivers.
</P>
<P>
   In this month's Atlantic Monthly, writer Michael Fumento
deconstructs the road rage phenomenon and finds the use of the
phrase by the media has skyrocketed while federal transportation
records reveal a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Headlines notwithstanding, there was not _ there is not _ the
least statistical or other scientific evidence of more-aggressive
driving on our nation's roads,'' he writes. ``Indeed, accident,
fatality and injury rates have been edging down. There is no
evidence that `road rage' or an aggressive-driving `epidemic' is
anything but a media invention.''
</P>
<P>
   The road-rage hype is seen as dangerous because it distracts
from more serious problems such as drunk drivers and the
less-than-rigorous process used to license young drivers, who are
among the most accident-prone on the roads.
</P>
<P>
   The hype around school violence and road rage harken back to
another epidemic of questionable origin: the burning of mostly
black churches two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The church burnings became a political issue in a presidential
election year, with Clinton personally touring arson sites.
</P>
<P>
   But a later review found much of the political rhetoric and
reporting on the issue to be flawed. Insurance records indicated
the number of fires at churches in 1996 was within the normal range
for what was reported in the six years prior. In addition, fewer
than 20 of the 73 fires that summer could be clearly linked to
racism.
</P>
<P>
   However, most of the reporting on the church fires referred to
an ``epidemic'' or ``wave'' or ``string'' of fires.
</P>
<P>
   If there are lessons in all of these cases, they may come from
the front line of reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Post reporter John Schwartz, who covered the
Jonesboro school shootings, offered some advice to his colleagues
in a first-person account of covering the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we should ignore stories like the one that
happened in Jonesboro,'' he wrote. ``I'm simply saying that as
journalists, we should cover these stories more thoughtfully, and
with decency and compassion instead of cookie-cutter bathos. We
should, in other words, do what we're paid to do: Get the story
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
