u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-REFLECT-BOS &LR;      08-31 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-REFLECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING THE SUMMER OF '68 _ WHEN SO MANY DREAMS DIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUMMER-REFLECT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago police beat demonstrators outside the convention hall,
and Humbert Humphrey barely defeated Senator Eugene McCarthy for
the Democratic presidential nomination, as the sizzling summer of
1968 drew to a close 30 years ago this week. America was on fire
that year _ politically, emotionally, and literally.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. and Robert F. Kennedy had been
assassinated; armies of demonstrators seized the streets in protest
of the Vietnam War, which shattered Lyndon Johnson's presidency and
cracked the core of the nation's self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, some prominent figures reflect on their thoughts
at the time _ on how the world might have been different had that
long, hot summer never taken place _ and on its lasting social and
political impact for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Reverend Robert F. Drinan was dean of Boston College Law
School in the summer of '68. He went on to become a Democratic US
representative from Massachusetts and a legal scholar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important event, I think, was Kennedy's
assassination. He would have been elected, and the whole world
would have changed. We might never had had Nixon and then Reagan.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bobby had won, the dream would have won. We would have
eased the cold war, we would have gone forward with education,
civil rights, and all those challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Nixon means no Watergate, and all the terrible things with
which we've been afflicted would never have happened. ...
Everything was going the wrong way ... there was a profound
rebellion in academia, and people knew something was fundamentally
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could be back there and deliver a message, I'd say that
campaign financing is the essence of all the corruption in politics
today, and and that is something that grew up then. I'd tell people
that the Soviets are going to collapse because of their own
contradictions, so instead of building nuclear weapons to bomb
Moscow, we should spend that money to improve conditions everywhere
...''
</P>
<P>
   ``As for lessons, I wish people would become politically active
again. If people were politically active, as they were, they would
have power ... people have become self centered, self-absorbed. ...
They forget this country can be amazing in its ability to do
good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Governor Jeanne Shaheen, who in '68 was a
Republican college senior who voted for Richard Nixon. By 1982,
events led her to cast her ballot for George McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was only 1968, but that was the beginning of
events for the next several years that changed our country. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, one of the interesting things about that period of
time is that it didn't tear our country apart. Yes, it was a
troubling time and, yes, there was a lot unrest, but we did
respond. We did get out of Vietnam, we have seen changes around the
civil rights movement _ not enough, but real changes, and the same
is true for women's rights. ... In any case, I think the country
has responded ... including with a change in the leadership of the
country. That didn't happen in '68, but a lot of what happened
since that time has happened as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watergate happened, I think, because Nixon felt threatened by
the war in Vietnam and by those who wanted to see real change in
the country. And the response to Watergate came about because of
what happened at the time, of the mentality of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message I'd deliver, if I could, from that time is
one that was given to me by a political science professor and that
I've always held onto. It's that, if you don't like what the
establishment is doing, then get involved in the establishment. You
don't drop out and say, `I'm not going to participate.' You get
involved. For me, that was the strongest message of that period.
And in a democracy, that's the only way you make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dick Gregory, who in the summer of '68 was a comedian, political
activist, and author. Today, he's a nutritionist and lecturer who
lives in Plymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the summer that the dream got busted, and America will
never be the same. It was the summer that people began to realize
that everything that happens in America happens for the benefit of
white folks, and I don't just mean that negatively ... it's just
the reality of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget that I ran for mayor of Chicago in '67, which
set the stage for some of what happened there the next year. Mayor
Daley, in calling out the troops, he was trying to teach the
Democrats, and America, that we can control young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was was the first time in the history of the planet
that we saw white folks being beat up by white folks. ... All at
once after that beating, there was this realization about authority
and how it doesn't see limits. I think nothing on the history of
the planet brought that out into the open, into white
consciousness, so dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those beatings in Chicago changed America. White folks didn't
know that cops would beat you for nothing. It changed America
because it changed the perception that this can happen anywhere in
the world, but it can't happen here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what has put us out here now, affected how we all
think about security and authority and safety _ because we know, in
our subconscious mind, that nobody's safe. There was a time when
people believed that if you behaved, if you obeyed the law, then
you'd be safe. Chicago changed all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, if I could have talked to the United States of now,
I would have said that we have a chance, we haven't gone beyond the
point of no return. In Chicago, we saw it happening, we saw the
evil and the bad behavior and the misuse of authority. Nobody had
to tell us about it; we watched it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot ... came down that summer, a lot that altered our lives
and our country, but I think that the cops in Chicago hitting on
all those kids, on all those protesters, that was the event that
turned things around. It cost the Democrats the election, and we
still feel the effects of that loss. And we will never look at cops
in the same way again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Attorney General Hubert H. Humphrey 3d, who in the
summer of '68 was was supporting his father's bid for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; ``1968 was the year that was the beginning of the end for the
decade of hope and inspiration, the 1960s. At the beginning of the
decade, we saw a new president, vital and energetic, challenge our
country: `Ask not what your country can do for you, but what you
can do for your country.' I was ready to change the world, and it
seemed everyone in the United States felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, 1968 arrived and with it a violent, turbulent end to the
optimism and dreams of many people. Two voices of peace, tolerance,
and hope met violent deaths _ Senator Robert F. Kennedy and Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. These two men, along with my father, were
part of the civil rights movement that wanted peace and
understanding and believed in basic human rights for all Americans.
Unfortunately, Kennedy and King fell prey to a hostility and anger
that had infected society. Hope was replaced by disillusionment and
despair. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``During 1968, the Democratic Pary was being torn apart _ the
country was being torn apart and people were afraid. I am amazed
this country held itself together and held an election; any other
country would have postponed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turbulence was seen by Dad a couple of years before the
riots and violent unrest in Chicago. In remarks to a 1966 White
House Conference, Dad foretold of the urgency to change from the
turbulent path America had appeared to choose: `There is, in short,
an urgent need to build a new climate of mutual respect among all
elements of society. For it is the absence of respect _ and the
sense of responsibility which is engulfed in respect _ which lies
at the roots of hostility and suspicion which today threatens the
tranquillity and progress of some cities.'
</P>
<P>
   ``These words could apply to many cities and rural areas in
1998. The lesson we should learn from 1968, when my father first
faced the challenge of defending Human Rights: We cannot let
hostility and hate rule the day. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson we need to learn is that human rights are not
`special rights.' Human rights are our `inalienable' rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
