A0852 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-GAY-POLITICS-2TAKE     08-31 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GAY-POLITICS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE CLOSET TO THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call 1998 the year that gay politicians came of age.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, at least 10 openly gay candidates are running
for state or congressional offices in next month's primary.
</P>
<P>
   That's a record number, and reflects an environment far
different from the early years of US Representative Barney Frank's
tenure; after being elected in 1980, it took him four terms in
Washington before he felt he could reveal his sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   But no longer does Frank stand out in the national political
landscape. Six other openly gay candidates are running for Congress
this fall _ the largest group to make a serious run for Capitol
Hill. Nationally, the number of gay officeholders has tripled since
1991 (from 49 to 156), and another 100 are candidates this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The advancement of any minority group that has candidates stand
for office _ rather than simply endorse others _ marks a crucial
development.
</P>
<P>
   But this year there is a further sign of the maturation and
political savvy of gay movement: Openly gay candidates are not
automatically winning endorsements from gay political caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached this odd state, where we have gone from
endorsing candidates, to running gay candidates, to the point where
we don't even have to endorse gay candidates,'' says Neil Miller,
author of ``Out of the Past: Gay and Lesbian History from 1869 to
the Present.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, gay candidates are no longer defined solely by their
sexual orientation. Rather, they are supported or opposed based on
the qualities that define any candidate: their stands on issues,
their record, and their personalities. No more blanket
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more apparent than in the Massachusetts 8th
Congressional District, where some gay groups declined to endorse
Susan Tracy, the only openly gay candidate in the race. The Lesbian
and Gay Political Alliance of Massachusetts endorsed Marjorie
Clapprood instead.
</P>
<P>
   And two gay newspapers, Bay Windows and In Newsweekly _ which
called on Tracy to drop from the race _ endorsed Clapprood.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Tracy was frustrated with the papers not endorsing
her, because, she says, neither talked with her beforehand. But,
she says, ``I am proud of the breadth and depth of my endorsements,
and I don't think it is fair to say `Susan is gay, so every gay
person is going to be with her.' Is every person of Italian descent
going to vote for Mike Capuano? No.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just in the 8th District that gay groups are
surprising some with their endorsements. In the 9th Suffolk
District, the Lesbian and Gay Political Alliance backed state
Representative Byron Rushing instead of either of two openly gay
challengers.
</P>
<P>
   That endorsements are no longer a reflexive matter of identity
politics ``is a sign of sophistication in the gay community,'' says
Sean Cahill, chairman of the Lesbian and Gay Political Alliance.
``We are thoughtful and don't automatically support someone because
of their sexual orientation. In a couple of races, Rushing's, and
the 8th Congressional race, we made the decision that the gay
candidate was not the best.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Washington-based Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund _ a group
dedicated to electing gays _ backs only about 18 percent of the
candidates that seek its support, says deputy director Kathleen
DeBold. The group endorsed Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure the candidate is viable, and we only pick
qualified individuals who happen to be gay or lesbian,'' says
DeBold. ``Susan Tracy is a qualified congressional candidate who is
a lesbian; she is not a lesbian running for office. Unless you are
looking for a date, there is no reason why you should care about a
candidate's sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexual orientation, however, does still matter. And not just to
the Anita Bryants of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no constituency that I am aware of where it is a
non-issue,'' says Mark Merante, cochair of Bay State Gay and
Lesbian Democrats. ``It is an issue, even in the most liberal of
districts. A certain segment of the population, either consciously
or not consciously, will not support you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett Barrios, who is running for a state legislative seat
from Cambridge _ arguably the most liberal city in the country's
most liberal state _ says he has felt the chill.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go door-to-door, and I have knocked on 4,000 doors,
generally people are interested in the issues. But I have
encountered homophobia before my sexual orientation comes up. Other
campaigns have contacted supporters to let them know `this man is a
homosexual.' That is gay-baiting, and it is disappointing, but we
have not made an issue of it. The issues are affordable housing,
schools, and child care.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Duffy, however, the Republican candidate for state
auditor, sees great differences between 1998 and 1990 when he ran
for a state legislative seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the convention this year, I was the Republican nominee for
state auditor _ a statewide position _ and I was unanimously
endorsed. There was no opposition, no dissent, and I think that is
an extraordinary thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
