u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CLONING-PETS-BOS &LR;      08-31 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CLONING-PETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO EVERY DOG HIS DAY...HIS DAY...HIS DAY... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the red-hot state of cloning research and the boundless
affection of many pet owners for their animals, it was only a
matter of time before something like the ``Missyplicity'' project
came along.
</P>
<P>
   For the anonymous couple who plunked down $2.3 million in an
effort to clone their 11-year-old, mixed-breed dog Missy, success
could mean never having to say a final goodbye to their
black-and-white pooch.
</P>
<P>
   And judging by the reaction to announcement of the effort this
week via an Internet site, success would also tap into the
yearnings of less-well-heeled pet owners, some of whom wrote that
they plan to freeze their own aged or dying animals in anticipation
of eventual cloning at Wal-Mart prices.
</P>
<P>
   It's a departure for cloning science, which until now has been
driven mainly by visions of megabucks in the livestock industry,
where copies of prize animals could be made and sold at high
prices. By contrast, the Missyplicity project is fueled ``mainly by
emotional reasons,'' said Lou Hawthorne, an intermediary for the
unidentified couple, in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne insists that the plan is serious and could produce
methods for copying the best search-and-rescue or guide dogs, and
for rescuing endangered species. But, he insisted, it is in no way
a step toward cloning humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has agreed that cloning Man is bad, but what about
Man's Best Friend?'' says Hawthorne in an Internet message on the
Web site. ``Most people aren't bothered as much _ or at all _ by
cloning dogs,'' he adds, noting that while the uniqueness of humans
puts cloning out of bounds for many people, ``our concept of a good
canine companion does not depend on uniqueness _ at least not to
the same degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne, who heads a newly formed company called Bio Arts and
Research Corp. _ yes, BARC _ said in a telephone interview that he
assembled a scientific advisory board to help choose the scientists
who would attempt to carry out the donors' wishes. The first
$500,000 has been forwarded to a livestock cloning specialist at
Texas A&AMP;M University, Mark Westhusin, who will head the effort.
Westhusin and his colleagues took tissue samples from Missy earlier
this summer as a start in identifying cells that might be suitable
for cloning.
</P>
<P>
   It is barely a year since the birth of Dolly the lamb, the first
mammal cloned from a single cell of an adult individual. The months
since have seen the birth of cloned calves, mice, and cattle, along
with sheep that were not only cloned but had genes inserted from
other species to cause them to produce medical proteins in their
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Copying the familiar domestic dog, however, will force
scientists to start practically at square one, because far less is
known about normal canine reproduction than that of livestock, said
Westhusin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know much less about how to collect and transfer embryos,
how to manipulate hormonal cycles, how to do in vitro
fertilization, in the dog than we do in livestock animals, because
there hasn't been the economic incentive,'' said Westhusin in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   He said a colleague in the project, Dr. Duane Kraemer, succeeded
10 years ago in transferring fertilized embryos from a female dog
to a surrogate mother dog which bore the puppies. But few if any
attempts at dog cloning have been reported, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What interested me is the challenge, the opportunity to do
really good basic science involving reproduction in dogs,'' he
said. The Texas scientists plan to use some variation of nuclear
transfer, the technique that produced Dolly and similar clones. It
involves extracting the nucleus of a mature cell from the animal to
be cloned, and fusing it with a fresh egg from which the nucleus
has been removed.
</P>
<P>
   When the scientists ``activated'' the artifically made embryo
for Dolly, for instance, the nucleus from the original animal cell
reprogrammed its genes, turning them all on so that they could
direct the complex development of an entire new animal. The
resulting fetus was implanted into the womb of a surrogate mother
to develop and be born.
</P>
<P>
   A cloning expert at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst,
Dr. James Robl, said the Missyplicity project stands ``a reasonable
chance of success,'' although it might take several years. Robl,
who founded a company to commercialize aspects of livestock
cloning, said he has had requests for a decade to clone dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago someone wanted to clone racing greyhounds,'' he
recalled. ``But most people are interested because they have a dog
that's been around for 10 or 12 years and is getting old but is a
part of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   To Dr. Peter Theran, vice president for health and hospitals of
the Massachusetts Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals,
interest in the project ``is a clear example of the strength of the
human-animal bond.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that ``whether cloning would really duplicate
what someone has and loves'' remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   And, like some others responding to the Internet announcement,
Theran had some reservations about taking this tack to replace an
aging animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of dogs euthanized every year for lack of
a home,'' he said. ``It's a shame to take this direction _ it's
like trying to clone people when there are a whole bunch of
orphans'' without a home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
