<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YELTSIN-DECLINE-HNS &LR;      08-31 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-DECLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN: THE HERO WHO TURNED INTO A BUMBLER 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Boris Yeltsin's tragedy is that by the time he got to
the top, he was no longer the man he had been on his way there.
</P>
<P>
   Illness, hard drinking and a lack of application to the arduous
tasks involved in running such a vast country as Russia have turned
the onetime national hero into a sad bumbler whose grip on affairs
of state seems to have all but vanished.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of political and financial turbulence unmatched
since the collapse of the Soviet Union, a humiliated Yeltsin went
on television Friday to insist he will not resign as president but
also to promise that he won't run for re-election when his present
term ends in two years.
</P>
<P>
   He was addressing a disgruntled people who, as he himself is
well aware, have no sympathy for him.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts predict that, as a consequence of the
botched job he has done ruling Russia in recent months, he will not
be able to resist the pressure on him to quit and could step down
soon after his summit with President Clinton ends.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is the same man who, in the late 1980s, broke ranks
with the communist leadership in the Kremlin to proclaim his faith
in a democratic future. Unlike his erstwhile mentor, Mikhail
Gorbachev, he recognized that the communist system had
irretrievably lost its grip and would not endure much longer.
</P>
<P>
   His incessant demands for far-reaching change made him the
dominant dissident voice among senior party bosses, antagonizing
Gorbachev, then seemingly entrenched and applauded around the world
for his attempts to modernize the Soviet state. One day, according
to Yeltsin's autobiography, Gorbachev summoned him to his office
and told him gloatingly that he was ``finished.'' Events were, of
course, to show that it was Gorbachev who would be ousted.
</P>
<P>
   After Yeltsin was fired from the ruling Politburo and ostracized
by his former colleagues, he deftly planned for the day when
communism would be overthrown. He arranged to be elected to the
traditionally powerless job of president of the Russian Federation,
which despite its huge expanse was at the time little more than an
administrative division of the Soviet Union, ruled from the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   But from this seemingly innocuous post Yeltsin built the power
base that soon would make him leader of an independent Russia. He
also gained great credibility by being the first leading communist
to risk running in a free election _ something Gorbachev had
declined to do.
</P>
<P>
   Then a year later in 1991, Yeltsin's moment came. In
circumstances that remain mysterious to this day, members of
Gorbachev's own government placed the Soviet leader under house
arrest while he was on vacation in the Crimea and declared they
were restoring ``order'' to the Soviet system.
</P>
<P>
   Some historians suspect Gorbachev connived in the plot as part
of a complicated strategy to drop his badly sagging liberal reforms
and return to authoritarian rule. Whatever the truth, the inept
plotters, by an incredible oversight, failed to arrest Yeltsin, who
instantly became chief of the popular resistance to the coup.
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous and determined, he was everywhere: addressing crowds
from the top of a tank, urging wavering troops not to back the
coup, calling on western governments to stand fast in support of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Within 72 hours, the coup collapsed. No one doubted that most of
the credit belonged to Yeltsin. A shaken Gorbachev returned to
Moscow, but his authority had been fatally weakened. Under constant
attack by Yeltsin, he found himself divested of office in December
1991 as the Soviet Union dissolved. Already the real power in the
land, Yeltsin immediately became president of an independent
Russia. But the best was already behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Pledged to establish a free market economy, Yeltsin never quite
came to grips with the challenge. His own grasp of the economic
problems involved was patchy, and internal feuding among his
advisers didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   As one reform plan after another was discarded, Yeltsin appeared
to detach himself increasingly from the day-to-day business of
governing. Occasionally he would act decisively, only to lapse back
into apparent apathy. When anti-Yeltsin members of parliament rose
up against the regime in 1993, he crushed them violently, sending
tanks and artillery to assault the parliament building.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, he appeared to dither as economic difficulties
mounted and popular discontent grew. Reports that he was drinking
heavily persisted, and his deteriorating health led to major
operations in 1995 and 1996. He was re-elected in 1996 _ mainly,
according to many experts, because his chief opponent was a
communist.
</P>
<P>
   Now the onetime national hero has become a despised figure to
millions of Russians who believe he has made their lives worse than
they were in Soviet times. They cannot wait to be rid of him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
