<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THIS COUPLE ON THE RIGHT TRACK TO RETIREMENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are 34 and 31 years old, respectively, and have
about $50,000 invested in mutual funds through our retirement
accounts at work and Roth IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   The investments are almost entirely in stock mutual funds. We
add approximately $1,200 a month to these savings. We are
comfortable with a life style that costs us $40,000 a year. If we
continue at this rate of savings, at what age can we reasonably
stop working?
</P>
<P>
   B.H., Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The bugbear in making calculations of the sort that you seek
is inflation. After running a few rough projections, I determined
that it will take roughly 25 years to attain your target.
</P>
<P>
   So the threshold question becomes, how many dollars will you
need 25 years from now to buy the same things that $40,000 buys
now. The answer is $83,751 if we presume future inflation at 3
percent; at 4 percent the number rises to $106,633.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you continue your current investment program for 25
years, a pace of 10 percent average annual growth would take you to
$2,022,766. Let's assume that you then divide that sum into two
segments. One, representing two thirds of the whole, would be
invested to bring you an income stream. The balance would remain in
stocks, designed to build a pool to protect you from the effects of
inflation later in your retirement. Following this reasoning, you
would have $1,348,509 to invest for income, and if you achieved a
6.5 average yield on the income portfolio, this would generate
$87,653 in annual income. And that's in the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't make much sense to try to get much closer than a
ballpark figure; too many uncertainties loom. What will be the
state of Social Security in the year 2023? Was that projection of
10 percent average annual growth for stocks too high...or too low?
Will a 6.5 percent yield from fixed-income investments be realistic
in the future?
</P>
<P>
   Will you receive raises which will allow you to accelerate your
savings program? When you project such uncertainties over a couple
of decades, the future looks pretty murky.
</P>
<P>
   The best practice at this stage to reanalyze your situation
about every five years, making sure you're on track, and assessing
how things may have changed. You should be able to make some pretty
solid judgments once you are in your last decade before retirement,
but everything before then is largely a matter of rough conjecture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My tax accountant and I are concerned about the capital gains
tax that was due on my 1997 income tax. I had capital gains of more
than $7,000, most of which came from holdings in Vanguard Wellesley
and Vanguard Windsor II funds. My wife and I are both 79 years old
and the portfolio allocation is 3.3 percent money market, 37
percent bonds, 25.1 percent balanced, and 34.6 percent equities.
For our age, I think the amount in equities is too high, but if I
sell some of it, the capital gains will increase even more. I now
have all dividends and capital gains reinvested. I was thinking of
having the capital gains transferred to my money market account; I
would still pay the tax, but it would stop the growth.
</P>
<P>
   W.F., Hellertown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Certainly ending the reinvestment of capital gains would be a
good idea if you think you're overcommitted to equities -- but why
stop there? Why not have both the dividend and capital gains
distributions transferred to either your money market account or
one of your other fixed-income holdings? This would not only tend
to reduce future capital gains distributions, but also might move
the portfolio (albeit at a snail's pace) away from the heavy equity
concentration.
</P>
<P>
   But the basic fact of the business is that those unpleasant
taxable distributions simply come with the mutual fund territory --
and indeed the distributions of which you complain were far from
huge. Windsor II's 1997 capital gains represented 7.66 percent of
its yearend share value, and the Wellesley capital distributions
represented 6.63 percent of yearend net asset value. Generally in
years such as 1997 there's only limited howling about these taxable
distributions, since they represented only a fraction of the fund's
gains; Windsor II had a 32.38 percent capital gain for 1997, and
Wellesley showed a 20.19 percent total return. It isn't always so
-- from time to time, especially when changing markets cause
managers to make large portfolio alterations, a fund might produce
substantial capital gains distributions in a year when the fund
shows a negative total return -- and the unhappy owner has no
choice but to face the tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   There are several things investors can do to minimize potential
liabilities of this sort.
</P>
<P>
   One is to consider the so-called tax-managed funds, where
portfolio managers are charged with doing everything possible to
keep distributions to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Another is to consider the typical level of portfolio turnover
before buying a fund. If the typical portfolio turnover is in
excess of 100 percent, you can expect a bumpy ride with the taxman.
On the other hand, as with the two funds you complain about, if the
turnover is lower than 50 percent, you can expect more moderate and
consistent levels of distributions.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, before buying a fund, you can look through the
financials (or in the Morningstar Mutual Funds reports) to discover
the potential capital gains exposure, which is the percentage that
would be distributed if the entire portfolio were liquidated. For
Windsor II, that figure is 33 percent; for Vanguard Wellesley, the
number is 18 percent. Such figures are fairly typical for long-
established low-turnover funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have been reading your column for several years, and
noticed you recommend Fidelity GNMA fund as a conservative
investment for people who want a steady income. I called Fidelity
and asked them what the management costs are. Fidelity charges .74
percent (annually), Dreyfus charges .65 percent, and Vanguard said
there was not any charge, which is very hard to believe. Why do you
recommend Fidelity which seems to have higher costs than the
others? I am 60 and retired and looking for a reasonably priced
fund with decent returns and moderate swings in price.
</P>
<P>
   F.D., Fairview, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. First of all, my general tendency is to recommend funds in
families that investors are already working with, provided that the
fund family in question has a decent offering in the category.
Second, while steady readers of this column probably have long ago
realized I have a strong preference for Vanguard funds -- based on
their low fees and straightforward approach to investing -- I
frequently mention similar funds in other families simply to
forestall objections such as one I once received from a gentleman
who was convinced I was a Vanguard hireling. (For the record, I
have no relationship with Vanguard save as an investor.) Anyway,
you're right that the Vanguard GNMA offering is generally superior
to either of the others, although this may not be entirely tied to
expense levels.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I can't make sense of your numbers -- any of them. To
begin with, in the case of Vanguard I think your question was
interpreted as a request for the sales charge, or load.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sales charge for any of the funds you mentioned,
although Dreyfus GNMA does have a .20 percent annual 12b(1) or
distribution charge. As for the expense ratios, according to
Morningstar Mutual Funds, the total expense ratio for Dreyfus GNMA
is .96 percent, for Fidelity Spartan GNMA it is .51 percent, and
for Vanguard GNMA it is .31 percent. Since Fidelity Spartan GNMA is
closed to new investors I called for information on Fidelity GNMA,
which is not currently tracked by Morningstar, and was told the
ratio is .74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More important that these expense ratios, though, are the bottom
lines -- the average annual returns over a long period of time.
Here's the lineup over a five-year period: For Dreyfus the figure
is 6.02 percent, for Fidelity Spartan GNMA it is 6.56 percent, for
Fidelity GNMA it is 6.34 percent, and Vanguard GNMA comes out on
top, at 6.98 percent. Over 10 years, the figures are 7.94 percent
for Dreyfus GNMA, 9.08 percent for Fidelity GNMA, and 8.27 percent
for Vanguard GNMA. The Fidelity Spartan GNMA fund, founded in 1990,
doesn't have a 10-year record. There are rumors that Fidelity
Spartan GNMA is soon to be merged into Fidelity GNMA, which is a
shame from my point of view. This fund, which shares a portfolio
manager with Fidelity GNMA, offered a lower expense level in
exchange for a higher initial investment ($10,000) and reductions
in privileges such as check-writing. If you look closely at the
five-year numbers, the difference in average returns between the
Spartan fund and the other come within 1 basis point of perfectly
reflecting the differences in the expense ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, at bottom you're right -- Vanguard GNMA is the
top of the heap here, although all are solid funds, all rated
above-average by Morningstar Mutual funds except Vanguard GNMA,
which gets top five-star grades.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, I hold share of Vanguard GNMA and a family
member is an investor in Fidelity Spartan GNMA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
