<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0862 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-UNCERTAINTY-BO     08-31 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-UNCERTAINTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS FACED WITH A WORLD OF UNCERTAINTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the dizzying 482-point drop last week in the Dow
Jones Industrial Average can be explained with a single sentence,
it is this: Markets hate uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months after Asia slipped into financial chaos, the
uncertainties are multiplying in the world economy. There are no
clear signs that the Asian crisis will end. Despite US pleas, Japan
has not roused itself out of recession. And last week, Russia
collapsed into political and economic meltdown, leading markets to
worry not only about Russia's ruble but about the security of its
nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did investors sell last week? I think it was that the
world looks crazy, and people said they don't understand it,'' said
Roger Brinner, chief economist at Parthenon Group, a Boston
consulting and investment firm. ``And when people don't understand
the world, they get out of stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was a turbulent ride on markets worldwide, as
investors fled stocks and rushed into investments they believe are
safer, such as US Treasury bonds. The Dow industrial stocks fell
5.6 percent, their worst decline in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Will the world economy get worse? Should Americans be alarmed?
Several economists considered these and other questions as the Dow
fell, and rose, and fell again last week. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Asian financial crisis began more than a year ago. Why are
markets so turbulent now? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are few signs that Southeast Asia is improving, and recent
figures indicate that some economies are shrinking even more than
expected. That has left investors wary of emerging markets
elsewhere in the world, from Latin America to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent turmoil began earlier this month in Russia,
where political developments prompted already-wary investors to
abandon the country.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had been selling off Russian stocks and rubles, but
the government scared them even more by freezing all payments by
companies on their foreign debt. The government also cut the value
of the ruble, leading investors to sell more stocks on fears that a
weaker currency would leave consumers and companies even more
impoverished and shrink the economy.
</P>
<P>
   By midweek, the clamor to sell rubles was so loud that the
government suspended trading, and investors responded by sending
Russian stocks into a freefall. The fact that President Boris
Yeltsin had fired his entire Cabinet raised fears that Russia would
revert to Soviet-style leadership, prompting investors around the
world to sell stocks. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why should the US markets care about Russia? &LR;   &UR; Total US trade
with Russia is only $8 billion, a tiny portion of the US economy. A
single Massachusetts company, Raytheon Co., reports 2.5 times that
amount in annual sales. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For American investors, the fear is not so much that a
weakened ruble makes it harder for Russians to afford Gillette
razors or Compaq computers. The bigger concern is the fate of
Russia's 22,000 nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is who has control of those nuclear weapons,
given the leadership vacuum,'' said Robert Litan, director of
economic studies at the Brookings Institution. ``Markets hate
uncertainty, and there's a lot of uncertainty about who is going to
get those weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a some chance that the weakened ruble could hurt
the US economy indirectly. German banks are heavily invested in
Russia, and big losses could force them to curtail lending. In
turn, that could limit growth throughout Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a weaker ruble cuts the price of Russian oil and
other natural resources on the world market. Countries from Brazil
and Venezuela to Canada sell the same products and could be forced
to cut their prices as well, hurting their economies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If investors are pulling money from Russia and Asia, won't they
also abandon Latin America? Would that hurt the US economy? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Latin America's emerging markets are very important to the US
economy. Mexico is our third-largest trading partner, and Brazil
and Venezuela rank in the top 20.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are eyeing these markets warily. If they continue to
pull money from Latin American stocks and currencies, the region's
economies will almost certainly contract, making it far harder for
US companies to sell goods south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   But there are important differences between Latin America and
Southeast Asia, economists say.
</P>
<P>
   In the industrialized West, investors buy stocks or loan money
to businesses based on the return they will receive. In South
Korea, Indonesia, and even Japan, it was the government that
largely determined which businesses received capital.
</P>
<P>
   This ``crony capitalism'' prompted Asia to invest too much money
in factories and real estate developments that now sit empty. The
owners could not repay their loans, and banks hid the losses. When
these problems were revealed, investors fled.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists say Latin America is now closer to the
``efficient'' Western economic model. That suggests its banks are
less likely to carry hidden bad loans, and that investors have
funded businesses based on realistic profit expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chile is a real market economy,'' Litan said. ``Argentina's
banking system is controlled mostly by foreign banks, so you don't
have banks going nuts lending for all kinds of crazy purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, investors may be more likely to retain confidence in
Latin America, leaving the region less vulnerable to the capital
withdrawals that have crippled Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never be too sure, and in two weeks I could turn out
to be wrong, but the overbuilding and crony capitalism seem less
deeply embedded in Latin America,'' Litan said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; There is so much turmoil in the world economy. How much should
events abroad worry Americans?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  On a scale of one to 10, Litan said, the United States'
anxiety level should not exceed a three or four.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Asian crisis is already hurting some US
exporters. The government reported last week that US corporate
profits fell 1.5 percent in the second quarter from the same period
last year. It was the first such decline in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the hype in recent years over globalization,
trade is not as big a factor in the US economy as some people
believe. &UR;  &LR; Exports account for only 12 percent of gross domestic
product, a broad measure of economic activity. If world demand for
US products dropped 10 percent _ a huge number, considering that
many national economies are still growing _ the US gross domestic
product would fall 1 percent, Litan said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the 1.5 percent to 2 percent economic growth
that many economists forecast for next year would be shaved by a
percentage point. That could raise unemployment levels by a half a
percentage point or more, Litan said. But the economy would still
be expanding, not contracting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to think of the 85 percent of the economy that isn't
significantly tied to international trade,'' said Tim O'Neill,
chief economist at the Bank of Montreal. ``What you've got is a
domestic economy that is doing very well.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If economists are holding their anxiety in check, at least for
now, what events would make them truly nervous? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The answer is one word: China. Almost alone among its neighbors,
China has held the value of its currency steady. Giving in to the
temptation to devalue the yuan would echo ominously around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   A devaluation by China would surely trigger similar moves by
other emerging nations as each attempted to make its products more
attractive on the world market. When Indonesia devalues, for
example, a US dollar can buy more Indonesian rupiah _ and therefore
more Indonesian toys or noodles.
</P>
<P>
   A new round of devaluations would mean US companies face more
competition at home from cheaper imported products. At the same
time, foreign consumers would have less-valuable currencies to buy
US goods, meaning they would buy less of them. This would squeeze
US corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also say they cannot account for how Americans will
act in the face of global uncertainty. For now, consumer spending
is keeping US economy robust, as companies build new homes, make
products, and hire employees to feed consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   But consumers appear to be spending freely because they are
making money in the market and their jobs are secure. If the
world's economic prospects continue to darken, there could be a
steep downturn in the market, which could choke off the consumer
spending that is the main fuel of US economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, the only risk for the second half of this year is
that the American consumer loses his or her confidence by reading
about things going on in the rest of the world,'' said Brinner.
``That's the main thing that could knock us off balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
