</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Off to college, not a moment too soon
 &HT;    By VICKI MARSH KABAT
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How well I remember the emotions of May. As we watched our
eldest son cross the stage at his high school graduation, our
hearts swelled with pride and our eyes with tears at the thought of
our ``little boy'' heading off to college.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference three months can make.
</P>
<P>
   There is some odd chemical reaction that apparently occurs
between parents and child during the time between high school
graduation and collge welcome week. I personally believe it's a
gift from God that makes the separation easier. For lack of a more
scientific definition, let's just call it ``mutual
disenchantment.''
</P>
<P>
   Last May I was visiting across the backyard fence with my
neighbor, who also was experiencing emotional angst about her
daughter's graduation. We had watched these two kids grow up
together, had attended the same PTA meetings and open houses, the
same elementary, junior high and high school programs and award
ceremonies. Now, here were our two ``babies'' about to leave home.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, her daughter is going to college in a far northern
state while my son is only going up the road a short piece. She has
a bit more reason to agonize than I do.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, that same mother and I met by the backyard fence a
few days ago, looked each other solemnly in the eye and almost
simultaneously asked, ``Are you as ready as I am to send these kids
off?''
</P>
<P>
   It has been the summer of our discontent _ for the kids and for
us. For their part, they seem to think they are independent. That
would indicate they are ``not dependent'' on parents or others for
such things as college tuition, room and board, meal plans,
spending money, etc. Silly children.
</P>
<P>
   We, the parents, seem to think they are still contributing
members of our families and households, since we are still feeding,
clothing and housing them. As such, we expect they will help around
the house, mow the yard, ferry younger siblings, shovel out their
rooms occasionally, and the like. Silly us.
</P>
<P>
   How sadly we both are disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   I began working fulltime not long ago. As a result, I have
expected a great deal more of our three sons, including cooking an
occasional dinner. I'm not asking for vichyssoise or beef
stroganoff, but when I told our eldest to fix us BLT sandwiches
recently, you'd have thought I asked him to prepare a four-course
meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have lettuce and tomatoes,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   OK, son, let's use a few problem-solving skills here. We live
six blocks from a grocery store. There's a car in the driveway.
What should you do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to the store,'' I finally told him.
</P>
<P>
   Sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you cook the bacon?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a skillet, on the stove.''
</P>
<P>
   No response.
</P>
<P>
   ``You turn the stove on medium heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have to cook both sides of the bacon?''
</P>
<P>
   I ask you, is this child ready to be on his own?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you turn the bacon or flip it?''
</P>
<P>
   You can tie it in little bows if you want, just cook the bacon!
</P>
<P>
   After we packed him off to his college dorm, I came home and
walked into his bedroom. Well, I had to kick several things on the
floor aside and then I walked into his bedroom. I picked up a shirt
he left behind and, overcome by tender reflection, I pressed it to
my face to inhale the scent of my little boy, now a man _ and
promptly gagged from the stench.
</P>
<P>
   You know, I think it's time.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
