<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIET-SUPPLEMENTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIETARY-SUPPLEMENT INDUSTRY FLEXES ITS MUSCLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals' Mark McGwire closes in on the home run
record. The Denver Broncos win the Super Bowl. And the dietary
supplements the athletes use disappear from store shelves around
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Driven in part by a national obsession with health and
longevity, the dietary supplement industry has grown to a $12
billion industry. But the booming business in so-called performance
enhancers such as androstenedione and creatine is occurring amid
conflicting claims about their effectiveness and safety, and in an
industry that is almost totally unregulated.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials are starting to search for a way to put on the
brakes _ especially because some manufacturers are aiming their
marketing strategies at high school athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do $100 million in annual sales,'' said Len Moskovits, the
president and chief economic officer of Met-Rx USA Inc., of Irvine,
Calif., an industry leader in the manufacturing of protein shakes
and bars, along with more controversial products containing the
amino acid creatine (CREE-uh-teen). ``We started out in 1991 and
we've doubled our sales almost every year we've been around, and I
believe it is not because we are such great marketers but because
the consumer interest just keeps on increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, more than 10 retailers throughout the Boston area
said they found themselves running through their available stocks
of testosterone precursor androstenedione (an-dro-STEEN-die-own)
after a bottle of it was discovered in the locker of McGwire _ who
is in a historic, much-publicized pursuit of the game's
single-season home run record.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers, who last week were forced to begin shipping their
product by overnight delivery, admit it will be autumn before they
can keep pace with the demand generated by the McGwire story.
</P>
<P>
   A similar increase in consumer interest in creatine products,
among the most popular dietary supplements, accompanied the Super
Bowl victory of the Denver Broncos in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creatine products started flying off the shelves _ just like
andro this week _ because three-quarters of the Broncos used these
products,'' said Rick Antonelli, a salesman at Newbury Naturals in
Boston. ``People were saying, `Wow! Did the Denver Broncos beat the
mighty Green Bay Packers. And they use this stuff?'''
</P>
<P>
   Creatine is a shining star in the dietary supplement industry.
In 1995, about six years after creatine was developed, sales
totalled $30 million, according to the Nutrition Business Journal.
This year, sales are projected to exceed $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione, and similar ``andro products'' like Met-Rx's
Androdiol, were introduced within the past year. Sales were
expected to total perhaps $10 million annually, at first. In the
wake of the McGwire story, Moscovits and others say they expect
sales to total $70 million to $100 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it do for this business?'' Moskovits said. ``If Mark
McGwire had said he eats a bunch of radishes every morning,
everyone would go out and buy radishes. Anyone who was on the fence
about these products before, they got off the fence this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the escalating consumer demand and the manufacturers' drive
to meet it is enormous concern about the consequences for public
health, and outright attempts to halt the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Association of Tennis Professionals Tour
reiterated its ban on androstenedione and the General Nutrition
Centers ordered its 3,700 stores not to sell it because of safety
concerns. Major League Baseball and the players' union called on
doctors to research muscle-enhancing supplements. In Rome,
meanwhile, a major Italian soccer commissioner suggested that
creatine be banned or greatly restricted.
</P>
<P>
   The decade-long trend of increasing interest in dietary
supplements is occurring amid relaxed government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Congress loosened restrictions on the sale of dietary
supplements. Driven in large part by consumers' voracious appetite,
a bi-partisan group of congressmen relaxed requirements for
pre-market approval by the Food and Drug Administration. They also
allowed the manufacturers greater flexibility to make claims about
the performance of their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``As dietary supplements become increasingly popular it is all
the more important that government have adequate tools to make sure
these products are safe and well regulated,'' said Bruce
Silverglade, legal director for the Center for Science in the
Public Interest. ``Unfortunately, Congress in 1994 rendered the
Food and Drug Administration toothless. Some people may have to get
hurt before Congress takes a look at it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, doctors and scientists are hoping that the
manufacturers police themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it really comes down to company by company,'' said
Richard Kreider, director of the Sports Nutrition Laboratory at the
University of Memphis. ``The major companies usually do a fairly
good job in honestly explaining what their products do and do not
do. Some of the newer smaller companies that are more aggressive in
the market, trying to find a niche, may be of more concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreider and other nutritionists said it is especially important
that companies support independent research. Moskovits says Met-Rx
is particularly proud of its spending on research, and officials at
EAS say they spend $1 million annually on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get creatine anywhere, but only a handful of companies
are standing behind it in that way,'' Kreider said.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few officials fear that young athletes are
particularly at risk in this unregulated market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want a kid influenced by a slick marketing technique
into taking something they ought not to be taking, especially if
the thought is that it is a shortcut to athletic success,'' said
Bill Gaine, of the Massachusetts Interscholastic Athletic
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Gaine said that coaches and athletic administrators around
Massachusetts have discovered what doctors and nutritionists
already know: Definitive information on many dietary supplements is
extremely difficult to come by. The association hopes to adopt a
more general policy this month mandating that use of the products
occur only under the supervision of parents and coaches and after
consultation with doctors, Gaine said.
</P>
<P>
   Moscovits admits that part of Met-Rx's marketing strategy for
creatine products is an appeal to youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advertise in publications that they read, like American
Football Quarterly, which goes to high school and college
coaches,'' he said. ``We offer a program called Mentor, and they
can get the same stuff the pros use but at a lower cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscovits said some of the ads feature high school cheerleaders
to attract the attention of young male athletes. But he also said
that Met-Rx would never market its Androdiol products to youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not pitch them to high school athletes because we think
it would be dangerous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Pastner, president of the Massachusetts High School
Football Coaches Association, says he sees more than a few
advertisements and solicitations for the supplements and enhancers.
``When I get them,'' Pastner said, ``I throw them right in the
trash.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastner and many nutritionists say the biggest danger of the
supplement fad is that younger athletes will simply forget that the
best way to train is to eat properly and work hard. Pastner says he
remains a devotee of ``three or four meals a day and lots of
frappes'' for players who need to bulk up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the high school audiences, advertising appeals to them
in a big way,'' said Nancy Clark, a sports nutritionist. ``They are
so malleable. What I get concerned about is that people forget that
food works. So many people reach for this magic bullet and they
forget about breakfast and lunch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
