<HEADER>
A0868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-BORDER-BOS &LR;      08-31 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BORDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CANADIANS VEXED BY STRICTER US BORDER PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Bad feelings are boiling along the world's
friendliest border.
</P>
<P>
   A move by Congress to tighten requirements for Canadians
entering the United States has Ottawa in a tizzy. Officials north
of the border say the scheme to force Canadians, like other
foreigners, to fill out immigration cards and undergo tighter
scrutiny upon entering the United States is a betrayal of the
``special relationship'' that has allowed citizens of both
countries extraordinary freedom in passing back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Canadians, American business and political leaders
from New England to the Pacific Northwest warn that Section 110 of
the immigration law _ which goes before the House of
Representatives next month _ will result in the loss of hundreds of
millions of dollars' worth of trade and tourism by discouraging
travel and creating hours-long traffic backups at busy border
crossings.
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives in Congress say Canadians should be treated no
differently than any other foreigners. They accuse Canada of
providing safe haven to terrorists under notably lax asylum laws,
and warn that maintaining soft entry rules along the northern
border exposes the United States to danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an open border that is an open invitation to people
who want to smuggle in drugs or people or terrorism,'' said
Representative Lamar Smith, the Texas Republican who is the main
author of the tough new immigration law. Although the law was
passed in 1996, enforcement of Section 110 _ the requirement that
Canadians fill out entry/exit forms _ has been delayed because of
bitter opposition from Ottawa and congressional leaders from
northern states.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Smith's office characterized Canada as a
``gateway for terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help Canada's case that the country's own spy agency,
the Canadian Security Intelligence Service, reported last April
that major international terrorist groups have ``established
themselves in Canada, seeking safe haven, setting up operational
bases and attempting to gain access to the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   One prominent case involved a Palestinian, Gazi Abu Mezer, who,
shortly after gaining refugee status in Canada, sneaked across the
border and was arrested in July 1997 for allegedly plotting to bomb
subways in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Canadian officials say the real border problem for
the United States is with Mexico, source of more illegal
immigrants, drugs, and other contraband in any given week than is
smuggled from Canada in a year. They say the law will cause
headaches and hassles for Canadians who pose no threat to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Section 110 is terrible for trade, terrible for tourism, and
just terrible overall for both sides,'' said Rodney Moore,
spokesman for the Canadian Embassy in Washington. ``Congress
essentially seems to be trying to address problems the US has on
its southern border without recognizing that the northern border is
not at all similar.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Canadians are in an uproar over a different part of
the immigration law that has already gone into effect that gives US
border inspectors sweeping and arbitrary powers to impose a
five-year entry ban on any non-citizen they suspect of
``misrepresenting'' his or her reason for coming to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The law was intended to provide officers with a way of turning
back would-be illegal immigrants, most notoriously from Mexico, who
try to enter the United States claiming to be short-term tourists
when their real aim is find permanent work.
</P>
<P>
   Critics in the north, however, assert that officers of the US
Immigration and Naturalization Service have used their new
authority to come down hard on Canadians for seemingly minor border
infractions.
</P>
<P>
   There is no judicial appeal process for the so-called expedited
removals _ the on-the-spot five-year bans that can now be imposed
by any border inspector.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a system wide open for abuse,'' said Anna Marie
Gallagher, a lawyer with the American Immigration Law Foundation,
which has filed a federal lawsuit in Washington, D.C., challenging
the law. ``It's giving low-level government officers power to act
as judge, jury, and executioner.''
</P>
<P>
   Last March 4, Donald Chatwin of Abbotsford, British Columbia,
was making the daily trip across the border to a job as a
consultant with a Bellingham, Wash., computer firm, of which he is
also a part-owner.
</P>
<P>
   But on that day, INS officers accused him of violating a
condition of his visa by performing sales duties for the company
when his application for the work permit claimed that the job only
entailed providing technical advice. He was grilled for several
hours, fingerprinted, photographed, and summarily banned from the
United States for five years under the controversial new procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Chatwin is reluctant to discuss the order, which he is trying to
have legally overturned, saying only, ``It's had a pretty drastic
impact on my life. It seems punishment out of all proportion to a
misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Chatwin's lawyer in the United States, Greg Boos of Bellingham,
put it more bluntly. ``The new powers given immigration officers is
turning the border into a ruder, more surly, and even frightening
place for Canadians.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent headlines in Canada certainly seem to suggest so.
</P>
<P>
   ``US border crackdown keeping Canadians out,'' proclaimed a
recent front-page article in the Toronto-based Globe &AMP; Mail, while
the Montreal Gazette ran this banner headline: ``US inspectors turn
trips into nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   Accurately or not, this perception has become common in Canada
since US immigration officers started wielding their new authority
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a bullying attitude at the border that wasn't there
before,'' said Ontario businessman Bud Williamson, who makes
frequent trips to the United States. ``And a lot of good will at
our borders is going down the drain. It's a huge issue for
Canadians, but Americans seem oblivious to the bad feelings your
new laws are causing among your best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   US border officials, however, say they are fed up with ``wild
rumors created by a Canadian media frenzy,'' in the words of
Russell A. Bergeron Jr., spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue has been overblown, hyped by Canadian newspapers and
TV seizing on a few cases,'' he said. ``The actual numbers of
Canadians subjected to expedited removal is minute, a tiny fraction
of 1 percent of the millions of Canadians who enter without any
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he warned, ``misrepresentation is
misrepresentation, a lie is a lie. Anyone who tries to enter by
twisting the truth or telling a half-truth is violating the law.
That's true in the US, just as it is true in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Since April 1997, when immigration inspectors started exercising
their new authority, a total of 62,706 foreigners seeking to enter
the United States from Canada or Mexico have been ejected and
slapped with five-year entry bans. But only 470 were Canadians; the
huge majority were Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   The most common misrepresentations are by Canadians entering the
United States to do business, legally or not, who claim to be
traveling on holiday, since they assume that will create less
hassle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a unique and special relationship on the northern
border,'' Bergeron said. ``But there is also supposed to be honor
between friends. A Canadian does not have an absolute right to
cross for any reason. A Canadian is not entitled to tell a white
lie just in hopes of avoiding legitimate questions from immigration
officers enforcing US law.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the cases of a few dozen Canadians hit with the
bans for seemingly petty infractions _ as opposed to Canadians
caught carrying drugs or blatantly trying to deceive _ have
generated extraordinary bad feeling in this nation. Special legal
seminars on ``how to enter the US'' attract thousands of
businesspeople fearful that the slightest slip of the tongue or
forgotten document will result in sanctions that might ruin their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a public relations disaster for the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that US Ambassador Gordon G. Giffin implored Canadian
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy not to let a ``few
misunderstandings'' harm relations.
</P>
<P>
   Top Canadian officials, for their part, are far less worried
about the expedited removal issue than the possibility that Section
110, imposing the new travel requirements, might still go into
effect Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new law could put a real chill in relations as well as
causing incalculable harm to businesses on both sides of the
border,'' said a senior Foreign Ministry official.
</P>
</TEXT>
