<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT ELVIS SHRINE, ARAB, JEW TUNE OUT DISCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In this land of biblical patriarchs there is still
only one man referred to simply as ``The King.''
</P>
<P>
   Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   And here in the Jerusalem hills, the life and music of Elvis
Presley, the king of rock 'n' roll, are displayed in all their
glory at a gas station and restaurant known as The Elvis Inn.
</P>
<P>
   From the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem highway, a 22-foot-high statue of
Elvis looms like an ancient icon over a hilltop between the Israeli
community of Neve Illan and the Arab village of Abu Ghosh.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a place devoted to Elvis in Israel began 25 years
ago when Uri Yoeli brought two pictures of The King to his small
restaurant, then known as ``The Mountain Inn.'' People commented
about the pictures, and soon the place was referred to by regulars
as the ``Elvis place.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Yoeli has named it ``The Elvis Inn,'' and the walls and even
the ceiling are covered with Elvis photographs, posters, framed
album covers, yellowed newspaper clippings, concert tour
promotions, and every imaginable form of Elvis souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   Every day from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m., the place moves to the beat of
Elvis hits from early numbers like ``Jailhouse Rock'' to later hits
like ``Burning Love.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yoeli has framed a ticket stub from the 1971 Salt Lake City
concert. He traveled there to see The King decked out in his
trademark white fringed jumpsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Yoeli, 52, remembers the first time he heard Elvis sing. In
1956, when the nation of Israel was less than a decade old, a girl
in his Jerusalem neighborhood had a 45 of ``One Night.'' His family
owned the block's only record player. It was the beginning of his
love for The King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person of our generation has an image of him, a memory
of him. That is what this place is devoted to,'' Yoeli said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Elvis Inn is more than a pop shrine.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place where Jews, Muslims, Christians come together. It's
not unusual to see an ultra-rthodox Jew in black garb filling up at
the gas station while an Israeli Arab family stops for ice cream at
picnic tables and a busload of Christian tourists pause for a
snapshot in front of the statue.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the peace process is deadlocked and the long,
simmering tension of this place can be draining, the Elvis Inn
offers a way of getting away from it all.
</P>
<P>
   Rafi Mohammed, 30, from Abu Ghosh and a regular at the
restaurant, said, ``All politics ends when you hear Elvis. The
truth is, things aren't moving with the peace plan. We all feel
stuck, and you can get very down. This place lets you forget all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Cohen of Jerusalem loves to stop for coffee. ``This is
where you can relax, you get away from all the divisions,'' he
said. ``Elvis is singing about love and about rock 'n' roll. It
makes you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce and Sherry Conrad, American tourists, were trying to
decide their favorite Elvis tune. For him, ``Love Me Tender.'' For
her, Elvis's version of ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lost trying to get to our hotel and an Arab guy told
us just to look for the statue of Elvis Presley,'' said Bruce, an
oil worker from Florida stationed in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in Israel a week and we've come here every day.
Hamburgers. Gas station. Cigarettes. Whiskey. Elvis on the jukebox.
Man, you can kid yourself for a minute that you're in America.
What's more American than Elvis?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Sherry added, ``He's not just about America, Elvis is
international. The whole world loves Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Charles M. Sennott is chief of the Globe's Jerusalem bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
