u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-INVESTORS-BOS &LR;      08-31 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-INVESTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS WILL WAIT, SEE WHAT HAPPENS NEXT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. JAFFE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One or two more bad days on Wall Street and some investors may
start to feel the walls closing in on them.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those nervous investors overcome their fears and stay
put or bust out and start selling in an attempt to lock in gains
will have a big role in determining what happens next on Wall
Street. And the next few days promise to be critical, both to the
future of individual investors and to the market itself.
</P>
<P>
   Investors may talk brave, but they don't always act that way,
and their resolve already has been tested by the stock market's
five-week, 13.8 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people are ready just yet to abandon ship, but
that could change if the market drops another 3 to 5 percentage
points,'' says Richard Geist, president of the Institute of
Psychology in Investing, a Boston research/consulting organization
that examines investor behavior. ``A bigger decline could change
the whole psychology of `buy on the dips.' If people sell on
strength instead of buying on weakness, everything changes.''
</P>
<P>
   While market watchers say investors have shown no signs of
panicking during the previous dips of the 1990s, investor
psychologists note that current market conditions are different.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the current downturn is slower and more torturous
than the 550-point freefall the market experienced last October.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University professor Jeffrey Heisler says that downturn
happened so quickly that investors were like deer in the
headlights, frozen by indecision and lucky that the downturn
quickly reversed direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What no one knows is whether no one bailed because everyone
stuck to their discipline or because the worst was over by the time
people recovered from being blindsided by it,'' Heisler says.
</P>
<P>
   How investors will react in the current downturn depends on what
happens next, but observers note that there are any number of
psychological factors at play. Consider the following:
</P>
<P>
   _If the Dow Jones industrial average loses another 114 points,
it will be off 15 percent from its peak on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly eight years since the Dow last gave back 15
percent of its value, the longest stretch in history without a
decline of that magnitude. The four next-longest periods without a
bear market ended in the crashes of 1929 and 1987, and with the
declines of about 25 percent over several years in the 1940s and
1960s. And none of those growth periods was even half as long as
the market's current spurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply a historical fact that the longer you go without
healthy corrections or bear markets, the more likely the next
downturn turns out to be something larger than anyone expects,''
says James Stack, publisher of the Investech newsletter in
Whitefish, Mont. ``People have learned to buy on the dips, but this
might not be just another dip. People should be worried about the
magnitude of what could happen next.''
</P>
<P>
   _If the Dow's loss grows from 114 points to 144, it breaks the
level it held at the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, psychologists warn, the nerves could really kick
in. One factor that has kept people in the market over the last
five weeks was that the market was still positive for the whole
year.
</P>
<P>
   Once you change that _ dropping below 8000 to boot _ there might
be more fear.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics note that other indices besides the Dow already have
lost more than 15 percent and that investors have held on, but
mounting declines across-the-board could eventually lead to
investors pulling the rip cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a point where people no longer see the market like
rust eating at the hull of the ship or moss eating the roof,'' says
Donald MacGregor, senior researcher at Decision Research in Eugene,
Ore. ``They decide `This is the bottom falling out quickly.'
Something is going to trigger that feeling, and that is when we see
investors cut and run.''
</P>
<P>
   _The vast majority of money in the stock market today _
including by most estimates almost 90 percent of everything in
stock mutual funds _ was not there for the last bear market.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of long, deep, slow losses is entirely new to
most investors. Moreover, psychologists note that people whose
expectations are met _ whether in investing or in general _ tend to
react very strongly when they suddenly are let down.
</P>
<P>
   It makes no difference whether they believe the talk shows,
magazines, newsletters, or in something silly like Super Bowl
theory _ by which January's win by the Denver Broncos of the
American Football Conference supposedly signaled a downturn for the
year. The one universal truth about investors is that none of them
wants to suffer losses for too long.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the success of the last few years may also cause
some people to pull back. The oversized gains of the mid-1990s have
helped some investors reach their goals, such as financing a
college education. They will not want to see that success snatched
away. That can prompt a switch into survival mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who say they will hold on through the bottom of a
bear market won't actually do it,'' says Mark Hulbert, a faculty
member for the Congress on the Psychology of Investing and
publisher of the Hulbert Financial Digest, which tracks newsletter
performance. ``They may believe in buy-and-hold now, but they will
get to a point _ if losses keep mounting _ when they say `I was
wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   Any number of indicators show signs that investor resolve
already is weakening. Less money is flowing into stocks and more
into money-market funds, a sign that investors are getting more
conservative. Early reports indicate that this change includes
assets held in retirement plans, which presumably are long-term
holdings in which the investor can ride out the downturns.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the financial psychologists acknowledge having no
idea how investors will react, most believe that staying the course
will be the right action for those who can stomach whatever comes
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will take some of the giddiness out of the market, but I
don't think it will make people suddenly believe that only idiots
invest in stocks,'' says Meir Statman, a Santa Clara University
professor who studies behavioral finance. ``Everyone believes
things will go up again in the future _ maybe soon, maybe not _ so
pulling back is probably a mistake. But investors are like kids
sometimes: They just don't get it and won't believe you until they
make mistakes for themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
