<HEADLINE>
CLANCY'S `RAINBOW' JUST TOO SILLY TO THRILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
RAINBOW SIX 
By Tom Clancy 
Putnam, 740 pp., $27.95 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happens when a writer of military thrillers runs out of
plausible enemies? Here's a hint _ it's not pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Just take a peek at the latest from old reliable himself, Tom
Clancy. He's in a bad way for bad guys. Since the Cold War ended,
Clancy has ginned up a succession of ruthless new adversaries _
Colombian drug lords, Iranian fanatics, Japanese lunatics. Yet
miscreants and malefactors have gotten a bit thin on the ground _
at least the kind suitable for the attentions of Clancy's
cold-eyed, high-tech warriors.
</P>
<P>
   But the god of bestsellers is a demanding god. Clancy knows that
he must continue to heap menace upon menace and thrill upon thrill
to keep his readers satiated. And so the dust jacket of his latest
book, ``Rainbow Six,'' promises the ultimate villains, ``a band of
men and women so extreme that their success could literally mean
the end of life on this earth as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The dust jacket tells us no more about these hell-spawned
fiends, perhaps to preserve an aura of suspense, but more likely to
prevent bookstore browsers from bursting into hysterical laughter.
</P>
<P>
   For this time out, Clancy's hero John Clark must save the world
from environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   You heard right. It's a cabal of tree-huggers, led by a biotech
billionaire who is convinced that the only hope for the earth's
ecosystem is the near-total extermination of the human race. Armed
with his limitless wealth, this mastermind launches an
international plot to infect all but a chosen few with a deadly new
strain of the Ebola virus that'll leave the earth fresh and pure
again, except for a few billion fetid corpses.
</P>
<P>
   The faithful Clancy fan, once he's stopped giggling, will notice
that the old boy has taken to repeating himself. It seems odd for a
free-market type like Clancy to choose plutocratic loonies as his
villains, but this makes his second trip to that well. A couple
books ago, in ``Debt of Honor,'' it was a Japanese magnate pulling
the strings. And then there's this business of the Ebola virus.
Just one book earlier, in ``Executive Orders,'' the Iranians tried
that trick.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, apart from the freelance mayhem of nut cases like the
Unabomber, the environmental movement hasn't displayed a whole lot
in the way of blood lust. Certainly not enough to allow for 740
pages of military muscle-flexing. So Clancy serves up a bizarre
plot in which our eco-psycho spends millions to fund a variety of
terrorist groups. It's hard to see why, when he's just going to
exterminate everybody in the end. But at least it gives John Clark
and his band of hard men lots of opportunities to shout ``Execute!
Execute!'' into their walkie-talkies while redecorating Europe with
the brains of their adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy made his name by building a thoroughly credible thriller
around an outrageous premise. ``The Hunt for Red October'' is a
rollicking read; it leaves you utterly persuaded that the CIA could
steal a nuclear submarine from the Soviet Navy, and get away with
it. Then again, Clancy stretched his legs a bit with ``Clear and
Present Danger.'' Amid the usual flag-waving, this book offered a
sober meditation on the limits of military force, and the
consequences of pulling the trigger once too often.
</P>
<P>
   But his series of novels about Clark and CIA
analyst-turned-president Jack Ryan become more implausible with
each outing. With ``Rainbow Six,'' Clancy's hit the wall. Even his
considerable narrative talent can do nothing to rescue this
ridiculous tale. And I fear there's worse to come. On a recent talk
show, Clancy said he's got three more novels in the pipeline.
There's no telling what we're in for _ an all-female army of
genetically engineered Amazons, perhaps, led by a fanatical devotee
of Minister Louis Farrakhan.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh _ people will buy it. They're buying ``Rainbow
Six,'' aren't they?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
