<SLUG> BC-TV-PAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAX TV TUNES IN TO SPIRITUAL SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Why a seventh network?'' repeated Lowell ``Bud'' Paxson. ``Why
not?''
</P>
<P>
   Paxson's jaunty optimism notwithstanding, skepticism surrounds
the launch today of Pax TV, his ``family-friendly'' alternative to
the television networks he dismisses as ``lemmings'': NBC, ABC,
CBS, Fox, UPN, and the WB.
</P>
<P>
   From Wall Street, Madison Avenue, and Hollywood have come
rumblings of doubt that Paxson can corral enough viewers and
advertisers to &UR;  &LR; make Pax TV more than a blip on the television
screen.
</P>
<P>
   But the 63-year-old multimillionaire who cofounded the Home
Shopping Network _ and who says he believes divine intervention has
played a hand in the establishment of his new network _ is not
easily daunted. ``The naysayers said we wouldn't launch, and now
that we're going to launch, they say we're going to fail,'' said
Paxson. ``They're going to be wrong twice.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Paxson sees it, at a time when other networks are
``fighting for the young and edgy shows and who can do the most
violence and sex,'' the Pax TV lineup represents the ultimate in
counter-programming, with reruns of such G-rated fare as ``Touched
by an Angel,'' ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman,'' ``Diagnosis Murder,''
``Highway to Heaven,'' and ``I'll Fly Away'' (shows drawn from the
very networks Paxson views as lemmings).
</P>
<P>
   ``Counter-programming is always a good idea,'' said Paxson, the
chairman of Paxson Communications Corp., a Florida-based company
that owns 75 TV stations. Paxson added that he views the ``Hallmark
Hall of Fame'' specials as a model for what his network will offer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reruns, the network also will show original
programming such as two new talk shows, ``Great Day America'' and
``Woman's Day,'' along with several children's shows and ``Flipper:
The New Adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he emphasizes ``this network is not here to
televangelize,'' Paxson says he wants Pax TV to ``tap into the
spiritual side'' of a nation where most citizens describe
themselves as religious. ``It's going to be family programming with
a little touch of the spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxson, a born-again Christian, says he discerns the hand of God
in the sequence of events that led to Pax TV. ``I don't say He
called; I never got a phone call, I never heard His voice,'' said
Paxson. ``But I kept seeing the doors opened. All the things that
happened to us couldn't have happened without a little divine
intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the launch of Pax TV, today marks the publication
date for ``Threading the Needle: The Pax Net Story,'' written by
Paxson with Gary Templeton. (The new network was originally called
Pax Net before being renamed Pax TV.)
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV will air on 88 stations, including stations in all top 20
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Though he hopes for more viewers, Paxson argues that Pax TV
needs only a .6 rating in prime time _ about 600,000 viewers _ to
break even, and predicts the network will turn a profit within its
first six months.
</P>
<P>
   TV industry consultant Paul R. Krumins, publisher of a newletter
called Syndication News, strongly disagrees with both assertions.
``No one in the television industry will agree with that,'' said
Krumins. ``The economics just don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   While Krumins said he thinks some viewers will be receptive to
family-oriented programming, he contended that neither national nor
local advertisers will be eager to sign up with a network that
can't deliver a sizable audience. Paxson needs strong ratings to
recoup the money he paid for programming, Krumins said.
</P>
<P>
   The debut of Pax TV has not been without controversy. Last
month, the network ran an ad in trade magazines that some critics
viewed as anti-gay. The ad accused ``some so-called creative
people'' of using TV to ``peddle every kind of alternative language
and lifestyle to our kids.'' Pax TV president Jeff Sagansky
apologized in July, saying the ad was meant ``to make the point
about the need for family programming and not to pass judgment on
any person or lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxson dismisses the flap as ``something the media people
dreamed up and tried to make a story of.'' He said the subject of
homosexuality will be ``treated with absolute respect'' on Pax TV.
``It's nothing we want to run from,'' he said. ``We want to treat
it with dignity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
