<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATES STICK VOLUNTEER RESCUE WORKERS WITH $4,000 BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHOHARIE, N.Y. _ The volunteer rescue workers who saved Graig
Douglas didn't expect money for the dangerous job they did. On the
hand, they didn't expect a bill either. But that's what they got.
</P>
<P>
   When Douglas found himself wedged in a tunnel on July 18, the
state of New York's emergency system kicked into high gear, sending
a C-12 military transport plane to pick up 11 volunteers from three
states who were experienced _ and small enough _ to rescue the
24-year-old Medford, Mass., man from the narrow cave.
</P>
<P>
   But after getting Douglas out of his tight squeeze two days
later, the volunteers, who had come from Maryland, Virginia and
West Virginia and already had missed a day of work, found that New
York state was in no hurry to send them home.
</P>
<P>
   With the emergency over, the volunteers were told that flying
them home was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way we could justify flying them back on a
military aircraft,'' confirmed Don Mower, spokesman for the State
Emergency Management Office.
</P>
<P>
   So, they were told, they'd have to wait at least a day, and then
pile into a 15-person van that one caving expert said couldn't
possibly have fit an 11-person team and all their climbing gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a physical impossibility,'' said Emily Davis Mobley, a
nationally known caver and spokeswoman for the Albany-Schoharie
County Cave Rescue Team. She said the arrangement also required the
volunteers to stay overnight at the State University College at
Cobleskill. Most, she said, were already taking personal time off
from work.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result of the state's decision, the volunteers who
rescued Douglas were left with a bill estimated at $3,000 to
$4,000. Of that, Mobley said she personally paid $1,500 to charter
a larger bus to drive them back that Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the bus, Mobley said she expects her home phone bill
to hit $600 to $800 for calls around the country in search of
volunteers. Other people have cell phone bills, although at least
one company, Cellular One, has agreed to forgive one volunteer's
bill of about $150 for the weekend. At least one rescue worker lost
a 100-foot climbing rope worth about $50, and another dozen or so
more ropes are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley said that since word got around about the bills, cavers
have raised about $2,000 from various donations including $750 in
loose change and bills that came in at the National Speleological
Society convention in Albany two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, still using crutches but hoping to walk without them in
a month or so, said his medical insurance covered his bills and
about the only expense he faced personally was ``my gear got beat
up.'' He said he's trying to help raise money to cover the
remaining bills; plans are being made for a bike-athon along the
Maine coast later this year.
</P>
<P>
   There is, so far, no exact accounting of the bills, which Mobley
said may also include some equipment lost by local fire or rescue
squads. Anything left over will be donated either to the society or
to local rescue companies, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
