<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VIDEOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITANIC' SETS SAIL; A SHALLOW `DREAM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES:  &UR; ``Titanic'' &LR;  _ By now everyone has made up their
minds about this mega-movie. Director James Cameron made Leonardo
DiCaprio a star, no small task, and revived Gloria Stuart's career.
But I don't think it's as good as ``The Poseidon Adventure.'' A
little too treacly and overwrought for my tastes. Rent ``Lifeboat''
instead and see what Hitchcock did with a lot less space and money
but a lot more talent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Dream for an Insomniac'' &LR;  _ Ione Skye, who showed such
potential in the brilliant teen noir ``The River's Edge,'' flattens
out in this pretentious trifle that panders to a young, supposedly
hip audience. If they are hip, they'll just stay away from this
silly love story. Jennifer Aniston co-stars as an actress and many
of the lines are ``Friends'' derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Absolutely Fabulous Moments''  &LR; _ Highlights from the
hilarious British comedy that originally aired on Comedy Central.
Some of the skits are even funnier in this form than in their
original context.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Naked Lies'' &LR;  _ Shannon Tweed, one of the most underrated
actresses, stars in another direct-to-video erotic thriller. Aside
from being sexy, Tweed has a great sense of humor and has shown, on
many occasions, an ability to interpret a role with far more
sophistication than many of her more highly regarded colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Homegrown'' &LR;  _ The mainstream studios rarely know what to do
with dark comedies and this hilarious ode to paranoia is a perfect
example. When it failed to do good business opening weekend,
Columbia lost interest in it theatrically. This is a terrific
word-of-mouth picture that should find its audience among the more
sophisticated of the video crowd. Hank Azaria is particularly good
in an ensemble cast that includes Billy Bob Thornton, John Lithgow,
and Jon Bon Jovi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS:  &UR; Sept. 8:  &LR; ``Primary Colors,'' ``A Call to
Remember,'' ``Children of the Noisy Village,'' ``The Spree,'' ``I
Love You ... Don't Touch Me.''  &UR; Sept. 15:  &LR; ``Lady and the Tramp,''
``He Got Game,' ``Deep Rising,'' ``Hush,'' ``Rhapsody in August,''
``Eat, Drink, Man, Woman,'' ``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer,''
``Suicide Kings,'' ``Man with the Gun,'' ``To Live.''  &UR; Sept. 22:
 &LR; ``Addams Family Reunion,'' ``Happy Together,'' ``Nightwatch,''
``Fallen Angels.''  &UR; Sept. 29:  &LR; ``The Object of My Affection,''
``The Song of Songs,'' ``The Trial,'' ``Milo,'' ``Two Girls and a
Guy,'' ``The Devil Is a Woman,'' ``Chinese Box,'' ``The Flame of
New Orleans,'' ``Paulie.''  &UR; Oct. 6 &LR; : ``Lost in Space,'' ``Holiday
Toons.''  &UR; Oct. 13: &LR;  ``The Big One,'' ``Black Dog,'' ``It's a
Gift,'' ``Million Dollar Legs,'' ``You Can't Cheat an Honest Man,''
``You're Telling Me,'' ``I Got the Hook Up.''  &UR; Oct. 20 &LR; : ``Chitty
Chitty Bang Bang,'' ``Red Corner.''  &UR; Oct. 27:  &LR; ``The Lion King II:
Simba's Pride.''
</P>
</TEXT>
