 Monday, Aug. 31, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed or will file these
stories for Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ President Clinton, flying to Moscow
for two days of talks with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, warns
that U.S. support of Russia is conditioned on a continuation of
economic and political reforms. Clinton arrives Tuesday. By STEWART
M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   YELTSIN-DECLINE (Paris) _ already filed _ By the time Boris
Yeltsin got to the top, he was no longer the man he had been on his
way there. Illness, drinking and lack of hard work have turned the
onetime national hero into a sad bumbler whose grip on affairs of
state seems to have all but vanished. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The waffling of House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt typifies the
confusion in both parties about how partisan to be toward President
Clinton's problems. When they tried to be statesmanlike, outraged
activists forced them to retreat into more one-sided language. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
