<HEADLINE>
NEW AND RECOMMENDED RECENTLY REVIEWED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Rings of Saturn''  &LR; by W.G. Sebald (New Directions,
$23.95). Fact or fiction? An exploration of the vanity of human
wishes, set in southeastern England, by a German master.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Belong to Me'' &LR;  by Kai Maristed (Random House, $23.95). A
thought-provoking, inventive collection of stories about horses and
their humans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Helen Keller: A Life'' &LR;  by Dorothy Herrmann (Kknopf $30).
Seeking the flesh-and-blood woman inside the ethereal myth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Whereabouts of Eneas McNulty'' &LR;  by Sebastian Barry
(Viking, $23.95). A graceful novel about the wanderings of an Irish
outcast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Hand'' &LR;  by Frank R. Wilson (Pantheon, $30). A
neurologist's provocative argument that the human hand, as much as
the human mind, has been the key to our evolution and our
intelligence.
</P>
</TEXT>
