<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
!!! 1/2 ``The Chambermaid''  By far the more interesting of the two
Titanic-themed movies of the '90s, this French film turns a chance
encounter on the eve of the sailing into a delicious meditation on
the progression from embellished storytelling to art (Unrated)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! &UR; 1/2 ``Doing Time for Patsy Cline''  &LR; Structually rambling but
involvingly performed, this Aussie road romance throws an innocent
dreamer (Matt Day) into the even more desperate dreams of a shady
promoter (Richard Roxburgh) and a fragile singer (Miranda Otto) as
they try to break free of the outback to make it to Nashville.
(Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! &UR; ``54''  &LR; This film about the heady whirl of Manhattan's disco
mecca of the '70s is too superficial to satisfy despite a highly
watchable performance by Mike Myers as Studio 54 mastermind Steve
Rubell. He's made user-friendly by being presented as mostly
zonked-out. The real story of the rise of celebrity culture is
submerged in a conventional struggle between bad glitz and
working-class purity, as embodied by Ryan Phillippe and Neve
Campbell. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! &UR; 1/2 ``Nights of Cabiria''  &LR; A beautifully restored version of
Federico Fellini's 1957 Oscsar-winning classic starring his actress
wife, Giulietta Masina, in her richest performance. She combines
ladylike spunkiness and sad-eyed clowning as a resilient Roman
streetwalker whose brutal life never extinguishes the romantic
longing in her innocent heart. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FL)!!! &UR; ``Slums of Beverly Hills''  &LR; Warm, funny, endearingly
raunchy coming-of-age film based on growing up tacky in Beverly
Hills. Natasha Lyonne is adorable as the teen heroine of a
hard-pressed family and Alan Arkin is poignant and funny as her
divorced dad who can't seem to get the American dream right. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! &UR; 1/2 ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love''  &LR; More ambitious than the usual
Hollywood biopic, and filled with snazzy musical numbers, this
easy-to-take film nevertheless misses getting under the skin of
single-hit doo-wop sensation Frankie Lymon as it tells the story
from the vantage points of the three women claiming to be his
widow, all wanting the royalties piling up since his death. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! &UR; ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors''  &LR; Not as jolting or invigorating as
``In the Company of Men,'' Neil LaBute's second look at savage
sexual game-playing sends six contemporary urban types to bed, all
miserably, an inevitability considering how little they bring to
it. There's black humor therapeutic intent beneath it all, but the
superior ensemble performance makes you dig through a lot of sexual
tundra to find it beneath the anger posing as lust. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
