<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-FIRELIGHT-BOS &LR;      08-31 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FIRELIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOVE AFFAIR WITH LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course he cries at the movies. British screenwriter William
Nicholson has written his share of poignant words for the cinema,
words that have engendered streams of tears in his audiences. So
it's only fitting that he, too, likes to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always cry in a good movie,'' Nicholson unabashedly admits.
``I will cry in a good commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   He creates his most lucid, genuine characters when he examines
life through the eyes of a woman. Nicholson helped Jodie Foster win
an Oscar nomination for his rendering of ``Nell,'' the heartfelt
tale of a ``woman-child'' raised in the backwoods speaking a
language all her own. He added dimension to Debra Winger's
character in ``Shadowlands,'' a biographical film about writer C.S.
Lewis that earned the screenwriter an Academy Award nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Nicholson has breathed life into another female
creation, Elisabeth Laurier, the strong-willed governess whose
story is central to ``Firelight,'' debuting in the States on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife says it's because I am a woman,'' explains Nicholson,
his eyes crinkling up little crescent moons. ``I'm interested in
all that feely stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In a red sport coat, the 50-year-old writer muses over a bowl of
pasta in a restaurant at the Four Seasons, trying to analyze how he
began his love affair with the story of love itself. After a few
minutes of tossing around some theories, he settles for a Freudian
approach: Love stories are therapy to Nicholson, a product of an
all-male boarding school in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I grew up very shy about girls,'' he reveals. ``I
certainly hadn't had a girlfriend until I left school at the age of
18. Well, I certainly was a virgin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lots of fears and anxieties about, you know, would
anybody love me? Would I ever find a girlfriend? ... Love stories
reassure those anxieties, because in a love story, the person who
wants the lover usually gets the lover.''
</P>
<P>
   With that known, there's little wonder that a happy ending
awaits in the costume drama ``Firelight.'' In the Victorian-era
piece, Nicholson intertwined his two passions _ love for a woman
and love for a child. The poor and headstrong Swiss protagonist
pays off her father's debts by bearing a child of an English
aristocrat, whose comatose wife was paralyzed in an accident. Seven
years later, curiosity leads Elisabeth to become governess to her
own daughter, who has grown up spoiled and in need of a mother.
</P>
<P>
   With his new film, the first he has directed, Nicholson hopes
audience members will experience the same gripping emotion he feels
when watching a good romantic movie. ``I don't know why,'' he says,
``but the best experience I can have in the cinema is to fall in
love with the main characters and long for them to get together. I
like to feel that sensation of a very good love story, where you
just go `Ahhhhhh.'''
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest complaints Nicholson has heard are that the
drama is too long and too ``period.'' But essentially, he says,
that's what he intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a pace that would serve the particular kind of
intensity I was seeking,'' says Nicholson, whose movie opened the
Seattle International Film Festival in May. ``If you're going to do
the kind of movie I was doing, you have to tell your audience right
away in the beginning: `Calm down. Pay attention. You're in good
hands _ I know what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteenth-century England seemed a likely setting for harsh
social mores oppressing two impassioned lovers _ in this case, a
poor governess and a married squire. Obstacles to such a match are
rarely seen in contemporary movies today, Nicholson says. As Jack
Nicholson's coarse and obsessive-compulsive character demonstrated
in ``As Good As It Gets,'' if many couples on-screen can't work out
a relationship, it's because of individual neuroses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it can be done brilliantly, what you don't get from
that is that tremendous surge of passion,'' says Bill Nicholson,
``that tremendous blood, relief, and excitement you get in an
old-style love story.''
</P>
<P>
   In his directorial debut, Nicholson reveled in his freedom to
compose images that would complement the words he had written. The
sudden ownership in crafting the visuals of a movie was ``like a
whole new toy box,'' he says. For instance, he constrasted the
cold, white winter light against the warm hues provided by the
firelight, a backdrop to many of the love scenes and meaningful
mother-daughter talks.
</P>
<P>
   He chose Firle Place, a mansion just 10 minutes from where he
lives, to shoot the movie. The middle-aged father of three _ ages
4, 7, and 9 _ says he can now provide a strong fatherly presence he
couldn't guarantee 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An aspiring novelist, Nicholson landed what he considered a day
job making documentaries for the BBC after graduating from the
University of Cambridge in England. He would spend three hours
before work every morning penning his manuscripts _ all eight to be
turned down by publishers. Meanwhile, he made about 50 television
documentaries from the mid-1970s to mid-1980s. ``I didn't take it
at all seriously, and as a result, I did it rather well,'' he
recalls. ``I was relaxed about it because I always assumed I was
going to be a famous novelist.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 20s, when he began ``making a mess out of
relationships,'' he allowed his inquisitive nature to cross over
from work to dating. He recalls quizzing every girlfriend, asking
them, ```What does it feel to be like you?' and `What do you want
from men?' `Who did you fall in love with first?' and `Why did you
sleep with him?'''
</P>
<P>
   From his casual interrogations over the years, he says, he
acquired a knowledge of the emotional dynamics between men and
women.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote ``Shadowlands,'' his retelling of the romance between
Lewis and American poet Joy Gresham, as a TV drama in 1985, and he
soon adapted it to a play and then a movie starring Anthony Hopkins
and Winger. All incarnations of ``Shadowlands'' won numerous awards
and put Nicholson on the map in the movie business.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Firelight,'' his pen has barely slowed. A movie based on
Nelson Mandela's autobiography, ``Long Walk to Freedom,'' will open
October next year. Also, ``American Caesar'' for Universal Studios
is still in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is a terrific cook and loves good food,'' Nicholson
says of Virginia, whom he married just 10 years ago. ``She's taught
me to love good food.'' As he munches on his cavatappi _ a noodle
he has ``never heard of in his life; it sounds like some dance'' _
he explains that before they met, he never bothered grocery
shopping or cooking. He dined in restaurants or simply ate
``rubbish.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is regarded as a hot screenwriter of this decade,
Nicholson still chooses not to read critics' reviews of his work.
If the comments are less than flattering, his wife informs the
family, ``Daddy got a poor review,'' to which the children reply,
``Oh, poor Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably think I'm a terrific failure,'' he says. ``But I
want them to know that I go on working even when things go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Firelight,'' Elisabeth's bold quest to find her daughter
reveals a human instinct to nurture one's own. Nicholson concedes
that he couldn't have written this script if he had not fathered
children. Having a child ``is a million miles more powerful than
anything _ sex, fame, being a millionaire,'' he says. ``Anybody who
has a child knows it, but nobody ever writes about it because it's
so normal, so common. And yet it's the most explosively
extraordinary experience of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   In a time of parody and satire, or clever movies about
detectives, or movies in which ``people chase each other and shoot
each other,'' Nicholson remains a lover of the simple story. He
despises convoluted plots that ``intimidate'' the viewer into not
criticizing them.
</P>
<P>
   Too many books and movies, he says, refrain from telling simple
stories because they fear others will find them simple and naive.
Instead they orchestrate a game to prove they're clever, a game
Nicholson says he'd rather not play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to communicate a message. All these stories are
about human truth. I just want to get that response from the
audience: `Yes, I've felt that, too.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
