<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SUNDANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT REDFORD'S INDIE VISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can't go to Sundance? No problem. Sundance is coming to you.
Once reachable only by trekking to Utah, it's now as close as your
couch and your cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, MediaOne has been beaming the Sundance Channel for
the last month to some Boston-area cable markets. It's a quantum
leap for the Sundance Institute, the independent filmmakers' haven
founded in 1981 by Robert Redford and named for the outlaw he
played in ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.'' In the near
future, there'll be another leap, as Redford moves Sundance films
into newly built movie theaters in different cities, in league with
General Cinemas.
</P>
<P>
   But that's then, and this is now. Redford, who just turned 61
and doesn't look jet-lagged, although he says he is after promoting
``The Horse Whisperer'' in Europe, has sidled into town to spread
the word about Sundance on TV. ``It's not about commerciality,''
says the actor, director, producer, and environmental activist.
``It's about whether a film has a fresh vision or a fresh voice.
I've worked on both sides of the street. My heart has been in the
smaller film, inclined toward personal stories that have a deeper
root beyond what I call the popcorn experience.''
</P>
<P>
   So while other movie channels will celebrate the kinds of names
that get preserved in Hollywood cement, the Sundance Channel will
spotlight indie diva Parker Posey next month by screening ``Party
Girl,'' ``Drunks,'' ``Waiting for Guffman,'' ``Basquiat,'' ``The
Daytrippers,'' and ``subUrbia.'' Showcasing various facets of
Parker's smart, sentient, edgy persona in different roles, the
films will be supplemented by interview footage in which Parker
goes on record about them and herself.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, says Redford, relaxing for a moment in a Harvard
Square hotel, it was important to dispel any idea that the Sundance
Channel might have been conceived as a vanity outlet. The films
don't reflect his personal taste, Redford says. The vigor of a
given filmmaker's vision is the only criterion. ``You might like
something that I think is lousy,'' Redford says, the point being
that it's not Redford's likes and dislikes that govern the
programming, but the principles of diversity, choices, and
providing visibility for films otherwise shortchanged in the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Among other September films on the channel will be ``Choose
Me,'' ``Blue Velvet,'' ``Notes from Underground,'' ``Fargo,'' ``The
Eighth Day,'' ``Savage Nights,'' ``The Darien Gap,'' ``Arizona
Dream,'' ``Inside Monkey Zetterland,'' and ``Nobody Loves Me.'' Few
of these independent features enjoyed long theatrical runs. Other
films on the schedule _ especially shorts, documentaries, and films
by gay and ethnic minority filmmakers _ hardly got runs at all.
Later this year look for the French film ``Ridicule,'' ``The New
Age,'' ``Touch,'' ``In the Company of Men,'' ``The Long Way Home,''
``Things to Do in Denver When You're Dead,'' and ``Looking for
Richard.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Sundance Channel unique, Redford says, is its
policy of showing everything, even premieres, uncut and
commercial-free. Also, he says, he won't restrict programming to
films previously shown at the Sundance Festival _ although many
will be Sundance alumni, including premieres deemed worthy of
festival showings, but as yet without commercial distribution
deals. That many got made at all is due to Sundance backing. When
Redford established the festival back in 1980, there was almost no
place for independent films to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to put something back in the industry,'' Redford
says. ``I didn't know at the time that it was going to coincide
with a change taking place in the marketplace with videos and
cable. The changes came on so fast and so strong that very quickly
it became clear that the distribution sources were going to
outweigh the production sources. You can do the math on it pretty
easily. Say the industry's going this way and the distribution
channels are going that way, and suddenly there's this gap. So the
purpose of just creating an opportunity for new artists to have a
place to come and work and develop their skills suddenly became an
opportunity in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, while wary of the danger that Sundance's rapid growth may
blur its original purpose, Redford says that smaller, quirkier,
more personal films may get made but, in many cases, still have
nowhere to go. Hence the cable channel, which will include uncut
premieres of films that might subsequently proceed to theatrical
release _ possibly even in the Sundance theaters Redford envisions.
These, he says, will be anything but the multiplexes dotting
suburban malls. They'll be free-standing buildings, Redford says,
either newly built or converted from other uses, with
community-oriented adjuncts, like coffee shops, bookstores, and
lecture rooms for audiences to meet filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Down the line, Redford says, will be live coverage of each
January's Sundance Festivals, enabling home viewers to track
audience awards and each year's surprises and crop of new faces.
When the festival began in 1981, Redford says, he personally saw
all 32 films. Now he can't see the dozens of presentations, culled
from hundreds of entries. Ironically, environmental activist
Redford has had to reconfigure the festival, putting limits on
growth, designating certain theaters for certain kinds of films,
such as, say, documentaries, alleviating the traffic jams on the
snowy streets of Park City, filled to overflowing each year,
especially with industry types.
</P>
<P>
   Redford's communally oriented view of what might be called the
off-Broadway film world may seem paradoxical, in view of his
private nature. He doesn't like talking about himself, makes a face
when he speaks of what he calls the ``cosmetic'' aspects of
maintaining his standing as the kind of star presence that makes it
possible for him to bankroll films and projects close to his heart.
He plays the game, but remains uncomfortable about plugging his
films, even ones in which he's totally immersed, like his current
``The Horse Whisperer.''
</P>
<P>
   Redford's focus on ``The Horse Whisperer'' meant he had to limit
his role in another pet project, ``A Civil Action,'' to that of
producer. Based on Jonathan Harr's book about a lawsuit brought by
eight Woburn families against coroporations they charged with
polluting their drinking water, and starring John Travolta and
Robert Duvall, it's due out at Christmas. ``Fewer and fewer films
are about real-life situations and communities in our society, or
affect people on the human level. This one had such a strong
root,'' Redrord says, ``people vs. the corporation and the power of
money that conceals those abuses and the cost of it all. I just
thought that was very dramatic stuff. Still do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
