<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMEDY-ALBUMS-BOS &LR;      08-31 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMEDY-ALBUMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDIANS GET SERIOUS ABOUT ALBUMS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Seinfeld, in a press conference prior to his live comedy
special earlier this month, proclaimed that his first comedy album
would be available in late September.
</P>
<P>
   First comedy album? It seems odd that the star of one of the
most successful situation comedies in television history and a guy
who's been at the top of the stand-up game for more than 20 years
is just releasing his first comedy recording.
</P>
<P>
   Seinfeld said that it was because comedy albums didn't sell in
the '80s and early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just started to sell again,'' he said, ``so we'll be
putting out a CD version of the special.''
</P>
<P>
   During the '60s and early '70s, many of today's comedians grew
up with comedy albums by Bill Cosby, Bob Newhart, Richard Pryor,
the Smothers Brothers, and other popular comic acts. Seinfeld
proudly points to the fact that he literally wore out Cosby's
records. In those days, comedy records such as Cosby's sold in the
millions. But sales dipped to practically nothing in the '80s. The
major cause for the decline was competition from cable television
and an oversaturation of the comedy market.
</P>
<P>
   But things are looking up. It's likely that Seinfeld's album,
``I'm Telling You For the Last Time,'' will sell a million copies
during its first week in release and, while there are no hard and
fast statistics on comedy album sales in general, their popularity
is steadily climbing.
</P>
<P>
   During the past week, I listened to a representative sampling of
some of the more interesting new albums and significant
re-releases. I give you both the witty and the witless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE AMERICAN COMEDY BOX _ 1915-1994'' (Rhino)
</P>
<P>
   At $50, the five-volume boxed set is pricey, but it's a
marvelous sampler of American humor. Bob and Ray, Richard Pryor,
Abbott and Costello, W.C. Fields, Joan Rivers, Stan Freberg, Spike
Jones, Lenny Bruce, Mort Sahl, Dick Gregory, Henny Youngman,
Phyllis Diller, Bob Hope, and Steven Wright are just a few of the
nearly 60 comics represented. While meant to entertain, this set
also allows the more intellectually inclined to see how trends in
humor have evolved. From the sexual suggestiveness of Fields to the
explicitness of Bruce, the humor reflects America's growing
acceptance of, well, dirtier jokes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``BABES IN JOYLAND: KATE CLINTON'' (Whyscrack)
</P>
<P>
   Kate Clinton is one of the best comics around with her easy
conversational style and sharp observational humor. While her quips
are often sympathetically aimed directly at the gay community, her
artistry transcends gender and sexual identity. Describing herself
as a ``recovering Catholic,'' Clinton targets political and social
hypocrisy. ``To me, the avant garde just means not knowing when to
clap,'' is a typical dead-on line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``BOBBY SLAYTON: RAGING BULLY'' (Parental Advisory) (Miramar).
</P>
<P>
   No one could be further from the political sensitivities of Kate
Clinton than Slayton. Yet, he is the funniest of the gargling
barbed-wire comics. He takes no prisoners in his assault on
virtually every ethnic group, political philosophy, and sexual
orientation. Make no mistake about it. He is raging and he is a
bully. His ranting and raving about minorities makes you wish that
HBO would put him and Chris Rock up against each other in a
no-holds-barred comedy laugh-off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``CHRIS ROCK: ROLL WITH THE NEW'' (Parental Advisory)
(Dreamworks)
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rock is a Richard Pryor/Lenny Bruce descendent who uses
his humor to attack hypocrisy wherever he finds it. He even does a
long, hilarious oration on why black people are more racist than
white people. His riff on O.J. Simpson is remarkable for both its
humor and insight, as Rock makes the case for Simpson getting off,
not because he is black, but because he is famous. Rock takes on
all comers. ``Women are like the police,'' he says, ``they can have
all the evidence but they want the confession.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``RODNEY CARRINGTON: HANGIN' WITH RODNEY'' (Parental Advisory)
(Mercury)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have to be from Texas _ and drunk _ to think this guy
is funny. While there are a few funny bits _ one involving shopping
for a casket and the other about sexual confusion _ Carrington
seems to think if he laughs loud enough at his own jokes, you will
too. The other irritating thing about this album is that it uses
repetitive material to fill out the CD. Listening to his silly
gender-confusing song, ``Dancing With a Man,'' once was bad enough.
But twice?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``PAUL RODRIGUEZ: CHEESE `N' MACARONI UNCOOKED'' (Payaso)
</P>
<P>
   It's great to see a Mexican comic who reverses the conventional
stereotype by poking fun at his Anglo sidekick, but Rodriguez has
to get beyond using old cultural stereotypes (such as Latinos don't
ski) if he's to move up. While some of his observations are funny,
particularly his commentary on the differences between Mexican and
American funerals and a commentary on white ebonics, much of the
material drags on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``JACKIE MARTLING: THE JOKE MAN'' (Off Hour Rockers)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For someone who can't remember a joke for more than five
minutes, I really admire the fact that Jackie Martling, whose
career took off through his exposure on ``The Howard Stern Show,''
recalls thousands of them. The problem is that most of them aren't
funny. Dirty? Yes. Disgusting? Yes. Revolting? Yes. Funny? Not
really. This Henny Youngman for the foul-mouthed generation,
rattles off bad jokes like the snake that he is. There's one good
one for 20 losers, and, even in baseball, that's a terrible
average. Comedy fans can excuse lapses in taste and judgment but
being unfunny is unforgivable. Sometimes not being able to remember
jokes, especially if they're Martling's, is an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``CLINTON: AN ORAL HISTORY _ DAVID FRYE'' (GAG MEdia)
</P>
<P>
   Every time there's a president in trouble, David Frye shows up.
The man, whose Nixon impressions drove the late President crazy, is
back with a timely indictment of Clinton's sexual escapades. Except
for George C. Scott as Generak Patton, Frye provides the major male
voices including Ted Kennedy, Henry Kissinger, John McLaughlin,
Peter Jennings, and Jack Nicholson while the equally talented Lynne
Marie Stewart performs as Monica Lewinsky, Linda Tripp, and Hillary
Clinton as Dr. Ruth. Timing is crucial in comedy and Frye's has
never been better. Surprisingly enough, the material is cleaner
than what we hear on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``ALBERT BROOKS: COMEDY MINUS ONE'' (Rhino)
</P>
<P>
   Originally released 25 years ago, the reissue of this remarkable
album is cause for celebration. Personally, it's my favorite.
Whether Brooks is rewriting the National Anthem or asking what the
listener thinks of the record, this is not just a compilation of
funny bits but an artistic interweaving of material that is
brilliantly hilarious. Brooks, who was born Albert Einstein, is a
comic genius who's gone on to become a writer, actor, and director
but this early stand-up work is as fresh and amusing as when it
first came out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``RICHARD BELZER: ANOTHER LONE NUT'' (Uproar Entertainment)
</P>
<P>
   Better known as a star of NBC's ``Homicide,'' Richard Belzer is
a remarkable commentator. Think of him as Mort Sahl's best material
as delivered by Norman Bates. And his best stuff is true. His
recollection of the time Hulk Hogan and Mr. T appeared on his
short-lived talk show is a dangerously funny bit where Belzer ended
up in the hospital, sued Hogan, and, despite a gag order, ended up
with a house in France for his trouble. Pathologically paranoid, he
adds new life to conspiracy theories. His description of the lone
bullet theory in the President Kennedy assassination case is worth
the price of the album.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
