<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-DEATH-BOS &LR;      08-31 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING A GATE TO LOVE AND RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DEATH IN SUMMER 
By William Trevor. Viking. 214 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 1995 novel, ``Felicia's Journey,'' touted as his
breakaway literary thriller into the mainstream, the Irish virtuoso
William Trevor rendered a serial killer with as much care and
intimacy as one might arrange flowers from the garden. And yes, the
novel was terrifying, but hardly for the usual reasons. Devotees of
Trevor's fiction had long known that the man was capable of making
a silent nightmare out of a walk in the park _ and not only because
of what might lurk near the footpath there. The world he inhabits
throws shadows in all directions; if things generally work out for
his characters (which isn't often the case), that happy coincidence
rarely has anything to do with providence or a deserving life. You
might call this authorial viewpoint one of hopelessness, if not for
the shrewd beauty at its center. Beloved for years as a master
builder of the modern English story, Trevor has a way of forcing
collisions between character and circumstance. Rather than merely
fortunate endings, we are afforded truth.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with ``Death in Summer,'' a spare novel chillingly
reminiscent of ``Felicia's Journey'' but also of Henry James's
foray into Gothic. Like James, Trevor attends to but then
transcends the ordinary conventions of suspense; like James, he is
more concerned with the dark anticipation of moral consequence:
Just how far will bad people go? Such a query in the realm of
literary Gothicis complicated by achingly flawed protagonists: the
bruised but well-intentioned, whether James's hapless innocents or
Trevor's Felicia or, here the recently widowed Thaddeus Davenant _
a man who can make wisteria bloom under the direst of conditions
but whose own heart lacks the sine qua non of love.
</P>
<P>
   Or did, until his daughter, Georgina, was born four months ago.
``Death in Summer'' opens with the premature death of Thaddeus's
wife, a new mother and woman of ``almost wayward generosity'' who
was bicycling home in Essex one afternoon _ her basket full of
young pullets _ when she was struck by a car. Now Thaddeus must
provide for the infant girl he adores: must blow open the sealed
castle of the family estate where he has taken refuge all these
years, letting in the aid, and possibly danger, offered by the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
   The main threat posed to Thaddeus's quiet existence appears in
the guise of a potential nanny for Georgina, a troubled girl named
Pettie whose story unfolds in alternating sequences with the more
tranquil life on the Davenant estate. But the greater, or more
thematic, hint of peril belongs to chance itself: So long as
Thaddeus is left alone, trimming his yew and selling his
vegetables, his heart is impenetrable to loss. With that
well-tended invincibility shattered, he finds awaiting him all the
compromises and misunderstandings of a life lived in the company of
others. His mother-in-law, a woman initially hesitant to warm to
Thaddeus, moves in to care for Georgina after a number of
unsuitable young woman are passed over for the job. An odd,
pathos-ridden woman named Mrs. Ferry, who briefly belonged to the
recklessness of Thaddeus's youth, has reappeared to pester him _
probably for money, rather than the pricier commodity of love. Both
these abstruse dramas are dutifully attended by the exquisitely
portrayed servants of the household, Maidment and his wife,
Zenobia; with his silent scrutiny and her feather-duster wisdom,
they are quite capable of tending to a small army of domestic
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   But it is within the characters of the emotionally damaged
Pettie and her mentally halting friend, Albert, that Trevor's
magnanimity is most revealed. Late adolescents who together
survived, then escaped, an orphanage called the Morning Star,
Albert and Pettie are functional members of the dispossessed. He
has found an anchor with the aging Mrs. Biddle, whom he cares for
and who rents him a room, while Pettie drifts from one
fantasy-ridden misfortune to the next, replaying the ugly
choreographies of her childhood. Like the delusional Hilditch of
``Felicia's Journey,'' Pettie is depicted from the inside out: We
don't so much fear her as we do her impulsivity _ her doing the
wrong thing out of need, rather than cruelty. In Trevor's world,
desperation can easily do as much harm as outright malevolence.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that ``Death in Summer'' is the story of a few warm
weeks in England when the vines were flourishing and hearts were
full of longing _ the story of the badly crossed paths of a few
unfortunates, and what they might do to each other almost
inadvertently. Faced with the impact of his own agency in the
world, Thaddeus is forced to confront his past; if he refused his
wife the love she needed while alive, he can at least treat her
memory with honor. The changes and possibilities in the realm of
melancholia where Trevor reigns are both small and infinite: A
missed step, a fleeting act of mercy, might well transform an
entire life.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to say more about the novel without exposing its
subtle beauties, which unfold one moment at a time and with
delicate, sometimes ominous, character revelations. ``Death in
Summer'' feels scant but pleasurable: It is neither so taut nor so
heartbreaking as ``Felicia's Journey,'' but it has the hue of
vintage Trevor _ the perfectly crafted sentences, the insights into
the human condition that are rare and breathtakingly charitable.
For all his keen understanding of the world's meanness, he also
captures the torturous? terrain of those paths of darkness _ the
stones and rainstorms that make one follow certain turns in the
road. If death opens this rueful novel and death hovers over its
fecund summer with barely a hope in sight, there is nonetheless a
gentle light by story's close that outshines every sadness within.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
