<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIVE AND WELL IN JAMAICA PLAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A HOME IN THE HEART OF A CITY 
By Kathleen Hirsch. North Point Press. 
244 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The heart of Jamaica Plain, a diverse bustle of a place in the
center of the city, can be found in the lank grass and bent willow
of Jamaica Pond, or the caramel-colored booths at Doyle's pub, or
the interplay of language and culture in Hyde Square. Annexed to
Boston in 1865, scarred by a ghost highway and sapped by
middle-class flight, it nevertheless held on stubbornly. Journalist
Kathleen Hirsch documents this holding fast and this history,
musing on the politics of place and doing up ``the grand old
buttons of a community's life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of her reporting, she finds something notable: a
small-town sensibility that flexes enough to contain the future.
The neighborhood's demographics _ 50 percent white, 33 percent
Latino, 17 percent black _ and its mix of niche businesses and
light industry _ already look like what much of urban America is
becoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``A city has two distinct kinds of history that set it apart
from other sorts of places,'' Hirsch writes. ``The first is the
random and the incidental. ... But there is the far more
significant history of the intentional, those principled moments
`of intensity when common action is exaggerated into visibility,'
as one historian put it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch moved to JP in 1990, a refugee from a younger, faster
track in Back Bay. In her mid-30s, she knew how belonging felt, she
writes, but not how it worked. She could envision the whole but had
yet to encounter the parts. A former writer at the Boston Phoenix
and author of ``Songs from the Alley,'' Hirsch blends the detail of
solid reporting with lyrical power. Her book belongs in the library
of anyone who yearns to understand what sustains a place and what
scorches it.
</P>
<P>
   She begins at Jamaica Pond, invoking Thoreau's walk through
equally wild frontiers, and finds natural beauty and repair. Cars
swerve down the Jamaicaway, but there is also this:
</P>
<P>
   ``On a morning in fall, the air is nippy when I arrive. But this
doesn't deter the regulars. A great shawl of green, willow and oak,
wraps the water in its calm just yards from a bustling parkway.
Thin layers of fog pull apart above the still water. The breath of
joggers clouds the air. Beneath the surface, salmon and bass drift
in granite caves. Wild swans cast their long-billed shadows. Loons
and cormorants and geese skim and bob in search of prey.''
</P>
<P>
   At the stolid, Tudor boathouse, she finds Christine Cooper,
neighborhood bulwark. Gripping a rake and a clutch of garbage bags,
laboring after work and on weekends, Cooper reclaimed the pond from
decay, briar, and bramble. By the summer of 1983, Cooper and
another activist, Gerry Wright, felt they had made enough progress
to hold a ceremony and plant a peace garden. By spring of 1984,
Cooper had a proposal for extensive park restoration and a petition
with 700 signatures in support. City Hall agreed, and the Jamaica
Pond Project began.
</P>
<P>
   After absorbing the lessons of the pond, and the community
taking shape by its shores, Hirsch begins to take regular, rambling
voyages out. She perfects the art of lingering. ``I found my way
onto detours and dead-end roads, following signs for lemonade and
yard sales. Whole chunks of reality fell down before me that I
hadn't noticed before.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood comes into a clearer focus as more characters
swim into view: Veronica Serrato, an assistant district attorney
who quit to work with Greater Boston Legal Services Center; pizza
purveyor Kathie Mainzer, who has an impulse to public service and a
knack for capitalism. (One activist interviewed in the book has
left the JP scene abruptly, and Hirsch may want to add a
postscript. Since the book was written, Boston Police investigators
reportedly have been probing the records of a summer cleanup
program at the Egleston Square YMCA to determine if city money was
diverted. Eddie Ortega, a former gang member who rose to become Y
director, resigned in March and his whereabouts are unknown.)
</P>
<P>
   Aptly enough, Doyle's pub on Washington Street receives its own
chapter, titled, ``Playing.'' But a sense of play and a splash or
two of Guinness are only part of the story. Jerry, Eddie, and Bill
Burke bought the pub in 1971, when JP's industrial base was
eroding, storefronts were vacant, and the Southwest Corridor
construction project was sowing disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle's provided continuity and something more: what sociologist
Ray Oldenburg calls the third place. A third place is convivial and
neutral, where visitors check status at the door and enjoy each
other's company. Successful cities, Oldenburg and others note,
thrive on such levelers. Play is also an important element, and
Hirsch makes a link between play and politics _ as in local. ``For
out of a community's play comes not just a certain tone but a
political confidence,'' she writes. ``Play fosters a politic that
is concrete and literal, and that doesn't exist in places where the
connections between people are more abstract and one-dimensional.''
The policy wonks, bus drivers, yuppies, local scribes, riot grrrls
and longhairs who commune at Doyle's share in the commonweal,
arguing, voting, running for neighborhood council, or pulling on
the mayor's coat.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hirsch's son is young, she knows the thorniest choices
of all await her _ public school or private? Moss Hill or Chestnut
Hill? Community cannot take root if young families flee. Hirsch
visits the Agassiz Elementary School and sees a screaming teacher,
a raging boy, and an assault with a rock. She wonders if she is
ready for the full-time job of sorting out the bureaucracy of the
Boston Public School system. The Agassiz seems the flip side of the
richly diverse community she and her son have found on the street:
Raw issues of race and class erupt, but an overburdened system
seems too deadened to respond. Hirsch is not ready to give up. She
advocates neighborhood-based schools until sixth grade, and hopes
to get children working on community projects, music, and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see if Hirsch decides to stay, and
which path she chooses for her son, assuming she has the means to
choose. Perhaps the schools will invite community and civility in,
as Hirsch hopes. Perhaps JP's ragtag band of activists will give
them a nudge. Because, as Hirsch has shown, one neighborhood has
much to teach in the age of microculture and individuality _
lessons about how to be public with one another, and how to find
joy in the particular.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ellen Clegg, a member of the Sunday Globe staff, is assistant
managing editor in charge of local weekly sections.)
</P>
</TEXT>
