<SLUG> BC-BOOK-OUTSIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LANDSCAPE AS SEEN FROM `OUTSIDE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
OUTSIDE LIES MAGIC 
Regaining History and Awareness in Everyday Places. 
By John R. Stilgoe  
Walker, 200 pp., $20  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of this book as a sort of mirror-image Zen guide. Where
the guide would instruct you to live in the present, the book
trains you to see the present as layers of past. Where the guide
would call on you to turn inward, the book's advice (and opening
line) is ``Get out now. ... Go outside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside Lies Magic'' is the operating manual for John R.
Stilgoe's life enterprise of accounting for the whole of the
human-contrived, American landscape and, in the process, revealing
our inescapable links to each other and the past.
</P>
<P>
   Stilgoe, a professor of landscape history at Harvard University,
has already wrestled with these subjects in a series of scholarly
masterpieces that include ``Common Landscape of America, 1540 to
1845,'' ``Metropolitan Corridor: Railroads and the American
Scene,'' and ``Borderland: Origins of the American Suburb.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, he takes a very different tack, offering a personal
meditation on what it is to be an ``explorer'' of everyday
landscapes in an era when most of the nation's terrain _ and many
of its citizens' lives _ seem parceled out and preprogrammed.
</P>
<P>
   The book has its flaws. Stilgoe's voice can be unnervingly
direct at times, like that of a drill sergeant in the face of a new
recruit. In addition, his concept of ``landscape'' can be confusing
to first-time readers. On the one hand, he doesn't mean nature as a
whole, but only those parts that humans have modified and molded.
On the other, he doesn't mean places like New York or Disney World
where the modification has gone beyond molding to complete
domination.
</P>
<P>
   Such problems aside, Stilgoe puts on a spectacular performance.
His ability to begin with his walking/bicycling explorer's
observation of something in the landscape, loop into an extended
disquisition on the thing, and finally circle back to the
explorer's journey, can be breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Here, for example, is Stilgoe taking off from the observation
that kitchen cabinet interiors of a certain period are often apple
green: ``In the first two decades of the twentieth century, experts
advised men to have their kitchens painted apple-green. The experts
believed that apple-green quieted nervous people, and especially
wives beginning to think of suffrage, of careers beyond the home.
...''
</P>
<P>
   Or here he is wrapping up a discussion of the ``military'' in
``military and interstate highway system:'' ``Few motorists
nowadays realize the relationship between aircraft design and
highway design, but bicyclists exploring back roads know the rare
thrill of seeing Wyoming highway troopers temporarily stopping
highway traffic while an immense B-52 practices emergency landings
a half mile away on the interstate.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Stilgoe's audience has been largely confined to
designers and historians. But with passages like these, ``Outside
Lies Magic'' could extend the author's influence to a wider public
and in the process help cast him as a modern Thoreau, an
observer/moralist/celebrant of the American landscape.
</P>
<P>
   That said, let me offer a single lingering doubt _ one raised by
the book's discussion of the recent craze for gated, themed
communities like Disney's Celebration, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Stilgoe's greatest accomplishment has been to help make
landscape a legitimate focus of cultural study; to show that it is
an object whose examination can reveal important truths about
society. He has done that by portraying it as the product of
natural and human forces beyond any one generation's ability to
control and therefore as a layered synthesis of the nation's entire
history.
</P>
<P>
   But what if _ as at Celebration _ most of the forces have been
controlled all at once? What if all the houses have been built and
the trees planted and even all the public monuments erected to
mimic the small town of ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' or ``Mayberry
RFD''? Does that make landscape any less important _ less credible
_ a bearer of history? Stilgoe seems to answer no, largely because
he doesn't think there is as much control in controlled communities
as meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But the author's principal argument for getting up now
and going outside is that it is the antidote for ``the trap of the
programmed electronic age so gently closing around so many people
at the end of the century.'' Why believe that the trap can only
snap shut on computer screens and television tubes? What keeps it
from closing in just as thoroughly on the land?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
