<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAIL-CYANIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. JUDGE DISCOVERS HIS NAME ON CYANIDE MAILING LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MELISSA GRACE and CAROL DEMARE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A New York state judge, who in 1994 committed a
woman to an Albany psychiatric hospital, says his name appeared on
the former patient's list of persons to whom she allegedly planned
to mail packets of sodium cyanide.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Harold J. Hughes says he was
contacted by California authorities last Monday with a warning not
to ingest anything he received by mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did call up my wife and warned her,'' Hughes says of the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Schoonover, 50, was arrested on Aug. 23 outside a post
office in Marina Del Rey, Calif., after she was spotted wearing
rubber gloves and filling cellophane packets from a can marked
poison. Authorities said she was preparing to send more than 100
packages containing the deadly cyanide.
</P>
<P>
   Schoonover, who spent two months in the Capital District
Psychiatric Center in Albany in the summer of 1994, faces up to 20
years in prison on each of two federal counts of using the mail to
send poison in an attempt to injure and kill. The charges are in
connection with two employees of the psychiatric facility who were
involved in Schoonover's treatment and who received suspicious
packets in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   More charges are likely, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   The judge remembers a June 1994 mental hygiene hearing at which
he committed Schoonover to the psychiatric center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any trouble deciding that if I let this lady go,
she'd get hurt,'' Hughes said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   John Sherman, the judge's law clerk, said his name also appeared
on Schoonover's list and that he received a similar call Monday
from California. Neither the judge nor Sherman received a packet
from Schoonover either at home or at the office, they said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the hearing, Sherman was an assistant state
attorney general and represented the psychiatric center, a state
facility.
</P>
<P>
   The judge and law clerk vividly remembered the proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave me a wild story, that she was a professor, and she
was going to a meeting at Harvard,'' Hughes said. ``But she had no
identification.'' Hughes recalled that Schoonover sat to his right
during the hearing in a room on the fourth-floor of the County
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   When Hughes ruled against releasing her, Schoonover stood up and
pretended to faint, while at the same time squirting a packet of
ketchup over her front. For an instant, people in the room thought
it was blood, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Schoonover had contested her involuntary confinement and
attorneys were assigned to advocate on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In correspondence with the Albany Times Union newspaper over a
three-year period beginning in 1994, Schoonover said the drugs and
other medications given her at the psychiatric center killed her
unborn child.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities told the newspaper at the time that she was not
pregnant and not mistreated at the center.
</P>
<P>
   According to medical records she sent the newspaper, Schoonover
was diagnosed as suffering from severe mental illness. In an
hour-by-hour and day-by-day diary of her stay at the facility,
Schoonover mentioned Hughes and Sherman and asserted they said
``there was insufficient evidence to indicate that I had been
invited to (Vice President) Al Gore's party,'' after graduation
exercises. Schoonover said she had maintained she was not invited
to Gore's party.
</P>
<P>
   When discharged on Aug. 12, Schoonover was given a one-way bus
ticket to Boston, according to documents she sent the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   After arresting her, sheriff's investigators in California
seized two ``hit lists'' from Schoonover's van, in which she was
living. Included on the lists were names of health care and law
enforcement professionals she believed wronged her.
</P>
<P>
   Federal court papers filed Wednesday alleged that Schoonover, a
cancer patient, sent packets of sodium cyanide disguised as
nutritional supplements in April or May to Kathleen Elbrecht of
Niskayuna, a nurse manager at the psychiatric center, and in June
to John Georgiopolos of Selkirk, a social worker at the facility.
</P>
</TEXT>
