<HEADER>
A0968 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMMAKING-VANCOUVER-     08-31 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMMAKING-VANCOUVER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD, B.C.: EXCHANGE RATE HAS U.S. FILMMAKERS FLOCKING TO
VANCOUVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Mulder and Scully have blown town, taking
their dough and their cult cachet with them. The dollar's on a
serious slide, and poised to plunge even lower.
</P>
<P>
   So why are film executives in ``Hollywood North'' smiling?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the enviable position of turning away business right
now,'' says Peter Leitch, vice president and general manager of
North Vancouver's Lions Gate Studios, a 14-acre lot that looks
decidedly more L.A. than B.C. ``Right now every single stage is
rented.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the five stages at Lions Gate that were occupied
by the extra-eerie, extra-terrestrial ``X-Files'' for five years.
Series stars David Duchovny (Fox Mulder) and Gillian Anderson (Dana
Scully) packed up at the end of spring and headed to Tinseltown
with their high-profile show, amid tearful farewells and much media
hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   The mourning period was a short one. You could almost hear the
door slam on Duchovny's back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think `X-Files' leaving had a very big impact,'' says
Sheila Mombouquette, director of the British Columbia branch of the
Canadian Film and Television Production Association. ``It just
freed up some badly needed studio space.''
</P>
<P>
   Space is, indeed, at a premium in film-happy Vancouver. The
cause, ironically, is bad news. And it has nothing to do with
``X-Files'' and everything to do with the X-change rate.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, a Canadian dollar was worth 75 cents American. Last
week, the rate was below 64 cents. That figure is a siren call for
bargain-hunting producers in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means every time they run a budget in Los Angeles, we come
out the low-cost alternative,'' says Peter Mitchell, director of
the British Columbia Film Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetening the deal is Vancouver's increasingly sophisticated
talent pool _ 97 percent of the cast and crew on any set is
Canadian _ and a user-friendly government that cheerily opens
doors, bends rules and even intervenes in labor disputes for
Hollywood films.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell calls this a ``policy awakening,'' and cites as a
recent example a shoot for ``Pittsburgh,'' a film that began
filming Aug. 3 with Jim Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittsburgh'' producers sold a placement ad for a beer company,
and wanted to plaster a billboard with the name of the beer for a
shoot. But laws in Canada prohibit advertising alcohol on
billboards. ``Ten years ago, it would have been a huge problem,''
says Mitchell. ``But I called the attorney general's office and,
within two hours, we had the go-ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The government similarly came to the rescue when Hollywood
filmmakers threatened to beat it east to Ontario, a province
competing with B.C. for ``Film capital of Canada'' status. To
entice filmmakers, Ontario passed generous tax incentives for film
projects. ``We were losing work to Toronto,'' says Mitchell. ``We
were forced to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   By June, the B.C. government had put together its own incentive
package, one that returns 11 percent of all labor costs on a film
project to foreign production companies. Fickle Hollywood producers
quickly unpacked their bags and settled back in to Vancouver digs.
``All our studios breathed a sigh of relief,'' says Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates 25,000 British Columbians are employed full or part
time in the film industry. And while some local cast and crew have
complained publicly about Hollywood attitudes _ criticizing what
they call a ``Mexicans with sweaters'' view of the low-wage work
force _ most in the city embrace the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a restaurateur, it has probably increased our business an
amazing 25 percent,'' says Umberto Menghi, a superstar on the
culinary scene with five Vancouver restaurants, including Il
Giardino, the elegant place to see and be seen. ``It's given us a
certain pride, a certain prestige. Vancouver people feel special
because Hollywood loves us.''
</P>
<P>
   Scorned lovers south of the border, meanwhile, are nursing their
wounds. ``The exchange rates are going to kill us,'' says Suzie
Kellet, who heads the Washington State Film Commission,
headquartered in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Once adored for its moody landscapes, Seattle has been
particularly hard hit by the Canadian dollar's long slide downhill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filmmakers have been flying over us on the way to Vancouver
for so long, they've lost a sense of us,'' says Kellet.
</P>
<P>
   Figure comparisons tell the story. Total film production
expenditures in Washington declined from $55 million in 1994 to
nearly $29 million in 1997. During the same period, expenditures in
British Columbia increased from $432 million Canadian ($275 million
U.S. at current exchange rates) to $630 million ($400 million).
Figures for 1998 could be $760 million Canadian ($483 million).
</P>
<P>
   It's a market flush with Hollywood money. Which raises a problem
for British Columbia's resident filmmakers. Many find it
increasingly difficult to shop for cast, crews and production
facilities with their weakened dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It drives up prices,'' says Vancouver producer Julia Keatley,
during a break from shooting ``Cold Squad,'' a celebrated Canadian
TV series. ``I still want top-notch crew, so I have to pay more.''
</P>
<P>
   Tabs can be staggering. ``Vancouver is the most expensive place
for an indigenous producer to shoot,'' says Keatley.
</P>
<P>
   Indigenous filmmakers account for about 10 percent of B.C.
production. The rest of the industry is dominated by Hollywood. At
Lions Gate Studios, a major player in Canada's film industry, the
figures are even more skewed. ``Ninety-five percent of our sound
stages are taken by American productions,'' says Leitch, sitting at
a conference table with fresh-off-the-press blueprints spread out
before him.
</P>
<P>
   The blueprints are plans for a new sound stage at Lions Gate. It
will be the seventh at the state-of-the-art studio, owned by former
securities honcho Frank Giustra and designed to resemble a
Hollywood lot. The studio contains production and distribution
facilities under one roof, so filmmakers can see a project from
start to finish on-site.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the studio's gated grand entrance is a bustling back-lot
scene. Actors and crew mill around mobile dressing rooms and
catering trucks parked by the sound stages.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the yawning buildings, a crew works around a crashed
spaceship on the set of ``Max Q,'' a Disney TV movie. Inside
another is a ``morgue'' with half-full beakers and a steel autopsy
table, a set for the TV series ``Millennium.'' There are signs
leading to ``Pittsburgh'' production offices, and a small crew is
arriving to finish pick-up shots for ``Snow Falling on Cedars.''
Trucks are just beginning to bring in props for ``Dudley
Do-Right,'' a feature action film that begins filming tomorrow,
with Brendan ``George of the Jungle'' Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   Stages are so packed, producers are subletting space to one
another, and construction crews are maxxed out. In the mill shop,
electric saws screech, hammers pound and drills hum as workers
build new sets, too busy to look up. ``We're building another
construction mill, and we already need two more,'' says Leitch.
</P>
<P>
   The cacophony paints a rosy picture of ``North Hollywood's''
future. Leitch cites reports that project British Columbia's film
industry will double in the next 10 years. Other insiders say
production expenses could reach the $1 billion (Canadian) mark by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That could all change if Canada's economic bad news turns good.
</P>
<P>
   The specter of the Canadian dollar recovering may be a happy one
for shoppers who like to dip across the border to the United
States, but it's a nerve-racking one for industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, there was a real sense that if the exchange
rate changed, the industry would go away,'' says Mitchell. ``We're
certainly at risk _ but even if the rate went up 10 percent, it
would still be 72 cents to a dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Insiders see the 80-cent dollar as a kind of benchmark. ``Up to
80 cents, we're going to have business,'' says Leitch. ``At 90
cents, it's pretty close to zero savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Hollywood call off the romance at that point? Could the
love dry up over dollars?
</P>
<P>
   No one's sure. But Leitch, for one, is banking on a lasting
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to understand that this industry is very
portable and can go elsewhere,'' says the studio executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we don't get too greedy, we can keep it here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
