<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' or ``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEBAKEY-SURGERY (New York) _ Dr. Michael E. DeBakey moved
like a dancer in a pas de deux, anticipating his surgical partner's
every move during a quadruple bypass operation on a woman at The
Methodist Hospital here the other day. As DeBakey deftly
manipulated scalpels, scissors and forceps for more than three
hours, his hands never quivered. What made it an extraordinary
operation is that DeBakey, the pioneering heart surgeon, turns 90
on Sept. 7. By Lawrence K. Altman. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEEPSEA-DIVING (Undated) _ Alvin, the world's first craft to
roam the ocean's abyss with relative ease, is getting a major
overhaul that may extend its reach and allow it to match and
possibly even surpass newer submersibles abroad, making it the
world leader. In a remarkable bonanza from the end of the Cold War,
the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, which runs Alvin, has
just received from the Navy a submersible known as Sea Cliff, which
has been decommissioned in the wake of military cutbacks and
changing priorities. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENS-FACES (Undated) _ A timeless movie scene many people
may they could forget: Leonardo DiCaprio climbing to the bowsprit
of the ``Titanic'' and crowing, ``I'm king of the world!'' The
latest word from scientists: He may have a point. Or, rather, a
fetching bit of roundness. In a new study of facial attractiveness,
researchers from Scotland and Japan have found that, much to their
astonishment, people of both sexes prefer feminine-looking men over
rugged, manly-miened men. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MATH-IMAGE (New York) _ The movie ``Good Will Hunting''
offers some of the worst stereotypes of mathematics and
mathematicians. The elegance of the subject, or its relevance to
science are not even suggested, while all the cliches are
exploited. But three other popular works of art are mathematically
inspired, showing that math is not just a collection of complicated
problems studied and understood by a few, but that it is a subject
which on a very profound and intuitive level speaks to all of us.
By Dan Rockmore.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANIMAL-ORIGINS (Undated) _ The first animals may have been
shocked into existence by the evolutionary one-two punch of a
climatic episode so cold that the oceans froze _ snowball earth _
followed by one of the hottest periods in earth history, according
to a new hypothesis based largely on studies of carbon atoms in
ancient sediments. ``We think we have, finally, an explanation for
the first appearance of animal life on earth,'' said the Harvard
geologist who led the study. By William K. Stevens. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEARING-LOSS (Undated) _ Researchers say they are making
progress against noise-induced hearing loss and have begun testing
treatments that may be able to rescue hearing in ears damaged by
unusually loud noise. Military researchers say they have developed
a technique that may be able to restore health to delicate cells
within the ear that are often irreparably damaged or killed by
excessive noise. It may also be possible, they add, to develop
drugs that can be taken in advance to protect against damaging
sounds. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The next high hurdle for the
personal computer industry is keeping many a chip maker and
computer manufacturer awake at night, because after 15 years of
building ever faster and more powerful machines, the wizards of
silicon increasingly find themselves at the mercy of local phone
companies. The hurdle is getting the phone companies to carry data
faster. By Rob Fixmer. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: And now, easy-on,
easy-off pollination. Dr. Anton Pauw, a botanist at the University
of Cape Town in South Africa, has uncovered a remarkable mechanism
this is used for pollinating a type of milkweed. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered; How many insects
and other arthropods you might find in a Northeastern backyard.
(300 words)
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ As baseball fans cheer on Mark
McGwire's effort to capture the seasonal home run record set by
Roger Maris in 1961, manufacturers of a dietary supplement called
creatine are cheering wildly, too. There is good reason for
creatine's popularity. Unlike the anabolic steroids that mimic the
effects of the male sex hormone testosterone, creatine does not
cause hair loss or make the testicles shrink. Although virtually
nothing is known about possible long-term hazards, no obvious
adverse effects have been linked to creatine use. By Jane E. Brody.
(``l'' code) (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROSTATE-HEALTH (Undated) _ Prostate cancer patients who are
given radioactive Iodine-125 seeds implanted into the gland can
fare as well or better than those who receive more conventional
beam radiation or prostate removal treatments, a new study shows,
based on 10-year survival rates. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   STYLIST-FASHION (Undated) _ The rise and rise of the fashion
stylist, exerting an increasing influence over designers. By
Constance White.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS-FASHION (Undated) _ News and notes on fashion. By
Constance White.
</P>
<P>
   BY-DESIGN-FASHION (Undated) _ A short on long pleated skirts for
fall. By Anne-Marie Schiro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TURANDOT (Beijing) _ Staging of the opera epic Turandot in
the Forbidden City, the very setting Puccini imagined for his
Orientalist fantasy of an icy princess who succumbs to love. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   ARTISTS-NATURE (Paris) _ Arts Abroad: Ever since cave painters
began sketching horses, bison, elephants and the like, artists have
wrestled with the relationship between man and nature. Fast-forward
20,000 years to the rural and maritime landscapes and the
still-life oils of the post-Renaissance and the question remains
unchanged. How should art respond to nature? A show in Paris has
advanced the debate. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   LEOPOLD-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``King Leopold's Ghost,'' by
Adam Hochschild (HM). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CLINTON-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Add yet another count to the
accumulation of misdemeanors being assembled against President
Clinton: He has incited a flurry of moralizing by television
journalists, who have enrolled themselves among the victims. Yes,
there is whining from reporters that they have been compelled to
devote themselves to Monica Lewinsky when they are longing to cover
Boris Yeltsin. A critic's notebook by Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-NOTES (Undated) _ Short items from the world of music
and the arts.
