A1079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES0     08-31 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Figuring out Diana
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our jet landed at London's Heathrow the day after Diana's
funeral. My guess was that the city still would be gridlocked.
Crowd estimates the previous day were just about anything you cared
to make them. Those of us headed north out of London figured we'd
have a tough time getting there.
</P>
<P>
   To our surprise, the city had pretty well cleared out. The
highways were open. Even the papers were sedate by British
standards. By the time I arrived north, people were beginning to
wonder what it all had been about. Aside from a few bouquets
beginning to wilt on a monument in the center of town, life had not
changed notably.
</P>
<P>
   We've had a year to consider. Television is serving up lots of
Diana, although insight quotient has not enhanced. The Diana story
has, in fact, become even more settled. Except for the cause of the
accident _ drunken foul-up? MI6 rubout? _ we have come to a
consensus view of Diana. Gorgeous superstar. Anguished, insecure
bulimic. Victim. Dedicated mum. Caring celebrity. Sly tease.
Accomplished manipulator of press and public. Cleverer than all the
Royals (no major accomplishment). She wickedly called them ``The
Leper Colony,'' and her husband's mistress ``The Rottweiler.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the sum of all these things that made Diana engrossing.
Diana was one of those people who cannot quite be brought into
focus. We keep making minute adjustments of the lens to clarify the
picture. It never works. Marilyn was like that.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
