<HEADER>
A1108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-31 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL DECIDE TO FILE FUTURE `MEGA-SUITS'? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorney General Dan Morales wasn't exactly the
Lone Ranger when he began shooting it out with the tobacco industry
two years ago. He had a posse of private trial lawyers who are
still hoping to cash in their silver bullets for a $2.3 billion
reward.
</P>
<P>
   But Morales acted independently of the rest of state government,
particularly the governor and the Legislature, when he sued
cigarette makers over smoking-related health-care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ironically, Morales' success may end up clipping the wings
of future attorneys general who may want to punish other corporate
goliaths for any number of alleged sins.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement that Morales negotiated with the tobacco industry
is not the issue, because even the attorney general's harshest
critics aren't about to thumb their noses at $17.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is how Morales rounded up his legal team, signing
without legislative approval _ which the attorney general said he
didn't need _ a contingency fee contract guaranteeing the private
lawyers 15 percent of whatever the state won or negotiated from the
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said it was necessary to contract the legal work out
because the Legislature never would have appropriated the millions
of dollars necessary to prepare and try such a complex, high-stakes
suit. As part of the deal, the private lawyers agreed to pay the
up-front legal expenses, which wouldn't have been reimbursed if the
state had lost.
</P>
<P>
   Morales also insisted that he needed the toughest, most
experienced plaintiffs' lawyers to wage war on a previously
unbeatable industry, and you don't find that caliber of legal
talent or experience working on the attorney general's state
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   No one challenged the contingency agreement when it was signed
in 1996 because 15 percent seemed like a pretty good deal. It was
less than half the percentage plaintiffs' lawyers normally obtain
in fees.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the truth be known, few other state officials expected
the attorney general to win the suit anyway. At that time,
cigarette makers hadn't started surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas secured a record settlement, and a federal judge
awarded the full 15 percent contingency. The sheer size of the
agreement made the lawyers' cut huge, and suddenly their fees were
an even larger controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The fees sparked a war, which raged the first half of this year,
between Morales on one side and Gov. George W. Bush, several
legislators and civil justice reformers on the other. There is a
temporary truce now, but the dispute still hasn't been settled, and
some lawmakers already are making plans to curb the independence of
Morales' successors.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who isn't seeking re-election, will leave office in
January.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, the influential
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, didn't challenge the
legal fees in the tobacco case and doesn't want to outlaw
contingency deals.
</P>
<P>
   But he believes the Legislature, as the budget-setting branch of
state government, should change the law during next year's session
to prohibit the attorney general or any other state official from
agreeing to contingency fees without the Legislature's approval.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislative Budget Board's approval could suffice when the
full Legislature isn't in session, Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that would compromise the attorney general's
independence any more than the Legislature already does when it
approves the attorney general's budget,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The founding fathers intended for the Legislature to control
the purse strings.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the two nominees for Morales' job differ on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republican John Cornyn, a former Texas Supreme Court justice,
said he believes the Texas Constitution requires lawmakers'
approval of contingency fee agreements because the fees amount to
an appropriation of state money.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who filed a suit challenging the tobacco fee arrangement
earlier this year, said he would support legislation to clarify the
Legislature's authority in future cases.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic candidate Jim Mattox, a former attorney general and
self-described champion of the ``little people,'' suggested the
attack on contingency fees was part of an effort by big businesses
and insurance companies, which heavily lobby the Legislature, to
seek more protection from public interest suits.
</P>
<P>
   The debate will continue.
</P>
<P>
   If the Legislature gives itself the clear-cut authority to veto
contingency deals, lawmakers _ and not the state's top lawyer _
would effectively decide how many, if any, ``mega-suits'' the state
files in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Their decisions could impact environmental, health and other
concerns of importance to millions of Texans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
