A1124 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-31 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO COPE WITH EMERGING FEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week was a painful lesson in how scary it can be to invest
in emerging, undeveloped stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Mexico reported that its gross domestic product
rose 4.5 percent in the second quarter, but that hasn't stopped the
Mexican stock market from plummeting 40 percent from the start of
this year through last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do now? If you have Latin American investments,
do you bail out or stay? If you don't hold any of these
investments, is this bottom-fishing time?
</P>
<P>
   Answering that question based on the advice from experts is
difficult because they offer contradictory advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not just run in and try to catch a falling knife,''
said David Doherty, a principal at Crawford-Doherty Capital
Management Group in Houston, a money management firm that
specializes in global investing. ``If you're trying to bottom-fish
right here, you're probably not going to reach the bottom and it
could go lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Wolper, associate editor of Morningstar Mutual Funds in
Chicago, which covers mutual funds, was more willing to take a look
at buying there now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have reason to be positive in that region, then this is
a good time because of the fall-down in the markets, but if you're
not that familiar with the region and you're just looking at the
prices, I wouldn't say you should jump in because they can always
fall further.''
</P>
<P>
   The Latin American markets could fall another 5 to 10 percent,
said Hamilton Lewis, a technical market analyst and head of
Hamilton Lewis Capital Management in Houston, a money management
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, nobody knows when the markets will hit bottom and
how much further they'll fall. This is why it's important for
investors to follow the cardinal rules of investing that over time
have generally held true.
</P>
<P>
   One of those rules is to buy and hold an investment for the long
term. By doing this, you don't have to worry as much about the
normal downs in the market because you know that over the long
haul, the stock market gives you the biggest bang for your buck.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. market, that philosophy has done well for investors
because stocks return an average 10 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   But that wisdom doesn't always hold true when you invest in
foreign stocks, especially those in developing markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexico Fund, a closed-end investment company, had a negative
0.8 percent average annual total return in the five years ended
July 31.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with a 5 percent average annual total return for
Latin America funds for the same period.
</P>
<P>
   And an average annual total return for foreign stock funds in
the five years ended July 31 was 11.6 percent, Wolper said.
</P>
<P>
   Portfolio theory holds that the safest way to make money over
the long term is to hold a broad mix of asset classes, including
small stocks, bonds, foreign stocks and domestic large-company
shares.
</P>
<P>
   It really pays to diversify. During these tough times, it
doesn't pay to own a fund that invests in stocks of a single
country.
</P>
<P>
   If you were diversified, the pain would have been less during
these turbulent times in the market. The challenge here is to find
ways to determine whether it's time for you to sell.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're like most investors, you're likely to react to the
market and get out at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt Associates, an employee benefits consulting firm, which
started an index to measure the behavior of those who invest in
401(k) retirement savings plans, found that those investors are
moving out of stocks when the market falls, and into stocks when
the market rises.
</P>
<P>
   That's the opposite of the investment adage of buy low, sell
high. Selling out now will lock in losses.
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself if you can afford further losses in your Latin
America investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the long-term perspective, you stay right where
you are,'' Doherty said.
</P>
<P>
   However, don't pour too much money into the region. Invest a set
amount consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not want to have more than 8 percent of your assets
in Latin America,'' Doherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have the skills to adequately evaluate where the markets
in the region are going?
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires a long-term outlook and it requires the capability
of identifying appropriate vehicles,'' said Jack Borland, manager
of the foreign exchange group at Chase Bank of Texas in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
