<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (jt)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Backyard Bugs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How many insects and other arthropods might you find in a
Northeastern backyard?
</P>
<P>
   A. The number of individuals and species would depend on many
variables, like soil condition and chemical use, but if the first
few inches of soil were included, the totals might be impressive,
said Dr. Kefyn Catley, a scientist at the American Museum of
Natural History in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A former curator at the museum, Frank Lutz, surveyed backyard
insects in the 1930s and collected 1,402 species, including 467
butterflies and moths, 258 flies, 259 beetles and 167 wasps, bees
and ants from a 75-by-200-foot garden in a northeastern New Jersey
suburb. He did not include arachnids like spiders and mites.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would like to do the same survey 60 years later and
compare changes,'' Catley said.
</P>
<P>
   A suburban lawn is a monoculture, a single-crop field, Catley
emphasized, ``and since, in general, biodiversity increases with
complexity, the number of large easily visible arthropod species on
the surface of the soil or in the grass itself would be fairly
low.'' He estimated 25 to 50, with the number greatly reduced if
pesticides had been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' he continued, ``if we include the fauna of the
litter layer and top few inches of the soil, provided it was not
compacted, we could find huge numbers of individuals of springtails
and mites, as many as tens of thousands per square meter, and up to
50 species of springtails per square meter have been found in
woodland soil.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions about science to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New
York, N.Y. 10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
