<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1159 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV06-NY     08-31 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE ENTENDRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)  
 (Eds: Items in boldface should be set in italics.)  
(lb) 
Taras Grescoe, a freelance writer who lives in Montreal, is working
on a book about contemporary Quebec. William Safire is on
vacation. By TARAS GRESCOE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a recent television profile, Sting argued that he was more
than just a pretty face. ``Rock stars and footballers are supposed
to be  &UR; idiot savants &LR; ,'' he trilled. ``We're not supposed to have
read Proust.'' Monsieur Sting's erudition may indeed be staggering,
but chances are  &UR; idiot savant &LR;  didn't come into his vocabulary by
way of Swann.
</P>
<P>
   First coined by the British doctor J. Langdon Down (he of the
famous syndrome) in 1887, the expression doesn't particularly
benefit from a Gallic accent _ since it is virtually unknown in
France.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for  &UR; double entendre &LR; ,  &UR; affaire d'amour &LR;  and
 &UR; resume &LR; . At SoHo galleries, such expressions give one's dialogue a
cachet, a certain  &UR; je ne sais quoi &LR;  ( &UR; n'est-ce pas, cheri? &LR; ). At a
Bastille vernissage, they'll provoke embarrassing silences,
incomprehension and slack jaws.
</P>
<P>
   When the French want to say a song has two meanings, one of
which is  &UR; risque &LR;  (which, incidentally, implies that it is
dangerous, not daringly suggestive), they'll describe it as  &UR; a
double sens &LR; , not a  &UR; double entendre &LR; . When they talk about
 &UR; affaires &LR; , they mean business, not  &UR; aventures amoureuses &LR; . And a
 &UR; resume &LR;  is the plot summary that precedes the final installment of
a  &UR; telefilm &LR;  _ unlike a  &UR; curriculum vitae &LR; , or CV, which precedes
the arrival of the job applicant.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's French or English doing the borrowing, most loan
words should be handled with more than a  &UR; soupcon &LR;  of suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Terms like  &UR; le fastfood &LR; ,  &UR; le jogging &LR;  and  &UR; le weekend &LR;  are
routinely cited as examples of how, faced with a changing world
tragically tongue-tied by a rigid, rule-bound lexicon, the French
are forced to borrow words wholesale from the more dynamic,
flexible English language. Unfortunately, the ``English'' that most
French people speak is a bizarre, English-like pidgin that would be
Greek to anyone born on this side of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   You may be able to muddle through a Parisian's complaint about
 &UR; le barman &LR;  who makes customers order at least  &UR; un dry &LR;  (martini,
that is) before he'll allow them to play  &UR; flipper &LR;  or  &UR; baby-foot &LR; 
(pinball or Foosball), let alone use  &UR; les waters &LR;  (the ones in the
closet,  &UR; bien sur &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   But when someone tells you that she threw on a  &UR; sweat &LR;  (as in
shirt, but pronounced like a brand of saccharin), hopped into her
 &UR; break &LR;  (station wagon) and headed to the Bois de Vincennes for
some  &UR; footing &LR;  (a jog or a brisk walk), you know you've entered a
linguistic no man's land.
</P>
<P>
   Parisians expect Anglophones to understand them when they
discuss  &UR; la speakerine &LR;  (newscaster) who went to Switzerland for
 &UR; un lifting &LR;  (of the face), accuse one another of  &UR; snobisme &LR;  or
complain about how it's impossible to rent a luxurious apartment
 &UR; de standing &LR;  on the strength of a mere  &UR; shake-hand &LR; . After all,
these are English words with an impeccable pedigree _ or so most
French people seem to think.
</P>
<P>
   The German linguist Herbert Pilch called this process
pseudoborrowing and noted that it was endemic among the
sesquilingual of Europe _ his name for those who have mastered one
and a half languages. Pilch argued that since English had become
Europe's de facto second language, speech peppered with Anglo-Saxon
expressions was becoming a hallmark of a higher education.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he pointed out, was that though many Europeans had
at one time studied English, they retained only a superficial
knowledge of the language. Since the sesquilingual in Europe aren't
routinely in contact with native English speakers, they chatter
away in quasi-English without fear of correction or contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the blissful persistence of words that bear a structural
resemblance to English: the misplaced apostrophes of  &UR; pin's &LR;  _ for
a metal lapel badge _ and  &UR; jean's &LR;  and the absurd gerund endings of
 &UR; le shampooing &LR;  (the product, not the process),  &UR; le travelling &LR;  (a
dolly shot in cinematography) and  &UR; le brushing &LR;  (a blow-dry).
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, English _ which has earned a reputation for being a
promiscuous language _ isn't guilty of too much pseudoborrowing, at
least when it comes to French. The sad fact is, since most North
American English speakers can only dream of speaking one and a half
languages, they're hardly capable of inventing words that look
foreign.
</P>
<P>
   Native English speakers prefer to haul out aging French
expressions, accents and italics intact, for ostentatious display
at gallery openings and cocktail parties and in op-ed pieces.
</P>
<P>
   A little linguistic knowledge can be a useful thing. The next
time you find yourself buttonholed by a tiresome snob proud of his
 &UR; repartee &LR;  (that's  &UR; repartie &LR;  in Paris), you might want to feign
incomprehension of some of his more egregious and obsolete
Gallicisms.
</P>
<P>
   If he mentions, for example, that he chose a  &UR; nom de plume &LR;  that
reflected the sophisticated milieu of his first novel, just look at
him blankly, wait a beat and reply: ``Ohhh, you mean you chose a
 &UR; pseudonyme &LR; .'' Taken aback, he'll scold you for not having heard
of his book, a literary  &UR; nonpareil &LR;  that was a real  &UR; succes de
scandale &LR;  thanks to its cast of  &UR; outre &LR;  characters.
</P>
<P>
   Imitate his pronunciation of ``ooo-tray,'' arch an eyebrow and
ask him what his characters were so outraged about. After
suggesting that he meant to say  &UR; outrancier &LR;  _ which is closer to
outrageous _ and  &UR; une chose sans pareille &LR; , ask him to explain
 &UR; succes de scandale &LR; . Along with  &UR; toupee &LR;  ( &UR; une moumoute &LR;  or
 &UR; postiche &LR; ) and  &UR; brassiere &LR;  ( &UR; un soutien-gorge &LR; ), the expression
has dropped out of French idiom.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that our language would be better off if a
few such overused expressions were bundled up in the middle of the
night and forcefully expatriated via Concorde and Eurostar Express.
``That's life'' and ``so-so'' would get along just fine without
their pretentious Continental cousins  &UR; c'est la vie! &LR;  and  &UR; comme
ci, comme ca &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   A few French phrases, however, express ideas more succinctly and
evocatively than any in English and deserve to be coaxed into
day-to-day use. I'd like to be able to  &UR; chambrer &LR;  a bottle of wine,
for example _ bringing it to room temperature sounds like too much
trouble. Sleeping off that same bottle the next morning has
something sordid about it, but I could  &UR; cuver &LR;  any amount of
Bordeaux with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, I miss being in a country where sleeping in after a
night on the town _  &UR; une grasse matinee &LR;  after  &UR; une nuit blanche &LR;  _
is not a sign of shameful sloth but a national pastime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
