<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ANIMAL-ORIGINS-NY     08-31 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANIMAL-ORIGINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT HEAT AND COLD MAY HAVE SPAWNED ANIMALS ON EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first animals on Earth may have been shocked into existence
by the evolutionary one-two punch of a climatic episode so cold
that the oceans froze _ snowball Earth _ followed by one of the
hottest periods in Earth history, according to a new hypothesis
based largely on studies of carbon atoms in ancient sediments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have, finally, an explanation for the first
appearance of animal life on Earth,'' said Dr. Paul F. Hoffman, a
geologist at Harvard University who led the study, a report of
which appears in the current issue of Science. It is, he said, a
question that ``has bedeviled paleontologists since before
Darwin.''
</P>
<P>
   Living things had materialized by 3.8 billion years ago, 700
million or 800 million years after the planet was formed out of the
same interstellar dust cloud that gave birth to the sun. But as far
as scientists can tell, for the next 3 billion years life consisted
of nothing more complex than bacteria and algae. The first tiny
animals, simple disk-shaped creatures, are thought to have appeared
about 600 million years ago, and the first diverse animals soon
afterward. Both events occurred near the end of a period of
alternating episodes of snowball Earth and hothouse Earth. ``We
think it's not a coincidence,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cataclysmic changes in the environment, it is now widely
believed, have often provided the impetus for evolutionary change
by wiping out some species and paving the way for others to arise.
Many such episodes have been documented, but they are far less
drastic than the events proposed by Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Their novel idea about the relationship of the snowball-Earth
cycles to the rise of animal life is untested. It is not clear that
a direct connection exists between snowball Earth, hothouse Earth
and the appearance of animals, said Dr. Douglas Irwin, a
paleontologist at the Smithsonian Institution who studies
large-scale evolutionary patterns. ``But clearly, these kinds of
extreme environmental fluctuations, if borne out, would provide a
very powerful motor of evolutionary change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoffman study may also lend weight to the controversial
theory of snowball Earth itself, and help explain how the Earth
recovered from that long-ago superglaciation _ and why there has
never been another so severe. The animals themselves, it seems, may
play a role in preventing the latter occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of snowball Earth was proposed in 1992 by Dr. Joseph L.
Kirschvink of the California Institute of Technology as a possible
explanation for magnetic and chemical evidence that ice had once
existed near the equator and that little or no oxygen had entered
the ocean from the atmosphere at that time.
</P>
<P>
   The idea stirred instant contention. Some scientists thought
that the overturning of ocean layers could explain the puzzling
data. Others believed a tilt in the Earth's axis different from
today's might have been responsible. And computer models of the
climate system had suggested that once the Earth entered a totally
frozen state, it would not be able to recover from it.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts, including Dr. Ken Caldeira, now of the
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in California, and Dr. James
F. Kasting of Pennsylvania State University, as well as Kirschvink,
suggested a possible way out: emissions of carbon dioxide from
terrestrial volcanoes, which would trap heat in the atmosphere and
build up over millions of years, rewarming the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and his colleagues have examined isotopes of carbon
buried in ancient ocean sediments in what is now Namibia between
750 million and 570 million years ago. The relative amounts of the
two isotopes, carbon 12 and carbon 13, vary depending on how much
organic carbon, the residue of dead microbes, is being buried in
the sediments. A low ratio signifies that none is being buried, as
would happen if the Earth froze over. This is because
photosynthesis in the ocean would cease, and no carbon-containing
microbes would exist to die and be buried.
</P>
<P>
   The carbon evidence was the piece of the puzzle Hoffman needed
to flesh out the new hypothesis. According to it, at least four
snowball glaciations took place between 750 million and 570 million
years ago, each followed by a hothouse episode. A much earlier
glaciation might also have frozen the seas about 2.2 billion years
ago. The glaciations were touched off, according to the hypothesis,
when an ancient supercontinent called Rodinia broke into several
continents. This created many thousands of miles of shoreline
sediments, along the coasts of the newly formed Pacific Ocean and a
precursor of the Atlantic, for instance, where carbon could be
buried. The scenario then continues:
</P>
<P>
   As more carbon was buried, less of the element, in the form of
carbon dioxide, remained available for the atmosphere. The planet
cooled as a result. Eventually, accumulating snow and ice reflected
so much of the sun's heat that the catastrophic snowball state was
reached, with ice covering the seas.
</P>
<P>
   But terrestrial volcanoes replenished the atmospheric carbon
dioxide over several million years. Eventually, the ice and snow
melted, a process that might have taken only a few thousand years.
After the melting, less heat was reflected from the planet, and the
warming atmosphere evaporated more water from the oceans. Water
vapor is an even more powerful greenhouse gas than carbon dioxide.
The result, according to the Hoffman hypothesis, was a catastrophic
warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the story,'' Kasting said. ``It appears to fit. From a
climatic standpoint, it makes a lot of sense.'' On the other hand,
he said, ``it's going to be controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dr. Louis Derry, a geochemist at Cornell University,
called the hypothesis ``speculative'' and the evidence on which it
is based ``ambiguous.'' The idea is ``kind of neat,'' he said, in
that it provides a framework with which to try to explain several
kinds of evidence. But, he said, ``It's not clear that it's
compatible with all the data we have.''
</P>
<P>
   How might the cataclysms have stimulated the appearance of
animals? First, Hoffman contends, most of the microscopic creatures
in the sea would have died, dwarfing any mass extinction since. But
a few, because of their genetic makeup, would have been tough
enough to survive, and they could have repopulated the world in new
forms once the icebox and hothouse climates had passed. Some
experts now even postulate that environmental stress can prompt
organisms to change their genetic makeup to overcome the stress.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said the rise of animals might have prevented the
snowball Earth from recurring. Snails and worms in the coastal
sediments eat organic carbon and churn the sediments so that it is
difficult to bury carbon there, according to this view. That means
more carbon is recycled into the atmosphere, keeping the planet
warm.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is subject to further testing and investigation, as
Hoffman noted. Derry called the part about the origin of animals
``highly speculative,'' and Kasting noted that it was puzzling how
a mass extinction of the order proposed by Hoffman could have gone
unnoticed by scientists. ``Maybe it's just the paucity of the
fossil record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hoffman contends that his hypothesis explains ``all the
major geological features of this time period.'' That, he said,
``is when you know you're on the right track.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
