<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1175 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PRIMER-0901-CO     08-31 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRIMER-0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A PRIMER ON RUSSIA
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CLINTON-0901.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSSIA: AT A GLANCE -- Here's a look at Russia and the problems
that brought it to its political and economic crisis:
</P>
<P>
   Population: 146.5 million, and declining as the death rate
outpaces the birth rate. Poor health-care and alcoholism means the
life expectancy for males is 58; 72 for women.
</P>
<P>
   Area: The largest country in the world, encompassing 11 time
zones and 6.5 million square miles -- or about 1.8 times the size
of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Government: President Boris Yeltsin is an almost monarch-like
leader, who appoints a prime minister and cabinet to run the
government. The 450-member Duma, the lower house of parliament, is
controlled by the Communists and other hard-line and nationalist
political factions. Its powers are limited, but as it has recently
demonstrated, it can flex its muscle on budget and tax issues and
approval of Yeltsin's appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Politics: Yeltsin, a former Communist official whose crusade for
democracy helped bring down the Soviet Union in 1991, holds
enormous powers granted him by the 1993 constitution. But his
tenure has been marked by repeated economic and political crises.
Russians enjoy personal freedoms unknown during Soviet times, but
the transition to democracy has been slow, in part because Yeltsin
holds almost dictatorial powers. He also has been unable or
unwilling to transform his economic promises into a truly free
market
</P>
<P>
   Economy: In terms of gross domestic product (GDP), the country's
total output of goods and services, Russia does not make the list
of the world's top 20 economies. In GDP, the economy actually
shrank about 40 percent from 1993-97. Oil is the leading export,
but flat world prices mean less-than-expected revenues. Projections
for 1998 show Russia's gross domestic product at just 5.5 percent
of the U.S. GDP. Since the Soviet Union collapsed, Russia has moved
slowly towards a free-market economy. But the privatization of
Soviet-era industry left the bulk of the country's wealth in the
hands of a small number of industrialists and financiers.
Meanwhile, most ordinary Russians have seen their standard of
living drop and the average monthly salary totals only about $200.
</P>
<P>
   Military: Russia's economic problems have forced it to cut back
its armed forces, but it remains the world's second largest nuclear
power. Russia has an estimated 22,000 nuclear weapons and caches of
weapons-grade materials.
</P>
<P>
   THE CURRENT CRISIS: STEP BY STEP
</P>
<P>
   How it began:
</P>
<P>
   Russia showed a glimmer of economic growth in 1997 after years
of declines since the Soviet Union fell. But having failed over the
years to enact economic reforms, unable to collect most taxes and
reliant on oil exports, the economy had deep flaws. Russian
financial markets have suffered since the Asian crisis hit the
economies of the Far East last fall.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next:
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors who poured into Russia in 1996 and 1997, began
pulling out, putting pressure on the government to borrow heavily
from banks abroad, increasing its already substantial debt. In
March, Yeltsin fired the government of Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin, saying it had not done enough to fix the economy. He
appointed former banker Sergei Kiriyenko, 36, as prime minister to
lead a team of other young reformers.
</P>
<P>
   Why things didn't get better:
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial markets continued to slide as investors
continued to bolt and world oil prices slumped. Also, with millions
of Russian workers awaiting back-pay from the state, miners and
other laborers began a series of strikes across the country. The
government was forced to ask for international help. The
International Monetary Fund in July assembled a $22.6 billion
bailout plan intended to give Russia time to enact reforms and get
its house in order.
</P>
<P>
   Why that didn't work:
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's one economic success over the past year had been his
ability to keep inflation low and the ruble, the country's
currency, steady. Russia's Central Bank continued spending its
hard-currency reserves to protect the ruble from falling in value
on currency markets. Eventually, the cash would run out, or Russia
would default on its loans.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis:
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 17, the government announced a controlled devaluation of
the ruble and a moratorium -- a de-facto default -- on the payment
of about $40 billion in foreign debt. The announcement sent already
dismal financial markets plummeting further and threatened a
free-fall of the ruble. On Aug. 23, Yeltsin announced the surprise
firing of Kiriyenko and his government, naming Chernomyrdin to
replace him. That shook the financial markets even further and sent
the ruble out of control. It also raised speculation that Yeltsin
would hand his presidency to Chernomyrdin when Yeltsin's term ends
in 2000, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of the crisis:
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy. The economic problems are deep and severe --
and are beginning to be felt on the street with a rise in consumer
prices and a loss of spending power. The crisis has raised a
fundamental debate over whether Russia should revert to a state
command economy as it had during Soviet times, or pursue meaningful
reforms to seek a free-market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Politics is now deadlocked, meaning Russia is without a
government and with no one leader clearly in charge.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Duma rejected Chernomyrdin as Yeltsin's nominee
for prime minister. If the chamber rejects the nominee or another
Yeltsin choice a total of three times, Yeltsin can appoint a prime
minister by decree and dissolve the legislature. New elections
would take place within three months. That could also bring
Yeltsin's regime crashing down.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
