<HEADLINE>
RICHEY KICKS DOWN FIRST BARRIER, ANYWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ So what was it you wanted to know about the 49ers
again?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, you did have questions, right? A few things still
puzzling you as the old town team finishes yet another summer
vacation? Not sure that this is your Super Bowl champion a'borning?
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's something to tide you over until next Sunday,
anyway. They have a kicker. Maybe. We're not sure yet. With these
guys, we never are.
</P>
<P>
   The new pied du jour is an annoyingly thin, exceedingly
boyish-looking fellow named Wade Richey, who seems to have won the
job the way 49ers kickers usually do _ by being the only guy on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not by default, actually. Richey celebrated his fourth day
as a 49er by making an actual impression in Friday's 21-20 loss to
Seattle. A 53-yard field goal. A 45-yard field goal. Five kickoffs
in the end zone. And finally, a 62-yard game-winning attempt that
fell short, but not so short that he wasn't congratulated by 49ers
and Seahawks alike.
</P>
<P>
   An impostor? A cruel hoax? A damned funny hoax? Nope. A 49ers
kicker who can actually be asked to kick a field goal from longer
than 30 yards, and can reach the end zone from his own 30. The
SciFi Channel has more believable stuff in its Godzilla-Meets-Rodan
library.
</P>
<P>
   But it's true. Wade Richey has leg, and he works in San
Francisco. Thus, unless the Falcons get drunk Sunday and cut Morten
Andersen, and then Andersen gets even drunker and decides he wants
to kick for the minimum salary, Richey is on his way.
</P>
<P>
   Well, kind of on his way. You can never tell with the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, let's not put him in the Hall of Fame yet,'' special
teams coach George Stewart said. ``You have to give a lot of credit
to the Seahawks' special teams coach (Pete Rodriguez, who had
Richey here until last week's cuts) for teaching him so much. He
still rushes a little bit, so we'll have to work on slowing him
down, but under the circumstances, he did very well. So we'll bring
him back to Santa Clara, and hope I don't screw him up.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, though, Stewart probably won't have enough time to
screw Richey up. The NFL waiver wire may emit a few intriguing
kickers Sunday afternoon, but Richey is already here, and even a
team as anti-kicker as the 49ers will tend to err on the side of
the guy whose moving expenses have already been paid. And the real
games start next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great about tonight,'' Richey said, wearing the smile
he stole off Sally Field's face the night she won her second Oscar
for Best Actress. ``But I still have a lot of work to do. I wasn't
very good before the game kicking from the left hash mark, so I
think they strategically put me on the right hash. I have a natural
break with my ball, but I'm trying to straighten it out. It's just
not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he didn't quite get all of his 53-yarder, and got
under the 62-yarder. ``I'd love to have that one back again,'' he
said in all seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even as the last one died on the ``H'' in the end zone
``Seahawks,'' he was given warm and heartiest from players on both
sides. ``I got a high-five from Steve Young,'' he said with a smile
that seemed to say, ``And I know kickers don't get high-fived
around this place very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Richey will be the sixth 49ers place-kicker of the decade, which
entitles him to a Styrofoam plaque and a key chain inscribed by all
the members of Eddie DeBartolo's Louisiana grand jury. No other NFL
team has been so relentlessly dissatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   And all Richey had to do, really, was kick poorly enough with
the 'Hawks to get cut in time for the 49ers to pick him up, which
coincidentally was right about the time they had made up their
minds that John Becksvoort had too many consonants, or not enough
leg, or something. It's hard to know what they like in a kicker,
because the only staff person who has ever been seen with a 49ers
kicker (other than the punter, who has to hang around with the
kicker just to have someone to bitch to) is Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   And Stewart tempered his rave just enough to keep from being
disappointed again. In his three years in Happy Valley, he has had
Jeff Wilkins, and then Ryan Longwell, and then Jon Baker, and then
Gary Anderson, and then Becksvoort, and now Richey. He has learned
not to get attached to kickers any more than you would get attached
to a steeplejack.
</P>
<P>
   So when Stewart cautioned against calling Canton, he was doing
it partly out of history, partly out of caution, and partly to
quell his own enthusiasm. To his sure amazement, he saw Young
kicking his foot and calling to coach Steve Mariucci to let Richey
try the 53-yarder with 5:35 left in the game. No 49ers quarterback
has been so enthused about a kicker since Steve Spurrier in 1970 _
and he was the punter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Richey can't maintain this glorious pace once he
gets to Candlestick, he may end up on the bone yard with his
illustrious predecessors: Anderson and Wilkins and Tony Zendejas
and Doug Brien and Mike Cofer. The 49ers did not get to where they
are by showing patience with a guy who never needs his uniform
laundered.
</P>
<P>
   But for one otherwise meaningless night, they liked their
kicker. Sally Field would have been proud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
