<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-GENEALOGI     08-31 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-GENEALOGIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST SAY `NON' TO `GENEALOGIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Genealogies of a Crime'' is a spooky French film by
writer-director Raoul Ruiz (``Three Lives and Only One Death'').
The subject is the ridiculousness of a certain brand of French
intellectuality and Ruiz and co-writer Pascal Bonitzer skewer it
with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Genealogies'' inadvertently is about the flaccidity of
modern film. With French film ever placing itself in the vanguard
of self-analysis, the movie is one of those overly self-conscious
treatises on the meaning of life, truth and other verities. It
bends awkwardly under the weight of its pretentious content.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Deneuve, who seems to grow colder and more vacant as
her ageless face defies time, plays two roles. First, she is
Solange, a criminal attorney famed for taking on impossible cases
and losing them.
</P>
<P>
   She agrees to defend Rene (Melvil Poupaud), a young man raised
by his rather cold-hearted psychiatrist aunt Jeanne (also Deneuve)
from childhood and treated by her as a laboratory specimen for
observation. Referred to as ``the monster'' from his earliest
years, Rene proves his dastardliness one day by killing said aunt.
</P>
<P>
   Like the lawyer in ``Jagged Edge,'' Solange is taken for a ride
by her client, but Rene is aided in his ruse by the members of a
controversial psychiatric society that is being investigated for
fraud and that is headed by a certifiable loony named Georges (the
incomparable Michel Piccoli).
</P>
<P>
   As flashback overshadows flashback, and as Solange reprises the
victim role once played by Jeanne, the circumstances of the murder
become fuzzier. There is Rene's version, and the version of the
only witness, who happens to be the barking mad Georges. Solange,
confused, remains dutiful about her responsibility to her client.
</P>
<P>
   The movie starts to seem pretty darn barking itself when Solange
falls in love with the vile Rene. You can imagine the mess this
creates.
</P>
<P>
   The nuttiness of psychiatrists becomes a running gag in this
otherwise humorless movie, thus members of the besieged
professional society are portrayed as powerless cultists. And
sometimes it seems as if the actors are treating the material as if
it were ``Alice in Wonderland,'' keeping straight faces while
uttering complete nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   I guess Francophiles may find it all irresistible. Moi, non.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
