<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1271 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DEBAKEY-SURGERY-A     08-31 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DEBAKEY-SURGERY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBAKEY AT 90: STRINGENT STANDARDS AND A STEADY HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Dr. Michael DeBakey moved like a dancer in a pas de
deux, anticipating his surgical partner's every move during a
quadruple bypass operation on a woman at the Methodist Hospital
here recently. As DeBakey deftly manipulated scalpels, scissors and
forceps for more than three hours, his hands never quivered. What
made it an extraordinary operation is that DeBakey, the pioneering
heart surgeon, turns 90 on Sept. 7. With bushy eyebrows, long dark
hair that is combed back on a balding scalp, and a tinge of gray on
his sideburns, DeBakey looks 20 years younger. Though he takes
fewer surgical cases these days, he maintains a whirlwind schedule
of travel and consulting. He is celebrating his 50th year at Baylor
College of Medicine, and only a disability will make him retire,
DeBakey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't changed a bit,'' friends told DeBakey at a golden
wedding anniversary party for another couple here the same night he
performed the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't you nice to say that,'' a smiling DeBakey replied. ``I
have been blessed so far.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent check-up found DeBakey in the physical shape of a man
much younger, with normal heart function, cholesterol and other
blood tests, he said. He has been a hospital patient twice. Once
was for surgery for a near-fatal bleeding ulcer in 1984. The other
was for smoke inhalation suffered in rescuing his infant daughter,
Olga, after a Christmas tree caught fire in his home in 1978. ``I
just barely made it out,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As a child growing up in Lake Charles, La., the usual fare was
fish and fresh vegetables from the family garden. Now, he says, he
consumes whatever he wants but is a light eater and often skips
lunch because of work. He said he has never deliberately exercised,
takes no vacations and last visited his 1,000-acre ranch in the
nearby Texas hill country two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Trim at 160 pounds and 5 feet 11 inches, DeBakey can fit into
his Army uniform from World War II. In those years, he helped
develop the mobile military army surgical hospitals, now popularly
known as MASH units, and systematic follow-up of veterans with
certain medical conditions in the Veterans Administration medical
system.
</P>
<P>
   As a civilian, DeBakey went on to pioneer many heart and blood
vessel operations, perform at least 65,000 operations, teach and
build Baylor College of Medicine into a top-flight institution,
serving 10 years as its president (from 1969-79) and then 17 years
as its chancellor (from 1979-96).
</P>
<P>
   Though now so firmly rooted in Texas that he wears gleaming
white cowboy-style boots in the hospital, DeBakey has stamped out a
glamorous career as an international medical statesman. He
experienced a taste for life abroad while doing surgical training
in Europe in 1935 and 1936, and he speaks Arabic, French and
German.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, DeBakey will visit Aspen, Col.; Brussels,
Belgium; Istanbul, Turkey; Stockholm, Sweden; New York, and
Washington in 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the United States, DeBakey is probably best known in
Russia, which he has visited at least 30 times to perform
operations and to work on cooperative health programs.
</P>
<P>
   It was 88-year-old DeBakey, not a younger American surgeon, whom
President Boris Yeltsin's doctors summoned to Moscow for
consultation for Yeltsin's quintuple bypass operation in 1996. In a
foreword to the Russian edition of DeBakey's 1997 book ``The New
Living Heart,'' written with Antonio Gotto (Adams), Yeltsin
described DeBakey as ``a magician of the heart'' and ``a man with a
gift for performing miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   Around Baylor, DeBakey's inexhaustible energy has led to the
nickname ``The Texas Tornado,'' and his demanding standards have
intimidated many of his staff members. When young doctors failed to
meet his expectations, DeBakey said, he would rebuke them: ``You
have four fingers and a thumb like I do. Why can't you use them the
way I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Noon, a former student and trainee with whom DeBakey
has worked for 30 years, said that over the years ``there were many
DeBakeys _ the chancellor, chairman of the department of surgery,
the teacher, the national and international leader.'' He often held
the positions simultaneously. ``He was good at getting everything
organized, but delays and disruptions made him mad,'' Noon said.
``Now his schedule is not as demanding, and he is less
high-strung.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his reputed temper, DeBakey said in his Louisiana
drawl, ``Maybe I should be more compassionate with people who do
not think as fast as I can.'' But he added, ``I have little
tolerance for incompetence, sloppy thinking and laziness.''
</P>
<P>
   A lengthy visit in late August attests that DeBakey still hates
to waste a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before performing the bypass operation, DeBakey went
straight to the office upon returning from a long weekend trip to
Azerbaijan, where he advised President Heydar Aliyev on the
creation of a new 100-bed heart center.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey lives a five-minute ride from the hospital in the same
house he lived in 50 years ago. The day he performed the operation,
DeBakey awoke at 5 a.m., had fruit juice and yogurt for breakfast,
read a newspaper and worked on a paper analyzing long-term findings
on thousands of operations he had performed. Before 8 a.m., he left
for the hospital, where he made a videotape promoting an
experimental device his team is developing to assist failing
hearts, before going to the operating room.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey heads the search committee for a top position at the
Baylor-affiliated Veterans Administration Hospital, and after
returning from the operating room, he interviewed a candidate.
Later, he reviewed the special heart X-rays known as angiograms of
three patients and advised them on the need for surgery. He also
answered a number of calls. DeBakey left the hospital about 6:30
p.m., as he does on most days.
</P>
<P>
   On this evening, his family was away. His second wife, Katrin,
an actress and artist he met as a widower at a party at Frank
Sinatra's home, was visiting in her native Germany. Olga, their
daughter, is spending her junior year in college studying in
Lebanon. (He has four sons from his first marriage; none are
doctors.) DeBakey spent nearly three hours at the anniversary
party, drove home in his Toyota Land Cruiser, and went to bed about
11.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   On other days, DeBakey worked on additional projects chiefly
related to heart disease, which is the leading cause of death in
developed countries. He talked about women and heart disease at a
luncheon sponsored by the American Heart Association; advised
doctors on plans to develop new cardio-vascular centers in China,
Lebanon, Turkey and Russia; worked on arrangements for the first
implantations of the heart-assist device in patients in Germany,
Sweden and Switzerland, and consulted through the Internet with
colleagues in foreign countries on complicated cases.
</P>
<P>
   His path to medical celebrity was set, indirectly, by his
father, who left Lebanon to escape religious persecution and
settled in Lake Charles, in the French-speaking Cajun country. His
father owned rice farms, real estate and drug stores, which became
a hangout for doctors. ``I became enamored of them,'' DeBakey said.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s, DeBakey and his mentor at Tulane University,
Alton Ochsner, both non-smokers, became two of the first scientists
to link the early rise in lung cancer to cigarette smoking. At the
time, other medical leaders attributed the cancer increase to the
aftereffects of the 1918 influenza epidemic, inhalation of
poisonous gases in World War I and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey's mother taught him to sew. In the early 1950s, he drew
on that know-how to make grafts from Dacron and use them to repair
aneurysms, or balloonings, in all parts of the aorta. Such grafts
are now part of standard treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really opened that field,'' DeBakey said.
</P>
<P>
   Peers acknowledge DeBakey's many talents, as well as his ample
pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, he has a pretty big ego,'' said Claude Lenfant,
the head of the National Heart Lung and Blood Institute, a federal
agency in Bethesda, Md. But, Lenfant added, ``his contributions
have been enormous, and he will leave an amazing legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other famous surgeons, ``Dr. DeBakey has exported
his know-how to the world,'' said Lenfant, who first met DeBakey
when he demonstrated open-heart operations as a visiting professor
at his medical school in France in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey has a knack for telling a good story and an appetite for
publicity. A framed copy of DeBakey on the cover of Time magazine
on May 28, 1965, is among hundreds of mementos that adorn the walls
of his office.
</P>
<P>
   When he first arrived in Houston, his ever-rising profile used
to get DeBakey in hot water with the doctors in the local medical
society. ``They did everything to denounce me because I was a
threat to them,'' DeBakey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've done has been resisted,'' DeBakey said, citing
such problems as revising the standard of surgical training in
Houston; overcoming the resistance of doctors and nurses in
starting the first intensive care units at Baylor, and admitting
black patients to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, he is treated with the deference of a living
legend. Around Houston, DeBakey is recognized instantly. At the
hospital, employees ask if they can have their picture taken with
him, and he complies. Even during the quadruple bypass, a young
surgeon stationed himself behind DeBakey so he would be included in
a photograph of the master performing the heart operation.
</P>
<P>
   After the operation, DeBakey took the elevator and inserted a
key that allowed it to climb nonstop from the third-floor operating
room to his ninth-floor office. The key was a compromise; a
benefactor wanted to build a private elevator for DeBakey, who
rejected the idea and settled for the key.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has no age limit on those performing surgery there,
DeBakey said. He said he does fewer operations now ``because the
surgeon in charge of the operation has responsibility for the
post-operative care, and I have been away more than I have been
here recently.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Operations tie you down,'' DeBakey said. So he refers many
patients needing surgery to Noon.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey freely talks about the rich and famous patients he has
treated. Sometimes it is to instruct, as in his American Heart
Association talk to women when he described the operation he
performed on Marlene Dietrich, the actress, to relieve blockage of
arteries in her legs.
</P>
<P>
   He also sprinkles his conversations with stories about meeting
Queen Elizabeth, about royalty from Belgium, and about the
generosity of patients whom he proudly said he recruited as donors.
His own name is affixed to buildings and medical wings at Baylor
and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey said he told wealthy patients like Stavros Niarchos and
Aristotle Onassis, who asked about his fees, that he would not send
them a bill. Instead, brought up his foundation: ``I said I would
like for you to consider making a contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation now contributes $2 million a year to Baylor's
research program, DeBakey said.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey's persuasiveness has shown up on the political front as
well. After World War II, he played a major role in replacing a
decrepit library in Washington run by the Army with the National
Library of Medicine at the National Institutes of Health, which is
in Bethesda, Md. It is now the world's premier medical library.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey thought the library should be near government
researchers on the Bethesda campus, but at first, published
accounts relate, James Shannon, the NIH director, did not agree.
DeBakey convinced him otherwise by asking Shannon how he started
his pioneering kidney research at New York University. By reading
in the library, Shannon replied.
</P>
<P>
   But The American Medical Association wanted the library built
next to its headquarters in Chicago, and with little interest in
the issue, Sam Rayburn of Texas, then the House speaker, held up
the bill backing the Bethesda site, which was sponsored by Sen.
Lister Hill of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey, though, had once operated on the husband of the
secretary of the national Democratic Party, Dorothy Vredenberg, and
he asked her for help. The next day she told DeBakey that Rayburn
would let the bill through.
</P>
<P>
   High on DeBakey's list of accomplishments is a Houston high
school he help start 25 years ago for students, mostly minorities,
seeking careers in the health care field. The school is now named
for DeBakey.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of pride is the 1,000 American and foreign
surgeons he has trained. Many of those surgeons are working in top
positions, including Renat Akchurin, who performed the quintuple
bypass on Yeltsin. Yet, DeBakey said: ``I'm shocked to hear some
are retired. Where did the time go?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
