<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CLINTON-NOTEBOOK-5     08-31 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLINTON-NOTEBOOK-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: COVERING THE CLINTON STORY, OH SO
APOLOGETICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add yet another count to the accumulation of misdemeanors being
assembled against President Clinton: He has incited a flurry of
moralizing by television journalists, who have enrolled themselves
among the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is whining from reporters that they have been
compelled to devote themselves to Monica Lewinsky when they are
longing to cover Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to find one of these arbiters of appropriate behavior
who is satisfied with the president's unapologetic public apology,
but no trouble at all finding prescriptions for what he should have
said and done and should be doing.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus is that the president has failed the contrition
test. Bill Kristol of ABC, a predictable critic (he said that his
former boss Dan Quayle would never have behaved so dishonorably),
summed up the prevailing spirit with a call for a ``bending of the
knee.'' The presidential knee would have had to be bent in defiance
of anatomical possibilities to satisfy Kristol, who sees Clinton as
``fundamentally corrupting,'' or to receive absolution from William
Bennett, proprietor of public morals, who on ``Meet the Press''
called the president a ``serial liar,'' a ``serial adulterer'' and
a ``felon.'' (He had to take back ``felon.'') But everybody has a
favorite apology that Clinton has neglected to make. The president
himself has drawn public attention to the virtues of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the criticisms heard on ``Larry King Live'' and
other exhorters of Presidential penitence:
</P>
<P>
   _ The president should have apologized to his wife and to
Chelsea, whose ratings seem to be rising, perhaps as a consequence
of this neglect.
</P>
<P>
   _ He should have apologized to the Cabinet members,
congressional supporters and White House functionaries who were
thrown before the cameras week after week to say they had no
suspicion of events that most of the nation took for granted.
</P>
<P>
   _ He should have apologized to Kenneth Starr for tempting the
special prosecutor's peeping-Tom propensities.
</P>
<P>
   _ He should have apologized to parents who found themselves
embarrassed by what their children were learning on news programs
that do not carry warnings about content.
</P>
<P>
   _ He should have apologized to Ms. Lewinsky for giving her a
romantic impression of their relationship and, as long as he was at
it, to all other White House interns and their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   _ He should have apologized to the Oval Office for irreverent
use of federal property during working hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ And he should have apologized more feelingly to ``the American
people,'' a phrase that easily wins the Nexis award for the most
frequently resorted-to safe haven for television pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it turns out that journalists, too, lay claim to a
share in the groveling stakes. Tim Russert, who presides over
``Meet the Press'' in a tough-minded, often rewarding way, also
works for MSNBC, his network's cable entry in Monicamania. Here, on
a channel distinguished by nonstop cablegabble, he announced, ``No
one has relished covering this squalid story.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, if only Clinton had taken into account what his
``inappropriate'' behavior was forcing the television community to
do, he might have had second thoughts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russert's report or confession is as hard to swallow as, say,
the president's understanding of what constitutes a sexual
relationship. It's like believing in the reformation of Geraldo
Rivera. But let's try to take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   What Russert must mean is that the whole company of cable news
eminences are in thrall to ratings; that their consciences ache as
they keep spewing scraps of information, bits of gossip, gobs of
speculation and free-floating opinions; that they are mortified at
the memory of the ideals that may have drawn them into reporting
and are pained by the recognition that significant events are being
thinly addressed while hours and weeks and months are lavished,
especially on MSNBC, on what Russert has called a ``squalid
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I can believe much of it. Journalists, like other wage
earners, do what they have to do; that applies even to the network
stars who set the standards for television. This is commerce, after
all. In particular, those who draw their livelihoods from cable
operations cannot afford much independence of market forces. In
tight competition for ratings and in the gaps between mourning for
Diana, Princess of Wales, a tale of presidential sex is their
channels' chance at drawing a sizable audience, all those people
who declare themselves to be sick of the story yet cannot get
enough of it.
</P>
<P>
   So all sympathy to Russert and colleagues. And now we know whom
to blame if many reporters are not proud of their puerile
assignments yet will continue to carry them out. That must be
Clinton's fault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
