<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1311 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-EXHIBIT-PRICE-HNS     08-31 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-EXHIBIT-PRICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN MODERNIST MOVEMENT REDISCOVERED AT CALIFORNIA EXHIBIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Detroit Institute of Arts is CQ in 8thgraf; contains optional
trims)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORAGA, Calif. _ One of the most fascinating episodes in
American art occurred during the first decades of the century when
many artists grew dissatisfied with the ossified styles that were
being taught in the art academies and looked for new ways to make
art.
</P>
<P>
   Far from Europe, where radical new aesthetic ideas were being
hatched with shocking regularity, they fell back on their own
resources, looking eagerly at the few works of European modernism
that came their way and poring over the small black-and-white
reproductions that appeared in newspapers and art journals. But for
the most part, they had to make it up for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nascent American avant-garde centered in New
York City has been often told, and the ultimate success of the New
York School after World War II retroactively turned artists like
Georgia O'Keeffe, Marsden Hartley and Arthur Dove into heroic
precursors. But the artists existed all over the United States, and
many of them, especially those who worked in the West, have still
not received the attention their pioneering work deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``C.S. Price: Landscape, Image and Spirit,'' at the Hearst Art
Gallery of St. Mary's College through Sept. 27, attempts to bring
critical attention back to at least one West Coast modernist.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton Price (1874-1950) lived a uniquely Western life. Brought
up on a ranch in Wyoming, as a young man he hired himself out as a
cowhand, working cattle drives across the plains. He showed
drawings of animals and other aspects of life on the range in
saloons, and when he was 32 a local rancher sent him to St. Louis
to study art.
</P>
<P>
   In 1915, Price went to San Francisco. He attended the
Panama-Pacific International Exposition, where, among 11,000 works
of art on display, he saw paintings by Cezanne, Gauguin, van Gogh
and Munch that confirmed his own inchoate attitude toward painting.
He also met Gottardo Piazzoni, the dean of the San Francisco art
community, who encouraged his explorations into a painting that
could convey both how things felt and looked.
</P>
<P>
   Piazzoni encouraged Price to move to California coastal
community of Monterey where an active art scene flourished. While
there he roomed with Augustus Gay, one of the Oakland-based Society
of Six painters who were also transformed by their experience of
European modernism at the Panama-Pacific Exposition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, Price moved to Portland, Ore., and in his old age, he
received national attention. In 1946, he was included in an
important exhibition of new American art at the Museum of Modern
Art in New York that also included work by Robert Motherwell,
Arshile Gorky and Mark Tobey, and he also showed in two prominent
New York galleries. The Metropolitan Museum, the Brooklyn Museum
and the Detroit Institute of Arts, as well as museums in Portland
and Seattle, purchased his work.
</P>
<P>
   Then he died and his work fell back into obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Mary's retrospective, which will travel to Eugene, Ore.,
and Monterey, suggests that rediscovery is merited.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition opens with ``Wolves,'' a 1944 work that shows
Price's mature style at its best. When I first walked into the
gallery, the 26-by-30 inch painting looked abstract. Then, I became
discomforted by two pairs of eyes staring out at me. Gradually, the
rough forms of two wolves came into focus.
</P>
<P>
   The oil paint, primarily dark with a few dramatic light
contrasts, was crudely spread on with a palette knife. The paint
surface was further scored by stabs of paint, and squiggles were
cut into the palette knife's broad marks with sharp instruments.
Using a repertory of mark-making techniques utterly lacking in
finesse, Price successfully captured a sense of the primordial, the
elemental, that was a common goal among advanced artists of the
era.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are very different, Price's ``Wolves'' shares a
world view (and subject) with Jackson Pollock's contemporaneous
``The She-Wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which includes 33 paintings and two etchings, is
divided into three categories by subject: landscape, boats and
animals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The landscape section includes some of Price's earliest mature
works, painted during his decade in Monterey. Two of the most
impressive are ``Coastline'' (circa 1924) and ``Monterey
Landscape'' (circa 1925), which are built up from bold color blocks
derived from post-Impressionism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coastline,'' particularly, captures the feeling of being on
the verge between two states of being that was also a subject in
the work of Hartley, Price's almost exact contemporary. Both men
knew what it was to live alone, and both men knew the power and the
terror of nature made manifest at the ocean's edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coastline'' is a handsome picture that Price could have turned
into a formula for a successful career, which was never his
motivation. Instead, he moved on to greater abstraction and more
direct expression of his feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Price's paintings featuring animals gave him the liberty to
explore life at its most elemental. As you would expect of someone
who spent the first 30 years of his life on a ranch, Price has
particularly insightful things to say in paint about horses.
</P>
<P>
   A little picture like ``Waterhole at Night'' (circa 1935) is
made of only a few daubs of paint scraped across a board, but it
plumbs Price's depth of feeling about the mysterious world of
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Also Hartleyesque is ``Fisherman'' (circa 1941), which shows a
solitary fisherman standing in a boat, his net spread out upon the
waters. Although Price's spiritual impulses seemed to be
uncontained by any religious dogma, the Christian symbolism here is
unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Gallery also is showing ``Small Wonders: The Etchings
of August Gay.'' Price's Monterey pal is best known as an original,
fauve colorist, but he also made a number of etchings in the late
'20s that were largely forgotten until fairly recently.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was an earlier show at St. Mary's that brought Gay's
printmaking to light. After an artist's retrospective, things tend
to come out of the woodwork, and a box of Gay's copper etching
plates, many of which had never been printed, was discovered at
that time. With permission of the estate, David Kelso made prints
from the plates, and the current show is the result.
</P>
<P>
   Gay's prints might not win prizes, but they are interesting
enough. His subjects are predictable: scenes of old Monterey,
houses from the Mexican era, boats in the harbor, fisherman's
shacks, cannery row _ but they hold a picturesque and nostalgic
appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
