<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYLITE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of approval.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Manhattan doctor who, for obvious reasons, doesn't want his
name used, was standing near the door, about to get off the train
to the Hamptons when a man, also about to depart, joined him.
</P>
<P>
   The man look at the doctor and said ``Lovely tie. Hermes?''
``Yes,'' said the doctor. The man went on to further judgment.
``Gift,'' he said, with not even a question in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   How did he come to this conclusion? ``The rest of you is a
slob,'' he said, sotto voce. The train stopped, and the two got off
without a further word.
</P>
<P>
   Could this possibly be a new fashion, replacing body piercing?
Victor Del Favaro was in the Metropolitan Museum of Art recently
when he spotted the familiar circular metal entrance tag, usually
folded onto a lapel, on the corner of a young man's lower lip.
</P>
<P>
   Gladys M. Distler was taking in the exhibition of Chaim Soutine
paintings at the Jewish Museum _ thickly painted canvases with bold
colors and distorted figures. Two other women were nearby, and as
she was leaving, she heard one say to the other, ``He's a good
painter _ but not for my living room.''
</P>
<P>
   I was in a packed matinee of ``Madeline'' with my 5{-year-old
niece and her father, across the aisle from a very noisy 4- or
5-year-old. A woman behind us finally blurted out, ``Can't you at
least try to control your child?'' The child's mother turned and
said, ``It's a children's movie _ that's what children do.''
</P>
<P>
   The other woman replied, ``But there are other children here who
are quiet and we can't hear because of yours.''
</P>
<P>
   The testy exchange continued until finally the mother of the
noisy child said, ``Would you like to step outside and settle
this?'' It took three nearby men to calm the situation.
</P>
<P>
   I love R-rated action movies, where bad guys are shot and
buildings get blown up. But it was only at ``Madeline,'' a G-rated
movie for children, that I got to see real New York City mean
street action.
</P>
<P>
   _ JEROME PUCHKOFF
</P>
<P>
   Bix Janni recently called a major airline's reservation desk and
had this conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Janni: I want to book a direct flight to Atlanta and would like
to pick up my tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Clerk: Where would you like to pick them up?
</P>
<P>
   Janni: In midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Clerk: How do you spell ``midtown''?
</P>
<P>
   Janni: Try ``New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   Clerk: What's the closest airport?
</P>
<P>
   Janni: JFK.
</P>
<P>
   Clerk: We have a pickup counter in the Plaza Hotel but it's
permanently closed.
</P>
<P>
   Janni used another airline.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda Dolobowsky was leaving a concert of the Wayne Chamber
Orchestra in Wayne, N.J., when she heard one woman ask her friend
if she had enjoyed it. The second woman replied, ``It was good but
there were too many notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Samuel I. Joseph was at the delicatessen counter of a market
in Baltimore when he heard a customer addressing the clerk. ``I'd
like some smoked turkey if it isn't too dry _ last week it was very
dry.'' A voice in the crowd called out, ``So how was it the week
before?''
</P>
<P>
   To be filed under ``Ups and Downs'':
</P>
<P>
   Edward G. O'Hara had to double-park when he recently took his
95-year-old father and 94-year-old mother to the doctor in
Brooklyn. As they were en route to the examination room, both
parents using canes, they passed through the waiting room where a
dozen elderly patients were silently waiting to be called.
</P>
<P>
   When his parents were finished and the three were leaving, again
via the waiting room, O'Hara stopped and with one parent clinging
to each arm, said in a loud voice, ``Which one of you is going to
drive home?'' The men and women in the waiting room broke up
laughing, and began talking to one another. O'Hara was pleased, and
his pleasure lasted until he got outside. His car had a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   It was very hot. I was the only customer at my favorite small
consignment shop, looking for a summer dress.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly a woman burst through the door. Out of breath, she
panted her way to a saleswoman. She was desperate. ``I need white
pants,'' she breathed. In a matter of minutes, the saleswoman
pulled out a few pairs of white pants in different styles. She held
up the first pair _ white linen bell-bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   The desperate customer took one look. ``Oh no, not in a million
years,'' she said. ``Maybe not even then.''
</P>
<P>
   _ KATHERINE DESMOND
</P>
<P>
   Who makes them, Harry Shechtman wondered, after spotting a sign
in Long Beach reading ``Handicapped Vans Only.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``According to Newsweek, Kenneth Starr is preparing a 300-page
report that is going to include graphic descriptions of the
President's sexual encounters with Monica Lewinsky. The report will
be distributed to all members of Congress and their 13-year-old
sons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been reported that an early draft of President Clinton's
speech contained an apology to Monica Lewinsky. And an even earlier
draft of the speech contained a thank you to Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Home-run hitter Mark McGwire has admitted to taking a
supplement that boosts your testosterone level. He also bragged
that if he keeps taking the supplement, he's not going to need a
bat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is Macaulay Culkin's 18th birthday. Apparently, he spent
a romantic evening celebrating around town with just his wife and
their fake IDs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On Martha's Vineyard yesterday, a large crowd on land cheered
as President Clinton went by on a boat. Mainly because they thought
he was leaving the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, the Clinton family did spend the whole day out on a
boat with Walter Cronkite. Afterwards, the First Lady admitted, 'It
was a little odd. I'm not used to being around the most trusted man
in America.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now in Williamsport, Pennsylvania, the Little League
World Series is going on. Once again this year, Michael Jackson
asked if he could sing the national anthem and then just sort of
hang around for a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier tonight on a special episode of 'Nightline,' Ted
Koppel spent 12 hours in a federal prison's solitary confinement
ward. Apparently, he was trying to simulate the conditions of
President Clinton's vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, a 10-year-old girl became the first person in
history to sing the national anthem at all 30 Major League baseball
parks. Then, after breaking the record, the little girl admitted
she's been taking a testosterone enhancing supplement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A new study shows that many New York City classrooms have more
than 30 kids. And that's not counting their 30 kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Flatley, 'The Lord of Dance,' said he's going to star
in a brand new movie that will encourage people to follow their
dreams. Which is odd because most people's dream is to never see
Michael Flatley again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Boris Yeltsin delivered a speech to the Russian people
about their economic crisis. In his speech, Yeltsin said that
things have gotten so bad, not only is the ruble worthless, but
they've also run out of ice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, the president of CBS television announced that
despite rumors, the network isn't for sale. Although he said
they'll take the best offer for Andy Rooney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow is Michael Jackson's birthday. He turns 40 years old.
When asked to comment, Jackson said his age doesn't depress him,
but Macaulay Culkin's does.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, the organizer of Harlem's Million Youth March said
Mayor Giuliani is the devil. Immediately afterwards, the actual
devil held a press conference and said, 'Oh yeah, like I would have
shut down New York's strip clubs.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how hurricanes get their names? They are all named
after stupid local TV reporters who died standing outside in the
last hurricane. 'Hi, my name's Bonnie. The winds are picking up
now. Everyone's evacuating except me. Aaahh!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what's going on in Washington. Vice President Al
Gore returned from his two-week vacation in Hawaii. I didn't know
he was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the latest polls, if Bill Clinton and Al Gore
were running for election today, it would be a dead heat. Al Gore
would be dead and Bill Clinton would be in heat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what's going on with Monica, or as President Clinton
calls her, 'My little humidor.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a rather obscure joke: what do Monica Lewinsky and
Lucille Ball have in common? They both had an intimate relationship
with a Cuban.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why this Ken Starr investigation has taken so long. For
the last five years he's been looking for a smoking gun. He
should've been looking for a smoking cigar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to producers at Playboy Television, you know where
the most uninhibited women in the world are? Russia. They said
Russian women love to get naked in public places. What a
coincidence. President Clinton's going there next week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This coming January 23, 50-year-old George Foreman fighting
48-year-old Larry Holmes. The excitement, the drama. Let's get
ready to stumble.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Yeltsin-Clinton summit will be news this week, but we're
still awaiting details of the recent Clinton-Clinton-Clinton
vacation summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
