<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZILFEST-MUSIC-REVI     08-31 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZILFEST-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BRAZILFEST': A BOSSA NOVA PRINCESS BLENDING SHYNESS AND FIZZ
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Brazilfest '98,'' a condensed program at the
Damrosch Park Band Shell on Sunday night, was pure Rio suavity,
most of it borne on the broad shoulders of Antonio Carlos Jobim,
with replications of original arrangements of his songs. The singer
Bebel Gilberto, daughter of Joao Gilberto, performed, as well as
the young singers Patricia Marx and Carol Saboya and the
light-classical chamber music group Quinteto D'Elas.
</P>
<P>
   But the deepest note was struck by the headlining act, Leila
Pinheiro, a popular Brazilian singer in her late 30s who is barely
known to New York audiences. A long-running candidate in her
country for the bossa nova princess of her generation, she radiates
sophistication. As she sang, accompanying herself at the piano for
half the set, her stage manner was self-possessed.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, sang some Jobim songs, including ``Corcovado'' and
``Garota de Ipanema.'' But when she sang a song from her recent
album, with music by Guinga (the composer Carlos Althier) and words
by the poet Aldir Blanc, the mood changed. Their collaborations on
the album result in intellectual urban songs about identity, chatty
and delicate. Ms. Pinheiro gets the best of them, with a quick,
understated delivery. The one she sang, ``Catavento e Girassol''
(``Windmill and Sunflower''), is about irreconcilable differences
in a relationship between adults who have settled into emotional
trenches with the man acting and the woman reacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a withdrawn manner, and you're expansive,'' she sang in
one lyric. ``I side with Mia Farrow, you with Woody Allen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sad song but hyperarticulate about who the speaker is and
how she thinks. She carried it off, with just the right mixture of
introverted fatalism and expressive fizz.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too quickly, it was away from her new repertory and back
into Jobim land, with a double encore of ``Aguas de Marco,''
performed by everyone on the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
