<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Doscher heard a New Yorker explaining the Grand
Central-Times Square shuttle train to a tourist. ``You can go back
and forth every day and never get anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently on a family trip to North Carolina, our 4{-year-old
son, Doron, was acting difficult. His justification was that he
missed Brooklyn, where we live. He proceeded to list all the things
he loved about the borough, including his friends and his favorite
activities. Out of frustration that we might never be able to take
a vacation again, we asked him if there might be some other place
he would be willing to travel to. He paused for a moment and then
replied, ``Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   _ SUZANNE ROSE SHAPIRO
</P>
<P>
   There were only two passengers aboard a Madison Avenue bus late
one evening and Judy Bucey was startled out of her reverie by the
ringing of the other passenger's cell phone. The surprise turned to
amusement when the driver called out, ``If that's my wife, tell her
I'm not here.''
</P>
<P>
   On another Madison Avenue bus, two women in their upper middle
years were discussing the sweltering weather. Monica Sands
overheard the following exchange:
</P>
<P>
   First Woman: ``It's so hot today, I think I'll call off my
appointment with my acupuncturist.''
</P>
<P>
   Second Woman: ``Why do that? It might cool you off. With all
those needles poking little holes in you, you'll be well
ventilated.''
</P>
<P>
   Emery Davis, an orchestra leader who describes himself as
aggressive, recently had an unusual experience _ brought on by
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He was in a taxi on 57th Street, headed to Madison Square
Garden. ``Get on to Ninth Avenue, to 31st Street and then around to
the Garden,'' he instructed the driver. An old-time cabby, the
driver not only ignored him but also remained where he was, in the
slower of two lanes. Davis suggested that they might move a little
faster in the other lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think you can do it better?'' the driver said in a
challenging tone. ``Yes,'' Davis said. The driver pulled over to
the curb. ``OK, you drive,'' he said. The two traded places and
Davis, using every ounce of his aggression, whizzed along his
preferred route. When they got to the Garden, Davis was so pleased
with himself, he added a generous tip. His reward: ``Not bad,'' the
driver said.
</P>
<P>
   Bothered by the litter of expired Metrocards at bus stops and
around turnstiles? Bob Fowlow offers a solution that he spotted on
a Queens bus. A small homemade container beside the fare box
sported a sign that read, ``Cemetery for Used Metrocards. ''
</P>
<P>
   Basil C. Levine wasn't the only one amused by the comment of his
8-year-old granddaughter, Carling, as she inspected an abstract
sculpture at a Manhattan art gallery. The sculpture, titled ``The
Dog,'' consisted of rectangular metal bars connected with wire.
Carling's reaction: ``If that's a dog, he's got a lot of
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a senior citizen, I still adhere to the rules of behavior
instilled in me as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, while seated in a subway car that had no
vacant seats, an elderly man, leaning on a cane, accompanied by a
young woman in her teens, entered the car and happened to stand in
front of me. I immediately jumped up and offered him my seat. He
thanked me and, apparently a gentleman of the old school of
manners, proceeded to offer my seat to the young woman who,
smilingly, accepted it. Talk of chutzpah!
</P>
<P>
   Standing over her and glowering, I said, ``Miss, I gave up my
seat for this gentleman, not for you. As you appear to be a few
years younger than both of us, and if this man does not want the
seat, please return it to me, its rightful owner.'' She started to
say something, thought better of it and gave back the seat. I was
pleased to note a number of looks of approval.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARCELLA L. TOBIAS
</P>
