<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1343 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URBAN-LEGENDS-AZR &LR;      08-31 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-LEGENDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN LEGENDS FIND NEW LIFE IN HOLLYWOOD, ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MONTY PHAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED) - This is a true story. We swear.
</P>
<P>
   The people quoted are real, and we didn't use any friends of a
friend, even though they're all totally reliable. Sure, you may
have heard parts of this story before, but if you don't believe
them, don't blame us. That's just what we heard.
</P>
<P>
   But here's one truth we find to be self-evident: Urban legends,
in one form or another, seem to be popping up on TV and in the
movies more often lately. They're the stories those friends swore
were in the paper a few months back, the same ones we pass on in
letters, faxes or e-mails over the Internet, the medium that did
for urban legends what Las Vegas did for sin.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, however, the legends recirculated by Hollywood
and Madison Avenue are campier versions of the original tales,
seemingly poking fun at the exaggerated logic of having a houseful
of people chopped up just to point out that you should lock your
door at night. And in the true spirit of urban legends, the stories
have been changed to fit the times.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it's camp that sells. Take a look at the
``Scream''-type movies, those horror flicks that mock cliches of
horror flicks while adhering to those same cliches. In fact, come
Sept. 25, a film called ``Urban Legend'' opens, telling the tale of
a killer who offs unsuspecting students by bringing popular, untrue
legends to life (or, rather, death).
</P>
<P>
   (Example: Considerate college student comes home late, leaves
light off for sleeping roommate, wakes up to dead roommate and
``Aren't you glad you didn't turn on the light?'' written in blood
on the wall. Note to college freshmen: It's false. But, hey, keep
those doors locked. We told you once already.)
</P>
<P>
   In a way, they're our present-day parables. Sure, most legends
are false, but many have some form of moral to them. For instance,
the lack of documented Halloween-related candy poisonings have led
researchers and folklorists to conclude that that legend is untrue,
but that doesn't mean we should trust all candy-bearing strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Because the movie ``Urban Legend'' is a slasher flick, it
focuses on some of the more violent tales. Like the ``Aren't you
glad you didn't turn on the light?'' story, those legends use
exaggeration to teach safety.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Urban Legends Archive (www.urbanlegends.com),
most such stories share certain traits, among them questionable
origins and elements of humor or horror. Other legends reflect
current concerns, such as Internet hoaxes that boast of an
increasing Big Brother-like technology. Basically, they're legends
in our own minds. One making the rounds of late is an e-mail
offering a prize to users who help Bill Gates and the Walt Disney
Co. test an e-mail tracking program by forwarding it to 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   Many also have a basis in fact, such as the one about Craig
Shergold, a British boy who, in 1989, was diagnosed with terminal
cancer. On his behalf, family members appealed to the masses to
send him get-well cards so he could set the world record.
</P>
<P>
   He made it into the ``Guinness Book of World Records'' with 33
million cards in 1992 before the category was retired. However,
forms of his story kept circulating the globe. E-mail did the most
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Shergold regressed in age, becoming a 7-year-old boy. He still
was dying of cancer. His last name became Shefford or Sherwood. He
lived in Atlanta. And then someone substituted the Phoenix-based
Make-A-Wish Foundation for The Children's Wish Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Shergold, incidentally, is a healthy 19-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' says Shergold, from his Wallington, England,
home. ``People are always getting the story wrong. I just wish it
would stop now.''
</P>
<P>
   The national office in Phoenix still gets about 100 calls a
week, and that's not including its 82 chapters nationwide. It even
has a toll-free number, 800-215-1333, to explain the legend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Wallington, the Shergold family deals with four to
five bags of mail a day; the family estimates Craig has received
about 250 million cards. But the get-well card requests may have
saved Shergold: Because of the commotion, a Virginia billionaire
found out about the boy's story and paid for both the family's trip
to the United States and for Craig's operation, which resulted in
the removal of all but a benign part of the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   But while the basis of the Shergold legend is easy to pinpoint,
the origin of the urban legend featured in another film, ``Dead Man
on Campus,'' is less apparent. The movie, which opened Aug. 21 and
is produced by MTV Films, is a dark comedy about two flunking
college kids who discover their school's little-known rule that if
your roommate commits suicide, you automatically get a 4.0. So,
instead of improving their grades by studying, they spend their
time looking for suicidal roommies.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, no college has a rule like that, but good luck
finding a campus without some form of the ``Suicide Rule.''
According to the Urban Legends Reference Pages (www.snopes.com), a
Web site maintained by the San Fernando Valley Folklore Society,
the legend was started in the mid-1970s and reflects students'
anxiety to maintain good grades.
</P>
<P>
   Young people are legendarily impressionable, so it's no
coincidence that the current ``Dead Man on Campus'' and the
upcoming ``Urban Legend'' cater to the late teens and college
crowd. They're easy targets, after all, and have yet to be exposed
to many of the legends adults have heard over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Gibson, an executive creative director at the
Minneapolis-based Campbell Mithun Esty ad , says he had the image
of free-spirited youth in mind when Kmart asked the company to
produce TV commercials for its Route 66 brand of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   While doing research on the road, the company kept happening
upon Route 66-related folklore. That led to two commercials: The
first was ``Concrete Car,'' in which a jealous cement-truck driver
returns home to an unfamiliar convertible car in his driveway and
his wife inside laughing with another man. So he fills the car with
cement, only to discover that his wife bought the car as a birthday
gift and had just signed the final papers with the salesman.
</P>
<P>
   In the other commercial, ``Last Dance,'' a college-age character
tells the story of a group of kids who have brief car trouble while
driving to a dance. They stop at a motel, where a girl asks them
for ride. At the dance, she borrows one boy's shirt, then
disappears. When the group returns to the motel the next day to
retrieve the shirt, they talk to the girl's mother, who says it
couldn't have been her daughter because she died 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both commercials show a group of young people listening to the
storyteller, who starts off the former commercial with ``my cousin
knew this guy'' and the latter one with ``my brother knew these
guys.'' Part of the reason the commercials show young people is
because Kmart wanted to market the Route 66 line to that age group.
But Gibson says the ad agency's reason for using urban legends went
deeper than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're drawn to the mystery of it as well as the
humor of it,'' he says. ``Young people find mystery intriguing in
stories like that. You're in on something and I feel that's
important. You want to feel like you're connected to something
important and different at that age.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Monty Phan can be reached at monty.phan(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
