<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brisk jet stream winds from the southwest will steer strong
Hurricane Danielle parallel to, but well away from, the Eastern
Seaboard Tuesday. Scattered thunder near the Carolina coast will
develop along a stalled front, but are not directly related to the
hurricane. Otherwise, large swells will continue to reach the
shoreline from northern Florida to the Middle Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Earl, with sustained winds near 50 miles an hour,
is expected to gradually strengthen in the central Gulf of Mexico
Tuesday. Bands of tropical showers and thunderstorms will produce
downpours near the central Gulf coast. Other thundershowers will be
widely separated near and inland from the coast, from Texas to
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front will sweep though the upper Midwest. Due to limited
moisture, only a few isolated showers will accompany the front.
Meanwhile, a jet stream disturbance will spark a cluster of
southward-moving storms in the middle Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A large ridge of high pressure near 18,000 feet will remain over
the West. A pocket of moist air in the lower half of the
atmosphere, stuck over the central Rockies due to light and
variable winds aloft, will sponsor clusters of thunderstorms from
the southern Sierra to Colorado. Meanwhile, sunshine and near
record heat will occur in parts of the interior Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a wedge of dry air will allow for ample sun and a
pleasant afternoon from the eastern Ohio Valley to the Northeast.
Temperatures in the 70s to lower 80s will be close to the long-term
average.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Related Rains
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 5 p.m. on Saturday, rainfall at Nome, Alaska, for
August reached 8.45 inches, making August the town's wettest month
on record. The previous monthly mark was 8.43 inches, set in July
of 1920. For much of August, a large, sprawling trough of low
pressure held steady at 18,000 feet over the Bering Sea and the
northern Gulf of Alaska, setting the stage for recurrent, heavy
rains. Because of the natural spacings between large troughs of low
pressure, another trough anchored itself over eastern Asia for much
of the month, touching off prodigious, flooding rains in parts of
China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
