<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOT PUTTER FIGHTING FOR REPUTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The irony has not been lost upon Randy Barnes. He hit a golden
``home run,'' of sorts, two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd stood and roared then, too, just like the cascades of
cheers that Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa are now hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But now Barnes worries. He wonders if his golden sheen has been
forever lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Mark McGwire nothing but the best,'' Barnes says. ``I
hope he breaks Roger Maris' record.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, yeah, I think it's ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   On a sultry night in Atlanta two summers ago, Barnes, the former
Texas A&AMP;M shot putter, soared from sixth place to the Olympic gold
medal on one dramatic, final toss. It was the first gold medal in
track and field won by the United States at the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   In April testers showed up at Barnes' South Charleston, W.Va.,
home for a routine, nothing-out-of-the-ordinary, out-of-competition
drug test. All world-class track and field athletes have to undergo
the random tests.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, Barnes was stunned to hear the world
governing body for track and field, the IAAF, announce that he had
tested positive for a prohibited substance and thereby faces a
lifetime suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' sample contained androstenedione, the nutritional
supplement at the center of the McGwire controversy.
</P>
<P>
   He took the stuff. Barnes makes no show of denying that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have one sport where there's no penalty at all for taking
what he did,'' Barnes says, underlining the irony. ``And you have
another sport where they try to ruin your reputation and ban you
for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes stands by his original statement after the IAAF
announcement _ that he ``never willingly did anything illegal,
immoral or unethically wrong.'' He would rather have any more
comments come from his attorney, Greg Duplantis.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes is appealing the suspension. He is expected to argue that
androstenedione was added to the International Olympic Committee's
list of banned substances only last December and, hence, the shot
putter had no idea the supplement was on the X-list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it as an over-the-counter, nonprescription supplement
that anybody can buy at a health food store,'' Barnes says, echoing
baseball's argument.
</P>
<P>
   Duplantis says they finally saw the updated list _ after the
suspension had been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Ignorance of the X-list, unfortunately, has never been a warmly
received defense when the Drug Hearing Board convenes. But therein
lies the despotic reasoning that permeates the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC doesn't know conclusively whether andro is harmful.
There isn't a lab rat on the planet that does. But because the IOC
does try to regulate levels of testosterone, it apparently slapped
a knee-jerk ban on andro, which is said to naturally enhance the
production of testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   There are all forms of other ``cousin'' drugs on the IOC banned
list. Valium, for instance, is OK, but certain varieties of
Tylenol, Dristan and Dimetapp are not. The IOC lumps them all under
the category of stimulants.
</P>
<P>
   Enlightened thinking remains discouraged. When IOC head Juan
Antonio Samaranch boldly said last month that it's time that the
Olympic fathers distinguish between drugs that are known to be
harmful and those that aren't, his own people cried that he was
misquoted. Still, a global Olympic summit has been called for
Switzerland in January to discuss, among other doping issues, what
to do about supplements like androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the Barnes case is a prior suspension in 1991 for
testing positive for methyltestosterone, a true anabolic steroid.
Barnes argued that a chain of unusual, messy handling procedures
should have made his sample invalid, and a U.S. panel concurred.
But the IAAF stuck by its two-year suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Duplantis hopes Samaranch's words don't come too late for
Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for people to imagine that in one sport it's
completely OK,'' he says, ``and in the other you're a druggie.
They're going to make you wear the scarlet letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes says he ``stands behind'' McGwire. He will be pulling for
him to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Barnes says, he feels empathy with the home-run
hero. He shares a particular pain at the foul publicity that
McGwire has been getting because of taking andro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a marvelous career,'' the Olympic champion says.
``But the thing I'm fighting for most is my reputation _ and how my
sport is going to remember me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not, he hopes, with a scarlet letter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
