<SLUG> BC-FBC-AGGIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M'S DEFENSIVE LINEMEN EAGER TO MAKE PRESENCE FELT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Like most football coaches, Bill
Johnson expects film study from his players. But this request was a
little different.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of breaking down the blocking techniques of upcoming
opponents, the Texas A&AMP;M defensive line coach wanted his troops to
examine the uppercuts of Sylvester Stallone. During two-a-days,
``Rocky'' became required viewing for Aggies' defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the pop quiz. Johnson asked players the lesson to be
learned from Rocky Balboa, Philadelphia street bum turned
heavyweight boxing contender.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, no one who will suit up for the 14th-ranked Aggies in
tomorrow's Kickoff Classic against second-ranked Florida State in
East Rutherford, N.J. offered the correct response.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all talked about how tough he was,'' Johnson said. ``But
that's not the point. The story of ``Rocky'' is how a guy from
nowhere took advantage of an opportunity and turned some heads in
the big city. That's what our defensive line is going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With no returning starters from last year's 9-4 team, A&AMP;M's
defensive line is cloaked in anonymity. Three sophomores, led by
the aptly named Rocky Bernard, are expected to make their first
career starts. They have combined for 37 tackles at the college
level, almost half by Bernard (17).
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum is realistic about what to expect when
defensive ends Bernard (6-foot-3, 269 pounds) and Ron Flemons (6-5,
247) join nose guard Ron Edwards (6-3, 262) in locking horns with a
Flordia State offensive line that averages 315 pounds per man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect all three of them will be in shock after the first
series,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   How well they respond, Slocum said, will tell a lot about what
the Aggies can expect from their guys in the defensive trenches in
1998. The three starters, as well as the top four reserves, were
all members of A&AMP;M's 1997 signing class. They lack size and
experience but have ample quickness, strength and desire, in
Johnson's estimation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent level is not a question in my mind,'' Johnson said.
``We've got plenty of athletic ability. Whether our personnel will
execute what we call, that's the biggest factor. If we can do that,
we'll hold our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Assignment busts have decreased daily during two-a-days, Johnson
said. But coaches remain curious about what will happen when
Bernard (17 tackles, 2 sacks), Edwards (11 tackles) and Flemons (9
tackles) perform together as a group for the first time under game
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest. They're not going to play their best career
games the first time out,'' Johnson said. ``But to hit a home run,
you've got to step up to the plate. We'll have a lot better idea
where we stand when this game is over.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, said Johnson, the situation is similar to 1994.
That year, an all-newcomer defensive line opened the season at LSU
and an unheralded performer named Brandon Mitchell registered three
sacks and three tackles for losses in an 18-13 victory. A&AMP;M
finished the season 10-0-1, in large part because of breakthrough
years from Mitchell and nose guard Edward Jasper, who were
considered question marks during fall drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of similarities between this group and that
group,'' Johnson said. ``But I'd say we have more quality depth
now. In the past, we've only been comfortable playing three or four
guys, for the most part. This year, we'll have seven or eight guys
that can play at a pretty high level without a lot of dropoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of that pack are Bernard, Flemons and Edwards. While
outsiders raise questions, they express confidence in each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what kind of abilities we have and I expect us to
surprise some people,'' Flemons said. ``Besides, when you look
around around the locker room, there's no one left. You ask
yourself, `If not me, then who?' That gets you excited to know it's
up to you to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the Aggies' defensive line has the potential to
rank among the nation's best ``if not by the end of this year, then
by next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard anticipates a quicker introduction to Elite Street. In
his personal version of ``Rocky'', he visualizes recording a couple
of sacks in an upset of Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it every night before I go to sleep,'' Bernard
said. ``People call us question marks, but I think they're wrong.
We'll be a dominating force by the end of the year. As time goes
on, we'll be recognized as one of the great defensive lines in
college football.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Rocky Balboa, another former unknown, ultimately
emerged as an American movie icon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
