A1357 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-TEX     08-31 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESSING SAMPRAS' NET VALUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pete Sampras has vanquished all comers, and stands as the
unquestioned king of his generation of tennis players.
</P>
<P>
   He has beaten Ivan Lendl and Andre Agassi to win the U.S. Open.
He has beaten Boris Becker to win Wimbledon. He beat the best of
the day when he arrived on the scene as a teen-ager, and he
continues to beat the pretenders to the throne as a 27-year-old
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Only one foe remains.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras begins the quest for his fifth U.S. Open crown tomorrow
in New York. Across the net will stand flesh-and-blood players, but
if he can defeat them, Sampras will stand face-to-face with the
toughest opponent of them all: history.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Open championship would allow Sampras to stake a claim as
the best ever. It would be his 12th singles title in a Grand Slam
tournament, tying Roy Emerson for the most ever. He is tied with
Rod Laver and Bjorn Borg for second.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll certainly go down as one of the greatest players,'' said
Tony Trabert, who has been involved in tennis as a player, coach
and broadcaster since 1950. ``Whether he'll go down as the best
remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   History will be difficult to conquer. It has the relentless
attack of Laver, the strategy of Bill Tilden, the shotmaking of
John McEnroe, the booming serve of Pancho Gonzalez, the service
return of Jimmy Connors, the endurance and grit of Emerson, the
backcourt game of Borg, the backhand of Ken Rosewall, the strength
of Lew Hoad, the power of Jack Kramer and the work ethic of Ivan
Lendl.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras counters with a pretty good game of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a big serve, first and second,'' Trabert said. ``His
backhand isn't great, but it's good enough. He has a good forehand.
And, like most champions, he doesn't like to lose. He has a
tremendous ability to make a shot when he needs to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras clearly is a great player.
</P>
<P>
   Is he the greatest?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good question,'' said Brian Gottfried, the French
Open finalist in 1977. ``It is really a different day and age now
than when we were playing and growing up and even the generation
before. Players are different, the equipment is different, the
conditions are different. So I think it's really hard to compare.
You can say one thing and I can say another, and neither is right
or wrong. You can have a good sports discussion, but really it's
just two guys talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who is talking, any discussion of the best ever
will include the same names.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras clearly belongs in the debate. His 11 majors and
five-year reign atop the computer rankings leave no room for
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Sampras has an amazing amount of talent,'' said
Johan Kriek, a contemporary of Borg, Connors, McEnroe and Lendl.
``To have won that amount of grand slams is amazing. Sampras has
had a tremendous run at the top. He's a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Laver is also. The 5-foot-8, 145-pound Australian ``Rocket''
twice won the Grand Slam, winning all four of the majors _ the
Australian Open, French Open, Wimbledon and the U.S. Open _ in 1962
and again in '69. Don Budge (1938) is the only other man to win the
Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Laver turned pro after winning the Grand Slam in '62,
effectively locking himself out of the four majors until the open
era dawned in 1968. He won Wimbledon that year, and achieved his
second Slam the next.
</P>
<P>
   Had Laver remained in the amateur ranks, he easily could have
won an unreachable 20 or more Grand Slam titles. But prior to 1968,
pro players were not eligible to compete in the slam events.
</P>
<P>
   The best-ever discussion also must include Emerson, who won more
majors than anyone else. Ten of his 12 came while some of the best
players of his day toiled in the pro ranks, but he did beat Laver
in the final of the U.S. and Australian Opens in '61.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion of the best ever also would have to include ``Big
Bill'' Tilden, who dominated the amateur ranks in the '20s before
turning pro; Kramer, the best player of the '40s; and Gonzalez,
whose resume lacks an abundance of majors only because he turned
pro in 1950 at age 21.
</P>
<P>
   The short list wouldn't be complete without Borg, Connors,
McEnroe and Lendl, the best players from the mid-1970s until the
late-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played it was Lendl, Borg, McEnroe and Connors,'' said
Kriek, who won the Australian Open in '81 and '82. ``At various
stages these guys dominated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the arguments against Sampras being the best
ever is the ease with which he has dominated his era. He lacks a
true rival who could challenge his supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect foil for Sampras should have been Andre Agassi, but
injuries and inconsistency have taken his game from giddying
heights to unbelievable depths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that hurt tennis in the last five years is the
Agassi-Sampras thing never materialized,'' Kriek said. ``Agassi was
on top, then he was gone for a couple of years. When he comes back
and beats Sampras, Sampras has to deal with him. It's probably
something that could work on his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The other argument against Sampras is he never has won the
French Open, the only major played on clay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think he'll be the best ever, others say he's
never won on clay,'' said Trabert, who won five titles in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The other knock against Sampras is he isn't always at his best
in non-major tournaments _ he was booed for a lack of effort in
losing in a U.S. Open warm-up in New Haven, Conn. _ and his
conditioning isn't the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure he's in good enough shape to win the U.S. Open,''
Trabert said. ``I wish he worked harder off the court so he'd be
more fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his results clearly stamp him as an all-time great.
</P>
<P>
   But best ever?
</P>
<P>
   As in most of these debates _ Jack Nicklaus or Arnold Palmer?
Muhammad Ali or Joe Louis? Michael Jordan or Magic Johnson? Willie
Mays or Babe Ruth? _ there can't be a clear answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players all have strengths and they all have weaknesses,''
Gottfried said. ``You look at Sampras, and he's got a weakness. You
look at Laver, and he had a weakness. If they played each other,
how would they get around their weakness? The great players find
ways to get to their strengths at critical points in the match. How
would they do that against each other?''
</P>
<P>
   That remains the unanswered question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
