<HEADLINE>
URBAN LEGEND: THE WAY THE COOKIE CRUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Every time the phone rings and the person on the other
end says ``cookie,'' Kitty Broderick just wants to put her head
down on her desk. As the public relations specialist for Neiman
Marcus in Arizona, she has spent years dealing with the fake recipe
legend that refuses to die.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, Neiman Marcus has been plagued by this particular
urban legend. Before that, in the mid-1980s or so, the story was
attached to Mrs. Field's Cookies. And long before that, a similar
urban legend about recipe retaliation involved the
Waldorf-Astoria's Red Velvet Cake.
</P>
<P>
   The outline of the Neiman Marcus story exemplifies all three
legends. A woman is dining in a Neiman Marcus restaurant and orders
the cookies for dessert. She likes them so much that she asks for
the recipe. She is told that it costs ``Two-fifty.'' But when her
Visa bill comes later in the month, she is shocked to find a charge
for the recipe for $250, not $2.50. Her lawyer says she must pay
the bill, but in revenge, she gives the recipe to everybody she
knows, and urges them to circulate it, too.
</P>
<P>
   All this is hopelessly, permanently wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even take Visa,'' Broderick said. ``And we've never
charged for a recipe, ever, in this store or any store. And we
don't make or serve cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's like the cookie recipe that refuses to die. We can
say it until we're blue in the face, and it turns up on the
Internet and everywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Because this particular urban legend urges people to ``spread
the word,'' there are instances where people have received the
recipe via the Internet from more than one source on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail is the fastest growing cookie-myth spreader,''
Broderick said. ``You look at these e-mails and each has been sent
to hundreds of people. There's no stopping this. It's like a bad
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Internet Web sites debunking urban legends
materialized, the major works on urban legends were books by
University of Utah English professor Jan Harold Brunvand. His 1990
``Curses! Broiled Again! The Hottest Urban Legends Going''
theorized that the cookie-recipe hoaxes have their roots in the
Waldorf-Astoria hotel story.
</P>
<P>
   In that one, a woman is billed $1,000 for a recipe for the
hotel's Red Velvet Cake, who gave out the recipe after learning the
hotel chef's ``secret'' ingredient is red food dye.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Neiman Marcus made up a cookie recipe to give out,
``just to be helpful,'' Broderick said. She said she made the
purported recipe once and it wasn't very good.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick is so sick of this myth that she just laughs now, she
said. But her mother called her not long ago to say she attended a
charity auction where one of the items on the block was the Neiman
Marcus Cookie recipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote a letter,'' Broderick said, to tell the group they had
auctioned off a bogus recipe. ``I said, `I hope you got a lot of
money for it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. At least $2.50. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
