<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-EMMITT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNDOWN? NOT COWBOYS' EMMITT SMITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith choked down a
bowl of cereal, then finished off his training-camp dinner with two
peanut butter and jelly sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Midwestern State University dining hall with its
pasta bar and deli depot must have offered more fitting fare for a
three-time NFL rushing champ. Certainly the workhorse of the
Cowboys running game, in his ninth NFL season, must need more
substantial replenishing after two-a-days in the searing Wichita
Falls heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen the food here?'' Smith asked.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, Emmitt Smith never gave his dubious diet a
second thought. He is not in a refueling mode despite public
contention Emmitt is low on fuel after a second consecutive
sub-Smith season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying to say it hasn't been frustrating,'' said Smith,
who limped through a 1997 season that ended with 1,074 yards
rushing (second-lowest in his career) and career-lows of two
100-yard-plus games and four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't become a three-time rushing champion by being a
fluke,'' he continued. ``There is a lot of character and
determination that goes into it. People criticized me before I came
in, saying I was too small and all that. I've been here before. I
got plenty of gas left in my tank and tread on my tires. Don't
think I can't do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the bells and whistles of Cowboys coach Chan Gailey's
new offense, which features five-receiver sets and the shotgun
formation, the Cowboys' plan to move the football is founded on the
principle of a strong ground game. Despite the off-season addition
of former Pro Bowl running back Chris Warren from Seattle, the
Cowboys are counting on Smith to carry the load.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy and spiritually content after rededicating his life to
Christianity last season, Smith said he is ready to prove to his
critics the wear and tear of more than 2,500 career carries have
not left him run down. Smith said there is no merit to accusations
his high number of rushing attempts have taken a toll on him just
as they did legendary Houston Oilers bruiser Earl Campbell, who
experienced a sharp decline at the end of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think there has been a dark cloud over my head the past
two years,'' said Smith, a native of Pensacola, Fla. ``Behind every
dark cloud there is sun. The key is enduring through the dark
cloud. When the sun comes out, there is going to be a new day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys coaches contend Smith can regain the form that
enabled him to top the 1,400-yard season-rushing total five
consecutive years. Like Smith, they blame his diminished output on
the erosion of the Cowboys offensive line and the team's stale
offensive attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of circumstances to Emmitt not having the
year we're all accustomed to Emmitt having,'' said Gailey, who
replaced Barry Switzer as head coach in the off-season and
installed a new offensive attack. ``To put it all on Emmitt, and
say he's down the tubes, that's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey didn't come to that conclusion lightly. He and running
backs coach Clarence Shelmon analyzed Smith's game tapes from 1997
and determined he had the physical tools necessary to be a major
contributor.
</P>
<P>
   Shelmon said Smith has been the victim of his own success and
few players could duplicate the numbers he put up on a yearly
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't hit the wall in my mind,'' said Shelmon, who coached
running backs in Seattle last season. ``Any player that plays that
long, there will be certain amount of wear and tear. By the same
token, from what I saw in his play, there is enough burst, enough
vision, enough instincts that he could still be one of the best
backs in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offensive line for 1998 seems to be improved over
last season because of the off-season signing of guard Everett
McIver, the weight reduction of guard Nate Newton, the addition of
rookie Flozell Adams and the return of fullback Daryl Johnston, who
missed the bulk of last season with a neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   Also key in the Cowboys' assessment of Smith is the new running
scheme in Gailey's offense. The Cowboys' offense is based on zone
blocking, rather than man blocking as in the past. This will
require Smith to be more patient and run more instinctively.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, I've been so accustomed to power football,''
Smith said. ``I would hit the hole and take everything I see. This
offense forces me to let things develop and set things up more. I
have confidence I can succeed in this style. I'm not fast but I got
good vision and some shakes.''
</P>
<P>
   So far so good. In his only significant playing time of the
preseason, Smith rushed 12 times for 110 yards and a touchdown in
the first half against the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   The preseason also proved to be the testing ground for another
Cowboys addition _ running back Warren. Though confident in Smith,
Gailey said the Cowboys needed to bring in another running back in
place of Smith's former backup, Sherman Williams.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Gailey has maintained Warren was brought in
to complement Smith by lessening his load. Gailey said Smith would
be the starter and Warren would be the third-down back and relieve
Smith when tired.
</P>
<P>
   However, Smith's two-year decline, Warren's stature as one of
the league's top runners and his relationship with his former
Seattle coach and friend Shelmon fueled preseason speculation
Warren was here to replace Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith admitted he was initially surprised when the Cowboys
signed Warren, 30, who in eight seasons in Seattle rushed for 6,706
yards and 44 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be tripping and lying if I said it didn't raise my
eyebrows,'' Smith said. ``But I had the feeling it was going to
happen because of the closeness with him and Clarence. It's easy to
think that Clarence might cut for Chris. But I try not to allow
myself to think like that. I understand they are close. But from my
understanding, it's my job unless I get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelmon said his relationship with Warren won't impact on-field
decisions. Warren, who said Shelmon was the reason he came to the
Cowboys, added there is no way he could supplant Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to spell Emmitt and be the third-down guy,'' Warren
said. ``I don't see me coming to take anybody's job. I know my role
and I accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cowboys owner Jerry Jones signed Warren, he said he
envisioned it as an opportunity to be smarter about how the Cowboys
used Smith and to prolong his career. That was originally the plan
with a healthy Warren, but the running back now is expected to miss
four to six weeks with a strained groin. If Warren can return
sometime soon, it could lead to big returns for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a legitimate debate to whether Emmitt's been
overused,'' Jones said. ``People have always questioned whether we
should be using him as much as we have. The name of the game is
managing his time, so we have the best of Emmitt at the right
juncture of the season and hopefully extend his career in the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he does run out, Smith said he is prepared. And though
he said the past couple of years have been a struggle because he's
seen the true side of people who have abandoned him during the down
times, he said he's better for the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's opened my eyes,'' Smith said. ``You find out quickly who
is truly behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, one of three Cowboys who were baptized along with
cornerback Deion Sanders after a game last season, said he's
endured because he's leaned on his faith and allowed his
relationship with Christ to take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has allowed me to see things differently in stressful
times,'' Smith said. ``I think that helped me out a great deal. I
found great comfort in my faith rather than try to figure things
out for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   What Smith no longer is trying to figure out is where he fits in
history among NFL running backs and how he will end his career.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered a threat to break Walter Payton's NFL rushing
record of 16,726 yards, Smith is a longshot after the past two
subpar seasons that have left him at 11,234 yards and needing
another five 1,000-yard-plus seasons to catch Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a distant goal, but I'm nowhere close to it,'' Smith
said. ``I'm going to take it one day at a time, one year at a time.
If I get closer to it, then it becomes a real goal again.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith can make a run at some other high-water marks. With 1,079
yards rushing, he would break into the NFL's all-time top five.
With 12 rushing touchdowns, he would eclipse Marcus Allen's NFL
career record of 123. And with 803 yards, he would supplant Hall of
Famer Tony Dorsett as the team's all-time leader rusher.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said he won't hang around just to try to break the
record if he's not being productive. He said he would like to play
out the remaining five years on his contract and finish his career
as a Cowboy. However, considering that he is expected to earn $25
million in base salary over the next five years, the salary cap
situation and the fact that the Cowboys might go through a
rebuilding process, Smith said anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Still baffled his toughness was questioned last season after
bruised ribs and other injuries forced him from four games when
they ``didn't question it when my arm was hanging off against the
Giants in 1993,'' Smith said nothing would surprise him. He rushed
for 168 yards in that game, despite playing the entire second half
with a separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't rule out anything,'' Smith said. ``Maybe the Cowboys
might want to make a major change. I would love to finish out my
career here. But I'm not going to be a fool and think it's a
guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said if the Cowboys decided to go in another direction and
he wasn't ready to quit he would consider playing somewhere in his
home state of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how it turns out this year or in the future, Smith
said he's at peace with himself and his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not content,'' Smith said. ``I would like to get another
1,500 or 1,600-yard season. But the main thing I want to do is do
my job and keep getting better. I know I've given my all to the
Cowboys. As long as continue to do that, I can look in the mirror
and say, `Job well done, you have run your race, you have finished
your course.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
