</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITESOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELE, RODRIGUEZ LIFT RANGERS PAST WHITE SOX, 5-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Two starting pitchers found themselves in deep trouble
in the sixth inning yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Aaron Sele found a way to keep the Chicago White
Sox from scoring. White Sox pitcher Mike Sirotka couldn't do the
same, then blamed his defense afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Sele's fortitude proved the difference in a hard-fought
nationally televised game that the Rangers won, 5-3, at Comiskey
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sirotka had a 3-1 lead going to the sixth, but the Rangers
rallied by putting together some intense at-bats and went ahead on
Ivan Rodriguez's three-run homer. Sele kept them in front by
striking out three consecutive hitters after walking Frank Thomas
and giving up a single to Albert Belle to start the Chicago sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron turned it up a notch, got ahead of the hitters and put
them away,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Sele has done that lately while winning his past three starts.
He also did that early in the season with an 11-4 start that put
him on the American League All-Star team. However, during a
nine-game, midsummer slump, Sele lost six of eight decisions
because he couldn't pitch out of trouble. The Rangers, who trail
Anaheim by two games in the AL West, couldn't afford another lapse
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For everything people have said about the way I've been
pitching, it just seems like I've been one pitch away a lot of
times and haven't been able to make that pitch,'' Sele said. ``It
just a case of you have to keep trying to make quality pitches. You
can do that sometimes, sometimes you can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele did yesterday after surviving a rough first inning in which
the White Sox scored their three runs. Sele got the trouble started
when he dropped a short flip from first baseman Will Clark on Mike
Caruso's one-out grounder. Doubles by Thomas, Belle and Ventura
then gave the White Sox a 3-0 lead. It could have been worse but
the defense rescued Sele.
</P>
<P>
   After Greg Norton struck out, Magglio Ordonez lined a single to
left. Rusty Greer charged the ball hard then made a strong throw to
the plate. Ventura beat the throw, but Rodriguez blocked the plate
and made the tag for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was a big play,'' Rodriguez said. ``Rusty made a
great throw, a nice one bounce and that gave me time to block the
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele took it from there, allowing only two hits and two walks
during the next seven innings. The only trouble was in the sixth,
but he struck out Ventura, Norton and Ordonez. Ordonez was 8-for-9
this season against Sele before that strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed him to turn it around after the first,'' Oates said.
``We needed some innings from him. You couldn't ask anything more
from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele said his goal was to keep it close, ``because you know our
offense just needs time.''
</P>
<P>
   That proved true in the top of the sixth. Sirotka had held the
Rangers to four hits through five innings, but Mark McLemore led
off with a blooper to left that fell in front of Belle. Greer then
reached on a one-out infield single, a grounder into the right side
hole that second baseman Ray Durham knocked down with a diving
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Sirotka thought both balls should have been outs, a debatable
point each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sele had all the plays made for him,'' Sirotka said afterward.
``When you give extra outs to a team like that, it's going to
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   That part was true. Juan Gonzalez worked the count full and
lined a single to left that drove in McLemore. Will Clark also
singled to left, but Belle got to the ball quickly and threw out
Greer trying to score.
</P>
<P>
   However that was only a temporary reprieve for Sirotka.
Rodriguez dug out a low curveball and smacked it over the
left-field wall to give the Rangers a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was only one pitch that I'd take back, and that was the
one to'' Rodriguez, Sirotka said. ``It was still a pretty good
pitch. We just couldn't quite make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele needed no such excuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
