<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-LATECH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA DUMPS LOUISIANA TECH, 56-27
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ Frank Solich conceded that he was relieved to
finally get his first game as a head coach out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   File this debut under ``successful but shaky.'' Nebraska's
offense appears healthy, but its defense might need some help.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska made Solich a winner with a 56-27 triumph against
Louisiana Tech in the Eddie Robinson Classic yesterday. However,
the Bulldogs rolled up 590 yards passing and wide receiver Troy
Edwards set an NCAA record with 405 receiving yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only interested in the win,'' Solich said when learning of
Louisiana Tech's gaudy statistics. ``For a first game, it was OK.
I'm satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years, Tom Osborne wasn't on the sidelines for a
Nebraska game. He was not in attendance, preferring to take care of
``personal business'' rather than serve as a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska's first play under Solich, a former Cornhuskers
fullback, was pure vanilla. Two tight ends, I formation, fullback
Joel Mackovicka up the middle for 12 yards. Solich had joked that
his first play call would be a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   He saved that for the third play. Sophomore quarterback Bobby
Newcombe hit tight end Sheldon Jackson down the middle for a
46-yard touchdown. It took the Cornhuskers 39 seconds to score
their first 1998 touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first quarter, Nebraska had 174 yards to
Louisiana Tech's 14. When the Bulldogs scored their first touchdown
to make it 21-6, Nebraska responded with a 99-yard kickoff return
by Joe Walker of Lamar High School.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half, Louisiana Tech's throw-it-every-time
offense started to wear out the Cornhuskers in the 90-degree heat.
Quarterback Tim Rattay was 46-of-68 for 590 yards and four
touchdowns; Edwards had 21 receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They passed all over us in the second half,'' defensive end
Chad Kelsay said. ``Rattay gets the ball off fast and with that
three-step drop, we had trouble getting any pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe was impressive in his first start. He completed nine of
10 passes for 168 yards and was solid running the option. And
sophomore I-back Correll Buckhalter had 143 yards rushing and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers totaled 462 yards, a typical day at the offense.
But that paled when compared to the work of the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Solich described the second half as ``sloppy.'' Nebraska went to
the locker room with a 35-6 lead, but the expected 50-point rout
never developed. Edwards' three long touchdowns in the second half
kept the 76,021 at Memorial Stadium/Tom Osborne Field uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win's a win,'' Kelsay said. ``But we've got a lot of work to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of it on the defensive side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
