</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-JILTED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF PLAYING OUT DREAM, FRESHMAN JILTED BY TCU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JEFF SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The TCU baseball cap Brian Brookhart once
wore lies abandoned in the corner of his bedroom. The picture of
him sitting on the TCU Superfrog's lap at his fourth birthday party
also has been discarded.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brookhart hasn't found a way to erase the picture in
his Crowley High School yearbook of his sister, Ashlie, and him
wearing TCU sweatshirts. Even more painful is the caption that
reads, ``Go Frogs.''
</P>
<P>
   While Brookhart is able to rid himself of each physical reminder
of his lifelong love affair with TCU, the mental images linger. The
memories of a nightmare that began 17 days ago, one day before
Brookhart was to register for classes and officially begin living
his dream of playing college basketball for his hometown school.
The day it was suggested to him by assistant coach Brian Fish that
he'd be better off not coming to TCU this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the perfect story and that day, the dream just went
away,'' says Ashlie, a TCU senior who was a cheerleader for the
men's basketball team for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Brookhart, 18, now a part-time TCU student looking to
transfer, had his dream swept away by the cold reality of Division
I athletics, where education and the ``college experience'' often
lose out to athletic interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd graduate from TCU with a good education and some
great memories from playing basketball, but I guess I've had my
first experience with how the real world works,'' Brian says.
</P>
<P>
   The experience has angered the Brookhart family and left the TCU
coaching staff red-faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I underestimated how important being at TCU right away was to
him,'' Fish says. ``It wasn't about academics or trying to ruin his
dream, I was just trying to be honest. I gave him my advice that a
junior college would speed up the progress of his game. I feel bad
for Brian and I feel bad for myself. I've been sick about the whole
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Billy Tubbs, who was out of town when the first
meeting with Brookhart and Fish took place, takes responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for Brian, but we were just suggesting a junior
college would be best for him. When we signed him, I knew he wasn't
an impact player, but in a few years, I thought he could make a
contribution. ... Looking back, I wish I could've talked with him,
but once his father stepped in and went above our heads, there was
nothing I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookhart's father, Pete, disagrees, saying Tubbs should have
rectified the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think all programs work like this but the system
allows people to manipulate it,'' he said. ``I hold Mr. Tubbs
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   When he signed a scholarship with TCU last November, Brookhart
had no doubt the next four years would be the most memorable of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't expect to be a star, at least not right away. He spent
the summer working out virtually every day, trying to add weight
and muscle to his slender frame. A good student, he wanted to earn
his bachelor's degree in business and pursue a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   After an early morning haircut Aug. 13, he stopped by the
family's house in the Overton South section of Fort Worth. His
mother, Joanne _ who received her master's degree from TCU in 1987
_ informed him Fish had called and asked for Brian to stop by the
office that afternoon. Brookhart was about to depart for the first
day of freshman orientation. Since Fish was the coach responsible
for recruiting Brookhart for TCU, Brookhart said he thought nothing
of Fish's request.
</P>
<P>
   Brookhart arrived in Fish's office around 1 p.m. and noticed
Fish was speaking to someone from Collin County Community College.
After he hung up, Fish told Brookhart he needed to talk about the
upcoming season. Fish explained that Brookhart could do one of two
things, either enroll in a junior college _ Fish's suggestion was
Collin County _ or redshirt his freshman season and receive little
or no practice time with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Players who redshirt, or sit out a season without losing
eligibility, typically practice with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that with Lee Nailon not going to the NBA like we
expected that everyone would move down the depth chart at the
`five' position and that a junior college would allow him to become
a better player,'' says Fish, who admits he would have chosen
different words were he allowed to have the discussion again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand,'' Brookhart says. ``They told me during
the recruiting process that redshirting was a possibility, and that
was fine with me, but this really shocked me. I didn't know what to
do. Why would I go to a junior college when I didn't have to?''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Brookhart gave his oral commitment to TCU in
October, several other Division I schools had offered him
scholarships. If he had waited for the spring signing period, he
undoubtedly would have gotten more offers. The 6-foot-10, 215-pound
center helped lead Crowley to a school-record 23 victories while
averaging 17 points and nine rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   From that first conversation, events unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling TCU didn't want him and knowing he wouldn't get practice
time, Brookhart discussed the situation with his family. He decided
not to register at TCU as scheduled on Friday. His father,
meanwhile, wanted answers as to why, on the eve of the school year,
TCU wanted Brian to attend a junior college. He put in phone calls
to athletic director Eric Hyman, Chancellor Michael Ferrari and
Tubbs.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Brookhart was assured Brian's scholarship would be
honored, but if Brian wanted to transfer, he would be forced to sit
out the 1999-2000 season because of NCAA rules. If Brookhart
remained at TCU as a full-time student _ even if he wasn't involved
with the basketball team _ he would be under a basketball
scholarship, meaning NCAA rules would prevent him from playing
elsewhere next season.
</P>
<P>
   Another option was not enrolling and looking elsewhere for a
scholarship. But Brian didn't want to fall behind academically and
his parents had not prepared for paying their son's college
education this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman offered a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   TCU would grant Brian a release from his basketball scholarship
and Brian could attend TCU as a part-time student this fall and
possibly next spring. He would get his tuition and books paid for
using non-athletic department funds, which is legal according to
NCAA rules. By taking only nine hours of classes, Brookhart would
be eligible to play basketball anywhere during the 1999-2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't make Brookhart happy, but, after talking with his
family, he agreed it was his best option. At least he would get
some schooling paid for and retain his options to play basketball
next season at a Division I school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with the Brookhart family last week and I understood
their concerns,'' Ferrari said. ``I am disappointed how this
particular instance was handled and think it would have been more
effective and appropriate if Brian's options were presented to him
at an earlier time. Coach Tubbs also should have been there for
that first meeting and I have spoken to him and my athletic
director about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyman refers to the episode as a ``misunderstanding between the
basketball staff and the Brookhart family.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Brookhart has not spoken to Tubbs since before his meeting
with Fish. He said he will not follow the Frogs this season, except
for looking for how his friends do in the box score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame the system and the individual,'' Brian says. ``It's
the system's fault because if it had done its job, this wouldn't
have been able to happen and it's the individual's fault because if
(Tubbs) didn't want this to happen, it wouldn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   In choosing his new school, Brookhart says he'll do more
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say that I wouldn't look back on this when the
recruiting process starts again, but I know that I'll be more
careful to look into how things work at each school and how they
treat their players.''
</P>
<P>
   Now only if the Superfrog would make one final visit _ this one
into Brookhart's closet _ and take the remaining TCU memorabilia.
Then there would be nothing left.
</P>
<P>
   They've already taken his heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
