<HEADLINE>
FORTUNATELY, TOM HICKS DOESN'T FIT THE MOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned about the Texas Rangers? You are not alone. So is Tom
Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   Excited about the Dallas Stars? Then join Tom Hicks in eager
anticipation of another NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   Heard the rumor about Hicks preparing to also buy the Dallas
Mavericks? Not so quick there. Actually, he and Junior Perot are
even on civil terms these days.
</P>
<P>
   But now for a personal note. As a jock-world franchise owner,
Hicks continues to be bad for business _ my kind of business.
</P>
<P>
   Sports-page columnists of this era greatly depend on rich-guy
team owners like Hicks to provide us with an easy work day. Just
sit back, wait, watch and listen. A juicy column, heavy on rip
jobs, will eventually be dropped right into your lap-top.
</P>
<P>
   Know what I mean, Mr. Jones?
</P>
<P>
   Or as the late great Burt Hawkins once said of a former Rangers'
owner, ``he runs his company with brainpower and his baseball team
with ego. How can he be that smart, yet not smart enough to know
the difference?''
</P>
<P>
   But thus far _ and I do stress ``thus far'' _ Hicks has defied
the stereotype, the logic, the whole package of what normally
happens when the highly successful businessman ventures into sports
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of waiting, watching and listening, that has been the
Hicks method. He's going on three years as owner of the Stars, and
three months as the official owner of the Rangers. Hicks stays
plugged in, but he also stays out of the way. What happens with
most owners in sports is they become fans, and they start to think
like fans, and throw around their opinions like fans. The next
thing you know, the owner is saying he's in charge of everything,
even socks and jocks.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, so far, stops way short. He's a hockey fan and a baseball
fan. Large-time. For that matter, he's also a football and
basketball fan. But beyond that, he waits, watches and listens to
the Bob Gaineys, the Ken Hitchcocks, the Doug Melvins, the Johnny
Oates.
</P>
<P>
   According to his baseball and hockey people, they know the hard
questions are coming when they privately go to Hicks with an
``idea.'' That usually means, of course, an idea that involves
spending more money. Provide all the right answers for Hicks, and
...
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull happens. The Rangers' trading deadline deal of a
month ago happens. A much-needed bouncer for the Stars happens.
Additional payroll expense happens. Locally, Hicks continues to
expand his reputation as a whatever-it-takes-to-win owner.
</P>
<P>
   But before departing Sunday morning for a business trip to South
America, Hicks was asked to comment on a variety of sports-related
topics.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his answers:
</P>
<P>
   On the Rangers' divisional race: ``Yeah, I'm a little concerned.
We certainly have our lapses when it comes to what seems to be
mental toughness. Defense, pitching, timely hitting _ every area
has been affected. But let this last month play out, and let's see
where we are. A lot is going to depend on how we do between now and
the end of September.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Hicks already looking ahead and planning for next season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Do the plans include pitching help?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he repeated.
</P>
<P>
   On the buying the Mavericks rumor: ``I don't think it's a secret
I tried to buy the team once before,'' Hicks said. ``Ross and I at
one time even tried to find a way to have joint ownership. But
things have gone in a different direction since. I'm very happy
with that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with Ross on the new arena, that's gone real well.
Hillwood \RPerot's company\S is the developer and they are doing a
great job. From what I see, this will be the best indoor arena in
the country, plus the development around the arena is going to be
something that benefits Dallas and the whole area.''
</P>
<P>
   On last week's signing of Brent Severyn as the Stars'
long-awaited tough guy: ``We absolutely had to have that,'' said
Hicks. ``In player personnel, it was the last piece of the puzzle.
Now, will everything fit into a team thing? I can't wait until we
get started so we can find out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, it would not be a surprise if Hicks adds the
Mavericks to his ownership cartel. But of more immediate interest
will be the baseball off-season, no matter if the current Rangers
win a divisional title or not. Remember, Hicks didn't officially
take over the baseball team until June.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has financed the Stars into a championship-caliber team,
and he has even more reason to do so with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Above all else, however, Hicks has also taken the poison out of
newspaper pens. Whatever he's done, he's done it right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
