<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU READY FOR SEASON-OPENER AGAINST IOWA STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ After nearly three weeks and more practices
than he cares to count, TCU offensive tackle Michael Keathley is
ready for something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a nice change to get after some new people,''
he said. ``We've worked hard, and we've pushed each other like you
wouldn't believe in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like we're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione has the same inkling but says he
can't be certain until Saturday, when the Horned Frogs travel to
Iowa State for their season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we are ready to play a game, but we're ready
to find out though,'' Franchione said. ``We're probably at a point
where we have to play a game to really get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a 1-10 season, the Frogs had plenty of room to
improve but also had several questions to answer. With only four
days of practice left before the season opener, here is how the
coaching staff has addressed many of the pressing issues they faced
heading into two-a-days:
</P>
<P>
   The staff appears to have settled on a starting offensive line
for the opener, with tackles Keathley and Russ Sanders, guards
Robert Wallace and Jeff Millican, and center Shane Ladewig.
Redshirt freshman guard Victor Payne had been an early favorite to
start, but a turf-toe injury sidelined him much of two-a-days.
Senior Greg Davis should vie for a starting job once his one-year
suspension is completed after the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Converted receiver Patrick Batteaux will be the Horned Frogs'
starting quarterback. His speed, quickness and understanding of the
offense gave him an edge in spring practice, and he never let the
others catch up. Two-year starter Jeff Dover and Kevin Colon are
battling for the backup spot.
</P>
<P>
   An injury to senior linebacker Cody Mortensen has prolonged the
battle for the starting inside linebacker job. Sophomore Shannon
Brazzell has performed admirably in Mortensen's place, and the
coaching must choose the starter opposite senior Joseph Phipps.
</P>
<P>
   In the defensive backfield, only the strong safety spot remains
unresolved. Sophomore Russell Gary has looked good since Eric
Anderson went down with a career-ending neck injury. Gary is
competing with Barry Browning, who seemed to bounce back this week
from nagging injuries and a change from cornerback to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione has said he would like to redshirt all of his
freshmen, but he won't this season. Tight end B.J. Roberts could
start the season opener depending on the offense's first alignment.
Former Wyatt star Jason Goss has made the transition from receiver
to defensive back smoothly this summer and will compete for time,
and Frank Montgomery or LaTarence Dunbar should emerge as the third
tailback. Joey Biasatti from Burleson is set to handle the kickoff
duties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
