<SLUG> BC-FBC-KICKOFF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITLE SERIES REDUCES PRESSURE AT KICKOFF CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Some years, Florida State coach Bobby
Bowden admits, he has turned a deaf ear to promoters seeking to
include his Seminoles in a high-profile contest to open the college
football season.
</P>
<P>
   But not this year. With the inaugural Bowl Championship Series a
reality in January, Bowden said some of the risk has been removed
from rolling the dice against a fellow heavyweight in August.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason Bowden agreed to bring his second-ranked
Seminoles to Giants Stadium for Monday's 7 p.m. meeting with No. 14
Texas A&AMP;M in the 16th annual Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever loses this game still has a chance to win the national
championship,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden bases that belief on the advent of the Bowl Championship
Series, which will use a four-part formula to match the top two
teams in college football Jan. 4 in the Fiesta Bowl. Part of the
formula is strength of schedule, which both teams will be enhancing
Monday by squaring off on national television.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the year, there's a good chance that everyone
might have a loss,'' Bowden said. ``With them matching No. 1
against No. 2, you're still in the running, even if you lose. Plus,
you've played an extra game against a quality team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year we won the national championship (1993) was the last
time we played in a game like this. We were 12-1 and Notre Dame was
11-1. At the end of the year, that one extra game can make the
difference. People see that and think a 12-1 might be better than
an 11-1. That's the plus side.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside is a history that shows the Kickoff Classic has
hardly been a springboard to glory for the team that loses. While
all of the game's 15 winners _ including two national champions _
went on to earn spots in the final rankings released by The
Associated Press, only four teams that lost the Kickoff Classic
were in the Top 25 at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the past eight teams to begin the season with a loss in
Giants Stadium have been shut out at the ballot box in January.
That tends to shoot holes in Bowden's theory that Monday's loser
will remain in the national championship hunt. But Bowden insists
the Bowl Championship Series provides a safety net unavailable to
previous participants.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said he has not spent much time
pondering the championship implications for his team, win or lose
against the Seminoles. As a two-touchdown underdog, he is more
interested in making sure the Aggies remain on an even keel after
the contest, regardless of the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of downside for us, no matter what happens.
No one is going to be shocked if we lose,'' Slocum said. ``But if
we win, we have a considerable upside. It would be a huge lift for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   That stands in marked contrast to 1996, when A&AMP;M opened the
season with a 41-37 loss to Brigham Young in the Pigskin Classic.
The Aggies ``rebounded'' three weeks later with a
confidence-shattering loss against Southwestern Louisiana, 29-22,
and stumbled home at 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said a shorter break between games (A&AMP;M plays again Sept.
12) and a more mature nucleus of players should prevent a repeat of
the team's 1996 collapse if his team falls in another August
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're further along mentally than we were two years ago,''
Slocum said. ``There's not a fragile nature about this team. We're
not going to roll out there and be in awe of Florida State. No
matter what happens, we're not going to get killed off by these
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M linebacker Dat Nguyen agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team we had two years ago wasn't nearly as focused as the
one we have now,'' said Nguyen, a fifth-year senior and four-year
starter. ``What happened against BYU, there's not a danger of that
happening again. We're not going to let one game ruin our season.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor would they let a victory swell their egos, quarterback
Branndon Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing this game for the challenge,'' Stewart said.
``When people talk about the top five teams in college football, we
want our name thrown in there. And right now, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you beat a big-name team, people won't talk about you or
vote you very high in the polls. And once you beat somebody good,
you've got to be able to follow it up and be consistent or they'll
forget about you real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   National-championship ramifications, at this juncture, seem
premature to A&AMP;M coaches and players. They simply seek consistency
and respect. Bowden, on the other hand, has an eye on the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got more to lose. We're favored,'' Bowden said.
``They'll climb high if they win, and we'll drop far if we lose.
But we won't disappear, no matter what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not. But if Monday's loser rebounds to finish in the Top
25, that team will be plowing fresh ground for a Kickoff Classic
participant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
