<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLORADO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO COACH GETS TOUGH IN HIS APPROACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Neuheisel worked his way up from a walk-on to a Rose Bowl
most-valuable-player quarterback at UCLA. After a 20-4 record in
his first two seasons as a college head coach, Neuheisel appeared
to have a golden touch.
</P>
<P>
   But Neuheisel understands how soon prospects become suspects.
And he knows that his coaching position at Colorado is under
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the lessons I learned last season is you don't inherit
success,'' Neuheisel said. ``You come to expect winning and the
fruits of that winning, instead of remembering the ingredients. I
experienced that firsthand, and hopefully the lesson has been
learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the Buffaloes were expected to be a top-10 team;
``The Sporting News'' picked Colorado as its preseason No. 1. But
after a humbling 27-3 loss at eventual co-national champion
Michigan, the Buffs played like Biffs, finishing 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never recuperated from that game,'' linebacker Hannibal
Navies said. ``Colorado teams in the past played through adversity,
no matter the situation. Last year, we didn't do that. That's got
to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel, 37, basked in the glory of 10-victory seasons in his
first two years. His New Age coaching style, which emphasized
happy-happy, joy-joy, appeared to be a perfect fit in Boulder, an
idyllic college town.
</P>
<P>
   But let the penalties mount, the mental mistakes multiply, and
the fans and media quickly pointed out that Neuheisel was too soft,
that he wasn't a strict disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone from two years of having people saying, `Please
stay' to having people say, `Please go' after last season,''
Neuheisel said with a laugh. ``I've learned to gain perspective.
I'm not as good as everybody thought I was, and I'm not as bad as
everybody thought I was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outsiders will look at this as a big point in my career. In
this profession, you learn to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Buffaloes ranked 69th nationally in rushing
offense and 97th in rushing defense. Both statistics were evidence
that Colorado had lost its toughness. In off-season meetings with
his staff, Neuheisel decided a get-tough policy was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mistake I made last year was basically giving starting jobs
to seniors just because they were seniors,'' he said. ``This year,
we opened up every position on the team in the spring. All the kids
fought for jobs, and I think that will make us a better football
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The most bitter battle was at quarterback. Neuheisel picked Mike
Moschetti, a junior-college transfer, as the starter. Junior Jeremy
Weisinger, who thought he had earned the job, has announced he will
transfer to Texas A&AMP;M. Sophomore Adam Bledsoe, Drew's younger
brother, is the backup, but Neuheisel has to be careful that
Bledsoe doesn't grow disenchanted, as Weisinger did.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado faces a difficult opener Saturday against Colorado
State in Denver. The Rams opened the season Saturday with a 23-16
victory against Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot as far as setting the tone for our season,''
Navies said. ``Obviously, they're going to be ranked ahead of us.
We have a lot to prove to the nation, that we are back. It's more
than our first game. It means the season for us, basically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
