<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS AN URBAN LEGEND? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Some urban legends arise from current concerns, such
as the spread of AIDS. Others use exaggeration to illustrate a
moral. According to the Urban Legends Archive
(www.urbanlegends.com), an urban legend:
</P>
<P>
   _ Appears mysteriously and spreads spontaneously in varying
forms.
</P>
<P>
   _Contains elements of humor and horror (the horror often
``punishes'' someone who flouts society's conventions).
</P>
<P>
   _ Makes good storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does not have to be false, although most are. Urban legends
often have a basis in fact, but it's their life-after-the-fact
(particularly in reference to the second and third points) that
gives them particular interest. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
