A1379 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     08-31 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF IT'S ILLEGAL FOR SOME TO BUY GUNS, WHY AREN'T THEY BEHIND BARS
FOR TRYING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was growing up in the rural Southwest, there was usually
a .22-caliber rifle around somewhere _ in the trunk or the gun
rack. Maybe a pistol under the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Snakes, you know.
</P>
<P>
   And I spent many pleasant Sunday afternoons shooting at bottles
out at the city dump.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is to say that I am comfortable around firearms and
have owned _ and still own _ a fair number. But I'm not a member of
the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   No particular reason, since I generally agree with the NRA about
the Second Amendment, except that I'm not much of a joiner other
than church and, beyond that, I have some difficulty with the more
extreme sides of the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   See, I'm not worried about the government knowing what weapons I
own. I don't mind waiting periods and background checks. I won't
ever need to buy a firearm instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to the Brady Act.
</P>
<P>
   I figure if the law stops even one killing, it's probably
worthwhile. (And no, I don't want to debate this. We're not going
to convince each other, so let's not try.)
</P>
<P>
   But every time we write about the Brady Act and include the
number of people rejected since its passage that the Clinton
administration is throwing around, I get calls asking a very
legitimate question:
</P>
<P>
   If it is illegal for certain people to possess handguns, isn't
it also illegal for them to attempt to possess them? And why aren't
those people being prosecuted?
</P>
<P>
   The question as presented may be somewhat disingenuous. It's in
the best interests of the anti-Brady people to prove that the law
is a fruitless waste of time and money _ and, since we obviously
aren't enforcing the laws already on the books, we don't need new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer, says Justice Department spokesman Gregory
King, lies in understanding the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention was not to create a new tool for prosecutors,''
he says. ``It was to keep guns out of the wrong hands. Congress
never intended that every single person who violated the Brady Act
would be prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress didn't appropriate the money to do that, he says. But
there is another issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to prosecute each and every one of those people,
you would tie up the courts and tie up the time and resources of
the prosecutors all over the country,'' King says. Just like with
any other crime, ``prosecutors have to make judgments as to which
crimes to put their resources behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent story in the Fort Worth Star-Telegram cited
figures from the Bureau of Justice Statistics for the years 1994-97
inclusive, saying there were 242,000 rejections out of 10.4 million
attempts to purchase handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA figures that those numbers include rejections from both
Brady Act and Brady-exempt states. States that already had or have
passed laws calling for waiting periods, instant checks or other
restrictive requirements don't fall under Brady. Some of the most
deadly cities in the United States _ New York, for example _ have
never been subject to it. Twenty-three states are covered
presently.
</P>
<P>
   If you are on the list of people prohibited from buying a
handgun by the Federal Gun Control Act of 1968, you'd have to lie
on the forms you fill out, and that in itself is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   And state laws dealing with parole or probation may also come
into play, says the NRA's Institute for Legislative Action Research
and Information Division.
</P>
<P>
   But the NRA _ citing a Dec. 24, 1997, Department of Justice
report that used statistics from the Executive Office of United
States Attorneys _ notes that ``during Fiscal Years 1994-1997 only
599 individuals were convicted of providing false information on
either federal forms 4473 (used to document retail firearms
purchases) or Brady handgun purchase application forms. During this
period, a minimum of 75 of those convicted provided false
information on Brady forms.'' The latter information comes, the NRA
says, from a letter from Acting Assistant Attorney General John C.
Keeney to Sen. Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Asking why there aren't more prosecutions is reasonable when
Congress has assessed severe penalties for the felon who buys a
handgun, says NRA spokesman Bill Parkerson. Parkerson is director
of the Research and Information Division of the Institute for
Legislative Action of the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's important enough to say, `You're going away for 10
years to the federal joint,' I think it's a really legitimate
question to say, `What are we doing here?''' Parkerson said.
``We're putting on severe penalties and then saying we don't have
the time to enforce them?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no real easy answers and I think that's part of what
Brady is all about,'' he says. ``It's feel-good legislation: Tell
the American people we're doing something about it and yet we're
not locking up the bad guys who are trying to buy guns illegally
because we don't have the money? We don't have the time?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell the people that,'' he says. ``That might be told to you
when you call the Justice Department, but I don't hear it in press
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the get-go, if you look at GAO \RGeneral Accounting
Office\S reports, they've always said, `This is not a prosecution
tool. That's not what we're about.' But that's never mentioned when
President Clinton is up in the Rose Garden with Sarah Brady,''
Parkerson said.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be change coming, says King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there have been concerns raised, we are working on
developing a protocol that we hope will be in place at the time the
national instant check system comes on board,'' he said last week.
Such a protocol would spell out more specifically when prosecution
is to be pressed.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of this column is not to settle this issue, because
I'm not sure it can be settled.
</P>
<P>
   But it is to say that I think news stories about the success or
failure of the Brady Act are incomplete _ no, they are misleading _
if the reporters do not ask the obvious next question. Readers
can't make an intelligent decision about something if they are
getting only part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is ombudsman for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
His e-mail address is harral(at)star-telegram.com. You may
telephone him at (817) 390-7692 or write him at P.O. Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
