<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1381 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX     08-31 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRUST BREEDS IN PLACES WHERE TRUTH ISN'T ALLOWED TO COME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``And the truth will set you free.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John 8:32
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how we mess things up when we fail to heed those words of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   We dig ourselves into a hole when we lie or deliberately
withhold the truth when it should be told. And once we get started,
the hole often just gets deeper and deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the mess we find ourselves in today because someone
lied or withheld the truth when it should have been revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us now think we have a president who is a liar. That is
tragic.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has lied _ although he does not seem able to
bring himself to use that word _ to us about his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky. It undoubtedly is not the first time he has looked
us square in the eye and ``lied.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has implied that this relationship is none of our
business. Bull corn! It became the public's business the minute he
put the issue before us and lied about it.
</P>
<P>
   How he goes about mending his ways with his family is a
different matter. That is a private matter, and the public needs to
butt out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lying is a tragic matter. Many will now be suspicious
of many of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   I do not think that our attacks on the installations in Sudan
and Afghanistan were attempts by Clinton to divert our attention
from the Lewinsky affair. I pray that they were not. If they were,
being ousted from office would be too good for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It is also sad for this nation that people are rejoicing about
Clinton's problems because they hate him. I suspect that in God's
eyes, hatred is probably a greater sin than are sins caused by
raging hormones.
</P>
<P>
   There is a wide gulf between hatred and criticism of another.
Hatred simply worsens a bad situation.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton's political support diminishes, I think the chances
of his resignation grow. If special prosecutor Kenneth Starr
presents sufficient evidence to warrant an impeachment, I think
Clinton will resign before he would permit all of the details of
his relationship with Lewinsky to be presented in detail to the
world.
</P>
<P>
   At least I would hope he would resign for our sake, his family's
sake and his own sake. This sordid matter needs to come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   And look at what withholding of the truth did to the Dallas
Cowboys during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the case. Cowboys player Everett McIver vanished
from the practice field. The rumors had it that he had been cut in
the neck and required stitches. The Cowboys, undoubtedly at the
orders of owner Jerry Jones, refused to disclose details of the
incident, calling it a ``family matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bull corn!
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies in Wichita Falls, where the team was
training, apparently bought the line at first. I wonder if they
would do so if the owner of a bar would ask them to leave after a
stabbing because the owner considered it a ``family matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The shield of silence raised by the Cowboys certainly triggered
suspicions. Word gradually leaked out that star receiver Michael
Irvin had stabbed McIver with a pair of scissors during a ruckus
about who was to be next in line for a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   Some suspected that Jones had ordered the shield of silence
because he feared that Irvin would end up in prison if the truth
became known. Irvin, you know, was on probation for felony drug
possession.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors continued to find their way into the newspapers and onto
radio and TV. One report had McIver being given a financial
settlement by Jones to prevent him from pursuing criminal charges
against Irvin. This finally brought a denial from Jones.
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Manny Alvarez of Dallas, who had put Irvin on
probation, finally had investigators for his probation department
look into the matter. Alvarez later informed the news media that
the investigation revealed that the stabbing was an accident, not a
deliberate act by Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little wrestling match started out innocently and someone
got hurt,'' the judge concluded. He considered the case closed.
</P>
<P>
   If that is true _ and I know of no reason to doubt the judge's
report _ then Jones did a terrible disservice to Irvin by clamping
a lid of silence on the matter. He subjected Irvin to unwarranted
suspicion simply because the truth apparently was withheld from the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Clinton owes the public an apology (say clearly and
distinctly, ``I have lied to you; I am sorry''), so too does Jones
owe an apology to his team, and especially to Irvin, for the
confusion, doubts and suspicions caused by the withholding of the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   All of us can learn lessons from these incidents.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be contacted at precord(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
