<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALWELL-NEWCHURCH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY'S TROUBLES BEHIND HIM, FALWELL LAYS PLANS FOR NEW
SANCTUARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell has had his ups and downs. Only a year
ago, the school he founded, Liberty University, was in trouble as
school officials sought to pay off a $100 million debt they had
owed for several years.
</P>
<P>
   But retired insurance tycoon Art L. Williams of Palm Beach,
Fla., came to the rescue in December with a $70 million donation.
The university has reduced its debt to $10 million and is moving
forward, Falwell said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Now Falwell, who emerged on the national scene in 1980 as
founder of the Moral Majority, is diving headlong into a new
project: building a 12,000-seat sanctuary for his 22,000-member
Thomas Road Baptist Church in Lynchburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The new church will be near Liberty University, about five miles
from the current 3,300-seat church, in central Lynchburg.
Groundbreaking is set for this fall, and the sanctuary is to be
completed by Christmas 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the largest sanctuary in North America,'' Falwell
said in a phone interview from Lynchburg.
</P>
<P>
   John Vaughan, founder of Church Growth Today, confirmed that
Falwell's sanctuary would be the largest. The largest now is the
10,145-seat Crenshaw Christian Center in Los Angeles, where the
Rev. Fred K.C. Price is minister, Vaughan said.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell's new church is expected to cost at least $20 million.
Falwell says three donors plan to contribute $5 million apiece,
although the money isn't in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the large donors back out, Falwell is expected to find a
way to carry out his plans.
</P>
<P>
   That has been his history since founding the Thomas Road church
in 1956. He began with 35 members who met in a 50-by-30-foot
building that formerly housed the Donald Duck Bottling Co.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell still keeps some of the soft drink bottles from the old
plant on his desk.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Lynchburg, Falwell was an improbable candidate for
the ministry. His 1987 autobiography, ``Strength for the Journey,''
says that his grandfather was an atheist and that his father, a
successful businessman, had a bootleg whiskey operation during
Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   But Falwell's mother made the difference, he has said.
</P>
<P>
   Every Sunday morning, she would waken her son with the smell of
bacon and eggs cooking. And she always had the radio tuned to the
sermons of Charles W. Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell says he first began thinking about becoming a Christian
when listening to Fuller, one of the first nationally broadcast
radio evangelists. Falwell attended Lynchburg College and later
graduated from Baptist Bible College in Springfield, Mo., a
fundamentalist Baptist institution.
</P>
<P>
   An avowed fundamentalist, Falwell has forged ties with the
Southern Baptist Convention since its leadership turned toward
conservatism. His church holds dual membership in the Southern
Baptist Convention and the Baptist Bible Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Falwell and members of his church were
messengers, or delegates, at the Southern Baptist national
convention in Salt Lake City this year.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell, who turned 65 on Aug. 11, has handed over some church
leadership duties to his son, the Rev. Jonathan Falwell, 32, who is
now executive pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the preaching pastor, but he runs the church,'' Falwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks proudly of all his children. His oldest son, Jerry
Falwell Jr., 36, is an attorney and chief counsel for Liberty
University. His daughter, Jeannie Falwell Savas, 34, is a surgeon
in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very blessed,'' said the elder Falwell, who has been
married to his wife, Macel, for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although at the traditional retirement age, Falwell says he's
not thinking of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a good 20 years left in me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides building the giant church, Falwell plans to be involved
in the upcoming presidential election. He believes Texas Gov.
George W. Bush will be the next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my conservative friends would disagree with me,'' he
said. ``But I'm a Bush man all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
