A1384 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TITANIC-VIDEO-TEX     08-31 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-VIDEO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITANIC' VIDEO RELEASE HAS MARKETING FOLKS GOING OVERBOARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where the heck's an iceberg when you need one?
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's much chance of one holding up in this heat. But
I'll take anything that will send the juggernaut that is
``Titanic'' mania to a well-deserved watery grave. The film's
release on home video Tuesday adds yet another swell to the
hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   OK, before the entire North American chapter of the Leonardo
DiCaprio fan club pulls out their official ``King of the World!''
ice blue stationery to fire off angry missives, or worse, before
director Jim Cameron phones the editors demanding a front-page
rebuttal, let me preface this rant with a clarification: I love
``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   When I first saw the movie in a packed octoplex last summer, I
was convinced then, as I am now, that Cameron's epic filming of the
1912 maritime disaster produced one of this decade's finest
American movies. ``Titanic'' encapsulates every emotional response
possible _ it's funny, frightening, romantic, angering and
extremely moving. I, along with millions of other moviegoers, can't
wait to relive the experience on video.
</P>
<P>
   What I hate is the ridiculous sea of hype the film has
generated. Tuesday's video release adds an entirely new level of
studio-generated ballyhoo, one so dizzying that even P.T. Barnum
would be reaching for the Dramamine.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster Video, a company big on subtlety, is staying open
till 2 a.m. Tuesday morning to make tapes available the first
minute it's ``officially'' okey-doky to go on sale (12:01 a.m). All
158 outlets in the Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex will be planning
activities, according to a company spokeswoman. There will be a
6-foot ice sculpture of the ship and the iceberg it hit (an ice
sculpture of an iceberg?) at the chain's flagship store on McKinney
Avenue in Dallas. The store will also feature a music trio _ like
the ill-fated musicians who went down with the ship. Store
employees will be decked out in life jackets while passing out
snacks.
</P>
<P>
   At least one store in Fort Worth is featuring life-jacket races
(whatever those are) from 10 p.m. to midnight; another is treating
video buyers to ``Titanic'' trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint plans to give away vouchers for a free copy of the film
if you switch your long-distance service. And Max Factor will
introduce a fall line of makeup in colors ``inspired'' by the film.
</P>
<P>
   All this is tied to the release of the video, which retails for
about $25. The two-tape set is available in pan-and-scan and
wide-screen editions _ traditionally you have to wait for the
wide-screen. An estimated 25 million copies of the video are due to
hit the shelves the first day. (Most fans signed up for copies
months ago.) QVC began pre-selling the title in June for $19.95 and
has reported taking orders for more than 200,000 units so far.
Paramount has reportedly pre-sold 3 million to 4 million copies
industrywide.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest crime against consumers, of course, is that soon
after they buy the video, they will be assaulted with ads for even
better versions of the movie. Once the initial buying tide begins
to ebb, expect a ``deluxe'' edition to hit stores with extra
footage, behind-the-scenes stuff and interviews _ prompting fans to
drop more cash.
</P>
<P>
   Then, once the overall feeding frenzy has slowed, there's even
more chum to dump onto the unsuspecting market. The ``Titanic'' DVD
edition, due next year but rumored to be available as early as
November, promises even more ``extras.''
</P>
<P>
   Does any of this sound familiar? It should. Fox did the same
thing to ``Star Wars'' fans with countless versions of the trilogy,
each supposedly better than the last. Whether you call it
distributing savvy or niche marketing, it still amounts to
premeditated fleecing, and the folks who are ultimately left out in
the cold are the film's fans _ too impatient to wait for the
``ultimate'' edition or too zealous to care.
</P>
<P>
   To heck with the lifeboats, I'm abandoning ship.
</P>
<P>
   That is, as soon as I get my copy.
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
