   PILOT-IRON MAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He's the Cal Ripken Jr. of fighter jocks, the
``iron man'' of the Air Force. Maj. Michael J. Brill, who makes his
living flying F-16 fighter planes, passed a milestone recently that
_ in the rarefied ranks of his calling _ is every bit as awesome as
Ripken's feat of playing in more than 2,600 consecutive
major-league baseball games. When ``Iron Mike'' took to the skies
Aug. 21 at Hill Air Force Base near Ogden, Utah, he logged his
4,000th hour in the cockpit of an F-16. That's more than any other
pilot has ever flown in the Fighting Falcon. And no other F-16
pilot is even close. By MICHAEL D. TOWLE. Story will move in ``a''
general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
