<HEADER>
A1389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMONE-MUSIC-REVIEW-A     08-31 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMONE-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 NINA SIMONE: RICH WITH LOVE, PRAYER AND POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a true diva, technique is irrelevant. Her performance is
about a beloved sound, a celebrated personality and a repertory
that magnifies them both. That was the kind of performance Nina
Simone gave on Sunday afternoon at the New Jersey Performing Arts
Center in Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   It was her first concert in the New York area since 1993, and
she declared, ``If you're going to come see me again, you've got to
come to France, because I ain't coming back.'' Ms. Simone has lived
abroad since the early 1970s; she also announced that she was
building a house in Ghana.
</P>
<P>
   Her adoring audience, primed by the rarity of her appearance,
was there to pay tribute to Ms. Simone's indomitable spirit and her
lifelong project of celebrating an African-American heritage of
dignity, spiritual fervor and resilience.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, when she could have had a supper-club
career, Ms. Simone had the nerve to sing material like
``Mississippi Goddam,'' about the brutality of last-ditch
segregation. Ms. Simone, who is now 65, has become an icon of the
struggle for civil rights. In Newark, she raised a fist and had the
audience chant ``Power!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Simone delved into nearly every African-American genre older
than hip-hop. She was by turns sanctified and lascivious, righteous
and tender. Her set started with gospel and spirituals, including
her hymnlike tribute to the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., ``Why
(the King of Love Is Dead''), which now mentions Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   With a diva's prerogative, she stretched her first song, ``Every
Time I Feel the Spirit,'' with two extended reprises, starting the
song anew twice after waves of applause, spurring ever stronger
call-and-response. At one point, Ms. Simone sang about praying five
times a day to Allah, something not usually heard in a gospel song.
</P>
<P>
   The set also included blues and blues-based songs (``I Want a
Little Sugar in My Bowl,'' ``My Baby Just Cares for Me''), pop
standards (her early hit ``I Loves You Porgy''), a song rooted in
African-American work songs (``See Line Woman,'' with just
percussion and her voice) and the gospel-charged ``Mississippi
Goddam,'' with its responsorial chorus, ``Too slow!'' and Ms.
Simone's insistent ``Just give me my equality!''
</P>
<P>
   As she sang Randy Newman's ``Baltimore,'' about a decaying city
where it's ``hard just to live,'' her band slipped a reggae beat
behind the chorus. At the end, she changed the name of the city to
``Newark,'' drawing hometown cheers.
</P>
<P>
   There is still power in her voice, but little of the subtlety
that made her such a striking singer when she emerged at the end of
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   With a voice that plunged to the baritone range and rose to a
self-possessed soprano, Ms. Simone had an aural presence that was
dignified and almost androgynous. Her tone could be sultry and
velvety, or it could shade into a raw groan that was both weary and
foreboding, the sound of someone who has been working far beyond
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tone that encompasses sufferings that date back to
slavery, and Ms. Simone uses it as both a complaint and a rallying
cry, one that galvanizes her listeners.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In ``Sinner Man,'' about a God who demands tribute in prayer
from someone with nowhere else to turn, her voice seemed desperate
and forsaken, and in ``Four Women,'' about America's heritage of
miscegenation, she used that rough-hewn tone over an inexorably
repeating piano line, giving the song a bitter clarity.
</P>
<P>
   But the lush side of Ms. Simone's voice has eroded through the
years, changing the balance toward dryness and bluntness. Her tone
made ``I Want a Little Sugar in My Bowl'' more comic than alluring,
as Ms. Simone cackled, ``You need some too?''
</P>
<P>
   Her version of ``I Loves You Porgy,'' which was once a hushed,
delicate, almost motionless confession, had sharper angles, with
Ms. Simone's phrasing almost brusque against a shimmering backdrop
of vibraphone and little bells. And as her notes arrived flat, she
turned a song like ``My Baby Just Cares for Me'' into a
near-parody.
</P>
<P>
   Yet her fans didn't mind. Ms. Simone was still singing, still
tough, still forthright. ``You're beautiful,'' she told the
audience during one of the standing ovations. ``Be strong!''
</P>
</TEXT>
