<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-UNIVERSITY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASKELL UNIVERSITY ON MISSION TO BECOME NATIONAL EDUCATION CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Rose Rodriguez grew up in mainstream America,
attending an inner-city high school in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But during the summers, she'd slip away to the Paiute Indian
Reservation north of the city to visit her aunts and grandmother.
There she heard about a college called Haskell where American
Indians like herself could learn about their culture and heritage _
and get a two-year college degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd come for two years, get a good base and move
on,'' said Rodriguez, now a 20-year-old sophomore at Haskell Indian
Nations University in Lawrence, Kan. ``When I found out (this year)
that American Indian Studies was going to be a four-year program, I
said, `Whoa, I'm staying.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Haskell took a big step this month in its mission to become a
national center for Indian education.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime Lawrence institution received permission to add
three baccalaureate programs to the one it began offering five
years ago in elementary education. Haskell President Bob Martin
said he hopes the new offerings will help boost the number of
four-year degrees earned by American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at the high dropout rates of many Native Americans
at mainstream institutions and we knew that if we could give them
the opportunity to complete not only an associate but also a
baccalaureate degree that we could increase the numbers that are
graduating,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell is preparing for an influx of students. Within five
years, it expects enrollment to increase by as much as 75 percent,
from 850 students this year to roughly 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell was founded in 1884 as a boarding school for American
Indian children. The federal government set it up to help the
children assimilate into Western culture and to prepare them for
vocational jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the school's more prominent students was athlete Jim
Thorpe. He enrolled at age 10 in 1898. Thorpe was a member of the
Oklahoma Sac &AMP; Fox tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the school began offering secondary and
post-secondary classes. In 1970, about the time that tribes began
setting up their own community colleges, the institution changed
its name to Haskell Indian Junior College.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were (American Indian) students who were going to
colleges, but the success rates were so bad,'' recalled Carol
Davis, a vice president at Turtle Mountain Community College in
Belcourt, N.D., who was involved in the early tribal college
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty tribes now operate their own community colleges, and many
are beginning to provide four-year degrees, said Paul Boyer, the
author of two reports on tribal colleges for the Carnegie
Foundation. Haskell is unique, he said, because it serves all
tribes in the nation that are recognized by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Haskell) has done a very intriguing transformation over the
decades,'' Boyer said. In the beginning, he said, its mission was
to squelch Indian culture, traditions and languages. ``That in no
way reflects the current philosophy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell and the tribal colleges are succeeding because they are
able to provide environments that honor and propagate Indian
culture, Boyer said. Their clear mission _ to prepare students to
become leaders in their tribal communities and in the nation _ also
is one of their strengths, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many mainstream universities have worked very hard to create
programs and service that encourage greater American Indian
enrollment,'' Boyer said. ``But as many as 90 percent of American
Indians who enroll at mainstream universities leave before getting
a degree.''
</P>
<P>
   American Indian students, more than any other ethnic group, are
considered to be at risk for failure: They have high percentages of
single-parent families, low family incomes, high sibling dropout
rates and limited proficiency in English, mathematics and reading.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics provided by Haskell illustrate the poor progress of
American Indians:
</P>
<P>
   Only 9 percent of American Indian adults have completed four
years of college, compared to 20 percent for the total U.S. adult
population.
</P>
<P>
   Only 34 percent of American Indian eighth-graders expect to
finish college.
</P>
<P>
   American Indians make up about 1 percent of the U.S. population,
but they account for only 0.4 percent of the scientific work force.
Only 0.2 percent earned doctorates in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Students who attend Haskell do not have to pay tuition or room
and board. Their fees amount to $105 a semester.
</P>
<P>
   The educations are provided by the federal government, part of
the deal set up in treaties long ago that forced American Indians
to give up their land.
</P>
<P>
   The price sounds low, but students generally need at least
$3,000 to cover expenses during the year, said Rodriguez, the Los
Angeles student who plans to major in American Indian Studies.
Students who live off campus pay much more because the government
does not pay for their room and board.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Haskell decided to work toward becoming a
four-year institution. Two of its newly approved programs _
business administration and American Indian Studies _ begin this
year. The other, in environmental science, will begin next year.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell opened a new dormitory last year and this year is
renovating two others. When the renovations are done next year, the
school will be able to accommodate about 950 students on campus, up
from 700 now. About 200 generally live off campus, a number Haskell
also hopes to increase.
</P>
<P>
   The school expects to pick up another 300 to 400 students
through satellite campuses and distance learning, which allows it
to offer classes electronically with computers. Enrollment should
total 1,450 to 1,550 within five years, Martin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
