<SLUG> BC-HEALTHY-TREES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE TO A HEALTHY TREE THAN LOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Trees add much to a property, including beauty,
wildlife, noise absorption, shade and a buffer to the cold of
winter.
</P>
<P>
   But even healthy-looking trees can be ailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because your trees are green or have green leaves doesn't
mean they are necessarily safe or healthy,'' said Sal Pezzino,
president of the New York State Association of Arborists and owner
of Artistic Arbor Culture in Huntington.
</P>
<P>
   Pezzino and other tree experts say homeowners can do early risk
detection once they learn to recognize some telltale signs of poor
tree health.
</P>
<P>
   Some common problems are unknowingly created by homeowners
thinking they're doing the right thing, Pezzino said. It's why he
said, ironically, that ``when I see an ugly lawn, I know the trees
are doing better.''
</P>
<P>
   One simple but potentially deadly problem is overwatering.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a potential for tree roots to not fully expand if they
get too much water,'' Pezzino said. ``Tree roots tend to stay
shallow in turf areas that are on an irrigation system and watered
two to three times a week. When the soil isn't allowed to dry out,
the root system won't get bigger and go deeper in search of
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Another danger comes from misusing lawn treatment chemicals,
Pezzino said.
</P>
<P>
   He said a great deal of stress is inflicted on trees by the use
of an overabundance of herbicides to kill lawn weeds and as a
result, end up killing tree roots as well. He also advises not to
use too much nitrogen-based fertilizer, which causes the tree to
produce more green growth (leaves and needles) than its root system
can support.
</P>
<P>
   Fungicides also can kill off mycorrhizae, a fungus that lives on
and around tree roots and helps trees to absorb water and
nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Groll, owner of Groll Tree Service in Hudson, N.Y., pointed
out other signs that are directed toward impaired tree health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look for things such as large rot spots or hollows in the
tree,'' Groll said. ``Carpenter ants are another danger sign, even
if they are in your house. They could be coming from a tree nearby.
Major cracks or splits in any branch, dead branches or if the root
system has moved in any way or heaved upward or at an angle
(especially through sidewalks or patios) are other red flags. Seek
help if a tree is losing more limbs than normal, especially during
a wind storm, or shedding leaves before fall, such as in
mid-to-late August. These are signs that your tree is weak,
diseased or sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Pezzino noted that when most trees blow over, it actually has to
do with damage done to the root system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You rarely loose any trees during a regular storm if they have
been trimmed and properly maintained,'' Pezzino said. ``Dead trees
never fall down in a storm; they usually fall down one day from
lack of support.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to maintaining healthy trees is regular maintenance. A
certified or consulting arborist can tell homeowners a lot about
their trees by doing a thorough inspection of them. Arborists
usually charge an hourly fee of approximately $65 to $140.
</P>
<P>
   ``A full canopy may make your tree top-heavy and cause it to
fall down because of the weight, or it can kill off the roots from
all the pressure,'' Pezzino said. ``Having your trees pruned and
inspected by an arborist on a regular basis may save them from
gravity and wind, and you from any danger, especially if the trees
are soft woods, such as a tulip, poplar or willow.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some homeowners like to do their own pruning, it may
not be feasible for them to do it themselves, especially if it's a
big job.
</P>
<P>
   Groll stressed that homeowners should never attempt to prune
tree branches in or around power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always call your local power company,'' said Groll, a former
power company lineman. ``They don't want inexperienced people
messing around power lines. You may not see the line through the
branches or slip and grab for a branch and touch the wire. They are
happy to come out and take care of the problem for you and they do
it for free.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arborists also can help detect hidden problems and potential
dangers down the road.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, root damage often is found near roads if they have
been paved or widened, and around sidewalk improvements, Pezzino
said. Severe root damage will decay the tree from the center
outwards.
</P>
<P>
   A problem that may not become apparent for 20 years or more
stems from new construction, Groll said. As a house's foundation is
being dug out with a backhoe, the vehicle may be shearing off
anchor and feeder roots that are essential to the life of a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a few years for the tree to die, but it will die,''
Groll said. ``We see this constantly around treed areas that have
undergone some type of construction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
