A1423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-31 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS ALL ATWITTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The tortured dithering of House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt last week
typified the confusion in Congress over how judicious or how
partisan to be toward President Clinton's potential impeachment
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting their position as national political leaders, both men
made noble attempts to sound statesmanlike on the subject of
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's pending report to Congress.
They tried to strike the fair-minded pose that would best serve
their mutual presidential ambitions in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich urged Republicans not to rush prematurely into
impeachment hearings and suggested that Congress should not take
any action unless the Starr report deals with serious crimes beyond
the evidence of illicit sex. He said that ``a pattern of felonies''
should be the criterion for launching any congressional crusade to
bring down the president.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, for his part, conspicuously failed to defend Clinton
against possible accusations of perjury and obstruction of justice
and conceded that the impeachment process might be unavoidable.
``We (House members) have to, under the Constitution, carefully
examine the facts and then make a judgment as to whether or not he
should be expelled,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   But both men beat a fast retreat from such responsible positions
within days, under pressure from their own outraged partisans.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders could not even count on their own deputies to
support their reasoned views. Rep. Tom DeLay, Gingrich's third in
command, is busily mobilizing a crusade to get Clinton to resign.
Rep. David Bonior, Gephardt's deputy, insisted that Democrats
should support Clinton and the country should abandon speculation
about how to punish him.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was accused of being too soft on the president and
undercutting GOP conservatives who want to campaign by taking
credit for leading him to the political guillotine. They have
pre-judged Clinton and are proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich hastily issued a statement revising his message to
insist that ``any evidence'' of possible presidential wrongdoing,
``whether one incident or many, would clearly have to be
investigated ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt got complaints that he was being too tough on the
president and encouraging Democrats to abandon him in the fall
campaign. By even acknowledging the legitimacy of a possible House
review of the president's actions, he had suggested that the
Democratic hierarchy would not require, or expect, party loyalty to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt rapidly softened his tone, expressing the support for
Clinton that was missing in his original neutrality. ``I thought he
apologized,'' Gephardt said, falling back on the familiar party
refrain that it is time forget the scandal and to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and Gephardt are caught in the contradictory pressures
their congressional troops feel as they face a campaign for
re-election in November. For so much at stake, too little is
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side can be confident how the public will react when the
Starr report actually materializes sometime this fall. Neither side
knows what will be in it, despite all the educated guesses.
</P>
<P>
   If it is devastating to the president, the election is likely to
become a national referendum on his conduct. No candidate wishing
to maintain a moral standing with constituents is going to defend
Clinton's fatal attraction to an aggressive young intern, let alone
his lies about it.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Gephardt says, the Democrats will have trouble
putting distance between themselves and their president. It is not
easy to deplore his personal behavior while supporting his public
agenda. The party is bound to lose seats. In that case, the
impeachment process will go forward in the hands of an expanded,
triumphant GOP congressional majority.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Starr report is limited to titillating but
inconclusive data about the Monica Lewinsky affair, giving the
president a pass on other investigations into financial and
political questions, its impact may be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Voters may stick to what they tell the pollsters now _ a
majority does not think Clinton should be impeached _ and
Republicans overeager to punish him could feel a backlash. If that
causes them to lose seats, any subsequent impeachment hearings
would become less likely because they would amount to a politically
reckless defiance of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be repeated too often that impeachment is a political
process more than a legal one. The rules are not written in stone.
</P>
<P>
   President Lyndon Johnson used to tell the story of an aspiring
teacher interviewed by a conservative school board for a
prospective position. Asked his view of the world, the nervous
candidate replied, ``I can teach it round or flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Torn between long-term and short-term worries, what Gingrich and
Gephardt would like to do is hedge their current political bets by
teaching it oblong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
