<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOT-IRONMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
F-16'S `IRON MAN' A CAREER CASE OF PLANE GREATNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He's the Cal Ripken Jr. of fighter jocks, the
``iron man'' of the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Michael J. Brill, who makes his living flying F-16 fighter
planes, passed a milestone recently that _ in the rarefied ranks of
his calling _ is every bit as awesome as Ripken's feat of playing
in more than 2,600 consecutive major-league baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Iron Mike'' took to the skies Aug. 21 at Hill Air Force
Base near Ogden, Utah, he logged his 4,000th hour in the cockpit of
an F-16. That's more than any other pilot has ever flown in the
Fighting Falcon. And no other F-16 pilot is even close.
</P>
<P>
   Brill, a 1979 Air Force Academy graduate, took his first flight
in the Fort Worth-made fighter in October 1980. He sat down and
wrote to his girlfriend _ now his wife _ about his new sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her I was in love, and found what I wanted to do for
the rest of my life,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``It
sounded so much like a Dear John letter that at the end, I had to
tell her I was talking about an airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years and 4,000 flight hours later, Brill is still
assigned to F-16s. As a full-time member of the Air Force Reserve,
he is operations officer for the 466th Fighter Squadron of the
419th Fighter Wing at Hill AFB.
</P>
<P>
   Brill, who lacks the cocky demeanor of the stereotypical fighter
pilot, said he is flattered that people compare his flight time in
the F-16 to the consecutive-game record of Ripken, who plays third
base for the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone once asked me if they could call me the Cal Ripken of
aviation,'' said Brill, 41. ``I would not say that, but I guess
there is some room for comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Ripken played in his 2,131st consecutive game
Sept. 6, 1995, breaking a mark set by Lou Gehrig of the New York
Yankees. Ripken has since extended his streak to more than 2,600
games.
</P>
<P>
   Brill said he could set his record partly because he is a
weapons specialist, a job that requires a lot of training as new
weapons systems come on line. He has also been a flight instructor
since 1984 and has participated in such competitions as Gunsmoke
and William Tell, the Air Force's worldwide air-to-ground and
air-to-air weapons competitions, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``The big reason I've been able to do this is that
I have had absolutely zero breaks from flying over 18 years. I have
never gone more than two weeks without flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill's feat is unlikely to be matched any time soon. Worldwide,
more than 3,000 pilots have 1,000 hours in the F-16. More than 400
have 2,000; only 21 have passed the 3,000-hour milestone, which
Brill reached first.
</P>
<P>
   No one is chasing his exhaust to reach 4,000. The Air Force said
it is almost unheard of for a pilot to log 4,000 hours in one type
of fighter plane. In fighters, the typical training mission lasts
less than 1 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I've been driving the same car for 18 years,''
Brill said of the F-16, which is built by Lockheed Martin Tactical
Aircraft Systems in west Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The F-16 has changed so significantly ever since it was built.
It seems like every other year, there is a new capability you are
challenged to master. It keeps you fresh, that's for sure. I like
the current version the best, but there is something about every
version that was attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials speak of Brill the way baseball fans talk of
Ripken: as a person who always shows up for work and does the best
he can, whether he's briefing fellow pilots, shuffling papers or
scooting around the sky in the Fighting Falcon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about Major Brill is that he never passes up
an opportunity to fly an airplane,'' said Col. Wayne Conroy,
Brill's commander at the 419th. ``He is thorough in his planning
and his execution. He is just a great role model for younger
pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill, who lives with his wife and three children near the Utah
air base, says he's not sure when he will stop his streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll keep going as long as I still enjoy it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
