<SLUG> BC-PARKER-JAZZ-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLIE PARKER JAZZ FESTIVAL: CELEBRATING PARKER IN HIS OWN
SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Staging a Charlie Parker Jazz Festival worthy of its
name is a difficult job, but the sixth annual edition of the
concert, at a packed Tompkins Square Park on Sunday afternoon, did
the trick in a way that was neither curatorially exact nor some
sort of seance.
</P>
<P>
   The great saxophonist's style of harmony, phrasing, composition,
tone, choice of repertory and bravado are part of the modern jazz
player's kit, and that was the conceptual starting point for all
four acts. The audience was a rare example of a jazz-concert crowd
that was full of musicians, laughing at musical jokes, cooing at
references.
</P>
<P>
   At times Parker's music was played, and the performers were
explicit about it; at other times, the connection was only there by
metaphor or a vague link. But the performances connected several
different generations of players _ which is something Parker also
did _ and healthily suggested many different ways of playing jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The Julius Hemphill Sextet, an all-saxophone band led by the
saxophonist Marty Ehrlich, played a strong set of Hemphill's
compositions. (He died in 1995.) With the rhythmic kick of Alex
Harding's baritone saxophone, the music represented the blues as
sophisticated and jocular chamber music.
</P>
<P>
   Each tune had a different soloist, and parts for different horns
kept wrapping around one another in twisty pieces that shivered
with modernist dissonance. Then a bass line would appear _ the one
in ``The Hard Blues'' resembled the down-and-up steps of the
rhythm-and-blues song ``Lonely Avenue'' _ grounding the music in
gut bucket persuasiveness.
</P>
<P>
   It's lovely music; Hemphill wasn't close to being artistically
finished at the time of his death, and the music still sounds
alarmingly fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The conguero Ray Barretto played with his own sextet, folding
conventions of Latin jazz into shared space with mainstream jazz
arrangements. The group played some be-bop and soul-jazz, but
mostly captured the crowd when his 12-year-old son, Chris, played
Parker's ``Now's the Time'' with the band, carefully carving out a
solo which at least for its beginning followed the lines of
Parker's famous solo on that tune. ``That's a message to Bird,''
announced Barretto, proudly, at the close of his set. ``This music
will never die.''
</P>
<P>
   Since her short walk-on stood out in most accounts as a high
point of last summer's festival, it was good to see Etta Jones
given a long set to herself this year. There are many shadings to
her voice _ a blues honk, a nasal, girlish whine _ and her
phrasings are all her own. When she sang ``What a Wonderful
World,'' audience members attempted to sing along according to
Louis Armstrong's model, but she kept shaking them off and they
finally stopped altogether.
</P>
<P>
   None of her sung lines on standards could be predicted, whether
she would stretch them past their usual boundaries with long,
wailing vowels, or tartly gun them down in half her allotted space.
</P>
<P>
   Timbrally, she recalls no singer as much as Billie Holiday, but
she distinguished herself neatly on that score: Singing ``Fine and
Mellow,'' she mimicked Holiday in the final verse, and it was both
wickedly precise and sufficiently different from her own style for
a listener to appreciate its own excellence.
</P>
<P>
   On several tunes she was accompanied by the violinist Claude
``Fiddler'' Williams, 90, who played in the late 1930s with Count
Basie; he took long choruses of his own, including a bit of
hurtling be-bop chromaticism into his warm, luxuriant swing.
</P>
<P>
   The alto saxophonist Lou Donaldson, one of the cheeriest
presences on jazz bandstands, finished the afternoon with endless
jokes and a with decidedly more down-home, roadhouse version of
Parker's repertory. Like Chris Barretto, he played the ``Now's the
Time'' solo, extending its narrative and taking it to new, earthier
conclusions; he did the same thing again with ``Parker's Mood.''
</P>
<P>
   The guitarist Peter Bernstein and organist Dr. Lonnie Smith also
delivered galvanizing improvisations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powerful music, the blues,'' Donaldson remarked, launching
into a story about a sad-sack friend who ``fell in love so fast he
didn't check it out,'' and went on to sing a funny, repetitive
blues about the source of his friend's troubles: a woman who put
whisky in her coffee, her tea and her whisky. It was a warm,
offhanded way to end the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
