<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: OLIVIER ON THE LITTLE SCREEN; `GINT' FINDS ITS
ROOTS; NEW HOME FOR RSC; YIDDISH COMES TO BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: BRITAIN; NORWAY; Calif., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning Tuesday, in a series of screenings titled ``Laurence
Olivier: Four Crowning Achievements,'' the Museum of Television and
Radio, in both New York and Los Angeles, will showcase the actor's
art as it was applied to the intimate medium of television in
collaborations with such colleagues as Alan Bates, Katharine
Hepburn, Malcolm McDowell, Leo McKern and Helen Mirren, among
others. In ``A Voyage Round My Father,'' playing Tuesday through
Sept. 20, Olivier portrays an irrepressible old lawyer; in ``The
Collection,'' Sept. 22 to Oct. 11, he is an aging couturier caught
in a romantic quadrangle; in ``Love Among the Ruins,'' Oct. 13 to
Nov. 1, he stars with Ms. Hepburn as an aging lawyer with a
troublesome client, and in ``King Lear,'' Nov. 3 to Nov. 29, he
gives a performance that won him his fifth and final Emmy.
</P>
<P>
   Going Home
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it seems like carrying coals to Newcastle, but Romulus
Linney's ``Gint,'' a very American version of Henrik Ibsen's
Norwegian epic ``Peer Gynt,'' will be performed by a troupe from
New York on Wednesday and Thursday in Oslo. But there's a story
behind it. The Theater for the New City production of ``Gint'' was
invited to Oslo by the National Theater of Norway to take part in
its International Ibsen Stage Festival. Every two years since 1990,
it has been inviting selected companies from around the world to
stage their Ibsen productions in Norway. The Theater for the New
City production, which had its world premiere in New York in
February, is billed as the first from the United States to be
selected for the festival.
</P>
<P>
   What to Be?
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Shakespeare Company has chosen a Dutch architect,
Erick Van Egeraat, to design its new home in Stratford-on-Avon, but
it is not clear what it will look like. Until recently, the idea
was to refurbish and modernize the existing Royal Shakespeare
Theater, which opened in 1932 and has long been considered
impractical. Now the company has disclosed that it may build an
entirely new theater on the same site on the banks of the River
Avon. No final decision is expected until 2000, although company
officials say they believe that a new building may prove to be the
cheaper option. Either way, the key variable may be whether the
company can get an $80 million grant from national lottery profits
and cover the rest of the estimated $137 million budget through
private donations.
</P>
<P>
   Upward Bound
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mandy Patinkin's hit one-man concert, ``Mamaloshen''
(``Mother Tongue''), is headed for Broadway after its sold-out run
last month at a former synagogue on the Lower East Side. Beginning
on Oct. 13, his evening of musical numbers sung in Yiddish _
everything from ``Maria'' (from ``West Side Story'') to ``Take Me
Out to the Ball Game'' _ will play 28 performances, through Nov. 7,
at the Belasco Theater.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
