<SLUG> BC-PAX-TV-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW NETWORK EMPHASIZES FAMILY VALUES, BUT DOES IT HAVE A HIDDEN
MISSION?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BC-PAXTV-BOX) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pax TV, the self-proclaimed seventh network, has been doing its
hard-sell best to drum into your head that it isn't out to conquer
the world, that it doesn't want to play God, instill spiritual
values, preach community responsibility or save our sick, morally
decaying society.
</P>
<P>
   It says it is simply this: a clean alternative to the TV filth
we consume from a daily diet of network and cable-television fare.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because its programming chief is Jeff Sagansky, a
sharp, experienced chap who learned during his days as head of CBS
that two of the broadcasters' Ten Commandments are ``Thou shalt not
touch politics'' and ``Thou had better steer clear of
spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV launched its broadcast lineup Monday with a healthy dose
of off-network shows augmented by original infotainment and
children's programs. And Sagansky and his network were so careful
to distance themselves from anything religious and political that
the start-up propagated an atmosphere of distrust, suspicion and
fear.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the public relations hole they've dug for
themselves is by professing not to be something they clearly are.
We're supposed to believe that the biblical white dove on its logo
means nothing in particular, and that attendees of a recent Pax TV
luncheon in Dallas just happened to be met at the door by a woman
dressed as an angel.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by Lowell ``Bud'' Paxson, 63, a born-again Christian
whose co-creation of the Home Shopping Network made him a
multimillionaire, Pax TV claims that it isn't based on Christian
beliefs as much as spiritual peace; that it's a venture combining
faith with fortune. (''Pax'' means peace in Latin.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this explains all the angels, which also dominate Pax
TV's programming. Reruns of ``Touched by an Angel'' and the angelic
``Highway to Heaven'' are staples of prime time; one original
children's program is ``Cloud Nine,'' hosted by a group of teen-age
angels running a public-access cable TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Another original show is ``It's a Miracle,'' a weekly hourlong
series with country singer Billy Dean and actress Nia Peeples
introducing ``miracles'' and human-interest stories that illustrate
``the power of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that some people give the phrase `family
values' a political connotation,'' Sagansky says, clearly unnerved.
``People think that we've got some right-wing agenda or some
religious agenda. We don't. But the paranoid people are always
looking to see if there's some conspiracy afoot. There's no such
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Jewish,'' Sagansky continues, ``so if that were true, he
(Bud Paxson) certainly wouldn't have gotten me to do this job. He
feels he has a calling from God. I don't feel I have the same
calling, but I do have a lot of idealism that I had when I started
in this business. We're young and we'll make mistakes. But we feel
we're onto something here.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has already been made of Pax TV's early mistake _ some
print ads in which the wording bordered on homophobia. A reference
to ``so-called creative people'' peddling ``every kind of
alternative language and lifestyle to our kids'' was yanked after
accusations that the wording was code for ``anti-gay.''
</P>
<P>
   What still concerns me is the overall tone of the network's $25
million publicity campaign, ads that are about as contradictory as
the network's hidden spiritual claims.
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV is against programming that teaches children to fear the
world, but its own ads prey on similar parental fears.
</P>
<P>
   One effective scared-straight commercial features an infant
watching television news as a narrator asks ``Is what your child
sees on television really the way you want him to see the world?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Day America,'' a one-hour, daily infotainment show that
kicked off the launch Monday, is designed as an alternative to
early-evening network news. ``Great Day'' will focus on parenting,
family finances, travel and the like, using a news-you-can-use
format along the lines of the last hour of NBC's ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, and with shows like ``Eight Is Enough'' and ``Father
Dowling Mysteries,'' the Pax TV menu won't be edgy or hip or even
all that steeped in reality.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Pax TV's world seems sanitized and sterilized, devoid
of crime and ugliness _ and people of color. The highest-profile
black performer is Della Reese of ``Touched by an Angel'' and there
is no Hispanic presence to speak of. Sagansky says diversifying its
lineup is ``one of the things we have to work on,'' even though Pax
TV is already planted in 43 of the top 50 cities. (To its credit,
Pax is airing the civil rights-based drama ``I'll Fly Away.'')
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Paxson is deep-pocketed and well-connected, having made millions
by co-founding Home Shopping Network in 1982, and later by buying
radio and television stations. Pax TV consists of 88 UHF stations,
71 owned by the Florida-based Paxson Communications Corp., which
owns more TV stations than any other U.S. company.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, those airwaves were used for wall-to-wall
infomercials _ a typical night on Channel 68 featured shows selling
weight machines and hair-care products _ but that lucrative
business has plateaued.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson was helped out tremendously by last year's ``must carry''
legislation that forced cable systems to add his UHF station to
their lineups, suddenly making it accessible to cable audiences and
a legitimate network contender.
</P>
<P>
   The skeptic in me asks whether Pax TV offers anything different
from what is already supplied by cable networks such as the Family
Channel and the retro-TV channels like TV Land and Nick at Nite.
Sagansky says Pax TV will lure viewers interested in a seamless
flow of ``inspirational'' programming no matter the hour.
</P>
<P>
   Some media buyers attending the Dallas luncheon feel good about
Pax TV's chances but were concerned that most Pax channels were
weak UHF signals. Others wondered how long such feel-good
television would keep the attention of a viewing audience
conditioned to edgier programming, such as shows on such network
upstarts as the WB.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that some of the talk shows on TV tried to clean
themselves up, and it didn't work. The ratings dropped,'' says
Terry Hanson, general manager of the local PAX affiliate. ``It's a
sad state of affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thinks all programming should mingle faith and
fortune, as Pax TV does, Hanson thinks a moment, smiles and
answers: ``There's a place for everything and anything. I'm just
glad `they' are carrying some of that everything.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
