<HEADLINE>
FACTS ON PAX TV
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-PAX-TV) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Launch date: Monday
</P>
<P>
   Penetration: 88 stations reaching 74 million households,
including stations in all of the top-20 markets.
</P>
<P>
   Hours of programming: 24 hours, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Hours of original programming: Four. (Five beginning in
November.)
</P>
<P>
   Programming overview: Family-oriented programs free of excessive
violence and gratuitous sex. Aimed mostly at women and children.
Schedule includes off-network reruns like ``Touched by an Angel,''
augmented with infotainment programs, game shows and children's
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Chances of success: Good, actually; family-friendly
entertainment could generate a loyal following. Pax TV will get
minuscule numbers compared with the lowest-rated network
competitor. But a single ratings point (representing 980,000
households) could make the network profitable, because its
advertising is sold locally, and local ad rates typically are
higher than network rates.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
