<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Sept. 6)  
(JT) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; London Architecture &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am thinking of visiting London this fall and would like to
see the work of modern British architects, including Sir Norman
Foster, Lord Richard Rogers and Nicholas Grimshaw. Are there any
such tours? _ Lois Widom, Santa Cruz, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is one tour company you should know about, as well as
one special event this month. Architectural Dialogue, West Hill
House, 6 Swains Lane, London N6 6QU, telephone (44-181) 341-1371,
fax (44-181) 342 9108, offers a regular cycle of Saturday
architectural tours. There are three that might appeal to you.
Contemporary London, available Oct. 17 and Nov. 21, is a look at
the work of the three architects you mentioned _ masters of Hi-Tech
and Post-Modernism; other designers whose work is on the tour
include Robert Venturi, the American post-modernist.
</P>
<P>
   Docklands Regeneration, this Saturday and again on Oct. 24,
focuses on the buildings _ good, bad and ugly _ that have gone up
after the demise of the city's docks 25 years ago. Included will be
Rogers' Reuters building and Grimshaw's Financial Times building.
</P>
<P>
   And the City of London tour, Sept. 26 and Oct. 31, explores the
financial district, a mix of medieval buildings, Christopher Wren
churches and modern office towers. That last group includes the
Lloyds of London building (by the Richard Rogers Partnership),
which has its ductwork and stairways on the outside, giving it an
``inside-out'' look.
</P>
<P>
   All tours depart at 10:15 a.m. and return by 1 p.m. The price is
$30, students $18.80, at $1.71 to the pound. Tours leave from the
forecourt of the Royal Academy, Piccadilly; participants are asked
to arrive 10 minutes early. Reservations recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The special event you should know about is London Open House on
Sept. 19 and 20. More than 450 buildings in the city will be open
for free tours, with the list spanning centuries and encompassing
everything from private homes to government buildings. A special
program for children ages 8 to 14 turns them into architectural
``detectives,'' looking for clues in the buildings on the tour
list. For details, contact London Open House, Post Office Box 6984,
London N6 6PY; Web: londonopenhouse.demon.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Notes on Volts &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently returned from Russia, and I took my camcorder.
Luckily one of my friends had a converter that allowed me to
recharge the batteries, otherwise my highlight tape would have been
a short one because all this talk of volts and wattage is a mystery
to me. For future reference, how can I tell if I need a converter,
and where can I get one? _ Robert B. Garber, Glen Rock, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's use as an example your trip to Russia, which uses 220
volts at 50 cycles per second. Many electronic devices come with
power supplies that can handle the world's three main voltage
systems: Japan (100 volts), the Americas (120), and Europe, Asia
and Africa (220). The fine print on the side will list the voltages
accepted. A typical multivoltage power supply will say something
like ``100-240V50/60Hz,'' which means that it will accept anything
between 100 and 240 volts, at 50 to 60 cycles per second. If this
is the case, you only need an outlet adapter so that the
American-style plug will fit into a Russian outlet. Such adapters
are commonly available at airports and electronic stores throughout
the world. On the other hand, the power supply might say something
like 120V60, which indicates that only 120 volts is acceptable. In
this case, a transformer is needed to convert 220 volts from the
wall outlet to 120 volts. Radio Shack sells several models that
handle 50 to 1,500 watts. To estimate the wattage needed, look at
the label again to see the output in volts and amps. Multiply the
volts and amps to determine the number of watts; then add 50
percent as a safety margin to get a ball park figure for power. For
example: for an output of 6 volts at 2.2 amps, 6 times 2.2 equals
13.2, and 150 percent of that is about 20 watts. Most camcorders
should be able to use a 50-watt transformer, which costs about $20.
You'll still need outlet adapters, which cost a few dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Portrait of Tuebingen &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently painted a winter scene of Tuebingen, Germany, from
a photograph. It piqued my curiosity about this city, which is on
the banks of the Neckar River. Can you give me some information
about it? _ James J. Curry, Point Pleasant, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. You chose a very lovely subject for your canvas. Tuebingen,
in southwestern Germany, in the state of Baden-Wuerttemberg, is 25
miles south of Stuttgart. It has been a college town since 1477,
when the University of Tuebingen opened, and has produced such
luminaries as the astronomer Johannes Kepler and the philosopher
Georg Hegel. Although this community of 85,000 might not be as
famous as another German university city, Heidelberg, it is still
one of the prettiest cities in southern Germany. Steep, winding
streets rise up from the banks of the Neckar from the Am Markt, the
square that is at the center of the old quarter. Alumni of the
University of Michigan might want to know that Tuebingen is the
sister city of Ann Arbor, Mich., the home of that Big 10 school.
</P>
<P>
   Among its sights is the 15th-century Stiftskirche. The choir,
noted for its late-Gothic vaulting and ornate tracery, was probably
built around 1470. The relief figures in the north window openings,
most notably the one depicting the martyrdom of St. George, are
another highlight.
</P>
<P>
   The schloss (castle), above the city, has an Outer Gate built in
1606; the present building dates from the early 16th century and
rests on a site of a castle dating from the 11th century. In the
cellar are prison cells and an 18,700-gallon wine vat.
</P>
<P>
   The lower town has numerous half-timbered buildings facing the
Neckar. One of them, the Kornhaus, 10 Kornhausgasse, now contains
exhibits on the city's history and artifacts on printing and
publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the better hotels are in the heart of Tuebingen. The
Hotel Krone, 1 Uhlandstrasse, PLZ 72072, telephone (49-7071) 13310,
fax (49-7071) 133132, has 66 rooms and charges $108 to $166 for a
double, at 1.75 marks to $1. At the Hotel Domizil, 5-9
Woehrdstrasse, PLZ 72072, (49-7071) 1390, fax (49-7071) 139250,
double rates in the 120 rooms are $111 to $131. The 20-room
Landhotel Hirsch, 28 Schoenbuchstrasse, 72074, (49-7071) 68027, fax
(49-7071) 600803, charges $137 to $154 for a double. All these
rates include breakfast, and there are less expensive hotels away
from the heart of the city. The Tuebingen tourist office is at An
der Neckarbruecke, Postfach 2623, 72016 Tuebingen; (49-7071) 91360,
fax (49-7071) 35070.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
