<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRYPTOPHAN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRYPTOPHAN CONTAINS SUBSTANCE LINKED TO FATALITIES, REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A popular dietary supplement sold over the counter
in health stores contains low levels of a contaminant similar to a
substance implicated in 30 deaths and at least 1,500 cases of
nonfatal illness a decade ago, researchers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The supplement is 5-hydroxy-L-tryptophan, also known as
``5-HTP.'' It is recommended by alternative medicine practitioners
and health store operators for a variety of ailments, including
depression, insomnia, obesity and headache.
</P>
<P>
   Many health food enthusiasts turned to 5-HTP in the late 1980s
when a related substance, L-tryptophan, was withdrawn from the
market after being implicated in a nationwide outbreak of a
condition health experts identified as eosinophilia mylagia
syndrome (EMS).
</P>
<P>
   The condition was responsible for the death of 30 people and
about 1,500 cases of painful tissue damage associated with
increased levels of eosinophils (white blood cells).
</P>
<P>
   In an article to be published Tuesday in the scientific journal
Nature Medicine, scientists at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn.,
report finding low levels of a contaminant that is chemically
similar to contaminants found in L-tryptophan linked to the EMS
cases.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the contaminant, known simply as ``Peak X,'' is the
same as that found in 5-HTP linked to a 1991 case of EMS, said Mayo
researchers Stephen Naylor and Gerald Gleich.
</P>
<P>
   Although Naylor and Gleich acknowledged in a press briefing that
they knew of no cases of illness associated with current
preparations of 5-HTP, Gleich said he personally believed anyone
taking the supplement should stop.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known how many Americans take 5-HTP, which is but one
of hundreds of so-called ``natural'' products that made health food
supplements a $14 billion industry last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dangerous practice and anybody taking 5-HTP as a
dietary supplement should be aware of the risk that he or she is
running as a consequence of this action,'' said Gleich, a
physician. ``We have sufficient evidence that links the contaminant
to disease that we felt it's important to alert consumers to the
potential dangers.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the two scientists have known of the presence of Peak X
in 5-HTP for about two months, but withheld an announcement in
order to accommodate a requirement that papers published in Nature
Medicine not be publicized until the day the journal publishes
them. Such requirements are common among scientific journals.
</P>
<P>
   Gleich and Naylor said they had informed the FDA of their
findings. An FDA spokesman said the agency was studying 5-HTP in an
attempt to see if its chemists also could detect Peak X in current
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murray, a Seattle alternative medicine advocate and
author of a current popular book recommending 5-HTP for a variety
of illnesses, dismissed the Mayo report, saying the researchers had
used extremely sophisticated laboratory techniques to detect very
low levels of the contaminant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the clinical significance of this finding
is,'' said Naylor. He said Peak X never was definitely identified
as the cause of the only case of illness ever linked to it and
added that the Mayo finding did not affect his enthusiasm for
5-HTP.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
