<HEADER>
A1443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-BANK-680&AMP;ADD-NY     08-31 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANK-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECIDING FATE OF AILING JAPANESE BANK IS TEST CASE FOR GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ With markets crumbling at home and around the world, one
of Japan's very large, very frail banks is turning into a critical
test case for the government in its effort to prop up the financial
system here.
</P>
<P>
   The markets are watching nervously to see what happens to
Long-Term Credit Bank, which used to be one of the world's biggest
banks and now appears to be one of the world's shakiest. There is
broad agreement that a serious mistake in handling the bank could
amount to a new blow to international financial stability.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's parliament on Monday began discussions on what to do
with the bank, and the question goes to the heart of Japan's
efforts to revive its economy. Fundamentally, the question is what
to do with huge banks that are as weak as they are gigantic: can
Japan afford to let them fail? Can Japan afford not to let them
fail?
</P>
<P>
   The government of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi insists that
Long-Term Credit and others like it must be rescued, otherwise the
collapse of such a vast institution _ Long-Term Credit Bank has
$175 billion in assets _ would echo around the world and create new
panic.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Obuchi defended the bailout of Long-Term Credit
as the only way to avoid global financial consequences, saying ``it
would have a serious impact at home and abroad'' to leave the bank
to the mercy of market forces.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the government has been trying to force Long-Term Credit
Bank to merge with a stronger bank. Obuchi summoned the head of
Sumitomo Trust &AMP; Banking Co. to his residence to try to force him
to take it over.
</P>
<P>
   But while the government insists that its approach reduces the
risk of a global financial cataclysm, this approach has also turned
off investors who see it as just one more sign that Japan is afraid
of the pain of free markets and is unwilling to allow market
solutions. This perception among investors has added to the
weakness in the Japanese stock and currency markets and has further
eroded the already limited credibility of Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's parliament also began discussions Monday on whether to
use taxpayers' money to rescue the Long-Term Credit Bank, and it is
too soon to know how it will end up. Markets will be jittery in
either case.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition alliance and a wide swath of investors alike are
calling for a ``hard landing,'' a direct slap at the soft-landing
approach favored by the governing Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``A soft landing in Japan means a postponement of
difficulties,'' said Yoshio Suzuki, an opposition Liberal Party
member who was a former executive director of the Bank of Japan,
the nation's central bank. ``Our proposal is a scenario of a hard
landing.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that unhealthy banks, big or small, should be allowed
to fail, once a safety net is put in place. Even now, he said, the
Bank of Japan is prepared to pour liquidity into the marketplace
and to be the lender of last resort.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are furious at the thought of a rescue merger. They see
it as an old-style tactic that in the past has avoided the very
problems _ a weak capital base, piles of bad debt, poor management
and little financial disclosure _ that have festered within Japan's
banking system for years.
</P>
<P>
   `` Market knows best,'' said John Alkire, managing director at
Morgan Stanley Asset &AMP; Investment Trust Co.in Tokyo. ``They have to
kind of purge the system, clear the system and weed out the good
from the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is that there is a sense of welling anger among
investors who want a clear sign from the government that it will
shed its anti-market ways and adopt modern-style capitalism. In
short, they are daring the government to let a big bank go under.
</P>
<P>
   ``People kind of feel frustrated _ they've lost a lot of money
in Japan,'' said a senior manager of derivatives at a foreign
financial firm, who spoke on the condition he not be identified.
``They're saying, `Let's get some blood because bankers are
extremely highly paid.' They want a pound of flesh for gross
mismanagement.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The government, of course, is petrified of what happens when
banks fail: when they allowed the Hokkaido Takushoku Bank, the
nation's 20th-largest bank, to fail last November, the Nikkei index
of 225 issues soared initially on hopes that the government was
letting the market decide. But the euphoria was short-lived.
Financial chaos ensued, with the collapse of other institutions,
and foreign banks increased interest rates for loans to Japanese
financial institutions. Share prices plummeted, the economy in
Hokkaido (where the bank was based) took a nose-dive, and
government officials rued the day they let a big bank fail.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that while some investors want blood, they will
probably flee at the first sighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is looking for a `Showcase Failure,''' said Michael
Yoshino, a Japanese business expert and a professor at Harvard
Business School. ``Bankers say it wouldn't hurt for one, two, three
major banks to go out of business. But if something happens, it
could trigger a chain of events.''
</P>
<P>
   The concern is the risk of a systemic crisis. If the government
allows one bank to fail, then investors might sell shares in other
banks believed to be on the verge of collapse and such a selloff
could trigger a liquidity squeeze and send another bank under.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, other banks have already begun to worry. Sakura Bank
declared on Monday that it would expand its capital base by 300
billion yen, or about $2 billion, by raising funds from its
shareholding companies, like Toyota Motor Corp. and the Mitsui
Group of companies, which are in close business partnership with
Sakura.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, which itself was the result of a merger of two banks
in 1990, has been pinned down by the market as a weak bank that on
its own might have difficulties surviving the next few years of
financial revamping.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of financial experts are saying that since
allowing banks to collapse would be too terrifying for Japan's
banking system, another solution would be for the government to
nationalize insolvent banks, with the goal of breaking them up. The
Liberal Party is also proposing this as an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``A radical solution is needed,'' said an executive at a foreign
financial firm who spoke on the condition he not be named.
``Effectively, they've got to nationalize the banking system.''
</P>
<P>
   For other investors, however, this would be too far from a
market solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's watching the movie backward,'' Alkire at Morgan Stanley
said. ``I don't think you can nationalize. We're in a free
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
