<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1462 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENX-COUPES-TEX     08-31 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENX-COUPES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO MAKERS SEE TWENTYSOMETHINGS, BOOMERS AS NEW MARKET FOR COUPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID WELCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Automakers think they have something that both Generation Xers
and baby boomers will agree upon: that two-door coupes are cool.
</P>
<P>
   Waves of 20-somethings are graduating from college and getting
jobs, making empty nesters of their parents. Automakers see this as
an opportunity to sell sportier cars with a little personality
(read: coupes) to both younger buyers with a taste for style, and
the baby boomers who no longer need minivans.
</P>
<P>
   So several automakers have been introducing new two-door models.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics _ including several analysts and consultants _ are
quick to point out that coupe sales have been dropping for years,
while motorists are climbing into trucks, sport utilities and
sedans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risky segment to go in because it's been a declining
segment,'' acknowledged Alan DeCarr, vice president of sales for
Toyota Motor Sales USA in Torrance, Calif, which just introduced
its new Camry Solara mid-size coupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people used to be at a stage where they needed a
minivan,'' he added. ``Where do these people go when they get out
of a minivan?''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the market hasn't shown much interest in coupes yet.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for all coupes, ranging in size from the small Honda Civic
to the burly Cadillac Eldorado, dropped 18 percent in 1996 and
another 9 percent in 1997, according to Ward's Automotive Reports,
a Detroit trade publication. Since 1995, sales have dropped 25
percent to 1.8 million vehicles a year, according to Ward's.
Figures for this year have not been tabulated yet.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, coupes such as Geo Metro, Eagle Talon,
Ford Thunderbird and Probe have become extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Still, automakers keep introducing new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Honda redesigned the two-door Accord last year, Chrysler
released the Sebring and Dodge Avenger two years ago, while General
Motors in the past two years has launched coupe versions of the
Oldsmobile Alero and Pontiac Grand Am and Grand Prix, just to name
a few.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota, for one, explicitly cites baby boomers when discussing
the target audience for coupe. Marketing brass at Toyota reckon
that something like 1.5 million people become empty-nesters every
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the notion that a coupe is a reward vehicle for
empty-nesters has surprised some analysts and consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's manufacturers, despite all evidence to the contrary,
insisting that American auto buyers haven't changed since the
1960s,'' said Eric Noble, principal of Auto Pacific Inc., an
automotive consulting and research firm in Santa Ana, Calif. ``The
reality is, a coupe is not a reward, it's a punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Noble said that only 20 percent of consumers age 50 to 64 that
now drive a mid-size car, such as a Camry, will consider buying a
two-door car next time they shop, according to a survey by Auto
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of buyers in their 30s driving a mid-size car
would consider a two-door, and 29 percent of buyers in the same
segment in their 40s would consider one.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason coupes have been losing popularity is because
they don't offer much in exchange for sacrificing two doors, Noble
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you get in return for what you give up?'' Noble asked.
``Absolutely nothing. You can't even say that most of them get that
much more sex appeal by eliminating the back doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, cars like Pontiac Grand Prix have bold styling and don't
lose much with four doors, said Jim Wangers, senior analyst with
Warren, Mich.-based Automotive Marketing Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry insiders won't dispute that the coupe segment has
been shrinking. But some are still optimistic about finding a
profitable niche.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Caddell, general product manager for Chrysler's small-car
operations, insists that two-door cars aren't dying out.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell pointed out that the large coupe segment is hurting the
most. Cadillac, for instance, has made sales gains with all of its
models in the first half of 1998 (before the GM strike) except the
Eldorado, a coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Honda has had success with the two-door Accord, selling 5,000 to
6,000 a month in the United States. Where manufacturers like to
keep 60 days worth of models in their inventory, Honda dealers have
just 10 days worth of two-door Accords, said Art Garner, a Honda
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But even with brisk sales, the coupe accounts for just 20
percent of Accord sales.
</P>
<P>
   Chyrsler's Caddell says the middle of the coupe segment is where
the growth is. That was Chrysler's thinking when the company
brought out the Dodge Avenger and Chrysler Sebring coupes, which
now sell about 80,000 cars a year.
</P>
<P>
   To sell successfully, coupes must have style, comfort and sporty
performance that beats most family sedans but aren't as aggressive
as hot rods or performance sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's Mercury division is chasing younger buyers with the
redesigned Cougar, said Charles Richardson, Cougar assistant brand
manager in Irvine, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury thinks the car will be a success because its styling is
more aggressive than most competitors, and it's fresher than
top-selling two-doors like the Chevrolet Cavalier, Dodge Avenger,
Mitsubishi Eclipse and Saturn SC2, Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   The risk to automakers in launching new coupes is plunging
vehicle development dollars into the segment.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that Ford probably spent about $500 million to
develop the new Cougar, which is built on the Ford Contour/Mercury
Mystique platform. Using an existing platform reduces costs, but
redesign is still expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota has hedged its costs with Solara by sharing parts with
the Camry. And the company is keeping its expectations in check
with plans to build just 40,000 to 50,000 vehicles in its first
full calender of production next year, DeCarr said.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Toyota sold almost 400,000 Camrys in 1997, making
it the best-selling passenger car in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way to do it, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Wangers said coupes aren't dead. They will find some empty-nest
buyers. And healthy sales among vehicles like the Grand Am two-door
and Chevy Cavalier and Pontiac Sunfire coupes show that young
buyers like them.
</P>
<P>
   As long as automakers keep their expectations realistic, a new
coupe can win, the analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
