<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, September 1, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-CORRECT _ Stocks' dismal performance in August removes any
doubt that the market is headed for a serious correction if not a
bear market. A careening selloff, paced by steep losses in some key
blue-chip technology issues, has sent major market averages into
the worst slump since last October's decline. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Charts will be posted on the server by 8 p.m. EDT. One set
of charts will include the Dow year to date, a pull out of the Dow
for August and an hour-by-hour chart of today's activity (size
still being determined). A second set of charts will be one column
wide and probable three inches deep each and will include charts of
the S&AMP;P 500, the NASDAQ andf the Russell index.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DOW-IMPACT _ With the decline in stocks, what's the impact on
mutual funds and retirement plans such as 401ks.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-READERBOX _ A short list of how today's market activity
affects consumers. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DAYTRADE _ A look at a growing pastime that, like gambling, can
make the player a lot of money or clean him out. It's day trading
in the stock market, where players head to personal computer
parlors and buy and sell stock all day. We have joints in Boca
Raton and West Palm Beach. (Pounds, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CNN-LAWSUIT _ CNN has filed a federal lawsuit against The Net
Inc., a New York corporation, alleging that The Net is abusing
CNN's trademark by using its name for a pornographic web site.
CNN's popular web site, CNN.COM, has 30 million visitors a week.
The net's site is CNN.ORG. suit filed in federal court Friday.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   REXALL-CLOSING _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Rexall Sundown Inc. plans to
close an Idaho vitamin manufacturing plant and will shift
production to its Boca Raton and Deerfield Beach facilities. About
12 to 18 of the Idaho plant's 110 employees are interested in
transferring to South Florida and have been offered jobs, Rexall
President Damon DeSantis said recently. The rest decided not to
apply and will be laid off, DeSantis said. (Galewitz, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-INSURANCE _ The coast is clear now, but would-be home buyers
and sellers should watch the Atlantic for storms that could
abruptly stop residential real estate deals. When a tropical storm
or hurricane blows into the box _ stretching from the Gulf of
Mexico to the Dominican Republic and from North Carolina to
Honduras _ the two state-created insurers of last resort won't
issue policies. (Owers, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-COMPUTER _ Next to deciding whether to go to class on a
regular basis, picking a computer to use at college is one of the
biggest decisions a student makes. Two-thirds of college students,
responding to a poll commissioned by Sprint, named the computer the
most important back-to-school item. It ranked ahead of calculators,
stereos and televisions. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ Perhaps it is something left over from the film
``2001,'' but I have always felt rather self-conscious talking to a
computer. Nonetheless, since publishers are claiming great strides
recently in the advancement of voice recognition systems, I am
talking to mine on a regular basis these days. The results are
mixed, at best. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ As the Internet has grown in popularity, so has its
appeal to criminals. They're using it increasingly to steal,
defraud and conduct scams. All is not lost, though. There are
plenty of ways to protect yourself. Many of the methods are
described in the September issue of PC World. The magazine
describes how to foil hackers and thieves, block junk e-mail and
scams and protect your credit card number. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ The low computer prices are real. But they can be
misleading, too. I'm not saying the stores are trying to deceive
you. What I am saying is that _ once you get in the store _ you may
find that the bargain basement PCs aren't for you. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ The developers of Mariner Write are nothing if not
courageous. They are releasing their simple but powerful word
processor just at the time when more and more people are playing it
safe by choosing Microsoft software. Maybe Write's developers hope
there's still a niche market for those looking for an inexpensive
alternative to Word 98, Microsoft's latest version of its word
processor. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ If you've ever seen the results for one of those
surveys about what kind of television people watch, you know most
of us favor educational programs and care nothing at all for the
shows that flaunt sex, violence and lowbrow humor. It's the same
with the Internet's World Wide Web. If you ask your co-workers and
friends how they use the Web, you'll find that almost all of them
are engaged in serious research. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Even when the stock market goes kablooey, as it did
last week, there are people who still want to get into it. ``How,''
a tenderfoot bargain hunter asked the other day, ``does a person
buy stock if he doesn't have thousands to put into a brokerage
account?'' It's a good question. There are two good answers _
mutual funds that will open very small accounts and direct purchase
or no-load stocks. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
