<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-0901-C     08-31 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, YELTSIN TO OPEN SUMMIT AS RUSSIA POLITICAL CRISIS
DEEPENS
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-PRIMER-0901.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Clinton begins a two-day summit in Russia on
Tuesday much like a tourist searching out a familiar landmark, only
to find it in shambles and with the repairmen brawling.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in Moscow early Tuesday (scheduled to arrive
7:40 a.m. local time/11:40 p.m. EDT Monday) with no one in charge
and officials warning that the country was on the verge of
political and economic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist-dominated Duma, the lower house of parliament,
soundly rejected President Boris Yeltsin's nominee for prime
minister by a more than 2-to-1 margin on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After the embarrassing vote, Yeltsin resubmitted Viktor
Chernomyrdin's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But the impasse left Russia without a permanent government amid
the most serious power rift since Yeltsin ordered army tanks to
fire on dissident parliament leaders in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection of Chernomyrdin also prolonged the uncertainty of
how and when Russia will embark on a plan to fortify the plummeting
ruble and salvage a banking system about to disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   Before departing Washington for Moscow, Clinton said his goal
was to keep Russia ``on the path of reform'' -- and hold Yeltsin,
or his possible successors to a pledge to seek democracy and free
markets since the fall of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But in Moscow, the summit Tuesday and Wednesday between Clinton
and Yeltsin, their first since March 1997, was an after-thought
among anxious Russians. In contrived events planned well before
Russia's crisis erupted, Clinton will dart from one photo
opportunity to another -- laying a wreath at Russia's Tomb of the
Unknowns, visiting a school on the first day of classes and
speaking at a school for international relations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also will hold talks with Yeltsin, Chernomyrdin and
opposition parliamentary leaders. But economic turmoil -- not NATO
expansion or nuclear disarmament or the list of usual U.S.-Russia
topics -- will rule the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In just about the only area of agreement since the crisis
erupted in August, both Kremlin officials and their Communist
opponents warned Monday that the outcome of their dispute could be
disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fail to reach an agreement here, everything will spill
out to the streets,'' said Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this chaos lasts for several more weeks, it may happen that
there will be neither Communists nor us,'' warned Yeltsin's
parliamentary envoy, Alexander Kotenkov. ``I mean a popular
uprising, merciless and senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's second-largest nuclear power is threatened with a
crisis which may take the post-Soviet market reforms with it,
leaving much of what the United States and other Western nations
have sought for Russia in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ```What I want to do is to go there and tell them that the easy
thing to do is not the right thing to do,'' Clinton said, referring
to pressure on Yeltsin from the Communists to enact Soviet-style
controls on industry and banking. ``The easy thing to do would be
to go back to the way they did it before, and it's not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional leaders, including House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., questioned the wisdom of Clinton's trip to Moscow
and its buzzsaw of economic and political problems.
</P>
<P>
   The view from Moscow is that the summit could certainly do no
further harm to the politically enfeebled and isolated Yeltsin. The
trip also allows the United States to broaden its contacts with a
range of political figures -- and potential new leaders in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only thing more dangerous that a nuclear power with
despotic leaders, is a nuclear power with feeble ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things that the United States cannot afford,
and Number 1 is chaos in Russia. There are too many nuclear
weapons,'' said Viktor Kremenhyuk, an analyst at the U.S.A.-Canada
Institute, a Moscow think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message to the Russians is much like the message from
a well-meaning hospital visitor at the bedside of a friend: Stay
the course on Western free-market reforms and you'll be on your
feet in no time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economies are increasingly interconnected ... The reason I
am going to Russia is because we have learned the hard way that
problems that develop beyond our borders find sooner or later their
way to our doorstep unless we help our friends and neighbors to
deal with them as quickly as possible,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to imagine what tangible support Clinton can
offer in the way of international help at a time when America's
economy is showing signs of decline and Congress is reluctant to
approve further foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has warned it will
withhold installments on a $22.6 billion support package if Russia
does not stick to economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to calm the fears of the Russian public, Chernomyrdin
announced Monday that the government would guarantee the savings of
every investor in Russia. The question is how, when the government
already cannot afford to pay salaries on time and repay its foreign
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who served as prime minister from 1992 until March
of this year, was derided by parliament, who called him responsible
for many of Russia's current problems. The vote for confirmation
was 94 for and 253 against; 105 Duma members did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament leaders agreed to hold talks Tuesday to formulate a
list of alternative candidates for prime minister to submit to
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists and other opposition parties want a prominent
place in the new government, including cabinet seats and a role in
shaping domestic policy.
</P>
<P>
   But if he was still seeking a compromise with the Kremlin after
the vote Monday, the Communist Party leader wasn't sounding
conciliatory. Zyuganov said Chernomyrdin ``does not possess a
single quality necessary for leading the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners also renewed calls for Yeltsin to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president must guarantee that he will resign after the
government is formed,'' Viktor Ilyukhin, a Communist member of the
Duma said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constitution, the Duma can vote three times on a prime
minister's nomination. If rejected, Yeltsin can appoint a prime
minister by decree and dissolve the legislature. New elections then
would take place within three months. But that kind of political
brinkmanship could also bring Yeltsin's regime crashing down.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
