<HEADER>
A1492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIWA-U.S.-850&AMP;ADD-NY     08-31 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIWA-U.S.-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE SECURITIES FIRM SEEKS U.S. INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yoshinari Hara, president and chief executive of Daiwa
Securities, is on a mission to New York this week to sell ratings
agencies, financial institutions and investors on the merits of a
purely Japanese securities firm.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese securities firms have struggled ever since the bubble
economy burst nearly a decade ago. Now deregulation has made things
worse, opening the firms to intense competition from foreign
concerns with expertise in products and services they know little
about.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders have already made big gains in Tokyo Stock Exchange
trading and pension-fund management. Merrill Lynch has taken over
Yamaichi Securities, and Salomon Smith Barney is in a joint venture
with Nikko Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Only Nomura Securities, the brawny leader of Japan's securities
firms, has a chance to survive as an independent, many analysts
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   So in July, when Daiwa, Japan's No. 2 brokerage, announced an
alliance with Sumitomo Bank, it was greeted with something verging
on disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo, Japan's No. 2 bank after the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi,
is the core of the keiretsu, or business group, that includes
Daiwa, and the alliance was largely seen as just another case of
circling the wagons.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Services, which had already put four Daiwa
subsidiaries on notice for a possible downgrade, said the
announcement did little to dispel its concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it lends credibility and substance to the group,''
Leslie Muranyi, senior analyst at Moody's in New York, said of the
alliance. ``But it doesn't provide any new products or services, it
doesn't create a new management structure, and it doesn't provide a
substantial inflow of new ideas and know-how.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ayako Sato, an analyst at Warburg Dillon Read, wrote in a
report, ``We should not expect too much from this merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Hara and his new adviser, Wilbur Ross, a high-profile turnaround
strategist at Rothschild Inc., beg to differ. They see room for a
purely Japanese firm and say Daiwa is redesigning itself to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might get higher marks from overseas markets if we tie up
with overseas partners,'' Hara said. ``But since we will be
focusing our business in the Japanese market with Japanese
customers and clients, it is their evaluation that is important.''
</P>
<P>
   That is only partly true. A downgrade by Moody's would push the
ratings of Daiwa's four subsidiaries to junk-bond status, greatly
raising the cost of borrowing abroad.
</P>
<P>
   And with Japanese companies increasingly reliant on capital
markets, not banks, for financing, global investors cannot be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Ross was retained. ``We wanted to know how we look
from the viewpoint of an overseas business consultant,'' Hara said.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, foreign consultants are usually retained merely as
window dressing. But so far, Ross has operated much the way he
would if working for an American company, calling reporters,
analysts and creditors to sing the praises of the Sumitomo alliance
and pushing Hara to do interviews, including this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge operation in an industry undergoing immense
change,'' said Ross, who has branched out from advising creditors
in bankruptcy cases to representing some of Asia's deeply troubled
corporations. ``Daiwa is undergoing probably the most radical
change of any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and reporters, he argued, have missed the fact that the
Sumitomo alliance will bring $1.25 billion to $2 billion to Daiwa
above and beyond the capital that will be transferred to the three
joint ventures Daiwa will form with the bank.
</P>
<P>
   That chunk of change _ which Ross said would be largely
tax-free, when counted against previous tax losses _ would buy
Daiwa the technical infrastructure it needs, with enough left over
to lure a few foreign professionals to manage new businesses like
derivatives and other exotic securities.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Muranyi, though, said there was nothing in the numbers
he had seen to indicate that Daiwa would get anything close to that
amount from Sumitomo. He is expected to meet with Daiwa officials
and Ross soon.
</P>
<P>
   Ross also said analysts had not taken adequate account of
Daiwa's strengths in retail brokerage and investment banking and of
the way they will be enhanced by an overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``They, meaning Daiwa, haven't done a very good job of telling
people what this means,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Muranyi and other analysts agree that theoretically there are
benefits to the structure Daiwa is adopting, but they say the proof
will be in the pudding.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is predicated on a reorganization of Daiwa
Securities into a holding company, a structure illegal in Japan
until recently.
</P>
<P>
   That structure, set to be in place by spring, is regarded at
Daiwa as an open invitation to foreign partners, and Hara says he
is in discussions with several foreign firms about running the new
asset-management subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Making an alliance with a separate subsidiary carries far less
risk of exposure to the parent's liabilities, which has been a
major concern of foreign investors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Seven subsidiaries will reside under the Daiwa Securities Group
umbrella. A retail brokerage will be a wholly owned subsidiary
while ownership of three other subsidiaries _ in investment
banking, asset management and risk management _ will be shared with
Sumitomo.
</P>
<P>
   With 300 billion yen in capital, the Daiwa-Sumitomo investment
bank will have the biggest cushion in Japan, Hara said. The
combination of Sumitomo's and Daiwa's asset management groups will
bring together some 3 trillion yen, or almost $21 billion, in
assets _ a drop in the bucket next to the more than $1 trillion
controlled by Merrill Lynch, but a decent-size pool for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   As a holding company, Daiwa may be better able to control costs
by more accurately assessing return on capital for each subsidiary
and using the flexibility the structure gives it to cut labor
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Hara regards Daiwa's commitment to the structure as a clear sign
of its commitment to new ideas. ``It takes a lot of courage to go
ahead and establish a holding company when no one else has done
it,'' he said. ``But we have decided to become a trend-setter. We
have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
