<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLINE FOR AN APPEAL IN EXPLOSIVE CASE NEARS IN ALBANY, N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Tinmes Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ September seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Circle that date on your calendar. That's Sol Greenberg's
deadline to file an appeal in the Jermaine Henderson case.
</P>
<P>
   You might have heard about all this. In October, a black college
student named Jermaine Henderson got into a flap in a bar with a
couple of white, off-duty Albany cops _ a guy named Sean McKenna
and one named William Bonanni. Henderson either did or did not
sucker-punch one of the cops. They busted him and either did or did
not beat the hell out of him later while he was in cuffs in a
police garage.
</P>
<P>
   The office of District Attorney Greenberg was to prosecute
Henderson. A special prosecutor, a lawyer named John Dorfman, was
named by a judge at Greenberg's request to prosecute the cops.
Somehow, though, both prosecutors screwed up the cases, and a judge
threw them all out.
</P>
<P>
   Now leaders of Albany's minority community are furious. They're
begging the federal government to investigate the case as a
potential civil rights violation. Mayor Jerry Jennings pledged to
pursue administrative charges against the cops. That now seems on
hold, however.
</P>
<P>
   Given the complexity of all this, it occurs to me that you might
have a few questions. Well, fire away: Q. Did Henderson really hit
the cop? Did the cops really beat him up when he was in custody?
</P>
<P>
   A. Beats me. I wasn't there. We'll probably never know unless
either or both of these cases make their way into a courtroom with
everybody testifying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did the prosecutors blow this?
</P>
<P>
   A. Each of them let their witnesses testify before separate
grand juries without first getting the witnesses to waive immunity
from prosecution for whatever they said. Under New York law, they
were golden from then on. Dorfman says he let Henderson testify
with immunity because he figured the case against the cops was
hotter stuff. It's not at all clear why Greenberg's office even
bothered with a grand jury. Henderson was charged with a
misdemeanor. The D.A. doesn't need grand jury action to prosecute
that.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would an appeals court would reinstate the charges?
</P>
<P>
   A. Who knows? Dorfman is appealing in the case against the cops.
So far, Greenberg shows no inclination to appeal in the case
against Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why not?
</P>
<P>
   A. His critics surmise _ and they're saying it openly _ that
Greenberg doesn't want anybody prosecuted, especially the cops. The
district attorney works very closely with the police department, of
course. They're charging that he doesn't want testimony in open
court that could incriminate those police officers. He also, by the
way, refuses to go to a judge to get Dorfman authority to prosecute
the cops on perjury charges for what they told the grand jury.
Without that, Dorfman probably doesn't have jurisdiction to go
after them.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why won't Greenberg do that?
</P>
<P>
   A. He claims that the existing court order gives Dorfman enough
authority to go after perjury. Legal people intimately familiar
with the case have told me that's just wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Then, just to be sure, why doesn't Greenberg ask for an
expansion of Dorfman's authority?
</P>
<P>
   A. Good question. By the way, do you smell something really
foul? I could swear that something has died around here.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will the feds get into this?
</P>
<P>
   A. They won't say. Bear in mind that the federal government is
under Democratic control, and Albany is one of the nation's great
Democratic party strongholds. Everybody we're talking about here is
a Democrat. Also, the mayor hasn't asked them to intervene. He has
howled about prosecutorial ineptitude, but that may have less to do
with concern about possible police brutality than with making sure
that neither Dorfman nor Larry Weist, Greenberg's chief deputy,
ends up as D.A. in a few years when Greenberg leaves office.
Jennings plans to back somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you ever heard of a thing like this before?
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure _ decades ago in places where politicians have names
like Billy Bob and Jimmy Joe. But in a northern city at the close
of the 20th century? Uh-uh.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
