<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-ECON-575&AMP;ADD     08-31 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ECON-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIAN PRIME MINISTER TAKES A DIFFERENT ECONOMIC TACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK Thailand _ Driving what he said was the only Asian car
to be parachuted onto the North Pole, Malaysia's prime minister led
what he called the world's longest motorcade this weekend, a convoy
of 1,988 Malaysian-made cars.
</P>
<P>
   It was cheaper than building the world's tallest building,
highest airport control tower or loftiest flagpole _ all of which
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad accomplished when Malaysia was
flush with cash during Asia's miracle years.
</P>
<P>
   But the message was the same. As one group of spectators shouted
while the six-mile-long motorcade drove through the rain on Sunday:
``Malaysia can!''
</P>
<P>
   Boosterism is getting tougher these days as the country's
economic troubles deepen into recession and embolden the political
opposition to Mahathir's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But the 72-year-old prime minister is fighting back. In what has
been, by Malaysian standards, a lurid back-room brawl, he has
sidelined his increasingly assertive deputy prime minister, Anwar
Ibrahim, and seized control of economic policy in a gamble on the
country's future.
</P>
<P>
   Turning away from the tight fiscal policies Anwar had been
pursuing as finance minister, Mahathir this month reasserted the
expansionist approach he has always favored, lowering interest
rates and raising government spending.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, 51, who represents a younger political generation, has
been Mahathir's heir apparent for the last six years, promising a
very different, more liberal future for the country.
</P>
<P>
   The odd but successful coupling of their two different styles
and philosophies has been strained over the last year as the
economy soured and as Mahathir rattled foreign investors with his
attacks on currency speculators, neo-colonialists and Jews, all of
whom he said were trying to ruin Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar was left to placate critics and at times to correct
Mahathir's statements, and his profile and popularity rose _
dangerously, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, at the annual general assembly of the ruling
party, Umno, Anwar's supporters tested their strength, mounting a
tentative challenge to Mahathir's leadership. One speech raised
accusations of corruption and nepotism _ code words drawn from the
opposition in Indonesia that successfully toppled former President
Suharto in May.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash was swift. Three editors seen to be aligned with
Anwar were forced from their jobs. The governor of the central bank
and his deputy _ also seen as close to Anwar _ stepped down in
protest against the changes in economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   And Anwar's clout was undermined by the appointment of his
predecessor as finance minister, Daim Zainuddin, as a special
economic adviser to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar got the message and has retreated from the limelight,
ostentatiously supporting Mahathir with statements like, ``Compared
to the prime minister I am just a student; I cannot fight my
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar is still alive politically, but he is severely wounded,
political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This latest episode has forced open the whole succession
question,'' said Razak Baginda, executive director of the Malaysian
Strategic Research Center. ``A year ago, I would have told you, no
question that it is going to be Anwar. Now I think almost everybody
has doubts that he'll make it to be No. 1.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But as in Indonesia and other nations suffering through Asia's
economic crisis, political maneuvering, even by a master, is no
longer enough. Economic hardships, often subject to forces beyond
national borders, can force political change, as they have already
done in Thailand, South Korea and Japan as well as in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Malaysia announced that it had fallen into its
first recession in 13 years, with its economy shrinking by close to
7 percent after a decade of growth of more than 8 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The construction sector _ a key barometer of economic health _
was down by 22 percent in the second quarter of the year, compared
with 12 percent growth in the same period last year, the central
bank announced. Nationwide unemployment rose to 6.7 percent in a
country that until recently had to import workers to fill its
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the currency has lost 40 percent of its
value against the dollar, and the stock market has lost 75 percent
of its total worth. More than 2,600 people are losing their jobs
every week, according to the Human Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, with Daim crafting an economic policy closer to
Mahathir's heart, the government launched a stimulus package called
the National Economic Recovery Plan. It aims to hold down
unemployment and keep businesses alive by lowering interest rates,
pouring money into construction projects and financing lending by
debt-ridden banks.
</P>
<P>
   The plan goes against economic orthodoxy and the prescriptions
fostered in the region by international lenders. Daim described it
as ``a package of programs to restructure the financial and
corporate sectors without abandoning our social agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also broke with the government's insistence on rosy
pronouncements, conceding, ``We are facing reality now and saying
the good old days will not return.''
</P>
<P>
   The period of denial in Malaysia is over, said an artist who,
like many people in Malaysia, insisted that his name not be printed
for fear of political repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nerves are raw now,'' the artist said, adding that he was
speaking for his friends in Malaysia's middle class. ``We know
things are going to be very hard, going to be terrible. So people
are watching really carefully. There's no way anymore to go about
hoodwinking the public.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean you can't have a big party, maybe even the
biggest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   For its national day celebration Monday, Malaysian officials
were preparing what they call the world's biggest beach party,
along with the world's biggest outdoor buffet, honored with the
world's biggest pop-up greeting card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
