<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a three-page package of stories
relating to the political turmoil in Russia and Tuesday's
Clinton-Yeltsin summit talks.
</P>
<P>
   The ledeall will move by  &UR; 9 p.m. Eastern time &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RDP (Moscow) _ Acting Prime Minister Chernomyrdin is
rejected by the Russian parliament on its first vote on confirming
his appointment; other developments. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   This story will move by  &UR; 7:30 p.m. ET &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT (Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina) _ With her bold
public stands undermined by irresolution in the White House and her
experience rendered less relevant by new economic crises, Madeleine
Albright has had a tough 20 months as secretary of state. A look at
Albright's role in the midst of the Russia crisis. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE (Paris) _ In the eyes of many of his fellow
leaders and ordinary people around the world, President Clinton has
suffered a loss of stature following investigations of his private
life and his admission that he had an inappropriate relationship
with a White House intern in the Oval Office. But he has lost
little of the authority and power conferred on him by the
presidency. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move by  &UR; 8 p.m. ET: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RESCUE (Undated) _ How to rescue the Russian economy? The
choices seem limited to just three: Tighten Moscow's direct control
over the economy and adopt foreign exchange controls; strike a new
compromise with the International Monetary Fund, paying at least
lip service to tight money, budget balancing and orderly debt
restructuring; or, most radically, link the country's finances to a
strong foreign currency like the dollar. The trouble is that the
choice Russia seems to be leaning toward, a populist package of
command and control measures, is one that seems the most likely to
lead to hyperinflation, social unrest and a lurch toward
nationalism. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUMMIT (Moscow) _ In the midst of the political and
financial turmoil, the Russians are preparing to host President
Clinton at Tuesday's summit meeting. What do they want out of it at
this point? By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   This story will move by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. ET: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DEBATE (Moscow) _ A look at the opposition in parliament
led by the Communists; the debate, the theater, the politics. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, RUSSIA-CLINTON, skedded earlier, is now scratched, with
spot elements folded into other Russia stories as needed.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
