<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1514 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOOSE-TEACHERS-COX     08-31 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOOSE-TEACHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Readin', writin' and wranglin': The annual clash between parents
and educators begins
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When school reformers demand ``choice'' in public
education, they usually mean the right for parents to choose their
kids' schools, a practice that some systems allow. But there's a
subtler choice movement afoot, and it's affecting probably every
public school in the country.
</P>
<P>
   More and more parents of elementary students are demanding to
choose the teachers who will educate their kids. They write letters
during the summer requesting particular instructors. When classroom
assignments are posted, some receive their wishes, while
disappointed parents park themselves in front offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now every principal can expect to be confronted with this
during the opening of schools,'' says Crawford Lewis, DeKalb
County, Ga.'s executive director of instruction. Lewis, who was a
principal for 13 years, says, ``It's become bigger and bigger every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The cause of this behavior is open to debate. Regardless of
whether it's because of the changing quality of teachers, or a
tendency among '90s parents to obsess over their children, the tug
of war over teacher choice gives administrators a stomachache.
</P>
<P>
   June Million, spokesman for the National Association of
Elementary School Principals, says, ``It is one of the most talked
about things when principals get together.''
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, schools give parents free rein to choose teachers.
But many do at least consider requests. In the absence of hard and
fast rules, each principal has a different approach and policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put gag orders on people. I don't say we won't
listen,'' says Lee Friedman, principal at Sarah Smith Elementary in
Atlanta. ``But we won't promise anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, at Oak Grove Elementary in Cherokee County, Ga.,
parents may submit requests for teachers. ``We try to give them due
consideration,'' says Principal Tommy Daniel.
</P>
<P>
   But such requests aren't considered at Haynes Bridge Middle
School in Alpharetta, Ga. ``Parents can write a letter and discuss
the type of learning environment and teaching style they want,''
says Principal Debbie Reeves. ``They cannot request a particular
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves says this policy is a necessity because of logistics.
``Let's be realistic. What happens if you have 1,000 parents that
request one specific teacher?''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Swahn, president of the North Fulton (County, Ga.) Council
of PTAs, agrees. Accepting requests from parents creates a
``scheduling nightmare'' and makes the principal prey to too many
pressures, she says. ``I don't like to see a principal be a
pushover.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, say other parents. What if it's your child who
happens to be miserable?
</P>
<P>
   Tarin Hampton's son Jamiel had problems communicating with his
fourth-grade teacher.``She didn't really baby them,'' Hampton says.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting the teacher and reaching an impasse, Hampton tried
to get Jamiel switched to another class at his school. ``Their
response was, `We don't do it just because parents ask. We try to
rectify the problem.'''
</P>
<P>
   That solution didn't satisfy Hampton, who eventually moved
Jamiel, now an eighth-grader, to a ``theme school.''
</P>
<P>
   Other parents would rather fight than switch schools.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Dale says she requested that her younger daughter,
Naomi, not be assigned to a particular team of sixth-grade teachers
at Inman Middle School in Atlanta. She wanted to avoid a teacher
who, she says, failed to challenge her older son, Avery, leaving
him so bored he got into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help. Naomi got just the teacher she didn't want. So
Barbara Dale pitched a fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was this madwoman,'' she says, sounding abashed. ``I think
it was terribly inappropriate. But I got exactly what I went in
there for.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with being a squeaky wheel, says Cathy
Henson, president of the Georgia PTA, whose child attends a Cobb
County, Ga. school. With school choice a hot topic among activists,
parents should have the basic choice, ``the ability to choose your
child's teacher,'' she argues. Henson says parents know the needs
of their children as well as administrators do.
</P>
<P>
   Henson's concern, though, is that active parents who volunteer
regularly are given a de facto choice. The principal assigns their
children to A-list teachers without being asked, as a form of
reward. Other parents, who might request those teachers, are told
that the school doesn't honor requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should have the right to request certain teachers,''
Henson says, ``and it should be extended to all parents, not just
the ones fortunate enough to be at the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Most principals will defend the quality of their teachers,
however, and deny the suggestion that they harbor incompetents. ``I
have two children here myself. I'd put them in anybody's class
because I do not have a weak teacher,'' says Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis says teacher assignments aren't made as rewards for
parents. He says classes are assembled by teachers and principals
according to other more important criteria: a diverse mix of
abilities, gender, race and background and a good match between
teaching and learning styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to stick to your guns,'' he says. ``You're not a
principal for the PTA folks, you're a principal for all the
folks.''
</P>
<P>
   If a parent is convinced that the child must switch teachers, it
can often be done. But it takes time, says Toni
Furman-Eichelberger, a school mother pursuing a doctorate in
education at Clark Atlanta University and writing a dissertation on
parental involvement in schools. Furman-Eichelberger says parents
who work within the system ``can get anything they want that is
conducive to the best educational experience for the child.''
</P>
<P>
   But trying to pick the best teachers is often problematic, says
Gary Henry, director of Georgia's Council for School Performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like trying to outguess the experts in the stock
market,'' says Henry, a professor at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   Parents sometimes base their choices on personal relationships
rather than ability. ``It's a fact that it's a headache for the
principals,'' says Henry, who suggests that parents turn that
energy toward helping kids with their homework.
</P>
<P>
   Karen LeBleu, a fifth-grade teacher, says being chosen by a
parent is an ego boost, but not a reliable indicator of teacher
quality. ``Just because they don't choose a certain teacher doesn't
mean that teacher isn't well-qualified,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and principals are divided as to why this generation is
more intent than the previous one on managing its offspring's
school experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have less stability in the teaching force. Parents know
fewer of the teachers from year to year,'' which leads to
insecurity and doubts, says Henry.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Dale says she thinks her parents ``were satisfied with
less,'' and that today there is more pressure to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel, a principal, points out that baby boomer parents grew up
questioning authority. ``Maybe this generation is holding public
agencies more accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it's because parents hold themselves less
accountable, says Friedman. ``I think to a great extent we don't
take responsibility for our own actions, and (we) tend to place
blame on others,'' he says. ``If the kid's not getting along with
the teacher, then it's the teacher's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
