<HEADER>
A1515 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOOSE-TEACHERS-TIPS-     08-31 0251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOOSE-TEACHERS-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to get class changed
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Toni Furman-Eichelberger, who is pursuing a doctorate
in education at Clark Atlanta University, has become something of a
parent's advocate in the DeKalb County and Atlanta school systems.
She contends that only about 2 percent of students are ill-suited
to their teachers. But if you must switch your child, this is how:
</P>
<P>
   _ Be familiar with the school. Volunteer; spend time helping in
the classroom. Observe the class.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to work with the teacher. Keep an open mind. Document your
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never criticize the teacher in front of the child. ``If you
feed that child with negative information, he's going to be
negative in that class.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If, after three meetings with the teacher, there is still a
problem, then begin working with the principal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Base your request on educational needs. For example: ``I would
like for my child to have this particular teacher because of my
son's strong interest in science and this teacher's master's in
science.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Failing a satisfactory solution, move up the chain of command
to the school board.
</P>
<P>
   Can parents succeed in getting action? ``People do not know how
powerful parents are in the school,'' Furman-Eichelberger says.
``Believe me, if they stay calm and rational and have legitimate
reasons, they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
