<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUPREE-SHOW-COX     08-31 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPREE-SHOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV Preview: ``Nathalie Dupree Entertains''
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOCIAL CIRCLE, Ga. _ A serene Nathalie Dupree is staring at
dozens of cardboard boxes stacked waist high in an upstairs bedroom
of her recently renovated Victorian home in Social Circle and doing
something that would likely give fellow TV cook Martha Stewart
hives: celebrating an imperfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Books,'' Dupree says calmly as her voice lifts into an
impromptu sing-song soprano. ``These are books ... more books.''
</P>
<P>
   The great wall of boxed tomes stands as a testament to Dupree's
long, long still-to-do list as she completes the move she started
more than five months ago from mega-cushy Ansley Park to this more
laid-back, historic, one-stoplight town 45 miles east of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Add to Dupree's list the equally imposing mound of boxes on the
second-story landing filled with hundreds of videotapes from her
wildly popular TV cooking shows. And the wall-to-wall sea of
glassware, knick-knacks and boxes that floods another upstairs
bedroom with enough apparent weight to cripple, if not sink, the
Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody who has a serene life,'' Dupree says.
``Do you? (pause) I didn't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people flee their homes during a renovation, opting for
live-in hotel chain suites to avoid the constant barrage of
painters, cabinetmakers and swirls of dust. But Dupree's built her
career by teaching the average cook to charge ahead no matter what
(``Something spills or breaks,'' she says. ``Big deal.''). So she
chose to film her 10th television cooking series at home while
renovating.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, her new Georgia Public TV-produced ``Nathalie Dupree
Entertains'' debuts on WGTV in Georgia, giving her fans their first
glimpse at the completed and elaborately decorated first-floor
rooms in her new digs. Later this fall, the series, based on her
new book, ``Nathalie Dupree's Comfortable Entertaining,'' will
begin airing on PBS stations across the country, including Los
Angeles, Chicago and Dallas. She will be in New York next Tuesday
to promote her new show and book on ``Today,'' and she has already
done or scheduled interviews for stories in USA Today, People and
House Beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Five rooms are fully finished, and those watching the 26
half-hour shows and three hour specials for ``Dupree Entertains''
will venture into most of them. There's the formal living room and
adjacent parlor, both bathed in glorious mustard-yellow walls and
furnished with a heady mixture of Dupree's personal antiques,
deep-cushioned sofas from Rooms to Go (donated for her show) and
lusciously painted artwork and collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   The dining room sports a 1920s French maple chocolate cabinet
(purchased recently at one of Social Circle's cache of antiques
shops one block away from her front door) and two large rectangular
glass tops sitting on Romanesque columns used as dining tables and
separated to make a center-of-the-room walkway. The all-white back
porch with wraparound windows is casually furnished with wicker.
It's where Dupree reads and she and husband Jack Bass eat supper.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there's the kitchen, the showplace of ``Dupree
Entertains,'' with a 4-foot-long butcher block island of Georgia
pine; tiered, dark-marble counter tops; old-color cabinets crafted
by Georgia artist Andy Inglett; and an intoxicatingly vibrant
picture window above the sink that lets in glorious natural light
while Dupree is on camera.
</P>
<P>
   Touches of Dupree's whimsy surface here and there. In the
downstairs bath, a colorful wooden female figure (the perennial
bridesmaid, Dupree says. ``She makes some men nervous.'') wears the
prestigious James Beard medal Dupree won for a cookbook. Just
outside the back door, a discarded bathtub is a container for
vibrant, sweet-smelling basil.
</P>
<P>
   Living here, Dupree says, makes her feel as though she's come
home. She had a restaurant in Social Circle in the early '70s, and
when her former mother-in-law and good friend Celeste Dupree, a
fierce preservationist, purchased the 1910 home for less than
$300,000 and offered Nathalie a deal to return, she set about
writing this new chapter in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very happy house, a very accommodating house,'' Dupree
says, sitting on a dark tanned sofa in her immaculate parlor. ``See
the wavery glass in that window? It's the original glass. There's
something about the wavery glass that makes being here seem surreal
and another time and place. It just takes you away from time and
you don't push the same way. All of a sudden, you are just
relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   You can sense her comfort. She's attired in a formal, deep-blue
silk wrap dress and large pearl necklace for some of the
photographs to be shot this day but has placed her feet inside
everyday bone-colored satin house slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when a photographer preparing to snap the living room
suggests that an umbrella container is sprouting too many
bumbershoots, Dupree momentarily halts an interview, gathers up the
offending rain gear in her arms, returns to the sofa and plops back
down. Her lap's now a resting spot for a gangly bundle of
umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   It's another unconsciously anti-Martha Stewart moment.
</P>
<P>
   Dupree is unflappable. And her fans and friends love her for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Nathalie, there is no such thing as a faux pas,'' says
longtime pal and admirer Bob Furnad, CNN Headline News president
and Social Circle resident. Furnad and his wife, Barbara Morgan,
have already been guests in Dupree's new home, and he describes the
feeling of visiting there as ``easy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nathalie is not one who makes a dinner party something
difficult,'' he says. ``It's not something that's got her tied in
knots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to watch her show every week,'' says Dupree fan Barbara
Hall, 49, of Warner Robins. ``One thing I like about her is that
she makes mistakes every now and then and she says you'll do better
at home. Everything is not edited out. It's real.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's ``Dupree Entertains'' boldly carries on the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   There Dupree is on camera, fidgeting with three different gas
burners until she lights the right one, talking stream-of-conscious
about the lemon souffle dessert she's making until she realizes the
gelatin warming on the stove has burned black.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mixture of right-way, wrong-way demonstrations that
culminates in an attractive presentation of delectable sweets for a
grand dessert party.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to inspire average cooks. Dupree wants them to reach
toward a pleasing style of entertaining that makes guests feel
comfortable and lovingly fed in an environment that underscores
personal expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything clean and everything perfect and everything
bow-tied means you are trying to impress people rather than express
yourself,'' Dupree says. ``How boring it would be for everyone to
have the facade of perfection. Life is very boring that way. A
perfect house is boring _ where nothing has any rough spots.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore her point, she leads a visitor to her backyard
garden. There amid the herbs and flowering plants is a beautiful
border made of chipped and broken china in various patterns. The
pieces are personal relics: remnants of plates that cracked when
washed in too-hot water, serving bowls from her old restaurant that
faltered over time and saucers that just last month broke in a
dining room accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my china garden,'' Dupree says. ``I can enjoy them out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Laid to rest in the dirt, their imperfection is perfectly
charming.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
