<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On The Newsstand: Women can now go Outside
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, there's a women's magazine that doesn't feature
articles about hair care or Demi Moore's marital woes. Making its
debut this week, Women Outside ($3.95) is aimed at a female
audience more interested in taking a road trip across the
Australian outback or dancing with the wolves of Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   Editors Susan Casey and Laura Hohnhold say they want to continue
the tradition that Outside magazine started 21 years ago. ``We
borrow from Outside the assumption that our readers are interested
in a wide range of topics, and that you love books and films and
the Internet as much as you love to travel, ski, hike, paddle and
climb,'' says Casey, creative director of Outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see funky outdoor clothing and a lot of very cool gear
in these pages, but you won't see the words empowerment or
self-esteem. We're a couple of decades beyond that, and we figure
you are, too. We like to think of Women Outside as simply more of a
good thing _ Outside with an estrogen chaser.''
</P>
<P>
   The premier issue is impressive: Sara Corbett describes her
journey across the Australian outback in a Subaru station wagon;
Hollywood stunt women put the latest outdoor clothing through a
strenuous workout; and a six-page section introduces some neat
gear, from a $650 mountain bike to an assortment of knives and
other sharp objects. Now the bad news: The next issue of Women
Outside won't be on newsstands until spring 1999.
</P>
<P>
   PRIDE OF THE YANKEES: The September issue of GQ ($3.50) is
fashion-heavy as usual, but there are some meaty articles if you
can wade through the clothing ads. Peter Richmond's cover story on
New York Yankee shortstop Derek Jeter reveals a young man who has a
heart as well as a sensational talent. Jeter started a foundation
for troubled kids after his first year in the majors and hired his
father to run it. And, no, there's no juicy gossip about his
relationship with Mariah Carey. Also of note: Steven Kotler's
fascinating profile of Clinton nemesis John Whitehead, the
conservative millionaire who funded Paula Jones' lawsuit. As
founder of the Rutherford Institute, Whitehead believes in God,
democracy and the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEWSWEEKLIES: It was a stormy week for news, as reflected by
Time, Newsweek and U.S. News &AMP; World Report. All offer in-depth
packages on the Russia crisis (most used headline: ``Russian
Roulette''), with takeouts on the fallout in political and global
markets. U.S. News writes about ``The cloud over Gore'' in the Reno
investigation into campaign fund-raising, and a Time story
headlined ``Stormy weather'' details how the the president is
trying ``to survive the (political) tempest.'' Meanwhile, real
hurricanes are featured in ``The Storms of August'' in Newsweek,
and Time rates the network coverage of Bonnie (CNN got 4 out of 5
umbrellas, Weather Channel only 2 1/2).
</P>
<P>
   For relief from maelstrom coverage, Time offers a life-size
replica of House Speaker Newt Gingrich's hand, explaining that
recently he tried to set a Guiness Book record as national public
figure who shook the most hands (3,609) in the shortest amount of
time (six hours). The replica is based on a fax sent to the
magazine ``by the Speaker himself,'' and readers are urged to help
Gingrich hold on to his new handshaking fame by cutting out the
hand and giving ``the Speaker a shake or two.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK READS: Elmore Leonard wasn't always a best-selling writer.
In an inspiring essay in P.O.V. ($2.95), the author of ``Get
Shorty'' and ``Out of Sight'' describes his life as a 25-year-old
married guy writing pulp fiction for two cents a word. ... People
($2.79) looks at famous couples who have gotten entangled in the
adultery web (Gary and Lee Hart, Frank and Kathie Lee Gifford, et
al) and how their experiences can help the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writerCarolyn Warmbold
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
