<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-COLUMN-COX     08-31 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: `Inappropriate' doesn't come from the penitent's
heart
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the good things about growing up Catholic was that your
sins were between you and your maker, not you and the media. In the
dark of the confessional you told the priest what you'd done, how
you'd slipped up and how you were going to redouble your efforts
not to be back the next week repenting the same sin you'd been
repenting for what seemed like your whole life.
</P>
<P>
   As God's liaison the priest had authorization to wipe your slate
clean, and after a few inaudible murmurings he would tell you to go
in peace and sin no more. There's nothing like the feeling of
complete absolution. Many were the Saturday afternoons I'd leave
that church and break into a skip, grateful I hadn't been struck by
a thunderbolt since my last visit and assured that if one struck me
now I at least wasn't going to the hot place.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling didn't last long, and as I got older it sometimes
didn't even carry over till the next morning. I learned there are
commandments that I'm always going to have trouble with. But one
thing I don't recall saying in the confessional was that I'd done
something ``inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   I just said guilty again, Lord, and hoped for a break.
</P>
<P>
   It takes awhile to get straight what's right, what's wrong and
what's inappropriate. If right leads to heaven and wrong to hell,
then maybe inappropriate leads to purgatory, a kind of waiting room
for those whose case has been taken under advisement by a higher
court.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, one of our children manfully agreed to write a
few paragraphs explaining some actions of his that had met with our
displeasure. They were nothing outrageous, not even something I'd
have carried to the confessional, but it would do him good to
ponder them on paper.
</P>
<P>
   We happen to believe that the best way to find out what you
really think about something is to write about it. So he wrote a
couple of paragraphs in which he told us he understood the larger
point we were trying to make and, the heat having subsided, was
sorry it happened. Reading it, I thought, ``This is pretty good.''
It was a personal accounting more than an act of contrition, and I
was proud of him.
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking this as I got to his final sentence, always the
one to take greatest care with. He could have ended matters a
sentence earlier, but some compulsion drove him to say one thing
more, to lay on a final coat of varnish for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   His actions were, he said, inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   When has a word been given such a ride as President Clinton has
given this bloodless clunker? A person can't acknowledge his
actions anymore without getting in touch with the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't use educationese, management mumbo-jumbo or therapists'
words,'' I said. ``Those are words of indirection and evasion. If
you're sorry, say that. If you think you were wrong, say that.
Maybe you think (BEGIN ITAL) we're (END ITAL) wrong; you can say
that, too. But use real words, not this counterfeit currency you
hear on TV and read in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the weirder consequences of President Clinton's attempts
to explain his ``relationship'' with Monica Lewinsky is that the
styles of public and private confession have merged. Turn on the
radio and within 15 minutes somebody's going to be calling
something ``inappropriate.'' The word is popping up everywhere, and
not only in reference to President Clinton. (It was a standby in
Dr. Laura's lexicon long before anyone had ever heard of l'Affaire
Lewinsky, which is ironic. For all her faults, you have to grant
her one thing: She has no patience with the namby-pamby coinages of
psychobabble.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Inappropriate'' threatens to replace ``a mistake in
judgment,'' the kind of phrase you hear from a congressman caught
in the washroom with a 13-year-old or a treasurer who's been making
himself personal loans from the company pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   The congenitally tone-deaf will ever be with us, the people who
habitually speak of impacting this and utilizing that. But there
are others who choose not to say what they mean. When silence is
not an option, there is refuge in remoteness. It's built into the
Bill of Rights, although it looks bad to take the Fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the wall separating the public and private collapsed
and lying in a heap, too many of us sound like robots and
mannequins, parroting the prefabricated words we've heard on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what they mean? Confession isn't the same as
self-exoneration, any more than absolution is the same as damage
control. The one is redemptive, the other merely deflective. The
one is good for the soul, the other bad for the public image. Once
a penitent opens his mouth these days, you know which one he values
more.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
