<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTULISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS LOOK FOR NEW TREATMENTS FOR BOTULISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Grace Wheeler is meticulous about taking steps to
prevent botulism when she cans vegetables from her East Greenbush,
N.Y., garden.
</P>
<P>
   But every three months, she voluntarily gets eight shots of the
potentially lethal toxin injected into the muscles of her neck.It
sounds odd, but this toxin, tamed and distilled, is being used to
treat everything from muscle disorders to wrinkled skin.
</P>
<P>
   At Albany Medical Center, researchers are testing yet another
type of botulism in hopes of offering a more effective treatment to
people who've developed immunity to the current strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard about it, I had a lot of questions,'' said
Wheeler, 64, who suffers from involuntary muscle contractions in
her neck.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of people, she was skeptical that the botulinum
toxin, which can cause death by paralysis when consumed in its
natural state, could alleviate her embarrassing muscle spasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head would swing to the left whether I wanted it to or
not,'' she said. ``If you've ever had this problem, you'll say to
yourself, `I have to try something.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some 300,000 Americans suffer similar symptoms from a group of
movement disorders known as dystonias. Characterized by twisting
repetitive movements, dystonias usually affect only a small part of
the body.
</P>
<P>
   A neck contorts sideways, or a hand cramps into a claw. Some
people's eyes twist shut, rendering them briefly unable to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people get dystonias of the vocal chords and they talk
like this,'' said Albany neurologist Dr. Stewart Factor, lowering
his voice into a harsh rasp.
</P>
<P>
   There is no known cause or cure. Until recently, physicians have
been limited in their ability to treat these problems. The most
common approach was a variety of neuromuscular drugs, effective
only in a minority of patients and usually with severe side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Dr. Alan Scott, a California ophthalmologist,
began tinkering with the botulinum toxin type A more than 15 years
ago to treat a pediatric eye muscle disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The toxin itself was formally recognized in 1793 when 13 Germans
reportedly shared a contaminated sausage. All became ill and six
died. The illness was later named botulism after the Latin word for
sausage.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria to blame was Clostridium botulinum, which naturally
occurs in the soil and thrives in conditions of low oxygen. Only
temperatures above 158 degrees Fahrenheit can kill it.
</P>
<P>
   That's why people who can their own vegetables are urged to take
proper precautions by using a pressure cooker and following proper
sanitizing directions.
</P>
<P>
   In their laboratory, Scott and his associates figured out a way
to capitalize on the toxin's natural abilities to cause paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   By injecting small amounts of purified botulinum toxin into the
afffected muscles, they realized they could block transmission of
the nerve impulses that cause some muscles to uncontrollably
contract with minimal side-effects.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Food and Drug Administration approved the toxin for
therapeutic purposes in 1990, no one has contracted botulism from
the injections, primarily because the dosage is so small or about
10 times less than the amount needed for a poisoning problem.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the laboratory toxin is less virulent than what
you'd encounter in contaminated food because it includes only the
protein, not the bacteria that facilitates the reproduction of the
toxin throughout the body's systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not infectious,'' said Dr. Eric Molho, a neurologist at
Albany Medical Center. ``There is no bacteria in there at all. You
can drink it and nothing would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are now trying to improve on that initial discovery
by studying a different strain of the botulinum toxin, type B. It's
believed to have fewer side effects and provide another alternative
to people who have developed immunity problems to type A.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 18 months, some 200 people across the country,
including 33 patients at Albany Medical Center, have been getting
regular injections, usually every three months, of botulinum toxin
type B to test its effectiveness. So far, both physicians and
patients are pleased with the results. The FDA could approve toxin
type B as early as 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news especially for Wheeler, who works as a bank
customer representative. Two years ago, she realized that type A
was no longer working as well, even with an increased dosage. The
last thing she wanted was a return to the kinds of problems she had
in the early 1980s, when she was first afflicted with her dystonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask questions,'' she said. ``I've had people stop me in
the street. I had a woman stop me and say, `have you been to a
chiropractor?' Some are very rude and some are just plain
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Dystonia isn't just a matter of an occasional muscle spasm.
Depending on the location of the dystonia, the condition can limit
people's ability to walk, eat and breathe. Only when the brain
relaxes does the body get relief.``It goes away only when they
sleep,'' Molho said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the injections work for everyone. Some people have
dystonias over too wide an area or in areas impossible to reach
with a hypodermic needle.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Greenberg, 47, of Clifton Park, considers herself
fortunate that her dystonia has been confined to the muscles in her
neck since she was diagnosed with the problem in 1988. Though rare,
some dystonias run in the family. Her daughter Melissa, now 20,
developed the disorder in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``My chin would slam into my shoulder,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she has no apparent problems, though she knows when her
shot is wearing off and its time for another, usually every 3 to 4
months. ``I can usually feel pulling in the muscles in my neck,''
she said. Some plastic surgeons and dermatologists are also finding
that the toxin can work to relax some of the wrinkles around
people's eyes and foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the toxin takes off as the next cosmetic hit remains to
be seen.
</P>
<P>
   A single dosage can cost as much as $500. And while insurance
companies usually pick up the cost for dystonia patients, they
don't cover cosmetic treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Having lived 16 years with her dystonia, Wheeler isn't
interested. ``I've earned every one of these wrinkles,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
