<HEADER>
A1538 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EQUITYLOANS-TEXAS-960     08-31 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUITYLOANS-TEXAS-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST EQUITY LOANS HAVE TEXANS TRADING ONE KIND OF DEBT FOR ANOTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM FUQUAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Eight months after Texans were finally
allowed to tap the value of their homes for extra cash, the No. 1
use of the home equity loans is not to start a business, put a
child through college or improve the homestead.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's debt consolidation _ rolling up the outstanding
balances on credit cards, personal loans and other pricey
obligations and paying them off with one, less-expensive
home-equity loan.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be the noblest of purposes, but it certainly
makes sense. Not only do home-equity loans carry lower interest
rates, but interest paid is deductible for federal income tax
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans carry an abnormally high debt load compared to the rest
of the country,'' said Greg Jewell, who runs Associates Capital's
home equity operation in the state. ``They have higher credit card
balances, higher personal loans, maybe because of the lack of home
equity lending.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's focus on debt consolidation hasn't surprised lenders.
They say that given the state's decades-long holdout against home
equity lending, a little home finance alchemy is bound to look
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that everything else is such a distant second has
raised some eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a big believer that in Texas, business (start-ups) was a
big part. But we're not hearing a lot of it,'' said John Gavin,
chief of Northwest Bank Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   What else do we know about Texans and home-equity lending? In
interviews, several lenders reported that:
</P>
<P>
   _The average interest rate charged is about 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _The average loan amount is about $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   _Refinancing makes up roughly one-third of all home-equity
loans, more than usually seen but not surprising given the sharp
rate declines so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the purpose, demand for home-equity loans has met or
exceeded lenders' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Home equity is the difference between a home's market value and
any loans on the property. A homeowner with a $100,000 home and a
$75,000 mortgage has $25,000 in home equity.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Texas law that went into effect Jan. 1, homeowners can
borrow up to 80 percent of their home's market value when taking
out a home equity loan. The 80 percent ceiling includes any
outstanding mortgages against the property.
</P>
<P>
   So how many billions in home-equity loans have been written?
It's too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to know how much business there is,'' but
nobody really knows yet, said Bob Mahalik, senior mortgage banking
analyst at the Dallas Federal Reserve Bank. He estimates at least
$10 billion in home equity loans will be written in Texas this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it's a huge market,'' said David Flores, senior vice
president at Chase Bank Texas in Houston. ``We're very pleased with
the volume.''
</P>
<P>
   By consensus, the Associates ranks No. 1 in home equity loans.
Jewell said the consumer-finance company had closed about $750
million worth of Texas home-equity loans as of mid-August.
NationsBank also drew numerous mentions.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new survey by the Texas A&AMP;M University Real
Estate Center in College Station, all of the state's large
commercial banks and roughly 75 percent of the smaller ones report
making the tax-favored loans.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 percent not making loans cited legal concerns related to
the stringent restrictions Texas lawmakers placed on home equity
loans, said Jack Harris, the center's director.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's survey of members of the Texas Banking Association showed
that two out of three respondents making home equity loans reported
that they had handled less than $500,000 in home equity loans.
Eight percent reported doing more than $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's roughly as expected, given the big banks' familiarity
with home equity lending through their operations in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones aggressively working that market are the largest
banks, the ones over $1 billion,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Associates clearly geared up to be Texas' most active home
equity lender.
</P>
<P>
   Spread over three floors of an Arlington office building,
Associates employees field 300 to 500 phone calls a day that stream
into the offices, which handle all the company's home equity loan
business in Texas. About 150 people work in the Arlington office.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Associates can throw so many resources into the
market is that it casts its net a bit wider than most banks. Jewell
said Associates' home-equity business is roughly divided into
thirds, divided equally between borrowers with sterling ``A''
credit, less-than-shiny ``B'' credit, and tarnished ``C'' credit.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Associates reports that it also lends money at
a considerably wider range than the banks.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Borrowers with good credit records and strong relationships with
their lenders can get rates as low as 7.75 percent, with the bulk
of the business being done at about 8 percent, lenders say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had specials in the high 7s, but it's mostly 8 to 8.25
percent,'' said Danny Smith, chief of Bank One Texas' Fort Worth
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell said Associates has made so-called ``subprime''
home-equity loans for rates as high as 13.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The state imposes a ceiling of 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, lenders said that regardless of income level or credit
rating, customers' loans tend to average $40,000 to $50,000. It
wouldn't seem that lower-rated homeowners would have a lot of home
equity built up, but the subprime market is hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to one subprime lender who said he can't rent enough
space and hire enough people to handle the business,'' Mahalik
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, legislative restrictions on the loans are undoubtedly
depressing demand somewhat, he and other lenders said.
</P>
<P>
   For one, lenders quickly realized that the state's definition of
an urban homestead is limited to 1 acre. That means, for example,
that a homeowner in the Fort Worth area with a home on 1.5 acres
has a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Some banks decided that a quick fix was to conduct a survey that
defined the acre that included the home. That acre then is
designated as the collateral for the loan.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``the cost associated with that has probably reduced
the appetite of many institutions and reduced demand from those who
have more than an acre,'' Flores said. Because fees can't exceed 3
percent of the loan amount, ``it's not as attractive to us,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the interest rate to recoup expenses is unattractive to
borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find ways to work around it, but the solutions aren't
necessarily beneficial to both parties,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Texas' unique restrictions on home equity loans have
hampered their sale on the secondary market. Most mortgage loans
today are bundled and sold to investors who are willing to shoulder
the risk of fluctuating interest markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the largest purchaser of loans on the secondary market,
Fannie Mae, said it currently is buying only Texas home-equity
loans that are first liens. Getting a first lien home-equity loan
requires the borrower to refinance the outstanding mortgage with a
new loan whose balance includes the extra money the borrower wants.
</P>
<P>
   That's called a ``cash-out'' loan. It's called that because the
borrower takes cash out of his or her equity, replacing it with
additional debt.
</P>
<P>
   A second lien stands second-in-line behind a first lien in case
of a default. That's one reason that second liens can't command an
interest rate as low as a first lien.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't said we won't buy second liens,'' said John Bauer,
senior business manager for Fannie Mae, a quasi-government
corporation. ``There's just a lot of complexity to the
constitutional amendment that regulates Texas home-equity loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenders said that the lack of a uniform, secondary market for
Texas home-equity loans can lead them to demand a slightly higher
interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loans being made today are being made by people who are
willing to hold them,'' said Mark Jones of Frost Bank Mortgage. ``I
don't think there's a premium to refinance and do it as a home
equity loan, but you have to keep in mind that there's not a
traditional secondary market for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, reverse annuity mortgages, intended for use by older
homeowners who want to tap their home equity for, say, medical
expenses without giving up their homes, also has been stymied by
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday the house is sold, and there's wording that makes it
unclear when the lender could actually sell it,'' Harris said.
``For all practical purposes, they don't exist'' in Texas, he said
of reverse mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Schneider, an attorney for the Austin office of Consumers
Union, said it's clear that both the 1-acre limit and the reverse
mortgage have problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are probably pretty easy fixes for that,'' Schneider
said.
</P>
<P>
   What's already clear, he said, is that interest rates and fees
on home equity loans vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   As always, it's imperative that consumers shop around, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
