r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIS-BOOK-LADN     08-31 2048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-BOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THROUGH THE FEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Stock up on extra toilet paper. Lay in a month's
supply of bottled water. Oh, and don't forget to stick a ``Fire
Sale'' sign smack in the middle of the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Davis is at it again.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.'s poet laureate of pessimism is predicting the worst. His
extended forecast: Floods, firestorms, tornadoes, earthquakes and
killer bees. Death, pestilence, ethnic conflagrations, plagues of
man-eating mountain lions and, yes, more tacky subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   And that's only the start of the perilous prophecies put forward
in Davis' just-published ``Ecology of Fear: Los Angeles and the
Imagination of Disaster'' (Metropolitan Books), a harrowing tour de
force that's sure to provide plenty of grist for politicians,
academics and talk-radio hosts this fall.
</P>
<P>
   While generations of Tinseltown fantasists have promoted the
Southland as an endless summer of sun and fun, Davis sees something
quite different. In ``Ecology of Fear,'' he makes the case that,
practically since its inception, Los Angeles has courted
environmental catastrophe through a lethal combination of greed,
myopic land management and arrogant disregard for the region's
abundant natural hazards.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he believes, we've had the dumb good luck to escape the
decades-long droughts and cataclysmic earthquakes to which our
boom-and-bust landscape is prone. But now, Davis argues, the law of
averages is catching up. We're verging on environmental meltdown,
while the powers-that-be bury their heads in the quicksand.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse, he contends, our cavalier attitude toward Mother
Nature mirrors our callous disregard of L.A.'s poor and powerless.
We're heaping the gasoline of political discontent on the bonfire
of overdevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   Result: Apocalypse Soon _ unless, Davis warns, we adopt more
sensible environmental policies and a more egalitarian
socioeconomic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think L.A.'s distinctive in the way that it combines
environmental and social problems in such an explosive mixture,''
says Davis, a faculty member of the Southern California Institute
of Architecture since 1986. ``You take Detroit's social problems
and spatial segregation and combine it with San Francisco's seismic
exposure, you end up with something like L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait. Haven't we heard this somewhere before? Well, yeah. Sort
of.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Davis _ a former truck driver and college
dropout turned free-lance Trotskyite scholar _ flipped L.A.'s
laid-back image upside-down with his first book, ``City of
Quartz.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhaustively researched and passionately argued, ``City of
Quartz'' offered an alarming behind-the-scenes tour of the Southern
California experience. Written in a style both slangy and
authoritative, caustic and humorous, it suggested a !ital!noir!off!
alternative reading of L.A. history, emphasizing its brutal ethnic
and class struggles and the plundering of a natural paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers on both coasts hailed the book as a brilliantly
written piece of journalism-cum-manifesto, an underground road map
of SoCal consciousness. Overnight, the highly quotable Davis became
L.A.'s favorite naysaying leftie, a coveted guest speaker and
regular contributor to op-ed pages (he's also a contributing editor
to New Left Review).
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the accolades have kept pouring in. Two years ago,
the Getty Center named Davis one of its scholars-in-residence.
Earlier this year he was awarded a $315,000 MacArthur Fellowship (a
so-called ``genius grant'').
</P>
<P>
   It's been an odd turn of events for the renegade son of a San
Diego meat cutter, who once supported himself by driving a big rig.
But then much of what Davis feels for his hometown smacks of
paradox. Perhaps no one else so aptly personifies Angelenos'
love-hate relationship with their city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that it's obvious, whatever the faults in my writing
style or the way I organize my arguments, that I am a fiercely
passionate Southern Californian,'' says Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an anger I feel of seeing so many of the things that
made a good life potentially available to everybody being lost. ...
Which doesn't necessarily mean that I'm setting out to make
Pasadena look like Havana.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his sulfur-tinged prose, Davis in person is a
surprisingly mild-mannered baby boomer of 52. Stocky and compact,
with a thatch of gray hair framing inquisitive gray eyes, he has
the look of a Welsh pub keeper.
</P>
<P>
   A careful listener, he can riff for hours on virtually any
subject _ the racial subtext of H.G. Wells' science fiction or
various endangered species of flora and fauna. A casual question
about the planned Newhall Ranch development (``a travesty'')
prompts a seminar on the utopian communities envisioned by Jane
Addams and Samuel Gompers. This guy must dream in complete
paragraphs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a kind of part public intellectual, part
raconteur, because I think that one of his great gifts is his
storytelling ability,'' says William Cronon, the Frederick Jackson
Turner chair of history, geography and environmental studies at the
University of Wisconsin at Madison. ``Nobody knows the histories,
stories and people of the L.A. basin better than Mike Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' tale-spinning talents help him straddle the line between
journalism and academia, between a popular following and a
specialized one. Though bristling with footnotes, ``City of
Quartz'' became a best seller that cut across marketing and
cultural boundaries. (Among its many local fans is Barry Munitz,
president and CEO of the J. Paul Getty Trust.)
</P>
<P>
   Rather than an ivory-towered hermit, Davis fits the profile of a
public intellectual, able to popularize complex theoretical issues
for a wide &UR;  &LR; audience. He has advised politicians and worked with
gang members, and you're as likely to find him organizing hotel
workers in Las Vegas or leading teen hikers in the San Gabriel
Mountains as pontificating in the faculty lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tricky place to be, but I think he has a lot of
credibility,'' says Stephen Pyne, an environmental historian at
Arizona State University, referring to Davis' hybrid career.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Steinberg, a history professor at Case Western Reserve
University in Cleveland, says Davis' books manage to avoid both the
leaden jargon of left-wing academic writing and the bland
banalities of mainstream political journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What passes for political reporting in America today is so, so
tame, so domesticated,'' says Steinberg. ``I think it's great
someone is out there yelling `Fire.' And that's what Davis is
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   As laid out in ``Ecology of Fear,'' the holocaust threatening
L.A. springs from shortsighted thinking by developers, politicians
and the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Davis argues, beginning in the booming 1920s, the
city blew a golden chance to create a lush ``medium-density''
environment dominated by townhouses and courtyard apartments,
surrounded by ample communal green space and pedestrian walkways.
He believes this ``alternative'' compressed Los Angeles would have
made rapid transit economically viable and reduced the enormous
distances that now separate home and working lives.
</P>
<P>
   In squandering its Eden, Los Angeles pushed relentlessly into
flood plains, fire zones and crumbling coastal areas, while leaving
its inner core and first-ring suburbs to deteriorate into
``postmodern slums.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same, Davis writes, there's ``a growing scientific
consensus'' that the region has built up a substantial ``earthquake
debt,'' of which the devastating 1994 Northridge temblor was merely
the first repayment.
</P>
<P>
   Though one reviewer has called the book ``Eco-terror at its
finest,'' Davis stresses he's not invoking a circle-the-wagons
mentality, but instead trying to remind L.A. of the costs of
ignoring its own past.
</P>
<P>
   Davis traces his ambivalent feelings about his hometown to his
parents, who fled West from Columbus, Ohio, after losing everything
in the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   His father was ``this innocent, sunny, naive kind of guy'' who
idolized California, while his mother had a dark, fatalistic Irish
imagination and hated her new home, a little bungalow alongside an
avocado orchard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of had in my parents this constant fight or dialogue
going on about Southern California, and I've inherited both of
their viewpoints,'' Davis says, managing a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Until his late teens, Davis was a ``right-wing,
ultra-patriotic'' kid who actually thought of informing on his
liberal father to the FBI. His adolescence passed in a
quasi-delinquent haze of ``stealing cars a bit, trying to drag
race, and getting in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Davis read John Hersey's ``Hiroshima'' and underwent a
political turnaround. At 18 _ shortly after being kicked out of
college for trysting with a coed _ he joined the radical Students
for a Democratic Society. He spent a couple years working for the
group in New York City until marriage and money problems drove him
back home.
</P>
<P>
   For a while he tried meat cutting, his father's profession. He
went through a series of blue-collar jobs until, finally, on a
generous scholarship from his father's union, he went to study
labor history at UCLA in 1974. He was almost 30. Later he went to
Northern Ireland, where he wrote his doctorate on the country's
working class. But it wasn't until ``City of Quartz'' was published
that Davis finally was able to concentrate full time on teaching
and writing.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades after his first fling with socialism, Davis
retains a certain innocent hopefulness about L.A.'s future, mixed
with a brawling, clannish protectiveness. He's like the uncle who
picks quarrels at the family reunion but will scrap with anyone who
criticizes his relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something is wrong, it offends him. He doesn't just
accept it as being one more lousy thing that's wrong with the
world,'' says regional planner David Stein, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Such an exacting worldview has made for a fractured personal
life. Married six times, Davis now lives in a Pasadena bungalow
with his current spouse, Alessandra Moctezuma, and his 16{-year-old
daughter by the first of two Irish ex-wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a kid who's inherited all my self-destructive qualities
of just saying what's on her mind to anybody,'' Davis says. ``She's
a natural-born rebel. She worships dead poets who have OD'd on
heroin and other figures that I sometimes have trouble coming to
grips with.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting a grip on Davis isn't always the easiest thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tends to get caught up in what he's doing at the moment and
forget everything else around him,'' says Stein. ``I think he's a
very lonely man in some ways. He's caught up in an intellectual
adventure, and while he's warm for the moment you're with him, then
he goes off and does something else, and you have to rebuild the
connection.''
</P>
<P>
   With his newfound celebrity, Davis is facing another challenge:
How to keep flogging L.A. politically when L.A. keeps begging for
more lashings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem is, I keep biting the hand that feeds me, and they
feed me more,'' he says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Davis fantasizes about chucking it all _ the political
crusades, the pursuit of literary fame _ and hanging out with his
son Jack in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The child was sickly when he was born, and he almost died. But
now he's a lively 5{-year-old, ``an extremely kind, sweet little
boy'' who lives with his mother on a peninsula on the north side of
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lives near horses and castles, and every week I write him a
children's story,'' says Davis, who visits his son several times a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing him describe Jack's idyllic existence, you wonder if
Davis is hearkening back to the fertile playground of his own
California youth _ a place that is precious not because it no
longer exists, but because in some ways it never really did.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could, I'd just take the MacArthur money and just be like
Robin Williams _ I can't remember the movie he's in where his wife
leaves him because he's just totally regressed, all he does is play
with the kids all day long, and she thinks he should have a career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could do that,'' &UR;  &LR; says Mike Davis, ``I would.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
