<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1555 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     08-31 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGER GOOFS BY TAKING OFFICE HEARSAY AS FACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken LLoyd, Ph.D., is a specialist in organizational behavior.
Questions can be sent by electronic mail to lloydonjob(at)aol.com,
or they can be mailed to P.O. Box 260057, Encino, CA 91426. Names
will be withheld upon request.) 
BY KEN LLOYD, PH.D.  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q My manager called me into his office and told me that several
of the people I work with complained to him about me. He said they
think I am too bossy, conceited and demanding. I told him I
disagreed, and that they never said this to me. He said I should
think about what they told him and try to do something about it.
I'm very upset and not sure what to do. L.S. &QL; 
A Your manager took a real misstep on this one. His first step
should have been to suggest that your associates meet with you to
discuss their concerns and see if there is a way for all of you to
resolve this matter on your own.
</P>
<P>
   Having tripped at the first step, your manager then took a giant
leap backward by believing only their side of the story. And then,
to make matters even worse, he threw all sorts of labels at you,
rather than discussing specific behaviors or incidents.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, you should meet with your fellow employees to
discuss the situation. Let them know you are honestly puzzled by
their reaction to you, as well as by their decision to take their
concerns directly to management rather than to you in the first
place. Then be quiet and listen. It is easy to become defensive in
these discussions, and it is essential to avoid doing so.
</P>
<P>
   You can present your side of the picture, but your real
objective should be to prevent this kind of situation from
recurring in the future. Hence, you should try to work toward a
mutual commitment from all of the players to try to work
productively together and to be open and proactive in dealing with
group problems.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to let your manager know what you are doing about group
problems, as it sounds like he may be causing more than a few of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Q We brought in a training program for the managers and, in the
last session, there was a short test that well over half of them
failed. This is a highly regarded program, and we are disappointed
with the performance of so many of the managers. What do you
suggest we do? T.P. &QL; 
A When well over half the class fails a program, it can be argued
that the real failure is the program itself. This type of failure
rate typically highlights a program's inability to capture and
sustain the motivation, drive and interest of the participants. In
this regard, before you blame your employees, it is important to
review the program's presenters, content, practice, opportunities,
feedback, materials and the test itself.
</P>
<P>
   One useful step is to meet with the participants to discuss all
of this. After all, it is standard operating procedure for
participants to evaluate the training programs they attend. By the
end of this discussion, you will have a clear idea of who and what
really failed here.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to remember that a training program may be
highly regarded, but that does not automatically mean your
employees will have any regard for it at all. &QL; 
Q I do not have many personal phone calls, but the last three times
my manager stuck his head in my office, I was on one. He gave me a
strange look, but I didn't say anything to him about how few
personal calls I actually receive. Should I? A.S. &QL; 
A At this point, it's getting too late to make that call. In a
broad sense, if you are ever concerned that your manager has
obtained an inaccurate picture of your performance, you should tell
him. However, you need to do so as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   If you approach your manager even a matter of days after the
fact, the message that you are sending may not be the one that he
receives. For example, he may have forgotten about the calls, but
you will have rekindled this telephonic memory. Or perhaps he still
has them in mind, and he may have figured that they were infrequent
occurrences, but since you stewed over them for some period of time
and then approached him, perhaps he should focus more attention on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, since it sounds like you are going to keep yourself
awake at night until you talk to your manager about this, you
should do so. After all, in most work environments, such calls are
not exactly rare. If your working relationship with him is
generally positive, there should be no problem in giving him a
quick update on your personal calls. And if your working
relationship is not that great, the personal calls are the least of
your problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
