<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE-9     08-31 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD LEADERS STILL BELIEVE IN POWER OF U.S. PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT, RUSSIA-RESCUE,
RUSSIA-SUMMIT, RUSSIA-DEBATE, RUSSIA-CLINTON) 
(js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the eyes of many of his fellow leaders and ordinary
people around the world, President Clinton has lost stature since
investigations into his private life and his admission of an
inappropriate relationship with a White House intern. But he has
lost little of the authority and power conferred on him by the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Some, particularly in the Arab world, fear that since the
disclosure of his conduct with Monica Lewinsky, Clinton no longer
has the moral authority to use his power in ways they would like to
see.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the Middle East and Africa say they believe that he
ordered military strikes against alleged terrorist targets in Sudan
and Afghanistan in order to divert public attention and fear that
he might be tempted to respond similarly in future crises.
</P>
<P>
   But leaders everywhere say that whatever the details of
Clinton's private life, his position as leader of the world's most
powerful economy and of the only military superpower makes him
indispensable in dealing with international problems, from
terrorism to turmoil in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, he went to Moscow Monday night with the
blessings of fellow leaders of the seven largest industrial
democracies.
</P>
<P>
   According to an informal survey by New York Times correspondents
on five continents, people, regardless of their personal feelings
about Clinton, stand in awe of the power of the U.S. presidency _
if somewhat less in awe of the character of the man now occupying
the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``An emperor should behave like an emperor, and a father should
behave like a father,'' said Yan Xuetong, a foreign policy expert
at the Chinese government-sponsored Chinese Institute of
Contemporary International Relations, citing Confucius.
</P>
<P>
   Because Clinton has been taken down a notch in the last month,
leaders in some countries are quicker than usual to take issue with
U.S. policies.
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking European official, who asked not to be
identified, criticized the president's determination to travel to
Russia this week, despite the political and economic turmoil that
has hobbled President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely useless meeting,'' this official said, ``but
neither Yeltsin nor Clinton could afford to be the first to say,
`Let's call it off.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Another, representing a different European ally, said, ``The
only thing worse than carrying out this meeting between two wounded
heavyweights would be canceling it.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst outcome of the Russia crisis, most European leaders
agree, would be abandonment of a commitment to democracy and to a
free-market economy. Clinton is still capable in their eyes of
conveying that the West will continue its support if Russia keeps
trying.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany, who is fighting against the
odds for re-election on Sept. 27, would have perhaps the most to
lose if Russia changed course. The German government and banks have
lent billions to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   As Kohl said in a television interview a week ago, ``Bill
Clinton is the Number 1 in the world. Whatever American domestic
politics are, he has his responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans have to exercise their leadership role,'' Kohl
said. ``In contact with Russia, Indonesia, or Japan, to name only a
few problems areas, it's absolutely necessary. There is no letup,
not for the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   So there is some built-in sympathy on this side of the Atlantic
for the president.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac of France referred to his ``personal
friendship'' with Clinton in a speech to French ambassadors from
around the world in Paris last week.
</P>
<P>
   But he also ticked off a list of differences between the United
States and France, saying that the United States had an
isolationist and unilateral streak that complicated international
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Africa, South America and Asia, there is bafflement
about a country where a president's foes can use his sex life to
attack him politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this an advanced form of democratic political conduct?''
the French foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine, mused the other day.
It seems more like a kind of Puritanical political persecution to
the French, he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Biehl del Rio, chief of staff to the Chilean president,
Eduardo Frei, said, ``Outside the United States, we do not give
this issue the same importance. We are all praying, or at least
crossing our fingers, that he is not hurt by this. The world faces
a recession, and the United States is holding the economy of the
world together almost alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Castaneda, a Mexican writer, said, ``There are a lot of
problems in the world that only the U.S. can fix, and there's a
sense among Mexicans that there wouldn't be this worldwide mess if
there was somebody in charge in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that if Clinton didn't have all these sexual
problems, he'd be able to act more decisively,'' he said. ``How can
a successful president who's brought prosperity and well-being to
the U.S. be weakened, destroyed or crippled by this silly story?''
</P>
<P>
   Tumi Mahabane, deputy editor of Y, a black youth magazine in
South Africa, said, ``I don't think people should look to
presidents for moral authority. Presidents should steer countries.
Their morality is peripheral.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But in the Arab world, the dominant view is that the U.S.
presidency has been weakened by the Lewinsky issue, as has the U.S.
ability to press Israel to negotiate with the Palestinians about a
further Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer possible to plan any policy with them,'' a
senior official in Saudi Arabia, a key U.S. ally, said after
Clinton's decision to bomb targets in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public opinion here is already persuaded that this
administration is the most pro-Israeli, anti-Arab and anti-Muslim
in American history,'' said the official, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed in some Islamic countries that Monica
Lewinsky was an Israeli agent placed in the White House. Without
his troubles over Ms. Lewinsky, some Palestinian and other Arab
officials contend, Clinton might have been willing to single out
Israel for not agreeing earlier this year to a U.S. proposal for a
settlement between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Hemi Shalev, a commentator for the Israeli newspaper Maariv,
wrote, ``The weakening of the president was a boon to the right
wing.'' He wrote, ``Quickly, they translated Bill Clinton's
troubles into local currency and reached the conclusion that a
president up against the boards is one who cannot pressure Israel
to implement the second redeployment.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction in much of the rest of the Islamic world was also
critical of the bombings, and inclined to see a connection with
Clinton's troubles over Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Sarote Phaksumlee, a leader of Ban Krua, the biggest Muslim
community in Bangkok, said, ``The timing is very strange. Nobody
has heard of Osama bin Laden before. It is obvious the attack is
staged to divert attention from Bill Clinton's sex scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If America can do what it did in Sudan and Afghanistan,
tomorrow it can bomb northern Thailand by saying we are growing
opium and manufacturing heroin and exporting it to America,'' he
said. ``America is not the world policeman and this is morally
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mansor Mohammad Noor, former leader of a fundamentalist
Islamic group in Malaysia and now a lecturer at University Science
Malaysia , said: ``Clinton has discredited himself even though he
might be right. The greatest error is that Clinton is sowing fear
among people throughout the world. He has shown the might of the
United States and it can hammer anyone anywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States can bomb anyone anywhere. This is a very
dangerous precedent, the world is at the mercy of America. Clinton
has frightened the world. A frightened world is a dangerous
world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Baki Kizginkaya, the Mukhtar or chief of the Emirgan
neighborhood of Istanbul, offered a different opinion. ``Clinton is
a very valuable man,'' he said. ``He did what was necessary in
Sudan, responding to terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of his trip to Russia, Clinton can
apparently expect a warm welcome afterward in Ireland, where he
plans to visit both the north and south of the country and then
relax for a few days to play golf before he goes back to
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
