<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Sept. 6)  
(JT) 
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CDC Warns of Flu in Alaska and Yukon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An investigation of a flu and pneumonia outbreak among travelers
to Alaska and the Yukon Territory of Canada has identified 2,199
cases, including 71 of pneumonia. In summer, 70,000 tourists may
visit the area each week, both on cruise ships and by land.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention now urges
travelers 65 or older, and anyone with a chronic medical condition,
to see a doctor before going into the area. Such travelers, the
government said, are more likely to develop pneumonia if they get
flu.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation by United States and Canadian health
authorities found that the influenza-A cases were often reported in
clusters among smaller groups sharing transportation, meals and
hotels. When those infected seek medical help on board a cruise
ship, for example, the infection can spread to other passengers and
crew.
</P>
<P>
   Potential travelers are urged to ask doctors ahead of time about
carrying antiviral pills. Taken within 48 hours of the start of
symptoms, the antivirals decrease the duration of the flu. As of
Aug. 24, the strain was believed to be similar to A/Sydney/5/97
(H3N2). A report on the outbreak, document 300004, is available
from the CDC fax service: (888) 232-3299.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Upgrades on American to Get Tougher in '99 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A mile doesn't go as far as it used to.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers on American Airlines who want to redeem frequent-flier
miles for first-class or business-class seats will need more miles
starting in February.
</P>
<P>
   The mileage required for coach tickets will not change, but
passengers will need from 10,000 to 25,000 more miles to buy or
upgrade to business- and first-class seats on domestic and
international flights.
</P>
<P>
   Many other major airlines said they were studying American's
changes or had no plans to raise their requirements.
</P>
<P>
   American's increases will require, for example, 30,000 miles
rather than 20,000 to upgrade to first-class from a discounted
domestic ticket. Travelers will also have to redeem 125,000 miles
rather than 100,000 to upgrade a discount ticket to Europe to a
first-class ticket under the advance-purchase plan.
</P>
<P>
   American said the change was due to strong demand for the seats,
as well as the airline's investment of $400 million to upgrade the
front sections of its planes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Folk Art Collection On View in Santa Fe &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1995, the Museum of International Folk Art in Santa Fe
got a huge gift _ more than 2,500 textiles, ceramics and folk-art
objects from all over the world collected by Lloyd . Cotsen, the
former chief executive of Neutrogena, and given jointly by him and
the company. The museum immediately set to building more exhibition
space. And now, for the first time, selections from the collection
are on view in the new 8,775-square-foot Neutrogena wing.
</P>
<P>
   The collection is a crazy quilt from ancient times right up to
today: rare Medieval Coptic Egyptian textiles, Greek embroideries,
Amish quilts, Hispanic folk carvings, ceramics made by the Rio
Grande Pueblo Indians, 19th-century Navajo weavings, contemporary
Hopi weavings, Kuba cloth from Congo, Japanese folk clothing,
weavings from ancient Andean cultures and contemporary harvest corn
dollies and decorations from Europe and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the new wing, the inaugural exhibition, ``The
Extraordinary in the Ordinary,'' puts just 200 of the 2,500 objects
on display. Many of the rest, however, can be seen in the wing's
open collections area, where visitors can examine some works in
``activity stations.'' Supervised by the museum's curators, these
stops allow visitors to look closely at selected objects and
conservation methods, for example. The permanent storage space will
also be visible through large glass windows, offering a look at
activities of curators. In a 280-page exhibition catalog (Harry N.
Abrams, $60 for the hard cover; $35 for paperback), organized
geographically, several scholars discuss the works.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of International Folk Art, whose permanent collection
of nearly 130,000 objects comes from 100 countries, is on Camino
Lejo off Old Santa Fe Trail. Telephone (505) 827-6463. Hours: 10
a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday through Sunday. Admission: $5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Seattle Symphony Gets a New Home (and View)  &LR;  The Seattle
Symphony has a new home this year, Benaroya Hall, the city's first
space designed specifically for concert music performances. Gala
celebrations and concerts will take place Sept. 12 to 20 to
inaugurate the hall, with the regular season beginning Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the symphony performed in the Seattle Center
Opera House, and was limited to performances on weekday nights.
When Rebecca and Jack Benaroya donated $15 million in 1993 (the
gift eventually rose to $16 million), the symphony decided to build
a concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   The $118.1 million building has a 2,500-seat main auditorium and
a 540-seat recital hall. The building sits on a whole city block in
the heart of downtown Seattle and has a circular lobby with large
windows looking over Puget Sound and the snowcapped Olympic
Mountains beyond. The Boeing Company Gallery along the Third Avenue
side of the building is an arcade housing shops and cafes, as well
as the box office.
</P>
<P>
   During construction, the architect on the project, Mark
Reddington of LMN Architects, and acoustical consultant, Cyril
Harris, overcame numerous obstacles _ including noise and
vibrations generated by Seattle's main transit tunnel _ to insure
that the building would have good acoustics. The main concert
auditorium is basically a box within a larger box separated by nine
inches of space. For the interior of the concert hall, dark, rich
makore wood from Africa was used on the walls to create an even
sound.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Sept. 12, the acoustical logistics will be put
to the test when the symphony, conducted by Gerard Schwarz, music
director, kicks off the inaugural celebrations with excerpts from
Wagner's ``Goetterdaemmerung,'' with Jessye Norman performing in
the Immolation Scene, as well as the world premiere of David
Diamond's ``Gala Celebration.'' More than 130 other performances of
contemporary and classical works are scheduled for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Benaroya Hall is at 200 University Street. For information or
tickets, contact the Seattle Symphony Box Office at Post Office Box
2108, Seattle, Wash. 98111-2108; (206) 215-4747;
www.seattlesymphony.org. Tickets (not including gala events): $15
to $75.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
