<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPREWELL-HNS &LR;      08-31 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPREWELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATRELL SPREWELL KEEPS COMEDY IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With all the dry-roasted issues of the day
currently occupying the largest part of our plates, we should still
take a little time for Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we're more interested in Mark McGwire, the home run chase
and that eye-of-newt/toenail-of-toad concoction he mainlines every
day. Of course we spend a hunk of the day wondering if the Giants
really do have one more big push left in them. Sure, we border on
obsessive when the topic turns to the 49er running game, or why the
Raiders even bother to play at home. We're even more interested in
Cal-Nebraska, if only for the reasons that homicide detectives
linger around a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, just off the radar, with that enigmatic smile, letting us
know that he hasn't really gone away after all, is Our Guy Spree.
</P>
<P>
   The last time we saw him, you may remember, he had done the
unthinkable _ construct a lawsuit so preposterous that a judge
laughed him out of court. He was trying to make the case that ...
oh, what's the difference?
</P>
<P>
   Whether he was trying to get his suspension lifted and his fine
reduced, or pull some of that big NEA jack for his performance art
piece on P.J. Carlesimo's thorax, it got slapped back in his face.
</P>
<P>
   With one noteworthy caveat. He could re-file the suit if his
next lawyer could come up with some reasoning that didn't cause
Judge Vaughn Walker's brain to roll out his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he holds a press conference to do that very thing. The
least we can do as his neighbors is feign attention.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is being re-filed without including the Warriors as
defendants, based apparently on the legal principle that the guy
with your prints on his windpipe makes a damned unconvincing
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he and his lawyer, J.Cheever Loophole, are targeting
the NBA alone in hopes of avoiding Judge Walker's considerable
scorn. This time, Our Guy Spree wants the NBA (a) to refund $5.4
million of the money it took from him; (b) to cap his fine at the
$1 million the Warriors took from him in the few hours they spent
actually trying to discipline him themselves; and (c) to admit that
it destroyed evidence that would have tended to support Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   What this evidence is, we presumably will have to learn in
court. Maybe a forensics expert will show that it was actually Rod
Strickland who choked Carlesimo from 2,600 miles away. Maybe they
will unearth a monstrous police conspiracy, even though the cops
were never called, not even in the 20 or so minutes it took for
Carlesimo's face to return to its original shape.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they will even haul Jane Alexander, the former director of
the National Endowment for the Arts, in to admit that yes, the
agency would fund his piece, ``Coach In Very Blue.'' At this point,
anything is possible, and we should fervently support their plunge
into the depths of the creative process.
</P>
<P>
   As we know, any old kidney pie can file a lawsuit. Indeed, until
we stumbled upon Judge Walker and his lofty ``For what reason do
you bring me this steaming tripe of a case?'' standards, we figured
that there were no standards whatsoever. If you wanted to accuse
your neighbor of breathing too loudly, your boss of having
unusually smelly feet or the government of not rigging the lottery
in your favor, some judge somewhere would listen to your complaint
for weeks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Our Guy Spree's case as originally presented, though, amazingly
passed none of these tests. Somehow, he managed either to find the
one legal tree with no limb to stand upon, or the one lawyer who
thought a tort was stuffed with jam. So he did what any
self-respecting gent would do _ he found another lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   And for this, we should all be grateful. For one, the baseball
season will soon be over, there's only one football game a week,
the hockey season doesn't really get going until after the first of
the new year, and there doesn't seem to be any NBA season at all.
There will be Stanford and University of California hoops, and the
Bill Murray Invitational in February, and that's it.
</P>
<P>
   For two, there isn't much of anything on Court TV these days,
what with O.J. all played out and the JonBenet Ramsay case set for
the twelfth of never. Judge Walker may be strict when it comes to
having lawsuits stay within the confines of the facts, but maybe
he's enough of a sport to let cameras in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   And for three, well, Our Guy Spree is still Our Guy. He's still
a Warrior, which you would think would be sufficient stigma to send
most people off the grid entirely. He still lives in the East Bay,
and as a homeowner he feels the Raider-enriched property tax hike
the same as the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   And he has apologized for whatever it is he may or may not have
done to Our Guy P.J., and if an apology would have gotten Our Guy
Billy Jeff Clinton off the hook, the logic naturally follows that
it should work for Our Guy Spree.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same logic, of course, that persuaded him to file
the suit in the first place, and it was just his deucedly bad luck
to get the one judge in America who didn't want the kind of cheap
publicity we thrive on.
</P>
<P>
   So you go, Spree. You file, and ask for punitive damages in the
billions. Make us proud, and if you can't manage that, at least
make us laugh. We can all use a little of that kind of sugar, even
in these hectic times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
