<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USWEST-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING NONUNION COMPETITION, US WEST SETTLES TWO-WEEK STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With nonunion companies competing hungrily for
telephone business in booming cities of the Rockies, U S West
tentatively settled a two-week strike Monday, and workers started
back to work at the nation's sixth largest Bell company.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which gave workers minor gains and faces
ratification by the 34,000 strikers, came as the company scrambles
to deal with an explosion in fax, pager and telephone lines in
Denver. Starting Tuesday, all local calls made within the Denver
area will require 10-digit dialing. In October, greater Denver is
to get an additional area code, 720.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bell companies are preparing to face increased competition
from fairly lean, nonunion companies going after their market
share,'' said Boyd Peterson, an analyst with The Yankee Group, a
Boston-based telecommunications research company.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that U S West stock only fell 7/16ths of a point Monday
in face of a sharp market decline, he added: ``Compared to the rest
of the market, it was positively stalwart.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Bell Atlantic reached a settlement after
only a two-day strike by the same union, Communications Workers of
America. In Connecticut, workers from same union last week rejected
a contract offer made by Southern New England Telecommunications
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``CWA is probably doing better than any union in the country,''
said Gregory Tarpinian, executive director for the Labor Research
Association, a New York-based consulting company for unions. ``They
have a tremendous amount of leverage because most of the telecom
companies downsized in the mid `80s and early `90s. They are left
with pretty lean operations.''
</P>
<P>
   At U S West, the number of employees dropped to 53,000 on
Monday, from 66,000 in 1984, the year of the company's creation.
Because of downsizing, the strike found the company without a large
number of middle level managers to perform unionized tasks _
directory assistance, repair and installation. At the same time,
the region's urban customers enjoy unprecedented choices because a
host of new companies have entered markets in the deregulated
environment caused by the Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The U S West strike affected service to about 25 million
customers in 13 of the company's states: Arizona, Colorado, Idaho,
Iowa, Montana, Minnesota, Nebraska, New Mexico, North Dakota,
Oregon, South Dakota, Utah, Washington and Wyoming. Unemployment in
the U S West service area is nearly one percentage point below the
national average of 4.5 percent. In August, it was hard to find
strike breakers in Nebraska, where unemployment in July was 2.1
percent, in North Dakota, where it was 2.2 percent, or in
Minnesota, where it was 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a tight labor market and an increasingly competitive
business environment, U S West agreed to wage increases of 10.9
percent over three years, slightly above inflation forecasts. In
addition, it agreed to cut in half mandatory overtime, to a maximum
of eight hours a week by January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, which also allowed for a 21 percent increase in
pension benefits and a $500 ratification bonus, must now be
ratified by the company's rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Pisha, vice president of Communications Workers of America
District 7, said that on Sunday night officials of the 65 striking
locals ``overwhelmingly'' supported the new contract. She predicted
that it would win approval of 60 to 70 percent of striking workers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the most controversial issue, the company agreed to make a
pay-per-performance plan voluntary for eligible employees.
</P>
<P>
   Before the strike, the company's younger managers sought to make
this plan mandatory for all new workers as a way of improving
efficiency and making the company more ``customer friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   David Beigie, a U S West spokesman, called union acceptance of
the voluntary plan as ``a breakthrough for the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Pisha said: ``The union is not going to recommend that
our members get in that plan,''
</P>
<P>
   In a company where union workers earn an average of $37,900,
however, some may ignore union appeals and go for the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line will be down the road, when we see how many
employees opt for pay for performance,'' Richard Hurd, a professor
of labor studies at Cornell University, said Monday. ``If the
company can convince people that pay for performance will mean they
can get higher pay, you will see a lot of employees going for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
