<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-VOTE-BOS &LR;      08-31 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REJECTION OF PRIME MINISTER CANDIDATE WIDENS RIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Defiant Russian lawmakers rejected President Boris
Yeltsin's choice for prime minister Monday after ignoring Kremlin
warnings that a ``no'' vote would prolong the country's profound
economic woes and could lead to mass civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The move came as President Bill Clinton departed for Moscow for
a summit that many Russian observers see as little more than a
misguided vote of support in an increasingly weak and isolated
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's vote dashed whatever faint hope remained that the
Kremlin and the opposition-dominated parliament might put their
considerable differences aside to address an economic crisis that
has left the stock market in collapse, the ruble sharply devalued
and teetering, the government unable to pay its foreign debts, the
country's banking system in ruins and Russian businesses across
nine time zones paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tackling the crisis that sent world markets diving
for a third straight day amid dire visions of political upheaval in
a nuclear superpower, Russia's warring factions instead attacked
each other as the country, already perched on the edge of financial
collapse, rumbled toward the brink of a new political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   During three hours of angry debate proceeding a resounding
251-94 vote not to confirm acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin, leaders of the State Duma, the lower house of
parliament, argued that the man who served as Russia's premier from
late 1992 until Yeltsin fired him this March was not the one to
solve the current crisis. Communist and liberal opposition groups,
sensing that the balance of power in Russia has shifted after five
years of near absolute rule by Yeltsin, stepped up calls for the
embattled president to resign and let the Duma choose a government
more to its liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our president, in the condition he is in, has paralyzed the
entire political and economical situation,'' said liberal lawmaker
Grigory Yavlinsky. ``It is time for him to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, 67 and in visibly poor physical condition, has said he
will not step down, even after losing the steady ruble that had
been seen as the one sure accomplishment of seven years of painful
reforms. From the rural hunting lodge where he has been holed up
for most of this crisis, Yeltsin responded to the Duma's challenge
by resubmitting Chernomyrdin's candidacy, forcing the Duma to hold
a second vote next week. If the Duma rejects Chernomyrdin a third
time, the Russian Constitution says that Yeltsin then dismisses the
legislature and sets new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been through all this before _ most recently, when
Yeltsin fired Chernomyrdin in March and forced the Duma to approve
his young and inexperienced candidate, Sergei Kiriyenko. But both
sides say the stakes are higher this time, after Yeltsin, in a
characteristically baffling about-face, fired Kiriyenko and
re-appointed Chernomyrdin after the ruble lost over a third of its
value on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is on the verge of political and economic collapse,''
Chernomyrdin said during a speech to parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this chaos lasts for several more weeks, it may happen that
there will be neither Communists nor us,'' added Yeltsin's envoy to
the Duma, Alexander Kotenkov, urging the house to approve
Chernomyrdin. ``I mean a popular uprising, merciless and
senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Communist members of parliament are reportedly looking
forward to the possibility of new elections, figuring voters will
be more likely to look left after the latest economic debacle. But
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, in urging parliament to vote
down Chernomyrdin, appeared to be also calling for a solution that
avoided elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fail to reach an agreement here everything will spill
out to the streets,'' he said, adding an appeal to the Russian
military and police force not to take part in any crackdowns.
</P>
<P>
   For all these dire warnings, Moscow seemed peaceful enough early
Monday. There was little sign of the panic buying that swept Moscow
when the crisis hit after the ruble lost 40 percent of its worth
overnight last month and Russians hurried to try to get at least
something for their money. The Russian currency even staged a mild
recovery in street trading after a series of sharp falls, and some
stores put on sales to adjust their prices to the higher ruble
rate.
</P>
<P>
   But for businesses, banks, or anyone with money in deposit
accounts, it was another day of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's banking system has effectively closed down, with a
number of institutions ready to go under. No bank business is being
done, meaning that no bills can be paid or money transfered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the impression that the whole banking system has
collapsed,'' said Anna Frantsuzeva of Diaog Bank. ``No payments
are being made.''
</P>
<P>
   And by the end of the day, consumers took another hit as the
Central Bank lowered the ruble rate by 18 percent to 9.33 to the
dollar, undercutting consumers who had been trading their
hard-saved dollars for as little as 8 rubles earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Moscow, where few people have extra money to spend,
the situation was getting worse. The semi-official Interfax news
agency reported that prices on many staple items had risen by 50 to
80 percent in some regions as sellers tried to hedge against
newfound uncertainty in the ruble. The price hikes are likely to
add to the difficulties of millions of workers who for years have
been paid late, or not at all, by the insolvent firms they work
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we drag on with the choosing of the government, soon there
will be no stores, and no bank accounts,'' warned centrist
legislator Oleg Morozov.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin had sought to strike a compromise with the
Communist-dominated Duma by offering a return to some Soviet-style
state controls on the econonmy, such as limited price fixing and
printing money to pay workers. Chernomyrdin also offered to
transfer some of Yeltsin's vast powers to parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But after a weekend of negotiations in which it became clear
that Yeltsin himself was not ready to cede his powers, all the main
factions of parliament except for Chernomyrdin's own party refused
to sign the political pact on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his deal with the Duma in tatters, Chernomyrdin still
may resort to printing rubles to solve the wages and banking
crises. In his speech Monday, also said his priorities would be
supporting industry and guaranteeing that depositors receive their
money.
</P>
<P>
   Western creditors have warned that printing money may lead to a
new round of hyperinflation that would sweep away what is left of
Russia's market economy, as well as its current leaders. Clinton
and other Western leaders have said the West will help, but only if
Moscow sticks to the austerity program prescribed by the
International Monetary Fund, which backed a $22.6 billion rescue
package for Russia in July.
</P>
<P>
   That bailout, however, failed to prevent the ruble from
devaluing or Russia from defaulting.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Russian observers see US support for Yeltsin as a
bankrupt strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin is worse than a lame duck,'' said Igor Bunin, an
analyst at the Center for Political Technologies in Moscow, was
quoted by The Associated Press as saying. ``Clinton is supporting
Yeltsin by inertia. It's no longer support of a concrete person _
it's fear of catastrophe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
