u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSTATE-SEEDS-BOS &LR;      08-31 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-SEEDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY REPORTS BENEFITS OF SEED THERAPY IN PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Implanting tiny radioactive pellets to treat prostate cancer
gives men as good a chance of beating the disease as surgically
removing the gland _ at least in cases diagnosed early _ suggests a
10-year analysis published today.
</P>
<P>
   Men have flocked to the pellet treatment because it avoids
incontinence, impotence, and other side effects of surgery. But in
a debate reminiscent of the mastectomy-versus-lumpectomy
controversy about breast cancer treatment in the 1980s, many
surgeons have warned that men opting for the new treatment were
risking their lives without good evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, the most long-term to date, shows that nearly two
out of three men survived 10 years after having the pellet
implants, which deliver radiation from inside the prostate. These
survivors also had very low levels of prostate-specific antigen, or
PSA, which can signal regrowth of the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the 147 study subjects died of prostate cancer.
The Seattle authors claim this record puts the new treatment on a
par with radical prostatectomy and makes it superior to external
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   In other studies of early-stage patients who received
prostatectomy, the Seattle group noted, 47 percent to 73 percent
were alive and disease-free 10 years later. In studies of those
treated with conventional external radiation, disease-free survival
at 10 years ranged from 13 to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will convince a lot of the skeptics,'' said Dr.
Leroy J. Korb of Northwest Hospital in Seattle, where the implant
procedure was pioneered. ``There will be skeptics regardless of the
data, but I think this will bring a lot of patients and surgeons
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the data at least demonstrate that brachytherapy, as
the pellet implants are called, can cure prostate cancer in some
patients _ a point that some have contested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most failures in prostate cancer occur between five and 10
years after treatment, so we're getting close to saying that
brachytherapy does cure some patients,'' said Dr. Anthony V.
D'Amico of Brigham and Women's Hospital and Dana Farber Cancer
Institute in Boston. D'Amico is author of a report, to be published
in two weeks, that compares five-year results of surgery, external
radiation, and brachytherapy in nearly 1,900 patients.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico and others cautioned, however, that a single center's
results with one type of therapy do not permit firm conclusions
about one therapy versus another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purist would say that this kind of analysis only
demonstrates that this therapy appears to be very promising,'' said
Dr. John Long, a urologist at New England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information you really need are results from head-to-head
studies of different therapies,'' Long said. ``But we certainly
don't have that and we're not likely to get it. We've got a sea of
opinions, and strictly speaking there is no standard of care for
managing patients with a new diagnosis of prostate cancer today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of such rigorous comparisons, there will be
plenty of room for debate about which therapy is best for any one
patient.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Doctors will still recommend prostatectomy for men with
cancers discovered at a later stage _ a sizable group, but one that
is dwindling due to the widespread use of a diagnostic test called
prostate-specific antigen (PSA) and regular rectal exams.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Long and many surgeons argue that younger men with
early prostate cancer, those diagnosed in their 50s or early 60s,
should go the prostatectomy route, partly in the belief that it is
more likely to excise all cancer cells, and partly because
radiation can make it harder to treat a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the biggest criticisms that the aggressive
surgical community will level: We don't know how to manage these
guys (who have had brachytherapy) when they fail,'' Long said.
``It's difficult to do a radical prostatectomy because of scar
tissue in the area of radiation. And you can't use radiation
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimal treatment of prostate cancer is a big issue. With
184,500 new diagnoses each year and 39,200 deaths, prostate cancer
is the second cancer killer among men, after lung cancer.
Americans' increasing longevity is driving the numbers continually
upward.
</P>
<P>
   Radical prostatectomy is still the most frequent treatment,
accounting for about 40 percent of all cases. About 30 percent of
patients receive external beam radiation, which often damages
normal tissue of the bladder, urethra, and intestines.
Brachytherapy, used in only about 2 percent of cases in 1995, is
now thought to account for 10 percent, with the remainder receiving
hormone therapy or only ``watchful waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   The new study involved patients whose tumors were diagnosed
relatively early, when they were still apparently confined to the
walnut-shaped gland. Still, 82 percent in the study had tumors that
doctors could palpate during rectal exams _ an indication that the
tumors were not as early as many diagnosed these days on the basis
of PSA readings and needle biopsies.
</P>
<P>
   One subgroup of Seattle patients, who were thought to be at
higher risk because their cancer cells appeared to be a more
aggressive type, received low-level external radiation in addition
to radioactive seed implants. But their survival rate was not
significantly different from the lower-risk group.
</P>
<P>
   This finding, Korb said, is leading the Seattle group to offer
low-dose external radiation in addition to brachytherapy to some
patients who are thought to be higher risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
