<HEADER>
A1594 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SILK-HNS &LR;      08-31 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILK REMAINS A MAINSTAY IN WARDROBES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRAN INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Fashion materials may come and go, but one fiber
that has remained a mainstay in well-rounded wardrobes is silk, the
oldest and strongest of all natural fibers.
</P>
<P>
   Silk fabric has been valued over the centuries for its luxurious
feeling of softness and for its exceptional ability to be evenly
dyed, giving it a richer appearance than most other dyed fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Before World War II, the hosiery industry was the biggest user
of raw silk (now most stockings are made of nylon). Today, silk is
used in everything from men's and women's fashions to upholstery
and other home decorating fabrics, from throw pillows to draperies
and paper-backed wallcoverings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like silk because it's a traditional natural fabric.
They can wear silk in any season, depending on the weight of it,''
said Jill Herskowitz, operations manager of Jean Lewis Maloy
fashions in Stuyvesant Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silk is also a very forgiving fabric, in that it can be worn
on any shaped figure. Instead of clinging to the body, it falls
very loosely. You can also pair it up with any other fabric, from
dungarees to a wool skirt or suit.'' Silk can be extremely light in
weight, making it ideal for lingerie. But it's also warmer than
cotton, linen or rayon clothing, allowing silk and silk knit
undergarments to do the job of several layers of often bulkier
thermal wear.
</P>
<P>
   It also travels well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrinkles just fall out if you hang the garment up in the
shower and let it steam for a few minutes,'' Herskowitz said.
``Because of the weight, silk is easy to pack and doesn't take up
much room in the suitcase or garment bag. Plus it's light to
carry.''
</P>
<P>
   Silk is more widely available and affordable than ever before,
said Jeffrey White, president of S. Shamash &AMP; Sons, an
international manufacturer of silk fabrics based in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big news in silks is that over the last 10 years China has
expanded the production of silk, so that it is now available and
affordable to a larger section of the population,'' said White.
``The other news is washable silks. Silk is more than 3,000 years
old and dry cleaning only 100. So people have washed silk for
centuries. But now more silks than ever before can be washed,
because of better dying techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   While washable silks can be hand- or machine-washed on a gentle
cycle, White said they should be line-dried, and never put in a
clothes dryer.
</P>
<P>
   Because silk goes with so many fabrics, it is woven in a variety
of textures from smooth to a rough. nubby finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satin silks are the most elegant,'' said White, ``like stiffly
woven duchess satin that couturier designers like Vera Wang use for
wedding gowns. Then there are the silk satins that are used for
pajamas, sheets and fashions for dressy occasions. Crepe de chine
tends to be used mostly for blouses.''
</P>
<P>
   Other popular silks weaves are organza, chiffon and shantung.
</P>
<P>
   Fashionable men's ties are made from either printed silk twill,
which is a ribbed or ridged fabric like denim or dyed Jacquard,
where the small pattern designs are woven in, according to White.
</P>
<P>
   The retail cost of silk depends on its quality. A recent trip to
stores in the Capital Region found taffeta blouses costing anywhere
from about $50 to more than $200; a silk shell top for $68, a skirt
for $88 and a long-sleeve silk knit for $48. Prices will vary from
store to store and between designer labels.
</P>
<P>
   Home furnishing fabrics made from silk add a wealth of ambiance
to any room.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Bellinger Inc., in Cohoes has been manufacturing silk
weave fabrics for upholstery and windows in her fabric collections
for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We add things as the times and market changes, but silk fiber
has always been a constant here,'' said Michelle Heffernan, display
coordinator for Bellinger. ``The fiber helps to not only make a
textile beautiful but durable as well.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not known when sericulture, the raising and keeping of
silkworms for the production of raw silk, actually began, but silk
has been documented as early as the 12th-century B.C. in China,
which still produces the bulk of all silk garments, followed by
Korea, India and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Silk comes from the Bombyx mori moth, which produces eggs that
evolve into caterpillars. These moths, who prefer mulberry leaves
to clothing, eat until they can't possibly chew one more mouthful _
and then begin the process of cocooning.
</P>
<P>
   They spin their cocoon around themselves by extruding liquid
silk that's covered with a tacky sealant called sericin. Once the
moth passes through its larvae stage, it burrows through the cocoon
and in the process breaks this valued filament.
</P>
<P>
   Silkworms raised on silk farms, who are fed only mulberry
leaves, are killed with heat or steam when they reach the larvae
stage, so that they don't break out of the cocoon and break the
thread, which when unraveled (and unbroken), can reach a length of
a mile long, according to White.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give you an idea of silk consumption, it takes 2,000 silk
cocoons to make a blouse,'' said White.
</P>
<P>
   Like people, silkworms have ``off'' times, too. If the climate
isn't just right, they can produce a lesser quality silk that tends
to be used in silk products that are more textured, rather than the
plush, smooth silks, satins and chiffons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
