</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION DEFENDS CLINTON TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Clinton arrives in a Russia with an uncertain
future to launch a summit of questionable consequence amid a world
economy in chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, nervous senior aides cobbled together the
final details of Clinton's summit with President Boris N. Yeltsin
as they confronted more unsettling news. The lower chamber of the
Russian parliament, the Duma, voted overwhelmingly Monday to reject
Yeltsin's appointment of Viktor S. Chernomyrdin as prime minister,
effectively stripping Yeltsin of a government beneath him. And the
New York Stock Exchange's Dow Jones industrial average plunged a
breathtaking 512 points.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to meet with Yeltsin Tuesday in what analysts and
even some countrymen have described as an extraordinary spectacle:
a Russian president with ailing health and no actual government
negotiating with an American president whose credibility and very
tenure have been called into question by a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended his trip Monday by saying it is incumbent on a
world economic power like the United States to rescue Russia from a
return to a state-run economy dictated by an authoritarian regime.
The timing of the summit, according to Clinton and some of his
aides, could not be more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is to go there and tell them that the easy
thing to do is not the right thing to do,'' said Clinton, speaking
at a suburban Washington elementary school hours before he flew
here. ``The easy thing to do would be to try to go back to the way
they did it before, and it's not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, again summoning the spectre of terrorists with nuclear
bombs, cited the issue of Russia's nuclear arsenal _ the world's
second largest _ as reason enough to continue working with the
Kremlin to nurse the nation back to economic health.
</P>
<P>
   ``A weakened Russia, a weakened Russian economy, would put
enormous pressure on people who have those technologies and
understandings to sell them,'' he said. ``We don't want that to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some aides maintained a good face when discussing the summit,
which will also include a round of meetings between senior economic
advisers from the two countries and direct talks between Clinton
and opposition leaders and lower government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is positively, absolutely the right time to do this,''
said one senior administration adviser, talking on the condition of
anonymity. ``While the two presidents are meeting, our economic
people will be helping them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were less sanguine about this gathering. Some White House
staff could not recall another event in this administration as
unscripted as this summit _ an appalling proposition to advisers
unaccustomed to such surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Many US officials are unclear about the potential benefits of
the summit and uncertain if the Russian leaders will continue
market reforms toward democracy or slip back into a world of
central planning from the old Soviet state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the preliminary stage for the next phase in
Russian history,'' said another administration official, who talked
on the condition of anonymity. ``And we don't know what is coming.
What you're seeing is the beginning of the end of Yeltsin, and we
don't know how long the transition will take.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unstated is the sharp contrast between this summit and
summits of old, especially during the height of the Cold War, when
two powerful world leaders _ Ronald Reagan and Mikhail Gorbachev _
met with all of their considerable negotiating skills to address
the life-and-death issues of nuclear holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Some administration officials have been reassured in part by the
opportunity that Clinton will have to meet face to face with
Yeltsin at a time of crisis. For months, press and intelligence
reports have chronicled Yeltsin's failing health, and the two-day
meeting will provide Clinton the chance to make his own
determination.
</P>
<P>
   The summit will also give Clinton an unusual opportunity to meet
with potential successors to Yeltsin and lesser officials who might
shape the future of Russian rule. Sandwiched between a daytime
meeting and a nighttime dinner, Clinton is planning to deliver an
address to a group of young Russians at the Moscow University of
International Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important for Clinton is to use the trip to get
directly from Yeltsin what plan he has to get out of this crisis,''
said James Goldgeier, a visiting fellow at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington think tank. ``It will be useful to see
Yeltsin and see how he is functioning and to see what his plan is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will also be useful to hear from opposition figures and
other government figures,'' said Goldgeier. ``On-the-ground
information gathering is the best use of this summit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Monday made several oblique references to helping Russia
through its economic peril, but provided no direct plan for
economic aid. Such aid may be used by Clinton as a carrot, although
the amount is expected to be relatively modest, as he and Yeltsin
negotiate agreements over nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they will stay on the path of reform, to stabilize their
society and to strengthen their economy and to get growth back,
then I believe America and the rest of the western nations with
strong economies should help them, and indeed have an obligation to
help them, and that it's in our interest to help them,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, most aides and analysts said the summit is
continuing only because the United States would have dealt a
devastating political blow to Yeltsin's already falling fortunes if
officials had called for its cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bizarre time, but it was scheduled, and in the end he
had to go,'' said Goldgeier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Marcus of the Globe staff contributed to this story from
Washington.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT-775(3     08-31 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT-775(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT HAS HAD A ROUGH 20 MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT, CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE,
RUSSIA-RESCUE, RUSSIA-SUMMIT, RUSSIA-DEBATE, RUSSIA-CLINTON) 
(lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ With her bold public stands
undermined by irresolution in the White House and her experience
rendered less relevant by new economic crises, Madeleine Albright
has had a tough 20 months as secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Albright remains the Clinton administration's principal foreign
policy voice and the liaison with a recalcitrant Republican
Congress, and she is very popular in the country beyond Washington.
But a president averse to military risk, preoccupied by the fallout
from his relationship with Monica Lewinsky and unwilling to offend
core Democratic constituencies has not supported her on key issues
like the Middle East and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Her assiduous courtship of Congress was instrumental in winning
Senate ratification of NATO expansion and the Chemical Weapons
Convention from a Congress verging on isolationism. But Albright
has had little to do with the other Clinton successes of his second
term: a settlement in Northern Ireland and a reinvigoration of
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as Russia melts, tainting one of the relationships of
which Clinton has been proudest, this is a particularly vulnerable
period for the administration's foreign policy. Russia was part of
widening international economic crisis that has now hit Wall
Street, threatening the economic boom that has kept his popularity
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright and the State Department have not been crucial
players, White House officials say. With Clinton so distracted, it
is not immediately clear who is in charge. The evidence appears to
favor National Security Adviser Sandy Berger and Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin, though, instead of Albright.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Albright bristled at specific criticism,
but says it is only natural that the economic experts take the lead
on their issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, what's important is what people think in years
hence,'' Albright said. ``Whether I used this four-year period in a
way that ultimately accomplished what I want: to create the
underpinnings for the American role in the next century, while
taking care of what needs to be done to problem-solve.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright attended only one recent meeting of the National
Economic Council, the functional equivalent of the National
Security Council, and that was on Japan. She and her officials did
regularly urge a broader view of U.S. interests in Asia than simply
the financial, including security and the stabilization of
democratizing Asian allies, and coordinated interagency aid
packages for Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   But her call for President Suharto of Indonesia to step down
occurred only hours before he did so anyway, and in general,
Albright and her department have let the Treasury Department run
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Was this an opportunity missed, or simply, as Albright and her
aides contend, the most efficient and collegial way to coordinate a
post-Soviet world with new, nontraditional challenges?
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle East, on the other hand, Albright has been
central, trying to coax and cajole Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu of Israel into a compromise that would refresh a
deterioriating peace and help restore U.S. credibility in the Arab
world. But her intensive efforts have not yet produced the clear
personal triumph that zero-sum Washington seems to require.
</P>
<P>
   In May, she gambled that public pressure and an ultimatum would
move Netanyahu, but the White House failed to support her in the
face of a lobbying firestorm stoked by the American Israel Public
Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   She kept the administration engaged in Bosnia, where it could
not reasonably retreat. Here in Sarajevo on Sunday and again
Monday, Albright spoke passionately and effectively about the
effort required to make a multinational, democratic Bosnia come to
pass, and she was eager to make it vividly clear that U.S. aid
would only come to those who worked to carry out the Dayton
accords.
</P>
<P>
   But her advocacy of an aggressive approach _ including a
credible threat of air strikes _ toward Serbian leader Slobodan
Milosevic, over his crackdown on ethnic Albanian separatists in
Kosovo Province did not find wide support within NATO and was
rejected by Clinton in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Her vow in March that ``we are not going to stand by and watch
the Serbian authorities do in Kosovo what they can no longer get
away with doing in Bosnia'' has proven hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Other U.S. threats have seemed equally empty _ against Iraq to
defend U.N. weapons inspections, for example. That has called into
question the U.S. commitment to a sustained war on terrorism, a
commitment Albright and others pledged would begin with the missile
strikes against Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SOME EARLY VICTORIES FOR A NEW SECRETARY
</P>
<P>
   Albright's accession as secretary of state, which made her the
highest-ranking woman in American history, prompted enormous
popular and media interest. She attracted attention for her newly
discovered Jewish background as well as for successful efforts to
expand NATO and to her push to articulate a more forceful U.S.
position than her dry, quiet predecessor, Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly earned respect from her French, Russian, Chinese and
Arab colleagues. Early victories in Congress were hailed, and she
has won important policy shifts on Iran and Cuba, while helping to
prevent a trade war with Europe over sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   But with domestic problems undercutting Clinton's international
credibility, U.S. foreign policy seems ever more reactive. And with
the bombing of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, followed by
missile strikes in Afghanistan and Sudan, with civil war in Kosovo,
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan, Russian economic and political
problems and the unresolved crisis in Iraq flaring again, the world
seems a more dangerous and unstable place than when Albright came
to office.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's greatest virtues _ clarity and an intelligent,
forceful voice that connects with the public and Congress _ have
not diminished, said a senior White House official who admires her.
But as the administration faces diverse and less manageable
problems, many due to Asia's economic problems, ``her virtues seem
less impressive or timely,'' the official said, ``because neither
economics nor strategy are her strengths, and her depth lies in
European issues, not Asian ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Albright's hard work with Congress _ in particular with
Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. _ has not yet produced a deal to repay
Washington's debt to the United Nations or the International
Monetary Fund, both described as high priorities by her aides.
Compromises have been stymied by a fight with House Republicans
over abortion policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My predecessors had a different world to deal with in which
the parameters were fairly set,'' Albright said. ``They had the
possibility of focusing all their attention on one or two issues.''
By contrast, she said, she is trying to ``put into play a lot of
issues that I see as challenges we're facing,'' like nuclear
nonproliferation, economics and the effective use of sanctions,
issues that were at the center of a January review of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   LAND MINES AND WAR CRIMES
</P>
<P>
   Albright has failed to achieve some of the human-rights goals
she described as among the most important to her. She was an early
champion of a ban on land mines. Last year, however, in Ottawa the
United States was nearly alone in opposing a treaty.
</P>
<P>
   As a Central European whose family fled first the Nazis and then
the Communists, she has been especially concerned about crimes
against humanity. She created an ambassador for war crimes and
lobbied for a permanent international tribunal to prosecute them.
</P>
<P>
   But at a Rome conference to accomplish that goal, the United
States was part of a small minority refusing to sign a treaty to
create a permanent tribunal. In both cases, the Pentagon and
Congress successfully argued that the United States required
special exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she continues to champion her principles, but she
cannot forget America's responsibilities. ``I have to balance
enunciating the principles and leading the way with the pragmatism
of getting things done and the power of the United States,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is now a new expression in diplomatic circles _ ``to
pull an Ottawa'' _ which means to promote a new initiative and then
abandon it at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's fierce rhetorical battles with the Iraqis at the
United Nations helped catapult her into the secretary's elegant
office. And in a corridor leading off from it, she keeps a comic
shrine, a collection of cartoons, newspaper cuttings and other
mementos of her tussles with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But the Iraq problem persists. The latest crisis is an outgrowth
of last March's inconclusive standoff that did little for the
reputation of Clinton's foreign-policy team.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq continues to serve as a reminder of the limits of U.S.
power in the post-Soviet world with difficulties in orchestrating
allies and of the continuing reluctance of Clinton to use force in
risky circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG FIASCO IN COLUMBUS
</P>
<P>
   But the televised ``town hall'' meeting in Columbus, Ohio, was
the most visible fiasco. Albright, National Security Adviser Sandy
Berger and Defense Secretary William Cohen were unable to silence
hecklers or to sound convincing about why a nearly isolated United
States might need to bomb Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio meeting, organized by the White House to use Albright's
skills and popularity, began the erosion of her reputation among
the foreign-policy elite of which she has been a member for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look around the world for the big challenges now,
where's the secretary of state?'' asked Robert Zoellick, former
under secretary of state for James Baker, who enjoyed a level of
influence over his president, George Bush, that seems denied to
Albright. ``To an outsider, she's MIA. People run issues case by
case, but there's a sense the show is being managed by Berger.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration manages crises but has no clear strategic
framework, Zoellick said. ``How do different problems relate to one
another? It starts with the president, but it's not her forte or
Berger's. If you don't have a sense of where you want to take the
country, you won't get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mandelbaum, who criticized Clinton's first-term foreign
policy as ``social work,'' thinks the current team is doing
decently at managing the smaller crises of the post-Cold War world,
which have less to do with national security and diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly in this second presidential term, by far the most
important figures in foreign policy'' are Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin and his deputy, Lawrence Summers, Mandelbaum said. ``For that
we should be grateful. A world with a financial crisis is far safer
than a world with a military crisis, and they've been doing pretty
well. ``But Albright doesn't seem to be a player in all this,''
said Mandelbaum.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SUCCESS WITH CHINA: WHO GETS CREDIT?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Haass of the Brookings Institution, who was a staff
member of the National Security Council under Bush, said ``the one
significant accomplishment in the second term'' has been to renew
relations with China. ``There you can see a policy initiative and
presidential investment,'' he said. ``One senses that the engine
for that has been the president and the National Security
Council.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Albright defended her involvement and that of
her strong team in the full range of foreign policy, from Asia and
China to Iran and Cuba. On financial matters, she said, she has
been working to ensure that the diplomatic, human and security
aspects are fully grasped.
</P>
<P>
   As a former academic, she has been happy to reach down to the
regional assistant secretaries and to urge them ``to think outside
the box,'' wanting career officers to compete for ideas with
outsiders. She has encouraged Under Secretaries Thomas Pickering
and Stuart Eizenstat, and Deputy Secretary Strobe Talbott, ``to
drive policy and make things happen,'' an official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic issues we have brought right into the department,''
Albright said, ``and we have an under secretary who's strong _ Stu
Eizenstat _ really working on sanctions issues and on trying to
meld the financial with the assistance part of the Asian financial
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   She has pushed hard, as she promised him she would, Eizenstat
said, to make the State Department a serious player again on
economic issues. Treasury gets the headlines over Asia, he said,
``but we and she have been intimately involved with the
humanitarian and political dimensions.''
</P>
<P>
   She is confident about her managing role as secretary of state,
as the prime foreign policy spokesman for the administration and as
a formulator of key policy. And she rejects the notion that
Clinton's choice of Richard Holbrooke for chief delegate to the
United Nations, who was said to have been a candidate for the job
before Albright was chosen, is a sign her own star is waning or
wanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is what it is,'' she said, shrugging. ``People
think you're terrific, and then they think you're too terrific, so
then they let you know that you're not. You can't be in a position
of being the visible voice for the United States and not be out
there to be praised and criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT A SURVIVOR OF THE DUKAKIS DAYS
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Berger have a friendship dating back to the
presidential campaign of Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, when
Albright was the chief foreign policy adviser to a candidate who
took almost unremitting heat for not having a strong foreign policy
view. Despite moments of annoyance, usually over personnel,
presidential briefings or second-guessing about the results of
specific diplomatic missions, they are each other's closest
advisers. They hash out policy in advance and speak many times a
day _ in sharp contrast to the tension between Christopher and
Anthony Lake, or the raging warfare under Jimmy Carter between
Cyrus Vance and Zbigniew Brzezinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the foreign-policy president who wakes up thinking
what notes he can pen to his foreign colleagues,'' a senior
administration official said, a reference, apparently, to Bush, who
was famous for his hand-written correspondence to world leaders.
``So Berger becomes the guy who doesn't make foreign policy so much
as broker it.''
</P>
<P>
   In meetings, another senior White House official said, ``she is
pragmatic and a consensus-builder, like Berger, despite her
reputation outside as an uncompromising, six-gun shooting
moralist.'' She arrives well-briefed and armed with a collective
department view, in contrast to Cohen, whose well-armed Pentagon
often gets its way regardless. She is ``articulate on issues she
knows well, and tends to put aside the talking points and draw from
her own experience, and she's best when she does that.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright dealt movingly with the emotional and security crisis
surrounding the bombing of the two U.S. embassies and the deaths of
many of her employees, and she has handled Clinton's personal
troubles with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING IT EASY ON THE IRANIANS
</P>
<P>
   But her finest policy moment lately has been a shift in the
treatment of Iran after the election of the moderate Mohammad
Khatami as president. While maintaining demands for a halt to
terrorism and a halt to Iran's nuclear, chemical and missile
programs, she pushed Clinton to a more receptive Iran policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard and she had internal criticism, but she got it
done with Sandy and the president,'' avoiding an interagency
battle, an official said. After her recent speech laying out the
new policy _ to which Iran has not yet responded _ the president
took her aside to congratulate her, she said, ``for threading the
needle.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, she used contacts with the pope, Congress and Cuban
exiles in Miami to allow direct relief flights from the United
States to Cuba to resume and to allow relatives to send money.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is also praised for her work with Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov, which helped forge a new relationship
between NATO and Russia. At one point, aides remember, as Primakov
argued for secondary military status for new NATO members, Albright
said: ``Neither the president nor I will negotiate over the heads
of the peoples of Central Europe. That happened once before, and
it's not going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright is also proud of using her unprecedented telephone
relationship with the Chinese foreign minister to organize the
Permanent Five to condemn nuclear tests by India and Pakistan. At
their June meeting in Geneva, she told the others that they are
``always talking about a multipolar and not a unipolar world.''
This was their chance to prove it, she said, ``so one country
doesn't take a principled stand and the others sign up the
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   SHE WILL AWAIT HISTORY'S JUDGMENT
</P>
<P>
   With all the ``profound ideological confusion'' facing a
post-Cold War secretary of state, said Moises Naim, editor of
Foreign Policy, this is not a period for ``grand strategy.''
Albright's role, he said, is inevitably one of a goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   But secretaries of state are often defined by challenges. Baker,
for instance, had a great crisis thrust upon him, the Persian Gulf
War, and a great opportunity, the collapse of Communism.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Albright has not had such a test or made such an
opportunity of Asia or Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't operate on the basis of instant gratification on any
part of my daily work,'' she said. ``The policies that are being
put into place are longer term. It may be the next secretary of
state will reap the rewards of what I've done. Sitting in this
chair you get the sense that you are a part of history.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted her recent induction into the Women's Hall of Fame.
``When they say I'm the highest-ranking woman in the history of the
United States, that's pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Kipper of the Council on Foreign Relations, while a
fierce critic of U.S. Middle East policy, praises Albright for
showing the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can be soft with her children, motherly and nice and go
shopping and be all the things a decent person can be, Ms. Kipper
said, ``but when it comes to the work, she's tough and serious.
There's no gender in the work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
