<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S POLITICAL RIFT WIDENS ON EVE OF CLINTON-YELTSIN SUMMIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's political crisis deepened Monday as President
Clinton, on the eve of an ill-timed summit, sought to bolster the
Kremlin's resolve to continue painful reforms even as the economy
falters.
</P>
<P>
   In another setback for Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
legislators in the Communist-led Duma rejected Viktor Chernomyrdin
as prime minister. The overwhelming vote, 253-94, came a day after
Parliament leaders opposed a pact that would have allowed Yeltsin
to form a new Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The move heightened the political confrontation roiling the
nation as its economy teeters near collapse. Both sides warned of a
possible uprising if the chaos continues.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia before leaving for Moscow, Clinton tried to urge the
Russians to stay on the path toward reform, saying the United
States and other Western nations had an obligation to help Russia
if it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is go there and tell them that the easy
thing to do is not the right thing to do. The easy thing to do
would be to try to go back to the way they did it before and that's
not possible,'' said Clinton, speaking at a meeting with educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if they will stay on the path of reform to stabilize their
society and strengthen their economy and to get growth back, then I
believe America and the rest of the Western nations with strong
economies should help them, and indeed have an obligation to help
them'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides noted the International Monetary Fund will soon decide
whether to make another $4.3 billion installment on its $22.6
billion bailout for Russia. The Russian government used the first
payment to prop up the ruble but that strategy failed. The
currency's value tumbled, the stock market went into a free fall
and the banking system neared failure.
</P>
<P>
   The economic turmoil prompted Yeltsin to turn to Chernomyrdin,
whom he had fired just five months earlier. An agreement between
Yeltsin and the Parliament this weekend called for an 18-month
truce if the president would surrender some of his sweeping powers.
But the Duma leaders rejected the pact, and Chernomyrdin's
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Duma leader Gennady Zyuganov blamed Chernomyrdin for Russia's
current economic situation, noting he presided over the nation as
the economy worsened.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported Zyuganov told Chernomyrdin, ``You
will fail and bring the country to ruin.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin told Duma members, ``Russia is on the verge of
political and economic collapse. We can only come out of the crisis
by uniting our efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin can submit Chernomyrdin's name two more times but
Parliament is expected to hold talks to suggest possible
alternatives. If the Duma, the lower chamber, rejects Yeltsin's
choice three times, the legislature can be dissolved and new
elections held.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fail to reach an agreement here everything will spill
out to the streets,'' Zyuganov said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's parliamentary liaison told the AP that the crisis
could lead to dire consequences for the entire government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this chaos lasts for several more weeks, it may happen that
there will be neither Communists nor us,'' Alexander Kotenkov
warned. ``I mean a popular uprising, merciless and senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   Russians continue to await the payoff of democratic reforms and
a turn toward a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   A stylishly dressed Aida Tairova, 28, huddled under an umbrella
with a friend and explained that she has been looking for a job for
more than a year. She cares little for Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of her friends and relatives live in poverty. They cannot
make ends meet,'' said a translator. Tairova, on one hand, wants
Russia to follow the United States' example, but then also talks
about how Russia was better under communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Russian people did not suffer and the living standards
were on the average OK. It was better under the communists,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Ivanova, 57, who runs a newsstand in an underground
shopping area, said, ``Life is not worse. Life is more difficult,''
she said, adding Russia cannot return to communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all in the past. We have come a long way since those
times. Some things are better, some things are worse. The very fact
we are moving forward is a good thing,'' Ivanova said.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides maintained the Duma's action should have
little significant impact on the summit between Clinton and
Yeltsin, a session already under question because both presidents
are embattled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an internal Russian matter,'' said P.J. Crowley, a
national security council spokesman. ``They'll work through this.
This was something you could anticipate given the rejection of the
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will still be greeted by Chernomyrdin, who remains the
acting prime minister, as he arrives for a two-day summit.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, the president explained why it was important for
him to visit with Yeltsin at this critical time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I'm going to Russia is that we've learned the hard
way that problems that develop beyond our borders sooner or later
find their way to our doorstep unless we help our friends and our
neighbors deal with them as quickly and as promptly as possible,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian people are to be commended for embracing democracy
and getting rid of the old communist system but they are having
some troubles today making the transition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted the United States and Russia still have the
largest nuclear arsenals in the world. He said Russia's cooperation
was critical to curtailing nuclear weapons and stopping sales to
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``A weakened Russian economy would put enormous pressure on
people who have those technologies and understandings to sell them.
We don't want that to happen,'' Clinton said. He also noted
Russia's partnership was critical to halting the war in Bosnia and
will be needed to stop bloodshed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Russia will stay on the path of reform, I believe America
and the rest of the West will help them,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
