</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT CALLS CLINTON'S BEHAVIOR WITH LEWINSKY `DISGUSTING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling President Clinton's behavior
``disgusting,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said the
president's affair with Monica Lewinsky and his lying about it have
damaged the presidency and raised questions about his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Lott predicted that the sex scandal would interfere with
congressional action in the coming weeks, including a fight over
the federal budget that could lead to a government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   While blasting the president during a news conference marking
the Senate's return from summer recess, Lott stopped short of
calling for Clinton's impeachment or resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can he lead? Can he provide leadership without the necessary
respect and with the problems that he has?''' Lott told reporters.
``Can he provide leadership at a very critical time internationally
and domestically? Guess only time will answer that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott also warned foreign groups against mistaking Clinton's
troubles for a weakness in U.S. resolve to combat terrorism. ``To
those that would threaten out country, to terrorists or anyone else
who think they could take advantage of what might appear as a
weakened presidency, on these matters we will stand united,'' the
Mississippi Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments from Lott came as Clinton left for a two-day
meeting with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who is struggling to
remain in power and grappling with economic crisis. From Moscow,
Clinton later this week flies to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel Kenneth Starr is preparing a report for
Congress outlining evidence gathered in a seven-month investigation
of Clinton's admitted affair with Lewinsky, a former White House
intern. The report, which is expected to be delivered in late
September, will address other issues, such as possible obstruction
of justice, that could lead to impeachment hearings against the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Clinton should resign over the affair and subsequent
public lies, Lott demurred. ``I think they are disgusting. I'm very
disappointed by the whole matter ... (and) the fact that apparently
these acts did occur in the White House and that he, well, lied
about it to the American people,'' the majority leader said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it will rise to levels that could justify
proceeding in the House on impeachment or anything else,'' Lott
said. ``So I am going to wait for that report and withhold judgment
or further comment until I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who has steered clear of public comments about the sex
scandal since Clinton two weeks ago admitted an affair, said he is
``offended by the president's behavior and by the tragic example he
has set'' for young Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a moral dimension to the American presidency, and
today that dimension, that power, has been lost in scandal and
deception,'' Lott said. ``I am disappointed in the way the highest
office in the nation has been reduced in stature and diminished in
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other Republican leaders, Lott accused Clinton and
congressional Democrats of refusing to yield in budget negotiations
in hopes of prompting a shutdown of federal agencies similar to one
three years ago. He said the scandal has cast a shadow over
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the present circumstances it could be tough to work
together, especially if the president's congressional allies circle
the wagons and try to shut things down.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has threatened to veto half the 13 spending bills that
must be signed into law by Oct. 1 to keep most federal agencies in
operation for the coming year. The measures under veto-threat were
amended by Republicans to include various policies or programs
opposed by Clinton, such as school vouchers, abortion bans and
funding cuts for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said it was ``laughable for
Senator Lott to suggest that the president or anybody else is to
blame if Congress doesn't complete its work in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said the president's
supporters in the Senate will try to amend upcoming legislation to
include health-care reform, campaign-finance revisions and the
president's school construction program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a danger of a (government) shutdown, we all know
where it originates,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
