<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-PALEO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ORDERS RECONSIDERATION OF GAS PIPELINE ROUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US government has ordered the companies laying a natural-gas
pipeline from Maine to Massachusetts to consider rerouting it
around one of the oldest inhabited sites ever discovered in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission has also demanded that
pipeline project officials explain why they did not seek required
federal approval to excavate the site in Eliot, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Artifacts as old as 12,000 years are believed to have been found
at the site near the New Hampshire border. Archeological excavation
was completed in July, but at least one person who worked on the
project believes pressure was applied to meet construction
deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Globe report on those concerns influenced federal
officials to investigate the decision to lay the pipe through the
Paleoindian site, a project official said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the pipeline's designers must either come up with a plan to
reroute the project or present a potentially risky defense of their
decision to disturb the Paleoindian site.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense might pit one historical era against another,
since officials say they routed the pipe to avoid disturbing the
historical remains of a Colonial garrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The garrison site was more important than anyone had
recognized. ... This is a rich and layered piece of land,'' said
John Flumerfelt, spokesman for the pipeline's company.
</P>
<P>
   The company, the Portland Natural Gas Transmission System, said
one of its subcontractors erred by failing to notify federal
officials of the archeological discovery and of the plan to remove
the artifacts. Working with the State Historic Preservation Office,
however, a plan was devised to excavate the area and route the
pipeline through the site, Flumerfelt said.
</P>
<P>
   But a top federal administrator, who can order the pipeline to
be re-routed, said state notification is not enough in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that your companies are not adhering to proper
procedures,'' Kevin P. Madden, director of FERC's Office of
Pipeline Regulation, wrote to project leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff was never afforded the opportunity to review the
treatment plan, and obviously had no opportunity to determine when,
and if, avoidance (of the archeological site) was prudent and
feasible,'' Madden wrote. ``I need a detailed explanation from you
regarding the events surrounding this most serious concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Flumerfelt said pipeline supervisors are confident that the
federal government will arrive at the same conclusion _ that
routing through the Paleoindian site is the best alternative. The
Colonial garrison, dating to about 1700, is nearby and also
considered an important, complex archeological site that pipeline
officials had to consider when devising a route.
</P>
<P>
   Because the site is located on private land, the owner's
concerns could also be a factor in placing the pipeline, project
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ate some humble pie and admitted we made a mistake'' by not
notifying the federal government, Flumerfelt said. ``FERC asked us
to do some further evaluation and analyze the site and minimize any
additional impact to the site.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Flumerfelt said project officials hope to lay the pipe
within the next two weeks, Madden said that no work will be
authorized until his office has approved the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way,'' Madden said. ``It's important that
applicants follow our regulations and requirements. Absent that,
you would have essentially an applicant who would build wherever
they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   One option suggested by federal officials would be to bury the
pipe under the site. Flumerfelt, however, said that alternative may
be even more disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have final say over the route of the
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not satisfied,'' Flumerfelt said, ``they can push
us back for more evaluation, and unilaterally impose an alternative
on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts uncovered in Eliot include red-flint scrapers from
Munsungan Lake, 250 miles away in northern Maine. Also found were a
stone drill and burned bone, which may reveal what game was hunted
by the region's earliest inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen Paleoindian sites have been found in New
England. The date of these artifacts comes from an era shortly
after a mile-long ice sheet had retreated northward from
present-day New England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
