<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STATE-FAIR-ART-800     08-31 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STATE-FAIR-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE FAIR, MIX OF THE NEW AND OLD, ON LINE TO SET ATTENDANCE
RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Just next door to the display of the state's
largest squash and only a flight of stairs above the room where
assorted jams vied for glory, Kate Broderick struck a pose.
</P>
<P>
   Her exuberantly purple gown was neither the worst nor the best
of the 42 outfits worn by as many teen-agers in a fashion revue
Saturday morning at the New York State Fair, but Miss Broderick,
16, of Rensselaer County, stood out nonetheless. Unlike most of the
other 4-H Club girls and boys on the stage, she had not stitched,
dyed, beaded or brocaded what she was wearing.
</P>
<P>
   The totality of her accomplishment had been to purchase it for a
really, really good price.
</P>
<P>
   As she sidled back and forth, beaming and iridescent, an
announcer explained that Miss Broderick had sought an affordable
dress and had come across this one ``when she was almost about to
give up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was stunned to find that the price was only $29.99,'' the
announcer marveled. ``She just couldn't beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Intrepid shopping on a par with intricate sewing? It spoke
volumes not only about the tenor of the times, but also about the
way the New York State Fair has endeavored to keep pace with them.
</P>
<P>
   For many city slickers familiar with state fairs only through
old movies or television programs, the annual, end-of-summer events
are anachronistic bastions of quaint pastoralism. To some extent,
that's accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The wonders of cultivation, from monstrous zucchini to mammoth
swine, are still celebrated. The divine arts of pickling, canning,
cookie baking and jelly making still garner intensely coveted blue
ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   But while the 152d New York State Fair includes cows trotted out
by breeders eager to show off their livestock, it also features
llamas leaping over a gradually raised bar for no purpose other
than entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   And while there are displays paying tribute to the homespun
ingenuity behind hat decorating and flower arranging, there are
also events and exhibitions honoring bicycle acrobatics, chain-saw
sculpturing and, in Miss Broderick's case, keen-eyed trips down the
aisles of Marshall's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take everybody into account when we prepare the fair,''
said Peter Cappuccilli Jr., the director of the New York State
Fair. ``We've had to make it interesting for all people.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers suggest that fair officials have succeeded. Last
year, 865,000 people attended the 12-day event, second only to
1995, when 882,000 went. Those numbers represented sharp increases
from the 1960s and 1970s, when attendance was usually about
500,000.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the fair, which began last Thursday and ends next
Monday, is on a pace to draw an all-time high of more than 900,000,
state fair officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They estimated that less than 5 percent of today's fairgoers
actually make their livelihoods from agriculture or livestock and
said that New York's fair, like scores of others across the
country, has evolved to reflect that.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a dizzying, all-purpose entertainment
extravaganza, replete this year with hard rock concerts, helicopter
rides and the tedious but awe-inspiring construction of what is
intended to be world's largest sand castle, which should top out at
about 35 feet and more than 400 tons by the time the fair closes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a kitsch-a-palooza, where people can drop by the Pan
African Village to purchase lilliputian African figurines that
function as refrigerator magnets, then amble over to the Center of
Progress for Hawaiian-style leis of flowers they select themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a helter-skelter smorgasbord of such dubiously
nutritious concoctions as snow cones, cotton candy, saltwater taffy
and, of course, golden, greasy funnel cakes. Fried dough is to
state fairs as chocolate is to Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state fair is an orgy of consumption,'' said Mark Ritson,
a marketing professor at the University of Minnesota who is
studying state fairs. As such, Ritson said, it captures the world
around it as well as it ever did.
</P>
<P>
   Americans once defined themselves by what they produced, and the
state fair's parade of newfangled tractors, plump tomatoes and
fleecy sheep paid tribute to that. Americans now define themselves
by what they purchase and consume, and the state fair exalts and
indulges their ravenous, sometimes indiscriminate appetites.
</P>
<P>
   State fairs began in the early 19th century as American
adaptations of European harvest festivals, which reveled in the
bounty of the land. They were vital to the agrarian economy,
serving as trade shows for farmers who needed to familiarize
themselves with the changing tools and methods of production or
advertise their goods to potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   But as the country industrialized and the number of small farms
and farmers dwindled, state fairs were threatened with irrelevance.
By the late 1980's, many state legislatures were cutting off tax
money for the events and insisting that fairs become economically
self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Joe LaGuardia, the marketing director for the New York State
Fair, said it stopped receiving public money for anything but major
construction work in 1990. While the fair is still its own quasi
agency within the State Department of Agriculture and Markets, it
now supports itself, in part through aggressive courtship of
corporate sponsors. Every other pavilion or event at the fair seems
to wear the tag of a company or brand name, from Coca-Cola to Pizza
Hut, Mikasa to Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Fair officials have also devised ways to sell its most
traditional elements to a modern audience by framing the fair as a
sort of living museum, a child-friendly educational bridge to a
simpler era.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The buildings devoted to cows and dairy products include not
only the animals themselves, but also a painted wooden effigy at
which children can mimic the task of milking, and a refrigerated
sculpture of a milk deliveryman made with 1,000 pounds of butter.
</P>
<P>
   There are tours of working barns that leave regularly from the
fairgrounds. Matt and Linda Clark and their three sons had just
returned from one when they sat down for a brief rest in the goat
and swine building on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most kids don't realize where everything comes from, and we
learned that 98 percent of a beef cow is used for different things,
not just for food,'' said Clark, a nuclear engineer from Parish,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   His wife nodded her agreement. ``A lot of people from New York
City don't know anything about this stuff,'' she said with more
than a touch of rural pride. ``They only know about the restaurants
where the beef ends up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia draws many people to the fair. Carol Koller of
Rockville Center, N.Y., came for a second year in a row and dwelled
upon a jar of award-winning pickled vegetables in the Home Art
Center on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way our grandparents lived,'' she said. ``Who has
the time today? Everybody runs around.''
</P>
<P>
   But the march of progress was evident even in the culinary
judging booth just feet away, where a panel of four women coronate
the fruitiest pies, fluffiest cakes and fudgiest brownies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more and more low-sugar categories,'' said Candy
Crider, a home economics teacher on the panel. ``Grilled vegetables
are new this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very trendy,'' chimed in another judge, Carol Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   The judges were in a delicate mood, for it was jam and jelly
day, not among their favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so sweet and unrelenting,'' said Ms. Bradford, who
received a nutrition degree from Cornell University and studied at
the Cordon Bleu in Paris, as she steered her plastic spoon toward a
paper plate with several gelatinous smears.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the jam entries had to be eliminated at the outset.
``One of the rules is that we won't eat anything that has a foreign
object in it, like hair or debris from the kitchen,'' Ms. Bradford
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the ones we can identify,'' said Ms. Crider, who
clucked appreciatively over a blueberry-spearmint entry in the
``herb jelly or jam'' category and a cranberry-jalapeno melange in
the ``favorite jelly'' field.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come was Spam day, rewarding the contestant who uses
the processed luncheon meat in the most ingeniously delectable
fashion with a $100 prize from Hormel Foods and the chance to
compete in the company's national Spam contest. One year, the
contest was won by someone who used Spam in a chocolate cake.
</P>
<P>
   Also ahead was the macaroni and cheese bake-off, which Sharon
Potucek of Skaneateles, N.Y., a regular fairgoer who was hovering
near the judging area on Saturday morning, said she was hoping to
win. ``You can do a lot with macaroni and cheese,'' said Ms.
Potucek, an office manager for a heating fuel company. ``And I'm
not telling you what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that in a new twist for her fair-obsessed family, she
and her husband were competing against each other, and not just in
one category. Both were submitting macaroni and cheese dishes and
fruit pies. ``I think we're headed for divorce,'' Ms. Potucek said.
</P>
<P>
   But for every fairgoer who approaches the event with the utmost
seriousness, there are several who revel in its sheer goofiness.
Events like the leaping llamas, staged on Friday night to a
recording of the Pointer Sisters song ``Jump,'' cater shamelessly
to that crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to do is pick out your favorite llama and cheer
'em on to victory,'' explained Valerie Podet, a graduate student in
geology at the State University of New York at Buffalo. Ms. Podet
had a special interest in the outcome; her department chairman,
Michael Sheridan, owned one of the llamas in the contest.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the serene beasts of burden, several of them shorn
and groomed to look like gargantuan poodles, were led on leashes
toward a horizontal wooden pole. Some simply planted their feet and
refused to budge. Some blithely barged into the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan's llama did fine at 30 and 32 inches, but failed at 34.
By 36 inches, the field of about a dozen llamas had been narrowed
to two, and ``Jump'' was on its third or fourth replay. The winning
height was 40 inches, nearly as high as the triumphant llama's
back.
</P>
<P>
   There were peals of laughter, hoots of delight and robust
applause. Then the 200 spectators scattered into the night. Candied
apples, laser tag games, a live shark exhibit and a show by the
Wallflowers, part of the Molson Concert Series, awaited them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
