<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1617 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HN     08-31 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
It has come down to this. The Comets vs. the Mercury yet again,
this time for all the marbles.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WNBA championship every team coveted when the 1998 season
began _ and that the Comets fought so gallantly on Saturday to
retain _ is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   But forget about the Comets' rally from a 12-point deficit late
in the second half to beat Phoenix 74-69 in overtime and even the
best-of-three series at a game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about that series-opening duel in the desert five days
ago, when the Comets shot terribly, scored a season-low 51 points
and fell into an 0-1 hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure's back on both teams. Period,'' Phoenix coach
Cheryl Miller said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Comets point guard Kim Perrot said all that will matter tonight
at 7 at Compaq Center is ``who wants it the most, who executes the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's no longer pressure, in one sense,'' Perrot
said. ``Going into the first game, everybody said (we had)
home-court advantage, when you really don't. When you have to play
in front of 16,000 or 17,000 screaming fans in Phoenix, that's not
home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pressured at that point. We were pressured to come
back Saturday night. We knew we had to win to bring it into another
game. So we were pressured then.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, it's a whole new ballgame. It's 0-0, and it's whoever
is going to want it most. I don't think that the Comets are being
pressured. I just think that we have some kinks to straighten out
so that we can be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is an advantage entering the rubber game of the series,
an argument can be made that it rests with the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   It took a 71-60 Phoenix victory over Cleveland in the third game
of their semifinal series _ played in front of a partisan Rockers
crowd at Gund Arena _ just for the Mercury to get to this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to it,'' Miller said. ``This team knows how to play
under pressure. Had to do it all season. So we're very
well-prepared for this game. We know what's at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Mercury didn't have the luxury of a record-breaking
season and 27-3 overall record upon which to hang its hat. Phoenix
came closer to setting a league record for consecutive losses than
to matching the Comets' WNBA-record 15-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   And despite seven wins in its last nine games, the Mercury saw
its entire season and playoff future come down to the final day. A
loss by New York at Detroit coupled with Phoenix's win over
Sacramento ensured the Mercury would be alive for the second
season.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been no cakewalk to the final dance for the Comets,
either. They wrapped up a playoff berth and clinched the league's
best record (and thus the home-court advantage) two weeks before
the season ended. Consequently, with nothing to play for, the
Comets slipped away from the team style that had carried them to
the top. Lacking intensity and motivation at New York on Aug. 15,
they suffered their worst loss of the season, 70-54 to the Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets regrouped to start the playoffs, with the offense and
defense working well in back-to-back semifinal wins over Charlotte.
But at Phoenix in Game 1 of the WNBA Championship Series, they
lapsed into a spotty performance that carried over to the first
half Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just experienced some pressure up until today,'' coach
Van Chancellor said Monday. ``We've been playing like the weight of
the world's been on our shoulders. We've just got to come out and
play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time WNBA Most Valuable Player Cynthia Cooper said it's
imperative for the Comets to jump on the Mercury early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of playing catch-up,'' she said. ``I want them to
play catch-up. I want them to have to worry about stopping us.
We've been playing catch-up since we've been in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for us to step up and play our game right from the
beginning. Every possession is very important, and we've got to
look at it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, said Chancellor, played some of the best defensive
basketball he has ever witnessed in throttling the Mercury over the
final 12{ minutes in Game 2. Janeth Arcain came off the bench to
spell Perrot, who is playing on two sprained ankles, and shut down
Michele Timms, a scoring machine for the Mercury until then.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper and Sheryl Swoopes combined for 20 of the Comets' final
22 points, and Swoopes became a terror on the backboards as she
recorded a finals-record 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said that what occurred over the final 12{ minutes
Saturday ``could be a momentum-shifter for this series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout this series, Phoenix has had the momentum,'' she
said. ``They've gone back and forth, playing at their place at
first and then coming in here with the feeling that they had two
chances to win one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had absolutely no pressure on them. Now, for the first
time, they have as much pressure as we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing for all the marbles,'' Cooper said. ``This is
the position we wanted to be in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in this position last year. And hopefully, the
comeback (Saturday) will bring us momentum going into this last
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
