u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-SUMMIT-510&AMP;ADD     08-31 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUMMIT-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERAGE RUSSIANS TAKE LITTLE NOTICE OF PLANS FOR CLINTON-YELTSIN
MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT, CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE,
RUSSIA-RESCUE, RUSSIA-DEBATE, RUSSIA-CLINTON) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's top network news program, ``Vremya,'' led
Monday night with parliament's rejection of Viktor Chernomyrdin as
prime minister, the ruble's continued wobbliness and the
anniversary of Diana's death. Then it flagged plans by Muslim
extremists for several villages in rural Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   And oh, yes _ the president of the United States arrives Tuesday
morning for a summit meeting with the president of Russia, Boris
Yeltsin. That item was relegated to the second half of the
newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Such meetings used to be called summit meetings for a reason.
One can harken to Reykjavik, where Ronald Reagan and Mikhail
Gorbachev nearly disarmed, or Vienna, where Nikita Khrushchev took
John F. Kennedy to the woodshed, or even Washington, where Yeltsin
ascended to the world stage on the arm of George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It would hardly be fair to call the latest meeting a nadir.
There still are important issues to chew on. But in Russia, at
least, it is close to a non-event.
</P>
<P>
   Four newspapers published Monday editions here (most newspapers
take the day off), including two serious journals, Sevodnya and
Komsomolskaya Pravda. None mentioned the next day's meeting _ not
merely on page 1, but anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no enthusiasm,'' said Sergei Karaganov, a foreign
policy specialist and sometime adviser to Russia's foreign
minister, Yevgeny Primakov. ``It's not an issue for the simple
reason that there are more important issues on the agenda. Most
people, even in the political class, do not even suspect or
remember that there is a meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the most spirited comment on the summit meeting came
Monday from Russia's wildest-eyed ultranationalist, Vladimir
Zhirinovsky, who said people with Russians' high moral standards
have no business meeting ``with a man who cannot settle his
relations with a secretary.'' ``According to the traditions of
Russian society, in this case, divorce the wife and marry the
secretary,'' Zhirinovsky said. ``Turn this disgraceful page over.''
</P>
<P>
   To an extent, Russians can be excused for their indifference. In
the judgment of most experts, the country is in its worst political
crisis since 1993, when Yeltsin's tanks shelled the parliament
building to put down a rebellion, and perhaps since the Soviet
Union dissolved in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The great national issues these days, discussed everywhere, are
the number of rubles a dollar will buy and the odds of a civil war
or putsch. Clinton's arrival seems trivial in comparison,
especially since he has little but moral support to lend Russia's
democrats after their calamitous seven-year experiment with
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's three-day visit will cover the usual weighty
summit-meeting bases, from international terrorism to nuclear
proliferation to disarmament. To average Russians _ indeed, to
Russia's parliament and much of its executive branch _ none of them
holds a candle right now to the 40 percent rise in the cost of
cooking oil at local markets or depositors' almost-complete
inability to tap savings accounts at the neighborhood bank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Clinton, this visit is also a comedown. His advisers first
held out the meeting as a glittering prize for Russia should it
finally ratify the Start II nuclear weapons treaty. Unfortunately,
the get-togethers are not so prized anymore, and the
communist-controlled parliament was more than happy to let the
treaty languish if that would keep Clinton out of town. And so the
president's trip has been recast primarily as an economic pep talk
for Yeltsin and his troops, urging them to stay the agonizing
course to free-market prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is to go there and tell them that the easy
thing to do is not the right thing to do,'' Clinton said Monday in
Virginia, in an apparent reference to alternatives to capitalism.
``The easy thing to do would be to go back to the way they did it
before, and it's not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a problem with this message, it is that Russians
have heard it several times from virtually every western leader,
and with the ruble's drop of close to 40 percent this month alone,
it may be starting to ring a bit false.
</P>
<P>
   The West may have had the best of intentions, Karaganov, the
policy specialist, said Monday, but its advice and Yeltsin's
Western-trained advisers ``have brought about the total collapse of
the economy and effectively bankrupted most of the Russian
bourgeoisie in the last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the little summit news that is playing in Moscow this
week, on talk radio and even in some newspapers, is more often the
refrain sung Monday afternoon by Kazbek Tzikou, a communist
legislator from the depressed southern region of Kuban.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin stands over everyone like a cobra and forces them to
do what his friend Bill wants,'' Tzikou told the lower hose of
parliament, the Duma, on Monday. ``Tell Clinton not to come. People
would tear him to pieces if they could. Let him go to the moon with
his advice and his dollars.'' But he added, ``Tell the American
people that we wish peace and accord with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
