A1625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-LAWSUIT-COX     08-31 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN sues over use of trademark on Internet
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving on (f) financial and (a) general news wires.)
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A New York Internet company is abusing Cable News
Network's trademark by using a Web address similar to CNN's to sell
pornography, CNN says in a federal lawsuit filed in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   CNN accuses The Net Inc., of Hewlitt, N.Y., of diluting its
trademark and tarnishing its name and seeks damages, attorney's
fees and a court order prohibiting The Net from continuing to use
its name.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN Interactive Web site is advertised as providing 24-hour,
up-to-the-minute news information and is viewed more than 30
million times a week by computer users. The Web site's ``domain
name'' is registered at the address of CNN.com. The Net's
pornographic site changes the ``.com'' portion of the address, but
maintains the ``CNN'' portion, the lawsuit says.
</P>
<P>
   The Net ``is a classic domain name pirate'' because it registers
names similar or identical to well-known trademarks, according to
the suit, which was filed Friday. The Net then ``holds the domain
names hostage until the trademark owners meet extortionist demands
for the transfer of the domain names,'' the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The Net has registered sites with domain names similar to
acronyms for numerous federal agencies and private companies: NASA,
NASDAQ, MCI and WNBC, the lawsuit said. The New York Web company is
operating for-profit pornographic Web sites using acronyms such as
DOJ and USDA, the lawsuit said, adding that some of the Web sites
include online casino services.
</P>
<P>
   The Net registered a pornographic Web site with an address
similar to CNN's. After finding out about it, CNN tried to resolve
the matter with The Net. The Net offered to take down its CNN Web
site, but only if CNN paid $2,500 to the New York company, the
lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at The Net could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great things about the Internet is that it
radically expands the number of people who can reach the world,''
Harvard law professor William W. Fisher III, a trademark
specialist, said. ``But it also means that opportunities to the
world at-large to make fun of, erode or tarnish trademarks are
increasing enormously.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
