<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      08-31 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK GROWS OF FED INTEREST-RATE CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-ASSESS, HONGKONG-MARKET MARKET-COMPARE,
MARKET-VOICES, MARKET-CYBERSPACE, MARKET-BROKERS) 
(JT) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As foreign and domestic investors fled to the safe
harbor of the U.S. Treasury market Monday, talk was growing of a
market-calming interest rate cut by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in Treasury buying came in the afternoon, as the stock
market lost its footing and the Dow Jones industrial plunged to its
second worst one-day point decline ever. The yield on the 30-year
bond dropped to 5.25 percent, the lowest for long-term rates in 30
years and a level that many or most of those who work on Wall
Street have not experienced in their working lifetimes. The yield
on the 10-year note fell to 4.96 percent, the first time it has
been below 5 percent since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   As the growing global economic crisis seems daily to impinge
more on the still healthy American economy, several analysts
predicted that the 12 percent decline in the Dow in the last week,
would help force the Federal Reserve to lower its benchmark
short-term interest rate soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't ignore the message of the market,'' said John
Lipsky, the chief economist at Chase Manhattan Bank, referring to
the fact that long-term interest rates are now well below the Fed's
5.5 percent target for short-term interest rates. ``And the message
of the market is that the risks are heavily weighted on the side of
a slowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barbera, chief economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co., said the stock
market fall also should prompt action by the Fed. ``This now
constitutes a breathtaking decline that central banks are supposed
to pay attention to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rapid decline in interest rates should provide some
offset to the drag from Asia, as lower rates spur the housing
industry. The plunge in the 10-year note, which is a benchmark for
mortgage rates, should mean that already low mortgage rates drop
further.
</P>
<P>
   But Lipsky argued that the economy has too much drag. At the
present time, he said, the Fed's 5.5 percent target for the Federal
Funds rate _ the rate on overnight loans between banks _ is higher
after adjustment for inflation than at the end of 1994. That was
when the Mexican peso was devalued, setting off a market selloff
that was serious but paled by comparison to the plunge in both
developed and emerging markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the 19-percent plunge in the Dow since July 17
is sure to make consumers more cautious, cutting into the strong
consumer spending that has kept the economy _ even though it slowed
in the second quarter _ stronger than many forecasters had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   This slowdown by the consumer, plus the already painful drop in
American exports because of the evaporation of buying from Asia,
should slow the economy to no growth in the second half of the
year, he said, a reason for the Fed to ease.
</P>
<P>
   Barbera argued that the Fed has to lower its interest rate to
ease the pressure on the troubled emerging markets, most of which
have large debts denominated in dollars that have to be rolled over
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policy makers are next scheduled to meet on Sept
29. At their Aug. 18 meeting they decided, as expected, to leave
their short-term interest rate target unchanged. In the minutes of
the July meeting Fed officials showed no inclination to cutting
interest rates, in part because the economy was still strong and
there were signs of inflationary wage pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy makers can act, however, at any time between
meetings. As the Asian economic crisis has spread to engulf Russia
and to threaten Latin America all talk of a Fed rate increase has
disappeared. But there is still a debate among economists over if
and when the Fed would decide to lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that Fed officials could ease some concerns with
just a hint, in a speech or comment, that the Fed is watching and
ready to take action if necessary. The Fed did announce Monday that
its chairman, Alan Greenspan, was monitoring the markets while on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the Fed is unlikely to act immediately
because that might be interpreted as a sign of panic. But the Fed
has taken such an action in the past with the interest rate cut
after the stock market crash in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   With Monday's decline in Treasury interest rates, the 30-year
bond yield of 5.25 percent, the 10-year note yield of 4.96 percent,
the five-year note yield of 4.78 percent and the two-year note
yield of 4.76 percent are all below the 5.5 percent Fed target for
the Fed funds rate.
</P>
<P>
   This is known as an inverted yield curve and has, in the past,
signaled a slowdown for the economy or even a recession. That has
been because the Fed funds rate moved higher than longer-term rates
as the Fed raised its target to slow economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the inversion has been produced by a drop in
longer-term rates as the Fed left its target rate unchanged. But
while this appears to be less negative, it seems to be signaling a
slowdown anyway.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the high level of short-term interest rates,
after adjustment for inflation, is a drag on the economy. Another
is that the flight to a safe harbor is a signal of weakening
economic prospects abroad, which, in turn, are bad for the American
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that both the flight to a safe harbor and the
realization that the U.S. economy is slowing should push interest
rates even lower. But if some calm returns to both foreign and
American markets, there could be a selloff that could force
interest rates higher temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
