<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-DEBATE-965&AMP;ADD     08-31 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DEBATE-965&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PARLIAMENT DEBATE HIGHLIGHTS LACK OF TRUST ON ALL SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT, CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE,
RUSSIA-SUMMIT, RUSSIA-CLINTON) 
(nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ For a country that hasn't had a government for a week _
a week in which its currency plummeted and its banking system
veered towards collapse, there was a striking lack of urgency to
the debate Monday in the Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the vote against confirmation of Viktor Chernomyrdin as
prime minister was a foregone conclusion, after the Communist
opposition pulled back from a power-sharing agreement on Sunday
that would have salvaged his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But as political leaders took their turns at the podium, the
debate veered away from the country's future to a fusillade of
political attacks and counter-attacks about its recent past,
zooming off at one point to a recommendation for President Clinton
_ due here on Tuesday _ to put his personal scandal behind him by
divorcing his wife, and marrying his ``secretary.''
</P>
<P>
   As political theater, the stormy language, the grand-standing
and the finger-pointing was impressive, but it did nothing to break
Russia's political deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a theme running through the debate, both in the
hall and in the corridors outside, it was the complete collapse of
trust between Russia's warring political forces. Communists Monday
attacked the proposed power-sharing agreement as worth no more than
the paper it was written on, while politicians of all stripes
derided Chernomyrdin _ who served five years as prime minister
until his ouster last March _ as a man who doesn't deserve a second
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kid in Russia can tell you the main problem of the Russian
government,'' said Grigory Yavlinsky, whose party, Yabloko, has
always been critical of Chernomyrdin's rule. ``It's that there are
thieves in it. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   In this all-too-familiar confrontation between President Boris
Yeltsin and the parliamentary opposition, both sides are
forecasting an apocalyptic conclusion, with street riots that lead
to the worst Russian nightmare of all, civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Given Russia's bloody history and the truly precarious state of
its economy, such dire predictions would be frightening _ if it
weren't for the fact that they have been usurped by politicians,
and inserted in a strangely hollow political debate.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what would happen if Yeltsin insisted on Chernomyrdin's
nomination through a third, and final, ballot, then dissolved the
lower house of parliament, Konstantin Savelyev, a Communist deputy
from the region outside Moscow, calmly went down a list of possible
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be a state of emergency, a dictatorship, and
lawlessness,'' he said. `There could be a civil war and then
everyone would be wiped out, Reds, Whites, Greens _ everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The same thoughts were echoed Monday by Yeltsin's parliamentary
envoy, and on Sunday night on television by Boris Berezovsky, the
multibillionaire and political intriguer, who played a key role in
bringing Chernomyrdin back to government.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office in the cultural affairs committee of the
lower house, or Duma, Nikoali Gubenko, a Communist deputy known
best to Russian audiences as an actor and theater director, was no
more sanguine about the outcome of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a third vote on Mr. Chernomyrdin, he will be
rejected, the Duma will be dissolved, and we will have a
dictatorship by a sick man,'' said Gubenko. He predicted that
opposition leaders will come forward this week with other names to
head a new government, but Yeltsin is certain to reject them. ``I
don't think it will work out,'' he said. ``He will insist on
Chernomyrdin, again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gubenko also rejected reports that the Communists were now ready
for serious horse-trading over jobs in a Chernomyrdin Cabinet. ``As
long as Yeltsin is in power, the Communists won't be in government
unless it is headed by someone from the center-left opposition,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other deputies were not sure that the Communists, in playing out
their hand, are not upping their bid for strong representation in a
Chernomyrdin government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the bargaining begins,'' said a deputy for Chernomyrdin's
own party, Our Home is Russia, as he rushed into the chamber to
cast his vote.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Ilyukhin, deputy leader of the Communists' parliamentary
group, said the Communists have sought 10 posts in a Chernomyrdin
cabinet, including the interior ministry. The other posts should
also be significant, he said, noting that anything less would be
``senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Grachev, a deputy from Yavlinsky's party, said Chernomyrdin
still may have a chance to put together a coalition cabinet, made
up of opposition figures and leaders from Russia's increasingly
powerful regions, that would satisfy parliament. But, he said, even
such a team will be incapable of governing the country, and putting
the economy back on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no hope that a Chernomyrdin government will be
effective,'' he said. ``He has shown us over five years that he can
move only through inertia. Power in Russia is not stable, the
position of Yeltsin is not stable, the Duma is not popular, and the
worsening of living standards makes the situation worse. The
possibility of a nonconstitutional outcome is likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin began the debate Monday with an attempt to focus
parliament's attention on the crisis at hand. ``Time is running
out,'' he said. But by the end of the day, he too was ready to join
in the fray, attacking his critics in disparaging terms, and
putting most of the blame on ex-Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko's
four-month government, and the radical anti-crisis program it put
into place on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot throw stones at anybody,'' he said, ``but what
happened on the 17th, should not have been done, and Chernomyrdin
would have never done it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to Communist Party leaders, attempts over the weekend
to patch together a political compromise were torpedoed by the
refusal of the president's negotiators to even consider some of the
leftist opposition demands _ which included a quick deadline for
legal amendments to the Russian Constitution, and mandatory
parliamentary approval for appointments to the defense, foreign
affairs and internal affairs ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Gubenko said that on Sunday morning, the Communist Party leader
Gennady Zyuganov understood that these positions had been rejected.
When the party's leadership met later that day, it unanimously
rejected the agreement, he said. ``They refused to sign such an
emasculated agreement, once it was clear the president's side was
doing it just to get Chernomyrdin through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you sign an agreement when you don't see the makeup of
the government?'' asked Ilyukhin. ``Who are you signing with? The
fact is we don't trust Chernomyrdin, and the people don't trust
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
