<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-BROKERS-570&AMP;AD     08-31 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-BROKERS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET FACES END OF LONG RUN OF BIG PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-ASSESS, CREDIT, HONGKONG-MARKET,
MARKET-COMPARE, MARKET-VOICES, MARKET-CYBERSPACE) 
(lb) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street is starting to count the cost of the
recent turmoil in financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney, one of the United States' biggest
investment banks, said Monday that in the last two months alone it
lost an estimated $360 million after taxes, in its arbitrage and
Russian-related credits businesses. After allowing for profits from
its private client and funds management business, Salomon said that
it expected its overall after-tax loss for the last two months to
be about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Such losses may spell the end of a long run of bountiful profits
for Wall Street _ a time when stocks, financial markets and the
fortunes of financiers have risen inexorably. Another Wall Street
firm, Credit Suisse First Boston said last week that its first-half
profits would be down $250 million because of losses on its Russian
and Russian-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is having to adjust to the possibility of a sea
change in the financial markets. The recent gloom over the markets
has already spread to such areas as giving advice on big mergers
and acquisitions, and initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   And there already is speculation _ denied by the principals on
Monday _ that such high-profile planned transactions as Citibank's
$70 billion merger with Travelers Group Inc. _ the parent company
of Salomon Smith Barney _ may be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Arda Nazarian, a spokeswoman for Salomon, the investment-bank
subsidiary of Travelers Group Inc., said the merger, which would
create a company called Citigroup, was on track.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Howe, a Citicorp spokesman, said: ``We remain confident
that the Fed will grant to Citigroup bank holding-company status in
the third quarter. But only the Fed knows the exact timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many on Wall Street expect Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. to postpone its
planned multibillion dollar sale of a slice of its shares. A
spokesman for the firm said Monday that it would not comment on
such rumors, and that Goldman's plans remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the financial markets continue to deteriorate, there
may be profounder changes on Wall Street. Firms could start to
consider cutting back on expenses, and particularly on jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street typically takes such measures when it falls on
leaner times, as it did after the October 1987 stock-market crash,
during the bear market of 1990 and after the bond-market rout of
1994.
</P>
<P>
   If there are similar rounds of sweeping job cuts, that in turn
would have a significant effect on the economy of New York City,
which has come to rely heavily on its brokerage firms, banks and
insurance companies for tax revenues and well-paid jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement about its recent losses in arbitrage and
Russian-related credits, Salomon said Monday that they resulted
from the recent ``extreme volatility in the global fixed-income and
equity capital markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage firm estimated that for July and August it would
have $60 million of Russian-related credit losses, $120 million of
losses on its U.S. bond arbitrage portfolio and $180 million of
losses on its international arbitrage business.
</P>
<P>
   Profits from more successful areas, such as the firm's
private-client and fund-management businesses, have so far helped
to offset losses from arbitrage and Russia-related credits. Such
profits would have to total as much as $210 million in the last two
months to cut the overall loss in the period to $150 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the moment, several of Salomon's big competitors are keeping
mum. ``As a matter of policy we do not comment intra-quarter on
results,'' said Tim Gillis, a spokesman for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Jon
Diat, a spokesman for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said his firm
would have no comment on its results for July and August, or on
what effect recent falling financial markets may have had on its
performance.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday afternoon, Jamie Dimon and Deryck
Maughan, the co-chairmen of Salomon Smith Barney, were guarded
about measures they may take to try to improve profitability, and
would not say whether their firm plans to cut back its staff,
always one of the biggest expenses on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is: You don't cut people because of losses,'' said
Dimon. ``We have been probably reducing risk around the company for
a while. You pray for the best and you plan for the worst. You have
to know your risks and exposures.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimon was also quick to stress that ``the rest of Travelers is
doing great,'' and that Salomon's business with Main Street
Americans has ``not seen a dramatic decrease in retail volume.''
</P>
<P>
   But both Maughan and Dimon sounded cautious. ``You'd be foolish
not to worry,'' said Dimon. ``Beware the ides of August,'' said
Maughan, adding that in recent years August had stopped following
the financial folklore that it was a quiet month for the markets.
Dimon should know; he cut short his family vacation in the eastern
Mediterranean to return home to discuss the recent losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
