<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ already filed _ President Clinton,
flying to Moscow for two days of talks with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, warns that U.S. support of Russia is conditioned on a
continuation of economic and political reforms. Clinton arrives
Tuesday. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   YELTSIN-DECLINE (Paris) _ already filed _ By the time Boris
Yeltsin got to the top, he was no longer the man he had been on his
way there. Illness, drinking and lack of hard work have turned the
onetime national hero into a sad bumbler whose grip on affairs of
state seems to have all but vanished. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ Senate majority leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., pronouncing himself disgusted at President
Clinton's behavior with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky,
said he is uncertain whether the president has the strength to go
forward with his term. Lott, however, did not call for Clinton's
resignation. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
