<HEADLINE>
ABL STAR STALEY JUMPS TO WNBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dawn Staley, one of the core group of players who helped
organize the American Basketball League, says she is jumping to the
rival WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult decision, considering I was a founding
member of the ABL,'' said Staley, the scrappy 5-foot-6-inch guard
who got to play in her hometown last season when the Richmond Rage
moved to Philadelphia. ``At the same time, I had to look at women's
basketball as a business, like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   According to WNBA president Val Ackerman, Staley's contract is
for three years, but no decision has been reached on which team she
will join.
</P>
<P>
   Staley was a member of the 1996 gold-medal US Olympic team, and
her desire to play on the 2000 team apparently was a factor in her
decision; she feels the WNBA's shorter season _ 30 games to the
ABL's 44 _ will be easier on her troublesome knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it basically came down to is longevity,'' said the
28-year-old graduate of the University of Virginia. ``I want to
play basketball as long as I can. It didn't come down to any
financial reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Staley, an All-Star in both of her ABL seasons, denied that her
decision reflected a lack of confidence in the survival of the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ABL will be around for as long as there will be
players,'' she said Monday. ``I think they're doing a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   With Venus Lacy's recent decision to re-sign with the ABL, the
lone ABL marquee player yet to state her intentions is New England
Blizzard guard Jennifer Rizzotti. A decision by the former
University of Connecticut star is expected as early as today.
</P>
</TEXT>
