</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARLIAMENT REJECTS YELTSIN'S CHOICE FOR PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT, CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE, RUSSIA-SUMMIT,
RUSSIA-DEBATE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's parliament emphatically rejected President
Boris Yeltsin's choice for prime minister on Monday, leaving the
nation virtually rudderless in the midst of its deepening economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Chernomyrdin implored lawmakers to approve his
appointment as prime minister on Monday, saying that he urgently
needed to start forming a new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia today is, in essence, on the verge of economic and
political breakdown,'' Chernomyrdin declared. ``Russia should not
be without a government.''
</P>
<P>
   But the appeal drew jeers from the Communists-led opposition,
which turned back his nomination by a vote of 253 to 94.
Chernomyrdin needed 226 votes in the 450-seat parliament to be
approved.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists' strategy seemed to be discredit the Yeltsin
government in the hope that the embattled president would finally
be driven to resign or at least agree to a more generous
power-sharing arrangement. The lopsided rejection also seemed aimed
at torpedoing Chernomyrdin's claim that only he could unify the
splintered nation and serve as Yeltsin's heir.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, however, demonstrated on Monday night that he was also
ready to engage in political brinksmanship by renominating
Chernomyrdin as prime minister..
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yeltsin's advisers warned that the parliament would
be dissolved if it refused to yield, setting the stage for a new
round of horse-trading over government posts and policies in the
days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Boris Yeltsin wants Viktor Chernomyrdin to become
the prime minister, and I do not recall a case such as this where
he has changed his mind,'' said Boris Berezovksy, the tycoon who
has sought to orchestrate Chernomyrdin's return to power.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the eve of the summit meeting between Yeltsin and
President Clinton, the angry standoff left the United States
wondering if Clinton would be meeting with a determined, if
embattled Russian leadership or a government that was about to
implode.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's acrimony marked an abrupt end to days of lofty talk of
compromise and coalition government designed to secure a bloodless
confirmation of Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got all the consent,'' Chernomyrdin complained to reporters
after Monday's debate. ``And all of sudden everything is
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Communist lawmakers said on Monday that the negotiations broke
down over a deadline for enacting amendments to the constitution
that would shift some power from the executive branch to the
legislature, among other power-sharing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Shokhin, the leader of Chernomyrdin's parliamentary
faction, suggested that the acting prime minister might still be
able to mollify the Communist opposition and salvage his
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin suggested that Chernomyrdin might identify his cabinet
choices and spell out his economic policy before the next vote on
his nomination. The idea would be to reassure wary lawmakers that
the new prime minister would honor his promises to left-wing
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Market reformers warned that there was a danger that
Chernomyrdin might now go too far in trying to placate the
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Chubais, who was fired from his post as the Yeltsin
government's negotiator with the International Monetary Fund,
warned that the Kremlin would be making a grave mistake if it gave
away the Finance and Economics ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know a single economist from the left side of the
spectrum who is capable of proposing anything reasonable to resolve
the crisis,'' Chubais said.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's leading politicians traded insults during Monday's
debate, it was sometimes hard to recall that the nation was
grasping for ways to stem the decline of its currency, fight
inflation and save its banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Zhirninovky, the strident nationalist, mocked Clinton
for his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Sergei Dubinin, the head
of the Central Bank, defended a loan he received to build a country
home.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist leader, complained that
Chernomyrdin's approval rating stood at a meager 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin derided his predecessor, the 36-year-old Sergei
Kiriyenko for leading a ``kid's government'' and blamed him for the
nation's economic ills, even though most economists say Kiriyenko
was struggling to correct policies that were adopted during
Chernomyrdin's first term as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   When Chernomyrdin addressed the financial crisis, his economic
prescriptions were vague, halting and, at times, nearly incoherent.
</P>
<P>
   The acting prime minister said that the government should use
credits to boost Russia's stricken industrial sector but conceded
in the same breath that the government had no money.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Yeltsin government's decision to devalue the
ruble was a mistake, but gave no hint of how he planned to prop up
the nation's sagging currency.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not allow the banking system to collapse, but
gave no details about how he could prevent the bankruptcy of some
of the nation's leading banks.
</P>
<P>
   His dominant policy goal since being selected as prime minister
last week, he said, was simply to avoid a total financial collapse
before he formed a new government and tried to figure out what to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing was to hold until the end of August,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The circus-like atmosphere of Monday's debate came against the
background of grim economic news. Russia's stock market was so
depressed that there were only three transactions during its first
two hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
