<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-IRA-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA DENIES  2 LINK TO BOMBING IN NORTHERN IRELAND
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ The Irish Republican Army, which has observed
a cease-fire for 13 months, made a rare public statement Monday,
denying any connection to a bombing that killed 28 people two weeks
ago in Omagh, Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA also rejected demands that it disarm soon and declare an
end to its war against British sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The statements, made in an interview with an unidentified IRA
leader, appeared to be an attempt to improve the group's image and
to help its political wing, Sinn Fein, in the new Northern Ireland
Assembly. The Assembly reconvenes in two weeks to try to enact
provisions of the Northern Ireland peace settlement approved last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The statements also seemed timed to improve the image of the IRA
and Sinn Fein before President Clinton arrives in Ireland later
this week. Clinton helped further the Northern Ireland peace effort
by supporting Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials and analysts noted that the interview was
released four days before it would normally be published in An
Phoblacht, a Republican weekly with IRA contacts that is based in
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Paisley Jr., son of the hard-line Protestant leader and a
member of the Assembly, said the statements were ``designed to
perpetuate the myth that there are good and bad terrorists, that
the good terrorists are telling off the bad ones so we can all
sleep easily. It is a meaningless statement driven by a need to be
seen to be doing something hours before President Clinton touches
down in Northern Ireland.'
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein and its president, Gerry Adams, have been under
increasing pressure to persuade the IRA to state categorically that
the war is over.
</P>
<P>
   Most, but not all, of the pressure has come from Protestant
Unionist leaders who insist that Adams not be given a minister's
post in the Assembly unless the IRA declares its cease-fire to be
permanent. The interview statements were also an attempt by the IRA
to clear itself of charges that it helped a splinter group, called
the Real IRA, commit the bombing in Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   Such speculation led Unionists to insist that because the IRA
might have been involved in the Omagh attack, Adams, by
association, should be ejected from the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   If that happened, the IRA would be expected to resume its
violence and the five-year-old peace effort could collapse in a new
round of killing by Catholics, who want more power in the North and
closer ties with the Irish Republic, and Protestants, who want to
remain part of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The statements also included an IRA promise to disclose the
burial places of members it had executed in disciplinary actions.
The statement admitted that it had executed and buried ``a small
number of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview called for disbanding of the Real IRA, describing
it as a small group of renegades that had broken away from the main
IRA after it called a cease-fire. The cease-fire led to the peace
agreement that produced the new Assembly, which includes members
representing Sinn Fein, who are widely recognized as the IRA's
representatives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The splinter group received no materials for military
operations, the statement said. Rather, the dissent was a failed
effort to destabilize the IRA leadership, it added.
</P>
<P>
   On the demands that it state that the war is over, and that
disarmament should begin, the IRA leader said the organization
considered the peace agreement a ``significant development.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That remains our view. We made our position absolutely clear
on this in April,'' the leader said.
</P>
<P>
   The April statement said, ``Let us make it clear that there will
be no decommissioning by the IRA.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's interview the leader said people should be using
their energy to make the peace effort work and not ``wasting time
on word games around whether or not someone is prepared to say the
war is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
