<SLUG> BC-GRANNY-DEAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TEXAS GRANNY DIES AT AGE 110 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
(Attn: Ark., N.M.) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ She was born when the Indian Wars were still going on,
when the Texas Revolution was more recent than World War II is
today. She plowed with oxen when cotton, not oil, was king in East
Texas. She lived during exactly half of the United States'
presidential administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Now Aley Ivy Cheairs LaRue _ called Granny, Other Momma and Big
Granny by her very large family _ has died at 110. She passed away
quietly early Monday at her small home near the communities of Ash
and Austonio in Houston County.
</P>
<P>
   Austonio is about 100 miles north of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard that lady say a single bad thing about any other
person. She never smoked, chewed, drank or swore,'' said her
daughter-in-law Arlene LaRue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the hardest worker I ever saw. She was working right
up to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Although blind and almost totally deaf and bedridden for the
past couple of years, Granny LaRue was apparently working in her
mind, for she continued to shout out orders to her children and to
give directions for the plowing and other farm work that needed to
be done.
</P>
<P>
   It was work she knew only too well.
</P>
<P>
   She was born March 23, 1888, on a large farm operated by her
parents, John and Elizabeth Cheairs. Her grandparents had come to
Texas in 1832, when it was still part of Mexico. Her father grew
cotton on the rich land of the Trinity River bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The eldest of eight children, she attended a one-room school
through the third grade. Then, when she was only 11, her mother
died and she started helping raise her five sisters and two
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on the farm since I was 10 years old,'' LaRue told an
interviewer when she was a spry 98.
</P>
<P>
   She helped educate her younger siblings, too. Until a couple of
years ago, she'd still proudly illustrate how well she knew her
lessons by reciting the alphabet _ backward.
</P>
<P>
   She met Tom LaRue from Lovelady shortly before World War I. They
rode a horse-drawn buggy to nearby Porter Springs to get married.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't even get out of the buggy,'' Arlene LaRue said.
``The man who performed the marriage came out to the buggy and
married them right there.''
</P>
<P>
   They raised seven children. Virgil LaRue, the oldest, is 83 now.
He and Carl, Thomas Jr. and William LaRue live in the Ash and
Austonio area. Annie Scogin lives in Silver City, N.M. Jay LaRue
lives in Santa Fe, N.M. The youngest, John LaRue died three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Granny LaRue is also survived by 23 grandchildren, 38 great
grandchildren and at least 17 great-great grandchildren, Arlene
LaRue said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband traveled widely and moved to western Texas
in the 1930s and then to New Mexico and then to Arkansas, where he
died in 1958. After he died, she decided to move back to Houston
County to be near her family.
</P>
<P>
   Proud of her roses, she also always raised a large garden and
kept a flock of chickens. Even blindness in recent years didn't
keep her from her garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gardened by feel,'' Arlene LaRue said. ``She could tell a
weed from a plant by touch and she never pulled up a plant by
mistake and never missed a weed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fond of eating fresh tomatoes, cucumbers and green onions from
the garden with good corn bread, she didn't let having no teeth
slow her down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been part of this family for 50 years and I never did
know her to have any teeth,'' Arlene LaRue said. She didn't bother
to put in store-bought teeth, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was also not one to seek medical attention for trivial
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had some terrible falls, but it never seemed to hurt her
much,'' said Arlene LaRue. ``She came out of field of corn
nine-feet-high once and fell flat as a fritter, but she didn't
break any bones. She did break her arm once, but she wouldn't go to
the doctor for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warned that eating fatty foods was bad for her, she went on
eating the fatty pork she so loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't have a gall bladder operation until she was 88
years old,'' her daughter-in-law said.
</P>
<P>
   A woman of strong religious beliefs, she attended the Ash Church
of Christ even after dwindling hearing made it impossible for her
to hear the sermons. She often told her descendants that just going
to church wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That building won't save you,'' she'd say. ``You've got to be
a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   After she was confined to a wheelchair and then to bed, she
refused to go to a nursing home. Her son Carl sometimes relieved by
other siblings, would spend the nights with her. A sitter was there
in the daytime.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, her sons made sure there was a garden for her to
watch out of the window and to eat from. This year it had mustard
greens.
</P>
<P>
   Her birthday was always a major family event. Three years ago,
when the clad last gathered to celebrate it with her, 83 relatives
showed up for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Her funeral is scheduled Thursday at Callaway-Allee Funeral Home
in Crockett.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
