<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NKOREA-MISSILE-ART-50     08-31 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-MISSILE-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA MISSILE TEST RAISES TENSIONS IN ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related NKOREA-MISSILE-U.S.) 
(ART ADV: a map/graphic for use with this story is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a move that immediately raised tensions in the
region, North Korea fired a ballistic missile into the Sea of Japan
at around noon on Monday. The launch may have been a test, but
North Korea offered no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, part of the missile flew over northeast Japan
and landed in the Pacific Ocean. If that is confirmed, it will add
to the apprehension by underscoring the range of North Korea's new
class of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of damage, although fishing boats ply the
Sea and aircraft fly over the area on a regular basis, and it was
not clear whether the firing was part of a series or just a single
launch. The Japanese Defense Agency, which said it received its
information from the U.S. Forces in Japan, said that the ballistic
missile was fired from the eastern coast of North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts said it was possible that the launch was a
nationalistic display of force linked to the upcoming 50th
anniversary on Sept. 9 of the secretive, renegade Stalinist state.
Other North Korea specialists said that it could be a statement of
political defiance, as negotiations take place in New York between
representatives of North Korea and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean Defense Ministry said on Monday that it
believed the missile was probably a test firing of the Taepo
Dong-1, a newly developed missile system with an intermediate range
of 937 miles to as much as 1,875 miles. Other estimates pinpointed
the range at 1,250 miles.
</P>
<P>
   If the missile was a Taepo Dong-1, it is not clear whether the
firing was a success, for the missile did not travel its full
range.
</P>
<P>
   Other military experts say the missile could have been the
shorter range Nodong-1, a medium-range ballistic missile. Still, if
the test is considered successful, North Korea may have developed
the capability to target American military bases on Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real reason for the North Korean missile is its target,
which is Japan,'' said Toshiyuki Shikata, professor at Teikyo
University and a retired general in the Japanese Self Defense
Forces. And the reason for Japan, he added, is that the American
military bases are located here.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea already has tested its Nodong class of missiles.
They are believed to be able to reach a broad swath of Japan, but
not the Tokyo area or the many American bases in Okinawa.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The missile landed on Monday at 12:12 p.m., smack in the middle
of Sea of Japan, by some accounts into the Russian exclusive
economic zone, directly south of the Russian city of Vladivostok.
It hit the water about 240 miles from Noto Peninsula, the nearest
coast of Japan, or 430 miles northwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a very political meaning,'' said Masao Okonogi, a
politics professor and expert on the Korean peninsula at Keio
University. ``They are now demonstrating their military capability
in political terms.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's missile program has attracted special concern
because the country is also believed to have some nuclear weapons.
It is not clear, however, whether North Korea has the ability to
construct a nuclear weapon small enough so that it can be delivered
on one of its missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, North Korea is believed to have tons of chemical
weapons, which would be much easier to deliver with missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka called the test
``deplorable,'' and said the firing was an ``extremely dangerous
act.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadaaki Numata, spokesman for Japan's Foreign Ministry said:
``We are seriously concerned about this because the deployment of
missiles by North Korea does affect Japanese security and it also
affects peace and stability in Northeast Asia. It also is of
serious global concern, in terms of the proliferation of weapons of
mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some analysts argue that Monday's missile firing could
be a flashy commercial, an advertisement to the Middle East and
other countries looking to buy cheap weapons. North Korea has
always been highly secretive about its weapons program, and
analysts say it would have been loathe to reveal its military
capabilities to the world, which is precisely what such a test
does.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials have said that North Korea's weapon sales
have been declining in recent years, bringing in only $300 million
between 1990 and 1995, compared to $2.5 billion during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ballistic missiles are the only North Korean product which can
get foreign currency,'' said Kensuke Ebata, military analyst in
Tokyo for Jane's Defense Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Ebata said that North Korea would be taking a domestic risk in
testing the Taepo Dong-1 so close to Sept. 9, when North Korean
leader Kim Jong Il is expected to officially assume the presidency
of that country. Because the missile travelled a distance far
smaller than it was designed to reach, the test could be perceived
by some at home to have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it succeeded, it would be very good propaganda, raising
national solidarity,'' said Ebata. ``But if it failed, it could be
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Billy Birdwell, a spokesman for the U.S. Forces in
Japan, confirmed the firing and said that the Department of Defense
regarded the action as a ``serious development.'' He would not
comment, however, on what kind of missile was fired, on the flight
of the missile, or on whether there were any signs that there would
be more missiles fired.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea previously conducted missile test firing in May
1993, when it fired four missiles into the Sea of Japan. Those
launchings sent Japan into a panic and prompted the government to
consider cooperation on a regional Theater Missile Defense System.
Such a system is still years away, at best.
</P>
<P>
   That 1993 test firing is believed to have been a Rodong-1, a
shorter range ballistic missile system, which is based on a Scud
missile engine.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government was alerted about two weeks ago to North
Korea's missile launch preparations, according to a report a week
ago in the Sankei Shimbun, a major Japanese daily. The report said
that both Japanese and American forces stepped up surveillance of
the Sea of Japan and that the U.S. military had dispatched a
ballistic-missile surveillance aircraft to its Misawa base in
northern Japan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
