<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NKOREA-MISSILE-U.S.-N     08-31 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-MISSILE-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA TEST RAISES FEARS OF SPREAD OF BALLISTIC MISSILES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related NKOREA-MISSILE) 
(HLW) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ North Korea's test of a medium-range missile
capable of reaching targets in Japan and beyond represents a
technological breakthrough that has raised new fears of the spread
of ballistic missiles, administration officials and arms control
experts said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With North Korea's record of exporting missiles and related
technology to countries like Iran, Pakistan and Syria, the
officials and experts said, they worry that more advanced,
longer-range missiles are now within the reach of less developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is serious stuff,'' a Pentagon official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's test was the first of a two-stage missile the United
States calls the Taepo Dong-1. It can carry conventional or nuclear
warheads, and the Pentagon estimates its range as more than 900
miles, while the Central Intelligence Agency puts its range at
1,200 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, North Korea had only succeeded in testing a
single-stage missile, the Nodong. That missile has a range of 600
miles, but is considered a relatively unsophisticated version of
the Scud missile.
</P>
<P>
   The officials and arms experts said the test also suggested that
North Korea had made real progress in its effort to build a
longer-range missile, the Taepo Dong-2, which is reportedly capable
of traveling 2,400 to 3,600 miles. That would give North Korea the
ability to strike targets throughout Asia and as far away as
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Henry D. Sokolski, the executive director of the
Nonproliferation Policy Education Center, in Washington, said the
ability to build rockets in stages opened the door to
intercontinental missiles that at least in theory would have
virtually unlimited range.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can no longer be dismissed as some crude welding of Scud
technology,'' he said. ``We're entering a new era.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Milhollin, director of the Wisconsin Project on Nuclear
Arms Control, another research organization in Washington, said the
missile test was ``a clear sign'' of North Korea's intent to
develop nuclear weapons, despite its 1994 agreement with the United
States to stop in exchange for Western assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Milhollin said a two-stage missile was too costly to construct
simply for delivering conventional weapons. ``It means they plan to
put a nuclear warhead on it or export it to somebody who will,'' he
said. ``The missile makes no sense otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon confirmed that North Korea sent the missile
streaking over Japan, firing it from a military base on its
northeastern coast. The first stage of the missile fell into the
Sea of Japan, while the second stage splashed down in the Pacific
Ocean after crossing over Japan.
</P>
<P>
   A report the Pentagon released last year warned that testing of
the Taepo Dong-1 ``could begin at any time.'' And the Central
Intelligence Agency had been monitoring preparations for Monday's
launch for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was little surprise, there was considerable
confusion about North Korea's motives.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's test came as North Korea's diplomats met once again
with administration officials in New York. In meetings over the
past two weeks, the American delegation, led by Charles Kartman, a
deputy assistant secretary of state, has raised American concerns
about North Korea's missiles and missile exports. The test was
discussed on Monday, but American officials declined to say what
explanation, if any, the North Koreans gave.
</P>
<P>
   The test came only weeks after American intelligence agents
detected work on a secret underground facility that they suspect is
part of North Korea's effort to revive its nuclear weapons program.
Republicans in Congress, citing those reports, renewed their
objections to the administration's policy of providing aid to North
Korea in exchange for a halt in its nuclear ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority leader, Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi,
used Monday's test to criticize the administration's policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been told that, `Don't worry. Now that we're helping
them, the North Koreans have frozen their weapons, their nuclear
activities,''' he said. ``And then we find out that they perhaps
are doing this underground nuclear facility. Now they fire a
missile across Japan territory. This is not good at all. It's very
dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
