<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-KIA-AUCTION-580     08-31 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-KIA-AUCTION-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW BIDS FOR KIA REFLECT EXCESS CAPACITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The auction of two South Korean automakers has become
a difficult process because none of the initial bids met the
sellers' minimum price, a sign of the obstacles that lie ahead as
the global auto industry continues to consolidate, auto executives
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite robust auto sales in North America and Europe, most of
the world's 33 mass-production automakers are losing money. There
are enough surplus auto factories around the globe to supply the
entire U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   But as the setbacks in the auction of Kia Motors Corp. and its
affiliate, Asia Motors Co. Ltd., show, merging the remaining
automakers remains a difficult task. Asian automakers currently
have the greatest excess capacity, but their enormous debts have
made American and European automakers reluctant to acquire them,
combine operations and close unneeded factories.
</P>
<P>
   Kia and Asia Motors were put up for sale together this summer by
their creditor banks after becoming unable to make payments on
their many debts, which total an estimated $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But bids by Ford Motor Co., Daewoo, Hyundai and Samsung have
drawn little enthusiasm from the banks. All of the bids would have
required the banks to write off some of their loans, auto industry
officials who insisted on anonymity said Monday. Ford and Hyundai
also bid less per share for Asia Motors than the banks' minimum
price, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the auction is to be announced Tuesday morning in
Seoul, South Korea. Some industry officials predicted Monday that
because the bids were so low, the auction would be canceled and
another would be held in October.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent failure of the auction lessens the likelihood that
Kia or Asia Motors will close any factories soon, so the global car
market is likely to remain glutted, depressing prices and profits.
The difficulties with the auction also represent a setback for
South Korea's efforts to streamline its industrial sector, which
suffers from heavy debts and excessive staffs in many industries.
</P>
<P>
   Auto-industry deals actually taking place now are unlikely to
reduce global overcapacity. Chrysler Corp. is preparing to merge
later this year with Daimler-Benz AG, for example, but the two
automakers have almost completely different lineups of vehicles and
no plans to close factories.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Eaton, Chrysler's chairman and chief executive, said in
an interview Monday that the recent plunge in stock markets around
the globe is very unlikely to affect the planned merger, in which
shareholders of both companies will turn in their stock for shares
in the combined company, DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler shares had tumbled 13.5 percent last Thursday and have
fared poorly since then along with the rest of the stock market.
The stock fell Thursday on speculation that the Daimler merger
might not take place, because Russia's economic and political
troubles had caused the German stock market to plummet, dragging
down the value of Daimler shares.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. market has also been battered since then. Eaton
said Monday morning that there had been no discussion of
renegotiating the merger terms. The merger would be in trouble only
if the performance of the German and American stock markets
diverged dramatically and the share prices of Daimler and Chrysler
also diverged, he said, adding that he believed this was very
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the markets move relatively the same, I don't see
any impact,'' Eaton said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another recently announced auto-industry transaction also
appears unlikely to relieve the industry's excess capacity. Toyota
Motor Corp. announced on Friday that it would spend $262 million to
raise its stake in Daihatsu Motor Co. Ltd. to 51.2 percent. But
Toyota's previous stake of 34.5 percent had already given it
control of Daihatsu, which is strongest in the manufacture of very
small cars, one of Toyota's few weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Kia sale has attracted international attention because
American, European and Japanese automakers have worried that if a
buyer accepts the company with all of its debts, the purchaser
could be forced to dump large numbers of low-priced Kia cars on
international markets in an attempt, which might be futile, to keep
up with interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler did not bid on Kia, partly because it is still busy
with the Daimler merger and partly because Chrysler executives were
dubious about the profitability of East Asian markets even before
the region's financial crisis began. ``The only way Kia would be
attractive to anybody would be if you restructured or reduced the
debt,'' Eaton said Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
