<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-COX     08-31 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga to make case for appeal
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson and Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Judge Mills Lane, he's not. While Leonard Coleman is
officially the president of the National League, he'll assume his
periodic judicial role today, when baseball's reigning Hit Man,
Andres Galarraga, gets his day in court.
</P>
<P>
   In town for the Braves' series with Houston, Coleman will hear
Galarraga's appeal of the three-game suspension and $1,000 fine.
The penalty was imposed after the Braves first baseman charged the
mound on Aug. 22, when the Dodgers' Darren Dreifort hit him for the
second time in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga, who was ejected after just missing Dreifort with a
wild left hook before wrestling him to the ground, insists that he
deserves, ``no suspension'' and that Dreifort was throwing at him
purposely . He said that 23 HBPs _ the latest was Saturday in St.
Louis _ is ``too many (times) to be too nice, too patient.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they hit me when I strike out four times?'' asked
Galarraga, who leads the majors in being hit by pitches. ``They
only hit me when I hit a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, of course, draw a different composite sketch of the
culprit: a right-handed power hitter with an open stance who
strides in toward home plate, only exacerbating the way pitchers
must work him to survive. By pitching him inside, they prevent
Galarraga from extending his arms and hitting another homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andres Galarraga is a guy with an open stance who dives at the
ball,'' Bob Gibson, the Cardinals' Hall of Fame pitcher and
arguably the premier practitioner of pitching inside, told an ESPN
national TV audience Sunday night. ``If you're going to pitch
inside, you'd better have some giddy-up.''
</P>
<P>
   And how would Gibson work Galarraga if he was still playing
today? ``I'd pitch him inside,'' he said. ``I wouldn't worry about
throwing strikes; I'd just pitch him hard inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser still does. Hard, yet carefully. ``When he's
struggling, he's diving into the strike zone,'' the Giants' pitcher
told the San Diego Union-Tribune. ``When his swing is on, he's
transferring weight.''
</P>
<P>
   And having a splendid season. Galarraga's two home runs Sunday
in St. Louis give him 42 homers and 112 RBIs. All of that despite
the bruises up and down his left arm and hand that cause him to
wear protective padding and would make other men flinch. ``I don't
know how he does it, getting hit all the time,'' said Braves backup
catcher Eddie Perez, a fellow Venezuelan who lockers next to
Galarraga and is perhaps his closest friend on the club. ``If it
was me, I'd be thinking about it (getting hit) every time I'm up.
But he keeps doing it. I know he has to be thinking about it, but
he doesn't say very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 23 times Galarraga has been hit this year, 20 have come
by right-handed pitchers throwing inside. Only two have hit him
twice: Dreifort and Masato Yoshii of the Mets. Three lefties have
hit Galarraga: Phillies starter Matt Beech and relievers Jeff
Tabaka of Pittsburgh and Gabe White of Tampa Bay, the first of
three Devil Rays pitchers to hit Galarraga on successive days.
</P>
<P>
   After being hit four times in April, Galarraga had an HBP-free
May. But once Boston's Derek Lowe drilled him on June 8, the hits
just kept on coming. Six in June. Seven in July, including three in
a four-day period. August's carnage: Six HBPs, HPBs, entering
Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's has been hit four times this season in games in
which he's homered. Only twice has he been hit after homering in a
game: On June 30, White hit him in the seventh inning after
Galarraga had twice homered; on June 15, Yoshii hit Galarraga in
the third inning after he'd hit a two-run homer in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga is most likely to be hit by a right-handed starter in
the first or third innings (four times each this season) or by a
reliever in the seventh (five).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two ways to look at this thing,'' said Dick Balderson,
a Braves major-league scout who was in Colorado's front office
during Galarraga's five years with the Rockies. ``You've got to
pitch big guys in; you can't let him extend the bat. But today, you
have a lot of pitchers who have the idea to pitch inside but can't.
You've got a lot out there who have no clue, and they hit him. I
think that's the frustration you see with Galarraga. I think he's
very frustrated with getting hit all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez recalled that when Galarraga was with the Rockies, ``We
would go in on him, because that way he can't extend his arms. But
you have to be careful when you go in there, because when he's
looking for a pitch inside, he can hit that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga can't get out of the way of an inside fastball,
especially when striding in toward the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That definitely fits in,'' said Balderson said. ``If you're
standing on the mound, and Galarraga's standing at the plate, you
see a huge area to throw to. As you start to throw, he steps in and
there's not a lot of room to throw to. That area becomes cluttered
with Andres Galarraga body parts. In some areas, it (the suddenly
shrunken zone to pitch inside to) is four, five inches, not a foot
like it looks like. And if you're a young pitcher and you leave a
fastball up to him outside or over the plate, it's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   So you throw inside. Way inside. Even if you're not particularly
adept at doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot of guys who didn't pitch inside in high
school, college, in the minor leagues,'' Balderson said. ``I was a
minor-league pitcher. It takes some (guts) to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, pitchers know it's a must.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got pitching coaches, advance scouts, scouting reports
that all say you've got to pitch him up and in,'' Balderson said.
``If you don't, you're not going to be in the league long.''
</P>
<P>
   If Coleman denies Galarraga's appeal, he'll begin serving his
suspension immediately, missing the last two games of the Houston
series and Friday's game in New York against the Mets. Whatever
today's outcome, one HBP truth is indisputable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who gets hit, it hurts,'' said Balderson. ``It's as
simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
