</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCWEST01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The 'Big Easy' Saints likely to have a tough time in '98
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Amusement-park owners post prominent warnings that
caution patrons with heart-related problems not to ride some
rollercoasters. Given the condition of the New Orleans Saints,
owner Tom Benson might consider printing a similar notice on game
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Having done little to improve the NFL's worst offense of a year
ago and with significant defections from an aggressive defense that
led the league in sacks, New Orleans could spend the 1998 season in
a free-fall. And as the Saints plummet, blood pressures in The Big
Easy, most notably that of volatile coach Mike Ditka, could
skyrocket right through the Superdome roof.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hopeful forecasts from Ditka, this remains a team
that must be avoided by the faint-hearted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we're going back to last year,'' said Ditka,
referring to the Saints' 6-10 record and fourth-place finish in the
NFC West. ``We're better than that, I promise you.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was little indication during the preseason that New
Orleans is poised to make even modest improvement. Since the 1970
merger, the Saints have 10 last-place finishes, the second-most in
the league. They should battle the equally beleaguered St. Louis
Rams this year for the cellar spot in the division. By mid-season,
Ditka's promise of better times ahead could ring hollow.
</P>
<P>
   If 1997 was the Year of the Sack, with New Orleans sacking the
quarterback 59 times, this probably will be a season fans come to
the Superdome with the traditional brown paper bags over their
heads. Not even the scheming of underrated defensive coordinator
Zaven Yaralian, whose blitzes catapulted a modestly talented unit
to a No. 4 ranking in the league, can camouflage the shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Gone from that defense are ascending middle linebacker Winfred
Tubbs (free agent), cornerback Eric Allen (traded), strongside
linebacker Richard Harvey (released) and tackle Darren Mickell
(retired). End Joe Johnson could end his holdout this week but
probably won't be ready for extended playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent linebacker Andre Royal, slated to replace Harvey, was
traded to Indianapolis on Sunday, in part because of his role in an
ugly hazing scandal at training camp. That incident, now under
investigation by NFL security officials, apparently has some racial
overtones and could be a season-long disruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still getting comfortable with the new guys who are
starting . . . so, no, we can't be as solid yet as we were last
season,'' defensive tackle Wayne Martin said last week. ``There's
some work to be done and not much time left to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger problem, however, is offense. Ditka likes the
toughness of quarterback Billy Joe Hobert, but the sixth-year
veteran might not be able to start for any other team in the NFL.
There is no deep threat among the receivers, and tailback Lamar
Smith, the man expected to be the workhorse in an offense designed
to cut down on last year's 55 turnovers, has averaged only 71
carries in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line includes three first-rounders, and perennial
Pro Bowl tackle William Roaf seems to have rededicated himself
after a subpar '97.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints' sinners
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans Saints led the NFL with 55 turnovers in '97, the
eighth-most in league history. These seven players accounted for 50
turnovers:
</P>
<P>
   Player _ Int. _ Fum.
</P>
