<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-RETURN-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK FROM VACATION, GORE TRIES TO CONDUCT BUSINESS AS USUAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ohio)  (js) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Back on the campaign trail in Illinois and Ohio after
his two-week holiday in Hawaii, Vice President Al Gore turned to
his companions Monday morning on Air Force Two: ``Anything happen
while I was gone?''
</P>
<P>
   This was about as close as Gore came publicly to alluding to the
difficulties that are roiling the Clinton-Gore White House: Two
weeks ago, there was the president's admission that he had an
improper relationship with Monica Lewinsky and misled the American
people about it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week, Attorney General Janet Reno ordered a 90-day
preliminary inquiry into whether Gore lied to investigators last
year when he was interviewed about his telephone fund-raising
solicitations from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, as Clinton headed for Russia, Gore could not take
solace in embattled President Boris Yeltsin's choice of his friend
Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime minister. Chernomyrdin's nomination is
in grave trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But in his first interview since Clinton's disclosure about Ms.
Lewinsky, Gore made clear that his strategy would be to say as
little as possible about the tribulations that threaten to dog him
until the November election and beyond, to his own planned run for
the Democratic nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Clinton had assured him he did not have a
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, Gore told reporters aboard Air
Force Two: ``I've never talked about my private conversations with
the president _ and I'm not going to start now.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said he did not agree with Democrats who say
they fear the Lewinsky matter will be a major liability in the
elections this year. Asked if he felt beleaguered, he said, ``Not
at all. Not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's calculation seems to be to stand by his close friend, the
president, but not too close. For example, he acknowledged in the
interview that he did not join Clinton in recent days in calling
leading Democrats on Capitol Hill to reassure them that they would
endure the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore insisted that he was not distancing himself from the
president, and said White House aides ``didn't ask me to make a
bunch of calls'' because he was tied up making calls on
international issues such as Russia and the U.S. cruise missile
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the interview turned from ethical questions to Russia
did Gore appear comfortable, answering questions and displaying his
expertise on foreign policy. Though he did not call Democratic
leaders, he said he had a ``lengthy conversation'' with
Chernomyrdin while on vacation in Hawaii.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As if to defy those who say the administration is in trouble,
Gore set off on a full round of campaign events. He started the day
talking to school children at a town meeting in Dayton, Ohio, then
attended a fund-raising event for Mary Boyle, the Democratic Senate
nominee from Ohio. In Chicago, Gore was the headline speaker at a
convention of the Communication Workers of America, then he
dedicated an AIDS prevention and care center, and ended the day at
a fund-raising reception for the re-election of Sen. Carol
Moseley-Braun.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore said nothing about the developments that have
buffeted the administration, they were clearly on the minds of
those in the audience. At the event for Ms. Boyle in Dayton, the
vice president drew perhaps his most sustained applause of the day
when he showed his allegiance to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say this loudly and clearly: I am proud that Bill
Clinton's policies have made this country a better place,'' he
said. ``I'm proud to serve with President Bill Clinton in helping
to improve the lot of working families in America.''
</P>
<P>
   As if he were oblivious to his own party's problems, Gore turned
his fury on the Republicans, asserting, ``The Republican Party is
in such disarray that the right hand doesn't know what the far
right hand is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But some in the audience said they feared that Clinton's ethical
woes and the fund-raising questions threatened Gore's political
future. ``I feel for him both on the personal level and on the
political level,'' said Jan Rudd, a veteran community worker and
Democratic organizer in Dayton. ``Already, you can see that
Republicans across the country are using the Lewinsky issue against
Democrats. Are they going to use it against Gore? Yes. Big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Jackson, a teacher who attended the Boyle event, said Gore
may not be safe from the taint of the Lewinsky matter because
``there's always the term, `guilt by association,' but I'm more
concerned that Reno says there should be an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gore was reciting the Clinton administration's
accomplishments in education and the economy, Jackson jabbed his
thumb toward the vice president in the distance and said, ``Any
time you're in politics you're going to be remembered more for the
problems than the good. That's why he's harping on the good
today.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Ruvolo, a former chairman of the state's Democratic
Party, said the Lewinsky matter should be the least of Gore's
worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's running mate is the economy,'' he said, speaking of
2000, ``not Bill Clinton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
