u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-CYBERSPACE-515     08-31 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-CYBERSPACE-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CYBERSPACE, INVESTORS' EMOTIONS FLARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-ASSESS, HONGKONG-MARKET, CREDIT,
MARKET-COMPARE, MARKET-VOICES, MARKET-BROKERS, MARKET-POLICY,
MARKET-CLINTON, LATAM-ECON) 
(lb) 
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heavy Internet traffic slowed many online investment sites
Monday as panicked investors mobbed cyberspace, checking their
stock prices and then sticking around to commiserate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the bears are patting themselves on their backs now,
saying `We told you so!' But they don't really care, do they?''
said one investor on a Yahoo discussion forum called Follow the
Yellow Brick Road. ``I'm back to where I was sometime in the middle
of January. I'll go slit my wrists now.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of calm expressed amid market chaos by many of middle
America's typical mutual-fund investors was nowhere in evidence in
Internet forums and chat rooms, where participants tend to be
active investors and where emotion is never quite as tempered as it
is in other environments.
</P>
<P>
   On America Online, where chat-room convention dictates a cheery
demeanor, the tone Monday afternoon had turned decidedly somber.
Investors kept one another up to date on what was happening on
CNBC. (``Shoot the jerks on CNBC,'' one suggested. ``Nothing but
bears, one after another.'')
</P>
<P>
   A typical exchange went like this:
</P>
<P>
   ROWNAROWNA: ``Hiya Cohen _ how are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   CohenInvGr: ``Not good. Bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   ROWNAROWNA: ``We all are.''
</P>
<P>
   Fozziebare, another regular in the America Online investor
forums, complained, ``Can no longer afford my AOL subscription.''
</P>
<P>
   David Gardner, co-founder of The Motley Fool, one of the oldest
investment sites in cyberspace, said that among the most popular
discussion groups on the online investment Web site Monday was one
titled ``Living Below Your Means.'' Another was ``Communion of
Bears.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, what characterized that conversation is they had
to team up together because they were so marginalized,'' Gardner
said of regulars in the bear forum. ``Now they're just calling for
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, sympathy for the market losers did not run deep on
several popular message boards on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told you people for some time now Dell is going to the
dogs!'' FantomBoy wrote in a discussion group about Dell Computer.
``Dell lost all its recent gains, and you folks call Dell bullett
proof! BAWHAHAHAHAH.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell's stock, which had held out until Monday, suffered a 16
percent decline Monday. The rout for technology stocks was
particularly hard felt by online investors who had remained
optimistic among the warning signs in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this isn't a free fall for the markets, and Dell, then I
don't know what a free fall is,'' wrote Stock Bull, a previously
bullish investor. ``Wish I had a parachute on.''
</P>
<P>
   David Zgodzinski, who writes a biweekly column for the
SiliconInvestor Web site that is based on conversations in the
discussion groups said online investors had been harder hit because
they typically owned stocks in individual companies rather than in
mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the reaction is shock,'' Zgodzinski said. ``These
people are more enthusiastic and more tuned in, and they're feeling
the loss more personally. The man on the street hasn't had the
perception of how bad the drop has already been.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One participant in a SiliconInvestor forum called ``The Big
Kahuna'' drew on the immortal words of Star Trek's Dr. McCoy to
convey his feelings: ``They're dead Jim, they're all dead. Japan,
Russia, and now China and Hong Kong. ANY BUYERS OUT THERE??''
</P>
<P>
   A relatively new investor on a Yahoo discussion group wrote:
``Gotta love this investment language. I figured I'd need to learn
about Fibonacci sequences and 10-Ks. Instead, I end up with
catching falling knives and dead cat bounces.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was an occasional clearing of the cybergloom on
Monday as investors reassured one another that this was in fact a
buying opportunity, and that they were in it for the long haul. The
Motley Fool's ``post of the day'' was an impassioned exhortation
from a Dell investor to look on the bright side:
</P>
<P>
   ``Subject: Self Fulfilling Prophecy
</P>
<P>
   ``Author: rj610w
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respects to those on this board who are so far
above me that I can't see the light of the sun coming over their
heads, let me sound a note of concern. I am concerned that the
bottom doesn't have to fall out from under us less we beat
ourselves into believing it's coming and stampede in fear. Once the
panic starts, we will have no one to blame but ourselves. I think a
lot of our future is in our own hands and how it turns out is up to
us. A little more encouragement and a little less scare talk may
serve everyone better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1701 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAVISION-MOVES-LADN     08-31 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAVISION-MOVES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER REFOCUSING CAMERA-MAKER PANAVISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Billionaire financier Ronald Perelman, in his
first move since taking over movie-camera specialist Panavision
Inc. in June, has announced that he will become the chairman at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Scott, Panavision's chairman and chief executive
officer since 1988, agreed to retire Dec. 31. Perelman, who has a
fortune estimated at $6. billion, promoted longtime Panavision
executive John Farrand, the 53-year-old president and chief
operating officer, to the CEO slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strong team in place to lead Panavision,'' Perelman
said Monday in a statement announcing the changes. ``I have every
confidence in John's ability to lead this company.''
</P>
<P>
   The news helped Panavision become one of the few issues to post
a gain on the New York Stock Exchange, rising 3/8 to $17 9/16 with
5,900 shares traded. The stock had fallen 36 percent since hitting
an all-time high of $27.50 in early May, and it recently warned
that third-quarter results would be soft due to fewer big-budget
films and lower commercial production.
</P>
<P>
   In the three months since the takeover, Panavision's employee
base has remained fairly stable with 313 employees at its Los
Angeles-area headquarters and 1,200 worldwide. Perelman, who owns
72 percent of Panavision through Mafco Holdings, has pledged last
year to increase sales and to maintain the company's status as the
leading supplier of cameras for film and TV production.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said Monday's announcements reflect that
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   According to the shareholder proxy statement for approval of the
takeover, Scott's employment contract called for an annual salary
of $800,000 and provided he be paid that amount if he left
voluntarily before next June. The pact also included a provision
that Scott, 64, agree not to compete for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement said Scott will remain on the board and
act as a consultant. Additionally, Chief Financial Officer Jeffrey
Marcketta will leave at the end of September to pursue other
interests and his duties will be assumed by longtime Perelman
associate Joseph P. Page, who was given the posts of vice chairman
and chief administrative officer.
</P>
<P>
   Panavision reported two weeks ago that it had taken a $58.6
million charge for costs associated with the takeover as part of a
$56.6 million second-quarter loss. Revenues was up 22 percent to
$46 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1702 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-POLICY-NYT &LR;      08-31 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLOFF DAMPENS AIR OF PROSPERITY, PUTS PRESSURE ON FED TO CUT
RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-ASSESS, CREDIT, HONGKONG-MARKET
MARKET-COMPARE, MARKET-VOICES, MARKET-CYBERSPACE, MARKET-BROKERS,
MARKET-PROGRAM) 
(JT) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The sharp stock market selloff is likely to ripple
through policy and politics, putting more pressure on the Federal
Reserve to cut interest rates and threatening the air of prosperity
that has been the foundation of President Clinton's political
support, analysts and government officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the stock market crash in October 1987, the financial
system handled Monday's downturn without any major problems, and
the Clinton administration rushed Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
out with soothing words about the continued soundness of the
American economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, who was back in Washington after two weeks of vacation,
said he had spoken during the day with Clinton, who was flying to
Russia during the afternoon as the market dropped precipitously,
and to Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, who was on
vacation in California.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Federal Reserve, Lynn Fox, said the
central bank had no comment on the market's decline. But economists
said that every sharp drop in the market helped build a more
compelling case that the economy could slow substantially in coming
months and that a cut in interest rates would not only help avert a
deeper downturn at home but help restore confidence and calm in
badly battered markets and economies around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not be able to control the global wildfire, but by
cutting rates we might be able to contain it,'' said Sung Won Sohn,
an economist at the Norwest Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has until the last few weeks regarded inflation as the
main threat to the continuation of the nation's long economic
expansion, which has driven unemployment down to 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts still think the Fed will not cut rates unless
there is more compelling evidence that the domestic economy is
sinking or the market slide accelerates so much that it endangers
the stability of financial system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 Greenspan _ faced with a more sudden market meltdown _
pressed lenders to make sure they made credit available within the
financial system and then cut rates to keep the economy from
stalling.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly 11 years later the banking and financial systems are
much stronger than they were then, interest rates are already low
by many standards, securities exchanges are better able to handle
floods of orders, and government officials and analysts said they
saw no need for any immediate action to keep the markets
functioning smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   The market is different in another critical way, as well.
Compared with 1987, the stock market today is more broadly based,
with many more households having invested in retirement programs
and mutual funds. Compensation for many corporate executives is
directly or indirectly tied to stock market performance through
options, employee share-purchase programs and other means.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Sinai, an economist at Primark Decision Economics, said
that the proportion of household wealth coming from the stock
market was nearly 30 percent last month when the market was near
its peak, up from 18.3 percent at the end of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, economists said, many consumers who have felt
affluent and confident over the past few years as the market has
surged and therefore spent more money than they would have
otherwise might now rein themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   For the economy, that could mean slower growth. And any slowdown
from dampened consumer outlays would only compound the effects of a
downturn in exports caused by the turmoil that has already sent
much of Asia into recession and is now threatening to roll over
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   While relatively few economists are predicting a recession in
this country, even a sustained slowdown in growth could push
unemployment higher, call into question the optimistic projections
of big Federal budget surpluses in coming years and leave Clinton
without the bulwark of a rock-solid economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political implications are clearly related to how much
consumers tighten their wallets,'' said Robert Litan, the director
of economic studies at the Brookings Institution. ``If they do, and
GDP growth slows and unemployment grows, then the bloom has come
off the rose and that would affect his standing.''
</P>
<P>
   With most of the administration's economic team en route to
Russia and many of Clinton's political advisers traveling or on
vacation, there was almost no public reaction from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin, who made a fortune navigating Wall Street's ups and
downs as a partner at Goldman, Sachs before coming to Washington in
1993, restated Monday what has long been the administration's
approach to the markets: that in the long run they will reflect an
economy's underlying strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals of the United States economy are strong, due
in part to the sound policies we have been following, and the
prospects for growth with low inflation and low unemployment
continue to be strong,'' Rubin said. ``The key is to continue on
the right policy path, and particularly to maintain our fiscal
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin urged other countries caught up the crisis, especially
Japan, to take the difficult steps needed to restore their
strength. And he again urged Congress to provide an additional $18
billion for the International Monetary Fund, which is running short
of money just as the crisis threatens to spread to Latin America
and other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is particularly important that Japan, the second largest
economy in the world, move ahead with actions to put its economy
back on track so it can be a source of strength in Asia and around
the world,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin is scheduled to meet on Friday in San Francisco with his
Japanese counterpart, Kiichi Miyazawa. Finance ministers from nine
Latin American countries will meet with IMF and U.S. officials in
Washington on Thursday and Friday to discuss what they can do to
avoid the economic fate that has befallen Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said officials from the Treasury and the Federal Reserve
were in contact throughout the day with their counterparts in the
other big industrial countries, as well as financial market
regulators in the United States including the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is currently working its way through a difficult
period,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our consultations indicate that the payment and settlement
systems and other market mechanisms are working effectively,''
Rubin said. He said the only problem had been at the Chicago Board
Options Exchange, and that it had been taken care of. He provided
no details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
