<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-IMPACT-COX     08-31 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-IMPACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts to retirement-planners: Keep your money where it is _
for now
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wrenching plunges in the stock market give individual investors
the heebie-jeebies, especially Americans who are putting a portion
of their current income into 401(k)s and other retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   They get the news about how much value their stocks or mutual
funds lost in just one day. A lot of people then wonder whether
it's time to get out _ accepting today's pain in hopes of avoiding
even more pain tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Not a good idea, professional money managers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're telling clients that they have a strategy, and that this
(their stock holdings) is long-term money,'' said Michael J. Smith,
a certified financial planner in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless their situation has changed, there's no reason to
change that strategy. Sit tight. Just continue to put your
contributions into your 401(k),'' Smith added. ``Ultimately, the
market will come back. It always has.''
</P>
<P>
   The 401(k) has been a hugely popular investment vehicle. One
reason is that income taxes are deferred on the money that workers
divert into a 401(k). Another is that more people have realized
they must take increasing personal responsibility for paying for a
prosperous retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the value of 401(k) assets leaped by $125 billion,
according to Cerulli Associates, a Boston-based research firm. A
portion of that growth resulted from rising share prices, but much
of it was from new contributions.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, the plans now hold $1 trillion worth of
retirement hopes. Cerulli estimates that number will continue to
grow by 13 percent to 15 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
   But will individuals flee after Monday's market fall? Recent
performance suggests only a small percentage will run.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dow plunged 554 points on Oct. 27, 1997, transfers
among 401(k) assets _ mainly away from stocks and into fixed-income
investments _ were four times the normal level. But even then, less
than 1 percent of investors actually moved money. The numbers were
provided by Hewitt Associates, a management consulting company that
is developing a daily index of 401(k) switching.
</P>
<P>
   In the current plunge, stockbrokers have reported business as
usual. ``Our clients are concerned, but they're not nervous,'' Lee
Jenkins, a stock broker with Raymond James, said. ``We've had such
phenomenal returns for the last few years that we've been preparing
our clients, telling them that things will return to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a certified financial planner with Financial Vision
Associates, said he heard from only a small percentage of his
clients Monday. ``Mostly they're concerned,'' he reported. ``We
reassure them, and they say, 'That's what I needed to hear.' ``
</P>
<P>
   None pulled money out of stocks, Smith added. He pointed to a
silver lining for those who continue putting retirement money into
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's buying more shares now, because prices have come down
considerably,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
