<HEADER>
A1704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      08-31 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BOASTS ABOUT ECONOMIC INDICATORS, REFRAINS FROM COMMENTING
ON MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-ASSESS, CREDIT, HONGKONG-MARKET
MARKET-COMPARE, MARKET-VOICES, MARKET-CYBERSPACE, MARKET-BROKERS) 
(JT) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He had good reasons to go to Russia, President
Clinton told a friendly audience in an elementary school gymnasium
in Virginia shortly before noon Monday. ``We have learned the hard
way,'' he said, ``that problems that develop beyond our borders
sooner or later find their way to our doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner, it turned out, rather than later. Less than three hours
after he left the gymnasium, the president was out of the country,
high over the Atlantic, when he received word from the White House
that his staunch political ally, the stock market, had gone south.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in a smaller and smaller world,'' Clinton had
said in Virginia, sounding a cherished theme about the economy that
might apply as well to how the political walls seem suddenly to be
closing in on him.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the market's drop was forwarded to the president. Later,
Clinton spoke by telephone with the treasury secretary, Robert
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   It has long been an inside joke at the White House that the
famously overstating president has been forbidden by his
understated treasury secretary to boast about the astonishing
performance of the stock market in recent years. Every now and then
_ as he did in meeting with a workers in Palo Alto on May 1 __ he
has let slip the observation that ``the stock market has gone from
3,200 to 9,000 since I've been president and there's no precedent
for that in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday in Virginia, as he usually does, Clinton confined himself
to boasting about other economic indicators. ``We've benefited a
lot from this global economy of ours,'' he said. ``We have over 16
million new jobs in the last six years, and we're about to have our
first balanced budget surplus in 29 years.''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton and many of his senior economic advisers up in the
air, it fell to Rubin Monday to provide the administration's calm
reaction to the steep drop, after consulting with the president.
``The world is currently working its way through a difficult
period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster, said he saw no such direct
connection between stock market conditions and presidential
popularity. ``Historically, there is very little relationship
between stock market gyrations on the one hand and people's
evaluations of the economy on the other,'' he said. They pay more
attention, he said, to matters like unemployment, inflation and
incomes, all of which are still reassuring.''
</P>
<P>
   But Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster, said: ``The weakness of
the stock market will soon be tied into attitudes toward him. He
will shoulder some of the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said that, in a survey he conducted last week, 54 percent
of likely voters this November said that they owned stocks or
mutual funds of some kind. He said that the poll had a margin of
error of plus of minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cook, an independent political analyst who is a close
observer of Congress, said he could not predict what effect the
drop in the market would have. But he said that, combined with the
possibility of more damaging information emerging from the inquiry
into Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, the stock market
performance did not bode well for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely certain a week ago that Clinton was going to
survive this thing, and that the impact on the elections wasn't
going to be that great,'' he said. ``And now I'm like totally
shaken.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
