</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPORTATION SECRETARY ASKS TO MEET WITH NORTHWEST AND STRIKING
PILOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ At the request of President Clinton,
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater on Monday asked officials of
Northwest Airlines and its striking pilots union to meet with him
in Washington on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has the power to order the pilots back to work for a
60-day cooling-off period, but the chief federal mediator, who is
responsible for recommending such action, said she did not think
such an order would be a good idea now.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Northwest canceled all its flights on Wednesday and
some international flights on Thursday as the strike by its 6,173
pilots went into its third day with no movement by either side.
</P>
<P>
   No negotiations were scheduled, as both sides stuck to their
final stances before the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on both sides to ``redouble their efforts to
resolve their differences,'' but said, ``it is up to the
negotiating parties to reach an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwest said its chief executive, John Dasburg, planned to
meet with Slater. A spokesman for the union, the Air Line Pilots
Association, said the union's president, J. Randolph Babbitt, also
would attend.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department emphasized that the meeting was
not a resumption of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary has called Babbitt and Dasburg to meet with him
to explain why the negotiations are not going on right now when
both sides have said they want to talk,'' said an official who
insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Slater, who met on Monday with Erskine Bowles, the White House
chief of staff, is being careful not to press the two sides too
hard to return to the table because Magdalena Jacobsen, the federal
mediator who has been supervising the talks, believes that further
negotiations when neither side is willing to compromise would be
counterproductive, and might even prolong a strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the point of pulling people together if there is
nothing to talk about?'' Ms. Jacobsen, who is chairwoman of the
National Mediation Board, a federal agency that oversees labor
matters in the airline and rail industries, said in an interview on
Monday. A meeting now could relieve some of the pressure on both
sides without advancing the negotiations, she said, and it could
also anger workers at the airline by raising false hopes of a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, criticized
Clinton on Monday for not intervening, saying that the strike had
already caused serious economic damage. The president has the power
to order the pilots back to work while an emergency board tries to
resolve the strike. Clinton used that power last year, when pilots
walked out at American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Jacobsen, who is responsible for making the
recommendation of intervention to the White House, said she did not
think it was a good idea now because the pilots could simply reject
the emergency board's proposal and walk out again in two months, on
the eve of the Thanksgiving holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are interested in is a resolution that translates into
a contract,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest said on Monday that as the strike continues it would
cancel flights 48 hours in advance. The carrier is still hoping
that the White House will order the pilots back to work before the
busy Labor Day weekend, so it does not want to cancel flights too
far ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   Disruption from the strike, which was anticipated for more than
a month before the pilots walked out early Saturday, was lighter
than expected over the weekend, but it became more serious on
Monday as business travelers faced their first day without the
airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing a much bigger challenge rebooking our
passengers,'' a Northwest spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, which is the country's fourth largest carrier,
reiterated its negotiating stance in a teleconference with Wall
Street analysts on Monday. It said that it was willing to pay its
pilots as much as their counterparts at Northwest's three larger
competitors _ United Airlines, American Airlines and Delta Airlines
_ but that the pilots' demand for an ``industry-leading'' contract
would cost too much and would compel Northwest to give equally
generous increases to five other unions that are negotiating
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest is offering a 9 percent raise over four years, a lump
sum of $57 million, the reduction of a two-tier pay scale to three
years from five years, and profit-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots say the package will still pay them less than what
pilots receive at the other airlines. They want a 15.5 percent pay
increase over three years, a lump sum of $86 million, elimination
of the two-tier wage structure and greater job security
</P>
<P>
   The pilots say the difference between the two sides amounts to
$70 million a year, but the airline told analysts that it believed
the number was closer to $170 million
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
