<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADER'S LOSS IN PANAMA CLOUDS FUTURE OF CANAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Politics here have been thrown into a
free-for-all after Panamanians crushed President Ernesto Perez
Balladares' hopes for a second term by a resounding margin of
nearly 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Voters defeated a proposal that would have amended the
constitution to allow him to serve five more years and thereby
control the Panama Canal when the United States relinquishes the
waterway at the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   According to complete unofficial results tabulated early on
Monday, 64 percent of the 1.1 million voters on Sunday rejected the
change. The defeat was larger than any poll had predicted. Perez
Balladares, once a member of the inner circle of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, said he regretted the results and promised ``a
pure and honest election'' on May 2.
</P>
<P>
   With the incumbent out of the picture, a scramble for nomination
of the ruling party is certain, and a larger number of opposition
leaders may also be tempted to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new scenario and and new political reality,'' said Jose
Blandon, a former confidant of Noriega who is a political
commentator on television. ``That will require a change of
strategy'' for the ruling Democratic Revolutionary Party and the
eight main opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   Noriega, the former dictator who was convicted in 1992 on eight
counts of drug trafficking, racketeering and money laundering, is
serving a 40-year federal sentence in the United States. He is
appealing the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The election in May is important to Washington because the new
government is to take possession of the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Perez Balladares has already appointed most of the board that
will run the waterway. But important decisions remain to be made on
expanding the canal and using real estate, worth more than $3.5
billion, that the United States is handing over.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling party most of the alternatives to Perez Balladares
are from the American point of view unappetizing.
</P>
<P>
   The party president and the majority leader in the legislature,
Gerardo Gonzalez, is virulently anti-American. His son was
acquitted last year on charges of murdering an American soldier
here after a trial that the U.S. Embassy characterized as unfair,
in part because of the father's interference.
</P>
<P>
   Two other possibilities mentioned frequently on Monday are
Housing Minister Francisco Sanchez Cardenas and Labor Minister
Mitchell Doens. But the United States has recently barred both men
from receiving visas, American officials said, because of their
activities under the Noriega dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, however, appears just as divided as it was in
1994, when their failure to unite behind a single candidate allowed
Perez Balladares to squeak through to victory with barely one-third
of the vote. Despite pleas for unity on Monday by Mireya Moscoso de
Gruber, leader of the Partido Arnulfista and apparently the
front-runner for the opposition, six other possible candidacies
were discussed on radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian political analysts said Perez Balladares' crushing
defeat would make it more difficult for the United States and
Panama to reach an agreement permitting American troops to remain
here after the canal transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of many in his party, the president
announced an accord nine months ago that would have allowed 2,000
American soldiers to stay on as part of a regional antinarcotics
center.
</P>
<P>
   But he almost immediately reversed himself.
</P>
<P>
   American officials were furious at what they saw as a breach of
promise, and negotiations have stagnated, in part because of
uncertainty about the political outlook. The Americans retain some
interest in the troop proposal, but Perez Balladares may be
hampered by his status as a lame duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the marked diminution of influence that comes with this
resounding defeat, it is going to be extremely difficult for him to
resuscitate the drug-center proposal,'' Ricardo Arias Calderon, a
leader of the opposition Christian Democratic Party and a former
vice president, said. ``If he had won he would have tried. But not
in this environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
