</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK MARKET PLUNGE LIKELY TO SLOW FURTHER MERGERS, ANALYSTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-ASSESS, HONGKONG-MARKET, CREDIT,
MARKET-COMPARE, MARKET-VOICES, MARKET-CYBERSPACE, MARKET-BROKERS,
MARKET-POLICY, MARKET-CLINTON, LATAM-ECON) 
(sw) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The recent volatility in stock prices is likely to
slow this year's flurry of mergers and acquisitions, analysts said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers say that many executives have put plans for deals on
hold until they understand what long-term impact the correction
will have on their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In situations where companies are considering deals, they now
have a wait-and-see attitude,'' said Scott Lindsay, co-head of
mergers and acquisitions at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``But I
don't see where anyone is slitting their wrists.''
</P>
<P>
   Most executives today, unlike those during the crash of October
1987, are not troubled by the economy here at home. ``There is not
the same doom and gloom,'' said Gregg Polle, co-head of mergers and
acquisitions at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Instead companies with exposure to Asia and Russia _ like
financial institutions _ or those that are heavily dependent on
exports for earnings, are perceived to be at the most risk in the
near future and a risky partner for a potential merger.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, merger activity among high-technology companies
could fall off sharply as a direct result of the market decline.
Internet stock prices, in particular, were in a free fall on
Monday, making it difficult for bankers and executives alike to
figure out what price an acquired company should command.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a chilling effect,'' said Gene Sykes, co-head
of the high-technology group at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``Some deals
won't get done for two weeks, maybe a month. No one really knows.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Wall Street watchers are cautious about the future,
there is little concern that deals already struck this year will
unravel. A market downturn itself is not enough to halt a
transaction, especially in stock-for-stock deals where the prices
of both company's stock have fallen in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   The real deal-killers will be companies that either miss
earnings or run into trouble abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the market has been rife the last two weeks with rumors
about what deal will be the next to be scrapped or renegotiated,
like the recent renegotiation of the merger between Tellabs and
Ciena. Early last week, for instance, rumors cropped up that the
Travelers Group and Citicorp merger was being renegotiated,
something company executives said was untrue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no truth to the rumors of any renegotiation of the
terms of the Travelers Group and Citicorp merger,'' said John
Morris, a spokesman for Citicorp. ``The only thing we are waiting
on is Federal Reserve approval.''
</P>
<P>
   And several companies have publicly reaffirmed their commitment
to a merger despite the tumultuous market. For example, executives
of the General Re Corp. said on Monday that they expected their
merger with Berkshire Hathaway Inc. to proceed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2103EDT &QL; 
