<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-COMPARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPARING MARKET DROPS, THEN AND NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related: MARKET, MARKET-ASSESS, HONGKONG-MARKET, CREDIT,
MARKET-VOICES, MARKET-CYBERSPACE, MARKET-BROKERS, MARKET-POLICY,
MARKET-CLINTON, LATAM-ECON) 
(ART ADV: a graphic comparing market drops is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the stock market, the sky is falling _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices are plunging, gurus are opining, and rattled
investors are biting their nails. Just as they did after similar
Mondays in October 1997, July 1996 and, yes, October 1987, the day
that Wall Street still calls Black Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When the bottom finally fell out of the stock market on Oct. 19,
1987, though, more than one fifth of the market's value was wiped
out in a single day. This year, by contrast, most of the major
market indexes _ including the Dow Jones industrial average of 30
blue-chip stocks _ have not yet lost that much from their peaks in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, investors can only hope that this Monday is another
case of deja vu _ because that would mean the worst is over. After
all of those historic blue Mondays, the stock market recovered, in
some cases very quickly. In 1996 and 1997, stocks regained their
previous peaks within a matter of months.
</P>
<P>
   It took almost two years for investors to recover their losses
from the Crash of 1987, but recover they did _ and then some. Hard
as it may be to remember, back then the Dow Jones industrial
average fell to 1,738; even after Monday's carnage, the Dow still
stood at 7,539 _ a 333 percent gain from the bottom nearly 11 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, that is over a period of more than a decade, which is far
longer than a lot of Americans have been investing. At the end of
1986, for example, fewer than 30 million shareholders had
mutual-fund accounts; today, there are more than 135 million mutual
fund accounts, according to the fund industry's trade group, the
Investment Company Institute.
</P>
<P>
   For those who missed the ugliness at the end of the 1980s, here
are some of the similarities _ and the differences _ between those
bad old days and today.
</P>
<P>
   SIZE: Monday's decline, though bigger than 1987's one-day drop
in terms of points on the Dow, pales on a percentage basis. Back
then, a 508 point drop was a sickening 22.6 percent plunge; the
recent 513 point fall amounts to only 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SPEED: Though many investors remember only the awful excitement
of that October Monday now more than a decade in the past, in fact
the market had started to fall apart long before the final plunge.
Back in 1987, the market peaked in August, and took two months to
fall 36 percent. This year, the market peaked in July, and took six
weeks to fall 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BREADTH: This is Wall Street jargon for how strong the market
is, based on the number of stocks that are rising versus the number
that are falling.
</P>
<P>
   When breadth is good, the generals and the troops are all
marching in the same direction, said James B. Stack of Investech, a
newsletter and research firm in Whitefish, Mont. When breadth is
bad, the generals are still marching forward, but the troops are in
retreat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
