<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACT UNCERTAINTIES HAVEN'T DISTRACTED WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All but one of the cubicles in the Yankees' clubhouse
are identical: about 4 feet deep; a bar across the top from which
to hang jerseys and workout gear and street clothes; several other
drawers and shelves for gloves and shoes and personal items, and a
chair in front.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams occupies the only aberrant cubicle. Built into a
corner, it is large enough for Williams, the Yankees' center
fielder, to draw his chair inside completely, and he often does
this, turning his back to the world as he plays his guitar
peacefully, in baseball pants, sleeveless royal blue T-shirt and
oval sunglasses with neon blue lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' whole season has been self-contained. He said in
spring training that he did not want to discuss his impending free
agency during the year, and he has not. He insisted he would not
negotiate while he played, and he has not. He has been adamant that
the possibility of his departure should not become a distraction
from the team's goal of winning the World Series, and it has not.
</P>
<P>
   He is just playing, and playing well. The Yankees have the best
record in the major leagues at 98-37, and Williams leads the
American League in batting average (.340) and on-base percentage
(.425) and ranks ninth in slugging percentage. He is also well on
his way to 100 runs batted in, driving in 81 so far, despite
missing more than a month with a sprained knee. Like the Mets' Mike
Piazza, Williams can sign with any team after this season, and
several clubs are expected to pursue him, including Arizona, Texas
and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Piazza, Williams chose not to engage in contract
discussions after spring training began. Piazza rejected an $84
million offer from the Los Angeles Dodgers early in the season, was
traded twice and has been the subject of many whispers. There has
been rampant speculation about where he may go, whether he is happy
with the New York Mets, whether his teammates like him. Piazza did
finally stop discussing his future, but by then fans were treating
him like an ungrateful mercenary.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, Williams plays his guitar and plays baseball. His
handling of his impending free agency, Yankees General Manager
Brian Cashman said Sunday, should be ``a case study.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been terrific,'' Cashman said. ``He's handled this the
way he handles everything _ with class. He hasn't let this become a
distraction to his teammates, to his club, to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months from now, Cashman and other Yankees officials will
determine what they believe Williams is worth. There exists a
strong possibility that the Yankees will not be willing to pay what
other teams might offer _ a six- or seven-year contract worth more
than $10 million a year. Cashman may call Williams' agent with word
that the Yankees' relationship with Williams is over.
</P>
<P>
   But those discussions will not take place until after the
season; Williams made that clear to Cashman in a February meeting.
``Bernie's concentrated solely on baseball,'' Cashman said, ``and
he's helped put this team in a position to win. This was the best
possible way to handle a delicate situation, and you've really got
to tip your hat to Bernie.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Postponing contract discussions, Williams said, ``has worked out
pretty well, because with the type of year we've been having, it
wouldn't make sense to talk about my contract.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the season starts, it's time to play baseball,'' he said.
``You've got to try to take care of things off the field in the
off-season, and if they aren't taken care of, then you try to play
through the season and put yourself in a good bargaining position
at the end of the next season. I strongly believe the season is not
the time to talk about your contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams believes that negotiating and talking about his
contract during the season would have bothered him. ``It just puts
unnecessary pressure on the things I'm trying to do,'' he said.
``If I'm trying to play to prove I'm worth whatever we're
negotiating for, that just takes the fun out of playing. It takes
the enjoyment out of it, and it's not a good situation. Nothing
would ever be good enough. You're always trying to drive in runs,
but it would be for the wrong reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has grown accustomed to the reality that baseball teams
operate as businesses. Players come and players go. But Williams
wants stability, for himself and his family. ``It's driving my
family crazy, not knowing where they're going to be,'' he said.
``It's been going on for six years. I've been fortunate enough to
play consistently enough to stay here. But year to year, we don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Yankees never leave, like Don Mattingly. ``He was a
guy who played here for like 13 or 14 years,'' said Williams,
before referring to his teammates Tino Martinez, Paul O'Neill and
Derek Jeter. ``Maybe Tino will have that, O'Neill will have that,
maybe Jeter, if they're smart enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I realize that unless something extraordinary happens _
and it wouldn't happen until after the year is over _ then
everybody's going to be forced to make some decisions. I wish it
could've worked out some other way, earlier on. That's part of the
game, though, and you have to live with that and try to make the
best of it. I'm looking forward to getting it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, musing about the way in which Williams has carried
himself this year, said, ``He just hasn't let his situation become
a distraction, in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez paused, before offering a sentiment that pervades the
thinking of many in pinstripes. ``Of course we want him back,'' he
said. ``Maybe the best way to make sure that happens is to win the
World Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
