<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-AD-COLUMN-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: VIAGRA APPEARS IN ADS FOR OTHER PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Madison Avenue is answering in the affirmative when
asked ``Am I blue?'' _ not a reference to Wall Street but to a
certain little pill.
</P>
<P>
   That pill is of course Viagra, the hugely popular drug from
Pfizer Inc. that treats male impotence. On the market only since
April, Viagra has already made a place for itself in the national
vocabulary faster than you can say ``Kinsey Report,'' ``Rubik's
cube,'' ``macarena'' or ``Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Viagra's ability to quickly become such a looming presence on
the cultural landscape has intrigued marketers and agencies, which
are always seeking ways to garner attention for what might
otherwise be prosaic advertisements. And because the upper echelons
of Madison Avenue are so dominated by older men, it's not
surprising that Viagra would be a subject near to their, er,
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Viagra is starting to play a cameo role _ usually
humorous _ in campaigns for goods and services that have nothing to
do with its intended purpose, despite some difficulties that
threaten to limit the scope and effectiveness of such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first job is to get the advertising noticed,'' said Paul
Cappelli, president at the Ad Store, a creative agency in New York.
``So topical matters are something we as advertising people should
jump on.''
</P>
<P>
   Viagramania _ the ability to see green where others see blue _
has been fueled in no small part by the intrinsic link between the
drug and what Joel McCrea in ``The Palm Beach Story'' labels
``Topic A.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidency became associated with sex in January, and
Viagra came after that,'' said Lawrence Brown, president at
Lawrence Brown Inc. in Bridgehampton, who invoked the drug in a
recent newspaper ad promoting his agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest in Viagra has been so intense because it reminds
people sex is important,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's ad, which carried the headline ``Announcing Viagra for
Business'' and promised ``no nasty side effects,'' is among several
in a growing category of variegated pitches inspired by Viagra.
Some use or allude to the drug's name; others show a blue pill, a
white pill bottle or similar imagery.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a newspaper ad for the Swatch Metrica watch sold
by Swatch Group, with a watchband that doubles as a ruler, showed
the product next to a blue pill and the words ``Size does matter.''
(In also borrowing the theme of the film ``Godzilla,'' the Swatch
ad represents a pop-culture ``twofer.'')
</P>
<P>
   American Quantum Motorcycles ran an ad depicting one of its
products above the headline ``For the 65 million men who don't need
Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to sell its motorbikes primarily to ``people
between 40 and 60,'' said Michael Jeary, president and chief
operating officer at the American Quantum agency Della Femina/Jeary
&AMP; Partners in New York, which is owned by top executives and
Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was tapping into what's happening in the marketplace with
a twist to make it more salient, more relevant,'' he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And two magazines are ``co-branding'' with Viagra in ads that
are part of new trade campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Wired, owned by the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance
Publications, is running a series of two-page ads comparing itself
with traditional business publications. One ad in the campaign, by
Black Rocket in San Francisco, shows on the left-hand page, perched
atop a pile of Forbes and Fortune magazines, four Viagra pills and
a shot glass filled with Scotch on the rocks. The headline: ``Old
CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   On the right-hand page, atop a pile of Wired magazines, is a
handful of M&AMP;Ms and a glass of amber beer. The headline: ``New
CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   The jab is meant to be playful, said Dana Lyon, Wired publisher
in San Francisco, who called the ad ``a way to look at the lighter
side of a competitive advantage Wired has'' in terms of ``a younger
median age'' for its readers.
</P>
<P>
   And Playboy magazine, owned by Playboy Enterprises, is featuring
Viagra in one of several ads by Kovel Kresser &AMP; Partners in Venice,
Calif., which carry the theme ``Life, liberty and the pursuit of
dreams.'' In the ad, the words ``The revolution isn't over, it's
just begun'' are superimposed over a photograph of a pill bottle,
the letters ``Viag'' visible, tucked inside the back pocket of a
pair of blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viagra has opened the door for sexual conversations among
many, many people,'' said Richard Kinsler, executive vice president
and publisher in New York. ``And not to brag, but people look at
Playboy as an authority on sex.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem that may halt or reverse the trend is taste _ or
specifically the lack thereof in many Viagra ads, which make
salacious, smutty or licentious assertions. For example, a trade ad
for FHM, a British magazine for younger men published by Emap
Metro, shows a Viagra bottle while bragging that when it comes to
circulation gains, ``Getting bigger has never been our problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Some agency executives did not agree that Viagra-themed ads
might be vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taste issue went out the window with the last election,''
declared Cappelli of the Ad Store.
</P>
<P>
   A much tougher obstacle is the increasing zeal with which Pfizer
is fighting ads that use the Viagra name or image without
permission. After Brown ran his ad, he received a letter from White
&AMP; Case, a Pfizer law firm in New York, insisting that he cease and
desist from his ``unauthorized'' use of the trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he complied, adding, ``I guess this rules out my
plans for a Viagra bed-and-breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   To Mariann Caprino, a spokeswoman for Pfizer in New York, such
japes are no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've written a number of complaint letters to a number of
companies because we're committed to enforcing our intellectual
property,'' she said, adding: ``Viagra is serious medicine for a
serious medical condition. There's nothing funny about erectile
dysfunction.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to policing ads about Viagra, Ms. Caprino said,
Pfizer is battling companies that are ``selling products with names
confusingly similar'' like Vaegra and Viagro.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer is running its own campaign for Viagra, which is aimed at
convincing men to ask their doctors about the drug. Ads by Cline,
Davis &AMP; Mann, an Omnicom agency, show a 50-something couple
dancing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
