</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDITOR-STUDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTING FIRMS FACING MORE PRESSURE FROM SEC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned about the millions of dollars' worth of consulting
that the Big Five accounting firms now do at some of the companies
they audit, the Securities and Exchange Commission wants auditors
to meet annually with company directors to explain why the
consulting services have not harmed the accountants' independence.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Turner, the SEC's chief accountant, made the proposal at a
meeting on Monday of the Independence Standards Board. The SEC
formed the eight-member board last year to address concerns about
the growing number of ties between auditors and the companies they
audit and to create a set of independence rules.
</P>
<P>
   But after 15 months, the eight-member standards board has done
little more than propose that auditors send a short form letter to
directors each year stating that they are independent.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said Monday that a letter was not enough. He wants the
auditors to detail their consulting services and other ties to the
company in a discussion with the company's audit committee. As part
of that meeting, Turner said, the auditors would say, ``Here's the
consulting services we've provided, here's the cost of those
services and here's why those services did not impair our
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner called the discussion and letter a start to addressing
the SEC's concerns about auditor independence. The SEC has also
suggested that auditors be prevented from immediately accepting a
job from a company they audit.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors must be independent from their audit clients because
their job is to protect investors by reviewing the financial
statements prepared by the company's management.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, about a dozen companies _ including Cendant,
Sunbeam and Livent _ announced that they had discovered accounting
irregularities in financial statements that had been audited and
that results would have to be restated.
</P>
<P>
   Since he began the chief accountant's job in July, Turner has
been discussing some of those accounting problems with accountants
and business executives to determine whether there might be a wider
flaw in the way public companies report financial information to
shareholders and the way that information is audited.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the Big Five accounting firms have become
increasingly dependent on consulting, which is more profitable than
auditing a company's books. Now about 30 percent to 40 percent of
the accounting firms' revenues come from consulting.
</P>
<P>
   One concern is that an auditor who finds an accounting problem
may not force management to correct it if the accounting firm also
has a lucrative consulting job with the company. The auditor might
fear that raising concerns about the accounting could anger
management, who could then dismiss the firm's consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he was also worried about the corporations that were
acquiring accounting firms. He said the SEC was reviewing American
Express Co.'s recent acquisition of Goldstein Golub Kessler &AMP; Co.,
a New York accounting firm, which audits the books of 15 public
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said that any accounting firm considering selling its
practice to a corporation should consult with regulators before the
sale takes place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
