<HEADER>
A1749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-COX     08-31 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington and Wendy Hundley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Two Al Gores visited Dayton on Monday _ an
intellectual policy wonk who chatted about educational reform at a
Dayton public school and a partisan pulpit pounder who preached to
the Democratic choir.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke at Dayton's Carlson Elementary School to rev up
support for a new Clinton administration proposal to provide $140
million nationwide to mentor at-risk students to stay in school and
go to college.
</P>
<P>
   Touring with Democratic U.S. Senate candidate Mary Boyle, Gore
told hundreds of students, teachers and local officials he wanted
to have a ``conversation about what it's like to go back to
school.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked to Carlson students about being safe in school and
using modern technology to prepare for the jobs of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of jobs that used to emphasize muscle power now
emphasize brain power,'' Gore told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   From there his limousine caravan headed to a Boyle fund-raiser
at the Dayton Convention Center, where a stream of Democratic
candidates and officeholders had addressed a crowd of 240 people.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Coleman, candidate for lieutenant governor, said Ohioans
are feeling disenfranchised under the Republican administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio gubernatorial race between Democrat Fisher and
Republican Bob Taft ``is about who is going to stand on the side of
working families,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cordray, who would like to replace Betty Montgomery as
Ohio attorney general, accused his opponent of defending an
indefensible school funding system, overseeing a $4 million
settlement to Lucasville prisoners and failing to vigorously
enforce discrimination and environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   With a mixture of jokes and challenges, Gore:
</P>
<P>
   Called on local Democrats to stop ceding the political call-in
radio shows to their zealous opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Blasted the Republican party as a group where ``the right hand
doesn't know what the far-right hand is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly diverged mid-speech to praise his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud to serve with President Bill Clinton,'' he said.
``This country is a better place because of Bill Clinton's
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyle used both events to drive home a message that her
opponent, Gov. George Voinovich, has done little while Ohio's
schools fell into disrepair. She said she would work on federal
programs to support local schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Voinovich did not deliver on his promise to be the
education governor, and he failed the 1.8 million public school
children in Ohio who counted on him,'' she said. ``Let's rate him
an 'F' for not fulfilling his promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Voinovich, she said, the percentage of state support for
education declined, the drop-out rate rose and Ohio got poor marks
for the condition of its school buildings, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She called for hiring 100,000 additional teachers, reducing
class size and creating more vocational and college opportunities
for students.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich's campaign Monday rejected the criticism by Boyle, a
Cuyahoga County commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing new with Mary Boyle,'' said Voinovich campaign
spokeswoman Caryn Candisky. ``She continues to attack the governor,
she has little to say on education and no record to speak of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boyle fundraiser brought in about $20,000 for her campaign,
according to campaign officials.
</P>
<P>
   Gore urged Democrats to support Boyle vigorously and to work as
hard as Republicans in being heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question falls to us: Are we willing to match their
intensity with some of our own?'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington and Wendy Hundley write for the Dayton Daily
News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
