<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUBIAK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heart disease cited in lawmaker's death
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State Rep. Dan Kubiak, who was found dead at his
Rockdale home on Sunday, was a victim of coronary disease, a Milam
County justice of the peace said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Twila Harris of Rockdale said preliminary results of an
autopsy performed by the Dallas County medical examiner's office
showed Kubiak, D-Rockdale, suffered heart failure as a result of
hardening of the arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Kubiak, 60, died while napping Sunday evening. The 11-term
lawmaker was seeking re-election in November.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Romo, Kubiak's legislative aide, said funeral arrangements
were being worked out late Monday. Kubiak had requested burial in
the state cemetery, according to Romo.
</P>
<P>
   Kubiak served in the House from 1969 through 1982, when he left
to seek the Democratic nomination for state land commissioner. He
lost, and supported eventual winner Garry Mauro _ now the
Democrats' gubernatorial nominee _ in his successful runoff race
against Pete Snelson of Midland.
</P>
<P>
   L.B. Kubiak, Dan's brother, ran and held the House seat through
1989. Dan Kubiak was re-elected in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Praise for Dan Kubiak came Monday from leaders and lawmakers who
worked with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all shocked and saddened by the sudden death of our
friend and colleague,'' said House Speaker Pete Laney, D-Hale
Center. ``We have lost a good friend, and the people of Texas have
lost an outstanding legislator who worked tirelessly on behalf of
his constituents to improve public education and to ensure that
state tax dollars were spent wisely and efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George W. Bush called Kubiak ``a good friend and
a capable legislator.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Kubiak, a former University of Texas football
player, threw his energy into the state's efforts to get ahead of
the year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in expressing frustration during a committee hearing,
Kubiak urged the Texas attorney general's office and Andersen
Consulting to stop arguing and work out a way to fix the computer
glitch in the state's child-support enforcement system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to negotiate for the next 51 years because
some of us may not be here,'' Kubiak said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
