<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHIS-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPOUNDED GORDON TIRES PASS INITIAL TEST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid persistent rumors that Jeff Gordon's Hendrick Motorsports
team has been cheating to improve tire performance in the latter
stages of races _ including Sunday's Farm Aid on CMT 300, which he
won at New Hampshire International Speedway in Loudon _ NASCAR
officials confirmed Monday that an initial postrace inspection
revealed no irregularites with the two tires Gordon had mounted
during a critical pit stop in his latest triumph.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be further analysis of the chemical compound
structure of Gordon's impounded tires ``to squash any perception
that there is any doctoring going on,'' said NASCAR spokesman Tim
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   That has been a growing perception ever since Gordon, the
Winston Cup points leader and winner of nine races this season, won
the Pepsi 400 at Michigan International Speedway, marking his
fourth consecutive triumph.
</P>
<P>
   At NHIS Sunday, Gordon started on the pole but fell as far back
as 17th place. After climbing back into the top 10, he made a
critical two-tire pit stop on Lap 233 and emerged with the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The win sparked even more rumors of cheating on Gordon's team,
headed by crew chief Ray Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't going to beat them guys on four (tires),'' Evernham
said. ``Our car wasn't good enough. We needed track position, and
the car was tight. The only way to free it up was to put just two
right sides on it. We did adjust the air pressure, and I know
there's a car owner fuming out there, saying we put something in
the tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we did put something in the tire,'' he added. ``We put
in air.''
</P>
<P>
   Car owner Jack Roush, whose driver, Mark Martin, led three times
for 193 laps but finished runner-up to remain 67 points behind
Gordon, complained loudest and demanded that NASCAR launch an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to appease anybody,'' said Sullivan. ``We just
want to put an end to all these rumors and speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials impounded not only Gordon's tires but also four
belonging to Martin. Both sets passed initial on-site inspection
but were sent to Charlotte, N.C., for further evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last three or four weeks, the perception had been
building that something was going on with (Gordon's) tires,'' said
Sullivan. ``We looked at them (Sunday) night and didn't discover
anything out of the ordinary. We found nothing that would cause us
to raise a red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   But inspectors were unable to conduct tests on the chemical
structure of the tires at the track, so officials forwarded them to
a laboratory in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's chemicals out there that will cause the compound
structure of the tire to break down,'' said Sullivan, ``and that's
what we're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the use of ``tire softeners'' was a common
practice among short-track racers, who use them to make tires more
pliable, enhancing their adhesion to the track.
</P>
<P>
   Most tire softeners, ranging in price from $25 to $159, can be
obtained at high-performance auto parts stores.
</P>
<P>
   Roush accused Gordon's teams of treating their tires with such a
substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception is that possibly they've been adding it to
their air,'' said Sullivan. ``And when they add air to the tire, it
coats the inside of the tire. That's been the talk out there. But
these guys police themselves and they do a very good job of it.
When you get 43 cars side by side in a garage, it's hard to do
anything to a car without anyone noticing.''
</P>
<P>
   After Gordon won the Pennsylvania 500 at Pocono, Pa., Roush and
fellow car owner Robert Yates ``stood by and watched us tear down
the 24 car to nothing but nuts and bolts,'' Sullivan said. ``Ray
was not a happy camper when they had to take that car home in
buckets.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham bristled again Sunday when confronted by Roush's
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to criticize, that's fine,'' Evernham said. ``But
when it's all said and done and they don't find anything, are the
same people that criticize going to stand up and admit that they
just got beat _ again?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
