<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1758 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     08-31 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEASON OF THE HOME RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is September now, but still summer ... still the Summer of
the Home Run.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs dominate the headlines. Home runs make the nightly
network news. In the absence of legitimate pennant races, home runs
have become more important than the games.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey came to Boston Monday and there was no way he was
going to visit Fenway without a discussion of home runs. That is
the way it goes in the Summer of the Home Run.
</P>
<P>
   Junior has sort of become the George Harrison of this Home Run
Derby. While Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa (Lennon and McCartney)
march in step toward the magical, mystical 61, Griff has dropped
back a bit and was leading the American League with ``only'' 47
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Only 47. Imagine having to say you're sorry for hitting 47
homers before the first of September?
</P>
<P>
   Junior doesn't like to talk too much about the homers. He likes
to talk about playing baseball for fun, and for victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same as when you are 10 years old,'' Griffey said
before Monday night's Mariners-Sox joust. ``You go 0 for 4 and you
win and you still go for ice cream and you're happy. You get a
couple of hits and you lose and you sit in back seat and ride home
with your parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The Home Run Chase is over for Junior. He ripped five in eight
games before coming to Boston. The Mariners have 26 games remaining
and Griffey needs 15 homers to beat Maris. Junior's a streak
hitter, but he's never hit more than 15 in a month (May 1994).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even worry about it,'' he said. ``My thing is I want
to be in the World Series. My dad played in one here a few years
ago. I want to get the flags over the mantel, like he has.''
</P>
<P>
   He's patient about the home run questions but not particularly
candid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you got some people going for history, people are
going to watch,'' he said. ``I just don't even worry about it. Once
the ball leaves my bat, I got no contol where it goes. If you find
yourself trying to catch one of them (Sosa or McGwire), you fall
further behind and that's not what I'm about.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's manger, Lou Piniella, said, ``The home run race has
been great for baseball. I equate it with boxing's heavyweight
championship. Nobody can tell you who the middleweight champ is,
but everyone knows the heavyweight champ. There's been a lot of
great performances in baseball this year, but they've all taken a
back seat to this. I'm as curious and as interested as anybody
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior hits 'em in bunches. But it's asking a lot for him to
do it now. He's got 47 and I don't see that as a disappointment.
It's quite an accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   While downplaying the chase, Griffey said he is watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you check out `SportsCenter,''' he said. ``But I don't
stand there and say, `Don't hit one.' I just want to help my team
as much as possible. I never thought I'd hit more than 20 anyway.
My dad wasn't a power hitter and I always wanted to hit like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey got roughed up by the New York media over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were dogging me,'' he said. ``One time when they talked
to me I had just woken up. I just didn't have much to say.''
</P>
<P>
   When we stopped asking about homers, he started talking. About
everything.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd rather prevent an opposing homer than hit one _
unless hitting one would win a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you bring one back, you can smile,'' he said. ``When I
hit a home run, I don't smile. I don't want to get hit the next
time up. You can only smile if it's a game-winning homer. You don't
embarrass other players.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't see the ESPN segment that compared the home
run poses of McGwire, Sosa, and himself. Griffey's pose (Junior
calls it ``the dismount'') was rated tops.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because I'm the only lefty hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   He advised all his young admirers to ``just be yourself and have
fun. You're not me. Be a kid. There's only a certain amount of
players that get to play this game professionally. So enjoy it. If
you enjoy it, you work harder at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is not a job. This is fun. A job is when you are
supposed to start work at 9 a.m. and you get there at 9 a.m. That's
a job. This is baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   And in baseball, this is the Summer of the Home Run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
