<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1760 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT-1STLD     08-31 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina: and Sudan.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOME EARLY VICTORIES FOR A NEW SECRETARY
</P>
<P>
   Albright's accession as secretary of state, which made her the
highest-ranking woman in American history, prompted enormous
popular and media interest. She attracted attention for her newly
discovered Jewish background as well as for successful efforts to
expand NATO and to her push to articulate a more forceful U.S.
position than her dry, quiet predecessor, Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly earned respect from her French, Russian, Chinese and
Arab colleagues. Early victories in Congress were hailed, and she
has won important policy shifts on Iran and Cuba, while helping to
prevent a trade war with Europe over sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   But with domestic problems undercutting Clinton's international
credibility, U.S. foreign policy seems ever more reactive. And with
the bombing of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, followed by
missile strikes in Afghanistan and Sudan, with civil war in Kosovo,
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan, Russian economic and political
problems and the unresolved crisis in Iraq flaring again, the world
seems a more dangerous and unstable place than when Albright came
to office.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's greatest virtues _ clarity and an intelligent,
forceful voice that connects with the public and Congress _ have
not diminished, said a senior White House official who admires her.
But as the administration faces diverse and less manageable
problems, many due to Asia's economic problems, ``her virtues seem
less impressive or timely,'' the official said, ``because neither
economics nor strategy are her strengths, and her depth lies in
European issues, not Asian ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Albright's hard work with Congress _ in particular with
Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. _ has not yet produced a deal to repay
Washington's debt to the United Nations or the International
Monetary Fund, both described as high priorities by her aides.
Compromises have been stymied by a fight with House Republicans
over abortion policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My predecessors had a different world to deal with in which
the parameters were fairly set,'' Albright said. ``They had the
possibility of focusing all their attention on one or two issues.''
By contrast, she said, she is trying to ``put into play a lot of
issues that I see as challenges we're facing,'' like nuclear
nonproliferation, economics and the effective use of sanctions,
issues that were at the center of a January review of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   LAND MINES AND WAR CRIMES
</P>
<P>
   Albright has failed to achieve some of the human-rights goals
she described as among the most important to her. She was an early
champion of a ban on land mines. Last year, however, in Ottawa the
United States was nearly alone in opposing a treaty.
</P>
<P>
   As a Central European whose family fled first the Nazis and then
the Communists, she has been especially concerned about crimes
against humanity. She created an ambassador for war crimes and
lobbied for a permanent international tribunal to prosecute them.
</P>
<P>
   But at a Rome conference to accomplish that goal, the United
States was part of a small minority refusing to sign a treaty to
create a permanent tribunal. In both cases, the Pentagon and
Congress successfully argued that the United States required
special exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she continues to champion her principles, but she
cannot forget America's responsibilities. ``I have to balance
enunciating the principles and leading the way with the pragmatism
of getting things done and the power of the United States,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is now a new expression in diplomatic circles _ ``to
pull an Ottawa'' _ which means to promote a new initiative and then
abandon it at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's fierce rhetorical battles with the Iraqis at the
United Nations helped catapult her into the secretary's elegant
office. And in a corridor leading off from it, she keeps a comic
shrine, a collection of cartoons, newspaper cuttings and other
mementos of her tussles with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But the Iraq problem persists. The latest crisis is an outgrowth
of last March's inconclusive standoff that did little for the
reputation of Clinton's foreign-policy team.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq continues to serve as a reminder of the limits of U.S.
power in the post-Soviet world with difficulties in orchestrating
allies and of the continuing reluctance of Clinton to use force in
risky circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG FIASCO IN COLUMBUS
</P>
<P>
   But the televised ``town hall'' meeting in Columbus, Ohio, was
the most visible fiasco. Albright, National Security Adviser Sandy
Berger and Defense Secretary William Cohen were unable to silence
hecklers or to sound convincing about why a nearly isolated United
States might need to bomb Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio meeting, organized by the White House to use Albright's
skills and popularity, began the erosion of her reputation among
the foreign-policy elite of which she has been a member for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look around the world for the big challenges now,
where's the secretary of state?'' asked Robert Zoellick, former
under secretary of state for James Baker, who enjoyed a level of
influence over his president, George Bush, that seems denied to
Albright. ``To an outsider, she's MIA. People run issues case by
case, but there's a sense the show is being managed by Berger.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration manages crises but has no clear strategic
framework, Zoellick said. ``How do different problems relate to one
another? It starts with the president, but it's not her forte or
Berger's. If you don't have a sense of where you want to take the
country, you won't get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mandelbaum, who criticized Clinton's first-term foreign
policy as ``social work,'' thinks the current team is doing
decently at managing the smaller crises of the post-Cold War world,
which have less to do with national security and diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly in this second presidential term, by far the most
important figures in foreign policy'' are Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin and his deputy, Lawrence Summers, Mandelbaum said. ``For that
we should be grateful. A world with a financial crisis is far safer
than a world with a military crisis, and they've been doing pretty
well. ``But Albright doesn't seem to be a player in all this,''
said Mandelbaum.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
