</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1761 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT-1STLD     08-31 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina: said Mandelbaum.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUCCESS WITH CHINA: WHO GETS CREDIT?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Haass of the Brookings Institution, who was a staff
member of the National Security Council under Bush, said ``the one
significant accomplishment in the second term'' has been to renew
relations with China. ``There you can see a policy initiative and
presidential investment,'' he said. ``One senses that the engine
for that has been the president and the National Security
Council.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Albright defended her involvement and that of
her strong team in the full range of foreign policy, from Asia and
China to Iran and Cuba. On financial matters, she said, she has
been working to ensure that the diplomatic, human and security
aspects are fully grasped.
</P>
<P>
   As a former academic, she has been happy to reach down to the
regional assistant secretaries and to urge them ``to think outside
the box,'' wanting career officers to compete for ideas with
outsiders. She has encouraged Under Secretaries Thomas Pickering
and Stuart Eizenstat, and Deputy Secretary Strobe Talbott, ``to
drive policy and make things happen,'' an official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic issues we have brought right into the department,''
Albright said, ``and we have an under secretary who's strong _ Stu
Eizenstat _ really working on sanctions issues and on trying to
meld the financial with the assistance part of the Asian financial
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   She has pushed hard, as she promised him she would, Eizenstat
said, to make the State Department a serious player again on
economic issues. Treasury gets the headlines over Asia, he said,
``but we and she have been intimately involved with the
humanitarian and political dimensions.''
</P>
<P>
   She is confident about her managing role as secretary of state,
as the prime foreign policy spokesman for the administration and as
a formulator of key policy. And she rejects the notion that
Clinton's choice of Richard Holbrooke for chief delegate to the
United Nations, who was said to have been a candidate for the job
before Albright was chosen, is a sign her own star is waning or
wanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is what it is,'' she said, shrugging. ``People
think you're terrific, and then they think you're too terrific, so
then they let you know that you're not. You can't be in a position
of being the visible voice for the United States and not be out
there to be praised and criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT A SURVIVOR OF THE DUKAKIS DAYS
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Berger have a friendship dating back to the
presidential campaign of Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, when
Albright was the chief foreign policy adviser to a candidate who
took almost unremitting heat for not having a strong foreign policy
view. Despite moments of annoyance, usually over personnel,
presidential briefings or second-guessing about the results of
specific diplomatic missions, they are each other's closest
advisers. They hash out policy in advance and speak many times a
day _ in sharp contrast to the tension between Christopher and
Anthony Lake, or the raging warfare under Jimmy Carter between
Cyrus Vance and Zbigniew Brzezinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the foreign-policy president who wakes up thinking
what notes he can pen to his foreign colleagues,'' a senior
administration official said, a reference, apparently, to Bush, who
was famous for his hand-written correspondence to world leaders.
``So Berger becomes the guy who doesn't make foreign policy so much
as broker it.''
</P>
<P>
   In meetings, another senior White House official said, ``she is
pragmatic and a consensus-builder, like Berger, despite her
reputation outside as an uncompromising, six-gun shooting
moralist.'' She arrives well-briefed and armed with a collective
department view, in contrast to Cohen, whose well-armed Pentagon
often gets its way regardless. She is ``articulate on issues she
knows well, and tends to put aside the talking points and draw from
her own experience, and she's best when she does that.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright dealt movingly with the emotional and security crisis
surrounding the bombing of the two U.S. embassies and the deaths of
many of her employees, and she has handled Clinton's personal
troubles with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING IT EASY ON THE IRANIANS
</P>
<P>
   But her finest policy moment lately has been a shift in the
treatment of Iran after the election of the moderate Mohammad
Khatami as president. While maintaining demands for a halt to
terrorism and a halt to Iran's nuclear, chemical and missile
programs, she pushed Clinton to a more receptive Iran policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard and she had internal criticism, but she got it
done with Sandy and the president,'' avoiding an interagency
battle, an official said. After her recent speech laying out the
new policy _ to which Iran has not yet responded _ the president
took her aside to congratulate her, she said, ``for threading the
needle.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, she used contacts with the pope, Congress and Cuban
exiles in Miami to allow direct relief flights from the United
States to Cuba to resume and to allow relatives to send money.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is also praised for her work with Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov, which helped forge a new relationship
between NATO and Russia. At one point, aides remember, as Primakov
argued for secondary military status for new NATO members, Albright
said: ``Neither the president nor I will negotiate over the heads
of the peoples of Central Europe. That happened once before, and
it's not going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov was silent, then diverted the conversation, and never
pressed the issue so hard again, the aides say.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian policy is generally run by Talbott and is dominated
by the economic and political crisis, making Primakov _ and
Albright _ less important.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also pushed the Pentagon to act more decisively in
support of political goals in Bosnia and to keep troops there
without a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Her conversations with Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic
were crucial in encouraging her to challenge Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   On Kosovo, she argues that _ unlike in Bosnia _ Washington and
NATO were involved early and got Europe to act. A resolution is not
yet clear, she says, but the ground is prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is also proud of using her unprecedented telephone
relationship with the Chinese foreign minister to organize the
Permanent Five to condemn nuclear tests by India and Pakistan. At
their June meeting in Geneva, she told the others that they are
``always talking about a multipolar and not a unipolar world.''
This was their chance to prove it, she said, ``so one country
doesn't take a principled stand and the others sign up the
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   SHE WILL AWAIT HISTORY'S JUDGMENT
</P>
<P>
   With all the ``profound ideological confusion'' facing a
post-Cold War secretary of state, said Moises Naim, editor of
Foreign Policy, this is not a period for ``grand strategy.''
Albright's role, he said, is inevitably one of a goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   But secretaries of state are often defined by challenges. Baker,
for instance, had a great crisis thrust upon him, the Persian Gulf
War, and a great opportunity, the collapse of Communism.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Albright has not had such a test or made such an
opportunity of Asia or Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't operate on the basis of instant gratification on any
part of my daily work,'' she said. ``The policies that are being
put into place are longer term. It may be the next secretary of
state will reap the rewards of what I've done. Sitting in this
chair you get the sense that you are a part of history.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted her recent induction into the Women's Hall of Fame.
``When they say I'm the highest-ranking woman in the history of the
United States, that's pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Kipper of the Council on Foreign Relations, while a
fierce critic of U.S. Middle East policy, praises Albright for
showing the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can be soft with her children, motherly and nice and go
shopping and be all the things a decent person can be, Ms. Kipper
said, ``but when it comes to the work, she's tough and serious.
There's no gender in the work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
