<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HATRED COMES IN ALL COLORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note language in 8th and 9th grafs.) 
(lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Raising hypothetical ``what ifs'' is an often
pointless exercise, but every once in a while it is necessary, even
unavoidable. So here goes.
</P>
<P>
   What if leaders of the Aryan Nation, those rocket scientists
convinced that blacks are an inferior race, were to announce that
they were storming into New York City to lead hordes of young
whites on a march affirming their self-esteem and calling attention
to issues of concern to Caucasians? What if they went out of their
way to invite neo-Nazi skinheads, who, besides not being brain
surgeons themselves, might arrive armed to the proverbial teeth?
</P>
<P>
   What is your best bet about what would then happen?
</P>
<P>
   Would most public figures in this normally liberal city _
whether black, white, Hispanic, Asian or whatever _ raise high the
shield of the First Amendment and harrumph about the need to
separate an important message from the objectionable messenger?
</P>
<P>
   Or would they agree with the late Justice Robert Jackson of the
U.S. Supreme Court that the Constitution is not a suicide pact?
Would they vigorously denounce any event brought to this ethnically
fragile city by hatemongers, and ask the mayor to make sure it
takes place under conditions that protect public safety?
</P>
<P>
   The betting here is that if it were the Klan coming to town, you
would not gather enough First Amendment purists to fill a subway
car. Why should it be any different with a march organized by
certified hatemongers who happen to be black?
</P>
<P>
   That is why the betting here, too, is that many New Yorkers side
with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani when it comes to the so-called Million
Youth March for blacks being arranged for Saturday in Harlem _ with
a special invitation extended to armed black gangs from around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The lead marcher, Khalid Abdul Muhammad, has a record of vicious
bigotry that is nothing short of breathtaking. Correction: make
that stomach-turning. This is a man who publicly calls the pope a
``cracker'' and homosexuals ``faggots,'' who talks about the
``peckerwood Jesus'' and advocates the massacre of South African
whites.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing compares with his hatred of Jews, whether he refers to
``the Jew-nited Nations in Jew York City'' or to the ``hook-nosed,
bagel-eating, lox-eating, perpetrating-a-fraud so-called Jew.'' And
Muhammad is just clearing his throat.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, for one, refuses to separate message from messenger,
and he has not shrunk from attacking the ``hate march'' or
lambasting political leaders who get wishy-washy about Muhammad and
what he stands for. ``The problem is when good people do nothing
about hatred, and equivocate about it,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday should be an important day in this affair. Federal
appellate judges will hear arguments from the Giuliani
administration, which prefers Randalls Island to Harlem as a site
for the march and wants the date switched to Sept. 19 instead of
the Labor Day weekend, which is crowded with events that may
overtax the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a U.S. District Court judge ruled against the mayor,
saying that First Amendment imperatives called for the event to be
held this Saturday and in Harlem, where Muhammad and Company can
more easily ``get their message across.'' Fair enough, some
disinterested New Yorkers would say. Giuliani has a habit of
interpreting free-speech rights far more generously when he agrees
with the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor never said the march could not take place, just
that it should be on a date and in a place where the police feel
reasonably confident about preserving public safety. Given the
possible presence of gun-toting gang members, his concern is not
out of left field.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Randalls Island and Sept. 19 did not come to Giuliani in a
dream. The organizers themselves had suggested that time and place
as a possibility when they first asked for a city permit, months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Questions have been raised about whether the mayor was
tactically wise to go after Muhammad as he did, thus giving him
publicity that he could not have hoped to buy. But Michael Meyers,
executive director of the New York Civil Rights Coalition and a man
who has tangled with Giuliani at times, says the mayor was right
when he decided that one element of leadership is labeling a
pernicious bigot for what he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership is required,'' Meyers said, ``to tell young people
that this is a racial hustle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
