<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-LARGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTITUTIONAL TRADING POUNDS BLUE-CHIPS, SMALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Institutional investors unloaded big blocks of stock at
virtually any price, pounding both blue-chip and small-company
stocks and driving the market down 6.4 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In panic selling that accelerated late in the day, institutional
investors of all stripes _ mutual funds, high-risk hedge funds, and
Wall Street investment banks _ created a market exodus that
heightened fears that a bear market in US stocks may be in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's steep decline of 512 points brought the four-day
decline in the Dow Jones industrial average to more than 1,000
points. But Monday was distinguished by the large volume of block
trades by billion-dollar institutional investors, market watchers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors ``were executing (sell) orders indiscriminate of the
price,'' said James Weiss, deputy head of equities for State Street
Research &AMP; Management, a Boston investment company with $52 billion
in assets of institutions and wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutions are banging the blue chips. Whether it's `Get me
out' because redemptions are coming or `Get me out' because I'm
protecting my performance _ I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, blue-chip stocks were hammered. Houston-based Dell
Computer Co., a darling of institutions, fell a whopping 18 3/4,
closing at 100. Retailer Dayton Hudson Corp. dropped 7 3/16,
closing at 36 3/4. Even drug companies, whose record profits had
protected them from the market declines, were in the selloff:
Warner-Lambert Co.'s stock fell 9 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Only long-term investors of pension funds or university
endowments seemed to sit on the sidelines. Their calm in managing
mega-billion dollar portfolios may have been the biggest factor in
keeping the market in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're long-term investors,'' said Scott Henderson, executive
director of the Massachusetts Pension Reserves Investment Mangement
Board. Nearly half of the $24 billion fund is in stocks. ``We're
sticking to the plan,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   But even individual investors who have stoically watched the
stock market decline from its July 17 high have become increasingly
nervous about their stock mutual funds. When mutual fund investors,
en masse, order their portfolio managers to sell their stake in the
fund, managers are forced to sell stock in big blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest mutual fund
investment company, said volume at its high-tech phone centers was
so high that the Boston company was forced to recruit executives to
help telephone operators take calls.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is among numerous fund companies that have reported
outflows in August, as investors shift their money from fund
companies' stock funds to more conservative bond or money-market
funds. That trend continued Monday. Although Fidelity would not
disclose the size of outflows from stock funds, ``it's very modest
relative to our size,'' said spokeswoman Jessica Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of blocks of stock by index funds in the last half-hour of
trading were also blamed for a precipitous 300-point drop during
that period short period before the market closes. Index funds
typically buy or sell securities at the end of the trading day to
adjust portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's selling may triggered by portfolio managers' need
to meet redemptions by individual investors _ or anticipated
redemptions.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's second-biggest mutual fund, managed by the Vanguard
Group, saw outflow of cash for the first time in years, said Gus
Sauter, who oversees the Valley Forge, Pa., company's group of
equity index funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard Index Trust, a $60 billion fund designed to track
the performance of the S&AMP;P 500 stock index, had ``very minor
outflows today. That's the first time'' since 1994, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the downward pressure, block sales by index funds
``kicked off'' arbitraging by sophisticated investors seeking quick
profits, said Michael Roth, chief executive of USAA Investment
Management Co. in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Investors such as New York investment banks arbitrage by buying
futures contracts and selling the actual indexes to make profits on
the differences in their prices. ``The spreads are so narrow they
leap on it so fast and they wrench a few bucks out of the market,''
Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds that had big bets in emerging markets from Singapore
to Russia have also been forced to sell their stock at firesale
prices to cover losses in overseas markets, investment managers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're highly leveraged,'' said one investor who spoke on
condition his name be withheld. When the emerging markets ``break
down and they're highly leveraged, they go through their equity
position and have to unwind.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is no longer simply the high-risk investors who are
moving the market. Trades executed by individual investors through
brokerage houses also have increased.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage division of USAA Investment hit record levels in
apparent selling by individual investors. The volume of trades hit
3,500 _ nearly double the average daily volume, said Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Roth declined to comment on the nature of the
transactions. &UR;  &LR; ``We'll have to see how the dust clears to see where
we really are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
