<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-MONEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wired kids alert mayor of city's missing money
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving on (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Seth Mnookin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ When you're running a city, you can use all
the help you can get.
</P>
<P>
   So Mayor Carol Hanson was plenty pleased when she got a letter
from a constituent pointing out that the city was owed $700 in
unclaimed money. Even if the letter did begin, ``Dear Mr. Mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Richie Behlog,'' the letter read. ``I am 12 years
old. I live in Boca Raton, Fla. I was on the Internet and found
this unclaimed money that belongs to you. My mom said I should send
it to you. So I am. I hope I am the first person to tell you about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Richie was the first person to bring the money to the
mayor's attention, although the city had been investigating any
unclaimed cash it was owed, city revenue accountant Nicole Gasparri
said. Richie and his 11-year-old brother, Anthony, were the first
to notice money owed to the Boca Raton Chamber of Commerce and West
Boca Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would just sit there all day,'' Anthony said. ``It was
exciting. We got to find all kinds of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Richie and Anthony have been avid Internet explorers for several
years, and have not yet tired of finding other people's money for
the sheer fun of it. They began their fiduciary quest in August,
when a friend of the Behlogs from New York said he had found the
family's name on a list of people owed unclaimed cash.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Richie and Anthony were spending their last days before
school searching the www.findcash.com Web site. Besides the $700
belonging to Boca, the brothers turned up $130 belonging to Boca
Raton High and about $600 belonging to the Boca Pops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unclaimed cash'' can come from a variety of sources, according
to a Florida Department of Banking and Finance spokeswoman: ``It
could be anything _ old bank accounts, insurance policies, payroll
checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Since school started, Richie and Anthony have been spending less
time on-line and more time in the classroom. But their late-summer,
on-line exploits have already gained the attention of some
prominent adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, am I ever impressed,'' Hanson wrote in her letter to
Richie. ``You are a wonderful citizen to take the time and trouble
and have the interest to help out our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
