<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARLIAMENT REJECTS YELTSIN'S CHOICE FOR PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout; contains 300-word optional
trim at end.)  (See also: RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT, CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE, RUSSIA-SUMMIT,
RUSSIA-DEBATE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's parliament emphatically rejected President
Boris Yeltsin's choice for prime minister after a rancorous debate
on Monday, leaving the nation virtually rudderless in the midst of
its deepening economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Chernomyrdin implored lawmakers to approve his
appointment as prime minister, saying that he urgently needed to
start forming a new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia today is, in essence, on the verge of economic and
political breakdown,'' he declared on a day in which Russia was
still struggling to halt the slide of its currency and prevent the
collapse of its banking and financial system. ``Russia should not
be without a government.''
</P>
<P>
   But the appeal drew jeers from the Communist-led opposition,
which controls the lower house of Parliament. In the first of as
many as three votes on his nomination, they rejected Chernomyrdin
by a vote of 253 to 94 with the help of the other left-wing
parties, the nationalists and the liberal opposition. Chernomyrdin
needed 226 votes in the 450-seat Parliament to be approved but got
only the support of his own party and an assortment of
independents.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists' strategy seemed to be discredit the Yeltsin
government in the hope that the embattled president would finally
be driven to resign or at least agree to a more generous
power-sharing arrangement. The lopsided rejection also seemed aimed
at torpedoing Chernomyrdin's claim that only he could unify the
splintered nation and serve as Yeltsin's heir.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin demonstrated on Monday night that he was also ready
to engage in political brinksmanship, as he has so many times in
the past. The president immediately renominated Chernomyrdin and
his advisers warned that the parliament would be dissolved if it
refused to yield, a worrisome prospect for many deputies who have
grown comfortable with the free apartments and other perquisites of
their office and might fear a national election.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for a new round of horse-trading over
government posts and policies in the days ahead. If parliament
rejects Yeltsin's choice for prime minister three times, it would
enable the president to dissolve the body and call for new
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Boris Yeltsin wants Viktor Chernomyrdin to become
the prime minister, and I do not recall a case such as this where
he has changed his mind,'' said Boris Berezovsky, the tycoon who
has sought to orchestrate Chernomyrdin's return to power.
Berezovsky should know: It was his opposition that Yeltsin defied
just four months ago through three confirmation battles in the
parliament to put Sergei Kiriyenko into the prime minister's job
from which he was dismissed last week.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a Russian-American summit, the angry standoff left
the United States facing a meeting with a determined but embattled
Russian leadership with no real government in place and the
prospect of political, as well as economic, implosion growing by
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's acrimony marked an abrupt end to days of lofty talk of
compromise and coalition government designed to secure a bloodless
confirmation for Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got all the consent,'' Chernomyrdin complained to reporters
after Monday's debate. ``And all of sudden everything is
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Communist lawmakers said on Monday that the negotiations broke
down over a deadline for enacting amendments to the constitution
that shift some power from the executive branch to the legislature,
among other power-sharing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Shokhin, the leader of Chernomyrdin's parliamentary
faction, suggested that the acting prime minister might still be
able to mollify the Communist opposition and salvage his
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin suggested that Chernomyrdin might identify his cabinet
choices and spell out his economic policy before the next vote on
his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The idea would be to reassure wary lawmakers that if he became
prime minister, he would honor his promises to left-wing
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Market reformers warned that there was a danger that
Chernomyrdin might now go too far in trying to placate the
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Chubais, who was dismissed from his post as the Yeltsin
government's negotiator with the International Monetary Fund,
warned that the Kremlin would be making a grave mistake if it gave
away the Finance and Economics ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know a single economist from the left side of the
spectrum who is capable of proposing anything reasonable to resolve
the crisis,'' Chubais said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN START HERE)
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's politicians traded insults during Monday's debate,
it was sometimes hard to tell that the nation was grasping for ways
to stem the decline of its currency, fight inflation and save its
banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Zhirninovsky, the strident nationalist, mocked
President Clinton for his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Sergei
Dubinin, the head of the Central Bank, defended a loan he received
to build a country home.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist leader, complained that
Chernomyrdin's approval rating stood at a meager 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin derided his predecessor, Sergei Kiriyenko, 36, for
leading a ``kid's government'' and blamed him for the nation's
economic ills, even though most economists say Kiriyenko was
struggling to correct policies that were adopted during
Chernomyrdin's first term as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   When Chernomyrdin addressed the financial crisis, his economic
prescriptions were vague, halting and at times nearly incoherent.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the government should use credits to boost Russia's
stricken industrial sector but conceded in the same breath that the
government had no money.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Yeltsin government decision to devalue the
ruble was a mistake, but gave no hint of how he planned to prop up
the nation's sagging currency.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not allow the banking system to collapse, but
gave no details about how he could prevent the bankruptcy of some
of the nation's leading banks.
</P>
<P>
   His dominant policy goal since being selected as prime minister
last week, he said, was simply to avoid a total financial collapse
before he formed a new government and tried to figure out what to
do. ``The important thing was to hold on until the end of August,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Before departing for the summit meeting in Russia, Clinton said
on Monday that the West should help Russia as long as it continues
to embrace capitalism, and he warned that any return to a
centralized economy would backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is to go there and tell them that the easy
thing to do is not the right thing to do,'' Clinton said, in an
appearance in an elementary school gymnasium in Herndon, Va., to
promote his education proposals. ``The easy thing to do would be to
try to go back the way they did it before, and it's not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``If they will stay on the path of reform to
stabilize their society and to strengthen their economy and to get
growth back, then I believe America and the rest of the Western
nations with strong economies should help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that it was in America's interest to help the
Russians for two reasons: Because a strong Russia can play a role
in resolving regional conflicts, such as the one in Kosovo; and
because of Russia's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want terrorists to get a hold of weapons of mass
destruction,'' he said. ``A weakened Russia, a weakened Russian
economy would put enormous pressure on people who have those
technologies and understandings to sell them. We don't want that to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that ``we are living in a smaller and smaller world,''
Clinton said that he had decided to go forward with his trip
``because we have learned the hard way that problems that develop
beyond our borders sooner or later find their way to our doorstep
unless we help our friends and our neighbors to deal with them as
quickly and promptly as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
