A1779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      08-31 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Catterton Group, which took over Halston this
year amid a large scale-back in the label followed by the stormy
departure of the designer Randolph Duke, seems unsure about what to
do with the storied brand.
</P>
<P>
   After Duke left in July, the company hired Kevan Hall to replace
him. Now, it is in talks with Vera Wang to join the staff. Her
minimal evening wear is a favorite of actresses like Sharon Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with Catterton began about a month or two ago, Ms. Wang
said, after Bonnie Pressman brought the sides together when Ms.
Pressman was still an executive at Barneys New York. It is not
clear how or whether Ms. Wang and Hall would work together if she
came aboard. Discussions with Ms. Wang have centered on her
designing evening and day wear, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who was the design director for Halston under Duke, said
Monday that he was not aware of talks with Ms. Wang. ``I'm taken
aback,'' he said. But he added that he would continue to work on
designs for spring 1999. ``I'm going forward with the collection,''
he said, ``and I'm staying focused on what I was brought here to
do, which is to expand the collection and fine-tune and focus it,
and return it to its original style and glamour that was Halston.''
</P>
<P>
   Designing for Halston would help Ms. Wang expand her customer
base. ``It was a big honor to be considered by them,'' she said.
``We haven't made a decision yet. We haven't said no.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Schnabel, the vice president of Catterton, declined to
comment. Melissa Krantz, a spokeswoman for the company, said, ``We
have been exploring a number of exciting opportunities, which could
include Vera Wang coming on board to Halston.'' She would not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Bergdorf Replaces Prada
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As if to prove that no one or nothing is
irreplaceable, Bergdorf Goodman has opened a Lambertson Truex
boutique on its first floor, where the Prada accessories shop used
to be. Prada, which will open a store on Sept. 12 at 724 Fifth Ave.
(56th Street), giving the label three stand-alone sites in
Manhattan, is no longer sold in Bergdorf.
</P>
<P>
   The last Prada merchandise at Bergdorf is being sold out from
the spring collection. Bergdorf and Prada decided to part ways when
the fashion house stated its intention to open down the street from
Bergdorf.
</P>
<P>
   Lambertson Truex's designs, for men and women, satisfy the need
for sleek city bags. Totes include pull-out organizers. A flat
oblong bag opens into a roomy pouch.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lambertson, who was a senior vice president for Bergdorf
and oversaw the Gucci accessories line under Dawn Mello, Bergdorf's
president, designs the collection with his partner, John Truex.
</P>
<P>
   The Lure of Orchard Street
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's one thing when low rents attract small
independent designers to the fashion frontier of Orchard Street.
But it's quite another when a successful establishment company like
Tahari takes a collection there.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Tahari, the owner of the company, plans to open a store for
Theory, his pared-down, stretch sportswear, which is one of the
hottest labels in department stores like Bloomingdale's. The store,
to open by Christmas at 175 Orchard St. (Houston Street), will
carry men's and women's wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hippest, coolest, sexiest neighborhood in the city,''
said Tahari, whose partner in Theory is Andrew Rosen. ``Theory
caters to that young hip Wallpaper magazine crowd who hang around
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The street's legendary ambiance _ rolls of fabric are piled in
doorways, and every shopkeeper is ready to make a deal on a leather
jacket _ makes the neighborhood only more attractive. ``It will be
a great contrast: the old and the new,'' Tahari said. ``You have a
lot of religious rabbis walking around there and women in wigs and
long skirts.'' In other words, the height of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
