<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE SLUGGER BEHIND THE SERVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just when men's tennis finds itself a qualitative
also-ran to the more charismatic and poignant women's game, who
should show up, fittingly enough, to kick off the U.S. Open on
Monday in Arthur Ashe Stadium than Goran Ivanisevic, the
power-serving human sleeping pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't see what the attraction is,'' said Mark
Woodforde, the unfortunate opponent, who succumbed like a fly to a
swatter, 6-3, 6-4, 6-4. ``He doesn't do anything except serve. If I
was paying money to come to the U.S. Open, I wouldn't go and sit by
his court.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic responded, with a rare return winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is time for him to retire,'' he said of the
32-year-old Australian. ``Pretty old, can't move, with that
backhand. You can't beat anybody. If I have son, just show
Woodforde picture, you can't play tennis like him.''
</P>
<P>
   And on that promotional note, we go to Miami, for an update on
Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Poor men's tennis, all bulked up with no place to go, with no
way out of the women's shadow for the next two weeks. Steffi,
Martina, Venus and Monica may have surrendered their Sunday network
championship slot to the National Football League but, make no
mistake, they are this Open's main event.
</P>
<P>
   If only the men could simply muscle their way back to past
levels of prominence, the way baseball has behind McGwire, Sultan
of Supplements. If only a weapon like Ivanisevic's _ which even
Woodforde had to admit is ``a beautiful serve to watch'' _ didn't
in the long run create the numbing effect of watching jets depart
from La Guardia Airport next door.
</P>
<P>
   If only tennis had long ago legislated against hormonal
experimentation with racquets, the result of which has turned the
men's game into a freak show of blurry fuzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was serving around 120 miles an hour, and I had no idea
where it was going,'' Woodforde said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he really thinks out there too much. I can't
believe that the game is going that way and the fans want to see
tennis like that. You just sort of walk back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   When the 6-foot-4-inch Ivanisevic's southpaw serve is on, forget
it; even Pete Sampras said he's not hitting it back. And this got
me to thinking about last week's howls of protest from the baseball
apologists, who were so offended by mere debate on McGwire's
nutritional supplement of choice, androstenedione, and had to
remind skeptics and heretics alike that hitting a baseball is and
has always been the toughest single act in sports.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, then how do they explain the fact that every
slugger worth his carton of creatine will weigh in this season with
40 or more home runs?
</P>
<P>
   All pro sports require dramatic combinations of physical talent
and acquired skill. It is ridiculous to claim one exceeds the
other, and ignorant to deny that their applications are tinkered
with from time to time for the purpose of personal and collective
enhancement.
</P>
<P>
   To suspect that McGwire's home run record chase has benefited
from his little bottled helpers is not to say he isn't a great home
run hitter. Woodforde, for the record, said Ivanisevic's serving
would be formidable even if he were still playing with wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it is a terrifically relaxed action, very natural, and
he is able to get a lot of disguise on it,'' Woodforde said. ``I
don't know whether the wooden racquets would slow him down, but I'd
like to maybe try that possibility. Suggest it to him when he comes
in here.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ivanisevic arrived in the interview room, he was fed up
with being cast as poster boy for the men's tennis blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Sampras' game, how many points he wins with his
serve,'' he said. ``Serve, serve, serve. But nobody talks about
him, only about me.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because Sampras has more than a serve, beginning with a
strategy, which explains his 11 Grand Slam titles to Ivanisevic's
none. Sampras, after eliminating Marc-Kevin Goellner in straight
sets, defended Ivanisevic, whom he beat in the Wimbledon final
earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most devastating serve I've ever seen or had to play
against,'' Sampras said. ``I actually like watching him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also said he is closely following McGwire and Sammy
Sosa. His own game enhanced by technology, he is clearly into
power, though his sport is hardly better off for it. Men's tennis
was much better before it got tough. Serve. Serve. Serve. If
baseball were all home runs, we would sit there wishing for a
snappy 6-4-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
