<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1781 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GATOR-COX     08-31 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alligator hunting season opens amid controversy
 &HT;    By Joe Brogan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ At a half-hour before sunset today, some
of the 680 men and women with permits for this year's state
alligator hunt will set out with harpoons and bang sticks to bag as
many as five gators apiece.
</P>
<P>
   It's illegal to use rifles or pistols to hunt the reptiles, so
many hunters use hooked baits, harpoons or arrows with lines
attached to bring the gators to the boat, said state biologist
Lindsey Hord.
</P>
<P>
   Once the animals are captured, hunters usually use a bang stick
to kill them, Hord said.
</P>
<P>
   Bang sticks, commonly used to kill aggressive sharks, contain a
bullet or shotgun shell that fires when the stick is pressed
against the back of a gator's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend time at seminars telling them how to humanely kill
(alligators),'' Hord said. ``The bang stick destroys the brain and
after that the spinal cord is severed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Animal Rights Foundation of Florida doesn't see it that
way. Members will demonstrate against the hunt at 6:30 p.m. at the
public boat ramp at the Belle Glade Marina and Campground on Torry
Island, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunters are killing these magnificent animals for no other
reason than pleasure from the kill, and shamefully, the state is an
accomplice in these despicable acts,'' said foundation spokesman
Nicolas Atwood.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt will be done in two, 15-day phases at 23 lakes and
rivers statewide until it ends Sept. 30, Hord said.
</P>
<P>
   After a 26-year ban, the state allowed the first open season on
gators in 1988 to help preserve Florida's population of American
alligators, which number about 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Florida residents paid $250 for a permit and non-residents
$1,000, if they were lucky enough to be picked at random from about
10,000 applications, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hunters is Daniel Fountain, a financial adviser from
West Palm Beach, who got six gators two years ago and is slated to
hunt Sept. 15 in Lake Okeechobee.
</P>
<P>
   Fountain uses a boat and trolling motor to sneak up on gators,
which become very wary during the hunt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a totally different hunt from being in a tree stand or
out in the woods,'' Fountain said. ``You're out there at night
hunting something most people are afraid of.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
