<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-STALLARD-MARIS-NY     08-31 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STALLARD-MARIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN LINKED TO MARIS ISN'T RETURNING CALLS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Tracy Stallard had called Monday, we could have wished him a
happy 61st birthday. And asked him about Roger Maris' 61st home
run.
</P>
<P>
   But Stallard's birthday passed without that opportunity, and at
the rate at which Stallard is not calling back, Maris' record may
pass, too, without the former pitcher telling today's major league
pitchers what it was like giving up the shot that broke Babe Ruth's
legendary record.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, may be the very reason Stallard, who pitched
for the Red Sox in 1961, has not responded to multiple requests for
a telephone conversation. He never seemed comfortable with his
place in history, apparently viewing it as a negative mark on his
record, his career and his soul, and he may not feel differently
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has talked to me about it, but I don't want to quote
anything he has said,'' his wife said last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She was speaking from their home in Virginia. Her husband wasn't
there; he was working a construction job in another state. ``He
calls me every night,'' she said. She did not say what they talk
about when he calls, but chances are Roger Maris is not a nightly
topic of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Stallard said she gave her husband the telephone number.
She had been given the number by Stallard's sister and the
communications director of the Major League Baseball Players Alumni
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not allowed to talk about anything,'' Stallard's sister
had said when she answered the telephone at her mother's house. ``I
haven't seen him or talked to him since this all came up.'
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stirewalt of the alumni association said he had received
calls from ``30 or 40 people'' seeking Stallard. All he could do
was forward the message.
</P>
<P>
   Stallard has not been heard from. In a year in which home runs
are the highest profile element of any sport, Stallard has
maintained a low profile. Thirty-seven years after the pitch, he
should understand it carries no shame. Let him ask Ralph Branca
about that.
</P>
<P>
   It took Branca time, but he got over the pitch he threw to Bobby
Thomson for his legendary home run that allowed the Giants to beat
the Dodgers in the 1951 playoffs. Branca now has made a mini-career
out of making joint public appearances with Thomson. Stallard need
not go that far, but he also need not continue to punish himself
for throwing that famous pitch on Oct. 1, 1961. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How would today's pitchers feel if they were on the opposite end
of No. 62? Someone is sure to find out soon, and chances are it
will be someone who pitches for Cincinnati, Houston, Pittsburgh,
Milwaukee or San Diego. He could even pitch for the teams Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa play for because St. Louis and Chicago have
a two-game series next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't like it,'' said Kent Bottenfield, one of the
Cardinals' starting pitchers. ``It may be a special thing for the
guy hitting it, but I don't think it will be a special thing for
the guy giving it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield gave up Sosa's 48th home run on Aug. 19. What if he
were to face Sosa next week with the record on the line?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't change my game plan,'' he said. ``That shows you're
pitching scared, and I don't agree with it. I like to go after guys
and challenge them.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Hamilton of San Diego expressed a point of view that
obviously is alien to Stallard.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it would not bother him to give up No. 62, Hamilton
explained: ``It would be an interesting trivia question down the
road. You might as well be remembered for something. As far as
being mad about it, no. It would be pretty neat. It would be kind
of a dubious honor, I guess, but nobody would ever forget your
name.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr., even with his impressive weekend display at
Yankee Stadium, appears to be too far away to challenge the record
this season, so American League pitchers should be safe. But when
Rick Helling of Texas recently talked about the possibility, he
offered a unique perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it came down to it, I'd do everything in my power not to
give it up,'' he said. ``It has nothing to do with my ego or being
the guy in the record books to give it up, but I wouldn't want it
to be broken being I'm from Fargo and that's where Roger Maris is
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Fargo, N.D., indeed is where Maris grew up, called home and
never forgot. Fargo has never forgot him, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that I guess means more to me than probably
anybody else in the big leagues,'' Helling said. ``It's kind of
personal. He was the last player before me to get to the big
leagues. It doesn't happen very often, people coming to the big
leagues from Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, 27 years old, has met members of Maris' family but
never met Maris. His father once met the local hero, though, and
got his autograph for young Rick. He still has it, stored away at
home in Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hero there, an icon, somebody you've heard about since
you were a kid,'' Helling said. ``If you played baseball in Fargo,
you knew who Roger Maris is, what he did, what he accomplished. I
went to the same high school, played on the same American Legion
team. As far as I'm concerned, hopefully that record never gets
broken. I'm sure it will someday. Maybe it's this year. But I hope
he keeps it as long as he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Stallard most likely harbors the opposite hope. But if he
doesn't call, how will we ever know? Happy birthday anyway, Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
