</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook: DL glut leaves roster flexible
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The postseason roster deadline was expected to pass
Monday with the Braves again remaining quiet.
</P>
<P>
   They will head into October with their present roster and the
ability to pluck anyone from their minor league organization for
help.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have a lot of flexibility because they have six
players on their disabled list and now have 31 players to chose
from for their 25-man playoff roster. And those six players _ Danny
Bautista, Rafael Belliard, Pedro Borbon, Mike Cather, Damian Moss
and Mark Wohlers _ on the DL can be replaced by anyone in the
organization as long as it is a pitcher for pitcher and position
player for a position player. For instance, Wohlers could be
replaced by prospect left-hander Odalis Perez, one of the minor
leaguers that will be given a chance to win a postseason spot this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Braves did make an internal roster move Monday,
promoting outfielder Curtis Pride from Class AAA Richmond and
optioning third baseman Wesley Helms to Class A Eugene. But this
was just a paper move to get Pride to Atlanta, as Helms will remain
with the team with the rosters expanding today. Helms was initially
brought up because the Braves felt they needed a third baseman when
Chipper Jones went down last week with a rib cage injury that
turned out to be nothing serious.
</P>
<P>
   Pride began the season with the Braves, hitting .275 with three
homers and seven RBIs in 59 games, but went down to make room for
Greg Colbrunn, who was acquired from the Rockies July 30.
</P>
<P>
   Struggles for Wohlers
</P>
<P>
   Class AAA Richmond has another week of games and Wohlers is
showing no signs whatsoever of improving. Wohlers has appeared in
15 games in Richmond and has an ERA of 18.97. He has thrown 17 wild
pitches and walked 33 in 12 1/3 innings. Wohlers, who last pitched
Saturday and allowed two runs and walked three in two-thirds of an
inning, was upset recently at a photograph that appeared in the
Richmond Times-Dispatch which showed a shorts-clad Wohlers smoking
a cigarette and talking on a cellular telephone after a bad
performance.
</P>
<P>
   This and that
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Rudy Seanez was not at Monday's game, instead flying to
San Diego where his wife Dianna was to give birth to their second
child. Seanez is expected to be back for tonight's game. . . . The
rosters expanding today, the Braves will promote a few players over
the next few days, including prospects Perez, Bruce Chen, and
George Lombard. . . . Chen and Perez will be coming from Richmond,
while Lombard is at Class AA Greenville. . . . Scott McGregor, one
of the two official scorers at Turners Field, is recoving from
pancreatic surgery at Dunwoody Medical Center. He will be released
later this week and should be back on the job for the team's next
homestand, which starts Sept. 11. . . . Javier Lopez hit his 31st
homer Monday night, the most for a Braves catcher since Joe Torre
had 36 in 1966. Torre hit 31 that year as a catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
