his quest for a record-tying 12th career Grand Slam title with a
6-3, 6-3, 6-2 romp. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HOUSTON -- Aug. 31, 1998 -- SCI-DEBAKEY-SURGERY-3, 8-31
-- Dr. Michael DeBakey at the Baylor College of Medicine in
Houston. Though so firmly rooted in Texas that he wears white
cowboy boots in the hospital, DeBakey - who turns 90 on Sept. 7 -
has stamped out a glamorous career as an international medical
statesman. While doing surgical training in Europe in 1935 and
1936, he became fluent in Arabic, French and German. (Sam C.
Pierson Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HOUSTON -- Aug. 31, 1998 -- SCI-DEBAKEY-SURGERY-2, 8-31
-- Dr. Michael DeBakey walking past photos and awards attesting to
his achievements during a half-century at the Baylor College of
Medicine in Houston. Outside of the United States, DeBakey - who
turns 90 on Sept. 7 - is probably best known in Russia, which he
has visited at least 30 times to perform operations and to work on
cooperative health programs. (Sam C. Pierson Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HOUSTON -- Aug. 31, 1998 -- SCI-DEBAKEY-SURGERY-1, 8-31
-- Dr. Michael DeBakey, a pioneer in aneurysm repairs and bypass
surgery, assists in a recent three-hour, quadruple bypass operation
at a Houston hospital. ``I have been blessed so far,'' says
DeBakey, who turns 90 on Sept. 7. (Sam C. Pierson Jr./New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1998 -- PARKER-JAZZ-REVIEW, 8-31 --
Etta Jones and Claude (Fiddler) Williams in Tompkins Square Park on
Sunday afternoon at the sixth annual Charlie Parker Jazz Festival.
The performances here connected several different generations of
players - which is something Parker also did - and healthily
suggested many different ways of playing jazz. (Ozier Muhammad/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1998 -- BRAZILFEST-MUSIC-REVIEW,
8-31 -- Leila Pinheiro in ``Brazilfest '98'' at Lincoln Center Out
of Doors. Ms. Pinheiro, a popular Brazilian singer in her late 30s
who is barely known to New York audiences, is a long-running
candidate in her country for the bossa nova princess of her
generation. She radiates sophistication and as she accompanied
herself at the piano for half the set, her stage manner was
self-possessed. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEWARK, N.J. -- Aug. 31, 1998 -- SIMONE-MUSIC-REVIEW,
8-31 -- Nina Simone on Sunday at the New Jersey Performing Arts
Center in Newark. Her adoring audience, primed by the rarity of her
appearance, was there to pay tribute to Ms. Simone's indomitable
spirit and her lifelong project of celebrating an African-American
heritage of dignity, spiritual fervor and resilience. (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- Aug. 31, 1998 -- DIET-SUPPLEMENTS-BOS, 8-31 --
Met-Rx products containing the amino acid creatine - believed to
help build muscles. Driven in part by a national obsession with
health and longevity, the dietary supplement industry has grown to
a $12 billion industry. But the booming business in so-called
performance enhancers such as androstenedione and creatine is
occurring amid conflicting claims about their effectiveness and
safety. (Thomas James Hurst/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) FORT KENT, Maine -- Aug. 31, 1998 -- CANADA-BORDER-BOS,
8-31 -- U.S. Immigration Inspector Patrick Rodgers questions a
motorist at the border crossing booth at the start of Route 1 in
Maine. ``We have an open border that is an open invitation to
people who want to smuggle in drugs or people or terrorism,'' says
Representative Lamar Smith, the Texas Republican who is the main
author of a tough new immigration law. (John Blanding/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
