<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-SELLOFF-BOS &LR;      08-31 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-SELLOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW SHEDS 512 POINTS AS SHAKY INVESTORS WEIGH WORLD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market erased its gains for the entire year
Monday as investors frightened by turmoil in Russia and elsewhere
dumped shares accumulated over an eight-year boom. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell more than 512 points, and has now lost
almost 20 percent of its value from its July highs.
</P>
<P>
   Such titans of the long bull market as Microsoft and IBM
suffered the most as shareholders dumped their winning stocks in
hopes of the best price. The technology-heavy Nasdaq Composite
Index lost almost nine percent of its value _ much of it in the
final, frantic minutes of trading _ to post its worst decline since
the October 1987 stock crash.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dow, the 512.61-point decline was the second largest
one-day point loss ever, trailing the record 554.26-point plunge
last Oct.27 but ahead of the 508-point drop of October 1987. In
percentage terms, which is the more important measure, the Dow fell
6.4 percent, modest compared to 1987's 22.61 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, the market not only had lost all of its gains for
the year but slipped into negative terriority. Volume on the New
York Stock Exchange was a near-record, with 916 million shares
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   Much now depends on who was selling Monday. If, as some analysts
argue, it was professional traders caught short by overseas events
and in need of quick cash, the market should stabilize quickly. But
if, as many worry, the sell-off was fueled mainly by individuals
shocked to see their new-found wealth shrinking after expanding for
so many years, the results could spill quickly into the economy and
set off a damaging, downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unnerving thing about the stock market is that it can
create its own reality,'' said Edward Yardeni, chief economist with
Deutsche Morgan Grenfell in New York. ``If US consumers get spooked
by this, we have a very serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund executives said that call volume at their telephone
service centers was up substantially during the day, but that few
customers were pulling the plug on their investments. Those at
Boston-based Putnam Investments, which manages $260 billion in
assets, said customer calls were running 20 percent above normal
and those from brokers about 10 percent. ``Most callers were
inquiring about their balances, although there was some exchanging
out of equity funds and into bonds or money markets,' said Putnam
spokesman Matthew Keenan. Keenan said he had no figures on the
amount of switching, but characterized it as ``very limited.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin sought to
reassure investors, saying that the American economy remains sound
despite Monday's selloff. ``The fundamentals of the United States
economy are strong due in part to the sound policies we've been
following,'' he told reporters. ``The prospects for growth, low
unemployment, low inflation continue to be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most analysts support Rubin's view, many caution that
it is becoming ever harder to predict the economy's course because
of two factors on prominent display in Monday's selloff: American
companies' growing dependence on overseas operations, and American
families' growing investment in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have become increasingly worried that economic
disarray overseas is damaging the prospects for US firms to produce
the higher profits needed to justify stratospheric stock prices.
Analysts are becoming fearful that sudden stock price drops like
Monday's will make families feel poorer and therefore less willing
to buy, compounding companies' profit problems and thus pulling
stocks still lower further.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Monday's plunge together with last week's
abrupt drop demonstrate that the combination of these factors is
making the nation uncharacteristically vulnerable to far &UR;  &LR; off
events like Russia's economic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've ever had an inter-related set of
world events cause a financial crunch'' here, said Allen Sinai,
chief global economist with Primark Decision Economics. ``We're in
an area that policymakers have no experience with.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``For 10 years, we saw all the positives of the global
economy; now we're seeing some of the negatives,'' said H. Vernon
Winters, chief investment officer with Mellon Private Asset
Management. ``We've all gotten tied together in the same system,
which means we end up moving more in sync.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Monday, investors knew that the US market would be
shaky; most markets in Asia and Europe had already tumbled on word
that a political deal to appoint a new Russian prime minister and
stabilize that country's economy was coming unhinged.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble here started in a sector where shareholders had made
some of the biggest gains of the bull market _ in computer and
technology stocks. Dell Computer Corp., which only last week posted
a 62 percent boost in quarterly profits, saw its shares fall 18 3/4
to 100. Microsoft shares dropped a similarly stunning 9 5/16 to 95
15/16. Intel fell 5 13/16 to 71 3/16, IBM lost 9 15/16 to 112 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   But the most frightening problems didn't emerge until the last
30 minutes of trading when stocks of all description came in for a
pounding, sending the Dow into a final 230-point plunge.
</P>
<P>
   The slide in computer stocks pushed the Nasdaq index down 140.43
or 8.6 percent to close at 1499.25, its worst one-day point loss
ever. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index tumbled 69.61, or 6.8
percent, to 957.53. The Dow and the S&AMP;P suffered their worst
declines since last October. All three indexes are now down for the
year. In the case of the Dow, the index has lost 4.7 of its value
since the opening bell on January 2.
</P>
<P>
   In what some analysts interpreted as a sign that investors think
the stock market's troubles will spread to the economy, retail
stocks also took a pummeling. Wal-Mart Stores Inc. fell 6 3/8 to
59. Home Depot Inc. lost 4 5/16 to 38 1/8. Retail stocks had been
rallying until recently because investors thought the
consumer-fueled US economy would keep growing even as economies
elsewhere sank.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's selloff was especially troubling for financial
optimists because it pushed stocks to within a hair's breadth of
the technical definition of a ``bear market,'' a 20-percent drop
from a market high. The Dow closed down 19.2 percent from its July
17th high, a mere 69.47 points away the 20-percent level. Until
recently, most analysts had characterized the market's gyrations as
a mere ``correction,'' or 10-percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over who was selling and what that means for
Tuesday's market was already under way before the closing bell
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   William J. Landes, Putnam's chief investment officer, said the
sellers were almost entirely professional traders who had borrowed
money to bet on the Russian and Asian markets, were caught short
and forced to sell quality stocks to pay their debts. He asserted
that individual investors were not selling, a trend that, if true,
cold help the market catch its balance.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy Kimelman, chief economist at Technical Data in Boston,
said that she believes individual investors have already begun
selling off their stocks or will do so shortly. ``I think we've got
a crisis on our hands,'' she said
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, you'll find Mom and Pop are going to jump right
out of the boat. They don't want to be in a boat headed in the
wrong direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
