<HEADER>
A1802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-TEXT-(2TAKES)-     08-31 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TEXT-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RUSSIA'S PARLIAMENT: NAME-CALLING, PLEADING, URGENCY, BUT NO
PREMIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-RDP) 
 Eds: Following are excerpts from statements made Monday by Russian
political leaders in the debate over the nomination of Viktor
Chernomyrdin as prime minister, as translated by The New York
Times.  
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Viktor Chernomyrdin, Acting Prime Minister
</P>
<P>
   You know that I have always been open to constructive dialogue.
And I do not shirk dialogue today. But time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   Seven days ago the President again asked me to head the
Government. It was a difficult choice for me _ not only because the
country finds itself in such a serious situation. During the last
six months I have been able to see more clearly many things and
many people whom I have dealt with during my many years of work.
</P>
<P>
   I saw the mistakes made, the miscalculations in the work. I see
some of my own blame. But I have already said _ and I will repeat
again, because I know the depth of the problems that have
confronted us _ I accepted the invitation in order to do everything
to solve these problems.
</P>
<P>
   I must say frankly that we did not make the best use of these
few days. Unfortunately a lot of time was misspent. Let me stress
again that we do not have as much as an hour left for discussions.
During the past week we have prevented a collapse, but the
situation today remains critical. In the present-day conditions our
main task is to minimize our common losses in this crisis.
</P>
<P>
   I am not trying to escape responsibility for the mistakes in
economic policy made by the Government that I headed. But I did not
make any announcements of devaluation or a moratorium on the
payment of Government debts. That was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Today it is not yet too late. Today we can still formulate a
reasonable policy of the exchange rate. Together with you, esteemed
deputies, we can still create a reliable mechanism of guarantees of
deposits in banks, we can still save the banking system from
disintegration, we can still help the banks overcome the present
critical situation.
</P>
<P>
   That critical mass of decisions will suffice to pull us back
from the brink. But to do that we need a working Government.
</P>
<P>
   This process cannot be dragged out; Russia should not be without
a Government. Esteemed deputies of the lower house, the present
conditions are anything but simple. All Russian people want an
early end to the crisis. I am sure that all the responsible
political forces and leaders are aware of it. And they do not just
understand it, they seek a solution. Life in Russia is incredible
difficult as it is and we have no right to make it still more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   We have no time; we have used up the margin of error, and this
makes our tasks all that much more important and serious. ...
</P>
<P>
   One should not confuse appointment of the Prime Minister or
cooperation with the Prime Minister with presidential campaigns.
You're in too much in a hurry. Don't rush. The Government has to be
formed. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I do not know what the President will do. I have to present the
proposals today on the Government formation, that unique thing to
which we have been moving for so long.
</P>
<P>
   In all respects, in constitutional amendments, in everything, we
came very close, and at the last stage we stumbled. Irrespective of
the decision on Chernomyrdin, it is impossible to take more time.
Russians should not have this lawlessness as well.
</P>
<P>
   Gennadi Zyuganov, Leader of the Communist Party
</P>
<P>
   I was going to make a short speech, but having listened to
Viktor Stepanovich, who as usual has said nothing, I have to make a
longer speech.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to think not only about the country but also about
the possibility of preserving the country. If in 1992-93 we had a
reserve of strength that we inherited from the Soviet power, that
was a strategic resource that has been used up and stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Today the state has nothing of the kind. But even what they have
been creating during the last seven years under the guise of
democratic reforms is in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   The entire financial credit system has been ruined; it does not
even get taxes from barely working enterprises. Those who have
created it have found themselves bankrupt. If today people block
the railroads, tomorrow they may not have enough money for bread
and water. And they will be standing near the administration
offices across the country demanding their meager wages.
</P>
<P>
   The causes are obvious: a lack of basic educated managers and
complete irresponsibility by the executive powers before the
people, the country and the legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The result of your appointment will be that you will not be able
to cope. Yesterday NTV, which has always supported your course,
reported that confidence in you is at 7 percent. To cope, one
should have 67 percent today. Even good proposals cannot be
implemented if neither legislators nor the people of the Russian
Federation have confidence. You cannot cope, and a vast collapse
will begin, even more than has already occurred. And then the
criminal oligarchy in the country will be bloody and the
dictatorship can be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Ryzhkov, Leader of People's Power faction
</P>
<P>
   A crisis, seen and unseen, has been raging in our country for
several months now. It became visible on Aug. 17, but the invisible
crisis appeared much earlier. Life has for all practical purposes
drawn its conclusions regarding those seven years of economic
activity by the Government of so-called monetarist economic policy,
of so-called shock therapy.
</P>
<P>
   And what has happened in this month _ there's nothing unusual
here. This was bound to happen. Whoever had been in the Government
in these days _ Chernomyrdin, Kiriyenko or someone else _ sooner or
later the actions would have an impact, and they have had an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis was unavoidable because the foundation for it was
laid six, seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And all these years, we spoke out _ the opposition, just
reasonable people _ and said: ``Please change course. It is
impossible to go along this course; this course is not acceptable
for our country. It will end badly.'' They did not listen; they
said, ``We are going along the right path, ladies and gentlemen,
comrades _ whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is where we have come to along the right path. Look at what
is happening in the country. The country is for all practical
purposes defeated, robbed, degraded.
</P>
<P>
   Who is responsible for this? Who is responsible for the fact
that we have in essence lost the national security of our state, in
the military sphere and in the food sector, goods and so forth? Who
is responsible for the fact that science, culture and education are
dying? And many such examples can be given.
</P>
<P>
   I think that those people who were the leaders during these
years, they must bear responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone says that what is happening in the country is the
result of a crisis that was born somewhere in the Pacific Ocean, in
Southeast Asia, and has reached us.
</P>
<P>
   It was not conceived there. Maybe it was born there, but it is
raging here. We have a completely different situation. Our crisis
is connected first of all with the fact that such policies were
carried out.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
