<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX CONTROL MARINERS, 5-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Maybe this is what happens when the Red Sox can see the
finish line to a playoff spot: Even Mo Vaughn starts to sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's daring on the basepaths dovetailed nicely with Bret
Saberhagen's four-hit pitching and Nomar Garciaparra's three RBIs
(on a two-run home run and sacrifice fly) in a 5-1 win over the
Seattle Mariners before a crowd of 28,553 in Fenway Park Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The running Red Sox, who also executed a double steal and scored
a run on a wild pitch, maintained their eight-game lead over the
Texas Rangers in the wild-card race, with just September left to be
played.
</P>
<P>
   Two of their runs were scored by Vaughn, who twice took an extra
base, once at the expense of Ken Griffey, and also scored ahead of
Garciaparra's 29th home run.
</P>
<P>
   With his next home run, Garciaparra will join Rudy York of the
Tigers, Ron Kittle of the White Sox, and Jose Canseco and Mark
McGwire, both with the A's at the time, as the only players to hit
30 or more home runs in each of their first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who had come away with no-decisions in seven of his
previous nine starts, won for just the second time since July 1. He
raised his record to 12-6 by limiting the Mariners to four hits in
6 2/3 innings. A nice turn by Dennis Eckersley, who recorded the
final out of the seventh with two Mariners on base, then worked a
1-2-3 eighth, assured Saberhagen of reentering the win column.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen's talk of taking early retirement has been replaced
by serious negotiations to spend the next three seasons in a Red
Sox uniform, now that he has resolved his alimony dispute with his
ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen is closing in on an incentive-laden deal that would
pay him no less than $8 million and perhaps as much as $12 million,
remarkable figures for a guy who signed a make-good deal with the
Sox after radical shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the 34-year-old righthander made it look like a
sound investment in the future, limiting the Mariners to Griffey's
double through six innings. Griffey, who had hit five home runs in
his previous eight games, began his night by bringing the Mariners'
lineup card to home plate, then lined his double off the wall in
left-center with two out in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen walked the leadoff man in the second, David Segui,
then set down the next 15 Mariners, at one point striking out Russ
Davis, Joe Oliver, and David Bell in order.
</P>
<P>
   That man Griffey broke the spell, lining a single to center to
open the seventh. Saberhagen retired the next two batters, Edgar
Martinez and Segui on fly balls, but Jay Buhner followed by lining
a single to left, which brought Red Sox manager Jimy Williams out
of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   His message was clear: One way or another, Oliver would be
Saberhagen's last batter. Oliver grounded the first pitch he saw
into right field for a single, scoring Griffey to make it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Out popped Williams, signaling to the bullpen on his first step
out of the dugout. Saberhagen left to a rousing standing ovation
and was greeted by Pedro Martinez on the first step of the dugout.
Eckersley entered and retired pinch hitter Rudy Ibanez on a roller
to second, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners starter Jeff Fassero set down the first nine Red Sox
until Darren Lewis beat out an infield hit off shortstop Alex
Rodriguez's glove. John Valentin followed with a ground ball down
the line that bounced under the glove of third baseman Davis and
off the box-seat railing for a double, Lewis stopping at third.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero walked Vaughn to load the bases, and Garciaparra hit a
ball that drove Griffey back to the track in center, deep enough
not only to score Lewis but to allow Vaughn to hustle to second,
just beating Griffey's throw with a thunderous head-first slide.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, perhaps still feeling the earth move after Vaughn's
vault, fell behind Mike Stanley, 3-and-0, then conceded the base to
the Red Sox DH by throwing the next one wide on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   He did not intend to throw the next pitch past catcher Oliver,
but that's what he did, allowing Valentin to score despite
tiptoeing into the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn singled with one out in the sixth in advance of
Garciaparra's 431-foot drive into the center-field bleachers, the
shortstop's second home run in two games and seventh of August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
