<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-GORE-NYT &LR;      08-31 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SEES HOPE FOR REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT, CLINTON-WORLD-IMAGE,
RUSSIA-SUMMIT, RUSSIA-DEBATE, GORE-RETURN)  
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Vice President Al Gore, an important voice in the
administration's dealings with Russia, said Monday that reforms
there were still possible despite the emergence of hard-line
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Communists in Russia today are not the same as Communists
of 50 years ago,'' Gore said told reporters on his plane traveling
here. ``And the idea that their participation in some coalition
would represent a return to Leninism or Stalinism is just as almost
certainly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ``labels alone are not any longer the best guide to what
these people are advocating.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued: ``I don't want to put too bright a face on it.
The fact is, we don't know what's going to happen there. But a lot
of the changes in Russia that have taken place are irreversible.
And the damage done by 70 years of Communism are, naturally,
difficult to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how weak President Boris Yeltsin had become, Gore said:
``Well, I don't want to create a diplomatic incident here. He's
still president of Russia. But obviously there are negotiations
under way that include consideration of how much authority he will
designate to his choice as prime minister. And that in turn could
trigger negotiations about how much power might be reshuffled from
the executive branch to the legislative branch .''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The president's trip will be very important in
buttressing the confidence that the Russian people ought to feel
that the U.S.-Russian relationship is a strong one and that we are
going to stand by our support for reform and democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
