<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: POTENTIALLY, THE HOME RUN CALL OF THE CENTURY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mark McGwire crushed his 53rd home run last week in
Pittsburgh, Joe Buck cringed. The St. Louis Cardinals' announcer _
who is also the lead baseball voice for Fox Sports _ was at home in
St. Louis, watching with his wife, Ann.
</P>
<P>
   `My wife said to me, `Don't you wish you were there?''' he said.
``It was killing me.''
</P>
<P>
   Paring his Cardinals radio-TV schedule to 100 games was designed
to let him spend more time with Ann and their 2-year-old daughter,
Natalie, before a postseason regimen for Fox that will rarely let
him escape the road.
</P>
<P>
   Buck has missed seven or eight steps in McGwire's march toward
Roger Maris' single-season record of 61 home runs. Jack Buck, his
father and one of his radio and television partners, has also
missed a few chapters, but has added some road games to his
itinerary to ensure that he misses no others.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad thinks McGwire will do it, and he's focusing on Sept.
24,'' Buck said. ``He figures one homer a series. I said: `That's
ridiculous. You can't predict it.' Now he thinks he'll do it
earlier than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shannon, who has called Cardinal games since 1972, has
witnessed each of McGwire's 55 blasts this season. ``It's been
interesting, to say the least,'' he said Monday from Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. ``It feels like it's been evolving since opening
day. Mark's made up his mind he can do it. In 162 games as a
Cardinal, he's hit 71. He knows what he's capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Cardinal, Shannon played against Maris in the 1964 World
Series, then with him in 1967 and 1968, after St. Louis acquired
him from the New York Yankees. Shannon shifted to third base to
make room for Maris in right field. Quickly, they became best
friends and hunting companions. Maris was six years past slugging
61 home runs, and a wrist injury had cut down on his power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still had an aura of power,'' Shannon said. ``He still had
the record. It took such a powerful person to do it, so you have
respect for it. Even in his last season, when he hit just a few
home runs, he was walked 22 or 23 times intentionally to face
Orlando Cepeda, who was having an MVP-type season.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in a subpar season, Shannon said, ``Roger never made a
mistake in the field, he never made a mistake on the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon said Maris discussed the 61-homer season; not the
day-to-day grind specifically, but his feeling that the Yankees
``didn't protect him or coordinate the press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He never really had a chance to enjoy it, but he was proud of
having broken the record,'' Shannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon said Maris would not have minded seeing his record
imperiled. ``He'd be so tickled that everyone is pulling for
Mark,'' Shannon said. ``Mark is so much like Roger was _ friendly,
compassionate and intelligent.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that McGwire has reached 55, how creative can a home run
call be? ``I don't plan them,'' Shannon said. ``They're
spontaneous. I just report what happens. And it's just so enjoyable
to watch the fan reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to say, `Track, wall, gone,' is ridiculous. With
McGwire, it's, `Bleacher, upper deck.' When it leaves the bat, it's
gone. He hit one 509 feet the other day. There's no suspense. Once
it's in the air, you think, `He's hit 54, and the magic number is
eight.' Instead of saying the score, you make it more personal to
McGwire and say where it landed.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Caray is not lying awake scripting memorable histrionics to
describe the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa's home runs on WGN-TV. He has
also resisted imitating the stylings of his grandfather, Harry, who
died last February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I thinking of saying, `That's a 61 salsa swat for Sammy'?
No,'' Caray said. ``I just hope I'm behind the mike, that I
describe it right, get the balls and strikes right and get out of
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given much thought to what I'd say if Sammy hits 61
or 62. Whatever comes out will come out.'' But for Sosa's 482-foot
54th on Sunday, he remembered saying: ``There it goes! How far is
this baby going to go? Wow.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phil Rizzuto, who called Maris' 61st, said he would prefer to
have thought about what he would say that day. ``If I did, I might
have thought of something else to say besides, `Holy cow.' Instead,
I yelled and screamed so much I had a headache for a week, like the
one I got after I got my first hole-in-one.''
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Rizzuto is having a grand time, discovering a rich
life after broadcasting, with his bride. ``Cora and I went to Paris
for two weeks for our 55th anniversary,'' he said. ``Boy, they know
how to live over there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
