<SLUG> BC-MARINES-ACCIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE PILOTS FACE NEW CHARGES IN ITALIAN ALPS ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Marine Corps said Monday that the pilot and the
navigator of a plane that struck a ski lift cable in the Italian
alps, killing 20 people, were being charged with obstruction of
justice for allegedly hiding or destroying a videotape, apparently
made during the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. Richard J. Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif.,
and the navigator, Capt. Joseph P. Schweitzer, 30, of Westbury,
N.Y., were originally charged with manslaughter and other offenses.
They are now accused of two new counts, removing the tape from the
cockpit, and ``endeavoring to impede an investigation by the
secreting and/or destruction of evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the two men were not immediately available by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines did not say what part of the flight they believed
was captured on the tape. The videotape in question is separate
from a tape discussed at pretrial proceedings in June. That tape
was found in the cockpit by Italian investigators and was black, as
if the camera had been run with the lens cap on, to tape over what
was originally there.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony from the June hearing indicated that Prowler crews
routinely brought hand-held video cameras into the cockpits with
them, in part because they serve an intelligence purpose when
flying over enemy territory. But people familiar with Prowler
operations also say that the videos are sometimes used by flight
crews to impress friends and family with evidence of low-altitude
derring-do.
</P>
<P>
   A similar videotape got another Marine officer into trouble
earlier this year. After the ski lift accident, on Feb. 3, the
Marines began an investigation of operations at all Prowler
squadrons, and the commander of a squadron, based in Cherry Point,
N.C., was found to have told his men to hide any such videotapes.
He was relieved of command.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement of the charges faxed Monday afternoon, the
Marines hinted that a third crew member was cooperating with
prosecutors in making a case against Ashby and Schweitzer. The
statement said the two men had ``solicited the support of Capt.
Chandler P. Seagraves,'' who was seated in the rear cockpit of the
plane, in a conspiracy to hide the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Seagraves, 28, of Nineveh, Ohio, was initially charged, along
with another crewman who was in the back seat, but a hearing
officer who heard testimony on the charges later recommended
against prosecuting the two men, who had no flight controls,
limited instrumentation and no view out of the front of the plane,
an EA-6B Prowler. The plane was on a training mission, and was
based at the NATO airbase in Aviano for duty over Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony and evidence show that the plane was flying lower and
faster than rules allow. Court-martials are scheduled for Ashby in
December and for Schweitzer in January. But the hearing officer,
after eight days of hearings, said that the outcome of such
courts-martial would be ``in substantial doubt'' because the Marine
Corps, the Air Force and a Pentagon map-making agency had made
systematic errors that contributed to the crash. Among other
problems with the case, the crew was given inaccurate information
with which to plan the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps, in a low-profile announcement on a Saturday
evening earlier this month, said it would limit punishment of the
other officers involved. The squadron commander was relieved of his
command and a second officer was given a letter of reprimand; two
others were not punished.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors thus face the possibility that the crash, which is
an irritant to American-Italian relations, could result in no
successful criminal prosecutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
