<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1817 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOV-COX     08-31 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mauro's campaign attacks poll results
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The latest Texas Poll shows Gov. George W. Bush
maintaining a massive lead over Democratic challenger Garry Mauro
as the campaign heads into its final two months.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's campaign responded by attacking the poll's credibility,
noting that in the previous two gubernatorial elections the poll
said the eventual loser was ahead at this point in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The poll numbers, released today, show Bush with support of 67
percent of likely voters and Mauro backed by 20 percent. The
previous poll, conducted last spring, gave Bush a 70-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Poll was conducted Aug. 12-27 by the University of
Texas Office of Survey Research for Scripps Howard media company.
The telephone poll of 1,004 adults asked the gubernatorial question
to the 718 who defined themselves as likely voters. The results on
that question have a margin of error of 3.7 percentage points,
meaning the results could vary that much in either direction.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers also showed Bush with strong job performance
ratings. Seventy-four percent of the 1,004 respondents said Bush
was doing a good or excellent job. The margin of error on that
question is 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The Mauro campaign attacked the poll's credibility and pointed
out its spotty track record. At a similar point in the 1990
gubernatorial race, the Texas Poll showed Republican Clayton
Williams in a 47-37 lead over Democrat Ann Richards, the eventual
winner.
</P>
<P>
   At this time in 1994, the Texas Poll showed Richards with a
47-43 lead over Bush, who won.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas Poll is very good at picking losers,'' said Billy
Rogers, Mauro's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Poll Director Ty Meighan stood by the numbers. He said
Bush's poll numbers are backed up by the 74 percent approval
rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just off the charts and he has sustained those ratings,
which is even more amazing,'' Meighan said. But he said ``a lot can
happen between Labor Day and the election'' as voters focus more
attention on the Nov. 3 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the governor is
pleased with the high approval numbers but ``is taking nothing for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's approval ratings have not fallen below 66 percent since
the fall 1995 Texas Poll. Richards, viewed as a popular governor
throughout her four-year term, hit 60 percent approval only once
while in office.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll shows Bush leading in all regions and among all
demographic group except blacks (Mauro leads 48 percent to 28
percent) and Democrats (Mauro leads 53 to 31). Independents favor
Bush 67 to 10. Hispanics favor Bush 51 to 31, down from a 67 to 20
lead in the June poll.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro today will focus attention on a low point in Bush's 1994
campaign by heading to Hamilton for the opening day of dove season.
Four years ago, in a classic photo-op-gone-bad, Bush invited
reporters to watch him shoot doves near Houston. Bush shot a
killdeer, a protected nongame bird, and paid a $130 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said a friend invited Mauro to hunt, and Mauro invited
the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been dove hunting, I believe, once or twice before,''
said Rogers, adding that Mauro knows the difference between a dove
and a killdeer. Bush begins a three-day campaign swing for
Republican candidates in Illinois, Georgia, Arizona and Colorado in
what will be his final out-of-state campaign events.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
