<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLAMOUR-EDITOR-ART-52     08-31 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLAMOUR-EDITOR-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EDITOR WHO CARED FOR ISSUES, NOT CLOTHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ruth Whitney, who steered Glamour magazine and
influenced several generations of women through the three most
important decades in American feminism, absolutely hates one of the
signal words of the feminist movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Em-pow-er,'' she said gingerly, her carefully painted lips
forming the word as if it were a vulgar graffito. ``Ugh,'' she
gasped. ``It's overused. It's very commercial. And it's used
cheaply.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mrs. Whitney's 31 years as editor of Glamour _ a middlebrow
Conde Nast publication with a current circulation of 2.3 million _
the magazine has addressed issues both homely and hot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as she prepares to step aside, Mrs. Whitney is reflecting
on her career. She sat recently in her 11th-floor office at Conde
Nast headquarters on Madison Avenue and pointed proudly to a story
titled ``Women's Health Crisis'' in the August issue, in which
women _ their real names and hometowns printed beside their
portraits _ describe their lives after they contracted venereal
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing is that this is an article about how the
government should be doing so much more,'' she said. ``I don't
think any other women's magazine will touch that.'' She paused, and
then added, ``This isn't flashy stuff, but it's obviously important
to our readers.''
</P>
<P>
   Flashy isn't Mrs. Whitney's style; she was wearing a
black-and-white check suit, and the gray streak in her brown hair
waved into a soft apostrophe over her face.
</P>
<P>
   Her origins are hardly glamorous. She was born Ruth Reinke in
1928 in Oshkosh, Wis. Her father, Leonard, was a designer of
gravestones and mausoleums, but the only effect that had on her,
she said, was that she learned to drive in a cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   She was awarded a scholarship to Northwestern University, where
she met Daniel Whitney, a journalism student, whom she married
after her 21st birthday. Unlike her husband, who eventually ran his
own advertising agency, she decided against journalism school and
instead worked for Time Inc. as a promotional copywriter. She
didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an election year, and I was madly for Adlai,'' she said
in a voice made tremulous by a vocal-cord disorder that has
affected her speech since last year. ``And the company was not
madly for Adlai. So I got more and more sullen and eventually they
fired me.'' The young Mrs. Whitney then found to her chagrin that
she could not get a job writing for Newsweek or Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I always say next is that if you had a uterus, you
couldn't write for those magazines,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She landed in women's magazines and, at age 28, became editor in
chief of Better Living _ ``one of those little magazines they sell
in supermarkets,'' she said, tossing her hand dismissively. After a
run at Seventeen magazine, she arrived at Glamour in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had a mission,'' she said. ``I wanted to broaden
the scope of a magazine to go with women's lives. I never wanted to
appeal to everyone. That's not what we were about, and that's not
the secret of our success. But I really wanted to make women feel
good about themselves, not just about what they wore.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Her family has long been connected with magazines: Mrs.
Whitney's husband served as her sounding board on all Glamour
matters until his death in 1995. Her son, Philip, 35, is vice
president of consumer marketing at Money magazine; Philip's wife,
Christina Ferrari, is managing editor of Teen People.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Mrs. Whitney made headlines by putting a black woman on
the cover of Glamour _ the first time a mainstream American women's
magazine had done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of discussion about that,'' she said. ``All
the way up to the president. Controversy always made us stand out.
We're very eager to take it on, whether it's racism or abortion or
lesbians. We want to be out front.''
</P>
<P>
   And while her retirement, she said, was a decision made jointly
with S.I. Newhouse, the chairman of Advance Publications and
overseer of Conde Nast, public remarks she made about her
replacement, Bonnie Fuller, generated the kind of uproar Mrs.
Whitney rarely cultivates.
</P>
<P>
   She was quoted in The New York Post, for example, as saying she
was very disappointed. ``There are all kinds of people I would have
recommended,'' she was quoted as saying. ``There are a lot of
strong, smart editors out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Glamour staff members say they've already noticed a different
feeling. Ms. Fuller, who comes from Cosmopolitan, where she
replaced Helen Gurley Brown two years ago, appeared in the Conde
Nast offices on Monday in black pants and a decidedly
un-Whitneyesque tank top (with bra strap showing, one editor
reported).
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitney, who favors Armani and Donna Karan suits, will stay
in the office until the end of this week. Asked to discuss Ms.
Fuller, she replied with one word: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   On the wall by her desk, among plaques from the American Society
of Magazine Editors and Planned Parenthood, is a plaque honoring
Glamour for an article titled ``Sexy Bottoms.'' (``See? We win for
all sorts of stories.'' )
</P>
<P>
   She reached for a picture of some women Glamour had singled out
as notable and pointed to her friends: Tipper Gore, Susan Faludi,
Christie Whitman, Donna Shalala, Pat Schroeder, Mary Matalin. Then
she pointed to a plaque commending an article titled ``Truth in
Fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We win a lot of awards for `truth in' stories,'' she said.
``Truth in Beauty. Truth in Fashion. Truth in anything. Because
when women think they're not getting all the truth, they're usually
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
