u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REDSKINS-850&AMP;ADD-     08-31 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: REDSKINS HOPE TWO BOOKENDS FIT IN TROPHY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Redskins reviewed their 8-7-1 season from a
year ago and found a hole in their hearts. A hole right smack in
the middle of their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents ran right at them. The Redskins allowed an average of
138.3 rushing yards a game, and that was the worst in the National
Football Conference. Washington allowed 4.4 yards a carry; that
equaled the Chicago Bears, a team that won only four games.
Washington's sack total was 37, 13th among the 15 NFC teams.
Overall, Washington ranked 16th in defense and 28th in rushing
defense in the 30-team National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   The more glamorous positions on defense, where money is more
often spent, are cornerback, linebacker and end. Rarely does a team
try to revamp its defense by acquiring tackles _ and by spending
$57.4 million to do it. But that was what Washington did.
</P>
<P>
   In are Dan Wilkinson from the Cincinnati Bengals and Dana
Stubblefield from the San Francisco 49ers. The average size of this
duo of defensive tackles is 6 feet 3 inches and 314 pounds. The
average of their contracts is five and a half years, $28.7 million.
Wilkinson was the NFL's No. 1 draft pick in 1994, a dominating
player from Ohio State who toiled in misery with the Bengals.
Stubblefield was the 1997 NFL defensive player of the year with the
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Dan and Dana.
</P>
<P>
   No. 94 and No. 95, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 25 and 27, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson on the left side of the defensive line, Stubblefield
on the right.
</P>
<P>
   The dream is that both will sparkle beginning on Sunday
afternoon in Giants Stadium when the Redskins clash with the Giants
in the season opener for both teams. The hope is that they will
plug the middle of the Washington defense. The concept is that with
a sure middle, the team's swift and strong linebacking trio, led by
Ken Harvey, and a prickly secondary, led by cornerbacks Darrell
Green and Cris Dishman, will soar even more.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins begin seeing if hope matches reality in five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful having these guys in here, but right now it's
still a dream that they solve the problem,'' said Mike Nolan, the
Washington defensive coordinator. ``In baseball, people there talk
about being sound up the middle; having a good catcher, shortstop
and second baseman and a good center fielder. In offensive
football, you talk about the middle, about having a center,
quarterback and running back. Well, on defense, you must have
tackles, a middle linebacker and safety, good ones, to win
championships. The last time I checked, the quickest and easiest
way to the end zone was right down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, that is where Washington added glue. Will it stick? ``One
or two players does not make a defense,'' Wilkinson said. ``But
maybe one or two guys can make a big difference for a defense. When
the Redskins signed Dana, it made the team more attractive to me. I
saw an opportunity to get with a team that could make the playoffs
and do something special. It was a chance for me to get my career
started the way I wanted. In Cincinnati in four seasons I had three
different line coaches and three different schemes. I didn't play
well and was put in bad situations with losing teams. This is a big
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubblefield, however, knows success. During his five NFL
seasons, all with the 49ers, he earned NFL defensive rookie of the
year honors in 1993, three trips to the Pro Bowl and a championship
ring in Super Bowl XXIX (San Francisco 49, San Diego 26). ``There
are a lot of reasons why I am here besides the money: a
playoff-caliber team, great linebackers, great coaching, great
organization, a great city,'' Stubblefield said. ``I want to help
this team practice harder. I want it to win big.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson and Stubblefield will go about it in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson is active. He is a big man who uses finesse and speed
to win his matchups and chase the ball. Stubblefield is a slugger.
He is often double-teamed and still packs a punch. If teams try to
block him with one lineman, he can often toss that guy aside as if
the player were a 150-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan is very athletic for a big man,'' Nolan said. ``He frees
himself and gets in the backfield. The thing is, we want him to
then make the play, to not be so quick that he runs by the play.
Dana wins at the point of attack. He wins the majority of his
one-on-one battles, and that is the essence of a football player.
And he's played in big games.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Stubblefield is a dominant player, he is often not
mentioned among the game's best. He is overlooked. He knows part of
that is because he plays at defensive tackle. Who notices tackles?
Not many.
</P>
<P>
   And for all of his career he has played in a place _ San
Francisco _ where offense was king.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to my name not being household,'' Stubblefield said.
``But I know my role and what I'm supposed to do. I'm supposed to
take on double-teams and free people, especially the linebackers. I
have to make the plays I'm supposed to make when they are there in
front of me to make.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Just when the Redskins believed they had solved a problem, here
comes another. Defensive end Rich Owens sustained a season-ending
knee injury in the preseason. Expect offenses, starting with the
Giants', to run plenty of backside or cutback runs against
Washington. The idea will be to start the running play at the
middle and then break it back to the outside, where the Redskins
appear to be weaker now.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tactic that Wilkinson and Stubblefield expect. The
Redskins must compensate. With a new stadium, so much tradition and
no playoff games since 1992, the time to make hope reality is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know all of that, and I don't see any reason to talk about
it anymore,'' Wilkinson said. ``Let's just go out and make it
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
