<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-WHY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTITUTIONAL INVESTORS SPUR DECLINE, ANALYSTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sensing a deteriorating world economy,
institutional investors went on a profit-taking spree that sent
U.S. stock markets swooning.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of near-record trade volume Monday, the Dow Jones
industrial average lost 512 points, or 6.4 percent of its value,
the second-largest point drop in the index's history. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 Index similarly fell with a 5.2 percent dip, while the
Nasdaq composite index lost 8.6 percent, its worst decline since
the crash of October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Trading took on a manic quality late in the day with 80 percent
of the Dow's losses occurring in the final 95 minutes of business,
or roughly 1 point every 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said responsibility for Monday's sharp decline lies
squarely with institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you see a huge plunge like this it's institutional
investors moving en masse to get out or lighten their load,'' said
Jeff Hooked, director of Washington, D.C.-based Emerging Markets
Partnership, a private placement investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after three years of phenomenal growth _ but more
recently, after several months of steady declines _ large investors
such as pension, hedge and mutual funds are trying to lock in
profits made on the stock market since 1995, said Susan Pevear, a
senior analyst at New York-based Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're afraid that's all going to be lost,'' Pevear said.
``You can cite Russia or Latin America or Asia as the cause, but
the cumulative effect is a (sell) mind-set.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the cash that was pulled from the market Monday appeared
headed for the safety of government bonds, which have seen yields
drop and prices rise.The 30-year Treasury benchmark bond rose
1.46875 points Monday, or $14.69 per $1,000 invested. Its yield,
which moves opposite the price, dropped to 5.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone just wants Treasuries, you're seeing that in all
markets,'' China Trust Bank's Bob Laskowski told The Associated
Press. Laskowski, who manages about $220 million in bonds for the
bank, said he expects yields on government bonds to decline
further.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not every large investor was in a stock-selling mood Monday.
And as prices dropped, some who earlier in the day had sold shares
found themselves wooed by low prices to reinvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Youcan't get around the fact that for every buyer there's a
seller,'' said Larry Harris, a former visiting economist at the New
York Stock Exchange and a professor at the University of Southern
California's Marshall School of Business. ``Some people panicked
and for them (a large drop) takes on a life of its own. Others
think it's a terrific opportunity to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, small investors Monday and in recent weeks have
emerged as more sedate than their professional counterparts,
several analysts said. Monday's sell-off was ``Wall Street in
action, not Main Street,'' Pevear said.
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis-based American Express Financial Advisors, which
manages $200 billion in assets, said as of last Friday that
investors in the company's mutual funds have deposited and
withdrawn funds in roughly equal amounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't see an outflow from small investors,'' said
Peter Anderson, American Express chief investment officer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were mixed Monday on whether the market has bottomed
out now, or more declines lie ahead. ``We're going to hit a floor
pretty soon or a lot of companies are going to become takeover
bait,'' said Hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Anderson, say the market may drop further,
perhaps to 7,200 before rebounding. ``But that's assuming we don't
roll into a recession in 1999,'' Anderson said. ``If we do, we
won't be seeing 500-point drops, but a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   While Monday's point drop was the second largest in the history
of the Dow, it was still far short of the 900-point drop necessary
for circuit breakers on the New York Stock Exchange to activate.
New steeper limits allow the NYSE to drop 10 percent, 20 percent
and 30 percent before graduated halts in trading go into effect.
Limits on computer-run program trading also are activated when the
market moves 50 points up or down.
</P>
<P>
   That trading was allowed to continue even in the near-free fall
of Monday's final hour is a good thing, said USC's Harris. ``Had
people been worried about the market closing, they might have tried
to trade ahead of that,'' sending stock down further still, he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
