<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Investors Ready to Seize the Day   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gas up the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Load your tackle box.
</P>
<P>
   Buy your bait.
</P>
<P>
   And then wait. Yup, wait.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably premature to start fishing the bottom of the
market for prize catches, but it may not be long before it's open
season on battered stocks. The plunge in the Dow Jones industrial
average is still a fraction of a percentage point from meeting the
technical criteria for a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow is down 19.26 percent from its all-time high in July,
and the academic definition of a bear market is a slide of 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, few fund managers and professional traders are
prepared to call yesterday's barbarous destruction the last of the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in a mad rush to do any (immediate) buying. I'm going
to sit on my cash and kind of see where this thing backfills,''
says Arthur Bonnel, manager of the Bonnel Growth Fund, part of San
Antonio's US Global Investors Group.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it's never too early to bait your hook and start to
focus on those stocks that you would like to buy when you think
they have hit their lowest ebb, Bonnel says. And naturally, the
veteran stock picker has a list of stocks he is eyeing.
</P>
<P>
   One favorite is Scientific-Atlanta, the Norcross, Ga., maker of
set-top boxes that convert digital television signals to analog
broadcast signals. Television stations will soon begin to send
digital signals, and consumers will be able to convert their sets
by buying or renting these boxes, he says. The stock closed
yesterday around $18, down 36 percent from its 52-week high of 28.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bonnel isn't alone. There isn't much else for fund
managers to do but scour the market for potential bargains. And
Alan Snyder of Snyder Capital Management in San Francisco is
scratching out his shopping list.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that list is Eidos, a United Kingdom-based video
gamemaker whose American depositary receipts, ADRs, are trading at
$9.50 _ off 57 percent from their 52-week high of about $22. What
Snyder likes best about the stock is that it is carrying about $5 a
share in cash and liquid assets, which means the shares are
actually selling for $4.50 a share. Sony has included one of
Eidos's games in its marketing materials, which should give the
British company's products an edge, Snyder says.
</P>
<P>
   Another stock is General Instrument, a Horsham, Pa. maker of
cable television equipment, including the boxes that go on top of
your set. The stock closed at about around $20 yesterday, down
about 32 percent from its 52-week high of $29.50.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder thinks the stock is undervalued because Wall Street
analysts have not focused on the company's wholly owned subsidiary,
NextLevel, which makes ``the guts of the cable television
equipment'' for telephone companies. Snyder contends that the
Street is ignoring the unit's value, which he says is worth $6 to
$8 a share.
</P>
<P>
   General Instrument was expected to spin-off NextLevel, and
Snyder is confident that the offering will go forward despite the
current market turmoil. Cable giant Telecommunications Inc.,
(better known as TCI) owns about a 22 percent stake in stock and
warrants. And thus, he speculates that General Instrument is
takeover bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the stock gets too low, I think somebody _ like TCI _ will
just (buy) out the company,''says Snyder whose firm manages assets
of about $1.25 billion. ``That's why I'm so high on the stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Another bargain hunter we checked in with is emerging growth
specialist James Broadfoot, chief investment officer of Ivy
Management in Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Broadfoot especially likes companies with little foreign
exposure, especially in Asia, solid and predictable growth, and
strong balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorites is Property Recovery Group International.
The firm provides accounts payable and other audit services to
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company closed around $19, down about 44
percent from its 52-week high. Broadfoot sees this company as a
grower whose services will be in even higher demand if the economy
starts to put the squeeze on retailers.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, bottom-fishing is fraught with risk. In fact, the
bottom of a market usually does not become totally evident until it
is in the rear view mirror, warns US Global's Bonnel. But still,
for those willing to cast their lines, there can be huge rewards in
picking a battered stock and watching it reach its full potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunes are made in bear markets, and fortunes are realized
in bull markets,'' Bonnel says.  &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
