<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT QUOTES GATES DEPOSITION IN DEFENSDING MICROSOFT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government is attempting to use Bill Gates' own
words against him, quoting from last week's deposition of the
Microsoft chairman in defending its case against the software
giant.
</P>
<P>
   The federal and state governments included Gates comments in a
lengthy document filed with the U.S. District Court Monday night,
urging a judge to reject Microsoft's request that the case be
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The government declined to make copies of the filing available
for reporters, saying confidential information had not yet been
edited from the document.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer familiar with the filing said that when Gates was
questioned at Microsoft last Thursday and Friday, he made comments
that supported the government case, and those comments were
excerpted in the filing.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer declined to be more specific, and Microsoft said the
oblique characterization of a secret deposition was unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Gates is scheduled to be deposed for a third day Wednesday.
Government attorneys said Gates was so argumentative that they
could not get answers to all their questions during the first round
of questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials responded that Gates was fully cooperative
during the questioning, and that government lawyers were frustrated
that he didn't say what they wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The deposition of Gates is to resume in Redmond, Wash., as both
sides frantically prepare for a Sept. 23 trial in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will be to determine whether Microsoft illegally
sought to extend a monopoly on computer operating system into the
market for Internet browsers, as is contended by the attorneys
general of the United States, 20 states and the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has sought to have the case dismissed, saying that an
appeals court ruling upholding its integration of an Internet
browser into an earlier version of its operating system vindicates
its marketing strategy and undermines the government's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the appeals court ruling, we believe the government's
case has been dealt a serious blow, and we believe the court can
resolve this matter for consumers without the need for a long and
expensive trial,'' said Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray.
</P>
<P>
   But in Monday's filing, according to a lawyer familiar with the
document, the governments argued against the dismissal. The
governments said there are facts in dispute in the case, which
means it can not be dismissed before a trial.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing, the government cites not only the Gates
deposition, but also depositions of officials from Intel, Apple
Computer and Real Networks to bolster its contention that Microsoft
has illegally sought to stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denies that contention, and says the effort to broaden
the case beyond allegations about the company's relationship with
Netscape shows that the government has become desperate to save a
weakened lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Microsoft has sought to bolster its defense by
subpoenaing internal Netscape Communications Corp. e-mail that
Microsoft believes will show Netscape engineers believed
Microsoft's browser was superior to Netscape's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
