<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEYBOLD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 This Year, Seybold Seethes With Fear _ Quark, Adobe Battle  Rattles
Publishing Forum   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
As he prepared to fly to San Francisco for a major publishing
industry conference this week, Quark Inc. CEO Tim Gill insisted
that he's not trying to start a fight, but a ``friendly
discussion'' about buying bigger rival Adobe Systems Inc.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If they do want to talk, that would be really cool,'' Gill
said in a telephone interview yesterday from Quark's Denver
headquarters. Gill added that he wants to get Adobe stockholders,
customers and executives talking about a deal ``and maybe they'll
come to a place that's a little more mellow.''
</P>
<P>
   But the brewing battle between two desktop publishing pioneers
has raised the level of angst among the more than 43,000 publishing
industry professionals who are descending today on San Francisco's
Moscone Convention Center for the Seybold Seminars Publishing 98.
Many see Gill as anything but mellow and consider Quark an
aggressor seeking to dismantle the consumer-friendly Adobe Systems,
which has emphatically rejected Quark's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be vehemently opposed to such an acquisition,'' said
Paul Beyer, who, as an executive at Boston's Banta Corp., a
printing and digital imaging firm, is a major customer of both
firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It foreshadows not only the eventual downfall of Quark, but it
would be a detrimental move for the whole graphic arts industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Quark's overtures to Adobe figure to be the major
behind-the-scenes topic during Seybold, which runs through Friday.
Conference organizers hastily scheduled a ``group therapy'' session
tomorrow afternoon for attendees to ``share your pain, to sort out
your confusion and soothe your anguish'' over the proposed
Quark-Adobe takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any bigger than this for our business,'' said
Thad McIlroy, a co-chairman of the conference, which shifts into
full gear today.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``People have these strong relationships with their
software,'' and news of Quark's bid for Adobe makes them nervous,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the fate of San Jose's Adobe Systems, which
announced a management shakeup last month and plans to lay off up
to 300 employees, about 10 percent of its worldwide workforce.
Adobe, known for graphics and desktop publishing programs such as
Adobe PhotoShop, Illustrator and PageMaker, projected flat earnings
or a net loss for the quarter ended yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Quark, a privately owned company whose flagship product is an
electronic page-layout program called QuarkXPress, is about
one-fifth the size of Adobe. But Adobe's stock, which peaked at
nearly $53 per share last September, has since plummeted 50 percent
to $26.25 per share yesterday, leaving an opening for Quark to make
an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe founders John Warnock and Charles Geschke, saying they
have not seen a specific, bona fide offer, have flat out rejected
Quark's overtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not for sale,'' Warnock said in an interview. ``That
doesn't mean that if someone should come in and offer one
incredible number and it was financible, we would turn it down. We
don't believe that is happening here.''
</P>
<P>
   Geschke said neither Gill nor Quark CEO Fred Ebrahimi has
personally contacted either him or Warnock about a sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disingenuous to say it's a friendly thing if you
don't make a little phone call and say, `Let's go to lunch and
discuss this,' '' Geschke said.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial and industry analysts were ready to dismiss the
move as a Quark publicity stunt or a last-gasp pre-emptive strike
to prevent Adobe from knocking Quark out of business with a new
``Quark-killer'' page-layout program scheduled for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of problems with a Quark and Adobe
combination,'' said Louis Mazzucchelli, an analyst with Gerard
Klauer Mattison. ``Even if Quark can scrape up enough money,
they're going to end up dismantling Adobe. I can't imagine either
Geschke or Warnock saying, `We think this is a good idea.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Adobe has reduced its dependence on the fate of Apple Computer,
so it might not benefit as much from Apple's recent resurgence,
Mazzucchelli said. Still, Adobe should be able to pull out of its
nose-dive if it can refocus its strengths in desktop publishing and
refocus on new Web-publishing products, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took their eye off the ball for a little while,'' he
said. ``But they have very good market share and good brand
equity.''
</P>
<P>
   But other observers say Quark and Adobe were two companies that
prospered in a desktop publishing market that now has peaked.
Combined, they finally could catch the wave in Web publishing that
both so far have missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is serious and well worth considering,'' McIlroy said.
``To me, there's nothing casual or careless or insincere on Quark's
part. Anyone who wants to ridicule Quark is just taking a cheap
shot. You can't make fun of their product or the talent of Tim Gill
or the people at the company.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  At least one publishing customer agreed that a Quark-Adobe
union might be beneficial. ``If they don't come together,
financially, they are both in trouble,'' said Walter Schild,
founder of Genex Interactive, a Culver City software developer and
interactive-advertising consultant. ``Their tools really work well
together, and I'd like to see them come together and make a solid
platform for publishing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
