<SLUG> BC-911PHONE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 911 Cell-Phone Location Just a Jingle Away   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
You're in an unfamiliar area, and you get into a car wreck. You're
not hurt, but there are injuries in the other vehicle. You whip out
your cell phone and dial 911. Then you try to explain where you are
so that the police can send help.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem of locating cellular callers has always been a
bugaboo for 911 workers, but a solution appears imminent. Starting
in November, Audiovox will ship a phone that uses a built-in global
positioning satellite service (GPS) to pinpoint a caller's
location.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing the 911 button on the Audiovox FoneFinder phone
initiates a phone call to 911 and sends your exact latitude and
longitude to the 911 center. The phone can be connected to any
cellular service, with no extra charge for calls utilizing the
location feature.
</P>
<P>
   The technology behind the phone was developed by Robert Tendler,
chairman of Boston-based Tendler Cellular, who got the idea after
inventing a similar system for ship-to-shore radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a patent attorney by trade who went wrong and actually
invented something,'' said Tendler, who is patent counselor for the
U.S. arm of Mitsubishi Electric.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is in talks with other phone manufacturers, including
Nokia, and that a major automaker may offer his system as an
accessory.
</P>
<P>
   The new phone does have a couple of drawbacks: It won't work
indoors (because it needs to ``see'' the satellites), and it's
expensive, at about $400.
</P>
<P>
   If you're willing to wait at least until next year, you may be
able to get 911-location service that will work with your existing
phone. Cellular companies are examining technology that will let
them locate callers using special networks at cell sites.
</P>
<P>
   TruePosition, a Pennsylvania company, has conducted successful
trials of the new network approach in New Jersey and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is looking at these two solutions, but Tendler is
the only guy with something that will solve the problem right
now,'' said Lynsie Hall, consultant to the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   James Daurio, a vice president for Audiovox, said his company
decided to make the FoneFinder ``because our feeling is it's an
immediate solution to a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, 911 centers receive an estimated 30 million calls from
cell phones each year. Tendler said Massachusetts, where he lives,
takes in 40,000 calls a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
