<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Norwest, Wells Pick Key Staff   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Wells Fargo and Norwest banks named executives to head six key
staff functions and four business units in preparation for their
impending merger.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Separately, the Federal Reserve Board announced yesterday that
it will hold a single hearing September 17 in Minneapolis for the
public to discuss the impact of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger is approved, as expected, by regulators and
shareholders, Wells President Rod Jacobs will be chief financial
officer of the combined bank, which will be called Wells Fargo and
be based in San Francisco. Norwest CFO John Thornton intends to
retire in mid-1999. Wells CFO Ross Kari will be deputy CFO.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Vice Chairman David Hoyt will head commercial and
wholesale banking businesses. Wells Vice Chairman Charlie Johnson,
who heads wholesale banking, plans to retire at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest Executive Vice President Tom Emerson will become chief
auditor. Wells EVP Eric Shand will be in charge of risk asset
review. Wells EVP Donald Dana will manage corporate properties.
Norwest's Bob Strickland will head investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest's Jerry Gray will lead small-business lending. Wells'
Dick Schliesmann will be in charge of auto finance. Deb Moore,
president of Norwest Card Services, will be in charge of card
services for the combined bank.
</P>
<P>
   In another announcement, Wachovia Corp. of Winston-Salem, N.C.,
has agreed to buy $304 million of credit card loans from Wells
Fargo. This follows Wells' announcement last month that it planned
to sell off about $700 million of its credit card loans, about 16
percent of its portfolio, that go to less credit-worthy consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
