<SLUG> BC-MA-GOV-POLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARSHBARGER, CELLUCCI INCREASE LEADS, POLL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With two weeks to go to the primary election, Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci holds a commanding lead over state Treasurer
Joseph D. Malone in the Republican gubernatorial primary and
Attorney General Scott Harshbarger has pulled far ahead of his two
Democratic rivals, according to two recent Boston Globe/WBZ-TV
polls.
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent survey taken Saturday and Sunday,
Cellucci, who trounced Malone at the Republican Party convention in
April, now leads by a 25 point margin _ 55 percent to 30 percent
with 12 percent undecided _ among 400 likely GOP primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger, who won a narrow victory at the Democratic Party's
endorsement convention in June, holds a 31-point lead over his
nearest rival, former state senator Patricia McGovern. Harshbarger
received 50 percent of the likely Democratic voters surveyed, while
McGovern polled 19 percent. Former US representative Brian Donnelly
received 8 percent. Twenty percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   With a series of televised debates and an expected ad blitz by
contenders from both parties still to come, strategists from all
the campaigns believe a significant number of people will make up
their minds or switch allegiances between now and Sept. 15. In
fact, McGovern, who has been absent from the airwaves throughout
the summer, plans to kick off a $600,000 TV campaign today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the GOP contenders square off in a televised debate
in Springfield Tuesday night. A media consortium that includes the
Globe, the Boston Herald, and major TV stations, plans two debates
before the primary: a Democratic debate at the Kennedy Library
Wednesday and a GOP debate from Worcester on Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe poll taken this weekend, conducted by KRC
Communications Research of Newton, has a margin of error of plus or
minus 5 percentage points. It is the second survey taken in the
last week confirming that the leads of Cellucci and Harshbarger are
substantial. An earlier one conducted by KRC between Aug. 24-27
showed the gap as wide as 41 points for both Cellucci over Malone
and Harshbarger over McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican primary voters feel Cellucci has done a very good
job as acting governor and see no reason to vote him out,'' said
Gerry Chervinsky, president of KRC Communications Research.
</P>
<P>
   Chervinsky explained the statistical differences in the two
samples by saying likely voters polled during the week may have
different opinions from voters found at home on the weekend. He
also said that the swing by some measures is statistically
insignificant when accounting for the margins of error in both
polls, even though the difference in the gap between the surveys
appear large.
</P>
<P>
   Because Cellucci and Harshbarger's leads seemed so large in last
week's poll _ and larger than in &UR;  &LR; other recent polls _ the Globe
elected to survey a second sample of voters last weekend. Although
the gap was narrower, the second poll still showed the two
front-runners far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are a blow to Malone's contention that he has
closed the wide gap between him and Cellucci. Last week, the Malone
campaign released its own poll showing him trailing the acting
governor by less than 5 percentage points. Other independent polls
have calculated the gap at between 18 and 30 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic contest, Chervinsky also noted that
Harshbarger's support is strong in all age, gender, and income
categories among those surveyed over the weekend. ``It appears that
the primary electorate has basically decided that he is the best
candidate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chervinsky said the survey did find that Harshbarger has not
connected as well as he might on the issues. ``It's more a question
of his ads, his party nomination, and the feeling among Democrats
that he is a winner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chervinsky said the poll indicates that independents, who often
have been a decisive factor in party contests, are shying away from
voting in either primary. In the Republican sample, 59 percent are
GOP registered and 41 percent consider themselves independents. In
some actual election primaries, independents have made up as much
as 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Even the negative television ads that both Republican candidates
have thrown at each other has not yet hurt them with voters.
Cellucci is viewed favorably by 63 percent of the GOP primary
voters, while 13 percent give him an unfavorable rating. Malone has
a 48 percent favorable rating and a 16 percent unfavorable rating.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democratic primary were held tomorrow, 50 percent of
likely Democratic voters surveyed said they would choose
Harshbarger. Of those voters, Harshbarger received slightly more
support from women than men, 51 to 49 percent, and from Democrats
than Independents by 51 to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's support also comes largely from people
aged 18 to 39. Within that age bracket, 54 percent support
Harshbarger, while 52 percent of the people over the age of 65
support him.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen percent of likely Democratic voters said they would
vote for McGovern. Her supporters are more likely to be women than
men, by 24 to 13 percent, and slightly more are likely to be
Democrats than independents, by 19 to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly would attract 8 percent of all likely Democratic voters
and his support comes more from men than women, but is split
equally among Democrats and Independents. Donnelly's supporters
also fall in nearly equal parts from every age range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
