r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      08-31 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Market's Rout Won't Cut Off Venture Capital to Startups   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Venture capitalist Roger McNamee paused during a telephone
interview about yesterday's market meltdown to shout at a partner,
``You buying Seibel (Systems)?''
<TEXT>
<P>
   McNamee's stock-buying spree was a sideline to his day job _
bankrolling startups. The good news, according to this venture
veteran, is that the current market rout won't cut off the flow of
capital to new startups, at least not for now.
</P>
<P>
   That's because VCs like him are already flush with cash that
poured into their funds while the stock market was booming. They'll
invest this money over the next few years, almost regardless of
what happens on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   That means startups are unlikely to break their leases or quit
hiring just because stocks are having a lousy month.
</P>
<P>
   Some startups will even find the nerve to go public in this
market maelstrom. eBay, the Internet auction site headquartered in
San Jose, is supposedly primed to pop out the IPO pipeline next
week.
</P>
<P>
   And keep your eye on Healtheon, the latest company founded by
Jim Clark. He's already scored twice with Silicon Graphics and
Netscape. Clark is poised for a threepeat and is rumored ready to
file an IPO for Healtheon, which uses the Internet to expedite
health insurance transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course if the market free-fall goes long enough and deep
enough, all bets are off. IPOs could dry up, which would eventually
staunch the flow of venture capital, and with it, Bay Area
startups.
</P>
<P>
   But McNamee was betting yesterday that wouldn't happen, that
Wall Street would soon hit bottom, making this a bargain market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through enough of these corrections to know it
doesn't matter what you owned going into them,'' he said. ``What
matters is what you own coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Lonely hearts club?  &LR; As if the crises in world and financial
markets weren't enough, researchers at Carnegie Mellon University
have sown doubt about one of the cherished notions of Internet
advocates _ that the global network brings people together into
``virtual communities.''
</P>
<P>
   In a scientific paper that will be published this week in the
American Psychologist, Carnegie Mellon social psychology professor
Robert Kraut suggests that even a few hours a week spent online can
make people more lonely and depressed.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's how the study was encapsulated in a New York
Times article Sunday, and that's how it will reverberate through
other media. Howard Rheingold, the Mill Valley man who coined the
term virtual community a decade ago, sighed yesterday as he tried
to boil a complex discussion down into the bite-size sounds of
public debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kraut is a serious social scientist who has raised important
questions,'' Rheingold said. ``But you can't draw simple
conclusions from a complex study.''
</P>
<P>
   Rheingold said he'll read Kraut's paper to learn about the 169
people who formed his study sample: How well do they represent the
larger population of Web users? What did they do online, flirt in
chat rooms or frequent debating forums?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we're fighting here is the mythology that
we've lost that Mayberry RFD community where everybody knew
everybody and nobody locked their doors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that face-to-face nirvana, if it ever existed, has long
since given way to the world in which autos and phones, jets and
television alternately tug us apart and pull us together. And he
hopes the current debate over Web communities doesn't lose sight of
the people for whom virtual friends may be the only kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've struck up an online friendship with a teenager afflicted
with severe cerebral palsy,'' he said. ``This is a person with no
other means of communicating with the outside world than punching
out messages into a keyboard with a stick on his head. Online has
widened his world.''
</P>
<P>
   For a scholarly look at how online technology has affected human
communities, Rheingold suggests a paper by Harvard University
sociologist William Galston  &LR; (www.ksg.harvard.edu/visions/ &LR; 
 &LR; galston.htm). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   David Farber, a University of Pennsylvania computer scientist
who publishes an influential online newsletter called ``Interesting
People,'' said most of his 25,000 subscribers have expressed
incredulity at the Carnegie-Mellon findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are online should poll others in their own personal
communities,'' he said. ``Ask them if they've seen more or less
loneliness or depression'' in their cyber circles.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; PowerBooked: &LR;  Apple Computer interim Chief Executive Steve
Jobs speaks at the Seybold publishing show at Moscone Center today.
Jobs, who always knows how to play to a crowd, is expected to tell
these Mac-loving folks that Apple will refresh its high-end
PowerBook line with three new systems based on the ultrafast G3
processor. The systems also will have 14.1-inch active-matrix
displays, faster bus speeds and memory caches to speed performance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
