<HEADER>
A1844 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPTIONS-SFCHRON &LR;      08-31 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPTIONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 As Stocks Skid, Tech Firms Examine Option Plans   By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
The stock market debacle of recent days could cause many Silicon
Valley companies to overhaul their stock-option programs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   High-tech workers traditionally receive the bulk of their pay in
stock options while accepting only modest salaries. But with stock
prices suddenly depressed, a lot of recently awarded option grants
have become worthless _ and if the bear market persists, they could
remain that way for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation experts say this could cause a lot of companies to
reprice their options _ reducing the exercise price at which
employees can buy stock.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Advanced Micro Devices, Netscape and Oracle all
have millions of options outstanding with exercise prices below
their current market prices.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, AMD granted its employees options on more than 3
million shares, at an exercise price of $37.50 per share. AMD
hasn't traded near that price in about a year; it closed yesterday
at $13.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape, which closed yesterday at $18, granted options on more
than 7 million shares last year at exercise prices ranging from
$26.38 to $47.88.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle issued more than 16 million shares worth of options last
year at exercise prices in the mid-$20s per share. Its stock closed
yesterday at $19.94.
</P>
<P>
   An AMD spokesman said the company, which last repriced its
options in December 1996, currently isn't considering it.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape and Oracle did not respond to requests for comment
about their stock-option plans.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are more or less forced to reprice their options if
they want to retain skilled workers in today's tight high-tech
labor market, notes Marty Katz, a compensation specialist with
William Mercer in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Carlson, chairman of Spectrum Economics in Palo Alto,
speculated that falling stock prices could lead to especially
serious labor problems at startup firms, where cash salaries are
practically nil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real threat is a downward death spiral for these
companies,'' he said. ``They could bleed to death as their
intellectual capital walks out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that might want to reprice their options currently are
under the gun because of a proposed ruling by the Financial
Accounting Standards Board.
</P>
<P>
   FASB wants to penalize companies that reprice their options by
forcing them to take a special charge against earnings. The charge
would be equal to the difference between the new exercise price and
any subsequent increase in the stock price, multiplied by the
number of shares for which options are granted.
</P>
<P>
   FASB won't put the rule into effect until it holds hearings and
solicits public comment. But sources say it wants to have the rule
apply to repricings that take place from 1999 onward.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley companies sometimes have repriced their options
even when the market was doing well. Occasionally, a company will
report disappointing earnings, its stock will tank and the board of
directors will respond by making it cheaper for employees to
exercise options.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer has repriced nine times, most recently in
December, when the stock was selling near its all-time low.
Employees were allowed to surrender their old options, most of them
priced well above the market, and receive new options that allowed
them to buy the stock at $13.69 per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employee retention was an issue, and the majority of options
were above the market price,'' says Nancy Paxton, Apple's director
of investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a great deal for the employees because the
stock soared as high as $43 last month. By yesterday's close, it
had been pummeled down to $31.19, but the option-holders still show
a fat profit of $17.50 per share.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Apple probably won't be repricing again anytime
soon, Paxton indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Some compensation specialists frown on repricings.
</P>
<P>
   Because employees with stock options pull in plenty of money
when the market is hot, they should ``take their lumps'' when the
market is cold, says Graef ``Bud'' Crystal, a nationally renowned
compensation expert who publishes the Crystal Report in San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
