<SLUG> BC-MUTUALFUND-BUZZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET DROPS HAVE MUTUAL FUND INVESTORS' PHONES RINGING OFF HOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Switchboards lit up at mutual fund companies
across the country as worried investors weighed their options in
reaction to the plunge of several stock indexes.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the markets closed Monday, investors' concerns were
well-founded. The nation's three most-watched indexes _ the Dow
Jones industrial average, the Nasdaq composite index and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index _ had each fallen by at least 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fund company officials characterized customer response as
concern, not panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a significant increase in telephone volume,'' said
Patrice Kozlowski, a spokeswoman at the Dryfus Corp. in New York.
``In the afternoon, the only redemptions we saw were those in
high-yield bonds but most of our investors looked at this afternoon
as a buying opportunity back into equities.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's bruising market activity increased calling volume by
about 20 percent at Kansas City, Mo.-based American Century
Investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the major dip, people were actually purchasing but as
the day wore on there were a lot of transfers from stock funds into
money market accounts. There were a few people that cashed out but
a majority of them did not,'' said spokesman Chris Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   Topped by Monday's sell-off, August did acheive a dubious
distinction: It was the first month in eight years that investors
took more money out of stock funds than they put in, according to
Santa Rosa, Calif.-based Trimtabs.com, which tracks 3,400 mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Trimtabs.com registered a preliminary net $1.9 billion outflow
from stock funds in August, compared with a $20.8 billion average
monthly inflow for the first seven months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Individual mutual funds are reporting similar results.
Baltimore-based T. Rowe Price said it recorded its first monthly
outflow from equity funds in five years, said spokesman Steven
Norwitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance, we've had a modest net outflow from equity funds.
All in all, investors are fairly concerned but we haven't seen
anything that resembles panic or people fleeing from stock funds,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Fidelity Investments anticipated Monday might be a
wild day so workers from other departments were drafted to work the
phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``As has been the case throughout the month of August, we saw
some investors moving more money from equities to more conservative
vehicles such as money market and bond funds. However, the vast
majority of our shareholders have chosen to stay still,'' said
spokeswoman Jessica Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was preoccupied with the Dow's plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Wanger, chief investment officer at the Chicago-based
Acorn Family of Funds, said that call volume at the company was
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing out of the ordinary. We had more calls relating
to two new mutual funds but nobody was worried about the market. I
think two people called that were worried about the market,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
