<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-MERCURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMETS SEEK FAST START IN FINALE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MELANIE HAUSER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The defending champion Houston Comets and the brash
Phoenix Mercury play for the Women's National Basketball
Association championship Tuesday night at the Compaq Center. Bring
combat boots, not a laptop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you thought Game 2 was a dogfight,'' Phoenix Coach Cheryl
Miller said, ``you haven't seen anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets' come-from-behind victory here on Saturday tied the
two-of-three-game championship series at 1-1. Trailing by 12 points
with seven minutes left, Houston came back and won 74-69 in
overtime to force the third game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to jump out and get a good start, which we haven't
done in the first two games,'' said Houston's Cynthia Cooper, the
two-time WNBA most valuable player, who scored 19 of her game-high
27 points after halftime Saturday. In Game 1 last Thursday, a
Comets comeback fell short in a 54-51 loss in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to play our game on offense and defense,'' Cooper
said. ``I just kept thinking about what it would have been like if
we'd played defense the way we did the last seven minutes for the
whole game. Or both games. If we do, it's going to be a long game
for them and a short one for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's star, forward Jennifer Gillom, likes her team's
chances. ``Us by 10, no less,'' she predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team will bill the game as a matchup of superstars, but
it's obvious that Gillom, who was held to 3-for-15 shooting in Game
2, has to be more involved in the offense for the Mercury to have a
chance. The Comets double- and triple-teamed her in a physical
battle under the basket on Saturday, but she's ready to fight back.
``It's going to be a war out there,'' Gillom said. ``Instead of me
taking it, I'm going to initiate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite winning 90 percent of their games in a 27-3 season and
sweeping Charlotte in the semifinals, the Comets entered the finals
with the pressure on them because the first game was at Phoenix.
Houston Coach Van Chancellor has tried to get his team to relax a
bit over the last two days so that the Comets will play their game,
not the one Phoenix has been forcing them into early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's dead even,'' he said. ``I think it's going to
come down to the last 30 seconds. One team will make a play, and
the other won't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
