<HEADER>
A1865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHURCH-DEMOLITION-     08-31 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHURCH-DEMOLITION-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO DEMOLISH CHURCH SPLITS PARISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN RATHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTER MORICHES, N.Y. _ When parishioners at St. John the
Evangelist Roman Catholic Church learned several months ago that
their bishop intended to demolish their 100-year-old church and
replace it with a larger one, they responded with both relief and
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Some welcomed a new church because for years parishioners have
had to celebrate Sunday Mass under basketball hoops in the gym of
an elementary school because their church has room for only 225
worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   Many others did not want to lose the old church. But the order
from Bishop John McGann of the Diocese of Rockville Centre,
spiritual head of Long Island's more than 1 million Roman
Catholics, was blunt: there was no way to expand the building _ a
Gothic Revival wood-frame structure with a stucco exterior and a
distinctive copper-clad steeple _ so it would have to be razed.
</P>
<P>
   For the diocese, the matter is elementary. The church is its
people, not its buildings, and what the people urgently need is an
adequate place to worship. This means a new building with room for
750 people in a parish that claims 5,000 member families. Moreover,
a new church could be designed to conform to the liturgical reforms
of Vatican II, bringing congregants closer to the altar.
</P>
<P>
   But even though diocesan officials found the merits of the plan
self-evident and St. John's pastor, Msgr. James McDonald,
vigorously supported it, the bishop's decree did not go down
easily.
</P>
<P>
   When some parishioners joined with preservationists to form a
committee to save the old church, what had been an issue in the
parish spilled noisily into a secular arena.
</P>
<P>
   The diocese turned down pleas that the old church be kept as a
chapel next to a new church. The committee reacted by asking the
Town of Brookhaven, where Center Moriches is situated, to designate
the building a historic landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Diocese officials immediately protested that any action by the
town to hinder the bishop's plans would be an affront to religious
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners on the committee, McDonald said, ``went to a
secular authority to go against their bishop, and that is not
acceptable in the Catholic Church.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, members of the Committee to Save St. John's are suing
the Town Board for refusing landmark status.
</P>
<P>
   The church was designed by Randolph Daus and built in 1898
around an altar originally in St. Augustine's Roman Catholic Church
of Brooklyn. That altar was designed by Patrick Keely, a noted
19th-century architect.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed Aug. 20 in state Supreme Court in Riverhead,
charges that six Roman Catholic members of the seven-member Town
Board, including Supervisor Felix Grucci Jr. and a councilman,
Edward Hennessey, a parishioner at St. John's, voted to deny
landmark status not on the merits of the case but to avoid being
branded ``ecclesiastical criminals'' by the diocese.
</P>
<P>
   It seeks a court order bestowing the landmark status or
requiring the town to hold a new hearing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The dispute with the Town Board dates to an emotional hearing on
the landmark designation held July 16, at which parishioners with
signs saying ``Obey the Bishop'' confronted parishioners carrying
signs saying ``Save St. John's.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, the diocese chancellor, Msgr. Francis Schneider,
told the board that under church law it was ``the obligation of
every Catholic, pastors and faithful alike, to adhere to decisions
of the bishop'' regarding ``when and where a new church will be
constructed'' and ``whether an existing church facility is to be
demolished or preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Disobedience is an ecclesiastical crime,'' Schneider told the
board members, ``and may be grounds for just punishment to foster
obedience.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the diocese, William Esseks, said that the
chancellor's statement had not been directed at the board. ``He was
talking to the people who were petitioning the board and who were
members of the parish,'' Esseks said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Patricia Strebel, the non-Catholic who cast the
lone vote for the landmark designation, and a board spokesman,
Kevin Molloy, also said religion had played no part in votes cast
by the other members. Hennessey said there had been no conflict
between his duties as a St. John's member and an elected official.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision dated four days after the hearing, the board
majority concluded that the church lacked the ``architectural and
artistic distinction'' of a landmark, partly because the structure
had received ``substantial alterations'' over the years, included
placing stucco over the church's original clapboard exterior.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why McGann will not allow the old church to remain as a
chapel, Joanne Novarro, a spokeswoman for the diocese, said: ``In
this diocese, the bishop has decided that we will have one place of
worship in each parish. And this is also about the cost of
maintaining more than one church.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Reid, a member of the Committee to Save St. John's,
said the committee had pledged $600,000 for maintenance of the old
church. A large portion of this would be donated by John Kanas, the
chairman and president of the North Fork Bank, who had attended the
church when he was growing up.
</P>
<P>
   Kanas confirmed that he had offered ``a substantial
contribution'' in a meeting with McGann and McDonald. ``They were
very courteous and they thanked me graciously,'' he said. ``But
they said there was no debate _ the church was going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parishioners, distressed by the July hearing and still in
favor of preserving the church, have left the parish. ``I can't be
a part of it,'' said one, Mary Maag, a legal secretary and lifelong
member of St. John's. ``It's just an awful situation. It's very
disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Town Planning Board hearing last Monday, only Reid and Mary
Field, a member of the committee but not the parish, opposed
approval of the site plan for the new church. They said they had
told others to stay away to avoid abuse from an audience that they
said was stacked in favor of the diocese position.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Armbruster, one of several parishioners who spoke in
favor of the diocese plan, told the board, ``The parish is the
people, not the building.''
</P>
<P>
   The board tentatively approved the site plan and granted a
parking variance. Part of the new parking lot will be where the old
church stood.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
