<HEADLINE>
HACKETT'S INFLUENCE SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thirty minutes into Paul Hackett's first game
Sunday, it was hard to tell that John Robinson still wasn't at the
helm of the USC football program.
</P>
<P>
   More disturbing than USC's 17-10 deficit was how it got to that
point. Mental miscues and a host of penalties _ like having 12 men
on the field _ were prevalent. The much-heralded defense allowed
Purdue to have the ball for all but two minutes of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Mediocrity, it seemed, had carried over for another season.
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett demonstrated he's no Robinson in the second half.
And because of that, USC is 1-0 after a 27-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It's not very difficult to see the changes Hackett has already
brought to the program:
</P>
<P>
   __He made a bold decision by playing quarterback Carson Palmer
in the third quarter. And despite the coach's cautious postgame
comments, the freshman provided the difference.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; !off! &LR; Hackett's commitment to conditioning paid off in
the stifling heat. USC was simply a stronger team than Purdue in
the second half. The players credited Hackett's new strength coach,
Matt ``Chickenhawk'' Schiotz, and it was hard to argue with the
results.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Trojans are not a significantly better team, they
will be better conditioned. That alone should quell some boosters,
who were tired of watching USC get beaten down in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   __The emphasis on special teams, led by new coach Shawn Slocum,
has already paid dividends. This year, USC begins practice by
working on special teams. Last year, it wasn't addressed until the
conclusion of practice.
</P>
<P>
   When Antuan Simmons broke through and blocked a Purdue field
goal, it might have been the first time Purdue's offense felt
frustrated Sunday. Chad Morton's 98-yard kickoff return and Adam
Abrams' two field goals, including a 45-yarder that was only a yard
short of his career best, were other highlights. Almost forgotten
was freshman punter Mike MacGillivray, who averaged 44.2 yards per
kick.
</P>
<P>
   __The Trojans were able to make adjustments at halftime. The
defense finally found its bearings after trying to get used to
Purdue's wide-open offense and regrouped nicely in the second half.
The failure to adjust was another major complaint about previous
regimes.
</P>
<P>
   How has this coaching staff been able to make changes?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of focusing on technical adjustments, it stressed
playing aggressively and cutting down on the miscues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't make the same mental mistakes in the second
half,'' defensive coordinator Bill Young said. ``It shows a little
maturity by the defensive players.''
</P>
<P>
   As first games go, survival might be the prime consideration.
Now that Hackett has done that, the bar will be raised, even if the
Trojans face San Diego State and Oregon State in their next two
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans still have some major problems _ the offensive line
to name one _ and will have difficulty with the elite teams on the
schedule. One game into the season, though, it's clear that
Hackett's decision-making skills paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer makes anyone look like a better coach. But does anyone
who watched John Fox play nearly the entire season before being
replaced last year believe a true freshman would have made his
debut this early under the previous staff?
</P>
<P>
   If there was a downside Sunday, it might have been Hackett
wasn't as bold at the tailback position. It's too bad freshman
Frank Strong didn't get a chance to play tailback, especially when
no one else was fooling Purdue's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The offense could still use a spark to compensate for its
overall lack of explosiveness, but wide receiver R. Jay Soward
returns for the next game.
</P>
<P>
   The big question during the next two weeks will be who throws
passes to Soward when USC takes the field again on Sept. 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
