</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO RUNS FIRST TV ADS IN SENATE RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 10 months of running a curiously quiescent
campaign for U.S. Senate, Geraldine Ferraro turned up the volume
Monday with her first two television advertisements, while her
opponents for the Democratic nomination, Mark Green and Rep.
Charles Schumer, spent the day touting their records on social
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Because the traditional start of all-out campaigning, Labor Day,
falls so late this year _ on Sept. 7 _ and the primary is just
eight days later, the candidates used the final day of August to
shake off the sluggishness of summer when the attention of most
voters is focused more on vacation than politics.
</P>
<P>
   Green, New York City's Public Advocate, appeared Monday
afternoon outside the midtown Manhattan offices of HIP, one of the
nation's largest managed care providers, to discuss his efforts to
regulate health maintenance organizations, and presented a 20-point
plan to do so.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour earlier, Schumer, the nine-term congressman from
Brooklyn, stood outside a midtown Manhattan police station and
stressed his support for increased federal money for shelters for
battered women. Flanked by women who run shelters, he said the
demand for space far exceeded the number of beds.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant development of the day was the introduction
of Ms. Ferraro's first television advertisements, two 30-second
spots that promote her experience as a mother, teacher, prosecutor
and congresswoman as qualifications that make her the best-suited
for the Senate. Aides said about $1 million was spent on the spots,
which are to run until primary day, Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who has been advertising heavily on television for
months, countered with what may be his most attention-grabbing
advertisement so far, a new 30-second clip in which he attacks the
``Senator Pothole'' reputation of the three-term Republican
incumbent, Alfonse D'Amato. The last scene takes a political poke
at D'Amato, showing an actor resembling the senator directing a
roadwork crew like an orchestra conductor.
</P>
<P>
   After criticizing D'Amato's voting record on crime, education
and health care, Schumer says sternly: ``He calls himself the
pothole Senator, but D'Amato's votes in Washington create thousands
of potholes here in New York. Then he fills a few near election
time, and he wants our vote?''
</P>
<P>
   All three of the Democratic candidates released information
Monday on their campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   The Green campaign said it had $1.1 million on hand, after
raising $240,000 in July and August and spending about the same
amount in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The Schumer campaign said it had $4.9 million in the bank, after
spending nearly $3 million and raising $630,000 in July and August.
</P>
<P>
   And the Ferraro campaign reported that she has $1.35 million on
hand, after raising $680,000 in July and August, including a
$300,000 personal loan she made to her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of three new advertisements seemed to confirm
expectations that the final days of the Democratic primary could
become a media war. Green is expected to begin his television
campaign this week.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shrum, the campaign consultant who developed Ms.
Ferraro's spots, said they would play a major role. ``New Yorkers
think they should have big and significant senators who can
accomplish big and significant things,'' he said. ``And I think
that's what people think about when they think about Gerry.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to noting Ms. Ferraro's experience, both of the
advertisements touch on many of the issues that polls have shown
are most on voters' minds now _ including hiring new teachers and
improving education, safeguarding the Social Security system and
protecting patients from the abuses of health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In a quick trip to Buffalo Monday afternoon, Ms. Ferraro touched
again on some of those issues during brief remarks at a shopping
center. In particular, she attacked D'Amato for accepting
contributions from the health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But she also tailored her message to some local concerns,
speaking out in favor of federal urban empowerment zones.
``Empowerment zones and enterprise communities are an effective way
to help New York's communities create jobs and prepare their work
force to take those jobs,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
