<SLUG> BC-NY-McCAUGHEY-ROSS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAUGHEY ROSS AND HUSBAND MEET ON CAMPAIGN'S FUTURE 
 (nk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wilbur Ross Jr., the investment banker who has been
financing the gubernatorial campaign of his wife, Lt. Gov. Betsy
McCaughey Ross, held a formal meeting with her on Monday night to
discuss the future of the campaign amid indications that he has
grown reluctant to give the campaign carte blanche, people close to
the campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Davitt, a spokesman for Ms. McCaughey Ross, said the
couple was having a routine dinner to talk about the campaign. But
people close to the campaign, who insisted on anonymity, described
it as more of a negotiating session between benefactor and
candidate than a conversation between husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Ms. McCaughey Ross, one of four Democrats
seeking the gubernatorial nomination, led her primary opponents in
the polls, and political strategists predicted a summertime
advertising blitz that would give her an even greater advantage.
She and some of her aides even talked of Ross spending $10 million
or more on the primary and the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor has a larger war chest than any of her
rivals: $2.6 million by Aug. 15. But most of the money has come
from Ross. And even as Ms. McCaughey Ross has fallen behind her
chief rival, Peter Vallone, in recent polls, she has spent hardly
any money, raising questions about whether Ross was really willing
to spend his money on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that Ms. McCaughey Ross is by far the best-known
Democrat in the race. But her three opponents all enjoy a generally
favorable reputation among the Democratic voters who know them,
while many more voters rate Ms. McCaughey Ross negatively than
positively. Supporters have been pressuring Ms. McCaughey Ross to
begin television advertising as the Sept. 15 primary nears, and
have become increasingly frustrated at her delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if she can get it together on television, that
she can very well be a success,'' said Stephen Sabbeth, the Nassau
County Democratic chairman, one of her strongest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Sabbeth said he thought Ross was not spending money because he
believed his wife could win the primary without it. But she will
probably persuade him to spend it anyway, Sabbeth said. ``Wilbur
Ross is a man of his word,'' he said. ``I don't think Wilbur wants
to pay for a landslide. But I think he'll spend what they need to
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
