<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NO MOONSHOTS IN MIAMI FOR McGWIRE  
(nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The sense of anticipation was certainly there. Every
time Mark McGwire batted Monday night, an unusually boisterous
Florida Marlins crowd booed and hooted when Marlins pitchers threw
him a pitch outside the strike zone. And they groaned when McGwire
made an out.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of groans by the end of the game, as McGwire
went 0-for-3 in the St. Louis Cardinals' 5-3 victory over the
Marlins at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After a pop-up, two strikeouts and two walks, McGwire still had
55 home runs _ six short of Roger Maris' record, with 25 games left
to play. And he had been tied by the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa, who
hit a home run in the fourth inning Monday night against
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins drew their fourth-largest crowd of the season _
36,584, about two-thirds of whom left after McGwire walked in the
top of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire came in knowing that he would represent the biggest
attraction of the Marlins' dismal season. ``I figured that out when
they said they were taking the tarps off up in the upper deck,'' he
said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 people were on hand just to watch him take
batting practice. He homered on nine of 20 pitches, with several of
them estimated to have traveled more than 500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``His biggest asset is that he has super powers of
concentration,'' Cardinals Manager Tony La Russa said of McGwire's
ability to deal with distractions surrounding the home run chase.
``He is concentrating on the things that mean the most to him.''
</P>
<P>
   When he is on the road, McGwire said, he sometimes uses several
friends in Los Angeles as sounding boards. Otherwise, he seems
content to listen to music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may think I'm a loner,'' he said. ``I'm not really
alone. I'm very content with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   His son Matthew, 10, is at many of his father's games _ he
sometimes flies in from San Diego to serve as a bat boy in Busch
Stadium _ and McGwire smiled as he anticipated his son's ``having
to miss some school'' as he gets closer to Maris' record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can spend a lot of time with your son at the ball
park, it's very, very special,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
