<HEADLINE>
KISS-AND-TELL TALE HAS EDITORS ABUZZ  
 ACCIDENTAL TOURIST  
 DELICIOUS ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two million dollars for a book by Monica Lewinsky? ``Not
exactly,'' book editor Judith Regan said Monday. ``And that's all
I'm going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she went on to say a lot more, calling herself ``a
great defender of Monica Lewinsky'' and calling Bill Clinton ``that
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The fuss began when The New Yorker magazine reported that Ms.
Regan, who has edited best sellers by Howard Stern, Kathie Lee
Gifford and Drew Barrymore, had offered $2 million. But the
magazine also said she had been topped by a $6 million deal from
another publisher, which it did not identify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how this gets started,'' Ms. Regan said. ``It's
like a game of telephone. The story gets bigger and bigger, as do
the numbers being bandied about.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear her tell it, the big-money days for book deals ended
long before the stock market's 512-point plunge on Monday. They
ended when so many books about the O.J. Simpson case fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that any publisher is going to offer her $10
million for the book rights,'' she said of Ms. Lewinsky. ``They'd
have to sell millions of copies in hardcover, which doesn't happen
anymore for anybody, not Tom Clancy, not Anne Rice.''
</P>
<P>
   What goes through an author's mind when someone hands the
president his book? ``Just when you think you've used your
imagination, reality has a way of catching up to you,'' said
Richard North Patterson, whose political thriller ``No Safe Place''
was given to President Clinton last week on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Accidental Tourist
</P>
<P>
   This sounds like a wild and crazy, but stylish, movie. Diane Von
Furstenberg missed the plane to the boat because she was in a car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   She was driving to a New York-area airport on Friday _ her
spokeswoman, Ruth Patkin, would not say which airport or where the
accident took place _ when it happened. Miss von Furstenberg had
been scheduled to fly to Alaska to join several hundred other
passengers on a cruise ship chartered by Paul Allen, a co-founder
of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she suffered broken ribs, cuts and bruises, and was
taken to a hospital, Ms. Patkin said. ``Diane was concerned that if
she was at all out of commission, people would think she's sick,''
Ms. Patkin said, ``and she's not.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what Miss von Furstenberg missed on the cruise, she could
have chatted with Candice Bergen, James Cameron or Dan Aykroyd,
among others. Or she could have braved 70 mph winds on deck.
</P>
<P>
   Delicious Romance
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first anniversary of the death of Diana, Princess
of Wales, and Dodi Fayed on Monday was just another day at the
Diana-Dodi delicatessen, on Second Avenue near East 13th Street.
The proprietor, Rahman Abdelnaser, was behind the counter of the
3-month-old deli, making coffee and sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had chosen the name because ``their story, it touched
me.'' But he did not go so far as to name anything on the sandwich
menu above the counter after them. A ``Princess Pastrami'' or a
``Dodi Deviled Ham'' would be, well, unseemly. ``I don't want to
use their name for that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the deli's name has not won unanimous approval from
customers. ``Some complain I'm cashing in'' on Diana's death, he
said. ``To cash in, you need T-shirts and things like that. This is
just a little store. Is anyone going to come here just because of
the name?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, maybe not. This much is certain, though: Diana-Dodi is on
an international block. Next door is a restaurant called Little
Poland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980831.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
