u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-TAX-PLAN-750(2TAKE     08-31 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TAX-PLAN-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SEES MANY WAYS TO REDUCE PROPERTY TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ The state Property Tax Commission, created by
Gov. Christie Whitman after her narrow re-election victory last
fall, has agreed on dozens of recommendations intended to lower
real-estate taxes in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   At the governor's request, the commission did not consider
statewide tax increases to offset property-tax bills, but panel
members said one proposal would give the state's largest cities and
towns new taxing authority.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of relying on property levies alone, municipalities
might be able to raise revenue by taxing parking, payrolls, hotels
or even entertainment and sporting events. The recommendation would
require approval by the state Legislature, where word of the
proposal has already met with some skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is also expected to recommend placing a cap on the
salaries of school, municipal and county employees, a proposal
guaranteed to draw strong union opposition. Other suggestions
include state incentives for local governments to share services
and having the state pick up the $200 million cost of New Jersey's
21 county prosecutor offices.
</P>
<P>
   During her hard-fought campaign last year, Whitman vowed to
tackle the issue after polls showed that voters did not think she
had answered their concerns about paying the highest property taxes
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-member panel, made up of local and state government
officials, as well as business and academic leaders, is expected to
outline its recommendations to Whitman early in September. Many of
the suggestions would require legislative action, panel members
said.
</P>
<P>
   While some panel members said there was no single suggestion
that would immediately deliver significant property-tax relief,
they also said that the recommendations, taken together, could
reduce property-tax bills over time.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is expected to point out that New Jersey's
longstanding tradition of home rule, including the reluctance of
communities and school districts to share costs and control, is one
of the biggest reasons property-tax bills are so high. The report
notes the hundreds of layers of local government: 566 municipal
governments, 21 county governments, 188 fire districts and 611
school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no easy answers,'' said Barbara Cannon, the mayor of
Old Bridge Township and chairwoman of the commission. ``Nothing is
simple. There are going to have to be some choices made here.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible solution was off limits, at Whitman's request: a
statewide tax increase. ``We did not want to increase the state's
overall tax burden,'' Ms. Cannon said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jerseyans pay the highest per-capita property taxes in the
nation. The average property-tax bill for homeowners is $4,000 a
year, with public schools taking the largest chunk of that money.
The state covers about 40 percent of the cost of local schools; the
national average of state assistance to public schools is 50
percent of the total cost.
</P>
<P>
   Although some experts say that significantly increasing state
aid, particularly to schools, would be the most direct way to
reduce local property taxes, New Jersey voters have already voiced
their disapproval of that approach.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Jim Florio was widely criticized for pushing through
a state income-tax increase in 1990 to bolster state assistance for
local schools and provide property-tax relief. He lost his
re-election campaign four years later to Whitman, who promised to
roll back the income-tax rate increases. She kept her promise in
her first term, but critics contend that she helped pay for part of
the tax cut by not increasing state aid to municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering specific suggestions, the commission's
recommendations are intended to raise awareness among taxpayers of
the cost of various programs and policy decisions, particularly
those concerning land use.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is expected to issue a warning to municipalities about
the high cost of some new development projects. For years, cities
and towns embraced development to expand their property-tax bases,
but the panel notes that unchecked development can often end up
adding to the tax burden.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is also expected to urge municipalities to follow the
state's master development plan when making land-use decisions. The
plan is an attempt to guide growth away from environmentally
sensitive and rural areas to parts of the state with existing roads
and sewers that can support new development.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since many of the commission's recommendations would require
action by the state Legislature, some lobbying groups, including
the state's largest teachers union, are already preparing for
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Joseph, a spokeswoman for that union, New Jersey Education
Association, said the association did not think that the best
approach to lowering property taxes was capping public employees'
salaries, as the panel suggests. ``We would be opposed to such a
move,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It remains uncertain which recommendations are likely to win the
backing of state lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a silver-bullet solution to this,'' said
Assemblyman Richard Bagger, R-Westfield, chairman of the Assembly
Appropriations and Budget Committee. ``It is a combination of a lot
of different ideas. But I am a dedicated incrementalist. And I am
very confident that there will be a series of proposals that the
Legislature can act upon and that will have some positive benefits
for property taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Joseph Roberts Jr., a Democrat who has been long
involved in state fiscal matters, said he agreed with some of the
recommendations that have been made public, particularly those
urging local governments and school districts to consolidate some
services. ``I have tried to keep an open mind until I see a final
document,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Roberts, whose legislative district includes the troubled
city of Camden, said he was concerned about the recommendation that
would allow cities and large municipalities to impose new taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A few cities _ Newark, Elizabeth, and Jersey City _ already have
authorization from the state Legislature to impose some levies
beyond property taxes, including payroll and parking taxes. The
recommendation would allow those cities to expand their taxing
authority and enable other large municipalities to impose new
taxes. In some cases municipalities may look to shift the burden
from residents to people who work or visit but who do not live
there.
</P>
<P>
   Newark's mayor, Sharpe James, said that he welcomed the
recommendation because it would give cities more flexibility and
help relieve the tax burden on residential-property owners.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, James said that Newark and other cities had to
be careful about not imposing any taxes that would hurt the city's
economic development efforts.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Joseph Kyrillos, R-Middletown Township, a member of
the Senate budget committee, said that the property-tax problem was
similar in some ways to the automobile-insurance problem. The
Legislature finally approved a package of bills earlier this year
that was intended to lower auto-insurance rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``With auto insurance, you had to change the product to change
the cost,'' Kyrillos said. ``With property taxes, we may not be
able to afford all the government that we now have. We are going to
have to make some real choices, and hopefully, people will allow us
and encourage us to make those types of choices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
