<HEADLINE>
SEVENTH TV NETWORK DEBUTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY ALEX ROTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just moments before air time on the set of ``Great
Day America'' and the premiere of the newest TV network in America,
a crew member barked into her headset, ``Susan has the puppy! I
repeat, Susan has the puppy!''
</P>
<P>
   The puppy was a golden Labrador retriever guide dog. And
co-anchor Susan Crenshaw, who was doing a segment on foster homes
for guide dogs, had the envious job of cuddling the animal in her
lap.
</P>
<P>
   The puppy was a perfect guest for the debut of ``Great Day
America,'' a late-afternoon talk show that aims to be cute and
entertaining but also informative.
</P>
<P>
   Other than a brief Teleprompter malfunction and a slightly
off-color anecdote by actor Rod Steiger, Monday's show went off
without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a camera briefly during rehearsal, but hey, it's the
first show,'' said co-anchor Michael Young, the former host of the
1970s show ``Kids Are People Too.''
</P>
<P>
   The live debut Monday at Universal Studios in Los Angeles of
``Great Day America'' also marks the launch of the nation's seventh
TV network, Pax TV.
</P>
<P>
   With programming ranging from a talk show on women's issues to
reruns of ``Touched by an Angel,'' the network is promoting itself
as a family-oriented alternative to its larger, more mainstream
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The network is going to fill a niche that's been kind of
vacated by family programming,'' Pax TV spokesman John Michaeli
said. ``There's not a lot of programming the entire family can
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, the network faces the challenge of altering the
public's notoriously deep-rooted television-viewing habits. And
with literally hundreds of cable channels to compete against, the
network could easily fall through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Day America'' will mix celebrity interviews with feature
segments on such topics as home decoration and health. Its target
audience is primarily women, whose other late-afternoon choices are
cartoons, game shows and the blood-and-guts of television news.
</P>
<P>
   The show is filmed in Universal Studio's former Roman Noodle
restaurant, which has been converted into a studio. The format is
loosely patterned after the ``Today'' show, down to the tourists
who can gawk at the taping through a window facing the studio lot.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday's show, guest Steiger discussed his battle with
depression. The 73-year-old actor was joined by a psychiatrist who
offered depression-warning signs and tips about treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Other segments included advice on inexpensive home decorating, a
feature on educational family vacation spots and an interview with
a Utah couple who have written 16 books on parenting.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, Richard and Linda Eyre, have nine children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had the ninth one first, she'd be an only child,''
Richard Eyre told the national audience.
</P>
<P>
   Studio officials were cautiously optimistic, although they admit
it's hard to tell whether the show _ and the network _ will
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a start-up network,'' Universal Studios Vice President
Kac Young said. ``There could be four people watching; there could
be four million. You never know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
