u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CLINTON-FORUM-445&AMP;     08-31 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-FORUM-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT NEW YORK UNIVERSITY: CLINTONS, GORES AND MINI-U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In what is shaping up as a remarkable lineup of
domestic and foreign leaders at New York University, President
Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton have agreed to lead a day of
discussions on the global economy at a conference later this month,
with guests including the prime ministers of Britain and Italy, the
White House said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is also likely to attend the daylong
session at the NYU School of Law, a White House official said on
condition of anonymity. University officials said the event would
be a historic concentration of political power in Greenwich
Village.
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 21 event coincides with the opening session of the
U.N. General Assembly, which accounts for the university's success
in drawing other heads of government to Clinton's afternoon
discussion. The law school dean, John Sexton, is a longtime friend
of the president and Mrs. Clinton, which in part accounts for the
Clintons' agreement to appear.
</P>
<P>
   The conference promises to be a notable moment even for this
president. Although Clinton has repeatedly demonstrated an affinity
for extended discussions of policies with scholars _ this one will
go at least 90 minutes, Sexton said _ it is the first time he has
attempted something like this with a panel of foreign dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   It also promises to be a notable moment for the NYU School of
Law, which is sponsoring the forum, titled ``Strengthening
Democracy in the Global Economy.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, a group of its students, selected
by lottery, and faculty members will in the space of the day
witness a morning seminar led by the first lady, a luncheon speech
by Gore, and an afternoon discussion of international affairs with
a panel that is to include Clinton, Prime Minister Tony Blair of
Britain and Romano Prodi, the prime minister of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Canada, Brazil, Bulgaria, Sweden and the
Netherlands also have been asked to attend, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The conference promises to be interesting for both political and
logistical reasons. As a rule, the General Assembly's opening
sessions, with their influx of foreign dignitaries, motorcades and
security details, bring traffic tie-ups and disruption to the
streets and sidewalks around the United Nations. The conference
promises to extend that confusion to Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that the Clintons will be attending the same
conference, though not necessarily appearing together, during a
time of public scrutiny of their private life could mean an unusual
amount of attention to a conference devoted to the arguably dry
theme of global economics and politics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whatever the case, White House and NYU officials said they were
delighted with the way the conference was shaping up. University
officials said it would draw attention to the new Global Law School
Program, which is devoted to the study of how democratic
governments have been affected by the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton's aides said it would give the president a chance to
be spotlighted talking about policy.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the discussions will be open to about 275 people,
including the students, faculty members and outside guests invited
by the university. ``We are aiming for a sizable group of people
from the general intellectual, business and labor community,'' said
Norman Dorsen, the chairman of the Global Law School Program.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the audience will be allowed to ask questions or make
comments, either by passing the questions forward on sheets of
paper or by going to an open microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton will lead the morning forum, which will be called
``Civil Society and the Future of Democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The president will lead the afternoon forum, which will be a
general discussion by the government leaders on themes that were
raised during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the president will talk about _ your guess is as good as
mine, if I may be only slightly facetious,'' Dorsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's communications aide, Sidney Blumenthal, said the
president's discussion would be devoted to ``strengthening
democracy in the world economy; globalization; everything from a
civil society to how you create more opportunity for people in the
new economy; how you respond to new realities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been an event like this,'' Blumenthal said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
