<P>
   MARKET-BROKERS (New York) _ Wall Street is starting to count the
cost of the recent turmoil in financial markets. Salomon Smith
Barney, one of the country's biggest investment banks, said on
Monday that in the last two months alone, it lost an estimated $360
million after taxes, in its arbitrage and Russian-related credits
businesses. After allowing for profits from its private client and
funds management business, Salomon said that it expected its
overall after-tax loss for the last two months to be about $150
million. Such losses may spell the end of a long run of bountiful
profits for Wall Street, a time when stocks, financial markets and
the fortunes of financiers have risen inexorably. By Peter Truell.
