<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TURANDOT (Beijing) _ Staging of the opera epic Turandot in
the Forbidden City, the very setting Puccini imagined for his
Orientalist fantasy of an icy princess who succumbs to love. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   ARTISTS-NATURE (Paris) _ Arts Abroad: Ever since cave painters
began sketching horses, bison, elephants and the like, artists have
wrestled with the relationship between man and nature. Fast-forward
20,000 years to the rural and maritime landscapes and the
still-life oils of the post-Renaissance and the question remains
unchanged. How should art respond to nature? A show in Paris has
advanced the debate. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CLINTON-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Add yet another count to the
accumulation of misdemeanors being assembled against President
Clinton: He has incited a flurry of moralizing by television
journalists, who have enrolled themselves among the victims. Yes,
there is whining from reporters that they have been compelled to
devote themselves to Monica Lewinsky when they are longing to cover
Boris Yeltsin. A critic's notebook by Walter Goodman.
</P>
