<HEADLINE>
REPORTER AT NEW YORK TIMES TO RECEIVE AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A reporter for The New York Times has won the 1998
John Chancellor Award for Excellence in Journalism, the Annenberg
Public Policy Center at the University of Pennsylvania plans to
announce on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   John Kifner, 56, now a metropolitan reporter for The Times, won
for the body of his work, for both foreign and domestic reporting.
The Annenberg School for Communication, which administers the
award, cited his ability to translate ``complicated changes in the
political, economic and cultural landscape for American readers.''
</P>
<P>
   In more than 30 years at The Times, Kifner covered the Iranian
revolution, the Persian Gulf War and the assassination of Yitzhak
Rabin. He also covered the 1968 Democratic convention, the Kent
State shootings, the busing crisis in Boston and the Oklahoma City
bombing. He won two George Polk Awards, most recently in 1989 for
his coverage of the Palestinian uprising.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-member committee of journalists and others chose the
winner. Sander Vanocur, a veteran television journalist, said, ``We
wanted to honor a working reporter who was still slugging it out _
who gives you facts over punditry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nelson, chief Washington correspondent of The Los Angeles
Times, said, ``I've had to compete against him; I know he's
hard-hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   The award is given in honor of John Chancellor, the NBC
television correspondent and anchor who died in 1996, and it will
be presented at a dinner in Philadelphia on Oct. 21. It carries a
$25,000 prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
