<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGEL WELCOMES MARCHERS BUT NOT LEADER TO HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Navigating the treacherous political waters of the
Million Youth March, U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel of Harlem on Monday
urged his constituents to welcome the young marchers, but he
criticized the event's organizers and praised Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani for his handling of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been critical of Khalid Abdul Muhammad, the
march's driving force, Rangel has been restrained on the issue of
the march itself. But with Muhammad having won a court battle last
week allowing the march, and with the date of the rally _ this
Saturday _ fast approaching, he said he saw the need to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show support for the young people without in any
way showing support for those that convened the march,'' Rangel
said in front of City Hall. ``We're just not prepared to allow
racists and bigots to chase us off our streets.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments on the march and Muhammad echoed remarks that
some other black leaders have been making for weeks. Many have
found themselves in a delicate position of not wanting to alienate
the thousands of young people expected to attend the rally, while
at the same time trying to distance themselves from Muhammad's
anti-Semitic, anti-white rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani has been accused of indirectly helping to
energize the event by calling it a ``hate march,'' Rangel praised
Giuliani, saying he had shown admirable restraint in being ``so
quiet about this march.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor returned the compliment Monday by exempting only
Rangel from another round of criticism of black leaders who he said
had failed to speak out loudly enough against the march.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would only hope that there would be more courage and more of
a willingness to stand up against hatred by the political
leadership,'' Giuliani said, ``and so far, the only one who's
unequivocally done that is Charlie Rangel, to his great credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, responding to reporters' questions, repeated his
criticisms of Muhammad and the march, saying that it was ``probably
a way of self-aggrandizing on the basis of hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's latest comments annoyed some black leaders who have
criticized both Muhammad and Giuliani for being inflammatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I counted 17 venues in the last three weeks where I have
denounced Khalid Muhammad's rhetoric, on television, on black
radio, and on the BBC if the mayor was tuning into that,'' said
state Sen. David Paterson, D-Harlem. ``The difference between
Rangel and I is that I've been raising issues about the mayor's
conduct in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who supports the march, said that he and
other religious leaders _ even some who oppose the march _ have
been planning ways to accommodate it. He said that Rangel was
simply acknowledging what is already happening. ``I think he sees a
tremendous mobilization among mainstream Harlem and I think that
makes him understand that this is not a hate march and never was,''
Sharpton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
