<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NEWCOMERS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GENERATION OF AMERICAN MEN FINDS WAYS TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Following in the sneakerprints of Pete Sampras, Andre
Agassi, Jim Courier and Michael Chang has the potential to be a
very thankless task. But Monday at the U.S. Open, several members
of the latest, if probably not greatest, generation of American
men's tennis players managed to prosper at the expense of visitors
from foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   There was Bob Bryan making his U.S. Open singles debut and
outlasting Marcus Ondruska of South Africa in five sets and nearly
four hours. There was Bryan's teammate at Stanford, Paul Goldstein,
getting his first Open victory at the expense of Australian Andrew
Ilie.
</P>
<P>
   There was also Taylor Dent, who turned professional this week at
age 17. Dent won his first three-of-five-set match without having
to flirt with the limit after his opponent, German qualifier Alex
Radulescu, defaulted early in the third set with a stomach ailment
evidently caused by antibiotics he had taken for a respiratory
infection. Dent was leading by 4-6, 7-5, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to be 1-0,'' said Dent, the son of former
Australian professional Phil Dent.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Dent is 1-0 with an asterisk, his father/coach was
pleased as well. ``I think for the first time out there in a big
event, he played well,'' Phil Dent said. ``He was composed: a lot
of good stuff. I would have liked for the match to continue because
it's good experience for him. But he'll get another match now.''
</P>
<P>
   So will Bryan and Goldstein, who both are friendly with
Stanford's most prominent undergraduate of the moment, Chelsea
Clinton, and who both reached the National Collegiate Athletic
Association singles final on May 31 in Athens, Ga. Though Goldstein
was the No. 1 player on Stanford's championship team and Bryan was
No. 3, the pecking order did not hold true in Athens. Bryan won the
title in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's only other loss in college this season came to
Bryan's twin brother, Mike, in a tournament in Los Angeles in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Mike was in the sunlit stands at Court 7 as his brother
rallied from a two-set deficit to defeat Ondruska, 3-6, 6-7 (5-7),
6-1, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Ondruska, who turned professional in 1989, has been plying his
trade long enough to have experienced plenty of five-set matches.
But for Bryan, this was a first, and his body was not about to let
him forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I'm going to feel tomorrow, but I think it's
going to feel like I played a whole tournament,'' he said after
experiencing shivering and numbness and leg cramping in the match's
final stages.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan still had enough energy to break the inconsistent Ondruska
at 4-4 in the fifth set and save a break point on his serve in the
final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother and I have been in the doubles here before, so that
took some of the nervousness away,'' Bryan said. ``But even if
we've been around here for four years, it's great to win the first
singles match.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Bryans turned professional in June after making the
difficult decision to leave Stanford following their sophomore
year. When they were young junior players, their parents
discouraged them from facing each other in tournaments, and the
twins would take turns defaulting when they reached finals. They
have stopped defaulting in recent years, and their singles record
against each other is a very brotherly 8-8. But only Bob earned a
wild card into the main singles draw of the Open, courtesy of his
NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein also received a wild card, and his match against the
gifted Ilie was very much a wild ride. After splitting sets, Ilie
began suffering visibly early in the third set, serving underhand
at 2-2 and vomiting on court two games later. He also began
experiencing cramps in his right hand, and at 3-4 he began
switching his racquet to his left hand. He later hit an overhead
with both hands on the grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my chances if he's switch-hitting,'' Goldstein said
after Ilie had defaulted with Goldstein leading, 6-7, 7-6, 6-4,
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein probably likes his chances less against another
natural right-hander in the second round. The right-hander's name?
Sampras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
