r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON &LR;      08-31 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 What to Do If the Works Isn't Enough   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
Q: The IBM Aptiva PC I bought last summer came loaded with
Microsoft Works (oxymoron!). I've been using it in my job as a
consultant, but it isn't easy to make labels, create databases and
perform mail merges. I am thinking about replacing Works with Word
or Office. Which would you suggest?
<TEXT>
<P>
   A: To be fair, Works isn't a heavy-duty program designed for
business use. It's just an integrated suite that includes a basic
word processor, database and spreadsheet. It will do the things you
require but not as well or as efficiently as a full-fledged office
suite.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Word by itself won't solve your problem. You need to
get the Professional Edition of Microsoft Office, which includes
Word as well as Access, a really good database program. You also
might consider two other options, the professional version of the
Corel WordPerfect Suite or the Lotus SmartSuite. They also have all
the weapons any consultant could ask for. Personally, I'd probably
opt for the Microsoft suite because it's so widely used. You can
send a Word document by e-mail and be fairly confident that the
recipient also will have Word.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a Windows PC with Netscape. When Macintosh users send
me graphics files as e-mail attachments, I can't use them. I can't
save the files, and Netscape won't open them in its mail program.
And sometimes, the attachments just come as garble inside the
message itself. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   A: Macs use a different method than PCs to encode e-mail for
transmission across the Internet. However, newer versions of
Netscape are equipped to decode the Mac system, which is called
BinHex. So under normal circumstances, you should be able to open
and read attachments.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Netscape tell me that your symptoms suggest that
the attachment either was improperly coded by the sending computer
or was corrupted during its trek through an Internet gateway.
</P>
<P>
   One possible solution is to ask senders to use MIME _ rather
than BinHex _ if their e-mail program supports it. MIME is the
standard Internet protocol and the method used most often in
sending messages between PCs.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, you might try asking the sender to
manually encode the graphic using UUencode before attaching it to
the message. They'll need a special utility for that, and you will,
too, because you'll have to decode the graphic when it arrives.
Fortunately, Uuencoding utilities are widely available as
shareware.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter has a 486-DX running at 33 megahertz with 8
megabytes of RAM and a 700-Mbyte hard drive. It's running Windows
3.1. Would this system support Windows 95 or Windows 98? And if
not, would you recommend upgrading or would you recommend a newer
system?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, your trusty old machine is too underpowered for
Windows 95 or Windows 98, both of which need a Pentium-class chip
and at least 16 megs of memory to perform adequately. To bring your
system up to par, you'd have to add memory, upgrade the chip, get a
bigger hard drive and add a CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   A total face-lift like that would run at least $600. You'd
probably be better off just buying a new system. For $800, you
should be able to find one with a 266 MHz chip, 32 megs of memory,
a 4-gigabyte hard drive and a 24x CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend of mine is producing a newsletter and brochures for
a community group and wants to make some backup files. However,
documents like the newsletter are too big to fit on a floppy disk.
The person doesn't have a Zip drive. So what are the options,
besides splitting the newsletter into five different documents?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your best bet is to compress the document using a zipping
utility. I was able to take a 2-Mbyte newsletter created on
Microsoft Publisher and get it down to less than 500,000 bytes by
using Zip-IT, a $39.95 program from Quarterdeck. The amount of
compression will depend on the kind of files you're dealing with _
some graphical images can be reduced by more than 90 percent! If
you're looking for a good shareware zipping program, try WinZip, a
perennial favorite.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &QC;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Create a Startup Disk for Windows 95 or Windows 98. If your hard
drive fails, you can use the disk to start your computer, diagnose
and fix common hard disk problems. Go to the Windows Control Panel,
open the Add/Remove Programs icon, tab over to Startup Disk and
follow the instructions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
