<HEADER>
A2069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-2NDLD-     08-31 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS AND HINGIS ZIP THROUGH FIRST ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for insert in Match Points section.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Pete Sampras is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(lh) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Start spreading the news: Pete Sampras is feeling
historic, Martina Hingis is feeling acquisitive and Goran
Ivanisevic is feeling like the turbo-charged hardcourts at the U.S.
Open are delivering his aces almost faster than he can send them
across the net.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to the U.S. Open, which cranked itself up to full speed
Monday at the National Tennis Center in Flushing Meadows, Queens,
to cut through the late summer haze and cut right to the chase. The
top-ranked Sampras, now just six victories from a record-tying 12th
Grand Slam title, and the top-ranked Hingis both zipped through
their opening-day assignments in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   And Ivanisevic was feeling invincible, at least for a New York
moment, in the same city where he had been paralyzed by first-round
ineptitude in three of his last four visits.
</P>
<P>
   Those who could handle the pace advanced; those who let jitters,
or the invisible flu bug that has been circulating through the
men's and women's locker rooms, undermine their energy level fell
by the wayside early. Justin Gimelstob of New Jersey and Andrew
Ilie of Australia, who are both subject to temper tantrums, were
downed by tempestuous cramps and defaulted. So was German qualifier
Alex Radulescu, who pointed miserably to his stomach as he went to
the net to concede prematurely to 575th-ranked Taylor Dent, the
17-year-old wild card who is the youngest man in the event.
</P>
<P>
   After getting through his first match unscathed, Sampras, who
gained his 11th Grand Slam title by downing Ivanisevic in the
Wimbledon final in July, could afford to be sympathetic to those
who did not handle the Open's opening day pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understand that this Slam, compared to all the rest, I think,
is the most hectic,'' said Sampras, a four-time Open champion,
after his untaxing 6-3, 6-3, 6-2 victory over Marc-Kevin Goellner
kept him on the road to tying Roy Emerson's record of 12 Grand Slam
singles titles. ``You walk out at Wimbledon, you feel kind of the
charm of the place. Here at Flushing, you just kind of feel a
certain electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of hoopla when you play here in New York, and this
one certainly is difficult to win, but I've been playing here
enough to kind of figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, whose precocity is unquestioned, figured the place out
at the age of 17, when she won the third of her 1997 Grand Slam
crowns by outwitting Venus Williams in the final at the brand-new
Arthur Ashe Stadium. On Monday, Hingis, who is making a title
defense here a priority after stalling in the semifinals at the
French Open and Wimbledon, was back inside the stadium, and back to
her old supremely confident self after trampling Aleksandra Olsza
of Poland, 6-2, 6-0, in just under an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely not as confident as I was last year, but this
year wasn't as bad as sometimes I hear on TV, that Martina Hingis
was so beatable,'' protested Hingis, whose last title was at the
Italian Open in May. ``Well, not by everybody, I wouldn't lose
against a nobody. Once you keep losing, one day you get sick of it,
so I am kind of moving up again. So far I haven't lost against
anybody who wasn't top 10, so it's OK.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hingis, who will face unseeded Iva Majoli, the 1997 French Open
champion, in the second round, denied that she had lost her
appetite for winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the Grand Slams, I won the first one, and this
one is still open,'' Hingis said. ``It's the last one of the year,
so you're going to put all your energy into this tournament. I'm
very positive, and I'm in a good mood now.'' She described herself
as the ``black horse'' last year, who sneaked up on the rest of the
field and ``won almost everything I played.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic, who won almost nothing he played this year until he
rediscovered his serving prowess at Wimbledon, left that tournament
a broken man after failing, for the second time in his career, to
get the better of Sampras in a Wimbledon final. He said he felt
like killing himself, but instead he took a boating vacation,
showed up in the United States on schedule for his summer campaign
and reached the final at New Haven, Conn., before his serving arm
went haywire again. But the arm and the man were back in form
Monday. With 23 aces, the Croatian Ivanisevic found safe mooring in
the second round after an acrimonious 6-3, 6-4, 6-4 defeat of
32-year-old Mark Woodforde of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Miffed that Woodforde, who had previously characterized the
14th-seeded Ivanisevic as a one trick pony with a big serve and
little else, failed to apologize after smacking him with a ball,
Ivanisevic later praised his own serve and denigrated his
opponent's entire game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my serve is there, then anything else I want to hit is
going in,'' he said. ``The way his game is, man, I think it's time
for him to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to emulate the example her older sister Venus set here
last year, 20th-ranked Serena Williams made a successful Open debut
despite being hobbled by a sore right hamstring midway through her
6-3, 3-6, 6-4 defeat of 94th-ranked Nicole Pratt of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old Williams squandered a pair of match points with
a wildly careering volley and a net-bound backhand before breaking
Pratt for her first Open victory. She later called it ``a case of
classic nerves.'' Made aware that her father and coach, Richard,
who was attending his first Grand Slam event with his daughters,
had attracted attention by exiting the Louis Armstrong Stadium in
the second set, Serena Williams played down the effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, my dad always said negative attention is better than no
attention, so long as the truth lives inside of us,'' she said.
``If I was in the crowd and saw someone playing the way I was
playing, I would have left, too; I don't think I played that
well.''
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS:
</P>
<P>
   The day session proved disastrous for just one seeded player,
15th-seeded Alberto Berasategui of Spain, who ran out of resilience
after the first set's tie breaker against Thomas Muster of Austria
and wound up wilting, 7-6 (7-1), 6-2, 6-3. ``I cannot really say
I'm afraid going out against anyone,'' said the 30-year-old,
30th-ranked Muster, who terrorized all comers back in 1995 when he
won the French Open but has never passed the U.S. Open's
quarterfinal round. ... Monica Seles, at her first Open since her
father/coach, Karolj, died of cancer, had a victorious evening. The
two-time Open champion Seles may be more welcome at Flushing
Meadows, where she is seeded sixth, than downtown at the New York
Stock Exchange, where she turned up Monday by invitation and rang
the bell that opened a horrendous day of trading. After a slow
start against 55th-ranked Florencia Labat, Seles turned on the
power and advanced, 7-6 (7-0), 6-2. ... After a career crisis that
sent his ranking plummeting to 141st last year, Andre Agassi's
season of resurgence sent him into the Open seeded eighth and
fixated on ending a three-year Grand Slam drought. Monday night the
28-year-old Agassi, the 1994 Open champion, ignited this year's
campaign with a 6-4, 6-1, 6-4 demolition of 75th-ranked Sebastien
Grosjean of France. ... Mirjana Lucic, the 16-year-old Croat,
eliminated Kristie Boogert of the Netherlands, 6-3, 6-2. ... Justin
Gimelstob, who said he had been diagnosed with anemia, was leading
his match with Wayne Black 6-3, 5-7, 3-2 when he was overcome by
cramps and had to default. ``I just started locking up
everywhere,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
