<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-LABOR-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR LOATH TO OPPOSE A POPULAR GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ About this time in election years, the political
gears of New York's powerful labor unions begin turning _ grinding
out mailings, setting up phone banks, organizing rallies and
issuing endorsements. In statewide elections, those blessings are
usually bestowed on Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But in the governor's race this year, the unions have been
mostly silent, and many labor leaders say they will remain neutral.
Gov. George Pataki, a Republican, spent his first 18 months in
office in pitched battles with unions. But over the last two years,
he has effectively neutralized the unions.
</P>
<P>
   That has not only denied the Democrats one of their most potent
allies but has also given Pataki a tactical advantage in not having
to defend against a well-financed and organized attack from labor.
</P>
<P>
   There is still no political lovefest between labor and Pataki.
But union leaders have calculated that the governor is almost
certain to win re-election and that going to war with him would be
pointless and would harm their future dealings with him.
</P>
<P>
   Labor chiefs have concluded, warily, that Pataki is someone they
can work with. They point out that since 1996, Pataki has eased up
on budget cutting and has signed a handful of labor-friendly bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This governor has a lot of drawbacks, but he's trying, and
we're trying to work with him,'' said Danny Donohue, president of
the Civil Service Employees Association of New York, which
represents 265,000 state and local government workers.
</P>
<P>
   But underlying such judgments is the calculation that a popular
governor is too powerful an enemy to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly a consideration and I'm not going to deny
that,'' said Roger Benson, president of the 53,000-member New York
State Public Employees Federation, a union of white-collar state
workers that does not plan to make an endorsement in the race. ``We
have to maintain a relationship with the governor. We're not
interested in being at war.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Lubin, executive vice president of the 400,000-member New
York State United Teachers, said: ``Some unions endorse an
incumbent, or stay out of it, because they know he's going to win.
Why waste your money when you can have more of an impact in close
races that you can make a difference in?''
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, Pataki's campaign manager, argued that labor
leaders view the governor more favorably because ``they've decided
that the governor's policies are working for their members.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic factor is that more of their members are working,''
she said. ``The governor's been able to improve the economy, where
union members are now employed.''
</P>
<P>
   Many union officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
say they prefer Peter Vallone, a Democrat, to Pataki, but do not
think he can win. Vallone, the New York City Council speaker, is a
leading candidate for the Democratic nomination for governor.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of unions, including the Buffalo Teachers Federation,
are in the Vallone camp. But leaders of many of the state's largest
and most politically active unions say their groups will probably
not make an endorsement in the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue said his group might actually endorse the governor. The
state AFL-CIO, representing 2.5 million union members, is likely to
remain neutral in the governor's race, according to several of its
board members.
</P>
<P>
   District Council 37 of the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees, the umbrella organization for 120,000 New
York City employees, is working for Vallone in the Democratic
primary, but Stanley Hill, the council's president, said he was
unsure whether it would play a role in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McCabe, Vallone's campaign manager, contended that the
unions' neutrality is actually a sign of the governor's weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're this powerful incumbent and things are going so
well, why isn't labor out there endorsing him?'' he asked. ``By
definition, some of the public employee unions aren't going to go
with us because they've got to work with the other guy to negotiate
a contract. But they can't go to their members with Pataki's record
and convince people that he's the right person.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Pataki is not the first politician whose power and
popularity have discouraged potential antagonists from taking
sides. Business groups that disliked Gov. Mario Cuomo, a Democrat,
were loath to take him on at the height of his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's one-time mentor, U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, has proved
to be an expert at co-opting his opponents. But D'Amato, who has
less direct power than the governor to influence the issues labor
cares most about, has not managed to silence unions the way Pataki
has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'd probably guess we're going to come out against
D'Amato, go with whoever wins the Democratic primary'' in the
Senate race, said Ed Cleary, president of the state AFL-CIO.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
