<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-PROFILE-2TAK     08-31 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-PROFILE-2TAKES(1100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENT AT LAST, SOSA KNOCKING THEM OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Sammy Sosa is in the batting cage at Wrigley Field,
and his coaches are talking hitting. They use a strange vocabulary,
with talk of tap stepping and loading up, of quiet hands and early
feet. They are all code words for patience.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six years of his career, Sammy Sosa was one of the
least patient players in the game. He could hit the long ball and
steal a base, but he was undisciplined. Moving the runner to third,
protecting the plate with two strikes _ these things were not his
style. Last year Sosa struck out 174 times, more than any Chicago
Cub since Wrigley was called Weeghman Park.
</P>
<P>
   Now he can joke about those years, saying, ``I was trying to hit
two home runs in every at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man in a hurry has learned to wait. At age 29, a
mature Sosa is handling more than National League pitching. He is
the cool competitor in the Roger Maris chase, the man who tied Mark
McGwire of St. Louis by hitting his 55th home run Monday night
against the Cincinnati Reds as they both push toward 61 home runs
and beyond. And Sosa has not been tossed from a game yet.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the cage, his coaches smile as Sosa sends another low
fastball into the seats. As he moves toward the conclusion of a
dream season, they recall the arc of his maturation as a player and
as a man.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa came to the Cubs at age 24, carrying a dual reputation. The
good Sammy loved to play. He appreciated what he had, and how he
had risen from poverty in the Dominican Republic. The bad Sammy was
a sucker for a two-strike curve in the dirt. He had a career
average of .233.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, he sometimes seemed to play for himself, not the team. He
would steal a base when it did the team no good, padding his
statistics. He did not always think where he should position
himself in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a rockhead,'' said Mark Grace, the blunt leader of the
Cubs' clubhouse. ``He played Barry Bonds and Rafael Belliard the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   And he tried to pull every pitch to left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy didn't believe there were any base hits in right
field,'' said Billy Williams, a Cubs coach and a Hall of Famer as a
player.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Sosa were Cub rookies together in 1992. Sosa had
just finished two dismal years with the crosstown White Sox, and
Williams was back with the Cubs at age 53, as the hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   Williams knows hitting (he is 164 career home runs ahead of
Sosa, who had 262 after Monday's game), and he knows the burden of
high expectations. Back in 1961, the kid from Whistler, Ala., was
the rookie of the year, and then an All-Star six times. He believes
the young Latin players of today have it a bit easier than his
generation of African-American players, despite the language
barrier. ``Now they have a veteran who will teach and talk and
tell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's talent was obvious. Ted Williams, an extraordinary hitter
in his day, has said the swing starts in the hips, and Sosa arrived
with one of the strongest lower bodies in the game. But he also was
quick with his hands. And the list of players with that combination
is short, say Billy Williams and Jeff Pentland, who became the
Cubs' hitting coach in 1997. There are Bonds, Gary Sheffield, Sammy
Sosa and not many more.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1992, one of the first things Williams taught Sosa was
to quit diving into the plate on every pitch, making himself
vulnerable to a ball thrown at his hands. Williams talked to him
about standing farther back. And he told him to keep his head back,
behind the point of contact.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa practiced hard, in the weight room and in winter ball, and
developed into a hitter. In 1993 Sosa became the first Cub to hit
30 homers and steal 30 bases. By 1995 he was second in the league
in both homers and runs batted in. In 1996 he reached 40 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player,'' Williams said, ``goes through that barrier
where he says: `Hey, I belong in the major leagues. I'm as good as
these other guys.'''
</P>
<P>
   A lesson in finesse came next. A former minor leaguer, Pentland
was Bonds' hitting coach at Arizona State. ``Sammy didn't have much
finesse,'' Pentland said. ``Sammy was all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentland collected videotapes of Sosa at the plate. As he
stepped toward the pitcher and just before he began his swing,
there in freeze frame was the ball _ already halfway to home plate.
``That's too late,'' Pentland said. ``You can't swing till the foot
hits the ground. It's called having late feet.'' They worked on
keeping Sosa's hands down, closer to the point of impact, making
his swing shorter. The goal was to give him more time to recognize
the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   And Sosa added another touch on his own: the tap step. Chipper
Jones of Atlanta uses it, as do others. Last August, Sosa began
learning the tap. Before the pitch is delivered, he steps back,
with his front foot, away from the pitcher. It's a timing device.
It starts a rhythm. First the back step and then the forward
explosion. ``Rhythm,'' Pentland said, ``is another word for
coordination.''
</P>
<P>
   The tap step also breaks the swing down into stages: a first
stage (the rearward tap step) that always happens, and a second
stage (the forward swing) that is held in reserve for the right
pitch. Tapping delays the launch decision a split second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives him time to read the pitch, to load up, to build
up,'' Pentland said. ``We want Sammy ready to swing even if he
doesn't commit.''
</P>
<P>
   While the coaches worked on Sosa's swing, Mark Grace worked on
his head. The first baseman is the only Cub who remembers the
team's last taste of the playoffs, in 1989. He had a few chats with
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he had accomplished everything he could as a
player,'' Grace said. ``He'd stolen 30 bases. He had 40 home runs
and 100 RBI. He was an All-Star. But he'd never been to the
playoffs. To be a superstar, you need to be a superstar in the
post-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa said, ``Well, I was in the playoffs in the Dominican
Republic,'' But Sosa knew what Grace meant. And now, with a month
to go in the season, Sosa is trying to pass Roger Maris'
single-season record of 61 home runs in 1961 at the same time he is
trying to push the Cubs past the Mets and the San Francisco Giants
in the National League wild-card race. It is a more complicated
assignment than McGwire has, because the Cardinals are not
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``My situation is different,'' Sosa said. ``I'm in the middle of
a pennant race and I can't go out there thinking about a home run
all the time. Mark's only looking for one thing _ to go out there
and break the record.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But with all that at stake, Sosa is more relaxed now than he
used to be, when a negative newspaper story would stay on his back
for a week. Now he relaxes after a game, an ice wrap on his ribs,
welcoming questions whether he hit a home run that day or not.
</P>
<P>
   It has all come together for him: the waiting, the early feet
and the tap step. Then, 55 times, the leap of exclamation, the
heart kisses for his family and the ``V'' signs he says are to
honor the late Harry Caray, the longtime Cubs announcer.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa still strikes out a lot _ 134 times entering Monday's game,
the most in the major leagues, and just ahead of McGwire, who has
struck out 129 times. But he is moving the runners over. He leads
the league in RBIs and total bases. With a month to go, he has a
third more walks than he had last season.
</P>
<P>
   A June 13 game in Philadelphia was an example of his
improvement. He hit a two-run home run _ to right field, where
one-fourth of his homers this year have landed. More important,
twice with two strikes he made just enough contact to drive in a
run _ on a groundout and on a sacrifice fly. The Cubs won, 10-8, in
10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa swings a light, black bat, 32 ounces, with a thicker handle
than most power hitters prefer. Unlike McGwire's high, towering
shots, many of Sosa's home runs are line drives. From just a few
feet away, the confrontation of bat and ball produces a
thunderclap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits the ball hard, doesn't he?'' Pentland said, watching
Sosa hit. ``He doesn't swing hard, does he? I call it easy power.
McGwire has it. Sammy has it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has done it with nothing stronger in his locker than baby
lotion, although he has used creatine, a muscle-building amino acid
powder, sporadically in the past.
</P>
<P>
   These days, on his way to work at Wrigley, Sosa can take a
detour on the Kennedy Expressway and drive past a three-story mural
of himself slamming a home run. It is being painted on the Bigsby &AMP;
Kruthers warehouse, where an image of Dennis Rodman and his
technicolor hair colors stopped traffic in 1996. Now Sosa is the
three-story man.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard for any player in his situation not to have an
inflated view of himself. But Billy Williams can still help with
that. As it turns out, he is now the Cubs' outfield coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``His errors,'' Williams said. ``Knowing where to position
himself and where to throw. He could improve on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
