<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULFWAR-SYNDROME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL FINDS INSUFFICIENT EVIDENCE TO TIE IRAQI GAS TO
ILLNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate committee has concluded that while the
government failed many veterans of the Persian Gulf war, there is
insufficient evidence to conclude that exposure to Iraqi nerve gas
caused the illnesses reported by thousands of American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Veterans Affairs Committee reached those conclusions
after a yearlong study and will present them in a 310-page report
to be released on Tuesday. Although highly critical of the
Departments of Defense and Veterans Affairs, the report's authors
said they could not conclude, as others have, that nerve gas caused
the so-called Gulf War Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is insufficient evidence at this time to prove or
disprove that there was actual low-level exposure of any troops to
chemical weapon nerve agents or that any of the health effects some
veterans are experiencing were caused by such exposure,'' the
Senate panel concluded.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the report might seem surprising, because the
Senate Veterans Affairs Committee _ like the House Committee on
Government Reform and Oversight and a pPresidential commission _
has been critical of how the Pentagon and Veterans Affairs
Department have handled soldiers' complaints of illnesses after the
1991 war.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear on Monday night whether the report's cautious
wording, and its stress on insufficient evidence, reflected the
background of the panel's chairman, Sen. Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania, who was a prosecutor before becoming a lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee concluded last October, after a 20-month
investigation, that ``a variety of toxic agents in the gulf war,''
including Iraqi chemical weapons and pesticides, were probably
responsible for the health problems reported by up to 100,000
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   And the presidential advisory committee concluded a week later
that the Defense Department had dismissed credible evidence that
thousands of Marines may have been exposed to poison gas when they
crossed Iraqi minefields in the war.
</P>
<P>
   In concluding that there was not enough evidence to blame
exposure to chemical weapons for the widespread illnesses, the
Senate panel nevertheless said the Defense Department and veterans
agency had not investigated diligently enough.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the veterans agency had shown ``chronic and
pervasive inability to generate valid and reliable data about the
Gulf war veterans it serves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
